const RECIPES = [{"id": 2, "t": "Perfect Éclairs", "c": "Baking", "d": "Is there a more iconic patisserie item than an éclair? Elegant, refined, and infinitely customizable, these glazed, cream-filled confections are a fundamental application for pâte à choux. For crack-free, consistent results, we’re pulling out all the pastry chef hacks: piping techniques, pre-treating the piped choux, customizable glazes, and a whole roster of options for the creamy filling. The re", "i": ["1 recipe Perfect Pâte à Choux , (see “Before we begin” note)", "Powdered sugar , for dusting , as needed", "1 recipe Pastry Cream , (see “Before we begin” note)", "550 g Heavy cream , chilled, divided", "Silver gelatin, 170 bloom , (2 sheets), or 3.8 g Knox powdered gelatin (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "226 g 70% dark chocolate , finely chopped (see “Before we begin” note)", "60 g Light corn syrup", "30 g Unsalted butter", "15 g Neutral oil", "Instant espresso powder , optional , as needed", "Gel food coloring , optional , as needed", "Luster dust, as needed - Gold leaf, as needed", "Gold leaf, as needed"], "s": ["Éclairs vs. choux au craquelin", "Pipe choux dough", "Spray and dust éclairs with powdered sugar", "Bake éclairs", "Make crème légère", "Fill and chill éclairs", "Make chocolate glaze", "Glaze éclairs", "Serve or store éclairs for later"], "tips": ["For better air flow and more even baking, flip your sheet pan.", "Use a paring knife to minimize the “tail” on piped éclairs.", "For more consistent piping, use guides.", "For crack-free éclairs, spray and dust ’em.", "Consistent oven temperature matters.", "Don’t overfill the piping bag.", "Flavor your crème légère.", "Not a fan of chocolate glaze? Make a customizable all-purpose sugar glaze.", "For perfect glazing, temperature matters.", "Make éclairs pop with some decorative flair."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/eclairs"}, {"id": 3, "t": "Classic Carbonara", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Carbonara barely needs an introduction: It’s a bacon-egg-and-cheese in pasta form, only better. Just like the other “core four” Roman pastas, carbonara is a simple dish that you can make or break with technique. We give the eggs and cheese the zabaglione treatment to guarantee a silky-smooth sauce that won’t ever break on you. save Print", "i": ["225 g Guanciale , (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Black pepper , coarsely ground (1 teaspoon), plus extra for serving", "3 Egg yolk(s) , large", "1 Egg(s) , large", "60 g Pecorino Romano , finely grated, plus extra for serving (see “Before we begin” note)", "60 g Parmigiano-Reggiano , finely grated, plus extra for serving (see “Before we begin” note)", "6 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "340 g Spaghettoni , (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["The “core four” Roman pastas", "Cut guanciale", "Render guanciale", "Bloom pepper", "Whisk egg mixture", "Cook pasta al chiodo", "Cook egg mixture zabaglione-style", "Finish cooking pasta", "Incorporate egg-cheese zabaglione off-heat", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Invest in a good pasta pan", "The grate debate: the best way to grate hard cheeses for pasta", "Pasta doneness: al chiodo vs. al dente", "No-scramble carbonara", "Mantecatura: the technique for emulsified pasta sauces", "How to plate long pasta like a pro"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pasta-alla-carbonara"}, {"id": 4, "t": "Ultra-Crispy Chicken Tenders", "c": "Baking", "d": "Few things are as universally appealing as chicken tenders. Kids love ’em, which is why they’re on every kid’s menu. Adults love ’em, too, which is why there are all those rules about adults ordering off the kid’s menu. But there are times when chicken tenders don’t live up to their potential as an S-tier dippable food. Sometimes, they’re just bad. The fact of the matter is that it’s challenging t", "i": ["675 g Chicken tenders , (12 tenders)", "1 kg Water", "74 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "240 g All-purpose flour , divided", "180 g Cornstarch , divided", "60 g Potato starch , divided", "16 g Granulated sugar", "4 g Baking powder , (1 1/8 teaspoons)", "2 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 g Garlic powder , (1/4 teaspoon)", "2 g Onion powder , (1/4 teaspoon)", "180 g Buttermilk", "140 g Vodka", "54 g Crisp Coat UC", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "675 g Chicken breast(s) , boneless, skinless (2 breasts)", "1 kg Water 70 g Kosher salt", "3 g White vinegar powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g White pepper , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Smoked paprika , ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "1 recipe Alabama White Barbecue Sauce , for serving, optional 1 recipe A Guide to Pie Dough: The Ingredients , for serving, optional 1 recipe Homemade Hidden-Valley-Style Ranch Dressing , for serving, optional 1 recipe Kansas City-Style Barbecue Sauce , for serving, optional", "1 recipe A Guide to Pie Dough: The Ingredients , for serving, optional", "1 recipe Homemade Hidden-Valley-Style Ranch Dressing , for serving, optional", "1 recipe Kansas City-Style Barbecue Sauce , for serving, optional"], "s": ["Trim chicken tenders", "Brine chicken tenders", "Make batter", "Make dredge", "Set up frying station", "Dredge chicken", "Fry chicken first time", "Double fry chicken", "Serve"], "tips": ["No tendies? No problem! How to cut chicken breasts into chicken strips.", "For the juiciest tendies, brine ’em.", "The elements of a crispy tender", "Fry twice to prevent overcooking and unlock the perfect crust.", "Skim your oil to keep it clean and last longer.", "Give your tenders a seasoning boost.", "Glaze, coat, or dip chicken tenders for a crispy-saucy experience.", "How to make killer better-than-store-bought frozen tenders"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fried-chicken-tenders"}, {"id": 5, "t": "Homemade Hidden-Valley-Style Ranch Dressing", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Who doesn’t love Hidden Valley Ranch? (Heathens, that’s who.) The iconic label with its rolling green hills and cloud-flecked blue skies is always a sign that you’re about to have a great time. We love it so much that we decided to give our homemade version a little something extra—bumping it up with both MSG and MSG-laced Kewpie mayo, and then folding in some minced fresh herbs and a little fresh", "i": ["200 g Sour cream", "50 g Kewpie mayonnaise , homemade or store-bought", "10 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon)", "3 g Onion powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (1/8 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Garlic powder , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "5 g Chives , fresh, thinly sliced", "5 g Dill , fresh, finely chopped", "5 g Parsley , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "4 g Tarragon , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "25 g Japanese (Kewpie-Style) Mayo", "3.5 g Salt"], "s": ["Mix dressing", "Put ranch to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Level up your ranch with “hidden” herbs", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/homemade-hidden-valley-style-ranch-dressing"}, {"id": 6, "t": "Alabama White Barbecue Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "Alabama white barbecue sauce is a tangy, mayo-based sauce designed specifically to go with smoked chicken, made famous by Big Bob Gibson Bar-B-Q in—you guessed it—Alabama. While its intended purpose is as a kind of mop for smoked chicken, it also works great as a sandwich spread or a dipping sauce for Ultra-Crispy Chicken Tenders. save Print Explore other Recipes 32 SEE THE RECIPE Millionaire’s Sh", "i": ["150 g Mayonnaise", "35 g Apple cider vinegar", "30 g Spicy brown mustard", "15 g Horseradish , prepared", "15 g Light brown sugar", "10 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1/2 lemon)", "4 g Onion powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.75 g Cayenne pepper , ground (1/4 teaspoon), optional", "0.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/8 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Mix sauce", "Put sauce to use or store for later"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/alabama-white-barbecue-sauce"}, {"id": 7, "t": "Spicy Peanut Dipping Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "Peanuts, fish sauce, lime, and chiles are a classic Southeast Asian combo that just works—the toasty richness of the nuts, the savoriness of the fish sauce, the bright acidity from the citrus, and the fiery heat of the chiles come together to give everything they touch a thrilling boost of flavor. It’s a perfect combo for a dipping sauce. This is a super-dippable riff on the spicy peanut sauce we ", "i": ["150 g Peanut butter , (see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g Lime juice , fresh (from 2 limes)", "45 g Fish sauce", "25 g Granulated sugar", "10 g Thai green chile(s) , (10 chiles) fresh, stemmed, seeded, and minced", "30 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, minced", "25 g Peanuts , roasted, unsalted, coarsely chopped"], "s": ["Mix sauce", "Put peanut sauce to use or store for later"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spicy-peanut-sauce"}, {"id": 8, "t": "8 Quick Sauces for Slathering, Dipping, and Dunking", "c": "Baking", "d": "Okay, so you’ve got your grilled proteins on lock. But what about that sauce, boss? Take your next grilled meal—plus apps, snacks, and side dishes—to EPIC level with these sauces. Using minimal ingredients and prep, these whip up fast so you can head to the grill, get saucy, and set the table in no time at all. Originally developed to work with our always reliable grilled chicken legs (made tender", "i": ["70 g Sugar , granulated", "9 g Cornstarch", "10 g Habanero pepper(s) , seeded and minced", "70 g Distilled vinegar", "1 Orange(s) , navel", "Salt , about 4g , as needed", "60 g Scallion(s) , bottoms and tops separated (about 1 bunch)", "2 Lime(s) , zested and juiced", "135 g Molasses", "135 g Brown sugar", "80 g Rum , spiced or dark", "25 g Fresh ginger root , grated", "3 g Allspice , ground", "1 g Black pepper , cracked", "4 g Kosher salt", "100 g Skippy’s peanut butter , smooth or crunchy", "100 g Lime juice , fresh", "75 g Fish sauce", "10 g Thai green chile(s) , sliced", "30 g Cilantro , fresh stems, sliced", "25 g Peanuts , roasted, chopped", "100 g Hoisin sauce", "60 g Honey", "60 g Malt syrup , or molasses", "10 g Soy sauce", "20 g Shaohshing rice wine , or dry Sherry", "3 g Five-spice powder", "10 g Sesame oil", "2 g White pepper , ground, optional", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , peeled and grated, optional", "150 g Tamarind concentrate , Dragonfly brand", "75 g Clover honey", "Orange juice , freshly squeezed, about 1 orange , as needed", "Orange zest , about 1 orange , as needed", "15 g Any oil , of your choice", "120 g Apple cider vinegar", "120 g Miso paste , any", "1 g Cumin seeds", "2 g Cinnamon stick(s) , optional", "70 g Red chiles , New Mexico, dried", "100 g Tomato paste", "50 g Raisins", "300 g Water", "150 g Mayonnaise , Best Foods brand", "30 g Spicy brown mustard", "15 g Horseradish", "10 g Lemon juice , from a quarter lemon", "4 g Onion powder", "0.75 g Cayenne pepper , ground, optional"], "s": ["Sweet and Sour Pepper Orange Marmalade Sauce", "Spicy Jamaican Jerk Sauce", "A Skippy Thai-Style Peanut Sauce", "Char Siu Sauce", "Honey Tamarind Sweet and Sour Sauce", "Garlic Miso BBQ Sauce", "New Mexico Chile Ketchup", "Alabama White BBQ Sauce", "You need something to put that sauce on"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/easy-sauces-for-your-grilled-meats"}, {"id": 9, "t": "Ultra-Flaky Scallion Pancakes", "c": "Baking", "d": "", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultra-flaky-scallion-pancakes"}, {"id": 10, "t": "Silky Cheung Fun (Chinese Rice Rolls)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Cheung fun is a simple and delicious dish of slippery and supple wide rice noodle rolls. It basically comes in two forms; if you’ve had dim sum, you’ve probably had the more refined version, delicate rice noodle sheets wrapped around fillings of succulent shrimp or minced beef. But there’s a street-food version—this one—and it might just be the best street food you’ve never had. Instead of neat ri", "i": ["50 g Rice flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Tapioca starch , (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "250 g Water", "2 Egg(s) , beaten (optional) 90 g Classic Char Siu , chopped (optional)", "90 g Classic Char Siu , chopped (optional)", "Light soy sauce , optional , as needed", "Sweet Soy Sauce , optional , as needed", "Fried garlic , optional , as needed", "Fried shallots , optional , as needed", "Toasted sesame seeds , optional , as needed", "Scallion(s) , thinly sliced, optional , as needed", "Sesame paste , optional , as needed", "Chile oil , optional , as needed", "Chili crisp , homemade or store-bought, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Street food-style vs. dim sum-style cheung fun", "Mix batter", "Set up steamer and preheat pan", "Cook rice roll batter", "Roll up cheung fun", "Cook remaining batter", "Reheat rice rolls", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": ["Customize street food-style cheung fun with toppings.", "Cheung fun, a dish that must be served hot", "Garnishing cheung fun"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cheung-fun-rice-rolls"}, {"id": 11, "t": "Dim Sum-Style Shrimp Cheung Fun", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "If there’s one dish at the dim sum table that is the epitome of finesse, it’s shrimp cheung fun (ha cheung). It consists of just rice batter, shrimp, and a slick of oil and soy sauce. But together they form a transcendent dish, featuring a translucent, silky rice sheet encasing just-tender, perfectly steamed shrimp. This recipe is all about managing steam to deliver consistently hot, fresh ha cheu", "i": ["50 g Rice flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Tapioca starch , (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Kosher salt , divided (3/4 teaspoon)", "250 g Water", "250 g Shrimp , jumbo (26–30 per pound; about 18 shrimp), peeled and deveined", "5 g Shaoxing wine , (1 teaspoon)", "3 g Cornstarch , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Toasted sesame oil , (1/4 teaspoon)", "1 recipe Dim Sum-Style Seasoned Soy Sauce"], "s": ["Street food-style vs. dim sum-style cheung fun", "Mix batter", "Butterfly and marinate shrimp", "Set up steamer and preheat pan", "Cook cheung fun batter", "Add shrimp filling", "Cook shrimp filling", "Roll up cheung fun", "Cook and roll 3 more rice rolls", "Reheat first plate of rice rolls", "Serve"], "tips": ["Cheung fun vs. hor fun", "Maximize efficiency with a 3-tier steamer setup", "Cheung fun, a dish that must be served hot"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/shrimp-cheung-fun"}, {"id": 12, "t": "Dim Sum-Style Beef Cheung Fun", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Beef cheung fun can either be done well—with a tender and delicate rice noodle sheet wrapped around tender minced beef, a dim sum dish that can almost rival its shrimp-stuffed sibling—or it can be done badly, in which case it’s completely forgettable. There’s nothing in between. If the beef is overcooked, it becomes rubbery and releases too much moisture, making the rice rolls unpleasantly wet; if", "i": ["50 g Rice flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Tapioca starch , (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "295 g Water , divided", "275 g Flank steak , (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Cornstarch , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "5 g Shaoxing wine , (1 teaspoon)", "5 g Light soy sauce , (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Oyster sauce , (1 teaspoon)", "5 g Toasted sesame oil , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1/2 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "0.5 g White pepper , ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "1 recipe Dim Sum-Style Seasoned Soy Sauce"], "s": ["Street food-style vs. dim sum-style cheung fun", "Mix batter", "Process beef", "Mix beef filling", "Set up steamer and preheat pan", "Cook cheung fun batter", "Add beef filling", "Cook beef filling", "Roll up cheung fun", "Cook and roll 3 more rice rolls", "Reheat first plate of rice rolls", "Serve"], "tips": ["Cheung fun vs. hor fun", "No food processor? Hand-mince the beef.", "Maximize efficiency with a 3-tier steamer setup", "Cheung fun, a dish that must be served hot"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-cheung-fun"}, {"id": 13, "t": "Ultimate Shoyu Ramen", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Shoyu ramen is the most classic style of ramen: A clear soup, stained caramel by a soy sauce tare, with pools of glistening fat floating over a nest of slinky and slippery noodles, crowned with a couple slices of tender roast pork chashu, a marinated soft-boiled egg, and a pile of sliced onions, it is as beautiful as it is delicious. This recipe offers a refined take on shoyu ramen, cribbing from ", "i": ["300 ml Super Soup Ramen Stock", "50 ml Sous Vide Dashi", "135 g Silky Ramen Noodles , or store-bought fresh-frozen noodles (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 ml Shoyu Tare", "30 ml Lard , or reserved fat from Super Soup Ramen Stock, melted (see “Before we begin” note)", "White pepper, as needed", "Chashu (Roast Pork for Ramen) , sliced into 1/8- to 1/4-inch pieces, optional , as needed", "1 Ajitsuke Tamago (Marinated Ramen Eggs) , halved or whole, optional", "Naga negi , (long onions), or scallions, thinly sliced, soaked in ice water, and drained (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "Nori , cut into 2- by 4-inch rectangles, optional , as needed", "Narutomaki , sliced into 1/8-inch-thick rounds, optional (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "300 ml Super Soup Ramen Stock 50 ml Sous Vide Dashi"], "s": ["Prep all the elements of ramen in advance", "Why ramen is optimized for single servings, and how to make multiple portions.", "Warm bowl and boil water", "Blend and heat stock", "Cook noodles and build soup", "Add noodles to soup", "Add toppings and serve"], "tips": ["Warming ramen bowls", "Heat ramen stock just before service for the best aroma and flavor.", "Dialing in stock ratios for different flavor profiles", "Do any last-minute topping prep as the noodles cook.", "Naga negi knife cuts", "How to “plate” noodles in soup", "How to place toppings on a bowl of ramen"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-shoyu-ramen"}, {"id": 14, "t": "Silky Ramen Noodles", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "There are all kinds of noodles that fall under the umbrella of “ramen”—super long and crinkly, wire-thin and straight, chunky and ruffled, wide and flat. There aren’t really any rules to the noodles, except for this one: Ramen must be made with an alkalized wheat dough. That’s true of these noodles, just as it is of our Chewy Ramen Noodles. This recipe produces softer, silkier noodles that are bou", "i": ["352 g Water", "9 g Sodium carbonate , (see “Before we begin note”)", "8 g Kosher salt", "732 g Bread flour", "68 g Tapioca starch , (see “Before we begin note”)", "16 g Egg(s) , (from 1 egg; see “Before we begin note”)", "Potato starch , or cornstarch, for dusting cut noodles (see “Before we begin note”) , as needed", "300 g Baking soda"], "s": ["Mix alkaline salt solution", "Mix flour, tapioca starch, and egg", "Add alkaline salt solution", "Press dough into a sheet", "Portion and knead dough sheets", "Thin noodle sheets", "Cut noodles", "Age noodles (optional)", "Put noodles to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Want extra chewy ramen noodles? We got you!", "No sodium carbonate? No problem! Toast baking soda to make sodium carbonate.", "Soboro—the perfect “pebble” texture for noodle dough.", "Cutting corners—good for noodle sheeting", "Use dough sheet length to dial in thickness.", "Age noodles for better texture."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/silky-ramen-noodles"}, {"id": 15, "t": "Super Soup Ramen Stock", "c": "Baking", "d": "A good bowl of ramen starts with a good stock, and for a great bowl of ramen, you need a great stock—and, boy, do we have the stock for you! For our Ultimate Shoyu Ramen we’ve created a pork-chicken double stock that’s every bit as flavorful and gelatin-rich as the stocks used in some of the best ramen shops around the world. And if you really want to go the extra mile, we give you the option of c", "i": ["3.2 kg Water , divided", "6 g Kombu , (3-inch square)", "1 Pork spareribs , whole rack, cut in half (1.3 to 1.6 kg; 3 to 3 1/2 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "1 Pig’s foot , (about 450 g; 1 pound; see “Before we begin” note), optional", "450 g Ground pork", "60 g Garlic clove(s) , (12 medium cloves), 6 cloves left whole, 6 cloves crushed, divided", "30 g Fresh ginger root , (2-inch piece) peeled and sliced into coins, divided", "2.3 kg Chicken wings , cut into drumettes, flats, and wing tips (5 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "300 g White onion(s) , (1 onion) thinly sliced", "40 g Scallion(s) , (about 2 bunches) thinly sliced", "190 g Napa cabbage , whole leaves (about 6 leaves)", "500 g Chicken breast(s) , boneless, skinless, cut into 1-inch pieces, optional", "Lard , or rendered chicken fat or neutral oil , as needed 1 Garlic clove(s)"], "s": ["Three paths to ramen stock: single, double, and clarified", "Soak kombu", "Bring pork stock to a boil", "Pressure cook pork stock", "Remove pork bones, add chicken, and bring back to a boil", "Pressure cook double stock", "Steep aromatics and kombu", "Strain and chill stock", "Blend chicken breast and stock (optional)", "Bring to a boil to form raft (optional)", "Simmer clarified stock (optional)", "Strain clarified stock (optional)", "Put stock(s) to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Cold-soak kombu for better flavor extraction", "Want a quicker ramen stock? We got you!", "“I’m cooking this stock twice? Why?”", "For stock with clean vegetal flavors, steep, don’t simmer.", "Put that aromatic fat to use", "Clarify a portion of the stock for “super soup” ramen"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-ramen-stock"}, {"id": 16, "t": "Chashu (Roast Pork for Ramen)", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "“Chashu” is a Japanese “loan word” from the Chinese “char siu,” and while both refer to pork roasts, they’re completely different preparations. Chashu is used as an umbrella term for the sliced pork served with ramen. It can be roasted, braised, or cooked sous vide to a tender, blushing pink; it is, sometimes, simply boiled in the stock used for making ramen. This roast pork belly chashu is simple", "i": ["9 g Kosher salt , (1% of pork belly weight)", "9 g Brown sugar , (1% of pork belly weight)", "900 g Pork belly , skin-off, center cut (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Soy sauce", "5 g Mirin , (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Cure pork", "Roast pork", "Marinate and chill pork", "Put chashu to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Cook chashu sous vide for a steaky alternative.", "Why marinate after cooking?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chashu"}, {"id": 17, "t": "Shoyu Tare", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Every bowl of ramen gets its seasoning from tare. “Tare” is a general term for “sauce” in Japanese. You may have seen it used for yakitori, as in our Tsukune recipe, but in the context of ramen, it basically means “noodle sauce.” Tare determines the flavor of ramen, and there are essentially three flavor categories for all styles of ramen: shio (salt), shoyu (soy sauce), and miso. This shoyu tare ", "i": ["400 g Soy sauce , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "6 g Kombu , (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Shiitake mushrooms , dried (1 mushroom)", "240 g Sake , dry", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) crushed", "40 g Mirin , (see “Before we begin” note)", "8 g Bonito flakes , (see “Before we begin” note)", "10 g Granulated sugar", "5 g Kosher salt", "40 g Fish sauce , (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Steep kombu and shiitake in soy sauce", "Cook sake au sec", "Infuse tare", "Strain and finish tare", "Put tare to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Balancing the elements of shoyu tare", "Cold-soak kombu for better flavor extraction", "Don’t boil kombu and katsuobushi."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/shoyu-tare"}, {"id": 18, "t": "Sous Vide Dashi", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Dashi is the foundational stock in Japanese cuisine. Packed with umami, it’s used in a wide variety of applications, like sauces, soups, custards, and braises. While you can make a dashi out of any ingredient—it just means “cooking broth”—it typically refers to a broth made with kombu, or dried kelp. Dashi that has been made with a combination of kombu and katsuobushi—shavings of boiled, smoked, a", "i": ["25 g Kombu", "1 kg Water", "10 g Dried anchovies , heads and guts removed (optional)", "25 g Bonito flakes"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Bag up kombu", "Steep kombu sous vide", "Steep katsuobushi and strain", "Put that dashi to use"], "tips": ["More about kombu, katsuobushi, and niboshi", "No-waste second dashi"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-dashi"}, {"id": 19, "t": "Ajitsuke Tamago (Marinated Ramen Eggs)", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "They’re called ajitsuke tamago and they’re in almost every bowl of ramen around the world—we even have a Joule guide for Ultimate Ramen Eggs. But we wanted to make this super simple, so we started with a seven-minute soft-boiled egg and then leveled them up with the soy and mirin curing process that is used when ramen eggs are made. When it comes to a seven-minute egg, precision is key. This is se", "i": ["12 Egg(s)", "100 g Soy sauce", "25 g White miso paste", "200 g Mirin"], "s": ["A Video Overview", "Make the cure", "Cook the eggs", "Cure the eggs", "Cut in half and serve"], "tips": ["Check out why less water is more efficient to cook your eggs!", "Impatient? Check out the difference. This is why you wait."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cured-ramen-eggs-you-can-t-stop-eating"}, {"id": 20, "t": "Cake Doughnuts", "c": "Baking", "d": "With a soft, tender, and crumbly crumb encased in a crisp outer shell, cake doughnuts are a deliciously affirmative answer to the question, “Would deep-fried cake be good?” What distinguishes cake doughnuts from other styles, like yeasted doughnuts and crullers, is the way the dough is leavened: Baking soda and baking powder give the dough lift, producing a fine-grained crumb with tiny bubbles thr", "i": ["150 g Buttermilk , full fat, room temperature (see “Before we begin” note)", "120 g Granulated sugar", "1 Egg(s) , large", "1 Egg yolk(s) , large", "10 g Vanilla paste , or vanilla extract (see “Before we begin” note)", "40 g Unsalted butter , melted", "300 g Cake flour , unbleached, plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Nonfat dry milk powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "4 g Baking powder , (1 1/8 teaspoons)", "1 g Baking soda , (1/4 teaspoon)", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "1.6 kg Coconut oil (refined) , or neutral oil (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Cocoa powder , (extra brute)", "recipe Cake flour , unbleached (see “Before we begin” note)", "recipe", "25 g Light brown sugar", "2 g Cinnamon , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 recipe Doughnut Glaze"], "s": ["Blend wet ingredients", "Sift and mix dry ingredients", "Mix dough", "Form and chill dough", "Roll and portion doughnuts", "recipe", "Set up frying station", "Fry doughnuts", "Glaze doughnuts (optional)", "Serve"], "tips": ["Cake vs. yeasted doughnuts", "Make it a chocolate or cider doughnut", "For best results, chill the dough before frying.", "Re-roll dough scraps for extra doughnuts", "Give doughnuts a sugar coating or glaze"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cake-doughnuts"}, {"id": 21, "t": "Apple Fritters", "c": "Baking", "d": "Crispy, craggy, and glazed on the outside, with a plush and light interior, apple fritters are one of the best doughnuts. But maybe “doughnuts” isn’t the best description for these delicious chimeras. Like those mythical beasts, they’re a mashup of different things, but in place of the lion’s claws and a serpent’s tail, apple fritters consist of an enriched yeasted dough that’s rolled up with a sp", "i": ["180 g Whole milk", "50 g Unsalted butter , divided", "110 g Granulated sugar , divided", "20 g Neutral oil", "1 Egg(s) , large", "8 g Kosher salt , divided", "315 g All-purpose flour , plus extra as needed", "30 g Diastatic malt powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "7 g Instant dry yeast , (see “Before we begin” note)", "7 g Cinnamon , ground, divided", "5 g Cornstarch , (2 teaspoons)", "150 g Granny Smith apple(s) , (1 apple) cored and cut into 1/4-inch dice (see “Before we begin” note)", "125 g Apple cider , freshly pressed (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Orange blossom water , (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note) optional", "0.5 g Malic acid , (1/8 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note) optional", "1.6 kg Coconut oil (refined) , or neutral oil (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Apple cider doughnuts vs. apple fritters", "Combine wet ingredients", "Sift dry ingredients", "Mix dough", "Proof dough", "Prepare apple filling", "Roll and portion doughnuts", "Cut and portion fritters", "Final proof", "Make cider glaze", "Set up frying station", "Fry fritters", "Glaze fritters", "Serve"], "tips": ["Secure your stand mixer", "Use coil folds in high-hydration doughs to build gluten and redistribute gases.", "How to turn your oven into a dough proofer", "Airy vs. craggy fritters"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/apple-fritters"}, {"id": 22, "t": "Apple Cider Doughnuts", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’ve ever gone apple picking, you’ve probably housed a couple of cider doughnuts—they’re a fixture of apple orchards because they’re a great way to use up apple cider. What’s funny about all that is cider doughnuts don’t really taste like apple cider! They are instead more of a celebration of autumnal warm spices—a cake doughnut with cinnamon incorporated into the dough, fried and coated with", "i": ["75 g Apple cider , freshly pressed, room temperature (see “Before we begin” note)", "75 g Sour cream , room temperature", "135 g Granulated sugar , divided", "85 g Light brown sugar , divided", "1 Egg(s) , large", "1 Egg yolk(s) , large", "5 g Vanilla paste , (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "0.5 g Almond extract , (1/8 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note) optional", "40 g Unsalted butter , melted", "300 g Cake flour , unbleached, plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Nonfat dry milk powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "4 g Baking powder , (1 1/8 teaspoons)", "1 g Baking soda , (1/4 teaspoon)", "6 g Cinnamon , ground, divided", "5 g Kosher salt , divided (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "1 g Cloves , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Malic acid , (1/8 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note) optional", "1.6 kg Coconut oil (refined) , or neutral oil (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Orange blossom water , (1 teaspoon) optional"], "s": ["Apple cider doughnuts vs. apple fritters", "Blend wet ingredients", "Sift and mix dry ingredients", "Mix dough", "Form and chill dough", "Roll and portion doughnuts", "Mix cinnamon sugar", "Set up frying station", "Fry and coat doughnuts in cinnamon sugar", "Cool and serve"], "tips": ["Cake vs. yeasted doughnuts", "For best results, chill dough before frying.", "Re-roll dough scraps for extra doughnuts", "Coat doughnuts with cinnamon sugar while they’re still warm.", "Not into a cinnamon sugar coating? Make a cider glaze instead."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/apple-cider-doughnuts"}, {"id": 23, "t": "Crullers", "c": "Baking", "d": "Ever wonder what happened to the crullers at ye olde local chain doughnut shoppe? Us, too! It’s not just that they don’t make ’em like they used to; at most shops, they don’t make ’em at all! Well, we took matters into our own hands. The key to making crullers that are even better than the classic ridged eggy O’s of fried dough? Nailing the precise frying temperature for the pâte à choux, the eggy", "i": ["113 g Water", "113 g Whole milk", "113 g Unsalted butter", "15 g Granulated sugar", "12 g Vanilla paste , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "6 g Kosher salt , divided", "135 g All-purpose flour , sifted", "225 g Egg(s) , (from 4 to 5 large eggs), divided", "125 g Orange juice , fresh, strained of pulp (from 2 oranges)", "10 g Orange zest , finely grated (from 2 oranges)", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed"], "s": ["Make dough", "Cook dough", "Beat eggs into dough", "Chill and rest choux batter", "Make glaze", "Temper batter and set up frying station", "Pipe crullers", "Fry crullers", "Glaze crullers", "Serve crullers"], "tips": ["Mix efficiently, mix well", "How to load a piping bag without making a mess", "Tempering batter for easier piping", "Piping variations"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crullers"}, {"id": 24, "t": "Old-Fashioned Doughnuts", "c": "Baking", "d": "If there’s one thing the whole world can agree on, it’s dougnuts: America has stalwart chains like Dunkin’ Donuts and Krispy Kreme along with local icons like Brooklyn’s Peter Pan Donut & Pastry Shop, Seattle’s Top Pot, Café du Monde in New Orleans, and Philadelphia’s Federal Donuts. Canadians swear by Tim Horton’s. Italians eat zeppole; Turks enjoy lokma; Jewish people eat sufganiyot or buñuelos ", "i": ["240 g Sugar , granulated", "90 g Egg yolk(s) , beaten (about 5–6 large)", "36 g Butter", "380 g Sour cream", "600 g Pastry flour , or all-purpose", "15 g Baking powder", "12 g Kosher salt", "1 recipe Doughnut Glaze , optional", "Oil for frying , we use canola , as needed"], "s": ["Combine wet ingredients", "Sift and combine the dry ingredients", "Think ahead", "Add dry to wet", "Prep a sheet pan", "Roll and cut", "Chill", "If you’re going to glaze...", "Prepare to fry", "Fry time", "Glaze", "Coffee time"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/old-fashioned-doughnuts"}, {"id": 25, "t": "How to Make Bulletproof Fluffy Yeasted Doughnuts at Home", "c": "Baking", "d": "Imagine a Krispy Kreme doughnut—yum, right? Okay, now lose that melt-in-your-mouth texture. We know, it’s hard to say good-bye. Stick with us here. Right. Now replace that texture with a briochelike one with a little chewy give. The springy dough has an almost savory flavor that adults and kids alike will freak out over. We know this because we watched the ChefSteps staff lose their business when ", "i": ["55 g Butter", "55 g Vegetable oil", "530 g Milk , whole", "150 g Egg(s) , whole, beaten", "21 g Active dry yeast", "940 g Bread flour", "170 g Sugar , granulated", "6 g Kosher salt", "47 g Diastatic malt powder , optional", "1 recipe Doughnut Glaze , optional", "Oil for frying , we use canola , as needed", "25 g Plant-based chocolate chips", "25 g Brown sugar", "2.5 g Orange zest , fresh", "2.5 g Cinnamon", "5 g Fine-ground coffee", "1.5 g Salt"], "s": ["Combine and warm to 110 °F / 43 °C", "Add the yeast", "Sift and combine", "Combine wet and dry ingredients; mix with a dough hook", "Mix. A lot.", "Form into a ball, cover, and refrigerate one hour", "Punch down, roll, and cut", "Punch out doughnuts", "Transfer and proof", "If you’re going to glaze...", "Heat fry oil", "Glaze. Or not.", "It’s time to find some coffee.", "Seattle-Style Monkey Bread"], "tips": ["Indent for more doughnuts!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-bulletproof-fluffy-yeasted-doughnuts-at-home"}, {"id": 26, "t": "Tacos al Pastor", "c": "Baking", "d": "Tacos al pastor are an S-tier taco option, but unless you have a custom-made trompo and are feeding a small village, making them at home requires a little ingenuity and compromise. We love giant elaborate fiery rigs of spinning meat more than just about anyone, but we’re also the first to admit that they aren’t super practical. But you know what is practical? Tiny meat spits, aka skewers! Introduc", "i": ["25 g Guajillo chile(s) , stemmed and cut into 2-inch pieces", "80 g Pineapple , fresh, cut into 1/2-inch-thick planks, plus extra thinly sliced for serving", "40 g Neutral oil", "100 g White onion(s) , (1 small onion) quartered, plus extra cut into small dice for serving", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (5 small cloves) whole", "42 g Kosher salt , divided", "125 g Roma tomato(es) , (1 medium tomato) quartered", "2 g Cumin seeds , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 g Black peppercorns , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Mexican oregano , dried (2 teaspoons)", "1 g Mexican cinnamon , (1/2 stick)", "85 g Achiote paste , (aka annatto paste; see “Before we begin” note)", "90 g Orange juice , fresh (from 1 orange)", "255 g Water", "40 g Apple cider vinegar", "2 kg Pork butt , boneless, skinless, sliced lengthwise into 1/8-inch-thick steaks (see “Before we begin” note)", "Corn tortillas , homemade or store-bought, warmed, for serving , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving , as needed", "1 recipe Guacasalsa", "1 recipe Cebollitas (Charred Knob Onions) , for serving, optional", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Toast chiles", "Char pineapple", "Cook marinade", "Blend marinade", "Trim pork steaks", "Layer and marinate pork", "Freeze pork", "Portion pork and form skewers", "Cook pastor skewers", "Assemble tacos and serve"], "tips": ["Toast chiles, don’t burn ’em.", "If your butcher can’t slice pork butt steaks for you, do it yourself.", "Trim pork steaks for super-clean skewers.", "Partially freeze meat for clean slices.", "Have outdoor space? Grill the pastor instead!", "Save those pastor drippings."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tacos-al-pastor"}, {"id": 27, "t": "Quesabirria Tacos", "c": "Baking", "d": "Crispy tortillas wrapped around meltingly tender birria and gooey melted cheese, a quesabirria taco is essentially a leveled-up quesadilla, and it’s all kinds of delicious. Served with a cup of consomé for dipping, it’s no wonder this dish has gone viral over the past few years. The key to great quesabirria, of course, is starting with excellent birria and consomé—our recipes for Tijuana-Style Bee", "i": ["300 g Tijuana-Style Beef Birria , or", "300 g Jalisco-Style Goat Birria , (see “Before we begin” note)", "Consomé , from Tijuana-Style Beef Birria or Jalisco-Style Goat Birria, (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "150 g Chihuahua cheese , shredded", "150 g Low-moisture mozzarella , shredded", "6 Corn tortillas", "90 g Fat , reserved from Tijuana-Style Beef Birria or Jalisco-Style Goat Birria, divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "White onion(s) , cut into small dice, for serving , as needed", "Cilantro , cut into a chiffonade, for serving , as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed", "Salsas , of your choice, for serving , as needed", "Hot sauce , for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Temper birria and heat consomé", "Crisp up tacos", "Finish and serve"], "tips": ["Quesabirria: A menu staple, a social media sensation", "Flip it and reverse it for a crispy cheese quesabirria."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/quesabirria"}, {"id": 28, "t": "Classic Carnitas", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Carnitas is a classic of Mexican cuisine: confit pork cooked gently until meltingly tender, then fried until crispy and stuffed into warm tortillas and topped with a bright salsa to balance the richness of the meat. This version uses traditional technique, dialed in with precision. We confit the pork low and slow in lard, then jack the temperature of the fat up to crisp the meat to finish. In a no", "i": ["1.9 kg Pork butt , boneless, skinless, cut into 3-inch cubes (4.2 pounds)", "1 Baby back rib rack , cut into 3-rib sections (1.2 kg; 2.6 pounds)", "30 g Kosher salt", "2.6 kg Lard", "2 Orange(s) , halved", "1 Garlic , head, halved crosswise", "1 White onion(s) , halved, plus extra cut into small dice, for serving", "10 g Oregano , fresh sprigs", "3 Fresh bay leaves", "Corn tortillas , homemade or store-bought, warmed, for serving, optional , as needed", "Salsa , homemade or store-bought, for serving, optional , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving, optional , as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving, optional , as needed", "2.6 kg Lard 2 Orange(s) , halved 1 Garlic , head, halved crosswise 1 White onion(s) , halved 10 g Oregano , fresh sprigs 3 Fresh bay leaves"], "s": ["Season pork", "Choose your doneness", "Cook carnitas", "Crisp carnitas", "Assemble tacos and serve"], "tips": ["Not-so-classic carnitas", "Sweetening the pot"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/classic-carnitas"}, {"id": 29, "t": "Ensenada-Style Fish Tacos", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Take a trip to Ensenada, Mexico, with these super-crispy fried fish tacos. Battered strips of fish, swaddled in corn tortillas, anointed with a simple tomato salsa, shredded cabbage, and mayocrema. These fish tacos are all gas and no brakes. The key is in that batter. We use a beer batter, bolstering the malty notes of a crisp Mexican lager with chicken bouillon powder (MSG, baby!), oregano, honey", "i": ["400 g Rice flour", "345 g All-purpose flour , plus extra for dredging", "20 g Chicken bouillon powder , Knorr brand", "15 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "11 g Baking powder", "1 g Mexican oregano , dried", "345 g Vodka", "50 g Yellow mustard", "40 g Honey", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 medium cloves) finely grated", "550 g Beer , preferably Mexican lager", "680 g Cod , skinless fillets, cut into 4- by 3/4-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "300 g Tomatoes , cored and cut into small dice", "35 g White onion(s) , cut into small dice and rinsed under cold water", "15 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade", "10 g Lime juice , fresh (from 1 lime)", "5 g Serrano chile(s) , (1/2 chile) stemmed, seeded, and minced", "75 g Sour cream", "75 g Mayonnaise", "20 g Milk", "3 g Garlic powder", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "Corn tortillas , warmed, for serving , as needed", "Cabbage , shredded, for serving , as needed", "Hot sauce , for serving , as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Make batter", "Season fish", "Make pico de gallo", "Make mayocrema", "Fry fish", "Assemble tacos and serve"], "tips": ["No vodka? No problem!", "The origins of the Ensenada-style fish taco"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ensenada-style-fish-tacos"}, {"id": 30, "t": "Tijuana-Style Beef Birria", "c": "Baking", "d": "You’d be hard-pressed to find a dish that’s blown up in popularity quite like birria in the past few years. Tacos, pizza, ramen—we can pickle birria that! And if you’ve had birria, odds are that you’ve enjoyed this beefy braised version from Northern Mexico, rather than the OG goat birria from Jalisco. Let’s get this out of the way: Beef birria is legit, it’s delicious, and, for most folks, it’s m", "i": ["2.8 kg Beef short ribs , boneless, cut into 7- by 5- by 2-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "35 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "80 g Lard , divided", "420 g White onion(s) , (1 large onion) cut into large dice", "80 g Garlic clove(s) , (16 medium cloves)", "55 g Ancho chile(s) , stemmed and seeded, torn into 1-inch pieces", "35 g Guajillo chile(s) , stemmed and seeded, torn into 1-inch pieces", "10 g Cascabel chile(s) , stemmed and seeded, torn into 1-inch pieces", "4 g Mexican oregano , dried (2 tablespoons)", "3 g Cumin seeds , whole (1 teaspoon)", "3 g Coriander seeds , whole (2 teaspoons)", "3 g Allspice , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Thyme , dried (2 teaspoons)", "6 g Mexican cinnamon , whole sticks", "1.2 kg Roma tomato(es) , quartered", "2.7 kg Beef Stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "35 g Distilled vinegar", "5 g Chicken bouillon powder , Knorr brand", "3 Bay leaf , fresh", "Corn tortillas , warmed, for serving , as needed", "Cilantro , leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving , as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed", "Hot sauce , for serving , as needed", "Salsa , of your choice, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Dry-brine beef overnight", "Sear short ribs", "Cook aromatics for consomé", "Simmer consomé", "Blend consomé", "Cook birria", "Finish birria and consomé", "Serve or make quesabirria"], "tips": ["Is it really birria if it’s made from beef?", "Birria is all about the consomé."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-birria"}, {"id": 31, "t": "Plant-Based, 100% Vegetable Taco “Meat”", "c": "Baking", "d": "Meatless Monday meets Taco Tuesday in this faux-meat miracle made entirely of vegetables. Don’t leave your plant-based friends nibbling on crudité or lonely tortillas without any fillings! This is a surprisingly meaty main made using an unexpected technique. The secret to this recipe is dehydration. Desiccating the vegetables unlocks a texture similar to the minced ground beef typically used for t", "i": ["1 recipe Three-Ingredient Plant-Based Ground “Meat”", "160 g Red onion(s) , small dice (about half an onion)", "80 g Canola oil , or any other neutral oil (divided)", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , minced or chopped", "60 g Poblano pepper(s) , small dice (about half a pepper)", "25 g Jalapeño(s) , seeded, small dice", "1 Taco seasoning , any brand", "8 g Kosher salt", "20 g Liquid aminos , optional but recommended", "250 g Water , as needed"], "s": ["Make the “meat” base", "Toast the onion", "Add garlic and peppers", "Add the dried vegetables", "Season the “meat”", "It’s totally taco time", "Plant-based but never boring"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/plant-based-taco-meat"}, {"id": 32, "t": "Butter Chicken (Murgh Makhani)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Butter chicken, also known as murgh makhani, is the most delicious use of leftover chicken in history. It was originally devised as a way to use up leftover tandoori chicken—yogurt-marinated chicken roasted in the super-hot cylindrical ovens known as tandoors—at the original location of Moti Mahal restaurant in what is now Old Delhi. It has since become a global phenomenon and a staple of Indian r", "i": ["900 g Chicken thighs , boneless, skinless (6 to 8 thighs)", "70 g Garlic clove(s) , (14 medium cloves) grated, divided", "68 g Fresh ginger root , (4-inch piece) peeled and grated, divided", "40 g Yogurt , plain, whole-milk", "15 g Neutral oil", "21 g Kashmiri chili powder , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Kosher salt , divided", "10 g Lime juice , fresh (from 1/2 lime)", "3 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "75 g Ghee , or clarified butter, homemade or store-bought, melted, divided", "1 g Green cardamom , whole (5 pods)", "1 g Bay leaf , dried (4 leaves)", "3 g Cinnamon stick(s) , (one 2-inch stick)", "200 g Red onion(s) , (1 medium onion) thinly sliced", "5 g Coriander seeds , ground (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "5 g Cumin seeds , ground (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "6 g Fenugreek leaves , dried, divided", "3 g Turmeric root powder , (1 teaspoon)", "600 g Fire-roasted canned tomatoes , crushed or blended (see “Before we begin” note)", "220 g Water", "265 g Heavy cream , divided", "15 g Unsalted butter , cold", "Basmati rice , cooked, for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Cut up chicken thighs", "Marinate chicken", "Broil chicken", "Cook aromatics", "Add spices and tomatoes", "Blend sauce", "Add broiled chicken and finish sauce", "Make tadka and garnish", "Serve"], "tips": ["Add sugar to adjust the tanginess of the sauce.", "Tadka: A finishing technique that boosts flavor, aroma, and texture."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/butter-chicken-murgh-makhani"}, {"id": 33, "t": "Chana Masala", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Chana masala, also called chole, is a spicy, tangy chickpea curry consisting of plump chickpeas swimming in a spiced, tomato-based sauce. A staple of Punjabi cuisine, the exact ingredients used in the preparation can vary, and the consistency of the curry—from soupy and thin to so thick it’s almost dry—depends on the tastes of the cook. This version, which draws inspiration from Amritsari Chole, b", "i": ["410 g Chickpeas , dried", "18 g Cumin seeds , whole, divided", "9 g Kashmiri chilies , dried, whole, divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "8 g Pomegranate seeds , dried, whole, divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Cinnamon stick(s) , (one 2-inch stick)", "3 g Black cardamom , whole (2 pods; see “Before we begin” note)", "6 g Black tea , loose leaf (2 tea bags; see “Before we begin” note)", "0.2 g Cloves , whole (4 cloves)", "1 g Bay leaf , dried (4 leaves)", "1 g Green cardamom , whole (5 pods)", "60 g Ghee , or clarified butter, homemade or store-bought, melted, divided", "4 g Ajwain seeds , whole (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "370 g Red onion(s) , (2 medium onions) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "5 g Thai green chile(s) , (4 chiles) fresh, 2 chiles thinly sliced and 2 chiles slit, divided", "20 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 medium cloves) grated", "20 g Kosher salt , divided", "15 g Coriander seeds , ground", "10 g Dried mango powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Turmeric root powder , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "4 g Fenugreek leaves , dried (3 tablespoons; see “Before we begin” note)", "425 g Roma tomato(es) , (3 tomatoes), blended smooth", "750 g Water", "20 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, finely chopped, divided", "115 g Yogurt , plain, whole-milk, optional, plus extra for serving", "Basmati rice , cooked, for serving, optional , as needed", "20 g Fresh ginger root , peeled and grated"], "s": ["Soak chickpeas", "Grind spices and make spice sachet", "Cook aromatics", "Add spices and tomatoes", "Add chickpeas and spice sachet", "Pressure cook chickpeas", "Mash portion of chickpeas", "Add cilantro and adjust seasoning", "Garnish with fresh herbs and aromatics", "Make tadka", "Serve"], "tips": ["No pressure cooker? No problem.", "Mash the chickpeas for a thicker sauce.", "Add yogurt for a milder chana masala (optional).", "Tadka: A finishing technique that boosts flavor, aroma, and texture."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chana-masala"}, {"id": 34, "t": "Ultra-Flaky Paratha", "c": "Baking", "d": "Paratha is one of the most delicious laminated breads in the world—crispy, flaky, buttery, and tender, all at the same time. The name is derived from the Sanskrit words for “layers” (“parat”) and “flour” (“atta”), and those layers consists of toasty ghee and a dough made from atta, or stone-ground whole wheat flour, which gives the flatbread its characteristic flavor. They’re delicious all on thei", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/paratha"}, {"id": 35, "t": "Aloo Paratha", "c": "Baking", "d": "Aloo paratha—potato-stuffed whole wheat flatbread—is a beloved dish across the Indian subcontinent. And what’s not to love? Thin layers of buttery fried bread sandwiching a filling of spiced (and spicy!) mashed potatoes. It’s a carb-on-carb celebration! Paratha dough can be stuffed with all kinds of things, not just mashed potatoes—radish (mooli paratha), cheese (paneer paratha), and cauliflower (", "i": ["512 g Atta , plus extra for dusting (see “Before we begin” note)", "12 g Kosher salt , divided", "330 g Water , room temperature", "30 g Neutral oil", "700 g Russet potato(es) , (2 medium potatoes), peeled, cut into 1-inch-thick pieces", "112 g Feta cheese , crumbled", "19 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, finely chopped", "5 g Thai green chile(s) , (1 chile) stemmed and seeded, minced", "2 g Ajwain seeds , whole (1/2 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "80 g Ghee , or clarified butter, homemade or store-bought, room temperature (see “Before we begin” note)", "390 g Whole wheat flour , stone-ground, such as Bob’s Red Mill", "133 g “00” flour", "Yogurt , for serving, optional , as needed - Achar , for serving, optional , as needed - Radishes , quartered, optional , as needed", "Achar , for serving, optional , as needed", "Radishes , quartered, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Paratha three ways", "Mix dough and rest", "Cook potatoes", "Pass potatoes", "Make potato filling", "Divide and portion dough", "Roll and shape the dough", "Roll out aloo paratha", "Dry-fry aloo paratha", "Fry aloo paratha", "Serve"], "tips": ["No atta? No problem! Make an alternative flour blend.", "No stand mixer? No problem!", "Rolling dough seam-side up prevents leakage.", "Par-cooking and freezing paratha", "How to serve paratha"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/aloo-paratha"}, {"id": 36, "t": "No-Nonsense Naan", "c": "Baking", "d": "Naan is the stuff carb dreams are made of. A soft, enriched dough, mildly salty and slightly charred, flash-cooked for big bubbles with a crispy exterior and pillowy insides, it’s the most indulgent utensil we’ve ever encountered. Originating in India and Pakistan, naan takes a richer turn from other flatbreads. We leaned into the tangy richness of yogurt to enrich ours, which complements a wide v", "i": ["225 g Plain Greek-style full-fat yogurt", "225 g Water", "14 g Sugar", "14 g Active dry yeast", "550 g Bread flour", "8 g Salt", "Neutral oil, as needed", "Garnishes , such as butter, garlic, turmeric root, fresh herbs (such as curry leaves or cilantro), optional , as needed"], "s": ["Heat yogurt and water, add to sugar and yeast", "Mix the dough", "Rest the dough", "Portion the dough", "Roll into balls; rest again", "Flatten each piece; prep your chosen cooking method", "Option 1: Stovetop", "Option 2: Oven", "Option 3: Grill", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/no-nonsense-naan"}, {"id": 37, "t": "Precision Clarified Butter", "c": "Baking", "d": "Clarified butter is a staple of kitchens all over the world, prized for its rich flavor and relatively high smoke point. Unlike whole butter, clarified butter is cooked until the fat, milk solids, and water separate and the water is boiled away, leaving you with milk solids and fat. Once strained of milk solids, clarified butter can be heated to much higher temperatures than whole butter can: The ", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 455 g Unsalted butter , cut into 1-inch cubes", "455 g Unsalted butter , cut into 1-inch cubes"], "s": ["Clarify butter", "Continue cooking to make ghee (optional)", "Continue cooking to make brown butter (optional)", "Strain butter"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/clarified-butter-ghee"}, {"id": 38, "t": "Precision Buttermilk Pancakes", "c": "Baking", "d": "A stack of beautifully browned, fluffy, and fat flapjacks is iconic. A mound of pale, dense pancakes ... not so much. The key to good pancakes isn’t just the right formula or the right technique, it’s both. This is why there’s that old adage about the first pancake never turning out right—typically, you need a tester or two to dial in the pan temperature just right. But with precise temperature co", "i": ["100 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs)", "250 g Buttermilk , full-fat (see “Before we begin” note)", "180 g All-purpose flour", "35 g Sugar", "25 g Buttermilk powder , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Baking powder", "5 g Kosher salt , (​1 1/4 teaspoons)", "70 g Unsalted butter , melted, plus extra for cooking and serving (see “Before we begin” note)", "Maple syrup , optional, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Temper eggs and buttermilk", "Make batter", "Cook pancakes", "Top and serve"], "tips": ["Tempering wet ingredients for a better batter.", "Dialing in pan temperature for pancakes.", "Adding mix-ins? Do it while the pancakes cook."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/buttermilk-pancakes"}, {"id": 39, "t": "Ultra-Fluffy Japanese Pancakes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Sometimes you want pancakes for breakfast, and nothing but a stack of buttermilk pancakes will do. Other times, you want those ultra-fluffy, souffléd, jiggly Japanese-style pancakes you’ve seen on your IG feed. This recipe is for those other times. Unlike “normal” pancakes, this towering masterpiece of fluff isn’t straightforward; you aren’t just mixing wet into dry and puddling the batter in a pa", "i": ["100 g Egg white(s) , (from 3 large eggs)", "0.5 g Cream of tartar , (1/8 teaspoon)", "45 g Egg yolk(s) , (3 large yolks)", "52 g Buttermilk , full-fat", "3 g Vanilla extract , (1/2 teaspoon)", "50 g All-purpose flour", "10 g Buttermilk powder , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 g Baking powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "45 g Granulated sugar", "Water , for steaming , as needed", "Butter , for cooking and serving , as needed", "Maple syrup , for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Temper eggs and buttermilk", "Make egg yolk base", "Make meringue", "Fold meringue into batter", "Choose your pancake size", "Cook pancakes", "Serve immediately and cook remaining batter"], "tips": ["Tempering wet ingredients for a better batter.", "Flipping your way to success."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fluffy-japanese-pancakes"}, {"id": 40, "t": "Buttermilk Crêpes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Imagine a tender, paper-thin crêpe. Now imagine it with tons of flavor. And what you get is ... buttermilk crêpes! Sitting right in the middle between the blank canvas of regular sweet crêpes and earthy buckwheat galettes, these crêpes have a pronounced tang of buttermilk that adds an extra bit of oomph that complements whatever you want to serve them with. Making crêpes is a technical challenge m", "i": ["200 g Egg(s) , (4 large eggs)", "400 g Buttermilk , low-fat (see “Before we begin” note)", "180 g All-purpose flour", "35 g Granulated sugar", "25 g Buttermilk powder , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "40 g Unsalted butter , melted, plus extra as needed for cooking", "Water, as needed", "1 Orange", "10 g Maple syrup"], "s": ["Temper eggs and buttermilk", "Make crêpe batter and rest", "Adjust batter consistency", "Choose level of browning", "Cook crêpes", "Jazz up crêpes with brown butter and orange (optional)", "Serve and enjoy"], "tips": ["Tempering wet ingredients for a better batter.", "Using a râteau"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/buttermilk-crepes"}, {"id": 41, "t": "Buttermilk Pancakes: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "Flapjacks, slapjacks, hotcakes, silver dollars, crêpes, blini ... whatever you call ’em, pancakes are delicious. A pancake is a deceptively simple preparation: Mix flour with some kind of liquid and leavening agent and puddle the mixture into a greased pan, and you’ll get a light cake-like foam that serves as a perfect canvas for everything from maple syrup and honey to caviar and sour cream. But,", "i": [], "s": ["The Criteria", "The Function of Different Pancake Batter Ingredients", "Buttermilk Crêpes", "Leavened Crêpes", "Thin Buttermilk Pancakes", "Classic Buttermilk Pancakes", "Fluffy Buttermilk Pancakes", "Soufflé Pancakes", "Ultra-Fluffy Japanese Pancakes", "We love our parametrics!"], "tips": ["Comparison of Pan Temperatures", "To Grease or Not to Grease? That Is the Question."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/buttermilk-pancake-parametric"}, {"id": 43, "t": "Grant’s Protein Powered Pancakes—From a Box!", "c": "Baking", "d": "Grant loves pancakes, but he doesn’t love that they’re usually empty carbs. The texture and flavor is on point but, honestly, we can do better. Grant shows you how in the video below. These pancakes are easy to whip up and are loaded with energy stabilizing protein. Tender and delicious, they’re nutritious and filling and the perfect way to power up your day. The secrets are protein powder—any kin", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Store-bought pancake mix, as needed - Protein powder , your choice; 1 scoop per 2 to 4 servings , as needed - Milk , your choice (dairy or vegan) , as needed - Cottage cheese, as needed", "Store-bought pancake mix, as needed - Protein powder , your choice; 1 scoop per 2 to 4 servings , as needed - Milk , your choice (dairy or vegan) , as needed - Cottage cheese, as needed", "Protein powder , your choice; 1 scoop per 2 to 4 servings , as needed", "Milk , your choice (dairy or vegan) , as needed", "Cottage cheese, as needed"], "s": ["Grant powers up store-bought pancake mix with an easy protein-heavy cooking hack", "Gather your goodies", "Preheat your pan or griddle", "Mix wet ingredients", "Mix dry ingredients", "Cook", "Garnish and eat", "Pancake perfection", "A brunch of epic proportions"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grants-tip-trick-to-make-a-power-pancake-in-under-a-minute"}, {"id": 44, "t": "Nick’s Molten Chocolate Lava Pancake", "c": "Baking", "d": "When you wake up with a serious sweet tooth or need a stunning brunch dish that’ll blow your guests’ minds, chef Nicholas Gavin’s ultra-indulgent pancake is here to save the day and bring down the house—in a good way. Inspired by molten lava cakes and chocolate soufflés, Nick keeps it sweet but simple, so you’re not starting the day with an ultra-involved recipe and tons of dirty dishes. Nick show", "i": ["175 g All-purpose flour", "45 g Cocoa powder", "5 g Kosher salt", "12 g Baking powder", "6 g Baking soda", "60 g Sugar", "2 Egg(s) , whole", "240 g Bulgarian buttermilk", "60 g Vegetable oil", "Hershey’s milk chocolate , 1 to 2 bars (for the molten center) , as needed", "Honey, as needed", "Butter , whipped , as needed", "Orange zest, as needed"], "s": ["Watch Nick make chocolate magic", "Preheat your pan or griddle", "Mix dry ingredients", "Mix wet ingredients", "Combine", "Cook", "Garnish it up and chow down", "Pancake perfection", "A brunch of epic proportions"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chocolate-lava-pancake-nicky-g-version"}, {"id": 45, "t": "Kyl’s Crispy Corn Pancake", "c": "Baking", "d": "Over the past few years, chef Kyl Haselbauer has become our resident expert on heirloom corn. While researching nixtamalization and developing the blender method to make fresh masa, he dove deep into tortillas, tamales, and other corn-centric foods like cornbread and Johnny cakes. Kyl demonstrates his corn cake recipe in the video below. Heirloom corn varieties are unrivaled in flavor, texture, an", "i": ["220 g Dried corn (kernels) , finely ground into flour using blender", "125 g Sugar", "14 g Baking powder", "7 g Kosher salt", "108 g Egg(s) , whole", "200 g Milk , whole", "132 g Butter , unsalted, melted"], "s": ["See Kyl griddle and flip", "Preheat your pan or griddle", "Mix dry ingredients", "Mix wet ingredients", "Combine dry and wet", "Add melted butter", "Cook them cakes", "Eat ’em up", "Pancake perfection", "A brunch of epic proportions"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/kyl-s-crispy-corn-pancake"}, {"id": 46, "t": "Matthew’s Plant-Based and Gluten-Free Pancakes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Tender, soft, and quick to put together, this is chef Matthew Woolen’s go-to recipe when he’s making pancakes at home. Lightly spiced, they’re loaded with hearty fiber, healthy fats, and some plant-based protein. Watch the video below to see how he makes these pancakes from start to finish. Since you don’t need gluten to develop in a quick batter for pancakes, it’s easier to swap in gluten-free fl", "i": ["110 g Rolled oats", "30 g Almond flour", "10 g Flaxseed meal", "6 g Baking powder", "4 g Kosher salt", "3 g Pumpkin pie spice", "130 g Soy milk", "65 g Maple syrup , plus extra to serve", "5 g Vanilla extract", "25 g Coconut oil (refined) , melted, plus extra to serve", "Berries , or other fruit, for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Watch Matt make pancakes", "Preheat your pan or griddle", "Combine dry ingredients", "Mix wet ingredients", "Combine wet and dry", "Add coconut oil", "Griddle", "Serve it", "Pancake perfection", "You won’t believe these are vegan"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/5-ways-to-pancake-plant-based-gluten-free"}, {"id": 47, "t": "Ultimate Chicken Bouillon Cubes", "c": "Meat", "d": "", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-bouillon-cubes"}, {"id": 49, "t": "Ultimate Pork Bouillon Cubes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pork stock isn’t as commonly used in Western kitchens as beef, veal, or chicken stock, which is a shame, because it’s just as delicious and versatile. This recipe produces cubes of super flavorful and gelatinous reduced pork stock, which can be used to make pan sauces for chops and roasts, fragrant soups, and even a near-instant ramen that’s just as good as bowls prepared at a shop. The process fo", "i": ["28 g Canola oil", "900 g Ground pork", "2 kg Water", "550 g Yellow onion(s) , (2 large onions) cut into 1-inch pieces", "260 g Carrot(s) , (2 large carrots) peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces", "115 g Celery , (2 ribs) cut into 1-inch pieces", "24 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 large cloves) whole, unpeeled", "5 g Black peppercorns , whole", "40 g Knox gelatin", "30 g Kosher salt", "10 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG)"], "s": ["Cook meat", "Pressure cook stock", "Season and reduce stock", "Portion and freeze cubes"], "tips": ["No pressure cooker? No problem"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pork-bouillon-cubes"}, {"id": 50, "t": "New Bay Seasoning Blend", "c": "Meat", "d": "You could sit and watch the tide roll away on the dock of Old Bay, or set sail for new and flavorful horizons. New Bay is here to assist with your every seasoning whim. When it comes to seasoning seafood, Old Bay—in its bright yellow tin—has been the go-to for over 75 years. We use it. We love it. We wanted to pay homage to this old-fashioned classic using 21st century techniques. We turned to our", "i": ["200 g Celery , stalk", "200 g Scallion(s)", "8 g Garlic , cloves", "40 g Parsley , Italian", "10 g Canola oil", "3 g Kosher salt", "15 g Mustard powder , Colman’s", "33 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce)", "2 g Cinnamon , ground", "5 g White pepper", "15 g Black pepper", "1 g Bay leaf", "10 g Fennel seeds", "15 g Brown sugar"], "s": ["Preheat the oven", "Roast then dehydrate the vegetables and herbs", "Grind the spices", "Grind the dehydrated veg and mix it up", "Add that New Bay to anything"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/new-bay-seasoning"}, {"id": 51, "t": "Ultimate Beef Bouillon Cubes", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe packs all the flavor of a well-made beef stock rich with gelatin into a 1-inch cube that’s ready at a moment’s notice to be used to make soups, stews, sipping broths, or sauces. These cubes are our new pantry secret weapon, and they blow away every other prepared or instant beef stock product at the store. They’ve got actual beefy flavor, from real beef (not autolyzed yeast extract com", "i": ["28 g Canola oil", "900 g Ground beef , 10% fat", "2 kg Water", "550 g Yellow onion(s) , (2 large onions) cut into 1-inch pieces", "260 g Carrot(s) , (2 large carrots) peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces", "115 g Celery , (2 ribs) cut into 1-inch pieces", "24 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 large cloves) whole, unpeeled", "5 g Black peppercorns , whole", "40 g Knox gelatin", "30 g Kosher salt", "10 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG)"], "s": ["Cook meat", "Pressure cook stock", "Season and reduce stock", "Portion and freeze cubes"], "tips": ["No pressure cooker? No problem"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-bouillon-cubes"}, {"id": 52, "t": "The Ultimate Umami Seasoning Powder", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Say hello to your new secret ingredient. From meats to broths to veggies, this umami-rich seasoning is an excellent upgrade from plain ol’ salt that’s guaranteed to leave your guests asking, “What is this?!” Cremini mushrooms, loaded with glutamic acid, are the heroes of this powdery blend. Combined with aromatics, the mushrooms are lightly roasted and dehydrated to concentrate the umami and then ", "i": ["450 g Cremini mushrooms", "15 g Garlic clove(s)", "60 g Shallot(s)", "15 g Serrano pepper", "20 g Chives", "20 g Worcestershire sauce", "15 g Canola oil", "2 g Nutritional yeast", "5 g Himalayan salt , optional"], "s": ["Gather your goods", "Preheat the oven", "Prepare the mushrooms", "Prepare the aromatics", "Marry the mix", "Get ’em roasty-toasty", "Dehydrate", "Grind into a powder and add salt", "Package it and enjoy!", "Seriously, you can sprinkle this on anything"], "tips": ["So many foods have MSG. Why did only creminis make the cut?", "Level up that umami"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/umami-mushroom-bomb-that-you-can-drop-on-anything"}, {"id": 53, "t": "Ultimate Turkey Bouillon Cubes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Turkey stock’s never around when you need it. Think about it: You’re figuring out the annual Thanksgiving dinner prep, you’re filling out spreadsheets, diagramming your oven Tetris strategy, and you’re thinking about gravy. All the recipes are calling for turkey stock but saying chicken stock is “fine.” Well, of course it’s fine! Who has turkey stock lying around before they break down and cook a ", "i": ["28 g Canola oil", "910 g Turkey , ground, preferably dark meat (turkey thighs)", "2 kg Water", "550 g Yellow onion(s) , (2 large onions) cut into 1-inch pieces", "260 g Carrot(s) , (2 large carrots) peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces", "115 g Celery , (2 ribs) cut into 1-inch pieces", "25 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 large cloves) whole, unpeeled", "5 g Black peppercorns , whole", "40 g Knox gelatin", "30 g Kosher salt", "10 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG)"], "s": ["Cook meat", "Pressure cook stock", "Season and reduce stock", "Portion and freeze cubes"], "tips": ["No pressure cooker? No problem."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-turkey-bouillon-cubes"}, {"id": 54, "t": "Creole Spice Blend", "c": "Meat", "d": "This Creole spice is a blend of three different onions, garlic, herbs, toasted chiles, spices, and an extra kick of pepper for good measure! Spice up anything you want to eat: fish; fried chicken; kale tacos—we have been eating tacos with vegetables roasted with this spice blend for our family meal, again and again. You can use this blend as a template and adjust it as you wish—experiment with you", "i": ["100 g Red onion(s) , half onion", "100 g Sweet onion(s) , half onion", "100 g Green onion(s)", "115 g Garlic , one head, sliced", "20 g Thyme , fresh", "15 g Oregano , fresh", "13 g Chiles de árbol , whole", "60 g Red chiles , whole, dried", "3 g Bay leaf", "15 g Coriander seeds", "12 g Cumin seeds", "30 g Black peppercorns", "10 g White pepper", "70 g Paprika , Hungarian", "80 g Salt , kosher"], "s": ["Dehydrate the alliums and herbs", "Toast the chiles and seed them", "Toast the spices", "Mix the salt and paprika", "Grind the alliums, chiles, and spices together", "Mix together"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/creole-spice-blend"}, {"id": 55, "t": "Grilled Pizza", "c": "Baking", "d": "With a spotty charred surface, a tender-crisp crust that cooks in minutes, and simple prep, grilled pizza is one of the best and easiest ways to prepare pizza for a few people or a crowd. While some may contend that grilled pizza is nothing more than a flatbread with toppings (the toppings are applied only after the topside is cooked), we can all agree that it should be delicious. What makes it wo", "i": ["300 g All-purpose flour , plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "7.5 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "6 g Sugar", "1.5 g Instant dry yeast , (scant 1/2 teaspoon)", "186 g Water", "122 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided, plus extra as needed", "8 Garlic clove(s)", "800 g Whole canned tomatoes , (28-ounce can)", "3 Scallion(s)", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "450 g Fontina cheese , or low-moisture mozzarella, shredded, divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "150 g Pecorino Romano , or Parmigiano-Reggiano, finely grated, divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "Basil , fresh leaves, thinly sliced or torn , as needed", "110 g Extra-virgin olive oil 8 Garlic clove(s)"], "s": ["Mix dough", "Knead dough", "Bulk ferment dough", "Portion and proof dough", "Make garlic oil", "Make sauce", "Slice scallions", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Roll out and par-grill dough", "Top pizza and finish", "Slice, serve, repeat"], "tips": ["Grilled pizza variations", "Heat transfer and grilled pizza"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-pizza"}, {"id": 56, "t": "Tavern-Style Pizza", "c": "Baking", "d": "A lot of pizza makers talk about their preferred style as an art form or a Platonic ideal. Chicago’s tavern-style pizza isn’t that. It’s the logical result of Chicago bartenders who wanted to serve up pizza so people would drink more beer, using kitchens that were likely smaller and worse-equipped than the one in your home. No one making tavern-style pizza set out to create a “style.” That means t", "i": ["363 g Bread flour , or high-gluten flour, unbleached; plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "13 g Fine cornmeal", "12 g Sugar , divided", "10 g Kosher salt , divided", "2 g Instant dry yeast , (1/2 teaspoon)", "185 g Water , cold", "45 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided, plus extra as needed", "15 g Unsalted butter", "85 g Tomato paste", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 small cloves) whole", "400 g Whole canned tomatoes , (14-ounce can)", "15 g Fish sauce", "7.5 g Marmite", "15 g Red wine vinegar , plus extra as needed", "1 g Basil , dried (1 teaspoon)", "0.7 g Oregano , dried (1 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Marjoram , dried (1 teaspoon)", "112 g Parmigiano-Reggiano , finely grated, divided", "340 g Low-moisture mozzarella , whole milk, shredded, divided", "368 g Italian sausage , casing removed, divided", "226 g Giardinieria , homemade or store-bought, drained, divided"], "s": ["Tavern timeline", "Mix dough", "Knead dough, divide, and rest", "Cold-proof dough", "Cook tomato sauce", "Add herbs and blend sauce", "Roll out and dock dough", "Cure dough overnight", "Heat oven and baking surface", "Top and bake pizzas", "Slice pizza and serve"], "tips": ["Controlled overproofing, easier rolling", "Rolling, docking, and curing", "Tavern topping geometry and baking", "The party cut"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tavern-style-pizza"}, {"id": 57, "t": "New England–Style Greek Pizza", "c": "Baking", "d": "Greek pizza is a hyper-local style of pan pizza made throughout New England—especially in Massachusetts and New Hampshire—in shops owned by Greek immigrants, which for some reason often have “House of Pizza” in their names. There aren’t a lot of great Greek pizza shops, but that doesn’t mean Greek pizza can’t be great. When done right, Greek pies boast a tender and airy crumb, a puffy rim, and a c", "i": ["495 g Bread flour , unbleached", "16 g Sugar , divided, plus extra as needed", "3 g Instant dry yeast , (3/4 teaspoon)", "305 g Milk , (any fat percentage) cold", "106 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided", "13 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "4 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 small clove) minced", "2 g Anchovies , (1 fillet) mashed into a paste with fork, optional", "2 g Oregano , dried (2 1/2 teaspoons), divided", "0.1 g Red pepper flakes , (1/8 teaspoon)", "600 g Whole canned tomatoes , (from one 28-ounce can), blended", "10 g Coconut oil (refined) , or vegetable shortening", "120 g Sharp white cheddar cheese , coarsely grated, divided", "120 g Low-moisture mozzarella , coarsely grated, divided"], "s": ["Mix dough and autolyse", "Knead dough", "Cold-proof dough", "Make sauce", "Pan up and proof dough", "Heat oven and baking surface", "Top pizzas", "Bake pizzas", "Cool slightly, slice, and serve"], "tips": ["Two types of oil? In this economy?", "Wait, wait, don’t slice me"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/new-england-style-greek-pizza"}, {"id": 58, "t": "Sfincione (Sicilian Pizza)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Sfincione is one of the classic, “true” Sicilian pizzas, although it’s distinct from the Sicilian American rectangular pies we’re used to in the U.S. Like the American version of Sicilian pizza, most sfincione pizzas are thick-crusted pan pizzas, cut into squares. But instead of getting topped with a classic red sauce and mozzarella cheese, they’re topped with an onion-heavy, slightly sweet tomato", "i": ["330 g All-purpose flour , unbleached (see “Before we begin” note)", "140 g Semolina flour", "9 g Sugar", "2 g Instant dry yeast , (1/2 teaspoon)", "340 g Water , 70 °F / 21 °C, divided", "128 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided, plus extra as needed", "11 g Kosher salt , divided", "58 g Anchovies , (10 to 14 fillets), divided", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 medium cloves) minced", "1.9 g Oregano , dried (2 1/4 teaspoons), divided", "1.9 g Red pepper flakes , (1 1/4 teaspoons), divided", "170 g Yellow onion(s) , (1/2 large onion) coarsely grated", "400 g Whole canned tomatoes , (14-ounce can), blended (see “Before we begin” note)", "85 g Panko breadcrumbs , or homemade breadcrumbs (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Pecorino Romano , finely grated (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Rosemary , fresh leaves, minced (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves, minced (1 teaspoon)", "10 g Coconut oil (refined) , or vegetable shortening", "226 g Caciocavallo , or provolone, grated", "9 g Kosher salt - Extra-virgin olive oil, as needed"], "s": ["Mix dough and autolyse", "Knead dough", "Bulk ferment in fridge", "Make sauce", "Mix breadcrumb topping", "Stretch dough and transfer to pan", "Heat oven and baking surface", "Top and bake pizza", "Cool slightly, slice, and serve"], "tips": ["Two types of oil? In this economy?", "Wait, wait, don’t slice me"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sfincione-palermitano"}, {"id": 59, "t": "Sicilian Pizza", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "In Sicily, pizza can take on a variety of forms, but in the U.S., “Sicilian” pizza usually means a thick-crust, rectangular pan pizza, topped with red sauce and cheese, and cut into squares. Most joints repurpose the same dough and toppings they use on their round pies, but they up the weight of the dough and let it proof a second time after it’s been panned to yield a tall, airy crumb. This recip", "i": ["330 g All-purpose flour , unbleached (see “Before we begin” note)", "140 g Semolina flour", "17 g Sugar , divided, plus extra as needed", "2 g Instant dry yeast , (1/2 teaspoon)", "280 g Water , 70 °F / 21 °C", "72 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided, plus extra as needed", "15 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "8 g Anchovies , (2 fillets) mashed into a paste with a fork, optional", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) minced", "1 g Oregano , dried (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "0.1 g Red pepper flakes , (1/8 teaspoon)", "800 g Whole canned tomatoes , (28-ounce can), blended (see “Before we begin” note)", "170 g Yellow onion(s) , (1/2 large onion), peeled, root end trimmed", "10 g Coconut oil (refined) , or vegetable shortening", "30 g Parmigiano-Reggiano , or Pecorino Romano, finely grated (see “Before we begin” note)", "226 g Provolone , or low-moisture mozzarella, coarsely grated (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Mix dough and autolyse", "Knead dough and rest", "Bulk ferment in fridge", "Make sauce", "Pan up dough and final proof", "Heat oven and baking surface", "Top and bake pizza", "Cool slightly, slice, and serve"], "tips": ["Two types of oil? In this economy?", "Wait, wait, don’t slice me"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sicilian-pan-pizza"}, {"id": 60, "t": "School Cafeteria Pizza", "c": "Baking", "d": "A fellow pizza geek once told me that school pizza is the best because it both sucks and is awesome at the same time. I think about that a lot. We pizza types have the bad habit of trying to “redeem” the perfectly good food of our youth. This recipe is no such thing. This recipe is from the United States Department of Agriculture’s 1988 Quantity Recipes for School Food Service, and all we’ve done ", "i": ["300 g All-purpose flour", "6 g Instant dry yeast", "50 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "24 g Sugar", "13 g Cornmeal", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "342 g Water", "5 g Vegetable oil , or extra-virgin olive oil (1 teaspoon)", "10 g Coconut oil (refined) , or vegetable shortening", "200 g Tomato sauce , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "200 g Low-moisture mozzarella , whole milk, shredded", "45 g Pepperoni , optional", "Parmesan , (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed"], "s": ["Mix dough", "Prepare sheet pan", "Transfer dough to pan and rest", "Preheat oven", "Parbake dough", "Top pizza and bake", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Using solid fat to grease the pan"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sheet-pan-school-pizza"}, {"id": 61, "t": "Grilled and Butter-Rested Ribeye Steak", "c": "Baking", "d": "The ribeye is one of the most desirable “trophy” steak cuts, with its ample amount of intramuscular fat and two tender and beefy muscle groups, the longissimus dorsi (the “eye” of the ribeye) and the spinalis dorsi (the “ribeye cap”). Since it’s such a rich cut, it tastes amazing when given a nice char on the grill. However, its fattiness makes grilling tough—all that fat causes flare-ups as it re", "i": ["340 g Unsalted butter , cut into 1-inch cubes", "2 Ribeye steak(s) , boneless, 1 1/2–2 inches thick (455–575 g; 1–1 1/4 pounds each)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "4 Rosemary , fresh sprigs", "2 Bay leaf , fresh, optional", "1 Lemon , quartered", "Flake sea salt , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Ribeye at a glance", "Ribeye butchery", "Selecting the best ribeye in the butcher case", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Melt butter", "Sear ribeyes on hot side", "Finish steaks in warm butter on cool side", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["A larger cool zone", "How to manage flare-ups (and get rid of soot).", "Keeping the steaks warm"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-butter-rested-ribeye"}, {"id": 62, "t": "24-Layer Lasagna", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Recently, Grant shared a story about his favorite lasagna, which he makes with fresh pasta, béchamel, ground cheese, fresh tomato sauce, and a spinach-basil blend. Then, he sears slices of it for crunchy, oozy lasagna. (Sometimes he eats lasagna for breakfast this way.) After reading the email, you wanted us to make this lasagna recipe for you. We listened to you. Get ready to make lasagna. Grant ", "i": ["2 recipes Fresh Sheet Pasta", "750 g Fresh spinach , stems removed", "60 g Basil , stems removed", "75 g Butter , unsalted", "75 g All-purpose flour", "675 g Milk , whole", "675 g Cream", "10 g Garlic , cloves", "20 g Fennel seeds", "10 g Kosher salt", "4 g Chile flakes", "75 g Olive oil", "800 g Tomato(es) , canned", "680 g Mozzarella , grated or ground", "220 g Parmesan , grated or ground"], "s": ["Make pasta dough", "Make your pasta sheets", "Boil the pasta, briefly", "Prep your greens", "Make the béchamel sauce", "Make tomato sauce", "Grind the cheese", "Assemble it all", "Bake the lasagna", "Sear the lasagna"], "tips": ["Know your flour", "Pasta roller", "Get a spider", "What if I don’t have a grinder for the cheese?", "Burp the lasagna"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-do-you-call-24-layer-lasagna-freaking-delicious"}, {"id": 63, "t": "Light and Bright Creamed Spinach", "c": "Baking", "d": "Classic creamed spinach is heavy, sludgy, and mushy. This creamed spinach? It’s light and bright, the spinach is tender-crisp, the sauce is super velvety smooth, and it comes together in 5 minutes. In the traditional version, spinach is just an afterthought—it’s more of an excuse to eat cheesy béchamel with a little vegetable matter mixed in than anything else. Here, the spinach is barely cooked, ", "i": ["100 g Heavy cream", "5 g Cornstarch , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "225 g Fresh spinach , (see “Before we begin” note)", "Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon), optional , as needed", "3 g Lemon zest , (from 1/2 lemon) finely grated", "Parmesan , finely grated, optional , as needed"], "s": ["A lighter approach to creamed spinach", "Cook cornstarch slurry", "Cook spinach", "Season and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/creamed-spinach"}, {"id": 64, "t": "Whoa. Something’s missing.", "c": "Other", "d": "", "i": [], "s": ["Whoa. Something’s missing. Check out the Recipe Gallery? Or contact us Email us Tweet us", "Check out the Recipe Gallery?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/new"}, {"id": 65, "t": "Millionaire’s Shortbread", "c": "Baking", "d": "With its buttery and tender base of shortbread, topped with a rich and chewy layer of caramel and crowned with a snappy layer of chocolate, millionaire’s shortbread is all about complementary textures and delicious excess. It’s a very well-heeled Twix. For our take on this Scottish treat, we start with a shortbread that’s better than the gold standard of Walker’s—tender and cakey and crumbly on th", "i": ["195 g Unsalted butter , softened to 65 °F / 18 °C, divided", "125 g Granulated sugar", "25 g Cornstarch", "7 g Kosher salt , divided", "15 g Egg yolk(s) , (1 large yolk)", "225 g Bleached cake flour , plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "125 g Light brown sugar", "115 g Corn syrup", "165 g Heavy cream", "200 g 60% bittersweet chocolate , coarsely chopped", "Luster dust, as needed"], "s": ["Hold on, is this just a fancy Twix bar? Kind of!", "Cream butter and sugar", "Add egg yolk", "Finish dough", "Bake and press shortbread", "Cook and cast caramel", "Temper chocolate", "Cast chocolate layer", "Portion cookies", "Serve or store for later"], "tips": ["Caramel temperature determines its texture.", "Probe placement ensures success with caramel work.", "What does “tempering chocolate” mean?", "How to “temper” chocolate with a microwave", "Warm water is the key to clean slices.", "Give your millionaire’s shortbread a little flair"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/millionaires-shortbread"}, {"id": 66, "t": "Walker’s-Style Shortbread", "c": "Baking", "d": "Rich and buttery with a tender crumb that crumbles, shortbread is a simple cookie that punches way above its weight class. This recipe uses Walker’s shortbread, the pride of Scotland, as its frame of reference, but we wanted these to be an improvement over something you can buy at the store. The one thing that this recipe gets you that Walker’s could never? The still-crispy edges and warm center o", "i": ["185 g Unsalted butter , softened to 65 °F / 18 °C", "125 g Granulated sugar", "25 g Cornstarch", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "15 g Egg yolk(s) , (1 large yolk)", "225 g Bleached cake flour , plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, optional , as needed", "Jam , for “jam-drops,” homemade or store-bought, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Ours vs. Walker’s: How the shortbread cookies crumble.", "Cream butter and sugar", "Add egg yolk", "Finish dough", "Shape and rest dough", "Roll out dough", "Portion dough", "First phase bake to set shape", "Second phase bake to finish", "Serve or store shortbread for later"], "tips": ["Temper dough to reduce cracking when rolling", "Make jam drop shortbread cookies", "Re-roll dough scraps for extra cookies"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/walkers-style-shortbread-cookies"}, {"id": 67, "t": "A Guide to Chinese New Year Dishes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Gung hei fat choi! (恭喜發財!) Chinese New Year is one of the most important holidays in Chinese culture. Like Lunar New Year celebrations in Korea and Vietnam, it marks the beginning of the year according to the lunisolar Chinese calendar, typically occurring from late January to mid-February. Just like new year’s holidays the world over, it’s a time for seeking blessings and giving out well-wishes f", "i": [], "s": ["The Symbolism of Chinese New Year Foods", "Wrapped Foods", "Dumplings (餃子, Jiǎo Zi)", "Spring Rolls (春卷, Chēun Gyún)", "Wontons (雲吞, Wàhn Tān)", "Large or Whole Foods", "Whole Fish (鱼, Yú)", "Roast Chicken (燒雞, Sīu Gāi) or Roast Duck (燒鴨, Sīu Aap)", "Lion’s Head Meatballs (獅子頭, Shīzǐ Tóu)", "Longevity Noodles (伊麵, Yī Mihn)", "Vegetable Dishes", "Braised Lettuce (蠔油生菜, Hòuh Yàuh Sāang Choi)", "Buddha’s Delight (羅漢齋, Lòh Hohn Jāai)", "Rice (飯, Fàn)", "Sweets and Desserts", "Glutinous Rice Balls (汤圆, Tāngyuán)", "Rice Cakes (年糕, Nián Gāo)", "Sesame Balls (煎堆, Jīn Dēui)", "Mandarin Oranges (橘, Jú)", "Modern Celebratory Dishes", "Lobster (龙虾, Lùhng Hā)", "Char Siu (叉燒, Chā Sīu) and Barbecue Ribs (叉燒骨, Chā Sīu Gwāt)", "Cantonese Roast Pork Belly (燒肉, Siu Yuk)", "How to Assemble a Balanced Chinese New Year Feast"], "tips": ["Color symbolism in Chinese New Year", "What about soup dumplings?", "What about drinks?", "The do’s and don’ts of a Chinese New Year meal"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chinese-new-year-guide"}, {"id": 68, "t": "Dim Sum-Style Seasoned Soy Sauce", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Seasoned soy sauce is what accentuates the restraint of delicate dim sum dishes like shrimp or beef cheung fun. Fragrant, deeply savory, and a little sweet, with a smoky-singed flavor from sizzling the sauce with hot oil, this seasoned soy sauce is the perfect complement to steamed dishes of all kinds. save Print", "i": ["60 g Light soy sauce , (see “Before we begin” note)", "60 g Water", "15 g Granulated sugar", "2 g Toasted sesame oil , (1/2 teaspoon)", "30 g Neutral oil", "10 g Scallion(s) , (2 scallions) sliced"], "s": ["Street food-style vs. dim sum-style cheung fun", "Mix soy sauce base", "Heat oil", "Sizzle soy sauce", "Put seasoned soy sauce to use or store for later"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dim-sum-seasoned-soy-sauce"}, {"id": 69, "t": "Teriyaki Roast Chicken", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Move over air-fried teriyaki chicken wings, it’s whole roasted teriyaki chicken’s time to shine! The problem with a lot of teriyaki chicken out there is that it’s grilled hard to get the char, which often results in dry, stringy meat. Our goal with this recipe for a whole bird was to pair the best part of the teriyaki eating experience—the sauce!—with succulent, nicely cooked meat. A two-step brai", "i": ["125 g Soy sauce", "145 g Mirin , divided", "120 g Water", "120 g Sugar , divided", "17 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) finely grated", "1 Chicken , whole (1.8 kg; 4 pounds)", "25 g Rice wine vinegar , unseasoned", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "1 g White pepper , ground (1/3 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "200 g Mayonnaise", "1 Iceberg lettuce , head, cut into wedges, for serving", "White rice , cooked, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Start teriyaki sauce", "Spatchcock chicken", "Marinate chicken", "Roast chicken", "Reduce sauce to a glaze", "Glaze and char chicken", "Make salad dressing", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/teriyaki-roasted-chicken"}, {"id": 70, "t": "Stovetop Mac and Cheese", "c": "Baking", "d": "Here’s the blue box mac and cheese you grew up loving—just a little more grown up. If there’s one thing the boxed stuff gets right, it’s the texture: glossy, smooth, and oh-so-creamy. But it doesn’t score high in the flavor department. We’re here to fix that. Using everything we’ve learned about melting salts and cheese sauce science, we’ve made a super-smooth sauce packed with sharp cheddar flavo", "i": ["480 g Whole milk", "150 g Aged white cheddar , coarsely grated (see “Before we begin” note)", "150 g Low-moisture mozzarella , coarsely grated (see “Before we begin” note)", "14 g Kosher salt , divided", "9 g Sodium citrate , (see “Before we begin” note)", "0.75 g Sodium hexametaphosphate , (see “Before we begin” note)", "45 g Unsalted butter", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) finely grated", "1.5 g Mustard powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Cayenne pepper , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "340 g Elbow macaroni , (see “Before we begin” note)", "23 g All-purpose flour", "6 g Black pepper , coarsely ground, plus extra for serving", "80 g Gochujang", "20 g Granulated sugar", "150 g Corn , frozen kernels, defrosted"], "s": ["Stovetop vs. baked mac and cheese", "Heat sous vide bath", "Bag up cheese mixture", "Pass the melting salts for a smooth cheese sauce.", "Melt cheese mixture", "Make garlic butter", "Blend cheese sauce", "Combine pasta and cheese sauce", "Serve"], "tips": ["No sous vide circulator? No problem.", "Want to use a different cheese? Adjust the cheese ratios.", "No melting salts? No problem! Make a roux-based cheese sauce.", "Make cacio e pepe mac", "Korean corn cheese mac"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/stovetop-macaroni-and-cheese"}, {"id": 71, "t": "The Science of Melty Cheese", "c": "Baking", "d": "If cheese has a problem, it’s that it’s an unreliable melter. American cheese stays perfectly ooey-gooey in a grilled cheese, and a box of Velveeta shells gets you a smooth, silky, and oh-so-creamy plate of mac. But give a couple chunks of your favorite aged Parm a blast of heat, and they’ll turn into an oily, greasy, hardened mess. Why do some cheeses melt while others turn into greasy blobs? And", "i": [], "s": ["What Is Cheese?", "The Properties of a Good Melting Cheese", "What Happens When Cheese Melts?", "What Are Melting Salts?", "Types of Melting Salts", "Other “Melting Salts”", "Melting It All Together", "Demystifying food science ingredients"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/science-of-melty-cheese"}, {"id": 72, "t": "The Ultimate Average Chocolate Chip Cookie", "c": "Baking", "d": "There is no reason this recipe should work, but it does. It’s the perfect blend of chewy, crispy, buttery, chocolatey goodness—it’s the ultimate chocolate chip cookie. It’s also the average chocolate chip cookie. What does that mean? After baking, testing, and analyzing the 10 best chocolate chip cookie recipes in the world for our parametric analysis, we wondered what would happen if we averaged ", "i": ["200 g Cake flour , unbleached", "200 g Bread flour", "287 g Unsalted butter , softened to 65 °F / 18 °C", "213 g Granulated sugar", "213 g Brown sugar", "11 g Vanilla extract", "5 g Baking soda , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "100 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs)", "436 g 60% bittersweet chocolate chips , or pistoles (see “Before we begin” note)", "Flake sea salt , for finishing, optional (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "436 g 58% bittersweet chocolate pistoles , thin disk shaped"], "s": ["Chocolate chip cookies for everyone!", "Sift flours", "Cream butter and sugars", "Mix in eggs", "Finish dough", "Portion and rest cookie dough", "Bake and shape cookies", "Cool and serve"], "tips": ["Need cookies fast? Skip creaming and start mixing!", "Roll and rest cookie dough to control spread.", "Cookies and carryover cooking", "Baking in batches: not recommended but can be done.", "It’s a monster! Make a freaky ultimate average cookie!", "The original recipe", "BTS: Developing the ultimate average chocolate chip cookie."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-guide-to-chocolate-chip-cookies-when-average-equals-amazing"}, {"id": 73, "t": "Chocolate Chip Cookies: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "How do you like your chocolate chip cookies? Do you like them chewy or soft with barely set edges? Do you like them thin and crispy? Or do you like ’em thick and chonky, maybe with a little sprinkle of flaky sea salt on top? You’re a grown-up. You can have whatever kind of cookie you want, whenever you want. We pulled together 10 of our favorite published recipes for chocolate chip cookies, ones t", "i": [], "s": ["The Infographic 2.0", "The Elements of Chocolate Chip Cookies", "The Chocolate Chip Cookies", "Grant Crilly - Chocolate Chip Cookies", "BraveTart - Chopped Chocolate Chip Cookies", "Serious Eats - The Food Lab’s Chocolate Chip Cookies", "Toll House - Chocolate Chip Cookies", "Christina Tosi - Best Ever Chocolate Chip Cookies", "Jacques Torres - Chocolate Chip Cookies", "Professional Baking - Chocolate Chip Cookies", "Anna Olson - Classic Chocolate Chip Cookies", "America’s Test Kitchen - Perfect Chocolate Chip Cookies", "Sarah Kieffer - Pan-Banging Chocolate Chip Cookies", "ChefSteps - The Ultimate Average Chocolate Chip Cookie"], "tips": ["The original infographic", "Become a Smart Cookie!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-guide-to-chocolate-chip-cookies-behold-the-cookie-calculator"}, {"id": 74, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Chocolate Chip Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’ve made chocolate chip cookies before, you probably know the ingredients by heart—chocolate, of course, but also butter, sugar, flour, eggs, salt, vanilla, and some baking soda—and you know how to put them together. But have you ever stopped to think about why we add eggs to the cookie dough? Or what would happen if you added an extra yolk or cut the sugar by half? Would it be edible? Would", "i": [], "s": ["The Elements of a Chocolate Chip Cookie", "Sugars", "Leavening Agents", "Chocolate", "Flavor Boosters", "Starches and Alternative Flours", "Cookie Technique", "How Dough Mixing Affects Cookie Texture", "How Portion Size Affects Cookie Texture", "The Importance of Resting Cookie Dough", "How Baking Time and Temp Affect Cookie Texture", "How to Dial in Your Perfect Chocolate Chip Cookie", "How to Make a Chewier Cookie", "How to Make a Softer Cookie", "How to Make a Crispier Cookie", "Find your perfect chocolate chip cookie!"], "tips": ["A (Very) Brief History of Chocolate Chip Cookies", "Flour trials", "Butter trials", "Sugar trials", "Egg trials", "Leavening agent trials", "Flavor booster trials", "Starch trials", "Creaming and mixing trials", "Resting trials", "Time and temperature trials", "How to tell when cookies are “done”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-guide-to-chocolate-chip-cookies"}, {"id": 75, "t": "Galette des Rois", "c": "Baking", "d": "Some French food traditions are just certified bangers. Galette des rois is a perfect example: A golden brown puff pastry crust that’s glassy and so crisp it shatters, encasing a smooth and custardy frangipane filling, with a little surprise tucked inside—because who doesn’t love a little drama? Traditionally served to mark the Epiphany, galettes des rois are served up in slices for the celebratio", "i": ["700 g Puff Pastry (Pâte Feuilletée) , or two (16- by 10-inch) store-bought puff pastry sheets, thawed (see “Before we begin” note)", "All-purpose flour , for dusting , as needed", "250 g Classic Frangipane , (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 Egg(s) , large", "10 g Heavy cream", "1 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "60 g Granulated sugar , for glaze, optional", "40 g Water , for glaze, optional", "5 g Light corn syrup , for glaze, optional"], "s": ["Savory vs. sweet pithiviers", "Troubleshooting wonky shapes", "Roll out and chill puff pastry", "Pipe frangipane onto bottom layer of puff pastry", "Assemble and chill galette", "Trim, crimp, and score galette", "First egg wash", "Second egg wash", "Decorate galette", "Make glaze (optional)", "First phase bake to puff pastry and begin browning top", "Second phase covered bake to compress galette", "Third phase bake to burnish top", "Cool and glaze galette", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Use pastry rulers to roll out a reliably even and precise thickness.", "Using store-bought puff pastry? Trim the dough sheets.", "Set up your station: galette assembly and decorating.", "Use a bowl (or tart ring) to help eliminate air pockets and seal galette.", "Use floss or string to find the center point.", "There’s more than one way to decorate a galette.", "Deeper scored lines are functional; faint scored lines are decorative.", "Cover galette to control the puff of puff pastry."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/galette-des-rois"}, {"id": 76, "t": "Classic Frangipane", "c": "Baking", "d": "Frangipane is a sweet almond cream that’s used as a filling for tarts and pastries, most famously in Galette des Rois. While it’s a classic French preparation, frangipane nowadays refers to two different sweet, spreadable, almond-flavored creams: French frangipane, which refers to almond cream mixed with pastry cream in a 2:1 ratio; and American frangipane, which consists of just almond cream. Thi", "i": ["225 g Unsalted butter , softened to 65 °F / 18 °C", "225 g Granulated sugar", "200 g Egg(s) , (4 large eggs)", "225 g Almond flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g All-purpose flour , sifted", "15 g Almond extract", "10 g Vanilla extract", "6 g Kosher salt", "450 g Pastry Cream , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Pastry flour , sifted"], "s": ["American frangipane vs. French frangipane", "Cream butter and sugar", "Add eggs and almond flour", "Add flour", "Flavor and season American frangipane", "Add pastry cream to make French frangipane (optional)", "Put frangipane to use or store for later"], "tips": ["The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/classic-frangipane"}, {"id": 77, "t": "Ultimate Pithivier", "c": "Baking", "d": "This savory pithivier is pure French cooking at its finest: Crispy and beautifully burnished puff pastry encasing distinct layers of squab breast, foie gras torchon, poached mushrooms, and a chicken-mushroom mousseline—with a little stuffed squab leg served alongside, just for fun. Served with a rich, fat-speckled Madeira Jus gras and a silky Caramelized Cauliflower Purée, it’s a master class in c", "i": ["2 Squab(s) , whole, head and feet on, with offal, if possible (see “Before we begin” note)", "120 g Whole milk , optional", "30 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh (4 sprigs)", "16 g Thyme , fresh (8 sprigs), divided", "208 g Kosher salt , divided", "65 g Granulated sugar", "14 Juniper berries , toasted", "1 Star anise , toasted", "60 g Neutral oil , divided, plus extra as needed", "450 g Cremini mushrooms , or other fresh mushrooms, cleaned, stemmed, and cut into 1/2-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "4 Garlic clove(s) , divided", "158 g Unsalted butter , divided", "225 g Chicken breast , boneless, skinless, cut into 1/2-inch pieces", "2.5 g Sodium tripolyphosphate , optional (3/8 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "1.1 kg Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock, divided", "5 g Dried shiitake(s) , or other dried mushrooms, such as morels, finely ground, optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g Crème Fraîche , homemade or store-bought", "350 g Collard greens , (1 bunch; see “Before we begin” note)", "80 g Prosciutto , or serrano ham (4 slices)", "Activa RM , optional (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "4 Shiitake mushrooms , fresh (about 3 inches in diameter), cleaned and stemmed (see “Before we begin” note)", "4 Black peppercorns , whole, plus freshly ground pepper, as needed", "160 g Foie Gras Torchon , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "4 Puff pastry , sheets (16- by 10-inch sheets), store-bought or homemade, fully thawed (see “Before we begin” note)", "180 g Egg yolk(s) , (12 large yolks)", "1 recipe Caramelized Cauliflower Purée , for serving, optional", "1 recipe Madeira Jus , for serving, optional"], "s": ["Choose your pithivier fighter", "Pithivier timeline", "Butcher squab", "Make squab cure", "Cure squab breasts and legs", "Sauté mushrooms for farce", "Make chicken farce", "Trim and blanch collard greens", "Assemble stuffed squab legs", "Cook stuffed legs", "Poach and punch shiitake disks", "Punch out foie gras torchon disks", "Roll out and cut puff pastry", "Assemble pithivier filling", "Assemble pithiviers", "Egg wash pithiviers twice", "Egg wash pithiviers a third time", "Sear and wrap stuffed squab legs", "Decorate pithiviers", "Bake pithiviers", "Flash stuffed squab legs", "Slice, plate, and serve"], "tips": ["Set up your station: squab butchery.", "Soak offal in milk to remove myoglobin and mineral flavor.", "When making farce, keep it ice cold.", "How phosphates work", "Set up your station: stuffed squab legs.", "Hedge your bets with meat glue.", "Got a combi oven? Skip the sous vide set up.", "Making Madeira Jus? Now’s a good time to start it.", "Set up your station: puff pastry cutting.", "Using the MoldBrothers set? Cutting puff pastry is a breeze.", "Set up your station: pithivier filling assembly.", "Using the MoldBrothers set? We got you.", "Set up your station: pithivier assembly.", "Options for covering pithiviers to prevent glaze from cracking", "Test to see if egg wash is set and ready for the next coat", "Making Caramelized Cauliflower Purée? Now’s a good time to do it.", "Set up your station: pithivier decorating.", "Decorating pithiviers with MoldBrothers set", "Get mise together and reheat while pithiviers bake", "Temping a squab and foie pithivier is tricky.", "Servings for a pithivier party"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-pithivier"}, {"id": 78, "t": "“Meatloaf” Pithivier", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you love the Cinderella meatloaf that is pâté en croûte and you get a little thrill when you see a knife slide through a perfectly made beef Wellington to reveal its glorious insides, then you’re going to love this pithivier. A pithivier is basically a French puff pastry pie. It originated as a sweet treat—layers of puff encasing something like frangipane, as in the iconic galette des rois, but", "i": ["80 g Cremini mushrooms , (4 medium mushrooms) cleaned and quartered", "15 g Neutral oil", "9 g Kosher salt , divided (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "100 g Red wine , dry", "20 g Shallot(s) , (1 large shallot) minced", "225 g Ground beef", "20 g Panko breadcrumbs", "30 g Whole milk", "90 g Egg yolk(s) , (6 large yolks) divided", "2 g Black pepper , coarsely ground (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Thyme , fresh leaves, chopped (3 sprigs)", "30 g Carrot(s) , (1 small carrot) peeled and cut into 1/8-inch dice", "350 g Collard greens , (1 bunch; see “Before we begin” note)", "225 g Chicken thighs , boneless, skinless, trimmed and cut into 1-inch pieces", "4 g Cornstarch , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "100 g Sour cream", "60 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "10 g Dijon mustard", "2 Puff pastry , sheets (16- by 10-inch sheets), store-bought or homemade, fully thawed (see “Before we begin” note)", "All-purpose flour , for dusting , as needed"], "s": ["Choose your pithivier fighter", "Roast and chop mushrooms", "Cook shallot jam", "Mix “meatloaf”", "Trim and blanch collard greens", "Make chicken farce", "Roll out and cut puff pastry", "Wrap “meatloaf” in blanched collard greens", "Assemble pithivier filling", "Assemble and egg wash pithiviers", "Egg wash pithiviers a second time", "Prepare pithiviers for baking", "First phase bake to puff pastry and brown top", "Second phase bake to cook filling", "Slice pithiviers and serve"], "tips": ["For a mosaic farce, add carrots.", "Set up your station: puff pastry cutting.", "Use a ruler to determine the exact center of the puff pastry square.", "Set up your station: pithivier filling assembly.", "Turn extra farce into a classic quenelle “dumpling.”", "Set up pithivier assembly station", "Egg wash layers: how to test them, and why they’re needed.", "Set up your station: pithivier decorating"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/meatloaf-pithivier"}, {"id": 79, "t": "Caramelized Cauliflower Purée", "c": "Dessert", "d": "When you want a “simple” side that tastes anything but boring, whip up this caramelized cauliflower purée. Cooking cauliflower in a generous amount of browned butter brings out toasty, malty notes reminiscent of a porter or roasted sunchokes. Add in a healthy dose of cream and a splash of sherry vinegar for balance, and you’ve got a rich vegetable purée that can complement everything from a simple", "i": ["600 g Cauliflower , (1 medium head)", "15 g Neutral oil", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 3/4 teaspoons) plus extra as needed", "75 g Unsalted butter", "310 g Heavy cream", "10 g Sherry vinegar , optional (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["A purée fit for a pithivier", "Cut cauliflower", "Cook cauliflower", "Simmer with cream", "Blend and strain purée", "Put purée to use or store for later"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/caramelized-cauliflower-puree"}, {"id": 80, "t": "Madeira Jus", "c": "Baking", "d": "With any classic French dish, a sauce is super, super important, a bit of gilding the lily that really ties the room elements of the plate together. This Madeira jus has a welcome acidic bite from sherry vinegar that cuts through the richness of any meaty main, but it’s particularly well-suited to accompany our Ultimate Pithivier. This sauce is a great example of the effort and patience that go cl", "i": ["30 g Neutral oil", "300 g Squab bones , from Ultimate Pithivier, or chicken bones, cut into 3-inch pieces, plus any extra skin, optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "113 g Unsalted butter , (1 stick; see “Before we begin” note)", "75 g Shallot(s) , (2 medium shallots) thinly sliced", "Kosher salt, as needed", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 medium cloves) crushed", "8 g Thyme , fresh sprigs (4 sprigs)", "20 Black peppercorns , whole", "224 g Sherry vinegar", "224 g White wine , dry", "750 g Madeira , (one 750 ml bottle; see “Before we begin” note)", "2 kg Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock (see “Before we begin” note)", "Knox gelatin , or silver (160 bloom) leaf gelatin, optional (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed"], "s": ["A sauce piquante for pithivier", "Brown bones (optional)", "Cook aromatics and deglaze pan", "Reduce white wine and Madeira", "Reduce stock", "Reduce and season Madeira jus", "Put Madeira jus to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Not browning bones? Brown some butter instead.", "Using store-bought stock? Add gelatin to give the sauce body."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/madeira-jus"}, {"id": 81, "t": "Ultra-Crispy Latkes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Ready for the best latkes you’ve ever had? Picture this: shatteringly crisp edges, tender-fluffy interiors, zero greasiness, and zero sogginess. We’ve dialed in all the variables—the cutting, starch regulation, moisture content, and frying technique—to give you our version of the perfect potato pancake. The bones of this recipe are traditional—just potatoes, onions, salt, and three key ingredients", "i": ["800 g Russet potato(es) , (2 potatoes) rinsed and scrubbed (see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g Yellow onion(s) , (1 small onion)", "80 g Potato starch", "4 g Baking powder , (1 teaspoon)", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoons) plus extra as needed", "30 g Egg white(s) , (from 1 large egg)", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed"], "s": ["Traditional vs. new-school latkes", "Process potatoes and onion", "Squeeze out excess water", "Make latke batter", "Fry latkes", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": ["Three key ingredients to crispier and more golden-brown latkes", "For perfectly shaped latkes, use a ring mold."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/potato-latkes"}, {"id": 82, "t": "Caramelized Apple Ketchup", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’re looking to capture autumn in a jar, there’s no better condiment than apple butter—a super-concentrated, rich, spiced, and velvety smooth condiment that hits all the cozy notes of fall. But what if we took that idea to its logical extreme? Enter our caramelized apple ketchup. The best apple butters rely on slow, methodical cooking to gently break down and caramelize the apples. Here, we p", "i": ["800 g Apple(s) , (3 to 4 large apples; see “Before we begin” note)", "150 g Granulated sugar", "45 g Water", "15 g Light corn syrup , (see “Before we begin” note)", "4 g Baking soda , (1/2 teaspoon)", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "1.5 g Cinnamon , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Nutmeg , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "120 g Apple cider , unpasteurized, freshly pressed (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Red miso paste , (aka miso; see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Malic acid , (1 teaspoon) plus extra as needed"], "s": ["Core and slice apples", "Make caramel", "Deglaze caramel with apples", "Add apple cider and simmer", "Blend apple ketchup", "Strain apple ketchup (optional)", "Put apple ketchup to use or store for later"], "tips": ["When handling caramels, swirl, don’t stir.", "Add baking soda to speed up breakdown and deepen caramel flavor"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/apple-ketchup"}, {"id": 83, "t": "Perfect Tarte Tatin", "c": "Baking", "d": "For a dessert that’s seemingly so simple and rustic, tarte Tatin presents some real technical challenges even for experienced bakers. Take it from Julia Child herself, who infamously unmolded a soupy catastrophe of apples and pastry on national television. Where do cooks go wrong? Usually trouble arises when they try to rush the process. The key to success is controlling moisture and caramelizatio", "i": ["1.3 kg Apple(s) , (5 large apples; see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Apple cider vinegar", "200 g Granulated sugar", "60 g Water", "16 g Light corn syrup", "40 g Bourbon whiskey , (see “Before we begin” note)", "56 g Unsalted butter , chilled, cut into 4 pieces", "3 g Malic acid , (see “Before we begin” note), optional", "290 g Perfect Pie Dough , (see “Before we begin” note)", "All-purpose flour , for dusting , as needed"], "s": ["The tarte Tatin timeline", "Peel and cut apples", "Poach apples", "Arrange apples in pan", "Make caramel", "Finish caramel sauce", "Cook apples in caramel", "Bake apples", "Chill apples in caramel overnight", "Roll out pie dough and top apples", "First phase bake to puff crust", "Second phase bake to cook crust through", "Cool tarte Tatin", "Unmold", "Serve and enjoy"], "tips": ["To reliably fit more apples in the pan, trim cores with a straight cut.", "Firm up apples with a quick poach.", "Bake the caramel sauce to a specific temperature for perfect color, flavor, and tart shape.", "For the best possible shape, arrange apples while still hot, then chill overnight.", "For picture-perfect results, cool it down before unmolding", "Don’t have a blowtorch? Use the stove to unmold"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tarte-tatin"}, {"id": 84, "t": "Perfect Pie Dough", "c": "Baking", "d": "Great pies start with great pie dough, and this is it: the only pie dough you'll ever need. It's easy to put together—you don't need a stand mixer or a food processor or any special tools, other than a bench scraper and a rolling pin. It's super versatile—you can use it to make both sweet and savory pies, you can use it to make tarts, you can use it to make hand pies. And it bakes up beautifully—c", "i": ["382 g Bread flour , plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "38 g Granulated sugar , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "10 g Kosher salt", "286 g Unsalted butter , chilled (see “Before we begin” note)", "170 g Ice water"], "s": ["Whisk dry ingredients", "Cut in butter", "Mix dough", "Fold and chill dough", "Portion dough", "Roll out dough", "Form and chill pie shell", "Blind bake crust with weights (optional)", "Remove weights and finish blind bake (optional)"], "tips": ["The materials science of pie dough.", "How different flours affect pie dough handling and performance.", "American vs. European-style butter", "Rub butter and flour together for more uniform flakiness and less pooling.", "Freeze the butter-flour mixture for ultra-flaky dough.", "Dough not coming together? Give it one more set of folds.", "Not baking a round pie? Here’s how to roll out a square of dough.", "Dock the dough to control expansion.", "Butter vs. lard vs. shortening: What’s the difference?", "Pie weight options"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/perfect-pie-dough-crust"}, {"id": 85, "t": "Rich as F*¢k Cornbread", "c": "Baking", "d": "Here’s what we love about cornbread: the sweet flavor of peak-season corn, a crispy crust, and a moist, tender interior that’s both light and super rich at the same time. We turned all those dials up to 11 to make this almost brownie-like riff on the corny quick bread. While that places our cornbread firmly on the northern side of the North/South divide (southern-style cornbread is savory and crum", "i": ["440 g Unsalted butter , divided", "830 g Corn kernels , frozen, thawed (see “Before we begin” note)", "145 g Heavy cream", "80 g Whole milk", "150 g Egg(s) , (3 large eggs)", "220 g Cake flour , unbleached, (see “Before we begin” note)", "205 g Isomalt , finely ground (see “Before we begin” note)", "145 g Cornmeal , medium grind, (see “Before we begin” note)", "80 g Granulated sugar", "9 g Kosher salt", "4 g Baking powder , (1 1/8 teaspoons)", "2 g Baking soda , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 recipe Honey Butter , room temperature, for serving, optional", "900 g Corn , frozen", "10 g Salt , kosher"], "s": ["Cook corn", "Preheat pans", "Blend corn", "Finish batter", "Portion and bake cornbread", "Cool cornbread", "Serve"], "tips": ["Cooking corn will alter the texture and flavor.", "Preheat pans for crustier cornbread", "Once you mix the batter, you’re on the clock!", "How to bake cornbread in a 10-inch skillet", "For extra crispy cornbread, get it out of the pan to cool.", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/rich-and-moist-cornbread"}, {"id": 86, "t": "Ultra-Creamy Baked Mac and Cheese", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Great baked macaroni and cheese is just great mac—tender pasta coated in a thick, creamy cheese sauce—bubbling in a baking pan beneath a blanket of crunchy, golden-brown breadcrumbs. But all too often that isn’t the case. Most baked mac and cheeses are stodgy and gluey, with the pasta hammered beyond belief. It’s a shame, because it doesn’t have to be this way. Our version solves all those issues.", "i": ["720 g Whole milk", "225 g Aged white cheddar , coarsely grated (see “Before we begin” note)", "225 g Low-moisture mozzarella , coarsely grated (see “Before we begin” note)", "16 g Kosher salt , divided", "13.5 g Sodium citrate , (see “Before we begin” note)", "1.5 g Sodium hexametaphosphate , (see “Before we begin” note)", "105 g Unsalted butter , divided", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) finely grated", "1.5 g Mustard powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Cayenne pepper , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "120 g White bread , torn into 2-inch pieces (2 to 3 slices; see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Parmesan , finely grated", "340 g Elbow macaroni , (see “Before we begin” note)", "35 g All-purpose flour"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Bag up cheese mixture", "Melt cheese mixture", "Make garlic butter", "Blend cheese sauce", "Make breadcrumb mixture", "Cook pasta", "Combine pasta and cheese sauce", "Bake mac and cheese", "Serve"], "tips": ["No sous vide circulator? No problem.", "Making stovetop mac ‘n’ cheese? Scale your cheese sauce accordingly.", "Pass the melting salt(s) for a smooth cheese sauce.", "No melting salts? No problem! Make a roux-based cheese sauce.", "Making stovetop mac? Save that pasta water.", "Don’t bake it and bring it to Grandma’s."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/baked-macaroni-and-cheese"}, {"id": 87, "t": "Tips & Tricks: The Secret to Smooth and Bright Purées", "c": "Baking", "d": "Fine-dining kitchens pride themselves on their smooth, vibrant purées, which can be used as the foundation for all kinds of sauces, soups, and emulsions. But how do they do it? How do those bright-green broccoli purées stay so green for so long? How do those carrot soups become so smooth and silky? The secret is hiding right in your kitchen cupboard: baking soda. And it all boils down to some simp", "i": [], "s": ["How to Do It", "Why It Works", "It Works for Root Veg, Too", "Frequently Asked Questions"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-tricks-smooth-bright-vegetable-purees"}, {"id": 88, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Ramen", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "What is ramen? Well, it depends on who you ask. Some might call it a miracle of industrial food production, a cheap and satisfying meal that anyone in the world can prepare in a matter of minutes. Others might call it junk food, a mix of highly processed starch and sodium designed to light up all our pleasure centers with the most delicious empty calories. And still others may say that it is the h", "i": [], "s": ["The Elements of Ramen", "Tare (Seasoning)", "Noodles", "Toppings", "Chashu", "Ajitsuke Tamago", "Other Toppings", "Putting It All Together", "Common Ramen Styles", "Ramen by Stock Type", "Ramen by Flavor", "Ramen by Topping", "Famous Regional Ramen Styles", "Instant Ramen", "Essential Equipment for Homemade Ramen", "Ramen Prep Tools", "Ramen Cooking Tools", "Ramen Service Ware"], "tips": ["MSG and Haimi", "Using rendered fat from the stock-making process", "Japanese dried seafood", "Brothless ramen", "How to level up instant ramen"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-ramen-guide"}, {"id": 89, "t": "Pasta alla Zozzona", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "What happens when you mash together amatriciana and carbonara? You get pasta alla zozzona, an over-the-top, more-is-more pasta that breaks from tradition in the name of delicious decadence. save Print", "i": ["225 g Guanciale , (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 Egg yolk(s) , large", "60 g Pecorino Romano , finely grated, plus extra for serving (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Black pepper , coarsely ground (1 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "170 g Italian sausage , sweet or hot (1 large sausage)", "112 g Yellow onion(s) , (1 small onion) cut into small dice", "1 g Red pepper flakes , (1/2 teaspoon)", "500 g Whole canned tomatoes , blended, or tomato passata (see “Before we begin” note)", "9 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "340 g Mezze maniche , or rigatoni (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["The “core four” Roman pastas and a “dirty” mashup", "Cut guanciale", "Render guanciale", "Mix egg yolks and Pecorino", "Cook sausage and onion", "Cook sauce", "Cook pasta al chiodo", "Finish cooking pasta in sauce", "Incorporate egg-cheese mixture off-heat"], "tips": ["Invest in a good pasta pan", "The grate debate: the best way to grate hard cheeses for pasta", "Tomato, tomahto: whole canned tomatoes vs. passata", "Pasta doneness: al chiodo vs. al dente", "For sauce that clings, finish cooking pasta with the sauce."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pasta-alla-zozzona"}, {"id": 90, "t": "Pasta all’Amatriciana", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "With sweet acidity from tomatoes and a pop of chile heat, amatriciana is the brightest of the “core four” Roman pastas. But don’t get it twisted—this isn’t a light and delicate tomato sauce. It’s got plenty of rich, porky funk from guanciale, background bite from black pepper, and a sharp finish of salty Pecorino Romano. The best part? It comes together in a flash and may just be the best pantry p", "i": ["225 g Guanciale , (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Black pepper , coarsely ground (1 teaspoon), plus extra for serving", "1 g Red pepper flakes , (1/2 teaspoon)", "800 g Whole canned tomatoes , blended, or tomato passata (see “Before we begin” note)", "9 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "450 g Mezze maniche , or rigatoni (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Pecorino Romano , finely grated, plus extra for serving (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["The “core four” Roman pastas", "Cut guanciale", "Render guanciale", "Bloom pepper and chile", "Cook sauce", "Cook pasta al chiodo", "Finish cooking pasta in sauce", "Finish off-heat with cheese", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Invest in a good pasta pan", "Tomato, tomahto: whole canned tomatoes vs. passata", "Pasta doneness: al chiodo vs. al dente", "For tomato sauce that clings, finish with pasta water.", "The grate debate: the best way to grate hard cheeses for pasta"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pasta-all-amatriciana"}, {"id": 91, "t": "Perfect Cacio e Pepe", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Cacio e pepe—is there a better example of a dish being greater than the sum of its parts? The simplest of the “core four” Roman pastas (gricia, amatriciana, and carbonara are the other three), with just three ingredients—pasta, pepper, and cheese—bound together with starchy pasta water to produce a punchy plate of in-your-face grownup mac and cheese. save Print", "i": ["10 g Black peppercorns", "6 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "340 g Spaghettoni , (see “Before we begin” note)", "200 g Pecorino Romano , finely grated, plus extra for serving (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["The “core four” Roman pastas", "Toast peppercorns", "Grind peppercorns", "Cook pasta al chiodo", "Finish cooking pasta in “pepper broth”", "Finish off-heat with cheese", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Invest in a good pasta pan", "Pasta doneness: al chiodo vs. al dente", "Mantecatura: the technique for emulsified pasta sauces", "Starch is key to a silky-smooth cacio e pepe.", "The grate debate: the best way to grate hard cheeses for pasta", "How to plate long pasta like a pro", "Restaurant vs. shepherd’s cacio e pepe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pasta-cacio-e-pepe"}, {"id": 92, "t": "Pasta alla Gricia", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Pasta alla gricia is the most under-appreciated of the “core four” Roman pastas. Carbonara and cacio e pepe get all the glory, and amatriciana gets plenty of love as all tomato sauces do. But gricia is given short shrift and often defined by what it’s perceived to be missing: “carbonara without the egg,” or “white amatriciana.” That’s a shame, because gricia is every bit the equal of the other thr", "i": ["225 g Guanciale", "2 g Black pepper , coarsely ground (1 teaspoon), plus extra for serving", "6 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "340 g Mezze maniche , or rigatoni (see “Before we begin” note)", "60 g Pecorino Romano , finely grated, plus extra for serving (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["The “core four” Roman pastas", "Cut guanciale", "Render guanciale", "Bloom pepper", "Cook pasta halfway", "Finish cooking pasta", "Finish off-heat with cheese", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Invest in a good pasta pan", "The keys to a silky-smooth gricia", "The grate debate: the best way to grate hard cheeses for pasta"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pasta-alla-gricia"}, {"id": 93, "t": "Omurice", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Omurice may just be the most viral Japanese dish in recent memory (sorry, ramen and tonkatsu). At its most basic, it’s just an omelet served with rice—Japanese home cooks will serve up an omelet with fried rice for breakfast, lunch, or dinner; more enterprising home cooks might even tuck the rice into the omelet as a filling. But the version that made omurice a social media sensation was made famo", "i": ["3 Egg(s) , large", "1 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "140 g Omurice-Style Fried Rice , warm (1 cup; see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Neutral oil , (1 teaspoon)", "60 g Chicken Demi-Glace , warm, optional, for serving", "Ketchup , optional, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Omurice illustrated", "Whisk and rest eggs", "Mold and form rice", "Set up omelet station and heat pan", "Scramble eggs", "Release eggs from sides of pan", "Shape omelet", "Flip and seal omelet", "Position dismount and set omelet over rice", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Make sure your rice and demi-glace are ready and warm before cooking the omelet.", "For the best omurice omelet, use a gas burner.", "Perfecting the scramble", "Use a wet kitchen towel to slow down cooking so you can focus on shaping.", "How to shape the omelet", "How to master the flip", "How to nail the dismount"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/omurice"}, {"id": 94, "t": "Omurice-Style Fried Rice", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "There are two parts to Japanese omurice: the beautifully made omelet and the rice it’s served with. While you could serve the omelet with plain steamed white rice, it’s typically served with fried rice spiked with a little ketchup. Yup, you heard that right: ketchup. The reason for that is that the version of omurice that’s most well-known today was created for the cult-classic foodie flick Tampop", "i": ["200 g Medium-grain rice", "240 g Water , plus extra for rinsing rice", "35 g Ketchup", "20 g Soy sauce", "2.5 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , or MSG (1 1/4 teaspoons; see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Toasted sesame oil , (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g White pepper , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "100 g Ground chicken", "10 g Neutral oil", "40 g Scallion(s) , (about 4 scallions) white and green parts separated, whites minced, greens thinly sliced; divided", "10 g Unsalted butter , softened", "5 g Furikake , (1 tablespoon; see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Cook and cool rice", "Mix seasoning sauce", "Fluff rice and combine with chicken", "Fry rice", "Serve or put to use in omurice"], "tips": ["For better fried rice, chill your rice uncovered.", "No rice cooker? No problem!", "Wok cooking happens fast. Get fully set up before you start.", "Bring wok hei indoors with “torch hei”", "No wok? No gas? No problem! Cook fried rice in a cast iron skillet.", "Chinese vs. Japanese fried rice"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/omurice-fried-rice"}, {"id": 95, "t": "Canelés", "c": "Baking", "d": "A canelé is a classic French pastry made from eggs, milk, flour, butter, and sugar. These little two-bite morsels encapsulate everything you want in a pastry: a delicate balance of sweet and savory flavors and a crunchy caramelized crust that gives way to a custardy interior. Pastry enthusiasts who evangelize canelés will tell you that the real things are available only in some fairy tale town tuc", "i": ["750 g Whole milk", "375 g Granulated sugar", "70 g Unsalted butter , cut into 1/4-inch pieces", "100 g Egg yolk(s) , (about 7 large yolks)", "225 g Bread flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "75 g Dark rum", "4 g Kosher salt", "1 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped, seeds reserved, or 15 g vanilla extract (see “Before we begin” note), optional", "Neutral oil , for seasoning canelé molds , as needed", "120 g Beeswax , food-grade (see “Before we begin” note)", "120 g Clarified butter , homemade or store-bought", "4 g Salt"], "s": ["Heat milk and melt butter", "Make batter and chill overnight", "Season canelé molds", "Coat molds with beeswax and clarified butter", "Fill molds", "First phase bake to set exterior", "Second phase bake to finish", "Unmold and cool", "Bake more canelés", "Serve"], "tips": ["For the best canelés, age the batter.", "The importance of seasoning copper canelé molds", "Beeswax and clarified butter: the magic canelé coating", "No canelé molds? Here are some alternatives.", "Use the Breville+ Cooking app and Joule Oven Air Fryer Pro to hack the ultimate canelés.", "Determining canelé doneness", "Canelés: a pastry best served at room temp", "Mind your beeswax", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/caneles--2"}, {"id": 96, "t": "Chilaquiles", "c": "Baking", "d": "Chilaquiles—crisp fried tortilla chips simmered in salsa and topped with fried eggs—sit in the pantheon of great breakfast foods. When done right, they can be texturally amazing, with freshly fried tortilla chips that stay crispy even after being coated and tossed in sauce. And if that sauce uses as its base a brick-red salsa roja that’s made with charred tomatoes, roasted garlic, and toasted guaj", "i": ["330 g Corn tortillas , homemade or store-bought, (20 to 25 tortillas; see “Before we begin” note)", "290 g Salsa Roja , (see “Before we begin” note)", "110 g Water , or chicken stock", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "2 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon) plus extra as needed", "4 Egg(s) , large", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "100 g White onion(s) , (1/2 medium onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "Mexican crema , or sour cream, for serving , as needed", "Queso fresco , or farmer cheese or cotija cheese, crumbled, for serving , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving , as needed", "1 Serrano chile(s) , stemmed, thinly sliced into rounds, for serving", "360 g Quick and Easy Salsa Verde (Mexican Tomatillo Salsa)"], "s": ["Chilaquiles rojos vs. verdes vs. divorciados", "Cut and dehydrate tortillas", "Dilute and blend salsa", "Fry tortilla chips", "Cook eggs", "Cook chilaquiles", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["For the crispiest tortilla chips, dry before you fry.", "Want to make chilaquiles verdes instead?", "Dilute the salsa for more control over the final consistency."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chilaquiles"}, {"id": 97, "t": "Salsa Roja", "c": "Sauce", "d": "There are a million red salsas out there, but this Jalisco-style salsa roja is the one to beat. Charred tomatoes, roasted garlic, and toasted guajillo and árbol chiles combine to produce a beautiful brick-red condiment that’s got a lot of personality—heat from the árbol, fruitiness from the guajillo, sweetness and savoriness from the tomatoes (and a pinch of chicken bouillon powder for a little ex", "i": ["750 g Roma tomato(es) , (6 tomatoes) whole", "65 g Garlic clove(s) , unpeeled", "25 g Guajillo chile(s) , dried (5 chiles), stemmed and seeded", "1.5 g Chiles de árbol , dried (5 chiles), stemmed", "150 g Water , heated to 200 °F / 93 °C", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "5 g Chicken bouillon powder , Knorr brand (1 teaspoon), optional", "Citric acid , or 30 g fresh lime juice, optional"], "s": ["Broil tomatoes", "Toast garlic and chiles", "Blend salsa", "Put salsa to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Toast chiles; don’t burn ’em.", "Don’t overblend your salsa (unless you’re making chilaquiles).", "Adjust acidity with citric acid."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salsa-roja"}, {"id": 98, "t": "General Tso’s Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "General Tso’s chicken is about as American a dish as you can get—a mainstay in Chinese American restaurant menus across the country. Whether you call it General Tso’s, General Gau’s (we see you, New England), or General Ching’s, its origins are distinctly rooted in American tastes. T.T. Wang, a Chinese immigrant, learned the original recipe from Peng Chang-Kuei, a Hunanese chef who claims to have ", "i": ["450 g Chicken thighs , boneless, skinless (4 to 5 thighs)", "90 g Shaoxing wine , divided", "45 g Light soy sauce , divided", "30 g Egg white(s) , (from 1 large egg)", "3 g White pepper , ground (1 teaspoon), divided", "144 g Potato starch , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g Baking soda , (1/4 teaspoon)", "200 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "30 g Oyster sauce", "20 g Dark soy sauce", "20 g Granulated sugar", "15 g Ketchup", "15 g Rice vinegar", "15 g Toasted sesame oil", "3 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g All-purpose flour", "50 g Wheat dextrin , (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Baking powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "20 g Neutral oil , plus extra as needed for frying", "20 g Fresh ginger root , (1 1/4-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 medium cloves) finely grated", "5 g Facing heaven chile(s) , (4 to 6 chiles) dried, cut in half (see “Before we begin” note)", "Broccoli , cut into 2-inch florets, blanched, for serving, optional , as needed", "Jasmine rice , cooked, for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["The big three of Chinese American chicken", "Dice chicken thighs", "Mix and divide marinade", "Finish marinade and coat chicken", "Mix sauce", "Mix dredge", "Set up frying station", "Dredge chicken", "Fry chicken first time", "Double fry chicken", "Cook sauce and coat chicken", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Stir for a stickier marinade and better cling.", "Light vs. dark Chinese soy sauce: What’s the difference?", "Craftin’ crunch: The elements of the dredge", "Garnishing with a full plate of broccoli? Cook your broccoli now."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/general-tsos-chicken"}, {"id": 99, "t": "Orange Chicken", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Orange chicken is a fan favorite takeout menu item, just like General Tso’s, and it totally makes sense: Sweet, savory, lightly spiced, and packed with orange flavor, it’s got a little bit of everything nice (and it goes amazing with rice!). This recipe pays tribute to the original version of this dish (Hunanese Chenpi Ji) by using three sources for that distinctive orange flavor: fresh orange jui", "i": ["450 g Chicken thighs , boneless, skinless (4 to 5 thighs)", "90 g Shaoxing wine , divided", "45 g Light soy sauce , divided", "30 g Egg white(s) , (from 1 large egg)", "3 g White pepper , ground (1 teaspoon), divided", "143 g Potato starch , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g Baking soda , (1/4 teaspoon)", "5 g Dried mandarin peel(s) , (four 1-inch pieces; see “Before we begin” note)", "125 g Orange juice , fresh (from 1 large orange)", "75 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "30 g Granulated sugar", "25 g Oyster sauce", "20 g Dark soy sauce", "15 g Ketchup", "15 g Rice vinegar", "10 g Toasted sesame oil", "8 g Orange zest , finely grated (from 1 large orange)", "3 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g All-purpose flour", "50 g Wheat dextrin , (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Baking powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "20 g Neutral oil , plus extra as needed for frying", "20 g Fresh ginger root , (1 1/4-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 medium cloves) finely grated", "2 g Facing heaven chile(s) , (1 to 2 chiles) dried, cut in half (see “Before we begin” note)", "Jasmine rice , cooked, for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["The big three of Chinese American chicken", "Dice chicken thighs", "Mix and divide marinade", "Finish marinade and coat chicken", "Hydrate and clean mandarin peels", "Mix sauce", "Mix dredge", "Set up frying station", "Dredge chicken", "Fry chicken first time", "Double fry chicken", "Cook sauce and coat chicken", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Stir for a stickier marinade and better cling.", "Light vs. dark Chinese soy sauce: What’s the difference?", "Craftin’ crunch: The elements of the dredge"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/orange-chicken"}, {"id": 100, "t": "Sesame Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "Sesame chicken often takes a back seat to other takeout menu items like General Tso’s and Orange Chicken, and that's a shame. Sesame chicken has all the savory complexity of General Tso’s, but it’s also jam-packed with toasted sesame flavor, from both toasted sesame seeds and toasted sesame oil. Most importantly, it shares the same foundation of crispy fried chicken. Potato starch and wheat dextri", "i": ["450 g Chicken thighs , boneless, skinless (4 to 5 thighs)", "90 g Shaoxing wine , divided", "45 g Light soy sauce , divided", "30 g Egg white(s) , (from 1 large egg)", "3 g White pepper , ground (1 teaspoon), divided", "144 g Potato starch , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g Baking soda , (1/4 teaspoon)", "200 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "40 g Light brown sugar", "30 g Oyster sauce", "20 g Dark soy sauce", "15 g Ketchup", "15 g Rice vinegar", "35 g Toasted sesame oil , divided", "3 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g All-purpose flour", "50 g Wheat dextrin , (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Baking powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "20 g Neutral oil , plus extra as needed for frying", "20 g Fresh ginger root , (1 1/4-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 medium cloves) finely grated", "16 g Sesame seeds , toasted, plus extra as needed for serving", "Jasmine rice , cooked, for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["The big three of Chinese American chicken", "Dice chicken thighs", "Mix and divide marinade", "Finish marinade and coat chicken", "Mix sauce", "Mix dredge", "Set up frying station", "Dredge chicken", "Fry chicken first time", "Double fry chicken", "Make sauce and coat chicken", "Plate chicken and serve"], "tips": ["Stir for a stickier marinade and better cling.", "Light vs. dark Chinese soy sauce: What’s the difference?", "Craftin’ crunch: The elements of the dredge"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sesame-chicken"}, {"id": 101, "t": "Charred Zucchini With Green Tahini Dressing", "c": "Baking", "d": "There comes a point every summer when there’s just too much squash kicking around. Farmers can’t sell it fast enough, and gardeners find every excuse to off-load it to their unsuspecting neighbors. So, what’s a cook to do with all that zucchini overflowing in their CSA box? We’re here to help, with a little inspiration, a little bit of char, and a lot of flavor. Zucchini doesn’t have as much flavo", "i": ["920 g Zucchini , green (6 to 8 small zucchini; see “Before we begin” note)", "40 g Neutral oil , plus extra as needed", "200 g Sweet onion(s) , (1 medium onion) thinly sliced", "6 g Kosher salt", "2 g Baking soda , (1/4 teaspoon)", "2 g White pepper , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "30 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves and tender stems", "80 g Extra-virgin olive oil , plus extra as needed for serving", "60 g Ice water", "70 g Tahini", "40 g White miso paste", "60 g White wine vinegar", "8 g Macadamia nuts , toasted and chopped, for serving", "5 g Mint , fresh leaves (5 to 6 sprigs), large leaves torn, small leaves left whole", "Sesame seeds , toasted, for serving , as needed", "3 g Marjoram , fresh leaves (1 to 2 sprigs; see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Ricotta salata , shaved (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Slice zucchini", "Cook vegetables for sauce", "Blend sauce", "Prepare grill (optional)", "Char zucchini", "Marinate charred zucchini", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": ["Add baking soda for greener vegetables and smoother sauces.", "Plate it Nordic style."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/charred-zucchini-tahini-dressing"}, {"id": 102, "t": "Miso-Glazed Eggplant", "c": "Baking", "d": "Miso-glazed eggplant, or nasu dengaku, is a popular dish in Japanese izakaya, drinking establishments where the focus is on small bites. The custardy, silky, scoopable eggplant with a sweet-savory, deeply caramelized exterior is perfect for nibbling on between drinks. Despite its simplicity, it’s a dish that punches well above its weight. It’s richer than you’d expect and more aromatic and intense", "i": ["800 g Eggplant , Japanese or baby Italian (3 small eggplant; see “Before we begin” note)", "50 g Distilled vinegar", "6 g Kosher salt", "30 g Neutral oil", "40 g Red miso paste , (aka miso; see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Mirin", "12 g Light brown sugar", "Sesame seeds , toasted, for serving , as needed", "28 g Scallion(s) , (2 scallions) thinly sliced, for serving", "Bonito flakes , for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare eggplant", "Roast eggplant", "Make miso glaze", "Glaze and caramelize eggplant", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": ["Miso varieties", "Prevent enzymatic browning and improve texture with vinegar.", "Make it a complete meal."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/miso-glazed-eggplant"}, {"id": 103, "t": "Ultra-Cheesy Fondue Smash Burgers", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Is there anything better than a smash burger? Yes! A double smash burger, nestled in a skillet of bubbling, melty cheese sauce! When we saw the “Touch Down Burger” served at American Diner Andra in Tokyo, we knew we had to develop our own riff on it. We tweaked our Cheddar Cheese Sauce to withstand rapid evaporation when it hits a screaming-hot sizzle plate, and we tinkered with our Ultimate Smash", "i": ["150 g Aged white cheddar , coarsely grated", "150 g Low-moisture mozzarella , coarsely grated", "480 g Whole milk", "9 g Sodium citrate , (see “Before we begin” note)", "7.5 g Kosher salt , divided", "0.75 g Sodium hexametaphosphate , (1/8 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "14 g Cornstarch", "450 g Ground beef , 20% fat (1 pound; see “Before we begin” note)", "7 g Knox gelatin , (1 packet)", "30 g Neutral oil , divided", "4 American cheese , slices", "2 Potato bun(s) , homemade or store-bought, lightly toasted", "Ketchup , optional , as needed", "Fried shallots , for garnish, optional , as needed", "35 g Unsalted butter", "35 g All-purpose flour"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Bag up cheese mixture", "Melt cheese mixture", "Blend cheese sauce", "Season beef and form patties", "Cook burgers", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": ["Pass the melting salt(s) for a smooth cheese sauce.", "No melting salts? No problem! Make a roux-based cheese sauce.", "Cornstarch stabilizes the cheese sauce for serving it HOT.", "Meats en Place: How to set up a burger station", "Charge your cheese sauce into a foam."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fondue-smash-burgers"}, {"id": 104, "t": "White Castle-Style Sliders", "c": "Sauce", "d": "The biggest problem with White Castle is there aren’t that many of them—remember when they made a whole movie about this? Unless you live near one, or want to go on an all-night adventure looking for one, the closest you’ll get to eating a bunch of White Castle sliders is by paying a visit to the freezer aisle at the grocery store. But microwaved frozen sliders are, at best, a guilty pleasure and ", "i": ["900 g Ground beef , 20% fat (see “Before we begin” note)", "11 g Kosher salt , divided", "4.5 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (1 teaspoon)", "75 g Neutral oil , divided", "200 g White onion(s) , (1 medium onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "180 g Water , divided", "12 Potato slider bun(s) , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "12 American cheese , slices, homemade or store-bought, folded into 3-inch squares", "Ketchup , optional , as needed", "Dill pickles , homemade or store-bought, sliced, optional , as needed"], "s": ["ChefSteps Ultimate Sliders vs. White Castle-Style Sliders", "Mix ground beef", "Shape ground beef into sheets", "Form and freeze patties", "Portion patties", "Cook onions", "Cook sliders", "Serve"], "tips": ["Holey patties, Batman!", "Why don’t we cook the onions like they do at White Castle?", "Meats en Place: How to set up a burger station", "Got a big griddle? Cook all your sliders at once."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/white-castle-sliders"}, {"id": 105, "t": "Potato Burger Buns", "c": "Baking", "d": "A burger is nothing without its bun. And if you’re going the distance on crafting the perfect burger patty, you might as well go all the way and serve it on the best burger bun: the potato bun! Potato buns are softer, fluffier, slightly sweeter, and more shelf-stable than any run-of-the-mill wheat bun. And that’s because of the potatoes: Mashed potatoes contain a ton of gelatinized starch, and jus", "i": ["350 g Russet potato(es) , (1 medium potato)", "615 g Water , divided", "50 g Unsalted butter , softened to 68 °F / 20 °C, cut into 4 pieces", "2 Egg(s) , large, divided", "40 g Honey", "0.5 g Ground tumeric , optional (1/8 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "400 g Bread flour , plus extra as needed for dusting", "8.5 g Instant dry yeast , (see “Before we begin” note)", "11 g Kosher salt , divided", "Sesame seeds , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Burger vs. slider buns", "Cook potato", "Mash potato with butter and wet ingredients", "Mix dough and rest", "Mix in salt and knead dough", "Proof dough", "Fold and chill dough", "Divide and shape buns", "Flatten buns and final proof", "Egg wash and bake buns", "Put buns to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Supercharge the water in your bread with potato skins.", "Mashed potatoes are another way to unlocking fluffy texture in breads.", "Rest dough to reduce mixing time and kick-start gluten development.", "Use coil folds in high-hydration doughs to build gluten and redistribute gases.", "Secure your stand mixer.", "How to turn your oven into a dough proofer", "Chill dough to slow down proofing and improve dough handling.", "How to make potato slider buns", "How to make foil rings for perfect burger buns", "The best way to determine level of proof"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/potato-burger-buns"}, {"id": 106, "t": "Classic Char Siu", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Good char siu is basically meat candy. Lightly sweet, super savory, and tender, but with a little bite, it’s the benchmark for many Cantonese barbecue, or siu mei, shops. That’s why you’ll see lightly charred slabs of mahogany-red roast pork hanging front and center in Chinatown shop windows. Unlike our Sous Vide Char Siu, this recipe is our take on the way char siu is traditionally prepared: mari", "i": ["1.5 kg Pork collar , or boneless pork shoulder (see “Before we begin” note)", "200 g Light soy sauce", "150 g Hoisin sauce", "100 g Granulated sugar", "75 g Chinese rose wine , (see “Before we begin” note)", "50 g Oyster sauce", "50 g Red fermented bean curd , (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Red yeast rice , ground (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 medium cloves) finely grated", "15 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "15 g Toasted sesame oil", "5 g White pepper , ground (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "3 g Five-spice powder , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "0.25 g Prague powder #1 , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g Maltose syrup , (see “Before we begin note)", "30 g Water , (only needed if cooking on a charcoal grill)"], "s": ["Butcher pork collar", "Make marinade", "Marinate pork", "Slow cook pork", "Make maltose glaze", "Glaze and char pork", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Split the collar into steaks to dial in doneness.", "Getting that iconic char siu color", "Use the same marinade for Cantonese barbecue spareribs.", "Portion super-sticky syrups with wet hands."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/classic-char-siu"}, {"id": 107, "t": "Chinese Barbecue Ribs", "c": "Baking", "d": "While char siu often gets all the attention at Chinatown siu mei shops, but Cantonese barbecue spareribs are also amazing. Think of all the fatty, lightly charred, slightly chewy bits of char siu, concentrated in rib form. This recipe is virtually identical to our char siu recipe, with a few tweaks to optimize the cooking process for ribs. Just like with the char siu, we use a two-stage cooking pr", "i": ["1 St. Louis-style pork ribs , slab (1.3 to 1.6 kg; 3 to 3 1/2 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "200 g Light soy sauce", "150 g Hoisin sauce", "100 g Granulated sugar", "75 g Chinese rose wine , (see “Before we begin” note)", "50 g Oyster sauce", "50 g Red fermented bean curd , (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Red yeast rice , ground (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 medium cloves) finely grated", "15 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "15 g Toasted sesame oil", "5 g White pepper , ground (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "3 g Five-spice powder , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "0.25 g Prague powder #1 , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g Maltose syrup , (see “Before we begin note)", "30 g Water , (only needed if cooking on a charcoal grill)"], "s": ["Separate ribs", "Make marinade", "Marinate ribs", "Slow cook ribs", "Make maltose glaze", "Glaze and broil ribs", "Serve"], "tips": ["Getting that iconic red color", "Use the same marinade for char siu.", "Portion super-sticky syrups with wet hands."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chinese-barbecue-ribs"}, {"id": 108, "t": "Ice Cream: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "Ice cream is so commonplace that it’s easy to forget how incredible it is. It isn’t just that it’s one of the most delicious creations humans have ever devised—creamy, sweet, and cold—for summer eating. It’s that it’s a technological marvel, a substance that is liquid, solid, and gas at the same time. Add in the fact that the word “ice cream” refers to a range of preparations, all frozen and cream", "i": [], "s": ["The Infographic", "The Elements of Ice Cream", "The Ice Creams", "Ice Milk (Stella Parks, Serious Eats)", "Soft Serve (ChefSteps)", "Jersey Milk Ice Cream (ChefSteps)", "Fior di Latte Gelato (Paolo Brunelli, Avanguardia Gelato)", "Frozen Custard (ChefSteps)", "Vanilla Ice Cream (Thomas Keller, The French Laundry, Per Se)", "Egg-Free Vanilla Ice Cream (ChefSteps)", "Vanilla Bean Ice Cream (ChefSteps)", "The sweet math of dessert parametrics"], "tips": ["Ice Cream Is All About Ice", "Sugars in Ice Cream", "How Commercial Soft Serve Machines Work", "Dairy", "How Commercial Gelato Machines Work", "Gelato vs. Ice Cream: What’s the Difference?", "How the Pacojet and CREAMi Work", "Pacojet vs. CREAMi: What’s the Difference?", "Overrun, Explained", "Eggs, Ice Cream, and Frozen Custard", "Emulsifiers and Stabilizers", "Churning Ice Cream With Dry Ice or Liquid Nitrogen", "Putting the Vanilla in Ice Cream"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ice-cream-parametric"}, {"id": 109, "t": "Yogurt Ice Cream", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is payback for all the times you’ve had frozen yogurt and wished you were eating ice cream instead. Frozen yogurt always sounds good in theory. A sweet, creamy, and light frozen treat, with a little of that lactic acid tang. You could brighten it up with fresh fruit, but it shouldn’t need it. But a lot of the time, frozen yogurt isn’t good; a lot of the time, it’s just kind of icy. Our", "i": ["110 g Granulated sugar", "50 g Nonfat dry milk powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Locust bean gum , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.6 g Guar gum , (1/8 teaspoon)", "0.4 g Lambda carrageenan , (1/8 teaspoon)", "150 g Whole milk", "100 g Heavy cream", "110 g Glucose syrup , (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Honey", "470 g Greek yogurt , whole milk, or labneh (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Vanilla extract , optional (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Combine dry ingredients", "Heat ice cream base", "Blend ice cream base", "Chill ice cream base", "Freeze base if using Pacoject or CREAMi (optional)", "Churn or spin ice cream", "Serve or freeze"], "tips": ["Improving texture with ice cream stabilizers", "For the best flavor, add yogurt and vanilla extract off-heat.", "Blend the base for better ice cream.", "For the best ice cream, age the base.", "Use a loaf pan as an ice cream storage container.", "Temper rock-hard ice cream in the fridge."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/yogurt-ice-cream"}, {"id": 110, "t": "Jersey Milk Ice Cream", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is an ice cream that’s all about milk. Originally conceived as a component in the Farm and Garden salad course for a spring tasting menu, the idea was to provide a bright and light palate-cleansing ice cream that helps dress the salad as it melts. Sweet and savory, with the inimitable flavor of good milk, it works so well that we reprised it for our Winter Studio Dinner Experience. But when w", "i": ["690 g Whole milk , highest quality possible (see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g Heavy cream", "60 g Granulated sugar", "44 g Nonfat dry milk powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "6 g Kosher salt", "100 g Glucose syrup , (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Heat ice cream base", "Blend ice cream base", "Chill ice cream base", "Freeze base if using a Pacojet or CREAMi (optional)", "Churn or spin ice cream", "Serve"], "tips": ["Using raw milk? Concerned about food safety? Pasteurize it.", "Blend the base for better ice cream.", "For the best ice cream, age the base.", "Use a loaf pan as an ice cream storage container."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/jersey-milk-ice-cream"}, {"id": 111, "t": "Vanilla Bean Ice Cream", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This is it: the best vanilla ice cream. If you’ve ever been guilty of using “vanilla” to mean “ordinary,” you need to try this ice cream! Because vanilla beans are a miracle. Made from the seed pods of an orchid, which has to be pollinated and harvested by hand, the pods are cured, dried, and aged to produce the constellation of aromas and flavors that we have named “vanilla.” Extracts and pastes ", "i": ["390 g Heavy cream", "354 g Whole milk", "160 g Granulated sugar", "80 g Egg yolk(s) , (about 6 large yolks)", "20 g Nonfat dry milk powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "1 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped, seeds and pod reserved separately", "8 g Vanilla extract , (see “Before we begin” note)", "Ice water , for chilling , as needed"], "s": ["Cook ice cream base", "Blend ice cream base", "Chill ice cream base", "Freeze base if using a Pacojet or CREAMi (optional)", "Churn or spin ice cream", "Serve or freeze"], "tips": ["Two types of vanilla? In this economy?", "For hands-off perfection, cook ice cream base sous vide.", "Blend the base for better ice cream.", "For the best ice cream, age the base.", "Use a loaf pan as an ice cream storage container.", "Temper rock-hard ice cream in the fridge.", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vanilla-bean-ice-cream"}, {"id": 112, "t": "Frozen Custard", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’ve had the pleasure of visiting the great American Midwest, you’ve likely licked your fair share of frozen custard—a dense and creamy frozen treat that is said to have been invented in New York but is undeniably loved best in our nation’s middle section. Frozen custard is all about eggy richness and flavor; after all, it’s basically a frozen crème anglaise. Cooking the custard base with pre", "i": ["505 g Heavy cream", "116 g Whole milk", "175 g Granulated sugar", "150 g Egg yolk(s) , (about 10 large yolks)", "35 g Nonfat dry milk powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "8 g Vanilla extract , (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Salt", "Ice , for chilling , as needed", "Water , for chilling , as needed", "Dry ice , about 1 kg , as needed"], "s": ["Cook custard base", "Blend base", "Chill base", "Freeze base if using a Pacojet or CREAMi (optional)", "Churn or spin frozen custard", "Serve or freeze"], "tips": ["For hands-off perfection, cook ice cream base sous vide.", "Blend the base for better ice cream.", "For maximum vanilla impact, add extract off-heat.", "For the best ice cream, age the base.", "How to add mix-ins", "Why make frozen custard in a stand mixer?", "Use a loaf pan as an ice cream storage container.", "Temper rock-hard ice cream in the fridge.", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/this-frozen-custard-is-one-smooth-sonuvagun"}, {"id": 113, "t": "Soft Serve Ice Cream", "c": "Baking", "d": "Soft serve ice cream should be light on the palate, but rich and creamy in texture. Achieving this contrast requires a base packed with milk solids but relatively little sugar. (“Relatively” being the operative word—it’s ice cream, after all. There’s going to be some sugar involved.) It’s now a well-known formula originally developed by rival ice cream monarchs Carvel and Dairy Queen, both of whic", "i": ["700 g Whole milk", "155 g Granulated sugar", "70 g Heavy cream", "66 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "2 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon)", "8 g Vanilla extract , pure (see “Before we begin” note)", "3.5 g Salt"], "s": ["Heat soft serve base", "Blend soft serve base", "Chill soft serve base", "Freeze base if using a Pacojet or CREAMi (optional)", "Churn soft serve ice cream", "Pipe and serve"], "tips": ["Blend the base for better ice cream.", "For maximum vanilla impact, add extract off-heat.", "For the best ice cream, age the base.", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/soft-serve-ice-cream"}, {"id": 114, "t": "Egg-Free Vanilla Ice Cream", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Classic French vanilla ice cream, with its characteristic golden hue, is as decadent as ice cream gets. The yolks in the rich custard base contribute to a smooth, easily churned scoop that melts slowly. The problem? It’s unmistakably eggy in flavor. We wanted to bring vanilla to the forefront without losing the richness and texture that egg yolks provide. A blend of locust bean gum, guar gum, and ", "i": ["160 g Granulated sugar", "40 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "2 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon)", "1 g Locust bean gum , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.6 g Guar gum , (1/8 teaspoon)", "0.4 g Lambda carrageenan , (1/8 teaspoon)", "450 g Whole milk", "350 g Heavy cream", "1 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped, seeds and pod reserved separately", "8 g Vanilla extract , (see “Before we begin” note)", "0.4 g Xanthan gum", "0.1 g Carrageenan, kappa"], "s": ["Combine dry ingredients", "Cook ice cream base", "Blend ice cream base", "Chill ice cream base", "Freeze ice cream base if using Pacoject or CREAMi (optional)", "Churn or spin ice cream", "Serve or freeze"], "tips": ["Improving texture with ice cream stabilizers", "For hands-off perfection, cook ice cream base sous vide.", "Blend the base for better ice cream.", "Two types of vanilla? In this economy?", "For the best ice cream, age the base.", "Why make ice cream in a stand mixer?", "Use a loaf pan as an ice cream storage container.", "Temper rock-hard ice cream in the fridge.", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/egg-free-vanilla-ice-cream"}, {"id": 115, "t": "How to Make Ice Cream With Liquid Nitrogen", "c": "Baking", "d": "The faster you freeze ice cream, the more delicious it will be. Great ice cream is all about forming the tiniest ice crystals possible, and for that, you need speed. The reason most countertop ice cream makers churn out icy, grainy ice cream is simply that they don’t have the freezing power of commercial machines. But liquid nitrogen does: It is super-charged freezing fuel! It sits at a frigid -32", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 4 l Liquid nitrogen , (see “Before we begin” note) 1 kg Ice cream base , (see “Before we begin” note)", "4 l Liquid nitrogen , (see “Before we begin” note) 1 kg Ice cream base , (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 kg Ice cream base , (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Liquid nitrogen vs. dry ice", "Churn ice cream base", "Torch bowl and continue churning", "Serve or freeze"], "tips": ["The original video", "Whip the ice cream to increase overrun.", "Use a loaf pan as an ice cream storage container."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/liquid-nitrogen-churned-ice-cream"}, {"id": 116, "t": "How to Make Ice Cream With Dry Ice", "c": "Baking", "d": "Ice cream is a matrix of tons of tiny air bubbles; ice crystals trapped in viscous, sugar-laden water; and tiny fat droplets that form a smooth, creamy, sweet frozen treat. But to yield that smooth, decadent consistency—rather than a coarse, grainy one—the ice crystals need to be really fine. The secret to small ice crystals? You gotta freeze the ice cream base fast. Trouble is: an enormous amount", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1.5 kg Dry ice , (see “Dry ice FAQ”) 1 kg Ice cream base , (see “Before we begin” note)", "1.5 kg Dry ice , (see “Dry ice FAQ”) 1 kg Ice cream base , (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 kg Ice cream base , (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Dry ice FAQ", "Dry ice vs. liquid nitrogen", "Process dry ice into a powder", "Churn ice cream base", "Rest ice cream to allow dry ice to fully sublimate", "Serve or freeze"], "tips": ["The original video", "Why it’s important to turn dry ice into a powder", "Whip the ice cream to increase overrun.", "Use a loaf pan as an ice cream storage container."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/making-ice-cream-with-dry-ice"}, {"id": 117, "t": "Cebollitas (Charred Knob Onions)", "c": "Sauce", "d": "No Mexican asada is complete without a side of cebollitas. Like a good salsa, cebollitas really tie the room—and a plate of tacos—together. They’re as simple as can be: charred knob onions with a tender bulb the size of your thumb, attached to a short length of the lower stem. Rather than just tossing raw onions on the grill and hoping for the best, we confit them first in lard until the bulbs are", "i": ["625 g Lard , (see “Before we begin” note)", "350 g Knob onions , or spring onions (about 12 onions), root ends trimmed and darker green parts removed (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Confit onions", "Char onions", "Serve"], "tips": ["Have outdoor space? Grill the cebollitas instead!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cebollitas"}, {"id": 118, "t": "Guacasalsa", "c": "Baking", "d": "Guacasalsa isn’t guacamole. And you won’t have to break the bank for a bag of avocados like some irresponsible millennial to make it, because it doesn’t contain avocados at all. Sometimes called salsa falsa (“fake sauce”), guacasalsa is one of Mexico’s greatest taco toppers and culinary slights of hand. Its super creamy and bright green appearance is giving avocado, but you won’t find any in the i", "i": ["135 g Neutral oil", "180 g White onion(s) , (1 medium onion) cut into 1/2-inch dice", "170 g Serrano chile(s) , (10 to 12 chiles) stemmed and thinly sliced into rounds (see “Before we begin” note)", "50 g Garlic clove(s) , (10 medium cloves) whole", "9 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "30 g Cilantro , (1 bunch) whole sprigs", "70 g Water , plus extra as needed", "Citric acid , or fresh lime juice, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Cook vegetables", "Blanch cilantro", "Blend salsa", "Put salsa to use or store for later", "Make ahead and storage", "Spice up your life with salsa"], "tips": ["How to use emulsified salsas", "Adjust acidity with citric acid."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/guacasalsa"}, {"id": 119, "t": "American Toast (ChefSteps Breakfast Egg)", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Hello, breakfast! Ooey-gooey sous vide egg yolk, Fried Egg White Foam, and smoky maple syrup—all delicately layered in a cup. That’s how we do first meal. But who are we kidding? This is a killer dish for any time of day. This recipe was originally inspired by Alain Passard’s l’Arpège Egg. Passard’s dish consists of a perfectly poached egg yolk topped with a sherry vinegar–infused cream and a driz", "i": ["90 g Egg yolk(s) , (6 large yolks)", "100 g Maple syrup , (see “Before we begin” note)", "2.5 g Liquid smoke , (1/2 teaspoon), plus more as needed", "Flake sea salt , for serving , as needed", "1 recipe Fried Egg White Foam , warm, held in 140 °F / 60 °C sous vide bath", "Sweet Spice, as needed", "75 g Brioche , 2 1/2-inch slices) homemade or store-bought, crusts removed and cut into 1/2-inch cubes", "Salt, as needed"], "s": ["Two ways to serve the ChefSteps Breakfast Egg", "Heat sous vide bath", "Bag yolks", "Cook yolks", "Make smoked maple syrup", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": ["How to make egg cups for serving", "Go the extra mile with decorated egg cups.", "Turn your water bath into a hot holding station.", "Add brioche for a breakfast course of champions", "Test the foam before plating.", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-toast"}, {"id": 120, "t": "Fried Egg White Foam", "c": "Sauce", "d": "You know that slightly sweet, caramelized flavor of a crisp-edged fried egg? This luscious and creamy fried egg white foam captures that flavor and turns it into an ethereal sauce. This foam is a key component in our American Toast (aka The ChefSteps Breakfast Egg) recipe, our riff on Alain Passard’s l’Arpège Egg. But it’s also great on a seared steak or as a hollandaise substitute for eggs Benedi", "i": ["45 g Neutral oil", "180 g Egg white(s) , (from 6 large eggs)", "310 g Heavy cream", "260 g Whole milk", "10 g Kosher salt", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground, (1/2 teaspoon)", "Silver gelatin, 170 bloom , (2 1/2 sheets), or 4 g Knox powdered gelatin", "5 Egg(s) , large", "9 g Salt", "Oil , for frying , as needed", "5 g Gelatin , 140 bloom", "260 g Cream"], "s": ["Brown egg whites", "Dissolve gelatin", "Blend and strain", "Charge whipping siphon", "Put egg white foam to use or hold warm"], "tips": ["Strain the base to avoid whipping siphon clogs.", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fried-egg-white-foam"}, {"id": 121, "t": "Sweet Spice", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This aromatic and versatile warm-spice blend is inspired by the spices traditionally used in French pain d’épices, a sweetened quick bread with an anise-forward flavor profile. We use it to add complexity to all kinds of preparations—from tasting menu dishes, such as our American Toast (aka The ChefSteps Breakfast Egg), to desserts like pumpkin and apple pies, as well as savory recipes like holida", "i": ["40 g Star anise , (see “Before we begin” note)", "16 g Ginger , ground", "12 g Vanilla bean , (about 4 vanilla beans) cut into 1-inch pieces", "12 g Black peppercorns , whole", "12 g Cinnamon stick(s) , (1 1/2 sticks)", "10 g Dried orange peel", "6 g Nutmeg , whole (1 piece)"], "s": ["Grind and sift spices", "Put to use or store for later"], "tips": ["The original Sweet Spice video", "Don’t skip the sift"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sweet-spice"}, {"id": 122, "t": "Ultimate Sunday Roast", "c": "Baking", "d": "There isn’t anything more British than the Sunday roast. A centerpiece “joint” served with Yorkshire puddings, crispy roast potatoes, and a few bites of veg, everything doused in a rich gravy … it’s a meal fit for the King. Like the full English breakfast and fish and chips, it’s hearty in the way of cold, Northern country cuisines, but then it’s also got all those odd-to-American-ears Britishisms", "i": ["1 Bottom round roast , fat cap on, silver skin removed (about 4.2 kg; 9 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt , (1.4% of the weight of beef roast), plus extra for gravy , as needed", "Black peppercorns , whole (0.4% of the weight of beef roast) , as needed", "Fennel seeds , whole (0.4% of the weight of beef roast) , as needed", "500 g Onion(s) , (2 onions) cut into 1 1/2-inch pieces", "300 g Carrot(s) , (2 medium carrots) peeled and cut into 1 1/2-inch pieces", "200 g Celery , (4 ribs) cut into 1 1/2-inch pieces", "1 Garlic head(s) , halved crosswise", "45 g Extra-virgin olive oil , or neutral oil", "8 g Thyme , (10 fresh sprigs), divided", "6 g Rosemary , (4 fresh sprigs), divided", "10 g All-purpose flour", "500 g Beef Stock , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "45 g Worcestershire sauce , plus extra as needed", "15 g Sherry vinegar , plus extra as needed", "40 g Dijon mustard", "35 g Horseradish , fresh, peeled and grated", "30 g Heavy cream", "1 recipe Perfect Yorkshire Puddings , for serving", "1 recipe Ultra-Crispy Roast Potatoes , for serving", "1 recipe Simple Buttered Vegetables , for serving"], "s": ["Elements of a Sunday roast", "The Sunday roast timeline", "Season beef roast", "High-temperature roast to crisp fat cap", "Low-temperature roast to finish beef", "Rest roast and make gravy", "Make horseradish cream", "Slice beef and serve"], "tips": ["Stick to the timeline: Make Yorkshire pudding batter", "Stick to the timeline: Bake Yorkshire puddings and parboil potatoes", "Stick to the timeline: Roast the potatoes", "Stick to the timeline: Finish the potatoes", "Stick to the timeline: Parboil carrots and cabbage", "Simmer roux-based sauces to maximize thickening potential", "Stick to the timeline: Reheat Yorkshire puddings, potatoes, and veg"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-sunday-roast"}, {"id": 123, "t": "Ultra-Crispy Roast Potatoes", "c": "Baking", "d": "There are tons of ways to roast potatoes, but this is one area in which Brits really excel. They might just make the best crispy roast potatoes ever. They start by parboiling extra-large chunks of potato until the outsides are softened and the surface starches are gelatinized, but the interiors are still raw. The parboiled pieces get aggressively tossed to rough them up, producing a fluffy, mashed", "i": ["1.8 kg Russet potato(es) , (about 5 large potatoes) peeled and cut crosswise into 2-inch-thick pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "250 g Beef fat , or neutral oil (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Rosemary , (10 sprigs) fresh leaves, finely chopped", "Flake sea salt , for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["The Sunday Roast", "Parboil potatoes", "Heat fat", "Roast potatoes", "Add rosemary and finish potatoes", "Serve"], "tips": ["For the crispiest potatoes, rough them up.", "Bigger is better"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultra-crispy-roast-potatoes"}, {"id": 124, "t": "Simple Buttered Vegetables", "c": "Meat", "d": "Vegetable side dishes are often either an afterthought or a burden, either a perfunctory nod to “health” or unnecessarily complicated. This side of boiled and buttered vegetables is proof that a simple side dish can be amazing. With little more than a pile of humble carrots and a head of cabbage, you can put together a delicious side dish that complements almost anything—a classic British Sunday r", "i": ["1 kg Savoy cabbage , (1 head) outer leaves removed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "500 g Carrot(s) , (about 7 medium carrots) scrubbed", "113 g Unsalted butter , (1 stick) softened, divided", "White pepper , ground , as needed", "28 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves and tender stems, finely chopped"], "s": ["The Sunday roast", "Prep cabbage", "Parboil carrots", "Parboil cabbage", "Finish with butter and parsley", "Serve"], "tips": ["Making a full Sunday roast? Wait to finish the vegetables."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/buttered-vegetables"}, {"id": 125, "t": "Perfect Yorkshire Puddings", "c": "Baking", "d": "You can’t have a British Sunday roast without Yorkshire puddings—airy, crispy, eggy, and hollow, they’re the perfect vessel for gravy, designed to be filled up and munched on as you graze your way across the plate of roast beef, crispy roast potatoes, and tender, buttery vegetables. The key to getting the impressive loft, crispy browned exterior, and cavernous interior of a great Yorkie is pouring", "i": ["4 Egg(s) , large", "140 g All-purpose flour", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "200 g Whole milk", "30 g Cold water , plus extra as needed", "90 g Beef fat , or neutral oil (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["The Sunday Roast", "Make batter", "Heat fat", "Bake Yorkshire puddings", "Continue baking to dry out puddings (optional)", "Serve"], "tips": ["Add water to the batter for crispier, puffier puddings.", "Rest the batter for taller, crispier, and airier puddings.", "Hot fat is essential for maximum rise.", "Extend the bake for crispy, tall Yorkies that won’t collapse."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/yorkshire-pudding"}, {"id": 126, "t": "Make-Ahead Bacon, Egg, and Cheese", "c": "Baking", "d": "Ask any professional cook, and they’ll tell you that making breakfast for a crowd can be a nightmare. And the same is true at home. Whether you’re cooking for the fam or hosting a weekend brunch, the last thing you want to be doing is cosplaying as a short order cook early on a Sunday morning before the coffee has kicked in. That’s where these streamlined BECs come into play. Using our make-ahead ", "i": ["12 Bacon , slices", "45 g Mayonnaise", "30 g Ketchup", "15 g Tabasco sauce , or other hot sauce of choice, optional", "1 recipe Silky Baked Egg Patties , (see “Before we begin” note)", "4 Hamburger bun(s) , or English muffins, split", "4 American cheese , slices, homemade or store-bought, optional"], "s": ["Two paths to quick and easy breakfast sandwiches"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/make-ahead-bacon-egg-and-cheese"}, {"id": 127, "t": "Silky Baked Egg Patties", "c": "Baking", "d": "If there’s anything that hammers home “convenience is king,” it’s a breakfast sandwich. Making one is easy, but most people just buy them on the way to work. Even just scrambling a couple eggs feels like a lot most mornings. We get it! Stars Chefs—they’re just like us! That’s why we came up with these silky-smooth baked egg patties, the make-ahead cheat code to killer at-home egg sandwiches, any d", "i": ["9 Egg(s) , large", "185 g Whole milk", "90 g Heavy cream", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoons)"], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/baked-egg-patties"}, {"id": 128, "t": "Make-Ahead Ham and Egg Breakfast Sandwich", "c": "Baking", "d": "Picture this: It’s Tuesday morning, and you’re rushing to get ready for work where you’re on deck first thing for a big presentation. You’ve got to shower, chug a big cup of coffee, and get out the door, stat. There’s a lot on your mind, but what you’re really thinking about is a breakfast sandwich. You don’t have time to make a detour to your favorite café, but you don’t need to. Because you thou", "i": ["1 Silky Baked Egg Patties , (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 Hamburger bun(s) , or English muffins, split", "2 Black Forest ham , slices, optional", "1 American cheese , slices, homemade or store-bought, optional", "15 g Ketchup , optional", "15 g Mayonnaise , optional", "15 g Relish , optional", "Arugula , optional , as needed"], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/make-ahead-ham-and-egg-breakfast-sandwich"}, {"id": 129, "t": "Hi-Tech Mushroom Burger", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Not so long ago, grilled portobello “burgers” were often the only vegetarian option at most restaurants. While no one wants to go back to those dark days, there’s a reason why mushrooms were the go-to option for meat-free foods. Earthy, complex, and super savory, they can be as satisfying and delicious as a juicy steak. So why not make a mushroom burger more burger-like? Taking a cue from U.K.-bas", "i": ["750 g Cremini mushrooms , (see “Before we begin” note)", "25 g Sodium caseinate , or micellar casein powder (see “Before we begin” note)", "25 g Activa RM , (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoons), plus extra for seasoning", "1 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (1/2 teaspoon)", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "60 g Unsalted butter , or neutral oil, divided", "Swiss cheese , slices, optional , as needed", "Hamburger bun(s) , homemade or store-bought, lightly toasted , as needed", "Mayonnaise , optional , as needed", "Ketchup , optional , as needed", "Lettuce , whole leaves, optional , as needed", "Tomato(es) , sliced, optional , as needed", "1.5 kg Mushrooms", "10 g Salt"], "s": ["Clean mushrooms", "Roast mushrooms", "Grind mushrooms", "Make mushroom burger mixture", "Form and chill patties", "Cook mushroom burgers", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": ["How to maximize yield with a meat grinder", "Meat grinder vs. food processor", "Getting mushrooms to bind", "For a snappier patty, bump up the casein.", "Use gloves when working with Activa", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hi-tech-mushroom-burger"}, {"id": 130, "t": "Mushroom Whiskey", "c": "Baking", "d": "Mushroom whiskey! Sounds weird, but it tastes delicious. It’s what happens when you combine the earthy, savory notes of mushrooms and the smooth, oaky flavors of good hooch, and it’s an endlessly versatile ingredient. Drink it on the rocks, use it in the most complex old-fashioned you’ve ever had, make an epic au poivre pan sauce ... you get the idea. Infusions are one of the oldest practices in c", "i": ["750 g Cremini mushrooms , fresh (see “Before we begin” note)", "750 g Whiskey , (see “Before we begin” note)", "60 g Mushroom Whiskey", "30 g Sweet vermouth", "2 drop Angostura bitters", "2 drop", "Orange peel, as needed", "5 g Water", "5 g Maple syrup"], "s": ["Clean mushrooms", "Slice mushrooms", "Roast mushrooms", "Combine roasted mushrooms with whiskey", "Pasteurize mushroom whiskey", "Steep whiskey", "Strain mushroom whiskey", "Put mushroom whiskey to use", "drop"], "tips": ["The key to infusions is maximizing the surface area.", "When canning, seal jars “fingertip” tight to ensure a proper seal and avoid accidents.", "Pasteurization eliminates any possible worry of foodborne pathogens for infused alcohol.", "Use a coffee filter for super-clear mushroom whiskey", "Don’t toss out those ‘shrooms!", "Make a mushroom Manhattan", "Make a mushroom old-fashioned"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/mushroom-whiskey"}, {"id": 131, "t": "Chicken Fat Dinner Rolls", "c": "Baking", "d": "You know how the best bite of a roast chicken dinner is that bit of bread you swipe through the drippings? Well, we turned that perfect bite into an epic, ultra-fluffy dinner roll! We served these chicken fat rolls alongside Poulet Farci for our Winter Studio Dinner Experience. The challenge was to incorporate the savory flavors of roast chicken into an ultra-fluffy dinner roll with staying power ", "i": ["346 g Bread flour , divided, plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "120 g Water", "135 g Whole milk , divided", "2 Egg(s) , large, divided", "6 g Instant dry yeast , (see “Before we begin” note)", "25 g Granulated sugar", "6 g Kosher salt , divided", "9 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , finely ground, divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "57 g Unsalted butter , (1/2 stick) softened to 68 °F / 20 °C and cut into 1-inch pieces", "130 g Chicken fat , rendered and melted, divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "120 g Whole milk 1 Egg(s) , large"], "s": ["Make tangzhong", "Whisk in milk and egg", "Mix dough and rest", "Mix in sugar, salt, and bouillon powder", "Add fats and knead dough", "Proof dough", "Divide and shape rolls", "Final proof", "Egg wash and bake rolls", "Brush with chicken fat and finish baking", "Serve"], "tips": ["Tangzhong is the key to unlocking amazing texture and shelf stability.", "Rest the dough to reduce mixing time and kick-start gluten development.", "Secure your stand mixer.", "Gauge gluten development with a windowpane test.", "How to turn your oven into a dough proofer", "Dividing and shaping for different pan sizes", "Two ways to determine level of proof", "Gilding the lily with chicken salt butter"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-fat-dinner-rolls"}, {"id": 132, "t": "Heat vs. Temperature: What’s the Difference?", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "What’s the difference between heat and temperature? While people often use these terms interchangeably, there’s a simple kitchen experiment that demonstrates how these two concepts are distinct from one another. Heat a sous vide bath to 140 °F / 60 °C and float two bowls in it—one containing water and the other containing oil. Give the liquids time to come up to temperature, and use a thermometer ", "i": [], "s": ["Defining Heat and Temperature", "Observing Heat and Temperature in the Kitchen", "The science of cooking"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/heat-versus-temperature"}, {"id": 133, "t": "Taiwanese Fried Chicken Cutlet (Dà Jī Pái)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Walk around in Taiwan’s famous night markets, and you’ll see people chowing down on hulking, bigger-than-your face cutlets of hot, crispy fried chicken. Bubbly, craggy, fragrantly spiced and super juicy, dà jī pái (which literally translates to “big chicken cutlet”) is Taiwanese popcorn chicken, super-sized. The shops that specialize in dà jī pái—like Hot Star, for instance—use massive deep fryers", "i": ["2 Chicken breast(s) , boneless, skinless (about 400 g; 14 ounces each)", "75 g Light soy sauce", "60 g Mijiu , or sake (see “Before we begin” note)", "7 g White pepper , ground, divided", "3 g Five-spice powder , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "5 g Sichuan chile powder , (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1/2 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Granulated sugar , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Rice vinegar powder , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "85 g Tapioca starch", "30 g Egg white(s) , (from 1 large egg), plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "400 g Coarse sweet potato starch , (see “Before we begin” note)", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed"], "s": ["Two ways to Taiwanese fried chicken", "Butterfly chicken breasts", "Marinate chicken", "Make seasoning powder (optional)", "Thicken marinade and coat chicken", "Set up frying station", "Dredge chicken", "Fry chicken first time", "Double fry chicken", "Wrap or slice cutlets and serve"], "tips": ["For more five-spice forward fried chicken, skip the seasoning powder.", "Adjusting marinade consistency with egg whites", "Two starches, in this economy??", "Don’t dredge all your chicken at once.", "Make a parchment pouch for that legit night market experience."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/taiwanese-fried-chicken-cutlet"}, {"id": 134, "t": "Taiwanese Popcorn Chicken (Yán Sū Jī)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Wander around any of Taiwan’s famous night markets, and you’ll see shops selling heaps of piping hot, fried popcorn chicken. Craggy and unbelievably crispy, Taiwanese fried chicken has exploded in popularity since its introduction in the 1970s. What makes yán sū jī (which translates to “salt crispy chicken”) special? For one, it’s far crispier than any American popcorn chicken—sorry, Colonel. That", "i": ["800 g Chicken thighs , boneless, skinless (6 to 8 thighs)", "75 g Light soy sauce", "60 g Mijiu , or sake (see “Before we begin” note)", "7 g White pepper , ground, divided", "3 g Five-spice powder , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "5 g Sichuan chile powder , (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1/2 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Granulated sugar , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Rice vinegar powder , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "85 g Tapioca starch", "30 g Egg white(s) , (from 1 large egg)", "400 g Coarse sweet potato starch , (see “Before we begin” note)", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "25 g Thai basil , fresh leaves, optional"], "s": ["Two ways to Taiwanese fried chicken", "Dice chicken thighs", "Marinate chicken", "Make seasoning powder (optional)", "Thicken marinade and coat chicken", "Set up frying station", "Dredge chicken", "Fry chicken first time", "Double fry chicken", "Fry basil (optional)", "Plate chicken and serve"], "tips": ["For more five-spice forward fried chicken, skip the seasoning powder.", "Two starches, in this economy??", "Don’t dredge all your chicken at once.", "Make it extra aromatic and crispy with fried basil."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/taiwanese-popcorn-chicken"}, {"id": 135, "t": "Cheesecake: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "Cheesecake is a uniquely American dessert. While there are many cakes that include cheese in their ingredient list all around the world, today, “cheesecake” calls to mind a smooth yet feathery custard with a distinctive lactic acid tang set atop a graham cracker crust, which was made possible by the rich, spreadable “full cream” cheese developed in the early 1800s in Pennsylvania and the populariz", "i": [], "s": ["The Infographic", "Liquid Cheesecake (Christina Tosi, Milk Bar)", "Basque Cheesecake (ChefSteps)", "New York Cheesecake (Junior’s)", "Classic New York Cheesecake (ChefSteps)", "Vegan New York Cheesecake (ChefSteps)", "Icebox Cheesecake (America’s Test Kitchen)", "Japanese Cheesecake (ChefSteps)", "Our Favorite Springform Pans for Cheesecakes", "Look at all these other parametrics!"], "tips": ["A Very Brief History of Cheesecake", "The Ingredients That Help Give Cheesecake “Tang”", "Use Cream Cheese With Stabilizers", "Pull Cheesecakes Early to Prevent Cracked Tops", "Bake a Super-Jiggly Japanese Cheesecake in a Rice Cooker", "Castella, Chiffon, and Other Foam Cakes"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cheesecake-parametric"}, {"id": 136, "t": "Basque Cheesecake", "c": "Baking", "d": "Basque cheesecake has got to be one of the most exciting innovations in the annals of cheesecake history. Dreamed up by chef Santiago Rivera at La Viña in Donostia-San Sebastian, it’s a sight to behold: the iconic burnished (not burnt!) top; the oozy, custardy center; and, of course, the complete lack of a bottom crust. Nailing it requires a two-phase bake, starting in a hot oven to brown the top,", "i": ["1.4 kg Cream cheese", "450 g Granulated sugar", "65 g All-purpose flour , unbleached, such as King Arthur brand", "8 g Kosher salt", "700 g Heavy cream", "9 Egg(s) , large", "15 g Vanilla extract , optional"], "s": ["No-crust cheesecakes", "Basque cheesecake flavor variations", "Soften cream cheese", "Blend cheesecake batter", "Rest and chill batter", "Prepare cake pan and cast batter", "First phase bake to brown top", "Second phase bake for a custardy center", "Cool cheesecake", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["For the silkiest Basque cheesecake, limit aeration.", "A silver lining", "Use a blowtorch to remove air bubbles.", "For a perfectly burnished top, give Basque cheesecake a spin.", "Pull cheesecake early to prevent cracking.", "Warm water is the key to clean slices."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/basque-cheesecake"}, {"id": 137, "t": "Classic New York Cheesecake", "c": "Baking", "d": "New York cheesecake should need no introduction. It’s a fluffy, creamy, rich, and tangy custard set atop a graham cracker crust, with blond sides and a very lightly mottled brown top. You know it, and to know it is to love it, since, like pizza, even when it’s just all right, it’s still pretty great. We set out to make the best New York cheesecake you’ll ever have. You want height? Well, this chee", "i": ["1.1 kg Cream cheese , room temperature (68 °F / 20 °C)", "400 g Granulated sugar , divided", "280 g Sour cream", "20 g Vanilla extract", "6 g Kosher salt , divided", "5 Egg(s) , large", "135 g Graham crackers , (9 cracker sheets)", "60 g Unsalted butter , melted"], "s": ["Can’t do dairy? Try our vegan cheesecake.", "Blend cheesecake batter", "Rest cheesecake batter", "Process graham cracker crust", "Prepare cake pan", "Bake crust", "Cast cheesecake", "First phase bake to set top", "Second phase bake to finish", "Cool cheesecake", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["A tale of two New York City cheesecakes", "Use a blowtorch to remove air bubbles.", "For a perfectly baked cheesecake, give it a spin.", "Pull cheesecake early to prevent cracking.", "Give your cheesecake a strawberry glaze.", "Warm water is the key to a clean release and clean slices."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/new-york-cheesecake"}, {"id": 138, "t": "Ultra-Fluffy Japanese Cheesecake", "c": "Baking", "d": "Japanese cheesecake is often called “cloud cake” because, well, putting a forkful in your mouth is like eating a cloud. Airy and light, with the characteristic tang that cream cheese provides, Japanese cheesecakes owe their unique texture to the fact that they’re basically a super-aerated foam. A sweet and cream cheese-y custard base is lightened up with a meringue, and there’s just barely enough ", "i": ["220 g Cream cheese", "90 g Whole milk", "100 g Granulated sugar , divided", "20 g Neutral oil", "15 g Vanilla extract", "10 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1/2 lemon)", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "1 g Lemon zest , finely grated (from 1/2 lemon; 1 teaspoon)", "60 g Egg yolk(s) , (4 large yolks)", "30 g All-purpose flour", "15 g Cornstarch", "1 g Cream of tartar , (1/4 teaspoon)", "140 g Egg white(s) , (from 4 large eggs)", "50 g Cake flour", "2 Vanilla bean , (if using extract, substitute 1 tbsp)", "2 g Xanthan gum , optional", "40 g Butter", "50 g Corn syrup", "2.5 g Salt", "150 g Heavy cream", "Fresh berries , for serving , as needed"], "s": ["No-crust cheesecakes", "Prepare cake pan", "Heat and blend cheesecake batter", "Whip meringue", "Fold meringue into cheesecake batter", "Cast batter", "First phase bake to brown top", "Second phase bake to finish", "Cool cheesecake", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Make cheesecake in a rice cooker.", "Watch out for leaks!", "For a perfectly baked cheesecake, give it a spin.", "Serving cheesecake warm or cold will produce different textures.", "Warm water is the key to clean slices.", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cloud-cake"}, {"id": 139, "t": "Vegan New York Cheesecake", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is a great New York–style cheesecake, full stop. It boasts a tall, fluffy custard with notes of vanilla and that distinctive cream cheese tang, set on top of a cookie-crumb base. The catch? It’s completely vegan! We didn’t want to come up with a vegan cheesecake that relied on store-bought vegan substitutes for the eggs, cream cheese, sour cream, and butter in our New York cheesecake recipe. ", "i": ["220 g Raw cashews", "200 g Biscoff cookies", "9 g Kosher salt , divided", "170 g Coconut oil (refined) , melted, divided", "800 g Coconut milk", "300 g Silken tofu", "35 g Vanilla extract", "1 Astaxanthin , softgel, optional, (see “Before we begin” note)", "240 g Granulated sugar", "6.5 g Citric acid", "1.5 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F", "0.8 g High-Acyl Gellan Gum LT100"], "s": ["Vegan vs. classic New York cheesecake", "The elements of vegan cheesecake", "Soak cashews", "Prepare cake pan", "Make crust", "Cook base", "Blend base", "Adjust color with astaxanthin (optional)", "Finish blending and cast base", "Chill to set cheesecake", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Don’t oversoak cashews", "Dock the crust, even though it isn’t baked.", "How to work with astaxanthin", "Work fast with fluid gels.", "Give your cheesecake a strawberry glaze.", "Warm water is the key to clean slices."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vegan-cheesecake"}, {"id": 140, "t": "Sous Vide Chicken Shawarma", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Chicken shawarma is a sandwich so iconic that it barely needs an introduction. Juicy marinated chicken thighs (with skin!), slow-roasted on a vertical spit until charred and crispy, are shaved into thin slices and wrapped in soft yet resilient saj flatbread along with garlicky toum and sour pickles. The whole wrap is then crisped on a griddle. Shawarma is deserving of its spot in the street food h", "i": ["80 g Yogurt , plain, whole-milk", "40 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 1/2 lemons)", "40 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "13 g Kosher salt", "10 g Garlic powder", "8 g Coriander seeds , ground", "5 g Ginger , ground (1 tablespoon)", "5 g Cumin seeds , ground (2 1/2 teaspoons)", "5 g Sweet paprika , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "3 g Cinnamon , ground (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "3 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "3 g Turmeric root powder , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Cloves , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Green cardamom , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Nutmeg , ground (1 teaspoon)", "8 Chicken thighs , bone-in, skin-on (200–230 g; 7–8 ounces each)", "45 g Neutral oil , divided", "4 Lavash , homemade or store-bought, or saj (see “Before we begin” note)", "240 g Toum (Levantine Garlic Sauce) , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "Levantine cucumber pickles , cut lengthwise into quarters (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed"], "s": ["Make marinade", "Bone out chicken thighs", "Pound thighs to even thickness", "Marinate chicken", "Heat sous vide bath", "Cook chicken thighs sous vide", "Sear chicken thighs", "Slice chicken thighs", "Assemble shawarma", "Sear shawarma", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["The hunt for great chicken shawarma"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-chicken-shawarma"}, {"id": 141, "t": "Ultra-Crispy Falafel", "c": "Baking", "d": "It’s hard to beat a well-made falafel. Crispy and craggy on the outside, fluffy, tender, aromatic, and verdant green on the inside, it’s a masterclass in textural variation and bold, fresh flavors. It’s an iconic food of the Levant. This recipe is about as legit as it gets. Where most run-of-the-mill falafel is pasty, dense, and yellow-to-anemic on the inside, ours pulls no punches to get you a co", "i": ["227 g Chickpeas , dried (1/2 pound)", "170 g Yellow onion(s) , (1 small onion) roughly chopped", "30 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems", "30 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves and tender stems", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 medium cloves) roughly chopped", "7 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "5 g Cumin seeds , ground (2 1/2 teaspoons)", "5 g Coriander seeds , ground (2 1/2 teaspoons)", "3 g Baking soda , (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Cayenne pepper , (1/8 teaspoon)", "Neutral oil , for deep-frying , as needed", "1 Lemon , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "Lavash , or saj, homemade or store-bought, optional (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "480 g Hummus , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 recipe Tahini Sauce , with or without vegetables, optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "Sambal oelek , optional (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "3 g Fresh mint , leaves, optional"], "s": ["Soak chickpeas", "Make falafel mix", "Set up frying station", "Shape falafel", "Fry falafel", "Slice lemon for sandwiches (optional)", "Make falafel sandwiches (optional)", "Make falafel platters (optional)"], "tips": ["The elements of great falafel"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/falafel"}, {"id": 142, "t": "Tahini Sauce", "c": "Sauce", "d": "For such a simple preparation, tahini sauce (tahiniyyah in Arabic) sure packs a punch. It hits all the notes: nutty, earthy, slightly bitter, savory, with a jolt of fresh lemon acidity. It’s a versatile condiment often served as part of the various small plates that make up a mezze spread. And it’s amazing paired with grilled meats, especially beef and lamb. The sauce is a simple emulsion of tahin", "i": ["100 g Tahini", "68 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 2 1/2 lemons)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "30 g Water , plus extra as needed", "150 g Tomato(es) , (1 medium tomato) quartered, seeded, and cut into 1/4-inch dice, optional", "95 g Persian cucumber(s) , (1 cucumber) cut into 1/4-inch dice, optional"], "s": ["Two ways to tahini sauce", "Whisk together tahini sauce", "Fold vegetables into sauce (optional)", "Put tahini sauce to use or store for later"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tahini-sauce"}, {"id": 143, "t": "Toum (Levantine Garlic Sauce)", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Toum, or mtawammeh as it’s known in Jordan, is an unapologetically garlicky sauce that seems to capture the hearts of all who try it. The word toum—which literally translates to “garlic” in Arabic—leaves no doubt as to its defining ingredient. Across the Levant, the sauce is served alongside grilled meats and is a mandatory accompaniment for chicken shawarma. Similar to traditional Spanish alioli,", "i": ["150 g Garlic clove(s) , (30 medium cloves)", "6 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "90 g Lemon juice , fresh (from about 3 1/2 lemons), divided", "660 g Neutral oil , divided", "105 g Ice water , divided"], "s": ["Two ways to toum", "Make garlic paste", "Emulsify toum", "Put toum to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Emulsify like a pro"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/toum"}, {"id": 144, "t": "Ultimate Birthday Cake", "c": "Baking", "d": "Picture the ultimate birthday cake. The one sitting in the display case of your favorite bakery, or maybe even the 🎂 emoji itself: a towering, triple-tiered, perfectly frosted construction of cake and cream, brimming with candles and cheer. This recipe gets you that. The cake is a hybrid between a chiffon and a high-ratio cake—two seemingly mutually exclusive cake styles—but the cake is light and ", "i": ["210 g Bleached cake flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "8 g Baking powder", "8 g Glycerol monostearate , (see “Before we begin” note)", "350 g Granulated sugar , divided", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "4 Egg(s) , large", "100 g Unsalted butter , melted", "100 g Neutral oil", "15 g Vanilla extract", "1 g Cream of tartar , (1/4 teaspoon)", "150 g Whole milk", "150 g Simple Syrup , (see “Before we begin” note)", "50 g Orange liqueur , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 recipes Silky Smooth Swiss Buttercream , (1.9 kg) room temperature (72 °F / 22 °C to 75 °F / 24 °C), divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "Sprinkles , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Two ways to cake", "Sift and mix dry ingredients", "Mix in fats and egg yolks", "Whip meringue", "Emulsify hot milk into cake batter", "Fold in meringue", "Bake cakes", "Chill cakes", "Trim and clean cakes", "Assemble cake", "Apply crumb coat", "Apply final coat", "Decorate cake", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Leave cake pan sides bare to maximize rise", "Reverse creaming", "The best of both cake worlds: high-ratio and chiffon hybrid", "Hot milk is key for consistent emulsification and texture.", "Baking three layers at the same time", "“Always work with cold cake.”", "Give cakes a “soak”", "The three stages of frosting", "The best temperature for Swiss buttercream", "A cake smoother is the right tool for the job.", "Applying a sprinkle border on the bottom edges", "Transferring a cake from a cake wheel", "For clean slices, use warm water."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-birthday-cake"}, {"id": 145, "t": "Simple Sheet Cake", "c": "Baking", "d": "Remember that half-eaten sheet cake at every party when you were a kid? The one from the grocery store with the criminally sweet frosting and “HAPPY BIRTHDAY” written in blotchy gel coloring? Well, we’re bringing it back! But better! Sheet cakes are built for ease and speed, which usually means you’re making some compromises on quality. But not this one! Sure, it’s simple—dump and stir, baby! No m", "i": ["200 g Bleached cake flour , (see “Before we begin” note), plus extra for dusting pan", "11.5 g Baking powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "4.5 g Glycerol monostearate , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "255 g Granulated sugar", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "50 g Egg(s) , (1 large egg)", "50 g Egg yolk(s) , (3 large yolks)", "10 g Vanilla extract", "113 g Unsalted butter , melted, plus extra softened butter for greasing pan", "60 g Neutral oil", "200 g Whole milk", "1 recipe Perfect American Buttercream , room temperature (68 °F / 20 °C)", "Sprinkles , for decorating, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Two ways to cake", "Sift and mix dry ingredients", "Make cake batter base", "Emulsify batter with hot milk", "Bake cake", "Frost cake", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Reverse creaming method", "Hot milk is key for consistent emulsification and texture.", "For thin batters, make sure your racks are level.", "Fancy up your frosting with a piping bag"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sheet-cake"}, {"id": 146, "t": "Silky Smooth Swiss Buttercream", "c": "Baking", "d": "You know those towering, triple-tiered cakes with perfectly frosted, perfectly smooth sides? It’s very likely that they’re frosted with Swiss buttercream, the pastry chef’s first choice when decorating celebratory cakes. Swiss buttercream (aka Swiss meringue buttercream) is the go-to for pastry chefs because of three key features: It’s silky smooth, it pipes and spreads like a dream, and it’s not ", "i": ["175 g Egg white(s) , (from 6 large eggs)", "315 g Granulated sugar", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Cream of tartar , (1/4 teaspoon)", "450 g Unsalted butter , softened to 65 °F / 18 °C and cut into 1-inch pieces (See “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Vanilla extract , (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Almond extract , (1/2 teaspoon) optional", "Gel food coloring , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Swiss vs. American buttercream", "Cook Swiss meringue", "Whip meringue", "Incorporate butter", "Add flavor and/or coloring", "Paddle buttercream to remove air pockets", "Put buttercream to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Look Ma, no bain marie. Make Swiss meringue with the Control Freak Home.", "The three meringues: French, Swiss, Italian", "Use a blowtorch to help smooth out buttercream.", "Frosting coloring guidelines", "To remove large air bubbles, paddle buttercream."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/swiss-buttercream"}, {"id": 147, "t": "Perfect American Buttercream", "c": "Baking", "d": "In the world of buttercream frostings, American buttercream is about as simple as it gets. It’s just powdered sugar and butter, whipped to a soft, spreadable consistency. But many American buttercream recipes suffer from a couple drawbacks: They can be cloyingly sweet, and the heavy proportion of powdered sugar results in a faintly gritty texture. This recipe produces a lighter, airier, smoother, ", "i": ["200 g Powdered sugar", "50 g Whole milk", "2 g Kosher salt", "300 g Unsalted butter , softened to 65 °F / 18 °C and cut into 1-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "200 g Light corn syrup , (see “Before we begin” note)", "60 g Heavy cream", "5 g Vanilla extract , (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "Gel food coloring , optional , as needed"], "s": ["American vs. Swiss buttercream", "Melt powdered sugar", "Aerate butter", "Add melted sugar", "Incorporate corn syrup", "Incorporate cream, vanilla, and/or coloring", "Paddle buttercream", "Put buttercream to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Aerating butter is key.", "Use a piping bag or plastic wrap to incorporate syrup without making a mess.", "For the smoothest buttercream, add cream.", "Frosting coloring guidelines", "To remove large air bubbles, paddle buttercream."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-buttercream"}, {"id": 148, "t": "Winter Studio Dinner Experience", "c": "Baking", "d": "In December 2024, we hosted a series of special dinners in our Seattle studio. Like the dinners we used to host in the early days of ChefSteps for friends and investors, we served a multicourse tasting menu featuring a mix of ChefSteps classics and new dishes, digging deep into our bag of culinary tricks, techniques, and toys. As a chef-driven brand, this gave us the opportunity to get back to our", "i": ["20 g Granulated sugar", "11 g Rapid set HM pectin", "3 g Malic acid", "2 g Kosher salt", "450 g Frozen concord grape juice concentrate", "450 g Water", "100 g Egg white(s)"], "s": ["Menu Planning and Development", "The Prep Push", "The Menu", "Greetings", "Crispy Grapes", "Fizzy Grapes", "Seatings", "Course 1: Cryo-Shucked Oyster", "Course 2: Split Peas", "Course 3: Canned Creamed Corn", "Course 4: Salmon 104°", "Course 5: World’s Best Chowder Bowl", "Course 6: Salmon 130°", "Course 7: Imfoiessible Pâté", "Course 8: Poulet Farci", "Course 9: Breakfast Egg", "Course 10: 100-Hour Pastrami", "Course 11: Farm and Garden", "Sweetings", "Course 12: Flourless Carrot Cake", "Course 13: Cinnamon Croissant Crunch", "Coffee Lab"], "tips": ["Beverage Pairings", "Crispy Grapes Kitchen Notes", "Fizzy Grapes Kitchen Notes", "Cryo-Shucked Oyster Kitchen Notes", "Split Peas Kitchen Notes", "Canned Creamed Corn Kitchen Notes", "Salmon 104° Kitchen Notes", "World’s Best Chowder Bowl Kitchen Notes", "Imfoiessible Pâté Kitchen Notes", "Poulet Farci Kitchen Notes", "How to get picture-perfect eggshells", "100-Hour Pastrami Kitchen Notes", "Farm and Garden Kitchen Notes", "Cinnamon Croissant Crunch Kitchen Notes", "86’d: Tiramisù"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/winter-studio-dinner-experience"}, {"id": 149, "t": "Clam Chowder au Craquelin", "c": "Baking", "d": "We’re often stopped by visitors around Pike Place Market for directions to that “famous chowder spot,” Pike Place Chowder, which is just steps away from our studio. So when we were planning our Winter Studio Dinner Experience, we thought it would be fun to come up with our very own “world’s best chowder bowl,” riffing on the chowder bread bowls you find in tourist traps in San Francisco. But, you ", "i": ["12 Choux au Craquelin , (see “Before we begin” note)", "250 g Yukon Gold potato(es) , peeled and cut into 1/4-inch dice", "14 g Kosher salt , divided", "Silver gelatin, 170 bloom , (1 1/2 sheets), or 2.5 g Knox powdered gelatin", "113 g Unsalted butter , cut into 1-inch pieces", "100 g Bacon , cut into 1/4-inch-wide strips", "100 g Celery , (3 ribs) thinly sliced", "50 g Sweet onion(s) , (1/4 onion) thinly sliced", "20 g Garlic , (4 medium cloves) thinly sliced", "500 g Heavy cream", "0.5 g Black peppercorns , whole (10 peppercorns)", "5 g Fish sauce , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Xanthan gum , (1/4 teaspoon)", "150 g Geoduck , cleaned and cut into 1/4-inch dice (see “Before we begin” note)", "14 g Brined green peppercorns , drained and minced (see “Before we begin” note)", "Trout roe , or caviar, for serving, optional , as needed", "Chives , thinly sliced, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Sweet onion choux au craquelin “bowls”", "Punch out choux au craquelin", "Cook potatoes", "Cook chowder base", "Strain and thicken chowder base", "Charge whipping siphon", "Heat potatoes and clams", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["How to keep a thick liquid vortex spinning", "Got extra potatoes, clams, and foam? More chowda!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/clam-chowder-au-craquelin"}, {"id": 150, "t": "Ultimate Sous Vide Tonkatsu", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Tonkatsu: It’s big in Japan. We’re not just talking about popularity. Some of the best tonkatsu spots offer up golden fried pork cutlets made from a wide variety of cuts, and some of them are absolutely massive. Think 2-inch hunks of juicy pork with a single rosy hue from edge to edge, surrounded by a crispy and airy shell of a crust that seems to defy gravity. This recipe gets you that—the most e", "i": ["2 Sous Vide Pork Shoulder Chops , cut into 2-inch-thick chops (see “Before we begin” note)", "200 g Egg(s) , (4 large eggs)", "120 g “00” flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "Nama Panko (Fresh Panko Breadcrumbs) , or 250 g store-bought panko (see “Before we begin” note)", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "400 g Green cabbage , (1/2 head) cored and finely shredded, for serving", "Short-grain rice , cooked, for serving , as needed", "Tonkatsu Sauce , homemade or store-bought, for serving , as needed", "5 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (1 1/4 teaspoons)"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Bag and reheat chops", "Set up frying station", "Bread and fry chops", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["“All-purpose umami seasoning” for super savory tonkatsu", "For the crunchiest cabbage, soak it in ice water."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-sous-vide-tonkatsu"}, {"id": 151, "t": "Classic Tonkatsu", "c": "Baking", "d": "“Tonkatsu” means “pork cutlet” in Japanese, and for many people, that would be enticing enough: a tenderized pork cutlet, seasoned, breaded, and fried to produce a crunchy golden-brown crust and juicy meat. Who can’t get down with that? What separates pretty good tonkatsu from great tonkatsu is the breadcrumbs. Here we ditch dried store-bought panko for fluffy, fresh Nama Panko, made from Japanese", "i": ["4 Pork chop(s) , boneless, 1-inch-thick, (about 200 g; 7 ounces each)", "Kosher salt , (1% of the weight of pork chops), plus extra , as needed", "200 g Egg(s) , (4 large eggs)", "120 g “00” flour , or all-purpose flour (see “Before we begin” note)", "Nama Panko (Fresh Panko Breadcrumbs) , or 250 g store-bought panko breadcrumbs (see “Before we begin” note)", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "400 g Green cabbage , (1/2 head) cored and finely shredded, for serving, optional", "Short-grain rice , cooked, for serving, optional , as needed", "Tonkatsu Sauce , homemade or store-bought, for serving , as needed", "5 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (1 1/4 teaspoons)"], "s": ["Pound and dry brine pork chops", "Set up frying station", "Bread and fry cutlets", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["“All-purpose umami seasoning” for super-savory tonkatsu", "For the crunchiest cabbage, soak it in ice water."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/classic-tonkatsu"}, {"id": 152, "t": "Nama Panko (Fresh Panko Breadcrumbs)", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "What’s the secret to the feather-light crispy breading that coats the best Japanese fried cutlets? Nama panko. Everyone is familiar with dried panko breadcrumbs, but in the States, it’s almost impossible to find nama panko, which translates to “fresh” panko. Nama panko is the softer, fluffier, and flakier version of dried panko, and it’s made from fresh loaves of shokupan, Japanese milk bread. It’", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 650 g Shokupan (Japanese Milk Bread) , (1 loaf) homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "650 g Shokupan (Japanese Milk Bread) , (1 loaf) homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Trim, slice, and freeze shokupan", "Shave nama panko", "Put nama panko to use or store for later"], "tips": ["For fluffy flakes, freeze the bread.", "No food processor? Use a mandoline.", "Don’t let nama panko dry out!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/nama-panko"}, {"id": 153, "t": "Tonkatsu Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Great tonkatsu—whether it’s Classic Tonkatsu, Ultimate Sous Vide Tonkatsu, or Air-Fried Tonkatsu—deserves a great sauce. Enter tonkatsu sauce, the A.1. of the crispy cutlet realm. Sweet and fruity, deeply savory, with just enough acidity to cut through the breaded fried crust and make the delicate pork beneath shine, our homemade tonkatsu sauce tastes brighter and fresher than the store-bought stu", "i": ["75 g Apple juice", "75 g Worcestershire sauce", "65 g Tomato paste", "40 g Soy sauce", "25 g Dijon mustard", "25 g Light brown sugar", "15 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon)", "8 g Distilled vinegar", "1.5 g Garlic powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Onion powder , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.7 g Ginger , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.25 g Cinnamon , ground (1/16 teaspoon)", "0.8 g Xanthan gum , (0.25% of the weight of tonkatsu sauce) optional"], "s": ["Whisk together sauce", "Thicken sauce with xanthan gum (optional)", "Put tonkatsu sauce to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Our favorite store-bought tonkatsu sauces"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tonkatsu-sauce"}, {"id": 154, "t": "Tiramisù Icebox Cake", "c": "Baking", "d": "Tiramisù—the classic Italian layered dessert—is a lot like pizza: Even when it’s bad, it’s still pretty good. But “pretty good” doesn’t cut it for us. For this version, we wanted to create a centerpiece tiramisù, kind of like a dessert Wellington or pâté en croûte. Drawing inspiration from classic icebox cakes, we came up with a more set and sliceable tiramisù (thanks to the power of xanthan gum a", "i": ["190 g Espresso , brewed (see “Before we begin” note)", "150 g Marsala wine , sweet, divided", "110 g Granulated sugar , divided", "5 g Kosher salt , divided (2 1/2 teaspoons)", "Silver gelatin, 170 bloom , (3 sheets), sheets cut in half, or 3 g Knox powdered gelatin", "90 g Egg yolk(s) , (6 large yolks)", "454 g Mascarpone , chilled", "240 g Heavy cream , chilled", "0.5 g Xanthan gum , optional", "18 Ladyfingers , store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "12 g Cocoa powder"], "s": ["Find the tiramisù for you", "Make coffee syrup", "Cook zabaglione", "Fold zabaglione into mascarpone", "Finish whipped mascarpone", "Assemble tiramisù", "Unmold, garnish, and serve"], "tips": ["Dialing in coffee syrup quantity", "Stabilize the double boiler with a towel", "Look Ma, no double boiler! Zabaglione with the Control Freak.", "Stabilize whipped mascarpone for tiramisù that lasts", "No piping bag? No problem!", "Good tiramisù deserves good cocoa powder.", "Warm water is the key to clean slices."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tiramisu-icebox-cake"}, {"id": 155, "t": "Ultimate Tiramisù", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’re going to put a spin on a classic, you gotta take a big swing. So here it is, our fine-dining take on tiramisù: espresso-soaked ladyfingers enrobed in a super-stable whipped mascarpone cream, coated in a magic shell of dark chocolate, and set on a crispy, crunchy tuile. Originally developed to be one of the desserts for a 14-course tasting menu, it’s designed to be visually striking and c", "i": ["65 g Marsala wine , sweet, divided", "Silver gelatin, 170 bloom , (1 1/2 sheets), sheets cut in half, or 1.5 g Knox powdered gelatin", "55 g Egg yolk(s) , (3 large yolks)", "53 g Granulated sugar , divided", "3 g Kosher salt , divided (1 teaspoon)", "226 g Mascarpone , chilled", "0.25 g Xanthan gum", "120 g Heavy cream , chilled", "70 g Cake flour", "60 g Unsalted butter , melted", "60 g Egg white(s) , (from 2 large eggs)", "8 Ladyfingers , store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "65 g Espresso , brewed (see “Before we begin” note)", "150 g 70% dark chocolate , pistoles, such as Valrhona, divided", "75 g Cocoa butter , pistoles"], "s": ["Find the tiramisù for you", "Cook zabaglione", "Fold zabaglione into mascarpone", "Finish whipped mascarpone", "Mix tuile batter", "Spread tuile batter", "Bake tuile", "Trim and weigh ladyfingers", "Make coffee syrup", "Assemble and freeze tiramisù", "Unmold tiramisù", "Make chocolate shell", "Spray tiramisù", "Serve and enjoy"], "tips": ["Stabilize the double boiler with a towel", "Look Ma, no double boiler! Zabaglione with the Control Freak.", "Stabilize whipped mascarpone for tiramisù that lasts", "DIY tuile stencils", "Use paper to make DIY “pastry bars”", "Use a bench scraper for perfectly flat tuile", "Dialing in coffee syrup quantity", "Spray it, don’t dip it"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-tiramisu"}, {"id": 156, "t": "Quick and Easy Tiramisù", "c": "Baking", "d": "Have you ever had a “tiramisù emergency”? We have. Sometimes, you just need dessert. And, sometimes, you really need that dessert to be tiramisù, because what the doctor ordered is something rich and creamy, shot through with the bold and darkly acidic notes of good espresso. This tiramisù recipe will get you exactly that in just 30 minutes. Unlike our Tiramisù Icebox Cake, this one won’t set up i", "i": ["285 g Espresso , brewed (see “Before we begin” note)", "90 g Marsala wine , sweet", "70 g Granulated sugar , divided", "4 g Kosher salt , divided (1 teaspoon)", "13 g Jell-O Instant Pudding & Pie Filling, Vanilla , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "300 g Heavy cream , chilled", "300 g Mascarpone , chilled (see “Before we begin” note)", "200 g Egg(s) , (4 large eggs) chilled", "28 Ladyfingers , store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "12 g Cocoa powder"], "s": ["Find the tiramisù for you", "Make coffee syrup", "Whip mascarpone base", "Assemble tiramisù", "Dust with cocoa and serve"], "tips": ["Concerned about raw eggs? Pasteurize them using sous vide.", "Stabilize whipped cream with instant pudding mix", "Tiramisù in any pan", "Good tiramisù deserves good cocoa powder."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/quick-and-easy-tiramisu"}, {"id": 157, "t": "Pork, Shrimp, and Cabbage Dumplings", "c": "Baking", "d": "A good dumpling is a study in textures. Taking a bite out of a well-made dumpling should get you a kaleidoscope of textures. The skin should be chewy, offering your teeth a little resistance, and yet still silky and slippery. It should surround the filling completely—no rips or tears. And it shouldn’t be mushy. The filling should be light yet cohesive; it should fall apart in your mouth, not in th", "i": ["300 g Taiwanese cabbage , finely chopped (see “Before we begin” note)", "8 g Kosher salt , divided", "5 g Cornstarch , (1 3/4 teaspoons)", "300 g Ground pork", "200 g Shrimp , jumbo (26–30 per pound), peeled, deveined, and finely chopped", "40 g Scallion(s) , (4 scallions) thinly sliced", "30 g Lard , melted (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Toasted sesame oil", "10 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and grated", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) grated", "5 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1 1/2 teaspoons; see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g White pepper , ground (3/4 teaspoon)", "36 Dumpling wrappers , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Neutral oil , for pan-frying, plus extra as needed", "All-Purpose Dumpling Sauce , for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Salt cabbage", "Mix filling", "Fill and shape dumplings", "Pan-fry dumplings", "Serve dumplings"], "tips": ["The function of cabbage in dumpling filling", "Leveraging the binding power of myosin", "Dumpling shaping for all skill levels", "Got leftover dumpling filling? Don’t waste it!", "How to boil dumplings", "How to steam dumplings"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pork-shrimp-cabbage-dumplings"}, {"id": 158, "t": "Crab and Mushroom Dumplings", "c": "Baking", "d": "Just like our Pork, Shrimp, and Cabbage Dumplings, these dumplings are carefully calibrated parcels of textural complexity: silky steamed dumpling skins encasing a luxurious filling of tender lump crab meat, crunchy water chestnuts, and meaty mushrooms. These are celebratory dumplings. Whereas our Pork, Shrimp, and Cabbage dumplings use a more classic (and more affordable) combination of ingredien", "i": ["45 g Shiitake mushrooms , dried", "400 g Lump crab meat , picked over for shells (see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g Water chestnuts , cut into 1/8-inch dice", "40 g Scallion(s) , (4 scallions) thinly sliced", "15 g Toasted sesame oil", "10 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "10 g Black truffle , finely grated, optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) finely grated", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "4 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1 1/4 teaspoons; see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g White pepper , ground (3/4 teaspoon)", "60 g Lard , melted (see “Before we begin” note)", "36 Dumpling wrappers , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "All-Purpose Dumpling Sauce , for serving, optional , as needed", "Chinese red vinegar , for serving, optional (see “Before we begin’ note) , as needed", "30 g Neutral oil"], "s": ["Hydrate dried mushrooms", "Mix filling", "Fill and shape dumplings", "Steam dumplings", "Serve dumplings"], "tips": ["Dumpling shaping for all skill levels", "How to boil dumplings", "How to pan-fry dumplings"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crab-mushroom-dumplings"}, {"id": 159, "t": "Homemade Dumpling Wrappers", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Making your own dumpling wrappers is well worth the time and effort—and it doesn’t even take that much time or effort! While there’s nothing wrong with store-bought dumpling wrappers—they’re convenient, reliable, and a stack of 50 typically costs a few bucks—making them yourself allows you to tailor the dough to your tastes. Want your dumpling skins thick and chewy or thin and delicate? You’re in ", "i": ["280 g All-purpose flour , unbleached, such as King Arthur brand, plus more for dusting (see “Before we begin” note)", "120 g Cake flour , unbleached, such as King Arthur brand (see “Before we begin” note)", "6 g Kosher salt", "212 g Boiling water , 212 °F / 100 °C (see “Before we begin” note)", "Cornstarch , for dusting , as needed"], "s": ["Choose your desired dumpling dough texture", "Mix dough", "Divide and roll out dough", "Punch out wrappers", "Put dumpling wrappers to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Add color to your dumpling wrappers", "Don’t have a pasta roller? Use a rolling pin.", "Cornstarch prevents sticking for long term storage"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dumpling-wrappers"}, {"id": 160, "t": "All-Purpose Dumpling Sauce", "c": "Sauce", "d": "A well-made dumpling doesn’t need anything—it should be perfectly seasoned and delicious all on its own, just like our Pork, Shrimp, and Cabbage Dumplings and our Crab and Mushroom Dumplings. But who are we kidding? Even the best dumpling in the world gets a little lift from a dipping sauce. This dumpling sauce is about as all-purpose as it gets: It works with our from-scratch dumplings with their", "i": ["15 g Dark Chinese soy sauce", "15 g Light Chinese soy sauce", "15 g Chinkiang black vinegar", "15 g Water , room temperature", "12 g Granulated sugar", "5 g Toasted sesame oil", "2 g Sichuan chile powder , (3/4 teaspoon) optional (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Make dumpling sauce", "Put dumpling sauce to use or store for later"], "tips": ["Jazz the sauce up with aromatics"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dumpling-sauce"}, {"id": 161, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Chinese Dumplings (Jiǎo Zi)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Frozen dumplings are the ultimate convenience food: Buy a big (affordable) bag at the grocery store, stash it in your freezer, and in minutes you can prepare a plate of tasty and plump dumplings any number of ways. And there’s nothing wrong with that! But the ubiquity of prepared dumplings, many of which are perfectly fine, may make the prospect of making them yourself seem silly. Why go through t", "i": [], "s": ["Getting to Know Jiǎo Zi", "The Wrappers", "Flour Type", "Hydration", "Mixing and Resting", "Rolling Out Wrappers", "Rolling Pin Method", "Pasta Roller Method", "The Filling", "Meat and Seafood", "Vegetables", "Seasonings and Aromatics", "Shaping and Pleating", "Dumpling Shapes for All Skill Levels", "Half-Moon (Bàn Yuè Jiǎo Zi)", "Pinched Half-Moon", "Open Potsticker", "Potsticker", "Pinched Potsticker", "Ingot (Yuán Bǎo Jiǎo Zi)", "2-Pleat Half-Moon (Yuè Yá Jiǎo Zi)", "Bidirectional 4-Pleat Half-Moon", "Bidirectional 6-Pleat Half-Moon", "Bidirectional 8-Pleat Half-Moon", "Unidirectional 8-Pleat Half-Moon", "Pleated Leaf (Liǔ Yè Xíng)", "Cooking", "Boiled Dumplings", "Steamed Dumplings", "Pan-Fried Dumplings", "Serving", "Make Ahead and Make a Lot"], "tips": ["Dumplings: A Lunar New Year tradition", "Protein content and gluten-forming potential", "What about flavoring or coloring dumpling dough?", "What about cold water doughs?", "What about store-bought dumpling wrappers?", "How to keep dumpling wrappers from sticking together", "How much filling should I use?", "Shaping and pleating tips", "What about dumplings with that cool lacy skirt?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/guide-to-chinese-dumplings"}, {"id": 162, "t": "Pollo en Mole Coloradito (Oaxacan Chicken Mole)", "c": "Meat", "d": "Give chicken legs a glow-up by braising them in ultra-savory and perfectly spiced Oaxacan mole coloradito. This is no humdrum weeknight meal. It has the depth of flavor of a carefully crafted mole, but it comes together in an hour thanks to the Mole Coloradito Paste that you’ve made in advance and stashed in the freezer for a rainy day. Today is that day. Buen provecho. save Print", "i": ["4 Chicken leg(s) , (about 1.1 kg; 2 1/2 pounds total)", "10 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "30 g Neutral oil", "690 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought", "350 g Mole Coloradito Paste , (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Granulated sugar , (1 teaspoon)", "Toasted sesame seeds , for serving , as needed", "1 recipe Arroz Blanco Mantequillado (Mexican Buttered Rice) , for serving", "Corn tortillas , warmed, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Sear chicken legs", "Simmer mole", "Braise chicken in mole", "Serve"], "tips": ["For the smoothest mole, strain it."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-mole-coloradito"}, {"id": 163, "t": "Mole Coloradito Paste", "c": "Meat", "d": "Oaxacan mole coloradito might not be as widely known in the States as its cousin from Puebla, but it is every bit as delicious. Mole poblano is prized for its rich, deeply spiced, and slightly sweet profile, whereas mole coloradito is a little lighter and brighter. Just like with our Mole Poblano Paste, we front-load all the work and don’t cut any corners, but the final product isn’t a finished mo", "i": ["140 g Lard", "45 g Almonds, raw", "15 g Sesame seeds , raw", "40 g Raisins", "3 g Black peppercorns , whole (3/4 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Cumin seeds , whole (3/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Cloves , whole (about 5 each)", "1 g Mexican oregano , dried (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "0.5 g Thyme , fresh leaves (1/2 teaspoon)", "45 g Baguette(s) , or other crusty bread, cut into 1-inch pieces", "45 g Guajillo chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "45 g Ancho chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "80 g Plantain(s) , (3/4 plantain) ripe, cut into 1-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "75 g Roma tomato(es) , (1 small tomato) cut into 1-inch pieces", "50 g White onion(s) , (1/4 onion) cut into 1-inch pieces", "20 g Garlic clove(s) , whole", "600 g Water", "50 g Piloncillo , grated, or brown sugar (see “Before we begin” note)", "40 g Mexican chocolate , chopped (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Toast almonds and seeds", "Toast raisins and spices", "Toast bread", "Toast chiles", "Brown vegetables", "Simmer and steep fried ingredients", "Purée mole paste", "Cook mole paste", "Put mole paste to use or portion and chill"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/mole-coloradito-paste"}, {"id": 164, "t": "Arroz Blanco Mantequillado (Mexican Buttered Rice)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Rice is nice, a 10/10 food. Buttered rice? 11/10! (Everything is better with butter!) Mexican arroz mantequillado is a little more refined than simply adding a couple knobs of butter to steamed white rice. By cooking the rice in chicken stock with a little garlic and onion, you get aromatic notes plain rice doesn’t have. Seasoned with salt and MSG (in the form of chicken bouillon powder) and plent", "i": ["460 g White rice , medium-grain (see “Before we begin” note)", "690 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 medium cloves) whole", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoon) divided", "3 g Chicken bouillon powder , (3/4 teaspoon) preferably Knorr brand (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "65 g White onion(s) , (1/4 small onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "25 g Unsalted butter , divided"], "s": ["Rinse rice", "Season chicken stock", "Toast rice and sweat onion", "Cook rice", "Finish rice and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/mexican-buttered-rice"}, {"id": 165, "t": "Choux au Craquelin", "c": "Baking", "d": "What happens when you combine a cookie with a cream puff? Choux au craquelin! A pastry that demonstrates the wizardry of French patisserie innovation better than almost any other, choux au craquelin consists of rich choux pastry topped with a cap of buttery cookie dough that crisps up into a crackly top, filled from edge to edge with crème légère (pastry cream lightened with whipped cream). It’s t", "i": ["100 g Light brown sugar", "85 g Unsalted butter , soften", "100 g All-purpose flour", "1 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 recipe Perfect Pâte à Choux , (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 recipe Pastry Cream , (see “Before we begin” note)", "250 g Heavy cream , chilled", "75 g Granulated sugar", "1 g Gel food coloring , (1/4 teaspoon) plus extra as needed"], "s": ["Make craquelin dough", "Roll and cut craquelin disks", "Pipe and top choux", "0.5 recipe", "Bake choux au craquelin", "Make crème légère", "Fill choux au craquelin"], "tips": ["Color your craquelin", "Don’t overfill the piping bag", "Flavor your crème légère"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/choux-au-craquelin"}, {"id": 166, "t": "Perfect Pâte à Choux", "c": "Baking", "d": "Choux pastry, or pâte à choux, is a classic French dough used to make all kinds of delicious sweet and savory treats. You know, like gougères, choux au craquelin, éclairs, crullers, and even Parisian gnocchi. Pâte à choux is something of an anomaly. Is it dough? Is it batter? Does it matter? (Not really!) The way it works is through starch gelatinization and mechanical leavening via the conversion", "i": ["113 g Water", "113 g Whole milk", "113 g Unsalted butter , cut into 1/2-inch pieces", "12 g Granulated sugar", "3 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon)", "140 g Bread flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "225 g Egg(s) , (from 4 to 5 large eggs; see “Before we begin” note)", "150 g Gruyère cheese , grated"], "s": ["Make choux dough", "Cook choux dough", "Incorporate eggs", "Rest choux dough", "Put choux dough to use", "Piping and baking basic choux items"], "tips": ["The extended choux-niverse", "For consistent choux, temp the dough.", "No food processor? No problem.", "Make cheesy gougères", "For easier piping, give choux a rest.", "For perfectly piped choux, stencil and secure your parchment."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/choux-pastry"}, {"id": 167, "t": "Enmoladas de Pollo (Mole Enchiladas With Chicken)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Enmoladas are like enchiladas, just better, because they’re cooked in delicious mole. They’re also a great way to underscore the utility and sheer tastiness of our homemade concentrated Mole Poblano Paste, since mole is used as both the filling and the sauce. The intensely flavorful mole paste is the key to the flavor of the dish, and it also makes a dish that could take hours to make into one tha", "i": ["635 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock, divided", "350 g Mole Poblano Paste , (see “Before we begin” note)", "8 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "5 g Granulated sugar , (1 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "70 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided", "250 g White onion(s) , (1 medium onion) thinly sliced", "100 g Carrot(s) , (2 carrots) grated", "20 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 cloves) minced", "1.5 g Oregano , fresh leaves (2 sprigs), minced", "650 g Chicken , cooked, shredded (see “Before we begin” note)", "12 Corn tortillas", "Mexican crema , for finishing , as needed", "Queso fresco , crumbled, for finishing , as needed", "Toasted sesame seeds , for finishing , as needed"], "s": ["Simmer mole", "Make filling", "Heat tortillas", "Assemble and bake enmoladas", "Finish enmoladas and serve"], "tips": ["For the smoothest mole, strain it."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/enmoladas"}, {"id": 168, "t": "Mole Poblano Paste", "c": "Baking", "d": "Mole is many things: It’s a sauce, a cooking medium, and a marinade, and it’s mind-bendingly delicious. It’s also notoriously time-consuming to make. With our 30-Minute Mole, we tackled the efficiency issue, leveraging the power of a pressure cooker to whip up a deeply flavorful mole quickly. For this version, we took a different approach: We made a concentrated mole paste that can subsequently be", "i": ["140 g Lard", "15 g Cashews , raw", "15 g Peanuts , raw, preferably red-skinned", "15 g Pumpkin seeds , raw", "15 g Sesame seeds , raw", "20 g Raisins", "20 g Golden raisins", "4 g Ceylon cinnamon , (1/2 stick) broken into 1-inch pieces", "2 g Black peppercorns , whole (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Coriander seeds , whole (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "1 g Fennel seeds , whole (1 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Cloves , whole (about 5 each)", "15 g Baguette(s) , or other crusty bread, cut into 1-inch pieces", "28 g Corn tortillas , (about 1 1/2 tortillas) cut into 1-inch pieces", "40 g Mulato chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1-inch pieces", "30 g Ancho chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1-inch pieces", "25 g Pasilla chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1-inch pieces", "80 g Plantain(s) , (3/4 plantain) ripe, cut into 1-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "50 g Tomatillos , (2 small tomatillos) cut into 1-inch pieces", "50 g White onion(s) , (1/4 onion) cut into 1-inch pieces", "20 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 medium cloves) whole", "600 g Water", "50 g Piloncillo , grated, or brown sugar (see “Before we begin” note), plus extra as needed", "40 g Mexican chocolate , chopped (see “Before we begin” note), plus extra as needed", "10 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed"], "s": ["Toast nuts and seeds", "Toast raisins and spices", "Toast bread and tortillas", "Toast chiles", "Brown vegetables", "Simmer and steep fried ingredients", "Purée mole paste", "Cook mole paste", "Put mole paste to use or portion and chill"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/mole-poblano-paste"}, {"id": 169, "t": "Glazed Pork Roast", "c": "Baking", "d": "A pork rib roast is a glorious holiday feast centerpiece that’s every bit as delicious and eye-catching as a prime rib or a beautifully glazed ham, provided you treat it right. This recipe and method guarantee you a picture-perfect glazed pork roast that also tastes incredible. Buy the right cut; trim, french, and truss it correctly (or have a butcher do it for you); cook it gently so the tender, ", "i": ["1 Pork rib roast , bone-in, skin-off, frenched and trussed (2 kg; 4 1/2 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt , (0.5% of the weight of pork roast) , as needed", "30 g Neutral oil", "1 recipe Sweet and Sticky Root Beer Glaze , warm, for glazing and serving", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, for finishing, optional , as needed", "1 Pork chain , from trimming and frenching pork rib roast (see “Before we begin” note) - Kosher salt , (1% of the weight of pork chain) , as needed - Brown sugar , (2% of the weight of pork chain) , as needed 40 g Sweet and Sticky Root Beer Glaze , warm", "Brown sugar , (2% of the weight of pork chain) , as needed"], "s": ["French, trim, and truss pork roast, if needed", "Dry brine pork roast", "Sear and press roast", "Wrap rib tips (optional)", "Score and glaze roast", "Slow low-temp roast", "Rest roast", "Glaze and finish with high-temp roast", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["“My butcher did the hard work for me!”", "Roast the chain for a cook’s treat", "In a hurry? Reduce dry-brining time to 1 hour.", "Continue roasting the chain"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/glazed-pork-roast"}, {"id": 170, "t": "How to French and Truss a Pork Roast", "c": "Baking", "d": "If the standing prime rib roast is the king of the holiday table, that’s only because most people overlook its porcine cousin: a pork roast! To make this under-appreciated roast shine, you have to source really good pork and use the right cut, and it has to be trimmed, frenched, and trussed properly. Even if you’re not planning on doing all of this yourself, it’s helpful to understand the process,", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 Pork rib roast , (aka rack of pork or loin roast), bone-in, skin-off, untrimmed (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 Pork rib roast , (aka rack of pork or loin roast), bone-in, skin-off, untrimmed (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Cut reference points and score membrane", "Begin separating meat from bones", "Remove membrane", "Peel membrane away from bones", "Remove rib meat", "Clean bones", "Remove remaining chine bones", "Trim fat cap", "Truss roast", "Yer a butcher, Harry!"], "tips": ["Cold meat is easier to trim.", "Use an S-hook for extra grip", "Scrape bones away from the roast", "Trimming the fat cap"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pork-roast-butchery"}, {"id": 171, "t": "Sweet and Sticky Root Beer Glaze", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pork roasts and hams just cry out for a sweet and sticky savory glaze, and this old-fashioned root beer glaze produces a gorgeous caramel-colored coating that makes the savory pork even more delicious. Using root beer as a base provides caramel coloring, hints of vanilla and sarsaparilla, and a hit of tanginess from the citric acid (or, sometimes, phosphoric acid), which is used as a preservative ", "i": ["1.5 kg Root beer", "175 g Granulated sugar", "25 g Honey", "10 g Sassafras root bark , dried (six 1-inch pieces)", "10 g Sarsaparilla root , dried", "1 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.2 g Wintergreen essential oil , (5 drops) optional"], "s": ["Reduce mixture to a loose glaze", "Strain and finish reducing glaze", "Add wintergreen essential oil (optional)", "Put glaze to use"], "tips": ["Maximize yield by straining glaze before fully reduced", "Wintergreen oil punches up the root beer flavor."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/root-beer-glaze"}, {"id": 172, "t": "Buttermilk Blini", "c": "Baking", "d": "Blini come in all shapes and sizes, although in the States we typically think of them as delicious little vehicles for caviar and crème fraîche. Our Buckwheat Blini are perfectly designed for that purpose, but after all the work we did on buttermilk pancake varieties, we came up with this tangy spin on the classic. With slight adjustments to the batter from our Precision Buttermilk Pancakes, these", "i": ["100 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs)", "300 g Buttermilk , full-fat (see “Before we begin” note)", "180 g All-purpose flour", "35 g Sugar", "25 g Buttermilk powder , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "6 g Baking powder", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "60 g Unsalted butter , melted, plus extra for cooking (see “Before we begin” note)", "Caviar , for serving, optional , as needed", "Smoked Salmon , homemade or store-bought, for serving, optional , as needed", "Crème fraîche , homemade or store-bought, for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Temper eggs and buttermilk", "Make batter", "Preheat oven (optional)", "Cook blini", "Serve"], "tips": ["Tempering wet ingredients for a better batter", "Dialing in pan temperature and cook time for blini", "For better blini, concentrate on texture, not color", "How to use a squeeze bottle to dial in the size of blini"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/buttermilk-blini"}, {"id": 173, "t": "Crispy Potato “Croissants”", "c": "Baking", "d": "Why should Cronuts, kouign-amanns, or croissants have all the crispy, multi-layered fun? Why can’t potatoes get the lamination treatment? We call this the potato “croissant”: a golden-brown, buttery, crispy-on-the-outside, creamy-on-the-inside rosette of deep-fried potato slices. You can call it 100% delicious. This idea came about while developing our Potato Pavé. We wanted to get all those layer", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1.4 kg Russet potato(es) , (3 to 4 potatoes) peeled and rinsed (see “Before we begin” note) 140 g Clarified butter , homemade or store-bought, melted - Neutral oil , for frying , as needed - Kosher salt, as needed", "1.4 kg Russet potato(es) , (3 to 4 potatoes) peeled and rinsed (see “Before we begin” note) 140 g Clarified butter , homemade or store-bought, melted - Neutral oil , for frying , as needed - Kosher salt, as needed", "140 g Clarified butter , homemade or store-bought, melted", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Choose your croissant size and cooking vessel", "Slice and rinse potatoes", "Build potato “croissants”", "Bake potato “croissants”", "Chill potato “croissants”", "Unmold potato “croissants”", "Fry potato “croissants”", "Serve"], "tips": ["For maximum yield, use a mandoline.", "Soak and rinse potatoes to prevent oxidation", "Clarified vs. melted butter", "Fill in any gaps with extra potato slices", "Use 2 sheet pans for added insulation", "No blowtorch? No problem."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/potato-croissants"}, {"id": 174, "t": "Potato Pavé", "c": "Baking", "d": "Top-tier fried potatoes have a couple things in common: crispy on the outside, creamy and tender within. That goes for (good) fries, it goes for tots, and it goes for air-fried spuds, too. Put those two qualities together with a stunning mille-feuille look and what do you get? The potato pavé, aka the crispy and creamy potato preparation that’s designed to live on fine dining restaurant menus and ", "i": ["2.2 kg Russet potato(es) , (4 to 6 potatoes) peeled and rinsed (see “Before we begin” note)", "168 g Clarified butter , homemade or store-bought, melted", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 3/4 teaspoons), plus extra for serving", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed"], "s": ["Level up the pavé with a potato “croissant”", "Trim, slice, and rinse potatoes", "Dry potatoes", "Coat and season potatoes", "Build pavé", "Bake pavé", "Press and chill pavé", "Unmold and portion pavé", "Fry pavés", "Serve"], "tips": ["For maximum yield, use a mandoline.", "Soak and rinse potatoes to prevent oxidation", "Clarified vs. melted butter", "Why use 2 sheet pans? Insulation.", "Press pavé for the most uniform slices", "No blowtorch? No problem.", "Fry the right size pavé for any occasion"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/potato-pave"}, {"id": 175, "t": "Tips & Tricks: How to Fix a Broken Pan Sauce or Gravy", "c": "Baking", "d": "Silky pan sauces and rich gravies can make a good meal great. The beauty of pan sauces and gravies is they’re not just delicious liquids, they’re delicious emulsions. That means they’re made up of tiny globules of tasty fat completely surrounded by and suspended within water (fortified, hopefully, with some of the tasty brown bits of fond scraped up off the bottom of the pan). But if that emulsion", "i": [], "s": ["How to Do It", "Why It Works", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Getting saucy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-fix-a-broken-pan-sauce-or-gravy"}, {"id": 176, "t": "Perfect Pumpkin Pie", "c": "Baking", "d": "A good pumpkin pie has a crisp, flaky crust and a silky-smooth custard filling. Unfortunately, most pumpkin pies miss the mark. This recipe gets you a perfect pumpkin pie. There’s no tricks, no gimmicks; in fact, it’s nearly identical to the recipe you’ll find on the can of pumpkin purée. Getting this pie right just comes down to technique and a few tweaks. We blind-bake the pie crust properly, so", "i": ["0.5 recipe Perfect Pie Dough , (see “Before we begin” note)", "110 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs)", "90 g Egg yolk(s) , (6 large yolks)", "396 g Sweetened condensed milk , (1 can)", "425 g Pumpkin purée , canned (1 can)", "350 g Evaporated milk , (1 can)", "5 g Ginger , ground (2 1/2 teaspoons)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Sweet Spice , (3/4 teaspoon) optional"], "s": ["Roll out and chill pie shell (if you haven’t already)", "0.5 recipe", "Blind bake crust with weights", "Remove weights and finish blind bake", "Mix custard", "Fill and bake pie", "Cool pie", "Slice and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pumpkin-pie"}, {"id": 177, "t": "Turkey Stock", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "A holiday roast turkey isn’t complete without a great gravy, right? And for the best gravy, you need to start with great stock. We’ve designed this recipe to work with the bones and trim leftover from breaking down a turkey for any of our killer sous vide turkey recipes. Since you’ll probably need the turkey stock, stat, we use a pressure cooker to speed up the process—just like in our Pressure-Co", "i": ["1.8 kg Turkey bones , (see “Before we begin” note)", "240 g Yellow onion(s) , (1 small onion) cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "80 g Carrot(s) , (1 carrot) cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "80 g Celery , (3 ribs) cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "30 g Neutral oil", "2.5 kg Water , divided", "2 g Black peppercorns , whole (3/4 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh (6 sprigs)", "2 g Thyme , fresh (2 sprigs)", "1 Bay leaf , fresh", "2 kg Water 2 g Black peppercorns , whole (3/4 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Break down turkey carcass", "Roast turkey bones and aromatics", "Scrape fond", "Bring stock to boil", "Pressure cook stock", "Steep herbs", "Strain and chill stock"], "tips": ["No pressure cooker? No problem.", "For a clear stock, depressurize naturally.", "For stock with clean herb flavor, steep, don’t simmer.", "Defatting hot stock"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turkey-stock"}, {"id": 178, "t": "Turkey Gravy", "c": "Baking", "d": "The best part of a holiday turkey dinner is the gravy. It’s the not-so-secret sauce that ties it all together. Turkey, stuffing, mashed potatoes—everything gets a drizzle of the good stuff. This gravy is as straightforward, easy, and delicious as can be. Brown some giblets, make a roux, add good stock (turkey or chicken), simmer it down to your preferred consistency, and season it just right. No t", "i": ["Turkey giblets , and neck, from 1 turkey, optional (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "200 g Unsalted butter", "120 g All-purpose flour", "150 g Yellow onion(s) , (1 small onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 medium cloves) minced", "180 g Sherry , dry, optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 kg Turkey Stock , or Pressure-Cooked Brown Chicken Stock (see “Before we begin” note)", "4 g Sage , fresh leaves (about 10 leaves)", "2 g Bay leaf , fresh (about 5 leaves)", "Kosher salt , (0.5% of gravy weight) , as needed", "Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (0.2% of gravy weight) , as needed", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "30 g Sherry vinegar , optional", "Lemon juice , fresh, optional , as needed", "1.8 kg Turkey bones , chopped, and giblets", "100 g Onion(s) , diced", "124 g Bread flour"], "s": ["Slice and rinse giblets (optional)", "Brown giblets and neck (optional)", "Make roux and cook aromatics", "Add stock and reduce", "Strain and season gravy", "Put gravy to use"], "tips": ["What’s this fond all about?", "For a thicker gravy, keep reducing.", "Adjusting seasoning to taste", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turkey-gravy"}, {"id": 179, "t": "DIY Butterball Turkey", "c": "Meat", "d": "For many folks, Thanksgiving is synonymous with Butterball turkey. A Butterball’s promise of juicy, succulent, and tender meat—no matter how you cook it—is hard to pass up. And if it’s your one shot in the year to cook a turkey, why stress when you can depend on a sure thing? We love that! We just wanted to make it even better. This is our take on a Butterball turkey—super-juicy and tender, but no", "i": ["2 kg Water", "58 g Sodium tripolyphosphate , (see “Before we begin” note)", "96 g Kosher salt , divided", "80 g Granulated sugar", "1 Turkey , whole, fresh or fully thawed (5.4 to 7.25 kg; 12 to 16 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "14 g Neutral oil"], "s": ["Mix brine solution", "Prep and inject turkey with brine", "Truss turkey and refrigerate", "Roast turkey", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["How phosphates work", "Dispersing and dissolving sodium tripolyphosphate"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/diy-butterball-turkey"}, {"id": 180, "t": "Poulet Farci (Chicken-Stuffed Roast Chicken)", "c": "Baking", "d": "How do you transform a chicken into a Michelin-starred dish? You make poulet farci, a fancy French term for a fancy chicken-stuffed roast chicken crown! Inception chicken, incroyable! You get all the best parts of a perfect roast chicken—browned skin and juicy breast meat—but with the added bonus of a luxurious mushroom-and-herb-flecked farce, made with the dark meat, layered between the skin and ", "i": ["300 g Cremini mushrooms , cleaned, stemmed, and cut into 1/2-inch-thick pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Kosher salt , divided", "30 g Neutral oil", "1 Chicken , whole (1.6 kg to 1.8 kg; 3 1/2 to 4 pounds), preferably air-chilled (see “Before we begin” note)", "200 g Water", "6 g Cornstarch", "3 g Chicken bouillon powder , preferably from Orrington Farms (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Garlic powder , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Onion powder , (1 teaspoon)", "150 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "5 g Honey , (3/4 teaspoon)", "28 g Canned truffles , drained and minced, optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "8 g Chives , thinly sliced", "0.5 g Thyme , fresh leaves (1 sprig), roughly chopped", "45 g Clarified butter , melted, divided", "1 recipe Chicken Demi-Glace , for serving, optional", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, for finishing, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Cook mushroom duxelles", "Prepare chicken crown", "Inject brine (optional)", "Stitch up crown", "Separate skin from breast", "Cut up skin and dark meat for farce", "Process farce", "Stuff crown with farce", "Slow low-temp roast for juicy meat", "Rest chicken", "Fast high-temp roast for crispy skin", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["Turn extra farce into a classic quenelle “dumpling”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/poulet-farci"}, {"id": 181, "t": "Super-Juicy Butterball Rotisserie-Style Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "Everybody loves a juicy and tender Butterball turkey or Costco rotisserie chicken. But most people only eat turkey once a year, and only the elite have access to Kirkland’s exclusive members-only club. So, we engineered our own Butterball-inspired chicken! This is the best rotisserie chicken you’ll ever have, no spinning rotisserie setup required. The key to a Butterball bird and grocery store rot", "i": ["500 g Water", "8 g Sodium tripolyphosphate , (see “Before we begin” note)", "25 g Kosher salt", "20 g Granulated sugar", "1 Chicken , whole (1.6 to 1.8 kg; 3 1/2 to 4 pounds)", "10 g Neutral oil", "185 g Liquid shio koji"], "s": ["Mix brine solution", "Prep and inject chicken with brine", "Truss chicken and refrigerate overnight", "Roast chicken", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["How phosphates work", "Dispersing and dissolving sodium tripolyphosphate", "Give your chicken an extra umami boost with a koji brine.", "Don’t want to use an injector? Use an immersion brine instead.", "If using an immersion brine, skip the overnight air dry.", "If roasting an immersion-brined chicken", "Taste-testing and comparing brining methods"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/butterball-rotisserie-style-chicken"}, {"id": 182, "t": "Stock Options: Store-Bought Chicken Stock Substitutes and How to Use Them", "c": "Baking", "d": "The best chicken stock is homemade—no question. But sometimes what you need isn’t “the best”; sometimes you just need something that works well enough. Convenience, sometimes, is king. We take an all-of-the-above approach to chicken stock—we always recommend making and using your own brown or blond chicken stock, but we sometimes list boxed chicken stock as an acceptable sub, and we sometimes call", "i": [], "s": ["Boxed Chicken Stock", "Chicken Bouillon Powder", "Chicken Bouillon Concentrate", "ChefSteps Ultimate Bouillon Cubes"], "tips": ["Stock vs. Broth: What’s the Difference?", "How to Fortify Store-Bought Chicken Stock Products With Gelatin", "How We Tested Store-Bought Chicken Stock Substitutes"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/best-boxed-chicken-broth-stock"}, {"id": 183, "t": "Pan-Seared Brick Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "A lot of roast chicken recipes promise crispy skin and perfectly cooked meat but fail to deliver on both. The only recipe that truly delivers on those promises is our Ultimate Roast Chicken. But there’s another way to cook a chicken so it’s got crisp skin and perfectly cooked meat: chicken under a brick. For our version, we debone a half chicken and use skewers to anchor the parts together, which ", "i": ["1 Chicken , whole (1.6 to 1.8 kg; 3 1/2 to 4 pounds)", "Kosher salt , (0.5% of deboned chicken weight), plus extra as needed , as needed", "75 g Neutral oil", "15 g Shallot(s) , (1 small shallot) minced", "60 g White wine , dry", "175 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "3 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "0.2 g Thyme , fresh leaves (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.2 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/8 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "25 g Unsalted butter , room temperature, cut into 1 1/2-inch cubes", "5 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon), plus extra as needed", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, for finishing, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Cook it like you would in a restaurant", "Debone chicken", "Season and skewer chicken", "Sear and press chicken", "Make pan sauce", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["In a hurry? Reduce dry-brining time to 1 hour.", "Cooking the whole chicken at once", "Maintaining the sauce emulsion"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pan-seared-brick-chicken"}, {"id": 184, "t": "Roasted Chicken Fat Mayo", "c": "Sauce", "d": "How do you improve upon the best condiment in the world (mayo)? Spike it with the flavor of a beautifully roasted chicken. One of the best parts of a roast chicken isn’t the chicken itself, but what settles at the bottom of the pan after a long roast: golden, rendered chicken fat and flavorful fond. Tragically, this stuff often gets tossed out, but savvy cooks will turn those drippings into a sauc", "i": ["100 g Neutral oil", "50 g Chicken fat , rendered from 1 to 2 roast chickens (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Egg yolk(s) , (1 large yolk)", "15 g Apple cider vinegar", "10 g Dijon mustard", "10 g Roast chicken drippings , (aka fond), reserved from 1 to 2 roast chickens (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1/4 teaspoon), optional", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Blend fats", "Blend mayonnaise", "Put mayo to use"], "tips": ["Finding the right ratio of unsaturated fat to saturated fat for mayonnaise"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/roasted-chicken-fat-mayo"}, {"id": 185, "t": "Double Chicken Salad", "c": "Baking", "d": "Chicken salad often tastes more like mayo than chicken. Most mayo—for better or for worse—masks all of chicken’s delicate flavors. But what if the mayo in your chicken salad actually tasted like roast chicken, too? Sounds pretty great, right? This recipe has all the classic flavors of chicken salad, but amps up the chicken flavor with a generous helping of our Roasted Chicken Fat Mayo. To boost th", "i": ["100 g Red onion(s) , (1/2 medium onion) cut into 1/8-inch dice", "85 g Roasted Chicken Fat Mayo", "15 g Dijon mustard", "15 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon), plus extra as needed", "5 g Worcestershire sauce , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1/2 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note), optional", "56 g Celery , (1 1/2 ribs) cut into 1/8-inch dice", "6 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves and tender stems, finely chopped", "5 g Chives , thinly sliced", "4 g Tarragon , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "4 g Dill , fresh, finely chopped", "400 g Chicken , cooked, boneless, skinless breast or thighs, cut into 1/2-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed"], "s": ["Soak onion to remove bite", "Mix dressing", "Build chicken salad", "Serve"], "tips": ["Rinsing onions to remove pungency"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/double-chicken-salad"}, {"id": 186, "t": "Chicken Demi-Glace", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "This chicken demi-glace is an elegant vehicle for delivering ultra-concentrated, roasted chicken essence in an umami-packed sauce, and it’s the ultimate secret weapon for leveling up your chicken dinners. Unlike our beef demi-glace and our vegetarian demi-glace, we don’t use any tricks or thickeners for this chicken demi. It’s just carefully prepared chicken stock fortified with aromatics and sher", "i": ["35 g Unsalted butter", "75 g Shallot(s) , (2 medium shallots) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 cloves) thinly sliced", "5 g Tomato paste , (1 teaspoon)", "200 g Sherry , dry (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 l Pressure-Cooked Brown Chicken Stock", "1 g Fresh bay leaves , fresh (2 leaves), cut into 1/8-inch strips", "0.2 g Thyme , fresh leaves (1 sprig)", "0.2 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "Kosher salt , (1.2% of demi-glace weight) , as needed", "Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (0.2% of demi-glace weight) optional , as needed"], "s": ["Sweat aromatics", "Add tomato paste and deglaze with sherry", "Add stock and reduce", "Strain and season demi-glace", "Put demi to use"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-demi-glace"}, {"id": 187, "t": "Ultimate Roast Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is roast chicken, perfected. It’s what every other roast chicken recipe in the world promises but doesn’t deliver: a beautifully browned bird with actually crispy skin and super tender, super juicy, perfectly cooked meat. The process isn’t quick, but it’s worth it: Inject the bird with brine, let it air-dry for three to five days to dry out the skin, then use a two-step cooking process with a", "i": ["500 g Water", "25 g Kosher salt", "1 Chicken , whole (1.6 to 1.8 kg; 3.5 to 4 pounds)"], "s": ["Remove wishbone and inject brine", "Tie legs and hang chicken", "Slow low-temp roast for juicy meat", "Rest chicken", "Fast high-temp roast for crispy skin", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["The original Ultimate Roast Chicken video", "How to dry and roast chicken without hanging it", "Using a Rational or countertop oven?", "Don’t smoke out your kitchen"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-roast-chicken"}, {"id": 188, "t": "Pressure-Cooked Brown Chicken Stock", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Pressure-cooked chicken stock is easy to make and takes a fraction of the time it would if you simmered it on the stovetop. Roasting the chicken bones and the aromatic vegetables adds deep flavor, thanks to Maillard browning and caramelization—especially if you scrape up all the fond from the bottom of the roasting pan. While this stock is a little more work than a blond chicken stock, it makes up", "i": ["2.3 kg Chicken bones , (see “Before we begin” note)", "300 g Yellow onion(s) , (1 onion) cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "100 g Carrot(s) , (1 carrot) cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "100 g Celery , (3 ribs) cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "30 g Neutral oil", "2.3 kg Water , divided", "2 g Black peppercorns , whole (3/4 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh (6 sprigs)", "2 g Thyme , fresh (2 sprigs)", "1 Bay leaf , fresh", "1.8 kg Water 2 g Black peppercorns , whole (3/4 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "700 g Onion(s) , peeled and quartered"], "s": ["Roast chicken bones and aromatics", "Scrape fond", "Bring stock to boil", "Pressure cook stock", "Steep herbs", "Strain and chill stock"], "tips": ["For a clear stock, depressurize naturally.", "For stock with clean herb flavor, steep, don’t simmer.", "Defatting hot stock", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pressure-cooked-brown-chicken-stock"}, {"id": 189, "t": "Pressure-Cooked Blond Chicken Stock", "c": "Sauce", "d": "This golden chicken stock is extremely versatile and ridiculously easy to make. With a pressure cooker, you can make stock in about a quarter of the time it takes in a regular pot on the stovetop, but this recipe works for both. It’s a great way to use chicken bones or carcasses that you would otherwise discard. Cook a large batch and stash it in your freezer. Use it for making soups, consommé, st", "i": ["2.3 kg Water", "2.3 kg Chicken bones , (see “Before we begin” note)", "300 g Yellow onion(s) , (1 onion) cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "100 g Carrot(s) , (1 carrot) cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "100 g Celery , (3 ribs) cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "2 g Black peppercorns , whole (3/4 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh (6 sprigs)", "2 g Thyme , fresh (2 sprigs)", "1 Bay leaf , fresh", "2.2 kg Chicken , bones, carcasses, or bone-in pieces", "700 g Sweet onion(s) , peeled and quartered"], "s": ["Bring stock to boil", "Pressure-cook stock", "Steep herbs", "Strain and chill stock"], "tips": ["No pressure cooker? No problem", "For stock with clean herb flavor, steep, don’t simmer.", "Defatting hot stock", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pressure-cooked-blond-chicken-stock"}, {"id": 190, "t": "Classic Chicken Consommé", "c": "Baking", "d": "Consommé is the apex of refinement: A strong, full-flavored stock is clarified using a little kitchen alchemy to produce a delicious, crystal-clear broth. It’s one of those French classics that you learn to make in culinary school and then often never think about again. But you should think about it, because it's fantastic as a sipping broth or elegant soup base. This recipe uses the classic techn", "i": ["2 Chicken breast(s) , boneless, skinless (about 680 g; 1 1/2 pounds total), cut into 1-inch pieces", "6 Egg white(s)", "150 g Onion(s) , (1 small onion) cut into 1-inch dice", "100 g Celery , (3 ribs) cut into 1-inch-thick slices, plus extra cut into brunoise for serving", "100 g Carrot(s) , (1 small carrot) peeled and cut into 1-inch-thick slices, plus extra cut into brunoise for serving", "55 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves, coarsely chopped", "8 g Thyme , fresh sprigs", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "2 kg Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt , (0.75% of consommé weight; see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (0.3% of consommé weight; see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "Knox gelatin , (2% of consommé weight; optional, see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "Shallot(s) , cut into brunoise for serving, optional , as needed", "1 recipe Perfect Sous Vide Poached Eggs , for serving, optional", "Extra-virgin olive oil , for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Classic vs. modernist consommé", "Form raft", "Combine raft and stock and bring to boil", "Ladle stock over raft", "Strain consommé", "Season and thicken consommé (optional)", "Serve"], "tips": ["Gently does it", "Level up your consommé with a French press"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/classic-chicken-consomme"}, {"id": 191, "t": "Pozole Rojo", "c": "Baking", "d": "Not all pozole is created equal. A deceptively simple soup, packed with plump kernels of hominy and tender morsels of meat and served with an array of raw vegetables and crunchy stuff like tortilla chips and fried pork rinds, pozole can run the gamut from bland to holy-smokes-this-is-good. Our pozole rojo might just be the champion of the latter camp. With a rich pork stock serving as the base, he", "i": ["500 g Dried corn (kernels) , preferably heirloom (1.1 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "8.9 kg Water , divided", "5 g Calcium hydroxide , (see “Before we begin” note)", "2.7 kg Pork neck bones , (see “Before we begin” note)", "75 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided", "25 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "3.6 kg Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "190 g Carrot(s) , (2 to 3 carrots) peeled and cut into 2-inch pieces", "100 g Celery , (3 ribs) cut into 2-inch pieces", "170 g Garlic clove(s) , (34 cloves) divided", "10 g Oregano , fresh sprigs", "3 Fresh bay leaves", "2 g Coriander seeds , whole (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "0.5 g Cumin seeds , whole (1/8 teaspoon)", "45 g Guajillo chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and torn into 1-inch pieces", "20 g Pasilla chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and torn into 1-inch pieces", "5 g Chicken bouillon powder", "0.5 recipe Classic Carnitas , (see “Before we begin” note)", "Roma tomato(es) , cored and cut into small dice, for serving , as needed", "Radishes , thinly sliced, for serving , as needed", "Cabbage , shredded, for serving , as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed", "Cilantro , leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving, optional , as needed", "Mexican oregano , dried, for serving , as needed", "Tostadas , for serving, optional , as needed", "285 g White onion(s) , halved"], "s": ["Pozole timeline", "Cook corn kernels", "Soak corn overnight and rinse", "Roast pork bones", "Make pork stock", "Cook mole base", "Blend mole", "Cook pozole", "0.5 recipe", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["What is calcium hydroxide? It’s the key to nixtamalization.", "Bumping up the flavor of pozole"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pozole-rojo"}, {"id": 192, "t": "Ultra-Tender Lion’s Head Meatballs", "c": "Baking", "d": "What do you get when you combine the richness of a braised pork shank, the delicate texture of a custard, the juiciness of a soup dumpling, and the bounciness of a good old-fashioned meatball? You get Lion’s Head Meatballs (shīzǐ tóu). The name alludes to their shape, which is said to resemble the head of the Chinese guardian lion. And they’re just as regal and majestic as they sound: massive, bas", "i": ["900 g Pork belly , skin-off, preferably center cut (see “Before we begin” note)", "60 g Light Chinese soy sauce , divided", "52 g Potato starch , divided", "45 g Shaoxing wine , divided", "45 g Granulated sugar , divided", "60 g Water , divided", "30 g Oyster sauce , divided", "4 g Baking soda , (3/4 teaspoon)", "5 g White pepper , ground (1 1/4 teaspoons), divided", "6 g Kosher salt , divided, plus more as needed", "140 g Water chestnuts , minced", "100 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs)", "90 g Scallion(s) , (6 scallions), 60 g (4 scallions) minced and 30 g (2 scallions) cut into 2-inch pieces, divided", "50 g Fresh ginger root , (3 1/4-inch piece), 20 g (1 1/4-inch piece) peeled and finely grated and 30 g (2-inch piece) sliced, divided", "10 g Neutral oil , plus extra as needed for frying", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 medium cloves) smashed", "20 g Dark Chinese soy sauce", "1 kg Chicken stock , homemade or store-bought low-sodium chicken stock", "10 g Toasted sesame oil", "4 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1 1/4 teaspoons; see “Before we begin” note)", "900 g Baby bok choy , halved lengthwise and washed", "Jasmine rice , cooked, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Process pork belly", "Mix meatball base", "Portion meatballs and chill", "Fry meatballs", "Build braising liquid", "Braise meatballs", "Blanch bok choy", "Thicken braising liquid", "Glaze meatballs", "Serve"], "tips": ["The keys to the lightest meatball", "No food processor? Hand-mince the pork belly.", "How to deal with lumps in your sauce"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/lions-head-meatballs"}, {"id": 193, "t": "Shrimp Toast", "c": "Baking", "d": "Shrimp toast is all about texture: juicy, succulent shrimp mousse cooked to a just-bouncy consistency, resting on an ultra-crispy, fried layer of fluffy milk bread. It’s crispy, it’s unctuous, it’s savory, and it offers an irresistible cascade of textures and flavors. That’s probably why dim sum restaurants sell shrimp toast in multiples, knowing full well you could never eat just one. Shrimp toas", "i": ["230 g Shrimp , jumbo (26–30 per pound), peeled and deveined", "2 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon)", "1 g Baking soda , (1/4 teaspoon)", "50 g Water chestnuts , cut into 1/8-inch dice", "20 g Scallion(s) , (2 scallions) thinly sliced", "10 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, finely chopped", "10 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and grated", "33 g Egg white(s) , (from 1 large egg)", "4 g Granulated sugar , (1 teaspoon)", "4 g Toasted sesame oil , (3/4 teaspoon)", "2.5 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (3/4 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "1.5 g White pepper , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "15 g Lard , (see “Before we begin” note)", "6 g Cornstarch", "Shokupan (Japanese Milk Bread) , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "50 g Sesame seeds", "50 g Neutral oil , divided"], "s": ["Keys to perfect shrimp toast", "Salt and tenderize shrimp", "Cut and divide shrimp", "Make shrimp mousse", "Cut bread squares or circles", "Build toasts", "Fry toasts", "Serve"], "tips": ["Ring molds are so back!", "Use a scale to portion shrimp mousse"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/shrimp-toast"}, {"id": 194, "t": "New School Egg Foo Young", "c": "Baking", "d": "Egg foo young is a distinctly Chinatown dish that’s been a mainstay in Chinese menus as far back as the mid-1800s. And it’s not hard to see why: It’s basically a deep-fried, savory omelet packed with all kinds of meats and vegetables, and draped in velvety, umami-rich brown sauce. It’s crispy, it’s savory, it’s a little greasy, and it’s deeply satisfying. This recipe puts a new spin on the takeout", "i": ["15 g Shiitake mushrooms , dried", "40 g Oyster sauce , divided", "10 g Dark Chinese soy sauce", "24 g Cornstarch , divided", "10 g Light Chinese soy sauce , divided", "5 g Sugar , (2 1/4 teaspoons)", "6 g Toasted sesame oil , divided", "2 g White pepper , ground (1 teaspoon), divided", "1 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1/4 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "220 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium, store-bought stock", "320 g Neutral oil , divided", "5 g Garlic , (1 medium clove) finely grated", "30 g Shaoxing wine", "30 g Corn , frozen kernels, defrosted", "30 g Frozen peas , defrosted", "40 g Scallion(s) , (2 scallions) thinly sliced, divided", "15 g Water", "4 Egg(s) , large, divided", "5 g Fish sauce", "1 g Cream of tartar , (1/4 teaspoon)", "30 g Mung bean sprouts , tails removed, optional", "White rice , cooked, for serving, optional , as needed", "100 g Chicken thighs , boneless, skinless, trimmed and cut into 1/4-inch pieces"], "s": ["Riffing on a classic", "Hydrate dried mushrooms", "Mix brown sauce base", "Cook brown sauce", "Cook vegetables", "Mix crispy egg topping", "Mix fluffy egg base", "Fry crispy topping and spread egg mixture", "Bake egg foo young", "Unmold egg foo young", "Serve"], "tips": ["Not into mushrooms? Make it a chicken egg foo young", "An alternative egg foo young dismount"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/egg-foo-young"}, {"id": 195, "t": "Crispy Cantonese Roast Pork Belly (Siu Yuk)", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Chinatown barbecue shops with char siu, roast duck, and soy sauce chicken hanging in their front windows specialize in a variety of foods collectively called siu mei—a catchall term for meats often roasted over an open-fire. There are few foods as emblematic of siu mei than Cantonese roast pork belly, or siu yuk—fragrant, succulent meat hiding beneath a uniform layer of golden brown, super-crispy ", "i": ["5 g Sand ginger , dried (5 small pieces; see “Before we begin” note)", "4 g White peppercorn , (1 teaspoon)", "48 g Kosher salt , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "0.5 g Five-spice powder , (1/8 teaspoon)", "3 g Granulated sugar , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (1/4 teaspoon)", "900 g Pork belly , skin-on, center cut (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Make belly cure", "Make dipping salt", "Cure pork belly", "Heat sous vide bath", "Bag pork belly", "Cook pork belly sous vide", "Air dry pork belly", "Air fry pork belly", "Carve roast pork belly", "Serve"], "tips": ["Cover for long cooking times", "The effects of air-drying cooked pork belly", "An easier way to carve Cantonese pork belly"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crispy-cantonese-roast-pork-belly"}, {"id": 196, "t": "Texas-Style Barbecue Ribs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "People think Texas barbecue is all about beef: thick slabs of tender, smoky brisket and Lone Star State–sized beef ribs. But Texans also smoke some killer pork ribs. Joe Yim of Knox Ave BBQ gave us the rundown on how to make the best Texas-style spareribs. Like brisket, they’re a study in moderation: completely tender, but with a little bite; seasoned with a judicious amount of salt and black pepp", "i": ["1 Pork spareribs , whole rack (1.3 to 1.6 kg; 3 to 3 1/2 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "Black pepper , coarsely ground (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Apple cider vinegar, as needed", "Water, as needed", "1 recipe Kansas City-Style Barbecue Sauce , (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["The barbecue rib timeline", "Trim ribs", "Season ribs", "Set up smoker", "Build color and bark; render fat", "Pass the “squish test”", "Glaze ribs", "Wrap ribs", "Finish tenderizing ribs", "Rest", "Slice ribs", "Serve"], "tips": ["Why it’s important to trim ribs properly", "Even seasoning and using other rubs", "Setting up other styles of grills", "The importance of temperature control", "When to spritz ribs", "Using a fan to give your smoker a temperature boost", "Getting the right consistency in a barbecue sauce", "Why you wrap ribs", "Extending the rest time with a cooler", "What ribs look like when they’re done", "The best rib texture"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/texas-style-barbecue-ribs"}, {"id": 197, "t": "Spareribs vs. Baby Back Ribs: What’s the Difference?", "c": "Meat", "d": "Not all pork ribs are the same. When shopping for ribs, you basically have two options: spareribs and baby back ribs. Spareribs can be broken down further to produce two other cuts: St. Louis-style ribs and rib tips. Butchers and barbecue pros generally favor spareribs over baby backs, but both can be delicious when treated right. This guide will take you through the key differences so you can fin", "i": [], "s": ["The Anatomy of Pork Ribs", "Spareribs", "Baby Back Ribs"], "tips": ["How to Break Down a Pig"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spareribs-baby-back-ribs-what-is-the-difference"}, {"id": 198, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Use a Cooler to Keep Barbecue Warm", "c": "Baking", "d": "The trickiest part about serving barbecue, whether it’s brisket, ribs, or pork shoulder, is serving it while it’s still warm. Smoking meat is a technique that operates on its own schedule, or rather, the meat’s schedule: It takes hours and hours to transform tough cuts into tender, smoky, barky barbecue. When the meat is finally done cooking, it needs to rest. And once it’s done resting, you need ", "i": [], "s": ["How to Do It", "Why It Works", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Right on ’cue"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-tricks-use-a-cooler-to-keep-barbecue-warm"}, {"id": 199, "t": "Smoked Brisket Burgers", "c": "Baking", "d": "When you make a Texas-style brisket, you end up with a lot of trim. And one of the best things you can do with that trim is grind it up and make smoked brisket burgers. They’ve got everything you love about smoked brisket, but they only take a couple of hours instead of 14 (or more!). Rich and juicy, with a beautifully smoky crust that’s reminiscent of the best barbecue bark, they’re an upgrade on", "i": ["910 g Brisket , (see “Before we begin” note)", "25 g Black pepper , coarsely ground (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Kosher salt", "15 g Beef tallow , or neutral oil (see “Before we begin” note)", "Cheddar , sliced, optional , as needed", "50 g Ketchup , optional", "50 g Yellow mustard , optional", "50 g Mayonnaise , optional", "2 g Celery seeds , (1 teaspoon) optional", "4 Hamburger bun(s) , toasted", "Fast and Easy Pickled Onion , optional , as needed", "Dill pickles , sliced, homemade or store-bought, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Grind brisket", "Form patties", "Set up smoker", "Season burgers", "Smoke burgers", "Sear burgers", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": ["Keep it ice-cold", "Setting up other styles of grills", "Seasoning burgers like brisket"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smoked-brisket-burgers"}, {"id": 200, "t": "Ultimate Texas-Style Barbecue Brisket", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We’ve tackled Texas-style barbecue brisket before. We’ve developed two indoor recipes that get you as close as you can get to the real thing without a smoker, using both sous vide and a low-temperature oven. But we’ve never done the real deal smoked brisket—until now. To get it right, we turned to pro pitmaster Joe Yim of Knox Ave BBQ, who honed his craft for years at some of the top barbecue spot", "i": ["1 Brisket , (5.9 to 6.8 kg; 13 to 15 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g Black pepper , coarsely ground (see “Before we begin” note)", "80 g Kosher salt", "Apple cider vinegar, as needed", "Water, as needed"], "s": ["The barbecue brisket timeline", "Trim brisket", "Season brisket", "Light fire", "Bring brisket up to temperature", "Enter “the stall”; build bark and color", "Exit “the stall”; render fat", "Wrap brisket", "Tenderize brisket", "Rest brisket", "Slice", "Serve"], "tips": ["Why it’s important to trim a brisket properly", "Even seasoning", "Setting up other styles of grills", "The importance of temperature control", "What is the “pellicle”?", "When to spritz a brisket", "What is “the stall”?", "Checking on a PK and kamado-style grill", "Why you wrap brisket", "Extending the rest time with a cooler", "Inside barbecue-slicing hospitality baseball", "Stressed about hosting a brisket cookout? Cook it the day before.", "Is wagyu brisket worth it?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-smoked-bbq-brisket"}, {"id": 201, "t": "How to Slice Barbecue Brisket Like a Pro", "c": "Baking", "d": "Once you’ve trimmed, seasoned, smoked, wrapped, and rested your barbecue brisket, it’s time to slice it. Just like every other technique associated with producing Texas-style barbecue brisket, the method for slicing it up is tailor-made to the preparation, designed to minimize waste and ensure that every slice that comes off the brisket has structural integrity and is surrounded by a continuous la", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 recipe Ultimate Texas-Style Barbecue Brisket , whole, cooked and rested to 160 °F / 71 °C (See “Before we begin”)", "1 recipe Ultimate Texas-Style Barbecue Brisket , whole, cooked and rested to 160 °F / 71 °C (See “Before we begin”)"], "s": ["Anatomy of a barbecue brisket", "Barbecue brisket slicing technique", "Separate flat from the point", "Slice flat", "Slice point", "Chop lean brisket from point (optional)", "Serve", "All the barbecue trimmings!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-slice-bbq-brisket"}, {"id": 202, "t": "How to Trim Brisket Like a Pro", "c": "Baking", "d": "Trimming a brisket properly is the first step in making a great barbecue brisket. Trimming helps the brisket cook more evenly, producing even bark formation; golden, rendered fat; and juicy meat. The goal for barbecue pros is to produce a smoked brisket that’s cooked in a way that every single slice will satisfy discerning paying customers. So, if you want to serve competition-worthy brisket, star", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 Brisket , whole, (5.9–6.8 kg; 13–15 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "1 Brisket , whole, (5.9–6.8 kg; 13–15 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["The anatomy of a brisket", "Trim away heel fat", "Trim away excess fat from bottom of brisket", "Flip and trim sides", "Remove mohawk", "Trim flat", "Trim away straggling meat and sharp corners", "Round off point", "Trim fat cap", "Last looks and organize trim", "Let’s ’cue up for the ultimate brisket at home"], "tips": ["Make sure the brisket is cold", "Cutting fat away with the grain for a better final result", "Trace a line first for big cuts", "Use long strokes for smooth surfaces", "Gauging the thickness of the fat cap"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-trim-brisket-bbq"}, {"id": 203, "t": "How to Wrap Barbecue Brisket Like a Pro", "c": "Baking", "d": "Wrapping is one of the key techniques for making great barbecue brisket. The wrap can be used for two purposes: to help rest a finished brisket or to help finish cooking a brisket that needs a little help getting to the “memory foam” tenderness we’re looking for in the flat before pulling it off the smoker to rest. For resting, the wrap ensures that every part of the oddly shaped cut of meat cools", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 recipe Ultimate Texas-Style Barbecue Brisket , whole, partially or fully cooked - Apple cider vinegar , optional , as needed - Water, as needed", "1 recipe Ultimate Texas-Style Barbecue Brisket , whole, partially or fully cooked - Apple cider vinegar , optional , as needed - Water, as needed", "Apple cider vinegar , optional , as needed", "Water, as needed"], "s": ["It’s a Wrap: Butcher Paper vs. Foil Boat", "Set Up Wrapping Station", "The Beginner Wrap", "The Pro Wrap", "The Foil Boat", "Fire up the kettle grill"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-wrap-bbq-brisket"}, {"id": 204, "t": "Plotting the Barbecue Brisket Timeline", "c": "Baking", "d": "Smoking a Texas-style brisket takes time—a lot of time—and patience. Transforming the oddly shaped cut of meat with two distinct muscle groups and tons of connective tissue and intramuscular fat so that it can be cleanly sliced, with each slice consisting of tender, juicy meat surrounded by a distinct ring of bark, is a careful balancing act of time, temperature, and moisture levels. And even when", "i": [], "s": ["The Timeline", "Trim and Season the Brisket", "Gather Your Materials", "Start the Fire (Early!)", "Raise the Brisket Internal Temperature (Hours 0.5–4)", "Building Color and Entering “the Stall” (Hours 4–8)", "Exiting “the Stall” and Tenderizing (Hours 8–10)", "Rendering Fat and Wrapping (Hours 10–12)", "Rest (Hours 12–14)", "Slice and Serve or Hold for the Next Day", "The whole BBQ kit and kaboodle"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bbq-brisket-timeline"}, {"id": 205, "t": "How to Shop for Better Steak", "c": "Baking", "d": "A great steak dinner doesn’t start in your kitchen—it starts at the store. The difference between a so-so meal and a stellar one isn’t just about cooking technique. Sourcing the best quality beef that fits your budget is just as important as getting a good sear and nailing the internal temperature. To help you cut through the noise and buy the best steak cuts possible while also taking into accoun", "i": [], "s": ["Steak 101", "Trophy Steaks", "Specialty Steaks", "Value Steaks", "How to Pick a Trophy Steak", "Filet Mignon", "New York Strip", "Ribeye", "Porterhouse", "Steak Shopping FAQ", "How much steak should I buy per person?", "Are bone-in steaks better than boneless steaks?", "How can I distinguish between tougher and more tender steaks at the butcher counter?", "Are steaks with more marbling better than steaks with less marbling?", "Does marbling affect the way you cook steaks?", "What’s the deal with beef quality grades? Should I always buy “Prime”?", "If I have the option, should I buy dry-aged beef?", "Do I cook dry-aged beef the same way as unaged beef?", "How does wet-aged beef compare with dry-aged meat?", "Everything else you want to know about beef!"], "tips": ["I Can’t Believe It’s Not Filet!", "Beef Tenderloin Butchery", "New York Strip Butchery", "Ribeye Butchery", "Porterhouse Butchery", "What’s the Difference Between a Porterhouse and T-bone Steak?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-shop-for-better-steak"}, {"id": 206, "t": "Decoding Beef Labeling", "c": "Meat", "d": "Whenever you go to a steakhouse, a butcher, or even the grocery store, you’re presented with a lot of industry jargon and confusing marketing terminology. From the diet and breed of the animal to the yield and quality grades, as well as how extensively it has been aged, there’s just a lot of information to sort through and analyze. To demystify the wide world of beef, we’ve put together this guide", "i": [], "s": ["Beef Grading 101", "USDA Meat Quality Grades", "Not All Prime Is Equal: Beef Purchasing Power and Quality", "High-Quality Ungraded Beef", "Japanese Wagyu Grades", "Aging Beef", "Dry-Aged Beef", "Wet-Aged Beef", "Grass-Fed vs. Grain-Fed Beef", "It’s a steak out!"], "tips": ["What Is Branded Beef?", "American Wagyu vs. Japanese Wagyu", "Old vs. Aged Beef", "Koji-Aged Beef", "Cattle Breeds"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/decoding-beef-labeling"}, {"id": 207, "t": "10 Epic Steaks, Cooked 10 Epic Ways", "c": "Baking", "d": "There’s nothing like a great steak dinner. Rosy red beef, some spuds, a side of creamed spinach, an ice-cold wedge salad, shrimp cocktail, and a towering slice of cake to cap things off. Our only beef with a steakhouse feast? The dent that it puts in your wallet if you’re footing the bill. With that in mind, we’ve set out to save you a few bucks by bringing the steakhouse to your house. Grant and ", "i": [], "s": ["Charting Your Steak Adventure", "Trophy Steaks", "Filet Mignon", "Poached Filet Mignon", "New York Strip", "Butter-Basted New York Strip Steak", "Ribeye", "Grilled and Butter-Rested Ribeye", "Tomahawk Steak", "Reverse Cryo-Seared Tomahawk Steak", "Porterhouse", "Ultimate Porterhouse Steak", "Specialty Steaks", "Toro Steak", "Toro Steak With Koji Brown Butter", "Picanha", "Slow-Roasted Picanha Steak", "Value Steaks", "London Royale", "London Royale Seared Beef Carpaccio", "Chop Steak", "Ultimate Chop Steak", "Chuck Steak", "Ultimate Grilled Chuck Steak", "Beef up on beef knowledge"], "tips": ["Beef Tenderloin Butchery", "Selecting the Best New York Strip in the Butcher Case", "New York Strip Butchery", "Selecting the Best Ribeye in the Butcher Case", "Ribeye Butchery", "Tomahawk Butchery", "Selecting the Best Porterhouse in the Butcher Case", "Porterhouse vs. T-bone Steaks: What’s the Difference?", "Porterhouse Butchery", "How to Carve Steaks for Maximum Tenderness With Just a Steak Knife", "Tallow (A Steak Is Born)", "Toro Butchery", "Looking for More Meaty Koji Applications? Use It to Rapid-Age Steaks!", "I Can’t Believe It’s Not Filet!", "London Royale Butchery"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ten-steaks-ten-ways"}, {"id": 208, "t": "London Royale Seared Beef Carpaccio", "c": "Baking", "d": "Say goodbye to London broil and say hello to the London Royale! London broil is a value steak, typically cut from the round, and it may be the worst named steak in the world. The cut doesn’t exist in London, for one thing, and this tough cut should never, ever, be broiled. Treat it with care, however, and you can turn this inexpensive cut into one of the most delicious steaks—so delicious that we ", "i": ["2 London Royale steak(s) , preferably 2 1/2 inches thick (113–170 g; 4–6 ounces each; see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "45 g Beef tallow , or neutral oil", "56 g Unsalted butter , softened, cut into 1-inch cubes", "20 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 cloves) thinly sliced", "1 Rosemary , fresh sprig", "Flake sea salt , for serving, optional , as needed", "Crusty bread , thickly sliced, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["London Royale at a glance", "London Royale butchery", "Leveling up London broil into London Royale", "Sear steaks", "Butter baste steaks", "Briefly rest steaks", "Slice steaks, toss in butter, and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/london-royale-beef-carpaccio"}, {"id": 209, "t": "Slow-Roasted Picanha Steak", "c": "Baking", "d": "Picanha is the steak that you can cook like duck breast. The sirloin cap, from the rump of the animal, even looks similar to a super-sized duck breast with a triangular shape and robust fat cap. We like to score the fat cap and slowly sear the picanha in a pan to evenly render and crisp the fat before giving it a butter baste and finishing it in a low oven. Because of the uneven shape of the cut, ", "i": ["1 Picanha steak , with fat cap, (1.4–2.3 kg; 3–5 pounds; see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Beef tallow , or neutral oil (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "56 g Unsalted butter , softened, cut into 1-inch cubes", "3 Garlic clove(s)", "1 Star anise", "1 Cinnamon stick(s)", "3 Bay leaf , fresh", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Picanha at a glance", "Trim picanha and score fat cap", "Render and crisp fat cap", "Butter baste picanha", "Slow-roast picanha", "Rest steak", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Leaning into the doneness gradient"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/picanha-steak"}, {"id": 210, "t": "Ultimate Porterhouse Steak", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The porterhouse is the king of steaks. The unique pleasure a porterhouse provides is that you get two steaks in one. It’s a cross section of the short loin that contains two prized cuts—a New York strip and a filet mignon—separated by a big old bone. Like a tomahawk, a porterhouse ain’t cheap, and we certainly wouldn’t fault anyone for taking a safe sous vide or reverse-sear cooking approach to pr", "i": ["1 Porterhouse steak , 2–3 inches thick (1.1–1.4 kg; 2 1/2–3 pounds)", "Beef tallow , or 45 g neutral oil (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "100 g Unsalted butter , softened, cut into 1-inch cubes", "6 Garlic clove(s)", "10 Rosemary , fresh sprigs", "10 Thyme , fresh sprigs", "Beef Demi-Glace , (see “Before we begin” note) optional , as needed", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Porterhouse at a glance", "Porterhouse butchery", "Selecting the best porterhouse in the butcher case", "Score fat cap", "Render and crisp fat cap", "Sear steak", "Butter baste steak", "Roast steak to finish cooking", "Rest steak", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["Porterhouse vs. T-bone steaks: What’s the difference?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/porterhouse-steak"}, {"id": 211, "t": "Toro Steak With Koji Brown Butter", "c": "Baking", "d": "Toro is the best steak you’ve never heard of. Why is that? Well, because it’s a cut that master butcher Kevin Smith of Seattle’s Beast and Cleaver came up with! Seriously, it’s one of the few steaks you won’t find in our Cuts catalog. The toro is the highest abdominal muscle on a cow, and it has a lot of marbling—it may just be the most marbled muscle on the whole animal. Because of that, and the ", "i": ["455 g Toro steak , (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "45 g Beef tallow", "40 g Unsalted butter", "45 g Shio koji , blended into a paste (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Toro steak at a glance", "Toro butchery", "Sear toro steak", "Butter baste steak", "Briefly rest steak and add koji to butter-tallow mixture", "Slice steak, toss in butter, and serve"], "tips": ["An abbreviated rest"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/toro-steak"}, {"id": 212, "t": "Porterhouse vs. T-Bone Steaks: What’s the Difference?", "c": "Baking", "d": "Master butcher Kevin Smith of Beast and Cleaver gets asked this question all the time: What’s the difference between a porterhouse and a T-bone steak? Basically, it comes down to size. While both steaks are cut from the short loin and contain a New York strip and a tenderloin steak, separated by a T-shaped bone, a porterhouse is essentially a super-sized T-bone with a larger tenderloin section. Ho", "i": [], "s": ["Porterhouse", "T-Bone", "Bone-In New York Strip", "Short Loin Butchery", "We meat again"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/porterhouse-vs-t-bone-steaks-what-is-the-difference"}, {"id": 213, "t": "Tips & Tricks: How to Carve Steaks for Maximum Tenderness", "c": "Baking", "d": "When a beautifully cooked hunk of beef hits the table at a steakhouse, you know what to do: Roll up your sleeves and go to town. Steak is beauty, steak is life, and that’s true whether you use a razor sharp steak knife and a fork, or you grab the dang thing in your hands like the glorious carnivorous animal you are and down it in huge, honking bites. There’s no wrong way to eat steak. However, we ", "i": [], "s": ["Filet Mignon", "Porterhouse", "Bone-In Ribeye", "Why It Works", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Raise the steaks"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-tricks-how-to-carve-steaks"}, {"id": 214, "t": "Poached Filet Mignon", "c": "Baking", "d": "The defining quality of a filet mignon is its tenderness. With relatively little intramuscular fat and a tight muscle grain structure, most tenderloin steaks can be cut with a spoon. In fact, the tenderloin is so tender that almost any classic cooking method will make it less tender—apply heat to the tender bundles of muscle fibers and they tighten and contract. We came up with a way to keep that ", "i": ["946 g Beef broth , low-sodium store-bought broth or homemade stock", "30 g Maggi Seasoning", "12 g Thyme , fresh sprigs", "2 Filet mignon(s) , center-cut, 1-inch-thick (140–170 g; 5–6 ounces each)", "10 g Granulated sugar", "21 g Knox gelatin", "20 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "Flake sea salt , for finishing , as needed"], "s": ["Filet mignon at a glance", "Beef tenderloin butchery", "Choose your doneness", "Poach steaks", "Make sauce", "Finish steaks", "Slice and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/poached-filet-mignon"}, {"id": 215, "t": "Butter-Basted New York Strip Steak", "c": "Baking", "d": "The New York strip is a classic steak: easy to find, easy to cook, and easy to eat—the Goldilocks steak. For this classic cut, we chose a classic cooking technique: a pan sear with a butter-baste finish. The high heat sear kickstarts surface browning, and the butter baste gradually brings the internal temperature up while fortifying the browning created by the sear, so you get a beautiful, burnish", "i": ["2 Strip steak(s) , boneless, 1 1/2-inches-thick, (400–455 g; 14–16 ounces each)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "15 g Neutral oil", "2 Garlic head(s) , outer papery skins removed and top 1/2-inch of heads trimmed away", "2 Shallot(s) , large, halved", "112 g Unsalted butter , cut into 1-inch cubes", "12 g Thyme , fresh sprigs", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, optional , as needed"], "s": ["New York strip at a glance", "Strip steak butchery", "Selecting the best New York strip in the butcher case", "Choose your doneness", "Trim steaks", "Sear steaks", "Butter baste steaks to finish", "Rest steaks", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Why we trim strip steaks", "“High Delta T” technique and carryover cooking"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/butter-basted-strip-steak"}, {"id": 216, "t": "Loaded and Laminated Wedge Salad", "c": "Baking", "d": "Let’s face it: Wedge salads aren’t usually prepared with a lot of care. Quarter a head of iceberg, toss it on a plate, douse it with lumpy blue cheese dressing, scatter some bacon bits and diced tomato and onion on top, impale it with a steak knife, and serve it up with some steakhouse sass and a martini. Of course, it’s delicious—no one can deny that. Like shrimp cocktail, even a bad wedge is pre", "i": ["60 g Panko breadcrumbs", "30 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "6 Bacon , slices", "180 g Sour cream", "30 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 2 lemons)", "8 g Lemon zest , (from 1 lemon) finely grated", "20 g Chives , thinly sliced", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.25 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "1 Iceberg lettuce , head", "125 g Tomato(es) , (2 medium tomatoes) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "80 g Red onion(s) , (1/2 medium onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "100 g Blue cheese , frozen"], "s": ["Building a better wedge", "Toast breadcrumbs", "Make bacon crumbles", "Prepare dressing", "Cut lettuce into wedges and separate layers", "Dress and assemble wedges", "Plate and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/wedge-salad"}, {"id": 217, "t": "Reverse Cryo-Seared Tomahawk Steak", "c": "Baking", "d": "In the world of steaks, the tomahawk is the showiest steak of them all. For folks that find that a regular bone-in ribeye just isn’t impressive enough and want their steak to come with a handle attached, here’s an extra-long, frenched, Fred Flintstone-specced, bone-in beef hammer. Necessary? Debatable. A flex? Absolutely. If you’re going through the trouble of procuring a showboat steak, we think ", "i": ["1 Tomahawk steak , 2–3 inches thick (about 1.1 kg; 2 1/2 pounds)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "Neutral oil , preferably peanut oil, for frying , as needed", "Rosemary , fresh sprigs, optional , as needed", "Thyme , fresh sprigs, optional , as needed", "Montreal steak seasoning , optional , as needed", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Tomahawk at a glance", "Tomahawk butchery", "Choose your doneness", "Precision cook steak", "Set up cryo-searing station outside", "Prepare liquid nitrogen bath", "Cryo-sear steak", "Fry herbs (optional)", "Carve steak and serve"], "tips": ["Prefer sous vide? Do it!", "See the steak future with a thermometer", "No cryo-searing station? No problem!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cryo-seared-tomahawk-steak"}, {"id": 218, "t": "Ultimate Chop Steak", "c": "Baking", "d": "You don’t have to pay $100 per pound for a steak that eats like Wagyu beef. In fact, you barely have to pay more than $5 per pound—if you’re designing your own. Okay fine, we admit that it’s not true Wagyu beef. Technically, you might find this item on a menu referred to as a “chop steak.” But unlike its often disappointing cousins—the Salisbury steak or cube steak—we’ve developed a resource for c", "i": ["3.2 kg Brisket , ground (total weight)", "48 g Knox gelatin , 1.5% of final grind weight", "32 g Salt , kosher, 1% of final grind weight", "Black pepper , coarsely ground , as needed"], "s": ["Chop steak at a glance", "Brisket breakdown", "Brisket Primal See the beef", "See the beef", "Grind your beef", "Upgrade your beef", "Shape it up", "Let it rest overnight", "Heat sous vide bath", "Cook sous vide", "Rest your steaks", "Get your gear ready", "Don’t have a charcoal grill?", "Seasoning and grilling", "Enjoy!", "Step into our kitchen", "The trials—how we got here", "Grind size", "Salt percentage", "Gelatin", "Lean-to-fat ratios", "Here is what we would eat with these"], "tips": ["Which brisket is best?", "Grading beef", "Adjusting flavor, fat, and tenderness", "Foil ring", "Check out our guide to sous vide burgers"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-grilled-chopsteak"}, {"id": 219, "t": "Ultimate Grilled Chuck Steak", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "So, you’re throwing a dinner party, and you’re stressed. We’ve all been there. You want to impress your guests with an impeccably cooked, flawless feast, the kind of food you dream about for years to come. The menu has been working its way through your mind for weeks—rosy, medium-rare steak atop a silky-smooth purée, flanked by vibrant veggies, and perfectly paired with a bottle of Yakima Valley C", "i": ["1 Beef chuck steak , about 1.4 kg (3 pounds), 1 1/2 to 2 inches (4 to 5 cm) thick", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "30 g Neutral oil", "2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional", "2 Fresh bay leaves , optional", "2 Rosemary , fresh sprigs, optional", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Chuck steak at a glance", "Heat sous vide bath", "Season and bag steak", "Cook steak sous vide", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Finish steak on grill", "Slice and serve", "Complete the meal!"], "tips": ["Cover for long cooks", "No grill? No problem!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-grilled-chuck-steak"}, {"id": 220, "t": "Char-Grilled Steakhouse Butter", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "At steakhouses, you’re often given the option to “enhance” the flavor of your pricey steak with a pat of pricey compound butter. This compound butter asks the question: What if you could pack all the flavor of a char-grilled steak into the butter itself? With beef tallow, bone marrow, and browned ground beef mixed up with the butter, it’s super beefy, with tons of the flavorful compounds produced ", "i": ["227 g Beef tallow , (see “Before we begin” note)", "700 g Beef marrow bones , cut lengthwise (aka canoe cut; see “Before we begin” note)", "112 g Ground beef , 10% fat", "227 g Unsalted butter , room temperature", "35 g Shallot(s) , (1 large shallot) finely chopped", "7 g Bay leaf , fresh (2 leaves)", "10 g Lava salt , finely ground, or kosher salt (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Black pepper , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (1/8 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Liquid smoke , (1/16 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Cook beef tallow base", "Blend beef tallow base", "Char butter with charcoal (optional)", "Chill and whip butter", "Form and chill butter", "Serve or store for later"], "tips": ["Aerating butter", "How to serve compound butter on steak."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/char-grilled-steakhouse-butter"}, {"id": 221, "t": "Five-Star Hotel Butter", "c": "Baking", "d": "Compound butters are a classic add-on at steakhouses and bistros. Slap a pat of herb-and-allium-flecked butter on a steak and watch it melt into a delectable sauce right before your eyes, or slather it on a dinner roll. How could you go wrong? And in the world of compound butters, there’s nothing more classic than maître d’hôtel butter. We love a classic, but you know what we love even more? Impro", "i": ["50 g Parsley , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into 2-inch pieces", "25 g Chives , fresh, cut into 2-inch pieces", "25 g Tarragon , fresh leaves", "35 g Shallot(s) , (1 large shallot) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 medium cloves) minced", "454 g Unsalted butter , softened to 70 °F / 21 °C, cut into 1-inch cubes, divided", "10 g Kosher salt", "5 g Lemon zest , (from 1 lemon) finely grated", "2 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Reimagining compound butter", "Blanch herbs and aromatics", "Chill and whip butter with aromatics", "Form and chill butter", "Serve or store for later"], "tips": ["Aerating butter", "How to serve compound butter on steak."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hotel-butter"}, {"id": 222, "t": "Jalisco-Style Goat Birria", "c": "Baking", "d": "Birria has exploded in popularity here in the States over the past few years and for good reason. Tender, braise-y meat swimming in a rich, spicy, and acidic consomé—what’s not to love? It’s great on its own, in tacos, quesadillas, and even mixed into instant ramen cups. If your local taqueria has recently added quesabirria to their menu, it’s most likely being made with Tijuana-Style Beef Birria,", "i": ["1.7 kg Goat shoulder , bone-in (1 medium shoulder; see “Before we begin” note)", "43 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "3.5 kg Water , divided", "100 g Ancho chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and torn into 1-inch pieces", "52 g Sesame seeds , roasted, divided", "24 g Granulated garlic , divided", "16 g Cumin seeds , ground, divided", "5.5 g Cloves , ground, divided", "5 g Black pepper , freshly ground, divided", "780 g Lard , divided, plus extra as needed", "1 g Mexican oregano , ground (3/4 teaspoon)", "790 g Roma tomato(es) , very ripe", "White onion(s) , cut into small dice, for serving , as needed", "Cilantro , leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving , as needed", "Corn tortillas , warmed, for serving , as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed", "Hot sauce , for serving , as needed", "Salsas , of your choice, for serving , as needed", "1.2 kg Water 100 g Ancho chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and torn into 1-inch pieces", "1.3 kg Water 790 g Roma tomato(es) , very ripe"], "s": ["Birria timeline", "Dry-brine goat overnight", "Steam goat", "Soften dried chiles for mole", "Blend mole", "Cook mole in lard", "Marinate goat in mole", "Simmer tomatoes for consomé", "Steep tomatoes overnight to ferment", "Blend consomé", "Roast goat", "Finish birria and consomé", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": ["Jalisco-style birria “tatemada”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/goat-birria"}, {"id": 223, "t": "How to Build the Ultimate Seafood Tower", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Behold the ultimate seafood tower! Nothing gets us quite as excited as a plateau de fruits de mer: oodles of oysters and clams on the half shell; plump shrimp cocktail; crab and lobster; crudos and conservas; and, if you’re living large, a tin of caviar and a tray of uni for good measure. It’s not just the delicious seafood—it’s the experience. The tower rises high above the table, glittering with", "i": [], "s": ["Elements of a Seafood Tower", "The Tower", "Serving Ware", "Seafood Tower Tier Placement", "The Seafood", "Raw and Shucked", "Marinated and Dressed", "Poached and Chilled", "Condiments and Sauces"], "tips": ["Aguachiles, Ceviches, and Cocteles"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-seafood-tower"}, {"id": 224, "t": "Sous Vide Smoked Mussels", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Smoked mussels are a staple for the tinned-seafood fan, whether they prefer the elegant ones from the Iberian Peninsula, which fall under the larger umbrella of tinned seafood known as “conservas,” or they get down with the ones produced domestically. This recipe is an upgrade on the canned-mussel experience, with perfectly cooked, plump mussels marinated in smoke-scented olive oil. By using sous ", "i": ["1 kg Mussels , fresh, scrubbed and debearded", "200 g Extra-virgin olive oil , plus extra as needed", "5 g Liquid smoke , optional", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Smoked paprika , (1/4 teaspoon), plus extra for finishing, optional", "2 g Lemon zest , finely grated (from 1/2 lemon)"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Blanch and shock mussels", "Shell mussels", "Bag mussels", "Cook mussels sous vide", "Chill mussels", "Decant liquid and pack mussels in oil", "Serve or store"], "tips": ["Cold-smoking mussels", "Why decant and discard the mussel liquid?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-smoked-mussels"}, {"id": 225, "t": "Succulent Sous Vide Shrimp", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Everyone loves shrimp, but nobody likes overcooked shrimp. And boy, are shrimp easy to overcook. Fortunately, sous vide takes all the stress and guesswork out of the process, guaranteeing perfectly succulent and sweet shrimp, with just the right amount of snap, every time. You’ll be slinging shrimp cocktail and whipping up sensational scampi and seafood paella without breaking a sweat. Whether you", "i": ["455 g Shrimp , colossal or jumbo (U10–16), shell-on (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt , (1% of peeled shrimp weight) , as needed", "Granulated sugar , (1% of peeled shrimp weight) , as needed", "15 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "Lemon zest , (from 1 lemon) peeled into strips , as needed", "1 kg Water"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Peel and devein shrimp", "Season and bag shrimp", "Cook shrimp sous vide", "Serve warm or chilled"], "tips": ["Prefer a traditional brine? No problem.", "Sealing shrimp before cooking sous vide"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/succulent-sous-vide-prawns"}, {"id": 226, "t": "Neon Mignonette", "c": "Baking", "d": "A good oyster, with its fresh, briny sweetness and beautiful texture, doesn’t really need anything more than a squeeze of lemon. But if you’re going to dress freshly shucked oysters with a mignonette, the condiment should complement the flavor of the oyster—neither too harshly acidic nor overloaded with extra flavors—and any added textural elements should be pleasing to eat (you don’t want large b", "i": ["150 g Distilled vinegar", "40 g Granulated sugar", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "2 Bay leaf , fresh", "1 g Black peppercorns , whole (1 teaspoon)", "0.5 Red onion(s)"], "s": ["Prepare brine", "Grate and rinse onion", "Steep onion in brine", "Serve"], "tips": ["Grate alliums for a brighter, more flavorful mignonette", "Turn mignonette into granita"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/neon-mignonette"}, {"id": 227, "t": "Shrimp Cocktail", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Like pizza, you can never go wrong with the classic pairing of chilled poached shrimp and sweet-and-spicy cocktail sauce. Even when it’s bad, it’s good. Spend just a little bit of effort on both elements, however, and you’ve got a passed hors d’oeuvre that can outshine even the most extravagant main! Cook the shrimp sous vide for maximum flavor and succulence. Spend a few minutes making cocktail s", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Ice , crushed , as needed 1 recipe Succulent Sous Vide Shrimp , chilled 1 recipe Cocktail Sauce - Lemon wedges , for serving , as needed", "Ice , crushed , as needed 1 recipe Succulent Sous Vide Shrimp , chilled 1 recipe Cocktail Sauce - Lemon wedges , for serving , as needed", "1 recipe Succulent Sous Vide Shrimp , chilled", "1 recipe Cocktail Sauce", "Lemon wedges , for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Plate shrimp on crushed ice", "Serve"], "tips": ["How to make ice that lasts"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/shrimp-cocktail"}, {"id": 228, "t": "Super Citrus Mayo", "c": "Baking", "d": "We packed this mayo with as much citrus as we could: the zest and juice from lemons, limes, and oranges, with an extra hit of malic acid to really get those citrusy notes dancing on your tongue. It’s the perfect accompaniment for all kinds of delicate seafood—shrimp, crab, lobster, mussels, tuna, salmon—as well as vegetables and fries, plus it makes for a great sandwich spread. If you’re looking f", "i": ["2 Lemon(s)", "2 Lime(s)", "1 Orange(s)", "50 g Egg(s) , (1 large egg)", "15 g Egg yolk(s) , (1 large yolk), optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Dijon mustard , optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "450 g Grapeseed oil , or other neutral oil", "10 g Granulated sugar , plus extra as needed", "8 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "1 g Malic acid , (1/4 teaspoon), or citric acid, optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 Lemon(s) 2 Lime(s) 1 Orange(s)", "Citrus zest , finely grated, from Step 1 , as needed", "60 g Citrus juice , from Step 1"], "s": ["Zest and juice citrus", "Blend mayo", "Finish mayo with more citrus juice", "Put mayo to use"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/super-citrus-mayonnaise"}, {"id": 229, "t": "All-Purpose Meyer Lemon Seafood Dressing", "c": "Baking", "d": "This bright and lightly acidic Meyer lemon dressing with pops of floral fennel is an easy level-up condiment that complements all kinds of seafood—raw or cooked, hot or cold. Drizzle it over poached shrimp, Dungeness crab, sliced raw scallops or Salmon Mi-Cuit ... if it came from the sea, this new “yellow goddess” is all you need! save Print Explore other Recipes 32 SEE THE RECIPE Millionaire’s Sh", "i": ["60 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "2 Meyer lemon(s) , scrubbed under warm running water (see “Before we begin” note)", "12 g Granulated sugar", "8 g Kosher salt", "30 g Fennel bulb , cut into 1/16-inch dice", "Fennel fronds , roughly chopped, optional , as needed", "60 g Extra-virgin olive oil 2 Meyer lemon(s) , scrubbed under warm running water (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Zest lemons into oil", "Finish dressing", "Put dressing to use"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/meyer-lemon-seafood-dressing"}, {"id": 230, "t": "Potato Chips", "c": "Other", "d": "Potato chips are delicious—plain and simple. (And if you make them yourself, they’re not really junk food, right?) Whether you like your chips thin and crispy, or you prefer them crunchy “kettle-cooked” style, our chips are sturdy enough to hold up to all sorts of dips. They’re pretty darn good on their own as well. save Print", "i": ["900 g Russet potato(es) , (2 large potatoes; see “Before we begin” note)", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "40 g Kosher salt", "10 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , optional"], "s": ["Wash and slice potatoes", "Dry chips", "Grind salt into a powder", "Fry chips", "Serve or store for later"], "tips": ["Dialing in the perfect thickness for chips", "Soaking chips", "Salt that sticks to chips"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/potato-chips"}, {"id": 231, "t": "Cocktail Sauce", "c": "Sauce", "d": "How do you make a cocktail sauce so good that even the most beautiful, perfectly cooked shrimp becomes nothing more than a vehicle for picking up as much sauce as you can with each dip? Make it all from scratch. We whip up a fresh chile ketchup and spike it with freshly grated horseradish for a cocktail sauce with deeply savory notes and two kinds of heat—the fresh bite of Fresno chiles and the no", "i": ["90 g Fresno chile(s) , (about 8 chiles) stemmed, seeded, and sliced", "65 g Shallot(s) , (1 small shallot) sliced", "160 g Water , divided", "7 g Lemon zest , (from 1 lemon) peeled into strips", "10 g Kosher salt , divided", "65 g Tomato paste", "240 g Distilled vinegar , divided", "80 g Granulated sugar", "160 g Horseradish root , fresh (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon)", "20 g Lime juice , fresh (from 1 lime)", "30 g Dried red chiles , such as guajillo, stemmed and seeded"], "s": ["Soften aromatics", "Finish cooking chile ketchup", "Blend chile ketchup", "Prepare horseradish", "Finish cocktail sauce and put to use"], "tips": ["Can’t find fresh Fresnos? Use dried chiles instead.", "Preparing horseradish for maximum “bite”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cocktail-sauce"}, {"id": 232, "t": "How to Shuck Oysters Four Ways", "c": "Baking", "d": "The reason most people only ever eat oysters at restaurants is they don’t want to shuck ’em at home, which doesn’t make sense to us. We love slurping oysters at restaurants as much as anyone, but we don’t have any problem serving them up at home. But maybe that’s because we know shucking oysters isn’t a big deal—in fact, once you get the hang of it, it’s downright easy. Here are four ways to shuck", "i": [], "s": ["The Classic Shuck", "The Lockpick Shuck", "The Blanch Shuck", "The Cryo Shuck", "Core seafood techniques"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/shucking-oysters-four-ways"}, {"id": 233, "t": "Tips & Tricks: How to Make Ice That Never Melts", "c": "Baking", "d": "Whenever you want to set food on a bed of ice for serving—whether you’re making a showstopping seafood tower or just shucking a dozen oysters—you’re in a race against time. On a warm day, a beautiful mini landscape of craggy ice can transform into a slushy mess in a matter of minutes. By using a combination of dry ice, rock salt, and, optionally, crushed ice, you can make a chilled seafood setup t", "i": [], "s": ["How to Do It", "Why It Works", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Ice, ice, baby!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-keep-ice-from-melting"}, {"id": 234, "t": "Getting to Know the Control Freak Home", "c": "Baking", "d": "Understanding how the Control Freak™ Home works makes it easier to use. We’ve put together a brief visual guide to help you to start cooking with this powerful machine. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Unboxing: Key Components", "How the Control Freak Home Works", "Induction-Compatible Cookware", "Features", "How to Use the Control Freak Home", "How to Use Manual Mode", "How to Use the Timer", "How to Set Heat Intensity", "How to Use the Temperature Probe", "How to Use Probe Alarm", "How to Use Probe Control", "How to Use Ingredient Presets", "How to Use Technique Presets", "How to Make Custom Presets", "How to Lock the Touch Screen", "Start cooking with the Control Freak Home"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/getting-to-know-the-control-freak-home"}, {"id": 235, "t": "Essential Equipment for Induction Cooking", "c": "Other", "d": "Induction cooktops are powerful and energy efficient alternatives to electric or gas cooktops. However, unlike electric or gas cooktops, they require specific cookware to work. To that end, we’ve put together a list of our favorite induction-compatible pans, pots, and accessories that work well with both the Control °Freak and the Control Freak™ Home. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["What Kind of Pans Work on Induction Cooktops?", "What Size Pans Work Best on the Control Freak?", "Skillets and Pans", "Dutch Ovens and Pots", "Saucepans", "Specialty Cookware", "Accessories", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Stock up your kitchen"], "tips": ["How to cook with non-induction cookware on an induction cooktop", "Thicker is better for induction-compatible cookware."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/best-cookware-for-induction-cooktops"}, {"id": 236, "t": "Precision Pork Schnitzel", "c": "Baking", "d": "Good schnitzel is all about the “puff.” Unlike other breaded and fried cutlets, like our updated take on chicken Kyiv, the crust on schnitzel should separate from the cutlet during cooking, which encourages it to become crispier. Since the cutlets are quite thin and the focus on cooking is the crust, they’re easy to overcook. By dialing in the precise temperature of the frying oil (like the chicke", "i": ["2 Pork chop(s) , boneless, 1-inch-thick, 150–170 g (5–6 ounces) each", "8 Egg(s) , large (see “Before we begin” note)", "240 g All-purpose flour", "425 g Breadcrumbs , fine, unseasoned (see “Before we begin” note)", "750 g Clarified butter , homemade or store-bought, for frying (see “Before we begin” note)", "250 g Neutral oil , for frying", "Kosher salt, as needed", "1 Lemon , cut into wedges or 1/4-inch-thick rounds, for serving"], "s": ["Pound pork chops", "Set up breading station", "Heat clarified butter and bread cutlets", "Fry cutlets", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-pork-schnitzel"}, {"id": 237, "t": "Precision Duck Confit", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "It’s hard to beat a well-made duck confit. Rich, fork-tender meat encased in crisp, mahogany-hued skin, it’s in the running for the bistro classic G.O.A.T. race; for our money, it might even rival steak frites. The process for making duck confit is super simple: Lightly cure duck legs with salt; gently cook them in fat until tender; and crisp the skin. Getting these steps just right requires preci", "i": ["4 Duck leg(s) , about 1.1 kg (2 1/2 pounds) total (see “Before we begin” note) - Kosher salt , (1% of duck weight) , as needed 1.6 kg Duck fat , rendered, plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note) - Flake sea salt , for finishing, optional , as needed", "Kosher salt , (1% of duck weight) , as needed", "1.6 kg Duck fat , rendered, plus extra as needed (see “Before we begin” note)", "Flake sea salt , for finishing, optional , as needed", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Coriander seeds , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Star anise , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Cinnamon , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Allspice , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "Spice mix , from Step 5, optional , as needed", "30 g Sherry vinegar", "10 g Dijon mustard", "8 g Shallot(s) , (1/2 small shallot) minced", "1 Orange , finely grated zest, fruit cut into supremes, divided", "3 Frisée , heads, cut into 1-inch pieces", "2 Radicchio , heads, cut into 1-inch pieces", "200 g Cherries , pitted and halved", "60 g Pistachios , roughly chopped", "5 g Chives , thinly sliced"], "s": ["Clean and score duck legs", "Cure duck legs", "Choose your doneness", "Confit duck legs", "Cool duck legs", "Make confit spice mix (optional)", "French duck legs (optional)", "Crisp skin", "Make frisée salad (optional)", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Decanting duck fat, removing glace"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-duck-confit"}, {"id": 238, "t": "Precision Chicken Leg Confit", "c": "Baking", "d": "Everyone knows duck confit. But chicken confit? What’s that? Think of a cross between those super-tender brined and roasted chickens at your favorite members-only grocery store, but with a beautifully crisped skin that’s more reminiscent of fried chicken, with more concentrated chicken flavor. Confit might just be the best way to prepare a chicken leg. And if you dial in the cooking and searing te", "i": ["4 Chicken leg(s) , (about 1.1 kg; 2 1/2 pounds total)", "Kosher salt , (1.25% of chicken weight) , as needed", "1.6 kg Neutral oil , plus extra as needed", "30 g Garlic , (6 medium cloves) whole", "15 g Lemon zest , fresh (from 1 lemon), peeled into large strips", "5 g Rosemary , fresh leaves (1 sprig)", "Flake sea salt , for finishing, optional , as needed", "30 g Aromatic oil , reserved from Step 6, or extra-virgin olive oil", "10 g Garlic confit , (3 to 4 cloves), reserved from Step 4", "40 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon), plus extra as needed", "12 g Dijon mustard", "30 g Red onion(s) , cut into small dice", "40 g Almonds , toasted, roughly chopped", "60 g Castelvetrano olives , pitted, thinly sliced", "100 g Radicchio , (1 small head) cut into 1-inch pieces", "100 g Lacinato kale , (about 5 leaves) stemmed, leaves cut into 1/8-inch strips", "55 g Feta cheese , crumbled, optional"], "s": ["Clean and score", "Cure chicken legs", "Choose your doneness", "Confit chicken legs", "Cool chicken legs", "French chicken legs (optional)", "Crisp skin", "Make salad (optional)", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Zest lemon directly into the mixing bowl."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-chicken-confit"}, {"id": 239, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Pan Searing With Precision", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Pan searing is a fundamental cooking technique that is perfected with practice. Line cooks can turn out steaks, chops, crispy-skinned fish, and chicken breasts cooked to specific serving temperatures all day, because they’ve cooked thousands of them before. Cook 50 steaks a night, and you’ll get pretty good at temping them by touch. But if you’re not working the meat station at a bustling brasseri", "i": [], "s": ["Frequent Flipping", "Pork Chops", "Unilateral Cooking", "Chicken Breast", "Salmon", "Scallops", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Why do I need to pat my steak dry before cooking?", "When should I season steaks, chops, and chicken before searing?", "What’s the best kind of pan for searing?", "Wait, so I shouldn’t always sear over the highest heat possible?", "Can I use butter for searing?"], "tips": ["Resting and carryover cooking", "Using cooking weights for a better sear", "Worried about skin sticking? Use parchment for perfect crispy fish skin.", "“Dry” vs. “wet” scallops"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pan-searing-guide"}, {"id": 240, "t": "Precision Pan-Seared Scallops", "c": "Baking", "d": "There are few things that are as delicious as properly pan-seared scallops. Crispy and browned on the serving side, silky, tender, and luscious within. With the right technique, you can sear scallops like a pro, dialing in the exact texture you want, while achieving an even, beautifully browned sear. The key to searing scallops properly is to cook them mostly on one side, a technique known as unil", "i": ["15 g Neutral oil", "6 Sea scallops , dry, U10, about 285 g (10 ounces) total (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "60 g Unsalted butter , divided", "10 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1/2 lemon)", "15 g Neutral oil 6 Sea scallops , dry, U10, about 285 g (10 ounces) total (see “Before we begin” note) - Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Choose your doneness", "Sear scallops", "Flip scallops and finish cooking off-heat", "Make pan sauce and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-pan-seared-scallops"}, {"id": 241, "t": "Precision Pan-Seared Steak", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "There’s nothing like a perfectly pan-seared steak: a burnished crust giving away to a rosy interior that extends from edge to edge. The challenge pan-searing presents is all the heat is coming from the pan’s surface, instead of being applied evenly (with sous vide) or not-as-evenly (in an oven) through convection. You also have two goals that exist in tension: creating that browned crust, which re", "i": ["15 g Neutral oil", "2 Strip steak(s) , boneless, preferably 1-inch-thick, about 300 g (10 1/2 ounces) each", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "10 g Unsalted butter", "4 Thyme , fresh sprigs", "Flake sea salt , for finishing, optional , as needed", "10 g Unsalted butter 4 Thyme , fresh sprigs"], "s": ["Choose your doneness", "Sear steaks", "Add butter and finish cooking steaks", "Rest, slice, and serve"], "tips": ["Seasoning meat: Cook right away or let sit for at least 45 minutes."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-pan-seared-steak"}, {"id": 242, "t": "Precision Pan-Seared Chicken Breast", "c": "Baking", "d": "The perfect pan-seared chicken breast is tender and juicy on the inside, with an actually crispy golden skin on top. Our method relies on a two-stage cooking process similar to how you would cook duck breast. Start the breasts skin-side down over medium-high heat to render fat and slowly crisp the skin while gently cooking the meat. Once the skin is golden brown and crisp, add a knob of butter, fl", "i": ["30 g Neutral oil", "2 Chicken breast(s) , boneless, skin-on, tenders removed, about 227 g (8 ounces) each", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "10 g Unsalted butter"], "s": ["Choose your doneness", "Sear chicken breasts", "Finish crisping skin with butter", "Flip chicken breasts and finish cooking", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Seasoning meat: Cook right away or let sit for at least 45 minutes."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-pan-seared-chicken-breasts"}, {"id": 243, "t": "Precision Pan-Seared Pork Chops", "c": "Baking", "d": "A nicely seared pork chop, with a deeply browned crust and a rosy and juicy interior with a minimal temperature gradient, is a deceptively simple preparation. Unlike well-marbled steak cuts, pork loin chops are lean, which means they’re easy to overcook, especially with a high-heat method like searing. The challenge searing presents is you’re juggling two goals with only one source of direct heat:", "i": ["2 Pork chop(s) , boneless, 1-inch-thick", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "20 g Neutral oil", "20 g Unsalted butter", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) thinly sliced", "5 g Rosemary , fresh leaves (1 sprig)", "Flake sea salt , for finishing, optional , as needed", "Dijon mustard , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Season pork chops", "Sear pork chops", "Choose your doneness", "Finish cooking pork chops", "Rest and serve"], "tips": ["Seasoning meat: Cook right away or let sit for at least 45 minutes.", "Give pork chops a mid-cook rest."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-pan-seared-pork-chops"}, {"id": 244, "t": "Precision Pan-Seared Salmon", "c": "Baking", "d": "You don’t need to head to a fancy restaurant to enjoy perfectly seared salmon with ultra-crispy skin. With proper technique, you can sear salmon fillets like a pro from the comfort of your own kitchen. The key to achieving crispy skin and perfectly silky fish is managing the temperature of your pan. For skin-on salmon, we use unilateral cooking to sear—cooking the fillets most of the way on medium", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 2 Salmon fillet(s) , skin-on, preferably 1 1/4-inches-thick, 170–225 g (6–8 ounces) each - Kosher salt , (1% of the weight of the fish) , as needed - Sugar , (0.25% of the weight of the fish), optional , as needed 2 g Neutral oil , (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 Salmon fillet(s) , skin-on, preferably 1 1/4-inches-thick, 170–225 g (6–8 ounces) each - Kosher salt , (1% of the weight of the fish) , as needed - Sugar , (0.25% of the weight of the fish), optional , as needed 2 g Neutral oil , (1/2 teaspoon)", "Kosher salt , (1% of the weight of the fish) , as needed", "Sugar , (0.25% of the weight of the fish), optional , as needed", "2 g Neutral oil , (1/2 teaspoon)"], "s": ["See Grant sear salmon", "Score salmon skin (optional)", "Dry-brine salmon fillets (optional)", "Choose your doneness", "Sear salmon on skin-side", "Flip and finish cooking salmon", "Rest and serve"], "tips": ["Dry-brining fish to reduce moisture content", "Worried about skin sticking? Use parchment for perfect crispy fish skin."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pan-seared-salmon"}, {"id": 245, "t": "Precision Cantonese-Style Sizzling Steamed Fish", "c": "Baking", "d": "If there’s one dish that captures the spirit and finesse of Cantonese cooking, it’s whole steamed sizzling fish: a whole fish steamed with aromatics, topped with julienned green onion, anointed with smoking hot oil, then doused in a slightly sweetened soy sauce. It’s a simple but dramatic preparation, but it’s tricky to get just right. The sauce is minimalist, ditto the aromatics, so there’s not a", "i": ["1 White fish , whole, scaled and gutted (680–900 g; 1 1/2–2 pounds); or fillets (340–455 g; 12–16 ounces total weight); (see “Before we begin” note)", "40 g Fresh ginger root , (3-inch piece) unpeeled, cut into 1/4-inch-thick slices", "150 g Shaoxing wine", "50 g Chicken stock , homemade or low sodium store-bought stock", "40 g Light Chinese soy sauce", "10 g Rock sugar , crushed into a coarse powder (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Toasted sesame oil , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1/4 teaspoon; see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g White pepper , ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "56 g Neutral oil", "Cilantro , fresh sprigs, for serving, optional , as needed", "Jasmine rice , cooked, for serving , as needed", "20 g Large Chinese scallion(s) , or regular scallions, white parts only; cut into 3-inch pieces and lightly smashed (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Prep fish", "Set up steamer", "Dial in time and temperature for any fish with precision", "Steam fish", "Mix seasoned soy sauce", "Sizzle fish", "Heat sauce and serve"], "tips": ["Cooking a fillet instead of a whole fish? No problem!", "A safer, more user-friendly steamer setup", "Not all steam is created equal. Reduce cook time if using a regular stovetop.", "For fillets, sizzle the flesh side."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-cantonese-style-sizzling-steamed-fish"}, {"id": 246, "t": "Precision Boeuf Bourguignon", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Ever since Julia Child burst onto the food scene, Americans have been in love with boeuf bourguignon—beef braised in red wine. As she notes in the inaugural episode of The French Chef, the dish offers a crash course in French culinary technique: How to brown and braise meat, how to sauté mushrooms, how to cook vegetables, and how to make a “wonderful” sauce. For the same reason, beef bourguignon i", "i": ["750 g Red wine , (1 bottle)", "90 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided", "150 g Cipollini onions , (about 8 onions) peeled and trimmed", "150 g Carrot(s) , (1 large carrot) peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces", "150 g Cremini mushrooms , cleaned and halved", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) crushed", "30 g Tomato paste", "450 g Beef chuck , cut into 2- by 1-inch-thick pieces", "3 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon) plus extra as needed", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "45 g All-purpose flour", "1 kg Water", "100 g Ultimate Beef Bouillon Cubes , (3 cubes)", "200 g New potatoes , whole, scrubbed", "2 g Rosemary , (1 sprig) fresh leaves, finely chopped", "1 g Thyme , (4 sprigs) fresh leaves, finely chopped", "28 g Flat-leaf parsley , (1 bunch) fresh leaves, roughly chopped, optional"], "s": ["Reduce red wine", "Brown vegetables", "Sear beef", "Make braising liquid", "Choose your doneness", "Start braise, covered", "Finish braise, uncovered", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-beef-bourguignon"}, {"id": 247, "t": "Precision Butter-Poached Lobster", "c": "Baking", "d": "Steamed lobster is a New England summer classic that more often than not turns out rubbery and tough. But there’s a much better way to cook lobster and all that’s required is precision temperature control. In a lot of fine dining restaurants, instead of getting dunked whole into a steamer or pot, lobster is carefully taken apart and its disparate pieces are par-blanched and shocked in ice water to", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 Lobster , whole, live (680–795 g; 1 1/2–1 3/4 pounds); or 2 shell-on lobster tails, thawed (140–170 g; 5–6 ounces each); (see “Before we begin” note) - Kosher salt, as needed 1.5 recipes Bulletproof Beurre Monté", "1 Lobster , whole, live (680–795 g; 1 1/2–1 3/4 pounds); or 2 shell-on lobster tails, thawed (140–170 g; 5–6 ounces each); (see “Before we begin” note) - Kosher salt, as needed 1.5 recipes Bulletproof Beurre Monté", "Kosher salt, as needed", "1.5 recipes Bulletproof Beurre Monté"], "s": ["Break down lobster and chill (optional)", "Prepare lobster for blanching", "Blanch lobster", "Shell lobster", "Choose your doneness", "Poach lobster in beurre monté", "1.5 recipes", "Reduce beurre monté", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["How to prevent the lobster tail curl"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-butter-poached-lobster"}, {"id": 248, "t": "Bulletproof Beurre Monté", "c": "Baking", "d": "Beurre monté—a warm butter emulsion—is a secret weapon in French kitchens. It’s a cooking medium, a welcome addition to almost any dish, and a sauce in its own right. The tricky bit about beurre monté—and the reason why its use is largely confined to professional kitchens—is that it needs to be kept warm. Too hot and the emulsion will break and the milk solids and butterfat will separate from the ", "i": ["227 g Unsalted butter , divided", "20 g Shallot(s) , (1/2 small shallot) thinly sliced", "2 g Garlic clove(s) , (1/2 clove) thinly sliced", "500 g Water", "5 g Kosher salt", "1 g Xanthan gum", "2 g Garlic , (1/2 clove) thinly sliced"], "s": ["Sweat aromatics", "Simmer butter and water", "Blend beurre monté", "Put beurre monté to use"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bulletproof-beurre-monte"}, {"id": 249, "t": "Precision Hollandaise", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Hollandaise is one of the most temperamental of all French sauces. Many cooks have tried to make hollandaise—tried and failed, cursing the heavens as they stare at a bunch of greasy scrambled eggs instead of creamy, hot mayonnaise. Over the years, we’ve come up with different methods to get from raw eggs, acid, and butter to a beautiful hollandaise—using a blender, using sous vide, and even a whip", "i": ["35 g Egg yolk(s) , (2 large yolks)", "20 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1/2 lemon; see “Before we begin” note)", "227 g Unsalted butter , softened to 70 °F / 21 °C, ​cut into 1 1/2-inch pieces", "20 g Water , plus extra as needed for reheating", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "0.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/4 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Whisk together and cook hollandaise", "Finish and keep hollandaise warm", "Serve, or reheat and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-hollandaise"}, {"id": 250, "t": "Mushroom Turnovers", "c": "Baking", "d": "These savory mushroom turnovers might just be the best pastry snacks, since they sound delicious at any time of day, from breakfast through to midnight snack—with midmornings, afternoons, and cocktail hours in between. These flaky, crispy pastries boast a rich and herby roasted mushroom and cream cheese filling that pairs just as well with a coffee or tea as it does a glass of wine. While making t", "i": ["500 g Mushrooms , fresh, cleaned, stemmed, and cut into 1/2-inch-thick pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "15 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "10 g Rosemary , fresh sprigs (2 sprigs)", "4 g Thyme , fresh sprigs (4 sprigs)", "225 g Cream cheese", "30 g Tender herbs , fresh, such as parsley or chives", "6 g Sherry vinegar", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon) plus extra as needed", "3 g Lemon zest , finely grated (from 1 lemon)", "3 g Creole Spice Blend , (1 teaspoon), optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "All-purpose flour , for dusting , as needed", "1 recipe Puff Pastry (Pâte Feuilletée) , (two 16- by 12-inch sheets) fully chilled, homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "50 g Water", "50 g Egg(s)"], "s": ["Roast mushrooms", "Make filling", "Portion puff pastry", "Assemble turnovers", "Bake turnovers", "Cool and enjoy"], "tips": ["Cutting puff pastry", "Get fancy with a scalloped edge", "Topping turnovers"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/mushroom-turnovers"}, {"id": 251, "t": "Ultimate Chocolate Babka", "c": "Baking", "d": "Layers of plush and buttery yeasted bread and slightly bitter dark chocolate, sweetened with syrup, twisted up and baked in a Bundt pan ... that’s right, it’s our take on chocolate babka! Babka comes in many forms—sweet, savory, and everything in between. The main pitfall of chocolate babka in particular is it can bake up a little dry. We solve for that by intentionally underbaking the bread. Star", "i": ["40 g Whole milk", "8 g Instant dry yeast", "60 g Egg(s) , whole (from 1 to 2 large eggs)", "40 g Egg yolk(s) , (from 3 large yolks)", "300 g Bread flour , unbleached, divided", "280 g Granulated sugar , divided", "9 g Kosher salt , divided", "140 g Unsalted butter , softened to 70 °F / 21 °C, divided", "250 g Water , plus extra as needed for sealing dough and spraying before baking", "100 g Cocoa powder", "35 g Grapeseed oil , or other neutral oil", "40 g Brown sugar", "50 g Dark chocolate , (60–80%) finely chopped (no larger than 1/4-inch pieces)"], "s": ["Mix dough", "Make syrup", "Make chocolate filling", "Make streusel", "Sheet, fill, and roll dough", "Shape and proof babka", "Bake babka", "Add syrup and cool", "Unmold and serve"], "tips": ["For cleaner edges, chill dough before cutting", "Underproofed? Underbaked? Don’t sweat it.", "Want babka stat? Use a fan to cool it down.", "Need help unmolding? Use a torch."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-chocolate-babka"}, {"id": 252, "t": "Cinnamon Babka", "c": "Baking", "d": "Think of the best cinnamon roll you’ve ever had. Got it? Now imagine the best coffee cake ever. Great. Now dial up the cinnamon flavor, make it more buttery, add in pecans and a heavy dose of caramel, and picture it coiled into a Bundt pan. There you have it: the best cinnamon babka. There are all kinds of babka—sweet, savory, and in any flavor combination you can imagine. This babka leans into th", "i": ["40 g Whole milk", "8 g Instant dry yeast", "60 g Egg(s) , whole (from 1 to 2 large eggs)", "40 g Egg yolk(s) , (from 3 large yolks)", "330 g Bread flour , unbleached, divided", "120 g Granulated sugar , divided", "9 g Kosher salt , divided", "140 g Unsalted butter , softened to 70 °F / 21 °C, divided", "115 g Water , divided, plus extra as needed for sealing dough and spraying before baking", "240 g Brown sugar , divided", "80 g Pecans", "35 g Grapeseed oil , or other neutral oil", "12 g Cinnamon , ground", "3 g Orange zest , finely grated (from 1 orange)"], "s": ["Mix dough", "Make syrup", "Make filling", "Make streusel", "Sheet, fill, and roll dough", "Shape and proof babka", "Bake babka", "Add syrup and cool", "Unmold and serve"], "tips": ["For cleaner edges, chill dough before cutting", "Underproofed? Underbaked? Don’t sweat it.", "Want babka stat? Use a fan to cool it down.", "Need help unmolding? Use a torch."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cinnamon-babka"}, {"id": 253, "t": "How to Butcher a Chicken: 10-Piece Country Cut", "c": "Baking", "d": "There are countless ways to break down poultry, depending on the culinary tradition you’re working in and/or the way you plan to use the various parts. For example, breaking down a bird yakitori-style requires a different approach than breaking down a chicken for Chili Fried Chicken. This method for breaking down a chicken yields 10 bone-in pieces—two drumsticks, two thighs, two wings, and four br", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 Chicken , preferably air-chilled", "1 Chicken , preferably air-chilled"], "s": ["Cut between breasts and legs and pop out thigh bones", "Remove legs", "Remove back", "Remove wings", "Split breast", "Split breast halves on “40-yard line”", "Split legs into thighs and drumsticks", "Get cooking!"], "tips": ["Consider the oyster"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/10-piece-country-cut-chicken-break-down"}, {"id": 254, "t": "Crispy Sous Vide Chicken Thighs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "If you are old enough to remember a world without the internet, you may also have enjoyed a childhood in which the chicken nuggets at a certain ubiquitous fast-food chain were consumed largely without question. Remember those golden bird bites—crispy on the outside, tender on the inside, magnificent when doused with spicy mustard sauce? If you did not grow up on the nug, fear not. We’re going to h", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 4 Chicken thighs , bone-in, skin-on - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed 30 g Neutral oil , divided 4 Thyme , fresh sprigs, divided, optional 2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, divided, optional", "4 Chicken thighs , bone-in, skin-on - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed 30 g Neutral oil , divided 4 Thyme , fresh sprigs, divided, optional 2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, divided, optional", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "30 g Neutral oil , divided", "4 Thyme , fresh sprigs, divided, optional", "2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, divided, optional"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Cut out bones", "Pound thighs to even thickness", "Season and bag thighs", "Cook chicken thighs sous vide", "Sear thighs to crisp skin", "Plate and serve!", "Pick your plate!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crispy-chicken-thighs-made-simple-with-sous-vide"}, {"id": 255, "t": "Pâté en Croûte", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pâté en croûte is the pinnacle of charcuterie. Endlessly variable and brutally difficult to prepare well, it’s a test of a cook’s ingenuity, skill, and creativity. Few preparations involve as many intertwined elements and processes, every one of which can go drastically wrong, and every wrong move often means ruining the entire preparation. The pâté en croûte maker is part butcher, part pastry che", "i": ["100 g Prunes , pitted", "40 g Calvados", "40 g Crème de mûre , or crème de cassis", "300 g Pork fatback , fresh, cut into 1/2-inch dice", "1.1 kg Pork shoulder , cut into 1-inch pieces, chilled, divided", "500 g Pork liver , cut into 1-inch pieces", "54 g Kosher salt , divided", "3.2 g Prague powder #1", "82 g Garlic , (17 cloves) minced, divided", "10 g Thyme , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "22 g Black pepper , freshly ground, divided", "14 g White pepper , ground", "7 g Red pepper flakes", "2 g Mace , ground", "2 g Allspice , ground", "200 g Pork belly , skinless, cut into 1/2-inch dice", "100 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs) divided", "70 g Pistachios , shelled", "160 g Pig’s blood", "30 g Breadcrumbs", "74 g Heavy cream , divided", "14 g Shallot(s) , (1 small shallot) minced", "800 g All-purpose flour , plus extra for dusting", "445 g Unsalted butter , room temperature, divided", "90 g Beef tallow , room temperature", "176 g Egg yolk(s) , (11 to 12 large yolks) divided", "94 g Cornstarch", "215 g Water , cold, divided, plus extra as needed", "45 g Activated charcoal powder , food grade", "85 g Egg white(s)", "85 g Bread flour", "100 g Foie gras , cut into 2-inch pieces and frozen", "1 l Aspic , or gelatin-enriched beef stock (see “Before we begin” note and tip)", "68 g Garlic clove(s) , (14 large cloves) minced (4.3% of total weight of pork meat)"], "s": ["Pâté en croûte timeline", "Soak prunes", "Blanch fatback", "Grind pork for farce and boudin noir", "Season ground pork for farce and grind again", "Finish and chill farce", "Make boudin noir base (optional)", "Make pastry dough", "Make tuile paste (optional)", "Roll out and cut pastry dough", "Apply tuile paste to dough", "Make egg wash, two ways", "Assemble pâté", "Bake pâté", "Cool pâté and add aspic", "Final aspic addition", "Unmold pâté", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["The elements of pâté en croûte", "How to hack aspic or make it the hard way", "Keep it all ice-cold", "Two kinds of egg wash for the perfect crust", "How to fix a pâté with air gaps"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pate-en-croute"}, {"id": 256, "t": "Precision Italian Beef", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Italian beef? Yes, chef! Ever since The Bear came out, everyone’s been running around calling each other chef, and everyone and their cousin have been asking us to put out an Italian beef sandwich recipe. Remember when Carmy had to use all his fine-dining cheffy skills to transform the wrong cut of beef into even-more-excellent Italian beef than the shop usually served? Yeah, we did that. Carmy ju", "i": ["15 g Kosher salt , divided", "10 g Black peppercorns , whole", "6 g Fennel seeds", "5 g Coriander seeds , whole (1 tablespoon)", "5 g Paprika , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "3 g Thyme , dried (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Oregano , dried (1 tablespoon)", "2 g Red pepper flakes , (1 teaspoon)", "1.8 kg Beef short ribs , trimmed of excess fat (4 pounds)", "30 g Neutral oil", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 large cloves)", "140 g Ultimate Beef Bouillon Cubes , (4 cubes)", "Italian Sandwich Rolls , homemade or store-bought , as needed", "0.5 recipe Hot Giardiniera , homemade or store-bought, roughly chopped, optional", "1 recipe Roasted Sweet Pepper Giardiniera , homemade or store-bought, roughly chopped, optional"], "s": ["Blend spice mixture", "Sear short ribs", "Cook short ribs", "Chill short ribs", "Reduce and strain gravy", "Slice chilled short ribs", "Warm sliced beef in gravy", "Assemble sandwiches and enjoy", "0.5 recipe"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-italian-beef"}, {"id": 257, "t": "Italian Sandwich Rolls", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’re going to make a proper Italian beef sandwich, you need the right roll. A roll that’s soft and squishy with a tight, even crumb that can stand up easily to a generous splash of gravy or a full dip. A roll with a tender crust that doesn’t shatter into a million little shards like a hoagie roll or a bánh mì. This is it. Using a relatively short proof time helps with that soft crumb, but it ", "i": ["300 g Water , 110 °F / 43 °C", "20 g Sugar", "6 g Instant dry yeast", "3 g Diastatic malt powder , (1 teaspoon), optional", "500 g Bread flour , unbleached, plus extra for dusting", "6 g Kosher salt", "45 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "Fine cornmeal, as needed"], "s": ["Dissolve yeast", "Mix dry ingredients", "Knead dough", "Bulk proof", "Portion dough", "Shape dough into logs", "Shape rolls and final proof", "Score rolls", "Bake and cool rolls"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/italian-sandwich-rolls"}, {"id": 258, "t": "Roasted Sweet Pepper Giardiniera", "c": "Baking", "d": "When you order an Italian beef sandwich, you can get it hot, sweet, or both. Getting it hot means you want it with hot giardiniera, the pickled mixed vegetables condiment used in so many iconic Chicago foods, including tavern-style pizza. Sweet means you want some sweet peppers—roasted until meltingly soft then skinned and seeded—to take the edge of the salty, juicy beef. For our Italian beef sand", "i": ["200 g Red bell pepper(s) , (1 large pepper) stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1/2-inch-thick strips", "200 g Yellow bell pepper , (1 large pepper) stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1/2-inch-thick strips", "200 g Green bell pepper , (1 large pepper) stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1/2-inch-thick strips", "350 g Sweet onion(s) , (1 large onion) sliced into 1/2-inch-thick pieces", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "50 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "30 g Garlic clove(s) , (6 medium cloves) roughly chopped", "50 g Apple cider vinegar", "1.4 g Oregano , dried (2 teaspoons)", "0.8 g Red pepper flakes , (1 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Season peppers and onions", "Roast garlic", "Roast peppers", "Marinate vegetables", "Serve and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/roasted-sweet-pepper-giardiniera"}, {"id": 259, "t": "Dirty Fried Rice", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Dirty rice is an iconic Creole dish of seasoned rice mixed with chopped up, cooked down offal, often chicken livers and giblets. The “dirty” in the name refers to the speckled brown coloring the rice takes on once the livers and giblets have been mixed in. Deeply savory, with a pronounced minerality from the liver and other offal, it’s one of the all-time great side dishes. Fried rice is an iconic", "i": ["350 g Jasmine rice", "250 g Chicken liver , rinsed and patted dry", "30 g Neutral oil , such as canola or grapeseed oil, divided", "90 g White onion(s) , (1/2 small onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "45 g Green bell pepper , (1/2 pepper) stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1/4-inch dice", "45 g Celery , (1 rib) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoons), plus extra as needed", "2 g White pepper , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (1/4 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "30 g Unsalted butter , cut into 1/2-inch cubes"], "s": ["Cook and cool rice", "Fluff rice", "Purée chicken livers", "Cook and “scrape” chicken livers", "Fry rice"], "tips": ["No rice cooker? No problem!", "Wok cooking happens fast. Get fully set up before you start.", "No wok? No problem! Cook livers in a cast iron skillet.", "No wok? No problem! Cook fried rice in a cast iron skillet."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dirty-fried-rice"}, {"id": 260, "t": "Cheddar-Tasso Hush Puppies With Apple Honey", "c": "Baking", "d": "Break out your cornballer, folks, because it’s time to fry some cornballs! Hush puppies are basically fried cornbread nuggets. Packed with cubes of smoky tasso ham, cheddar, and sliced scallions, these nuggets are crispy, light, salty, tangy, and slightly sweet from the corn—the perfect side dish. Our batter uses a mix of cornmeal and all-purpose flour, enriched with buttermilk and eggs and leaven", "i": ["1 kg Apple cider , unpasteurized, freshly pressed (1 liter; see “Before we begin” note)", "795 g Sugar , divided", "15 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon)", "230 g Cornmeal", "180 g All-purpose flour", "8 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "5 g Baking powder , (3/4 teaspoon)", "5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (2 teaspoons)", "200 g Buttermilk", "150 g Egg(s) , (3 large eggs)", "120 g Tasso ham , cut into 1/4-inch dice (see “Before we begin” note)", "120 g Cheddar , shredded", "50 g Scallion(s) , (4 scallions) thinly sliced", "Neutral oil , such as canola or grapeseed oil, for deep-frying , as needed"], "s": ["Make apple honey", "Mix dry ingredients", "Mix wet ingredients", "Finish hush puppy batter", "Fry hush puppies", "Drizzle hush puppies with apple honey and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cheddar-tasso-ham-hush-puppies-with-apple-honey"}, {"id": 261, "t": "The Choose-Your-Own-Adventure Muffin", "c": "Baking", "d": "We’ve been hard at work producing a series of recipes for the ultimate versions of standard muffin flavors: blueberry, lemon-poppy seed, corn, double-chocolate, banana-nut. Each one treats muffins like the little cakes they are, and we spared no effort in making those cakes as delicious as they can be. However, we realize that most people just want to throw muffins together as quickly as possible.", "i": ["260 g All-purpose flour", "150 g Granulated sugar", "50 g Brown sugar", "6 g Baking soda , (1 teaspoon)", "6 g Baking powder , (1 teaspoon)", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "350 g Sour cream", "100 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs)", "18 g Vanilla extract , (1 tablespoon)", "80 g Unsalted butter", "10 g Nonfat dry milk powder , optional", "Mix-ins , (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed"], "s": ["Before we begin: Choose your muffin adventure", "Sift dry ingredients", "Mix wet ingredients", "Finish batter and let rest", "Portion muffins", "Bake muffins", "Enjoy!"], "tips": ["Over the top", "Brown butter and toast milk solids", "Portion by volume", "All-purpose glaze?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/master-muffin-recipe"}, {"id": 262, "t": "Ultimate Double-Chocolate Muffins", "c": "Baking", "d": "Who wants chocolate cake for breakfast? Maybe the better question is: Who doesn’t want chocolate cake for breakfast? With a super-tender crumb, cocoa powder and dark chocolate chunks in the batter, and a chocolate glaze on top, these rich muffins blur the line between muffins and cakes more than any other muffin recipe. Add in a layer of streusel in the middle and on top, with the option of spikin", "i": ["140 g Unsalted butter , softened to 70 °F / 21 °C, divided", "80 g Brown sugar , divided", "380 g All-purpose flour , divided", "6 g Kosher salt , divided", "150 g Granulated sugar", "20 g Cocoa powder", "6 g Baking soda", "6 g Baking powder", "350 g Sour cream", "100 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs)", "18 g Vanilla extract", "10 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "480 g 70% dark chocolate , such as Valrhona, coarsely chopped, divided", "35 g Whole milk"], "s": ["Make streusel dough", "Sift dry ingredients", "Prepare wet ingredients", "Brown butter and temper wet ingredients", "Finish batter and let rest", "Portion muffins", "Bake muffins", "Make glaze (optional)", "Glaze muffins and serve"], "tips": ["More than one way to streusel", "Skip the browned butter, if you like", "Portion by volume"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/double-chocolate-muffins"}, {"id": 263, "t": "Ultimate Banana-Nut Muffins", "c": "Baking", "d": "Banana-nut muffins are S-tier muffins. They're one of the tried-and-true flavor combos that most anyone would welcome at breakfast, so good that even when the muffin itself is kind of dry or bland, you’re still pretty happy. If they've got got nuts and bananas, they're fine. But we wanted an “ultimate” banana-nut muffin! And while we basically took the same tack as with our Ultimate Blueberry Muff", "i": ["600 g Banana(s) , (4–5 bananas) whole, peeled", "130 g Orange juice , fresh (from 3 large oranges), divided", "5 g Orange zest , finely grated (from 1 large orange)", "0.25 g Malic acid , (1/8 teaspoon), optional", "240 g All-purpose flour", "16 g Freeze-dried banana powder , divided", "4.5 g Baking powder , (3/4 teaspoon)", "4.5 g Baking soda , (3/4 teaspoon)", "3 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon)", "168 g Pecans , finely chopped, divided", "85 g Unsalted butter , softened to 70 °F / 21 °C", "170 g Granulated sugar", "60 g Brown sugar", "9 g Banana extract", "9 g Vanilla extract", "2 Egg(s) , large, in shell"], "s": ["Prepare bananas", "Sift dry ingredients", "Cream butter and sugar", "Mix eggs into batter", "Finish batter and let rest", "Portion muffins", "Bake muffins", "Make glaze (optional)", "Glaze muffins and serve"], "tips": ["Portion by volume"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-banana-nut-muffin"}, {"id": 264, "t": "Ultimate Blueberry Muffins", "c": "Baking", "d": "We’ve got problems with most blueberry muffins. Sure, you get to eat cake for breakfast, and you get to feel good about it because it’s got fruit in it. But if you’re going to eat cake for breakfast, you might as well be eating the best freaking blueberry cake. Don’t settle for mediocre continental breakfast buffet muffins! Let us introduce you to our ultimate blueberry muffin. Just like our super", "i": ["173 g Unsalted butter , softened to 70 °F / 21 °C, divided", "30 g Brown sugar", "400 g All-purpose flour , divided", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon) divided", "400 g Blueberries , fresh or frozen (thawed if using frozen) (see “Before we begin” note)", "25 g Freeze-dried blueberry powder , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "1.5 g Malic acid , (1/4 teaspoon)", "10 g Baking powder", "30 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "225 g Granulated sugar", "12 g Vanilla extract", "6 g Blueberry extract", "100 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs) in shell", "130 g Buttermilk", "10 g Lemon zest , finely grated, from 2 lemons", "40 g Lemon juice , fresh, from 2 lemons"], "s": ["Make streusel dough", "Muddle and mix berries", "Sift dry ingredients", "Cream fat and sugar", "Temper eggs and buttermilk", "Mix eggs into batter", "Finish batter and let rest", "Portion muffins", "Bake muffins", "Make glaze (optional)", "Glaze muffins and serve"], "tips": ["Tempering butter, eggs, buttermilk on the stovetop"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-blueberry-muffins"}, {"id": 265, "t": "Ultimate Lemon-Poppy Seed Muffins", "c": "Baking", "d": "Blueberry muffins, corn muffins ... doesn’t matter what kind of muffin you’re making, the name of the game when making the ultimate version of these muffins is dialing up their flavors without compromising the texture of what are basically cakes. Like corn muffins, lemon-poppy seed muffins run up against a textural obstacle. You want to pack the muffin batter with lemon flavor, which is relatively", "i": ["150 g Poppy seeds", "150 g Water", "320 g All-purpose flour", "6 g Baking powder", "6 g Baking soda", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "130 g Unsalted butter , softened to 70 °F / 21 °C", "200 g Sugar", "100 g Brown sugar", "35 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "12 g Lemon extract", "12 g Vanilla extract", "150 g Egg(s) , (3 large eggs) in shell", "180 g Yogurt , plain, whole milk", "65 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 2 lemons), divided", "20 g Lemon zest , finely grated (from 6 lemons)", "0.5 g Malic acid , (1/8 teaspoon) optional"], "s": ["Soak poppy seeds", "Sift dry ingredients", "Cream fat and sugar", "Temper eggs and mix into batter", "Blend seeds and yogurt", "Finish batter and let rest", "Portion muffins", "Bake muffins", "Make glaze (optional)", "Glaze muffins and serve"], "tips": ["Muffin pan prep"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/lemon-poppy-seed-muffins"}, {"id": 266, "t": "Ultimate Corn Muffins", "c": "Baking", "d": "The key to the best corn muffins is treating them like sweet and delicious corn cakes, not sweeter, mini-portions of cornbread, and then figuring out how to amplify the corn flavor without making a batter that bakes up leaden and dry. We use both cornmeal and corn kernels to double up on corn flavor, but there comes a point at which jamming more corn into the recipe has an adverse effect on the te", "i": ["180 g Unsalted butter", "300 g Corn kernels , fresh (from about 2 ears of corn) or frozen (thawed)", "1 Vanilla bean , cut into 5 pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "100 g Cornmeal , (see “Before we begin” note)", "220 g Sugar , divided", "180 g Cake flour", "8 g Kosher salt", "6 g Baking powder", "5 g Baking soda , (3/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Cayenne pepper , (1/8 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Malic acid , (1/8 teaspoon) optional", "250 g Yogurt , plain, whole milk", "65 g Maple syrup", "30 g Egg yolk(s) , (2 large yolks)", "60 g Egg white(s) , (from 2 large eggs)"], "s": ["Blacken butter and cook corn", "Blend cornmeal", "Sift dry mixture", "Blend wet mixture", "Whip meringue", "Mix and rest muffin batter", "Portion muffins", "Bake muffins", "Cool and enjoy"], "tips": ["Level up your corn muffins!", "Whipping egg whites by hand", "Muffin pan prep"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-corn-muffins"}, {"id": 267, "t": "Christmas Pudding", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Christmas pudding is a classic holiday dessert with medieval roots that serves as a great introduction to the wild world of British cuisine. It’s a pudding but not a custard. It’s a dessert, packed with beef fat. It’s (sort of) a cake that’s steamed, not baked. If you’re going full medieval, you make it a year in advance, wrap it in a pillowcase, and hang it over the fireplace until next Christmas", "i": ["175 g Sultanas , or golden raisins (see “Before we begin” note)", "75 g Dried figs , roughly chopped", "62 g Candied orange peel , or other candied citrus peel, cut into 1/4-inch dice (see “Before we begin” note)", "38 g Dried cherries , halved", "160 g Brandy , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "Unsalted butter , melted, for greasing pudding mold , as needed", "175 g Brown sugar", "150 g Egg(s) , (3 large eggs) beaten", "125 g Quince , (1 quince), or apple, coarsely grated on largest holes of a box grater", "125 g Beef suet , chilled, coarsely ground or grated on largest holes of a box grater (see “Before we begin” note)", "125 g Breadcrumbs , unseasoned (see “Before we begin” note)", "88 g Self-rising flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Orange zest , finely grated (from 1 orange)", "38 g Orange juice , fresh (from 1 orange)", "10 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "5 g Baking powder , (1 teaspoon)", "3 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Allspice , ground (3/4 teaspoon)", "1 g Cinnamon , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "150 g Heavy cream , for serving", "35 g Powdered sugar"], "s": ["Soak dried fruit", "Mix pudding base", "Fill and wrap pudding mold", "Steam pudding", "Unmold pudding", "Sweeten cream", "Set pudding on fire and serve"], "tips": ["Short on stovetop space? Making multiple puddings? Use the oven."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/christmas-pudding"}, {"id": 268, "t": "Ultimate Roast Porchetta", "c": "Baking", "d": "Real-deal porchetta is a beautiful thing: A whole, boned-out pig, seasoned with fennel and garlic, roasted until the skin is crispy and glassy and the meat is meltingly tender and juicy. Chop it all up for a delicious mix of lean and fatty meat with shards of crunchy skin, stuff it into a sandwich, and you’ve got one of the most iconic Italian street foods. Making it is obviously a chore—like whol", "i": ["3.6 kg Boneless pork middle , skin-on belly with loin attached (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt , (1.6% of pork weight, after trimming) , as needed", "16 g Fennel seeds , whole, divided", "15 g Black pepper , freshly ground", "4 g Red pepper flakes", "20 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 large cloves) minced into a purée", "175 g Flat-leaf parsley , (2 bunches) leaves and tender stems, roughly chopped", "60 g Basil , (1 bunch) fresh leaves, roughly chopped", "15 g Rosemary , (2 bunches) fresh leaves, roughly chopped", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon or fleur de sel , as needed"], "s": ["Choose your porchetta fighter", "Bonus butchery: How to break down a pig", "Air-dry pork belly (optional)", "Remove and butterfly loin", "Trim belly", "Score skin", "Make seasoning mixture", "Season, roll, and tie porchetta", "Roast at high heat to crisp skin", "Reduce heat and finish roasting", "Rest and carve porchetta"], "tips": ["Score skin diagonally in order to truss porchetta vertically", "Mastering the butcher’s knot with a master butcher", "Two-stage cooking for three pork textures in one roast", "A better carving station setup"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-roast-porchetta"}, {"id": 269, "t": "Easy Sous Vide Porchetta", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Porchetta—a whole boned out pig, seasoned, and roasted until the skin is crisp and the meat is meltingly tender and juicy—is almost impossible to get right at home. We say almost impossible because it can be done, it’s just a project. We enlisted the help of master butcher Kevin Smith to show how it’s done with our Ultimate Roast Porchetta, replete with tips and detailed butchery demos so you can ", "i": ["1.6 kg Pork belly , skin-off, preferably from “chuck” end (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Kosher salt , (1.25% of pork belly weight) plus extra as needed", "8 g Fennel seeds , ground (0.5% of pork belly weight)", "4 g Black pepper , freshly ground (0.25% of pork belly weight)", "2 g Rosemary , dried, ground (0.1% of pork belly weight)", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 large cloves) minced into a paste or finely grated", "15 g Extra-virgin olive oil , plus extra as needed", "2 Thyme , fresh sprigs", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon or fleur de sel , as needed", "150 g Apple cider vinegar", "100 g Honey", "2 Fennel , bulbs, trimmed, cored, and thinly sliced; fronds reserved 15 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves - Extra-virgin olive oil, as needed - Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon) , as needed - Lemon zest , finely grated (from 1 lemon) , as needed - Kosher salt, as needed", "15 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves", "Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon) , as needed", "Lemon zest , finely grated (from 1 lemon) , as needed"], "s": ["Choose your porchetta fighter", "Heat sous vide bath", "Make seasoning mixture", "Butterfly pork belly", "Season, roll, and tie porchetta", "Cook porchetta sous vide", "Roast porchetta to crisp fat", "Make agrodolce (optional)", "Make fennel salad (optional)", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["Porchetta seasonings", "Cover for long cooking times"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-porchetta"}, {"id": 270, "t": "Herb-Crusted Sous Vide Chuck Roast", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We all know the stories. “The Ugly Duckling.” “The Frog Prince.” “She’s All That.” We can’t help but root for a seemingly homely hero who undergoes a transformation that reveals the true beauty lurking just below the surface. And everyone lives happily ever after. Our favorite culinary version of that fable is the one that stars the humble beef chuck roast, a cut often overshadowed by its two poli", "i": ["1 Beef chuck roast , boneless (2.7–3.6 kg; 6–8 pounds)", "30 g Neutral oil", "20 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "20 g Black pepper , coarsely ground, plus extra as needed", "5 Garlic clove(s) , unpeeled, lightly crushed", "3 Rosemary , fresh sprigs", "40 g Herbs , such as thyme or rosemary, fresh leaves, roughly chopped", "1 Egg white(s)", "500 ml Beef Stock , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Trim and tie roast", "Presear chuck roast", "Bag up roast", "Cook chuck roast sous vide", "Preheat oven and prepare herb rub", "Coat roast with herb rub", "Finish roast in oven", "Make beef jus (optional)", "Slice roast and serve"], "tips": ["No vacuum-seal bags? Double-bag it.", "Cover for long cooks"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/flavor-packed-feast-worthy-chuck-roast"}, {"id": 271, "t": "Ultimate Chicken Kyiv", "c": "Baking", "d": "Chicken Kyiv is a classic, if dated, dish consisting of pounded chicken cutlets wrapped around cold compound butter packed with garlic and herbs, breaded, and deep fried—essentially a chicken cutlet that sauces itself once you cut it open. It’s a little bit of old-timey culinary sleight of hand, a way to elevate a breaded cutlet into a performance on a plate. This is our take on it. Sure, it doesn", "i": ["800 g Clarified butter , homemade or store-bought", "75 g Garlic clove(s) , (25 large cloves), whole, peeled", "28 g Water", "15 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1/2 lemon)", "900 g Chicken breast(s) , boneless, skinless (2 breasts)", "300 g Egg(s) , (6 large eggs)", "240 g All-purpose flour", "250 g Panko breadcrumbs", "28 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves, cut into a chiffonade (1 bunch)", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon), plus more for seasoning", "1 recipe Creamy Smashed Potatoes , for serving, optional"], "s": ["Confit garlic", "Make garlic purée", "Pound chicken breasts", "Set up breading station", "Season and bread cutlets", "Fry cutlets in clarified butter", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": ["“Look what you did to my beautiful chicken Kyiv!”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-chicken-kiev"}, {"id": 272, "t": "Precision Caramelized Onions", "c": "Baking", "d": "It’s a truth universally acknowledged that caramelizing onions takes way longer than any recipe would have you believe. Until now. The issue most cooks have with following instructions for caramelizing onions is that the process is deceptively simple. Three ingredients—onions, butter, salt—cooked in a standard-issue pan ... how complicated could it be? But as soon as you get the pan on the hob, co", "i": ["1 kg Yellow onion(s) , cut into 1/8-inch-thick slices", "100 g Unsalted butter", "10 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Kinds of Caramelized Onions", "Caramelized Onions", "Lightly Caramelized Onions", "Extra-Dark Caramelized Onions", "Not (Yet) Caramelized Onions", "Sweated Onions", "Sautéed Onions", "Golden Onions"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-caramelized-onions"}, {"id": 273, "t": "No-Fuss French Fries", "c": "Baking", "d": "Making french fries at home ... no thanks. It’s such a hassle. Making them well is a huge ordeal, and it requires a ton of cleanup. Chances are there’s a joint nearby that sells ’em cheap, crispy, and delicious. When it comes to frites, outsourcing is the way to go. Yep, we feel this way, too. Even though we have all these different french fry recipes— thin, thick, super crispy. This is why we fig", "i": ["455 g Russet potato(es) , (1 large potato), scrubbed and cut into 1/4-inch-thick batons (see “Before we begin” note)", "850 g Peanut oil , or other neutral oil, such as canola oil", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Soak and dry potatoes", "Fry potatoes", "Serve"], "tips": ["Chasing maximum crispiness? Double-fry with a cold start."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/no-fuss-french-fries"}, {"id": 274, "t": "Precision Scrambled Eggs", "c": "Baking", "d": "Scrambled eggs ... everyone’s got an opinion. Maybe you like them fluffy. Maybe you like them fancy and French—so runny and custardy they puddle on the plate. Maybe you swear by the method of that shouty British chef, who mixes up his oeufs with a little crème fraîche. We don’t judge. Scrambled eggs can be prepared a million different ways. Conventional recipes rely on a conventional bag of tricks", "i": ["3 Egg(s) , large", "10 g Unsalted butter , (2 teaspoons)", "10 g Heavy cream , (2 teaspoons)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "15 g Milk , whole (1 tablespoon)", "5 g Potato starch , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "4 Egg white(s) , large", "1 Egg yolk(s) , large", "American cheese , sliced, or other melty cheese, optional , as needed", "Chives , thinly sliced, optional , as needed", "20 g Water , 4 teaspoons", "5 g Distilled vinegar , (1 teaspoon) or other vinegar, such as rice wine vinegar", "56 g Neutral oil , such as canola or vegetable oil", "Kecap manis, as needed"], "s": ["Ultra-Creamy French-Style Scrambled Eggs", "Soft-Scrambled Eggs", "Tender Scrambled Egg Whites", "Kid-Friendly Fluffy Scrambled Eggs", "Diner-Style Scrambled Eggs", "Bodega-Style Scrambled Eggs", "“Reverse” Scrambled Eggs", "Crispy “Fried” Scrambled Eggs", "Unleash the power of precision induction cooking!"], "tips": ["Strain eggs before cooking for a streak-free scramble", "Potato starch: The secret ingredient for perfect scrambled eggs", "Kid-tested and -approved!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/precision-scrambled-eggs"}, {"id": 275, "t": "Chili Fried Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "Every culture has its fried chicken. Crispy, salty, meaty, and juicy—it’s easy to see why it’s universally loved. This fried chicken, the signature dish at Pecking House in New York City, is a marriage between Nashville hot chicken and Taiwanese popcorn chicken. A buttermilk brine produces deeply seasoned, tender, and juicy meat, while a mix of modified starches in the flour dredge creates a super", "i": ["1.6 kg Chicken , (1 whole chicken) preferably air-chilled, or bone-in pieces", "220 g Buttermilk", "355 g All-purpose flour , divided", "55 g Dijon mustard", "37 g Kosher salt , divided", "10 g Onion powder", "10 g Garlic powder", "6 g Five-spice powder", "69 g Sugar , divided", "13 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , divided", "150 g Tianjin chiles , dried", "50 g Sichuan peppercorns", "55 g Rice vinegar powder", "300 g Duck fat", "300 g Canola oil , plus extra for deep-frying", "150 g Potato starch", "150 g Cornstarch", "120 g EverCrisp Breader & Batter Boost"], "s": ["Elements of exceptional fried chicken", "Break down chicken (optional)", "Marinate chicken", "Make dry chile mix", "Make chile oil", "Make dredge", "Set up frying station", "Dredge and fry chicken first time", "Double fry chicken", "Douse chicken in chile oil and serve"], "tips": ["A symphony of flavors"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chili-fried-chicken"}, {"id": 276, "t": "Sweet Cheese Claws", "c": "Baking", "d": "The healthiest way to start your day is with a hearty breakfast rich with fiber—fruit, whole grains, a bean dish or two if you’re super serious about it. But the best way to start your day? A buttery, crispy, flaky, cheesy, and sweet puff pastry treat. Hello, cheese claws! They’re like the steamy, hot love child of a cheese Danish or bear claw and a turnover. These delicious numbers take all of ab", "i": ["325 g Cream cheese", "115 g Sugar", "25 g Egg yolk(s) , (about 2 large yolks)", "1 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon), plus extra as needed for egg wash", "1 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped, or 6 g vanilla extract (see “Before we begin” note)", "0.5 recipe Puff Pastry (Pâte Feuilletée) , (one 16- by 12-inch sheet) fully chilled, homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "All-purpose flour , for dusting , as needed", "50 g Water", "50 g Egg(s) , (1 large egg)", "40 g Crystal sugar"], "s": ["Make filling and chill", "Cut pastry and chill", "0.5 recipe", "Roll out dough strips and chill", "Fill, shape, and cut claws", "Bake cheese claws", "Cool and serve"], "tips": ["Cutting puff pastry", "Egg wash variations", "Baking the pastry through"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cheese-claws"}, {"id": 277, "t": "Puff Pastry (Pâte Feuilletée)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Making puff pastry is a challenge, even for experienced bakers. In professional kitchens, puff dough is often made with pastry sheeters, but you can make beautiful dough at home that’s way better than any of the stuff from the freezer aisle with just a stand mixer, a little patience, and some elbow grease. The texture of baked hand-made puff pastry is incomparable: It’s crisp and super flaky but a", "i": ["382 g Bread flour , divided", "382 g Unsalted butter , or vegan butter, chilled, cut into 1/4-inch cubes, divided (See “Before we begin” note)", "170 g Water", "10 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Make dough block (détrempe)", "Make butter block (beurrage)", "Enrobe beurrage", "First turn: letter fold", "Second turn: book fold", "Third turn: second letter fold", "Fourth turn: second book fold", "Sheet dough", "Use dough or store for later"], "tips": ["Mark your dough and parchment to keep track of turns", "Cutting puff pastry", "Baking puff pastry"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/puff-pastry"}, {"id": 278, "t": "Sous Vide Holiday Turkey", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Holidays are all about tradition, even though observing traditions often trumps tastiness. And there’s no better example than the Thanksgiving turkey, which is often dry, overcooked, and bland. This year, we’re asking you to consider stepping away from tradition and making the best dang turkey you’ve ever had. The key to success? Using sous vide. A precision temperature-controlled water bath will ", "i": ["1 Turkey , whole, fresh or fully thawed (5.4–7.25 kg; 12–16 pounds)", "Kosher salt , (1% of breast and leg weight) , as needed", "Sugar , (0.5% of breast and leg weight) , as needed", "180 g Neutral oil , divided", "6 g Sage , fresh leaves, optional", "1 Yellow onion(s) , cut into 8 pieces", "8 g Black peppercorns , whole", "3 g Thyme , fresh sprigs"], "s": ["Turkey Checklist", "Heat sous vide bath", "Break down turkey", "Scale dry-brine mixture", "Presear breasts", "Presear legs", "Bag and season turkey", "Cook legs sous vide", "Make stock (optional)", "Lower sous vide bath temperature and add breasts", "Sear breasts and legs", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["Adding herbs to meat cooked sous vide", "Cover for long cooking times", "Even sous vide has limits. When to pull the legs."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/a-better-way-to-turkey-cook-that-bird-sous-vide-for-the-best-feast-ever"}, {"id": 279, "t": "Thanksgiving Turkey Nuggets", "c": "Baking", "d": "Who doesn’t love chicken nuggets? Not us. We could slam a 20-piece, easy, and not think twice about it. But what if those nuggets actually tasted like ... something? We’re not just talking about the seasoning—the white pepper, the MSG, the garlic and onion powders—that makes the sort-of-crispy, sort-of-springy nug of processed poultry so delicious. What if the nuggets tasted like an actual bird? W", "i": ["900 g Turkey thighs , boneless, skinless, cut into 1-inch pieces (2 pounds)", "10 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "30 g Egg yolk(s) , (2 large yolks)", "58 g Potato starch , divided", "12 g Chicken bouillon powder , preferably from Orrington Farms, divided", "6 g White pepper , freshly ground, divided", "3 g Garlic powder , (1 teaspoon)", "3 g Onion powder , (1 teaspoon)", "140 g All-purpose flour", "3 g Baking powder , (1 teaspoon)", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "325 g Cold water , plus extra as needed"], "s": ["Season turkey", "Process and portion turkey", "Dredge nuggets", "Batter nuggets and first fry", "Second fry", "Serve"], "tips": ["Not planning on eating 45 nuggets at once? Freeze after the first fry."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/thanksgiving-turkey-nuggets"}, {"id": 280, "t": "Holiday Turkey Floss", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Meat floss (rousong in Mandarin, or yuk sung in Cantonese) is a pantry staple with a cotton candy–like texture that’s equal parts savory and sweet, and it’s used as a topping for buns and pastries, rice, congee, and even soy milk and soft tofu. It’s traditionally made with pork, but it can be made with any kind of meat. So why not make a festive floss to level up your holiday feasts this year? Tur", "i": ["1.9 kg Water", "900 g Turkey thighs , bone-in, skin removed and trimmed of excess fat", "15 g Kosher salt , divided", "7 g Onion powder", "5 g Nutritional yeast , (1 tablespoon)", "3 g Sage , dried (1 tablespoon)", "1 g Turmeric root powder , (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Black peppercorns , whole (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Celery seeds , dried (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Parsley , dried (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Rosemary , dried (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Thyme , dried (1/4 teaspoon)", "50 g Sugar", "15 g Light Chinese soy sauce", "10 g Neutral oil", "5 g Dark Chinese soy sauce , (1 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Boil turkey", "Make seasoning blend", "Shred turkey", "Paddle and season turkey", "Cook and season floss", "Cool and start flossing"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/holiday-turkey-floss"}, {"id": 281, "t": "Instant Turkey Gravy", "c": "Baking", "d": "Everyone always talks about the bird during Thanksgiving, but everyone also knows that the gravy is what brings the whole meal together. You drizzle it over the turkey, sure, but it also complements the stuffing, the potatoes, and all the leftovers. Making good gravy ultimately comes down to basic sauce-making technique: You make a roux or starch slurry, add good stock and maybe some pan drippings", "i": ["15 g Neutral oil , optional", "Turkey giblets , (heart, gizzard, liver) from 1 turkey, optional (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "113 g Unsalted butter", "5 g Sage , fresh leaves (5 leaves)", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 large clove) crushed", "1.5 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1 teaspoon)", "70 g All-purpose flour", "70 g Ultimate Turkey Bouillon Cubes , (2 cubes)", "830 g Water", "3 g Kitchen Bouquet Browning and Seasoning Sauce , (1/2 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Brown giblets (optional)", "Brown butter and cook roux", "Add bouillon and finish gravy", "Strain and serve"], "tips": ["Simmer roux-based sauces to maximize thickening potential"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/instant-turkey-gravy"}, {"id": 282, "t": "Ultra-Tender Sous Vide Turkey Breast", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Chances are that when you think of turkey breast, you don’t think of something juicy, succulent, and impossibly delicious. That’s about to change. Cooking a lean turkey breast sous vide transforms it into something extraordinary: crisp skin lying atop super-tender and juicy meat. The key here is treating breast meat—which we think of as white meat, similar to chicken breast—like tough dark meat si", "i": ["1 Turkey crown , (bone-in breast); or 1 whole turkey; or 2 skin-on boneless turkey breasts", "Kosher salt , (1% of breast weight) , as needed", "Sugar , (0.5% of breast weight) , as needed", "90 g Neutral oil , divided", "3 g Sage , fresh leaves (optional)"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Break down turkey (optional)", "Scale dry-brine mixture", "Presear breasts", "Bag and season turkey", "Cook breasts sous vide", "Sear for crispy skin", "Serve"], "tips": ["Adding herbs to meat cooked sous vide", "Cover for long cooking times"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-most-tender-turkey-breast-ever"}, {"id": 283, "t": "Crispy, Tender Sous Vide Confit Turkey Legs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Not for the first time, we find ourselves wishing we could just reach through this screen and hand you a bite of food: Once you taste these crispy-skinned sous vide turkey legs, you’ll never cook your holiday bird any other way. The gentle application of heat for 24 hours in a sous vide bath transforms the tough turkey legs, making them velvety-tender, intensely succulent, and super-juicy, as the ", "i": ["2 Turkey legs , (leg quarters), or 1 whole turkey", "Kosher salt , (1% of leg weight) , as needed", "Sugar , (0.5% of leg weight) , as needed", "90 g Neutral oil , divided", "3 g Sage , fresh leaves (optional)"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Break down turkey (optional)", "Scale dry-brine mixture", "Presear legs", "Bag and season turkey", "Cook legs sous vide", "Sear for crispy skin", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["Adding herbs to meat cooked sous vide", "Cover for long cooking times"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crispy-tender-confit-turkey-legs"}, {"id": 284, "t": "Sous Vide Turkey Roulade", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "One of the things we like to do for Thanksgiving turkey is separate the legs from the breast and use the dark meat to make a roulade seasoned with thyme and sage. If you know, you know: People love a roulade. There’s just something irresistible about a perfectly round slice of meat. A lovingly plated roulade shows your commitment to creating a meal that’s both beautiful and delicious. And it’s a c", "i": ["2 Turkey legs , (leg quarters), or 1 whole turkey (See “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt , (0.6% of weight of cleaned and deboned legs) , as needed", "Sugar , (0.4% of weight of cleaned and deboned legs) , as needed", "Activa RM , (0.5% of weight of cleaned and deboned legs) , as needed", "2 g Flat-leaf parsley , finely chopped", "2 g Sage , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "2 g Thyme , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "Neutral oil , for deep frying , as needed", "Flake sea salt , for serving, optional , as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Debone legs", "Remove tendons", "Scale salt-sugar mixture and season turkey", "Dust with Activa RM", "Add herbs and spices (optional)", "Form roulade", "Cook roulade sous vide", "Unwrap roulade and pat dry", "Crisp skin", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Using needle-nose pliers to remove tendons", "For a roulade, go lighter on seasoning"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turkey-roulade"}, {"id": 285, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Brining Turkey", "c": "Baking", "d": "“Should I brine my turkey?” “Is ‘brining’ just a fancy word for ‘salting’?” “What does a brine even do?” “I’ve got to brine my bird for 5 days??” For many home cooks, the questions of when and whether to use a brine (and why!) mostly come up during the holidays, when you’re getting a big old turkey ready for Thanksgiving. There are several different brining methods that you can employ, each with p", "i": [], "s": ["Start Here!", "“Should I brine my bird?”", "Poultry Brining Calculator", "The Brining Table", "Different Kinds of Brines", "Dry Brine", "Dry Cure", "Gradient Brine", "Equilibrium Brine", "Frequently Asked Questions"], "tips": ["How to weigh a turkey"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/brining-guide"}, {"id": 286, "t": "Sous Vide Pomme Purée", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Smooth and creamy potato purée is one of the simplest and most satisfying things to eat in the world. Lots of cooks have their own tried-and-true methods for silky Robuchon-style potatoes, but we believe our sous vide method is the easiest. (Our low-fi stovetop version is great, too.) We bag up and cook thinly sliced potatoes with milk and butter and cook them until tender. Instead of using a blen", "i": ["910 g Yukon Gold potato(es) , peeled and cut into 1/4-inch-thick pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "250 g Milk , whole", "455 g Unsalted butter , melted", "8 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "White pepper , ground , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Bag up potatoes", "Cook potatoes sous vide", "Pass potatoes through food mill", "Whisk potatoes into butter mixture", "Pass purée and serve"], "tips": ["No vacuum-seal bags? Double-bag it."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pomme-puree"}, {"id": 287, "t": "Chicken Liver Pâté", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Creamy, buttery chicken liver pâté—it’s the stuff you order at a French bistro, not something you make at home. Maybe it’s never crossed your mind—it’s just one of those preparations that seem to exist outside the domain of the home kitchen, its liver-y beginnings perhaps better left a mystery. So, imagine your friends’ surprise at your next dinner party when you serve up grilled bread topped with", "i": ["100 g Bacon , ground or finely chopped", "200 g Onion(s) , (1 small onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "50 g Shallot(s) , (2 shallots) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "100 g White port , dry, or red port", "100 g Madeira", "50 g Apple brandy", "500 g Chicken liver , trimmed", "200 g Egg(s) , (4 large eggs)", "15 g Kosher salt", "2.5 g Prague powder #1 , (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.8 g Sweet Spice , (1/4 teaspoon)", "200 g Unsalted butter , melted, or clarified butter"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Sweat bacon, onion, and shallots", "Add white port, Madeira, and apple brandy", "Strain", "Blend", "Remove air (optional)", "Cast into jars and seal", "Cook pâté sous vide", "Chill pâté", "Serve"], "tips": ["Monitoring temperature while blending", "Sealing jars “fingertip tight” for sous vide cooking", "Pretty in pink(s)"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-liver-pate"}, {"id": 288, "t": "Baklava", "c": "Baking", "d": "There isn’t much that goes into baklava. In fact, the best baklava filling is made with just pistachios and salt. And yet with just a short list of ingredients, you can make one of the most delicious pastries in the world: crisp layers of phyllo dough soaked in sugar syrup surrounding a filling of pure pistachio. Since there’s so little to it, using the best ingredients is the best way to make gre", "i": ["250 g Sugar", "300 g Water", "20 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon)", "450 g Pistachios , raw, shelled (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "200 g Clarified butter , warmed to 100 °F / 38 °C, divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "6 Phyllo sheets , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Cook syrup and cool", "Grind pistachios, season, and divide", "Assemble baklava", "Bake baklava", "Douse with syrup and sprinkle with pistachios", "Cool and serve"], "tips": ["Go nuts with other nuts!", "How to temp syrup", "Using fresh phyllo dough? Make the baklava at the same time."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/baklava"}, {"id": 289, "t": "Hot Giardiniera", "c": "Baking", "d": "Giardiniera is a Chicago pantry staple. It’s spicy (or not), fresh, crisp, vibrant, and the perfect foil for the light fare that the Windy City is known for, like tavern-style pizza and Italian beef sandwiches. Luckily, it’s not difficult to make at all. Buy a bunch of produce, some of those fancy French clamp-lid jars, and make a big old batch of it. If you’re invested enough in pizza to make you", "i": ["175 g Cauliflower , (1/4 head) cored and cut into 3/4-inch florets", "90 g Carrot(s) , (1 medium carrot) peeled and sliced into 1/4-inch-thick batons with a crinkle cutter", "70 g Celery , (2 small ribs) cut crosswise into 1/2-inch pieces", "40 g Red bell pepper(s) , (1 pepper) stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1/2-inch-wide strips", "180 g Serrano chile(s) , (about 18 peppers) stemmed and sliced into 1/2-inch-thick rounds", "75 g Kosher salt", "1.3 kg Water , cold", "236 g Distilled vinegar", "160 g Grapeseed oil", "60 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "1.4 g Oregano , dried (2 teaspoons)", "0.8 g Red pepper flakes , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "1.4 g Celery salt , (1/4 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Brine vegetables", "Marinate vegetables", "Serve and enjoy"], "tips": ["Give your giardiniera a vinegar-pickled bite"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hot-giardiniera"}, {"id": 290, "t": "Pizza Doughs: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pizza is large, it contains multitudes. Whether you’re mangia-ing a puffy Neapolitan cornicione, hoovering up a crispy tavern pie between rounds of brews and Malört (Go Bears!), or scarfing down a fresh-from-the-deck rewarmed slice of pepperoni before schlepping into Brooklyn, you’re eating pizza. You call it pizza, you think of it as pizza, and you love it as pizza, even if a slice of Sicilian is", "i": [], "s": ["Tavern", "Neapolitan", "Grilled", "New York Pizza", "New England–Style Greek", "Sicilian and Sfincione", "Detroit", "School Cafeteria", "Cool parametric, bruv"], "tips": ["Before We Begin, a Note on “Hydration”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pizza-dough-parametric"}, {"id": 291, "t": "Tips & Tricks: How to Handle High-Hydration Doughs", "c": "Baking", "d": "At some point in every bread baker’s life, they decide to up the water content of their dough. Adding more water to dough can be beneficial—greater loft, a more tender crumb, more extensibility, longer shelf life—but high-hydration doughs are notoriously challenging to work with. They can be difficult to shape because they’re so sticky. Luckily, there’s a simple trick to making high-hydration doug", "i": [], "s": ["How to Do It", "Why It Works", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Get that bread"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-handle-high-hydration-doughs"}, {"id": 292, "t": "Triple-Malted Soft Pretzels", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pretzels have the edge over every other baked good because of their deeply browned surface, the direct result of treating the outside of the bread with an alkaline solution before sticking it in the oven. The heat and the alkaline solution encourage a ton of Maillard browning, which packs the big, soft twists of dough with all the toasty, roasty flavors we all know and love. Despite their nearly u", "i": ["300 g Dark beer , such as porter or stout, warmed to 80 °F / 27 °C", "20 g Malt syrup", "5 g Diastatic malt powder , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "3 g Instant dry yeast , (3/4 teaspoon)", "120 g Rye flour , whole grain", "370 g Bread flour , unbleached, divided", "6 g Kosher salt", "40 g Unsalted butter , softened", "500 g Water", "15 g Lye , (sodium hydroxide), food-grade (see “Before we begin” note)", "Pretzel salt , or coarse salt , as needed"], "s": ["Make sponge", "Mix dough and bulk ferment", "Portion and round", "Shape pretzels and retard", "Final proof", "First bake", "Prepare lye bath", "Lye dip and second bake", "Enjoy!"], "tips": ["Are we mixin’ or not?", "Don’t want to use lye? Use baking soda instead."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/soft-pretzels"}, {"id": 293, "t": "How to Use Lye Safely", "c": "Baking", "d": "Making great pretzels and bagels can be a dangerous bit of business. Yes, the dark and malty twisty breads. And the reason why is lye. Lye is the ingredient responsible for the distinctly dark burnishing on the outside of pretzels and for their distinctive mineral taste. Lye also happens to be a powerful corrosive, one seemingly designed to melt your biological meat suit’s mix of proteins and fats", "i": [], "s": ["Setup and Process", "What to Do if You Come Into Contact With Lye", "Lye Frequently Asked Questions", "What Is Lye?", "What Is Lye Used For?", "Why Is Lye Used in Baked Goods?", "Are There Safer Alternatives to Working With Lye?", "We’re not basic, these are basic"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/lye-safety-guide"}, {"id": 294, "t": "Pollo al Carbon", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Every cuisine has a bunch of different ways to cook pollo al carbon, which essentially translates to “charcoal chicken.” This recipe leans toward the pollo al carbon commonly served on the roadside in Sinaloa, Mexico. We spatchcock the chicken to promote even cooking and easy handling on the grill, then marinate it in a paste made from guajillo chiles, aromatics, spices, and citrus and pineapple j", "i": ["1 Chicken , whole (1.8 kg; 4 pounds)", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon) plus extra as needed", "1.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/2 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "75 g Neutral oil", "100 g White onion(s) , (1/2 medium onion) cut into 1-inch dice", "150 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 heads) whole", "40 g Guajillo chile(s) , dried (6 peppers), stemmed, seeded, and broken into small pieces", "1 g Chiles de árbol , dried (2 peppers), stemmed", "1.5 g Mexican cinnamon , whole (1/2-inch piece)", "0.8 g Cumin seeds , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Mexican oregano , dried (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Cloves , (15 pieces)", "100 g Achiote paste", "550 g Water", "50 g Lime juice , fresh (from 1 lime)", "50 g Orange juice , fresh (from 1/2 orange)", "50 g Pineapple juice", "20 g Apple cider vinegar", "Knob onions , whole or halved (see “Before we begin” note), for serving, optional , as needed", "Corn tortillas , warmed, for serving , as needed", "Refried beans , for serving , as needed", "Mexican red rice , for serving , as needed", "Salsa , of your choice, for serving , as needed", "Valentina hot sauce , black label, for serving , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving , as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Spatchcock and season chicken", "Cook marinade", "Blend marinade", "Marinate chicken", "Prepare grill and temper chicken", "Grill chicken", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pollo-al-carbon"}, {"id": 295, "t": "Tomato-Raspberry Gazpacho", "c": "Baking", "d": "When you think of gazpacho, you probably think of a bright red chilled soup made with the best, reddest tomatoes in existence. Race car red. Ruby red. Fire engine red. Red as Campbell’s tomato soup red, but not cooked, not Campbell’s. Huh? Well, you know what we mean: super red! Our version dials up the red color by incorporating ruby-red watermelon and raspberries. The extra water content, sweetn", "i": ["450 g Cherry tomatoes , halved, plus extra for garnish", "225 g Watermelon , rind removed, cut into 1-inch cubes, plus extra diced for garnish", "150 g Raspberries , plus extra for garnish", "150 g Persian cucumber(s) , sliced, plus extra diced for garnish", "120 g Red bell pepper(s) , (about 1/2 pepper) stemmed, seeded, thinly sliced", "60 g Orange juice , fresh (from 2 small oranges)", "55 g White balsamic vinegar , or white sherry vinegar", "30 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon)", "30 g Sherry vinegar", "15 g Fresno chile(s) , (1 pepper) stemmed, seeded, thinly sliced", "6 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "0.75 g Malic acid , (1/4 teaspoon) optional", "0.75 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "100 g Crushed ice", "12 g Basil , fresh leaves, plus extra for garnish", "Extra-virgin olive oil , for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Macerate fruit and vegetables", "Blend gazpacho and chill", "Garnish and enjoy"], "tips": ["Compress diced vegetables for garnish", "Another way to purée red gazpacho"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tomato-gazpacho"}, {"id": 296, "t": "White Gazpacho", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is a loose riff on ajo blanco, aka white gazpacho, from the Andalusia region of Spain. It is usually made with almonds, bread, and a healthy amount of garlic. Our version omits the garlic and uses homemade nut milk and grapes for a super-refreshing ivory chilled soup that’s perfect for the dog days of summer. The key to the soup’s flavor—and color—is fresh nut milk. Using raw, whole al", "i": ["80 g Almonds, raw , whole (see “Before we begin” note)", "60 g Pine nuts , raw", "450 g Water , divided, plus extra for soaking nuts", "100 g Bread , crusts removed, torn into 2-inch pieces (see “Before we begin” note)", "45 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 1/2 lemons)", "35 g Sherry vinegar", "700 g Green grapes , stemmed and washed, plus extra for garnish", "6 g Kosher salt", "0.75 g Malic acid , (1/4 teaspoon) optional", "12 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves, roughly chopped, plus extra whole leaves for garnish", "6 g Mint , fresh leaves, roughly chopped, plus extra whole leaves for garnish", "Tear Your Bread for Better Croutons , for serving, optional , as needed", "Extra-virgin olive oil , for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Soak nuts", "Blend and strain nut milk", "Soak bread", "Blend and chill soup", "Finish with herbs and serve"], "tips": ["Other ways to purée white gazpacho"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/white-gazpacho"}, {"id": 297, "t": "Super Green Gazpacho", "c": "Baking", "d": "This green gazpacho is your new favorite savory fruit soup, bursting with veggies, fruit, and herbs. It’s an arrestingly green way to turn amazing summer produce into a cooling and refreshing dish. Taking a cue from ajo blanco, a white gazpacho that’s enriched by almonds, we give you the option of adding shelled and peeled pistachios, which add creaminess and richness to the soup. Their distinctiv", "i": ["60 g Pistachios , raw, shelled, optional", "200 g Honeydew melon , (1/2 melon) or other green-flesh melon like Galia; peeled, seeded, and cut into 1/4-inch slices", "125 g English cucumber(s) , (1/2 cucumber) cut into 1/4-inch slices, plus extra cut into 1/4-inch dice for garnish", "70 g Green bell pepper , (1/2 pepper) stemmed, seeded, and cut into 1/4-inch slices", "2 g Thai green chile(s) , (1 chile) fresh, stemmed, optional", "45 g Sherry vinegar", "30 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon)", "6 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "0.75 g Malic acid , (1/4 teaspoon) optional", "150 g Sugar snap peas , stemmed and ribbed; plus extra, halved, for garnish (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves (from 1/2 bunch)", "10 g Basil , fresh leaves, plus extra for garnish", "200 g Coconut water , or water", "75 g Ice", "Extra-virgin olive oil, as needed"], "s": ["Soak pistachios (optional)", "Macerate fruit and vegetables", "Blanch and shock peas and herbs", "Blend gazpacho and chill", "Stir, garnish, and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/green-gazpacho"}, {"id": 298, "t": "Golden Gazpacho", "c": "Baking", "d": "This golden-hued gazpacho is a celebration of all the yellow and orange tomatoes of the tomato season—it’s like sunshine in a bowl. The focus of the flavor is on melon and tomatoes, and one of the keys to this recipe is finding great produce. Unlike more traditional gazpachos, we skip the bread and the alliums—there’s nothing to mask the flavor of your fruit, so get good stuff. You don’t have to w", "i": ["400 g Melon , (about 1/2 melon) peeled, seeded, thinly sliced (see “Before we begin” note); plus extra for garnish, optional", "225 g Tomato(es) , cut into wedges or halved depending on size (see “Before we begin” note); plus extra for garnish, optional", "175 g Carrot(s) , (2 medium carrots) peeled, sliced into coins", "150 g Yellow bell pepper , (about 1/2 pepper) stemmed, seeded, thinly sliced (see “Before we begin” note); plus extra for garnish, optional", "10 g Fresh ginger root , (1/2-inch piece) peeled, thinly sliced", "6 g Fresh turmeric root , peeled and thinly sliced, or 1/2 teaspoon turmeric powder", "4 g Habanero pepper(s) , (about 1/2 chile), stemmed, seeded, thinly sliced, optional", "35 g Sherry vinegar", "35 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon)", "4 g Lemon zest , finely grated (from 1 lemon; 2 teaspoons)", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon) plus extra as needed", "0.75 g Malic acid , (1/4 teaspoon) optional", "200 g Ice", "12 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves, roughly chopped", "8 g Basil , fresh leaves, roughly chopped", "Extra-virgin olive oil, as needed"], "s": ["Macerate vegetables and fruit", "Grind vegetables and chill soup", "Finish, garnish, and serve"], "tips": ["Tomato seed gel garnish", "Other ways to purée golden gazpacho"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/golden-gazpacho"}, {"id": 299, "t": "Souped Up: How to Gazpacho Your Way", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Gazpacho! Everyone knows what it is, right? Maybe. In what might be the strongest example of menu word association, as soon you see gazpacho listed among appetizers and salads, your brain immediately reads it as “cold soup.” (Maybe some of your brains do something a little more interesting—“light liquid lunch,” say, or “salad smoothie.”) “Watermelon gazpacho”? Cold watermelon soup. “Avocado gazpac", "i": [], "s": ["What Is Gazpacho?", "Choose Your Own Gazpacho Adventure", "Ingredients", "Preparation", "What are you waiting for? Go gazpacho!"], "tips": ["Soup, salsa, dressing—it’s all about ratios"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/gazpacho-guide"}, {"id": 300, "t": "Smoked Salmon (Nova)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Cold-smoked salmon isn’t something that most cooks make at home. We get it. You’re used to picking up a vacuum-sealed package at the supermarket when you’re hosting a bagel brunch. You might know it as Nova. It’s sometimes referred to inaccurately as “lox.” (If you find the terms confusing, check out our guide to cured and smoked salmon varieties). Regardless of what you call it, smoked salmon is ", "i": ["2 kg Salmon , (1 side) scaled, skin-on, pin bones removed (see “Before we begin” note)", "60 g Kosher salt , (3% of salmon weight) (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Brown sugar , (1.5% of salmon weight)", "Wood chips, as needed"], "s": ["Make cure", "Cure salmon", "Unwrap and dry salmon", "Smoke salmon", "Wrap and chill salmon", "Slice salmon", "Serve"], "tips": ["What is a pellicle?", "Using a Smoking Gun Pro?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smoked-salmon-nova"}, {"id": 301, "t": "Succulent Hot-Smoked Salmon", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Hot-smoked kippered salmon is a thing of beauty. Tender and succulent , seasoned with salt, sugar, and smoke—it’s one of the best ways to eat salmon. Unfortunately, most people have only ever eaten it cold, or flaked into cream cheese. The best way to eat hot hot-smoked salmon is to make it yourself. But hot-smoking salmon is hard. You need to know your way around a smoker, and you need to be care", "i": ["900 g Salmon fillet(s) , skin-on (four 8-ounce fillets; see “Before we begin” note)", "90 g Brown sugar , (10% of salmon weight)", "13.5 g Kosher salt , (1.5% of salmon weight)", "9 g Liquid smoke , (1% of salmon weight), optional (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 recipe Our Favorite Simple Kale Salad , optional"], "s": ["Make cure", "Cure salmon", "Heat sous vide bath", "Cook salmon sous vide", "Smoke salmon", "Reheat salmon", "Serve"], "tips": ["Using a Smoking Gun Pro?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-hot-smoked-salmon"}, {"id": 303, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Salmon", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Salmon! We love it, you love it—we all love it every which way: poached, pan-seared, roasted, cooked sous vide, raw (on rice), near-raw (on a bagel), and even straight out of a can plucked from a supermarket shelf, saltines optional. Heck, you could say America loves it, since it’s our nation’s No. 1 beloved finfish: According to the National Fisheries Institute, a nonprofit trade group, Americans", "i": [], "s": ["What Is Salmon?", "How to Shop for Salmon", "Salmon Species", "Farmed vs. Wild", "Fresh vs. Frozen", "What About Lox and Smoked Salmon?", "How to Butcher and Store Salmon", "How to Season and Brine Salmon", "How to Cook and Prepare Salmon", "Cured and/or Smoked", "Grilled", "Seared", "Roasted and Broiled", "Air-Fried", "Raw or Near Raw"], "tips": ["“Sashimi-Grade” Salmon", "Brining Trials"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cooking-salmon-everything-you-need-to-know"}, {"id": 304, "t": "Tips & Tricks: How to Remove Pin Bones From Salmon", "c": "Baking", "d": "Even the biggest fans of fillets o’ fish share this one, huge gripe: bones! They’re annoying! No one likes doing the whole half-spitting-on-your-fingers as you pull a small bone out of your mouth like a gross magic trick while trying to enjoy a perfectly seared salmon fillet. Of course, if you know how to remove pin bones from a fillet with confidence, you won’t ever have to peh peh peh your way t", "i": [], "s": ["How to Do It", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Here are some ideas to get you started!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-remove-bones-from-salmon"}, {"id": 305, "t": "Know Your Nova From Your Lox: A Guide to Cured and Smoked Salmon", "c": "Seafood", "d": "Walk into any appetizing shop worth its salt, and you’ll see a display case filled with sides of salmon prepared in various ways. All of them are cured—that is, salted and left to sit—so their flesh is silky smooth, soft but firm, ready to be sliced so diaphanously thin they’re almost transparent. Some might be seasoned with dill and juniper, along with a little gin or vodka in the mix; some may h", "i": [], "s": ["Cured and Smoked Salmon at a Glance", "Gravlax", "Nova (Smoked Salmon)", "Other Cold-Smoked Salmon", "Kippered Salmon", "Salmon Candy", "Salmon Roe (Ikura)"], "tips": ["“Cured”? “Brined”?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/a-guide-to-cured-and-smoked-salmon"}, {"id": 306, "t": "Perfect Grilled Salmon Burgers With Instant-Pickled Lemons", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pre-made salmon burgers are one of those things I refuse to buy. They’re really easy to make yourself in very little time, and they’ll be much better than anything you can buy in a store. The most important part of making salmon burgers is buying the highest quality salmon you can find. Once you’ve got your high-quality salmon, you want to keep it cold and work fast. Salmon is a fatty fish—and for", "i": ["910 g Salmon fillet(s) , skin and pin bones removed", "2 Egg yolk(s)", "4.5 g Kosher salt , 0.5% weight of salmon (1 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "Hamburger bun(s), as needed", "Mayonnaise, as needed", "1 recipe Fresh and Bright Instant-Pickled Lemons", "Bibb lettuce , leaves , as needed"], "s": ["Chop and mix salmon", "Portion salmon", "Form patties", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Presear patties", "Finish grilling burgers", "Build and serve"], "tips": ["Chilling before grilling", "How to set up a grilling work station"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-salmon-burgers-leveled-up"}, {"id": 307, "t": "Spanakopita (Spinach and Cheese Pie)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Spanakopita is the Greek spinach pie that’s pretty great even when it’s mid: Greasy layers of phyllo dough packed around wads of spinach are given the semblance of seasoning by gluey supermarket feta. But what if you made it actually great? What if you used Savoy spinach, mixed with homemade farmer cheese, wrapped in flaky layer after flaky layer of scratch-made phyllo dough? Well, that’s what we ", "i": ["200 g Farmer cheese , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "90 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided", "50 g Red onion(s) , (1/4 onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "200 g Fresh spinach , (1 bunch) trimmed and washed (see “Before we begin” note)", "20 g Tender herbs , picked and washed (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Lemon zest , finely grated, from 1 lemon (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Aleppo pepper , (1/4 teaspoon) optional", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "6 Phyllo sheets , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Cook onions and greens", "Finish filling", "Layer phyllo sheets", "Build pie and chill", "Bake pie", "Rest, slice, and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spanakopita"}, {"id": 308, "t": "How to Make Phyllo Dough", "c": "Baking", "d": "Why make phyllo from scratch? Because it’s so much more delicious than the store-bought frozen stuff—and it’s FUN. Your spanakopita and baklava will thank you: Fresh phyllo, or filo as it’s sometimes written, bakes up ethereally light and crispy; it tastes like the marketing photograph on the package of frozen phyllo dough looks. But that’s not the only draw here! Fresh phyllo is supple, very exte", "i": ["230 g Water , warm, 90 °F / 32 °C–100 °F / 38 °C", "60 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "17 g Distilled vinegar , or other vinegar, such as red wine, apple cider, or champagne", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "525 g Bread flour , unbleached, divided, plus extra as needed", "25 g Cornstarch"], "s": ["Mix and rest dough", "Portion and rest dough", "Make bench flour mixture", "First roll out", "Second roll out and final stretch", "Put phyllo sheets to use or save for later"], "tips": ["Turn phyllo scraps into cinnamon twists"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/phyllo-dough"}, {"id": 309, "t": "Northern Thai Herbal Sausage (Sai Ua)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Sai ua is a coarsely ground pork sausage seasoned with red curry paste, aromatics, and spices. Although the dish originated in Northern Thailand, Laos, and Myanmar, it’s so delicious it’s become popular all over Thailand. The combination of lemongrass, cilantro, makrut lime leaf, and red curry paste produces an herbaceous flavor profile that’s complemented beautifully by the smoky aroma the sausag", "i": ["1.5 kg Pork shoulder , boneless, skinless", "400 g Pork belly , boneless, skinless", "400 g Pork fatback", "188 g Red curry paste , (see “Before we begin” note)", "55 g Fish sauce , preferably Red Boat", "50 g Lemongrass , (2 stalks) bottom 4 to 5 inches only, outer layers discarded, tender core bruised and minced", "30 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, chopped", "20 g Curry powder , (see “Before we begin” note)", "10 g Makrut lime leaf , fresh or frozen (about 10 leaves), mid-ribs removed, minced (see “Before we begin” note)", "10 g Dried Thai chile(s) , finely ground", "9 g Kosher salt", "5 g Sugar , (1 1/4 teaspoon)", "3 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1 teaspoon)", "5 g Neutral oil", "Hog casings , soaked (see “Before we begin” note) , as needed", "Sticky rice , cooked, for serving , as needed", "Green cabbage , raw, cored and cut into small wedges, for serving , as needed", "Peanuts , roasted, skin-on, for serving, optional , as needed", "Pork cracklings , optional , as needed", "1 recipe Nam Prik Num (Thai Roasted Green Chile Relish)", "5 g Neutral oil - Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Grind pork", "Mix sausage meat", "Test sausage for seasoning", "Stuff sausage into casings", "Twist off sausages", "Prick and chill", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Grill sausages", "Serve"], "tips": ["Grill’s hot? Make nam prik num."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sai-oua-northern-thai-herbal-sausage"}, {"id": 310, "t": "Nam Prik Num (Thai Roasted Green Chile Relish)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Nam prik num, a roasted green chile condiment, is in a class of Thai relishes that have a consistency somewhere between a paste and a sauce. It’s the ultimate flavor booster for grilled meats and raw vegetables, and it’s a great stress reliever, since making it requires smashing stuff into teeny-tiny pieces with a heavy stone. Win-win! Nam prik relishes, like curry pastes, are traditionally prepar", "i": ["75 g Jalapeño(s) , (3 medium peppers) stemmed", "75 g Shallot(s) , (3 medium shallots)", "60 g Green banana pepper(s) , fresh (5 to 8 peppers), stemmed", "38 g Garlic clove(s) , (10 cloves)", "15 g Thai shrimp paste", "8 g Thai green chile(s) , fresh (5 to 6 peppers), stemmed", "75 g Cilantro root(s) , (roots from 1 bunch) cleaned and thinly sliced (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "38 g Palm sugar , softened", "77 g Fish sauce , preferably Red Boat", "75 g Lime juice , fresh (from 2 limes)"], "s": ["Prepare two-zone grill", "Grill aromatics", "Chop vegetables", "Pound relish", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/nam-prik-num"}, {"id": 311, "t": "Fried Egg and Thai Sausage Breakfast Sandwich", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "This Thai-inspired riff on a breakfast sandwich is an excellent way to put Sai Ua sausage to use in a less traditional way. In fact, it’s so good that you might even consider making the sausage specifically for this sandwich. As a bonus, that means you don’t have to mess around with casings and a sausage stuffer. Along with richness from the liquid yolks on crispy-edged Thai-style fried eggs, the ", "i": ["620 g Northern Thai Herbal Sausage (Sai Ua) , raw, uncased", "250 g Kewpie mayonnaise , homemade or store-bought", "150 g Nam Prik Num (Thai Roasted Green Chile Relish)", "15 g Lime juice , fresh (from 1/2 lime)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Neutral oil , divided , as needed", "4 Egg(s) , (4 large eggs) for serving", "4 Brioche roll(s) , toasted, for serving", "20 g Cilantro , fresh leaves, for serving", "20 g Fried shallots , for serving"], "s": ["Form sausage patties", "Make nam prik num mayo", "Smoke sausage", "Sear sausage patties", "Fry eggs", "Assemble sandwiches and serve"], "tips": ["Using a Smoking Gun Pro?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/northern-thai-herbal-sausage-breakfast-sandwich"}, {"id": 312, "t": "Sizzling Pork Sisig", "c": "Baking", "d": "Sizzling sisig has been the best-selling dish at Pig and Khao ever since we opened. It’s the ultimate drinking food: salty, acidic, crispy, chewy, fatty, and meaty—it almost demands being served alongside a bucket of cold beers. Just like at Chili’s, once we run one sizzling platter out of our open kitchen, more orders come flying in—for pig’s head, not mid fajitas. A traditional Filipino dish, si", "i": ["1 Pig head , or 910 g (2 pounds) mixed boneless pork cuts (see “Before we begin” note)", "1.9 l Water", "75 g Soy sauce", "60 g Apple cider vinegar", "48 g Kosher salt", "55 g Garlic clove(s) , (11 cloves), 15 g (3 cloves) whole, 40 g (8 cloves) minced, divided", "24 g Sugar", "4 g Black pepper , freshly ground", "3 Fresh bay leaves", "1 Star anise", "40 g Neutral oil", "80 g Red onion(s) , (1/2 small onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "32 g Fresh ginger root , (1 1/2-inch piece) peeled and minced", "12 g Fresh red Thai chile(s) , (6 chiles) stemmed and thinly sliced", "50 g Maggi Seasoning , plus extra as needed", "20 g Fish sauce , plus extra as needed", "3 g Makrut lime leaf , fresh or frozen (4 large leaves), mid-ribs removed, cut into a chiffonade", "15 g Lime juice , fresh (from 1/2 lime), plus extra as needed", "15 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1/2 lemon), plus extra as needed", "4 Egg(s) , large", "10 g Cilantro , fresh leaves", "Jasmine rice , cooked, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Break down pig head (optional)", "Preheat oven and prepare braising liquid", "Braise pork", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Grill and dice pork", "Sear and season sisig", "Fry eggs and finish sisig"], "tips": ["Level up with crispy pig ear “croutons”", "Makrut lime leaf “hair”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sisig"}, {"id": 313, "t": "Thai-Style Steamed Fish With Garlic and Lime (Pla Gapong Neung Manao)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Pla gapong neung manao is a classic Thai dish consisting of steamed fish served in an acidic broth with lots of minced garlic and fresh chiles. It’s as easy to prepare as it is impressive to serve and tasty to eat. The fish is scored, stuffed with lemongrass, gently steamed, and typically served in a fish-shaped heated serving platter with a chamber that can accommodate hot coals or a can of Stern", "i": ["1 Whole red snapper , scaled and gutted (about 800 g; 1.75 pounds)", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "3 Lemongrass , stalks", "128 g Fish Stock , homemade or store-bought, or chicken stock", "20 g Palm sugar", "2 Cilantro root(s) , cleaned (see “Before we begin” note)", "45 g Garlic clove(s) , (16 cloves) minced", "45 g Shallot(s) , (2 large shallots) thinly sliced", "60 g Lime juice , fresh (from 3 limes)", "50 g Fish sauce , preferably Red Boat", "13 g Fresh red Thai chile(s) , (10 to 12 chiles) stemmed and minced", "1 Lime(s) , sliced into 1/8-inch-thick rounds, optional", "40 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, roughly chopped", "Jasmine rice , cooked, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Set up steamer", "Score and season fish", "Steam fish", "Simmer sauce", "Sauce, garnish, and serve"], "tips": ["Using a heated serving dish? Adjust the cooking time."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pla-manao-thai-style-whole-steamed-fish"}, {"id": 314, "t": "Filipino-Style Grilled Pork Belly (Inihaw na Liempo)", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "You can find grilled pork belly all over the Philippines: Marinated in an acidic, slightly sweet, and very savory soy-based mixture to tenderize and season the meat, the pork belly is then cooked from start to finish on a grill, the marinade basted generously over the belly until the outside is sticky, caramelized, and charred. Cooking pork belly from start to finish on a grill is tricky, especial", "i": ["130 g Soy sauce", "167 g Sugar , divided", "80 g Cane vinegar , such as Datu Puti", "80 g Oyster sauce", "80 g Banana ketchup , (see “Before we Begin” note)", "80 g Garlic clove(s) , (18 cloves) minced, divided", "48 g Kosher salt , divided", "8 g Black pepper , freshly ground", "3 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG)", "910 g Pork belly , boneless, skinless (2 pounds)", "325 g Hot water", "250 g Distilled vinegar", "35 g Kimchi seasoning paste", "1 g Dried Thai chile(s) , (1 chile), finely ground", "1 Pineapple , peeled, cored, and cut into 2 1/2-inch by 1/2-inch batons", "Fried garlic , for serving, optional , as needed", "Scallion(s) , thinly sliced, for serving, optional , as needed", "Garlic fried rice , for serving (see “Before we Begin” note), optional , as needed"], "s": ["Make the marinade", "Marinate pork", "Make pineapple atchara", "Heat sous vide bath", "Cook pork belly sous vide", "Chill pork belly", "Slice pork belly and reduce cooking liquid", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Grill pork belly", "Slice and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/inihaw-na-liempo-grilled-pork-belly"}, {"id": 315, "t": "Blackened Tri-Tip Steak Salad", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Tri-tip—aka Newport or Santa Maria steak—doesn’t get much love, and that’s a shame. It’s super flavorful and beefy, and like our other favorite, under-appreciated cut, chuck, it can be prepared as a showstopping roast or as a killer, budget-friendly steak. Cooking tri-tip properly can be challenging. It’s a whole muscle of uneven thickness; the direction of the grain changes about halfway through ", "i": ["35 g Brown sugar , divided", "25 g Molasses, light (mild flavor)", "20 g Worcestershire sauce", "15 g Smoked salt , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "12 g Black pepper , freshly ground, divided", "5 g Liquid smoke , (1 teaspoon)", "1 Beef tri-tip , (about 1 kg; 2.2 pounds)", "9 g Dried orange peel , finely ground", "2.5 g Cinnamon , ground (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "2.5 g Allspice , ground (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "2.5 g Cumin seeds , ground (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "2.5 g Mustard powder , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Rosemary , dried, finely ground (3/4 teaspoon)", "1 g Red pepper flakes , finely ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "30 g Neutral oil , plus extra as needed", "2 Radicchio , heads, quartered lengthwise (about 275 g)", "2 Gem romaine lettuce , heads, halved lengthwise (about 225 g)", "1 recipe Grilled Tomato Vinaigrette , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "150 g Cherry tomatoes , quartered", "65 g Red onion(s) , (1/4 medium onion) thinly sliced", "40 g Pine nuts , toasted", "22 g Basil , fresh leaves (about 1 bunch)", "56 g Goat cheese , such as Humboldt Fog, crumbled, optional"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Prepare marinade", "Prepare and bag tri-tip", "Cook tri-tip sous vide", "Make spice rub", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Season tri-tip with rub", "Grill radicchio and lettuce", "Grill tri-tip", "Assemble salad and slice tri-tip"], "tips": ["The importance of slicing against the grain"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/blackened-tri-tip"}, {"id": 316, "t": "Grilled Tomato Vinaigrette", "c": "Baking", "d": "This grilled tomato vinaigrette is a great way to use up gorgeous, in-season tomatoes. We originally developed it for a riff on panzanella, but we liked it so much that we felt it deserved a recipe all of its own. Even after charring tomatoes on the grill, they still contain a bunch of water. To account for it, we reduce sherry vinegar to concentrate its acidity and flavor. Buzz the tomatoes, vine", "i": ["8 g Fennel seeds", "240 g Sherry vinegar", "24 g Sugar", "1 Tomato(es) , large beefsteak (about 425 g; 15 ounces)", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "0.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/4 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "110 g Extra-virgin olive oil"], "s": ["Toast fennel and reduce vinegar", "Prepare the grill", "Char the tomato", "Blend dressing"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-tomato-vinaigrette"}, {"id": 317, "t": "Cochinita Pibil", "c": "Baking", "d": "Cochinita pibil is a Yucatecan preparation that’s more of a ritual than a dish: whole suckling pig, doused in an aggressively spiced marinade of citrus juice, vinegar, and achiote (aka annatto; for its distinctive red coloring), wrapped in banana leaves and slowly cooked in a “pib,” a kind of earthen oven dug in a hole in the ground. If you want to break down a whole pig and dig a hole in the grou", "i": ["1 Pork shoulder , bone-in, skinless, about 3.2 kg (7 pounds)", "25 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "95 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 head) unpeeled", "20 g Black peppercorns", "9 g Cumin seeds", "8 g Mexican oregano , dried", "8 g Mexican cinnamon", "1.5 g Cloves , (23 pieces)", "1.5 g Allspice , whole (11 pieces)", "5 Bay leaf , dried", "265 g Lime juice , fresh (from 9 limes)", "125 g Orange juice , fresh (from 3 oranges)", "100 g Achiote paste , (aka annatto paste)", "75 g Apple cider vinegar", "454 g Fresh banana leaves", "200 g Lard , softened", "900 g Chicken stock , homemade or store-bought", "24 Corn tortillas , homemade or store-bought, warmed, for serving", "90 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving", "2 Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving", "1 recipe Salsa de Habanero , for serving", "1 recipe Yucatán-Style Pickled Red Onions , for serving"], "s": ["Score and season pork", "Roast garlic and toast spices", "Make marinade", "Warm banana leaves and line Dutch oven", "Marinate pork", "Cook pork", "Serve"], "tips": ["What is a pib?", "Level up your cochinita pibil tacos"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cochinita-pibil-oven"}, {"id": 318, "t": "Yucatán-Style Pickled Red Onions", "c": "Preservation", "d": "These lightning-quick pickles get a little zip and zap from a bit of habanero and Mexican oregano, so they’re perfect for whenever you want to add a little personality to a meal by offering a condiment for the table. They’re particularly excellent served alongside cochinita pibil. save Print", "i": ["185 g Red onion(s) , (1 medium onion) thinly sliced", "7 g Sugar", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "4 g Habanero pepper(s) , (1 small pepper) stemmed and thinly sliced", "1 g Mexican oregano , dried (1 teaspoon)", "80 g Lime juice , fresh (from 4 limes)", "15 g Distilled vinegar"], "s": ["Macerate onion and habanero", "Add acid and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pickled-red-onions"}, {"id": 319, "t": "Salsa de Habanero", "c": "Sauce", "d": "This simple but fiery salsa is a great example of the big, bold flavors of the Yucatán Peninsula. It’s great on anything from grilled meats and seafood to tacos stuffed with delectable braises—if you’re making cochinita pibil, you’re going to want some of this stuff to serve alongside. Blooming the habanero in oil before blending the salsa intensifies the capsaicin heat, even as it brings out more", "i": ["125 g Neutral oil", "360 g White onion(s) , (about 1 large onion) cut into 1-inch dice", "75 g Garlic clove(s) , (15 cloves) whole", "4 Allspice , whole", "50 g Habanero pepper(s) , (6 chiles) stemmed", "135 g Orange juice , fresh (from 3 oranges)", "60 g Lime juice , fresh (from 2 limes)", "8 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "60 g Water"], "s": ["Sauté aromatics", "Blend salsa", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salsa-de-habanero"}, {"id": 320, "t": "Sous Vide Pastrami", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We’ve got sous vide versions of all your ’cue favorites—brisket, butt, ribs, short ribs—and they’re just as good, if not better and easier to make than the real deal. We took all our experience with turning tough hunks of meat into tender and juicy ’cue and translated it to the task of creating our version of the star of the Jewish delicatessen: sous vide pastrami. “Pastrami” comes from the Turkis", "i": ["9 kg Water", "655 g Brown sugar , divided", "375 g Kosher salt , divided", "60 g Prague powder #1", "68 g Coriander seeds , whole, divided", "10 g Yellow mustard seeds , whole", "82 g Black peppercorns , whole, divided", "8 g Pink peppercorns , whole", "4.5 g Fennel seeds , whole (1 1/2 tablespoons)", "3.2 g Cinnamon stick(s) , (2 sticks)", "8.5 g Chile flakes , whole, divided", "0.7 g Cloves , whole (about 12 cloves)", "4 Fresh bay leaves", "4 kg Beef short ribs , bone-in, two 3-bone plates", "10 g Juniper berries , whole", "10 g Garlic powder"], "s": ["Prepare brine", "Trim short ribs", "Brine short ribs", "Make spice rub", "Season short ribs", "Smoke short ribs", "Heat sous vide bath", "Bag short ribs", "Cook short ribs sous vide", "Remove bones and slice pastrami", "Serve"], "tips": ["Rapid-chill the brine", "Grind spices in stages", "No vacuum-seal bags? Double-bag it.", "Cover for long cooks"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-pastrami"}, {"id": 321, "t": "Microwave Barbecue Pulled Pork", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "There’s nothing like pulled pork, cooked low and slow for hours until the meat falls apart when you look at it, inviting you to slather it in sauce and pile it high onto a soft, sweet bun. Except ... that’s not true. There’s microwaved pull pork cooked from start to finish in two hours. If that sounds odd to you, you just haven’t been paying attention. The microwave is one of the most powerful too", "i": ["1.5 kg Pork collar , boneless, or pork butt (shoulder)", "38 g Yellow mustard", "Carolina Gold Barbecue Rub, as needed", "Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue , optional , as needed", "50 g Water , plus extra as needed", "1 recipe Carolina Gold Barbecue Sauce , (choose one sauce)", "1 recipe Lexington-Style Barbecue Sauce , (choose one sauce)", "1 recipe Eastern North Carolina–Style Vinegar Barbecue Sauce , (choose one sauce)"], "s": ["Season pork", "Wrap and microwave pork", "Uncover and finish cooking to set bark", "Chop, dress, and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/microwaved-pulled-pork"}, {"id": 322, "t": "Sous Vide Barbecue Beef Short Ribs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Short rib is one of the most flavorful cuts of beef: Lots of bold, beefy flavor and super tender and juicy when cooked properly. For us—and for some purists these will be fighting words—short ribs are a much better cut for barbecue than brisket, as long as they’re treated right: Cooked low and slow in a moist environment until all the connective tissue converts to gelatin. (It’s also a superior op", "i": ["2.4 kg Beef short ribs , bone-in, 3-bone plate (5.3 pounds)", "30.5 g Brown sugar , (2.5% of short rib weight)", "12 g Kosher salt , (1% of short rib weight)", "12 g Black pepper , freshly ground (0.5% of short rib weight)", "2.4 g Prague powder #1 , optional (0.1% of short rib weight)", "30 g Molasses , (2.5% of short rib weight)", "12 g Liquid smoke , optional (0.5% of short rib weight)", "Texas Black Pepper Barbecue Rub, as needed", "Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue , optional , as needed", "1 recipe Sweet and Sticky Barbecue Sauce , optional, for serving"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Trim short ribs", "Make cure", "Make glaze", "Glaze, season, and bag short ribs", "Cook short ribs sous vide", "Separate ribs", "Glaze and season with rub", "Smoke short ribs or finish in oven", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["Getting a barbecue smoke ring without a smoker", "No vacuum-seal bags? Double-bag it.", "Cover for long cooks"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bbq-beef-short-ribs"}, {"id": 323, "t": "Sous Vide Barbecue Brisket", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Brisket is a pitmaster’s mainstay, but let’s face it: It’s often poorly executed, and ends up being dry, bland, blah. Tired of the ho-hum stuff (and never willing to shy away from a challenge), we set out to make a better brisket, with juicy, smoky meat and a sticky, satisfying bark. Just to up the ante, we decided to develop it without the aid of a smoker, taking a modernist approach using liquid", "i": ["1.9 kg Beef brisket point , (1 brisket point)", "95 g Brown sugar , (5% of brisket weight)", "28 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1.5% of brisket weight)", "19 g Kosher salt , (1% of brisket weight)", "1.8 g Prague powder #1 , optional (0.1% of brisket weight)", "45 g Molasses , (2.5% of brisket weight)", "9 g Liquid smoke , optional (0.5% of brisket weight)", "Texas Black Pepper Barbecue Rub, as needed", "Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue , optional , as needed", "1 recipe Sweet and Sticky Barbecue Sauce , optional, for serving", "8 kg Water , cold", "540 g Smoked salt , divided", "6 kg Brisket", "60 g Liquid aminos , or soy sauce", "120 g Chipotle chile powder , or smoked paprika", "45 g Mustard powder", "30 g Onion powder", "15 g Garlic powder"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Trim brisket", "Make cure", "Make glaze", "Glaze, season, and bag brisket", "Cook brisket sous vide", "Glaze brisket and season with rub", "Smoke brisket or finish in oven", "Rest, slice, and serve"], "tips": ["Getting a barbecue smoke ring without a smoker", "No vacuum-seal bags? Double-bag it.", "Cover for long cooks", "The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smokerless-smoked-brisket"}, {"id": 324, "t": "Sous Vide Barbecue Ribs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We believe you should be able to make barbecue wherever you live, whether you live on a big-skied prairie or in a tiny studio smack in the middle of a skyscraper. Not just when the weather permits or once you’ve amassed the funds to invest in a smoker: You should be able to create incredible barbecue, indoors, whenever you damn well please. And if you don’t want to wear pants while you do it, well", "i": ["150 g Kosher salt , divided", "5 g Prague powder #1 , (3/4 teaspoon), optional", "150 g Molasses", "75 g Liquid smoke", "2 Baby back rib rack , about 3 kg (6.6 pounds) total", "100 g Smoked paprika", "50 g Yellow mustard seeds , whole", "30 g Granulated garlic", "25 g Black peppercorns", "10 g Onion flakes", "10 g Cumin seeds , whole", "200 g Brown sugar", "Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue , optional , as needed", "Kansas City-Style Barbecue Sauce , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Prepare salt mixture", "Prepare smoky glaze", "Prep ribs", "Season ribs with salt mixture", "Glaze and bag ribs", "Cook ribs sous vide", "Make rib rub", "Glaze and sprinkle ribs with rub", "Finish ribs in oven", "Carve and serve"], "tips": ["No vacuum-seal bags? Double-bag it."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smokerless-smoked-ribs-incredible-barbecue-no-smoker-required"}, {"id": 325, "t": "Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue", "c": "Baking", "d": "Making great indoor barbecue is hard; purists argue that it’s impossible. Specifically, they argue that the bark, the iconic and elusive feature of nicely smoked meat, can’t be done without a smoker. For the uninitiated, “bark” is that almost crispy layer of deeply browned to blackened spice, meat, fat, and smoke that develops on the surface of smoked meat. And to a certain extent, we agree with t", "i": ["100 g Isomalt", "50 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "20 g Baking soda", "10 g Citric acid"], "s": ["Grind into a powder", "How to use Bark Builder for indoor barbecue"], "tips": ["What is bark?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bark-builder"}, {"id": 326, "t": "Caldo de Siete Mares (Mexican Seafood Soup)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Caldo de siete mares—“soup of the seven seas”—shares characteristics with other seafood stews from across the globe. Legend has it that, like cioppino or bouillabaisse, it was created out of necessity, a way for fishermen in the Ensenada area of Baja California to use up their unsold catch. And like all great seafood soups, the key to a killer caldo de siete mares is a super flavorful stock. Here,", "i": ["175 g Neutral oil , divided", "40 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "130 g Garlic clove(s) , (26 cloves) minced, divided", "495 g Carrot(s) , peeled, cut into 1-inch obliques, divided", "485 g Roma tomato(es) , (3 tomatoes) quartered", "20 g Guajillo chile(s) , stemmed and seeded", "2 g Chiles de árbol , dried, stemmed and seeded, finely ground", "70 g Chipotle chiles in adobo sauce", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.7 g Cumin seeds , (1/4 teaspoon)", "7 Allspice , whole", "2 Fresh bay leaves", "454 g Shrimp , (large 10–15 count), shell-on, peeled and deveined, shells reserved", "10 g Mariscos Sazón (Seafood Seasoning Blend)", "120 g Unsalted butter", "3.5 kg Chicken stock , homemade or store-bought", "454 g Halibut , or cobia, fillet, cut into 2-inch cubes", "410 g Squid , cleaned, bodies cut crosswise into 1/2-inch-thick rings, tentacles kept whole, optional", "400 g Octopus , cooked, cut into 1-inch pieces, optional", "30 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "355 g New potatoes , whole, scrubbed", "266 g Dungeness crab , (about 1/2 crab) cooked (see “Before we begin” note)", "580 g Clams , Manila or littleneck, fresh, scrubbed, purged (see “Before we begin” note)", "454 g Mussels , scrubbed and debearded", "Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving , as needed", "Lime wedges , for serving , as needed", "Valentina hot sauce , black label, for serving , as needed", "Corn tortillas , homemade or store-bought, warmed, for serving , as needed", "250 g White onion(s) , (1 medium onion) cut into 1-inch dice", "75 g Shrimp shells"], "s": ["Cook aromatics for stock", "Simmer stock", "Blend stock", "Marinate seafood", "Make the soup", "Finish soup", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/caldo-de-siete-mares"}, {"id": 327, "t": "Camarones al Mojo de Ajo (Mexican Garlic Shrimp)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Think of these wok-seared shrimp as a supercharged savory-spicy Mexican version of shrimp scampi: succulent shrimp in a buttery, garlicky, chile-spiked sauce designed to be mopped up with a crusty heel of bread. Even though it takes less than 10 minutes to cook, this dish is packed with flavor. Cooking the shrimp in a wok over charcoal (instead of sautéing them on the stovetop) maxes out Maillard ", "i": ["30 g Neutral oil", "900 g Shrimp , (jumbo 4–6 count) shell-on, split lengthwise and deveined", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon) plus extra as needed", "60 g Mariscos Sazón (Seafood Seasoning Blend) , divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "155 g Red onion(s) , (1 small onion) thinly sliced", "100 g Garlic clove(s) , (20 cloves) minced (see “Before we begin” note)", "226 g Unsalted butter , cold, cut into 1-inch cubes", "18 g Soy sauce", "18 g Maggi Seasoning", "18 g Valentina hot sauce , black label", "28 g Lime juice , fresh (from 1 lime)", "Garlic bread , for serving, optional , as needed", "White rice , cooked and buttered, for serving, optional , as needed", "Salad , (iceberg lettuce, tomato, and red onion tossed with lime juice, olive oil, and salt) for serving, optional , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into a chiffonade, for serving , as needed", "Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves, finely chopped, for serving , as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare grill", "Preheat wok", "Cook shrimp", "Serve"], "tips": ["Mexican-style garlic shrimp, cooked in a wok ... on a charcoal grill?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/camarones-al-mojo-de-ajo"}, {"id": 328, "t": "Pescado Zarandeado (Chile-Marinated Grilled Fish)", "c": "Baking", "d": "You can find a lot of versions of pescado zarandeado—whole fish that is butterflied, brushed with a chile-spiked mayo-based marinade, and grilled over charcoal—throughout Mexico. While some versions take a light approach to seasoning, this one leans heavily on dried chiles and spices to produce a grilled whole fish with tons of flavor. The marinade is packed with glutamates—soy sauce, tomato paste", "i": ["1 Snapper , whole (about 700–900 g; 1 1/2–2 pounds)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "10 g Ancho chile(s) , dried, stemmed and seeded", "7 g Guajillo chile(s) , dried, stemmed and seeded", "125 g Mayonnaise", "70 g Tomato paste", "35 g Soy sauce", "25 g Yellow mustard", "25 g Garlic powder", "25 g Lime juice , fresh (from 1 lime)", "20 g Valentina hot sauce , black label, plus extra for serving", "15 g Worcestershire sauce", "10 g Maggi Seasoning", "1 g Mexican oregano , dried (1 teaspoon)", "Corn tortillas , homemade or store-bought, warmed, for serving , as needed", "White rice , cooked and buttered, for serving , as needed", "Black beans , cooked, for serving , as needed", "Lime(s) , cut into wedges, for serving , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, whole or cut into a chiffonade, for serving , as needed", "Red onion(s) , thinly sliced or cut into a small dice, for serving , as needed", "Avocado(s) , cut into thin wedges, for serving , as needed", "Tomato(es) , cut into thin wedges, for serving , as needed", "Salsa , of your choice, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Butterfly, debone, and season fish", "Grind dried chiles", "Make marinade", "Marinate fish", "Prepare grill and temper fish", "Grill fish", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pescado-zarandeado"}, {"id": 329, "t": "Quintessential Americana Cherry Pie", "c": "Baking", "d": "We think the phrase “as American as baseball, hot dogs, and apple pie” needs an update to include this supercharged version of summer’s true superstar: the cherry pie. We use a three-stage baking process that guarantees a crisp, evenly browned crust. To ensure the filling survives the extended bake time, instead of using cornstarch, we use clear jel, a modified cornstarch that’s way more heat resi", "i": ["400 g Bread flour", "250 g Unsalted butter , cold, cut into 1-inch cubes", "10 g Kosher salt", "160 g Ice water", "950 g Sour cherries , frozen, see “Before we begin” note", "250 g Sugar", "75 g Clear jel , see “Before we begin” note", "5 g Citric acid , or Malic acid, optional", "150 g Cherry juice , see “Before we begin” note", "35 g Lemon juice , fresh, from 1 lemon", "50 g Water", "50 g Egg(s) , (1 large egg)", "Demerara sugar, as needed"], "s": ["Mix dough", "Divide dough and chill", "Make filling", "Roll out top crust", "Roll out bottom crust", "Assemble pie and chill", "Bake pie", "Serve"], "tips": ["Go the extra mile: Add booze or booze-infused dried fruit to your filling", "Keep those frozen cherries frozen!", "Upgrade that top with a lattice", "Or skip the top and go Dutch"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cherry-pie-quintessential-americana"}, {"id": 330, "t": "DIY Sous Vide Spam", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Homemade Spam? Yes! Oh, were you asking why we, you, or anyone else would make homemade Spam? Got it! Well, homemade Spam is better than the stuff in the can. It’s as simple as that. Spam is just ground up meat that’s heavily seasoned and cooked, which is also essentially what a McRib is (or a meatloaf), so it seemed like a simple pivot to mold ground meat into a Spam can–like shape and call it a ", "i": ["370 g Ground pork", "116 g Pork fatback , cut into 1/2-inch cubes", "116 g Ice , crushed, see “Before we begin” note", "28 g Potato starch", "8 g Kosher salt", "1 g Prague powder #1 , (1/8 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Mix meat", "Pack mixture into loaf pan", "Heat sous vide bath", "Bag meat mixture", "Cook sous vide", "Chill", "Unmold and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-spam"}, {"id": 331, "t": "Pastry Cream", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pastry cream—also known as crème pâtissière—is a sweet, stirred custard made with eggs, dairy, sugar, and starch. It’s used for filling tarts, doughnuts, croissants, and you guessed it ... cream puffs. It’s also served all by itself with fresh berries and granola, maybe with a little whipped cream. Pastry cream is versatile, because it sets up into a soft and sliceable gel when chilled. And with a", "i": ["380 g Whole milk", "135 g Heavy cream", "1 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped, pod and seeds reserved separately (see “Before we begin” note)", "85 g Sugar , divided", "35 g Cornstarch", "50 g Egg(s) , (1 large egg)", "30 g Egg yolk(s) , (from 2 large eggs)", "0.5 g Kosher salt , (1/8 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Infuse dairy", "Temper eggs", "Cook custard", "Mix until completely smooth", "Chill pastry cream", "Whip pastry cream for a pipeable consistency"], "tips": ["Don't stop stirring!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pastry-cream"}, {"id": 332, "t": "How to Build the Ultimate Hibachi Grill for Yakitori, Skewers, and Kebabs", "c": "Baking", "d": "Tired of your gas grill’s weak sear? Frustrated by the heat output on your Weber? Annoyed by all your wooden skewers going up in smoke before your kebabs are done? We’ve got a solution to all those problems! Behold: the DIY hibachi grill! If you’ve ever wanted a high-performance, super-high-heat-output, precision grill designed specifically for grilling skewered meats and veggies, look no further.", "i": [], "s": ["Hibachi? A Note on Terminology", "How It’s Made", "How to Make It Yourself", "The Project Rundown", "Direct, Intense Heat", "Made for Skewers", "Control Heat Intensity", "Two- and Three-Zone (!) Grilling Possibilities", "Customization!", "Try it out!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/diy-hibachi-grill-konro"}, {"id": 333, "t": "Tsukune (Yakitori-Style Chicken Meatballs)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Every good yakitori shop takes pride in their tsukune, or chicken meatballs, because they test the limits of a cook’s creativity and ingenuity. You have to transform a humdrum food, often made with scraps, into something extraordinary. Yakitori chefs dial in the proportions of lean and fatty meat to skin and cartilage in order to produce the most texturally interesting meatball they can. Then, the", "i": ["800 g Chicken leg(s) , (2 leg quarters; about 1.8 pounds)", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "2 g Sansho pepper , ground (1 teaspoon)", "35 g Egg yolk(s) , (2 large yolks), plus optional extra 4 large yolks for cured yolk sauce (see “Before we begin” note)", "25 g Panko breadcrumbs", "50 g Sake", "50 g Mirin", "50 g Soy sauce", "10 g Brown sugar", "2.4 g Cornstarch", "10 g Fresh ginger root , cut into 1/8-inch-thick slices", "35 g Scallion(s) , (4 scallions) minced (7% of the chicken weight)", "300 g Chicken bones , from Step 1, optional"], "s": ["Break down chicken legs", "Blend and portion tsukune base", "Start your grill", "Form and skewer tsukune", "Grill bones and scallion for tare (optional)", "Make tare", "Grill tsukune", "Serve"], "tips": ["Kettle grill instructions", "Kettle grill instructions, continued", "Make a cured egg yolk sauce"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tsukune"}, {"id": 334, "t": "Adana Kebab (Turkish Ground Lamb Kebabs)", "c": "Baking", "d": "In Turkey, adana kebabs are a point of national pride. Rightly so, since they’re super delicious: hand-minced lamb, fortified with extra fat, seasoned with fresh sweet red peppers (also hand chopped) and salt, molded onto flat metal skewers, and grilled over oak. Those qualities are all non-negotiable, since adana kebabs are protected by a designation of origin with specific prescriptions for how ", "i": ["35 g Fresno chile(s) , (about 4 peppers) minced", "30 g Clarified butter , room temperature", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (about 4 cloves) finely grated", "14 g Kosher salt , divided", "6 g Lemon zest , freshly grated (from 1 lemon)", "11 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce) , divided", "10 g Sumac , ground, divided", "6 g Urfa biber , ground, divided", "5 g Cumin seeds , ground (1 1/2 teaspoon)", "910 g Ground lamb , (see “Before we begin” note)", "400 g Cherry tomatoes , quartered", "75 g Red onion(s) , (about 1/2 medium onion) cut into 1/8-inch-thick slices", "40 g Lemon juice , fresh (from 1 lemon)", "35 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves (from 1 bunch)", "30 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "5 g Mint , fresh leaves, thinly sliced (from 1/2 bunch)", "1 recipe Lavash , for serving, optional"], "s": ["Mix base seasonings", "Mix kebab mixture", "Portion and chill", "Form kebabs", "Set up grill", "Make the salad", "Grill kebabs", "Rest and serve"], "tips": ["Just using a kettle grill?", "Kettle grill instructions, continued"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/adana-kebabs"}, {"id": 335, "t": "Lavash", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Lavash is a flatbread with history. In 2014, UNESCO added lavash to its “Representative List of the Intangible Cultural Heritage of Humanity,” noting its integral importance to Armenian cuisine. It’s so delicious that it’s also a staple in the neighboring countries of Azerbaijan, Iran, and Turkey. Like other flatbreads, lavash has a short list of ingredients, and its preparation is fundamentally a", "i": ["250 g Water , 85 °F / 29 °C to 90 °F / 32 °C", "2 g Instant dry yeast , (1/2 teaspoon)", "200 g All-purpose flour , unbleached, plus extra as needed", "200 g Whole wheat flour , sifted", "25 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "8 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Mix dough and bulk ferment", "Proof dough", "Divide and portion dough", "Preheat oven and pan", "Roll out flatbread", "Bake", "Serve"], "tips": ["Add your old dough", "Portioning and rolling out flatbread for different pans", "Alternative cooking methods"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/lavash"}, {"id": 336, "t": "Ground and Grilled Skewers: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "Long before the burger, there were kebabs. Once reserved for Ottoman royalty, minced meat, seasoned with salt, spices, and aromatics; kneaded by hand until tacky and sticky; wrapped around lengths of steel or wood; and roasted over a live fire is enjoyed all over the world. It’s a street snack, elevated cuisine, and home-style comfort food all at the same time. There isn’t really all that much to ", "i": [], "s": ["Making a DIY Skewer Grill", "The Infographic", "Chạo Tôm, Andrea Nguyen", "Tsukune, ChefSteps", "Sai Krok Isan, Leela Punyaratabandhu", "Nem Lụi Huế, Vy Tran (Serious Eats)", "Seekh Kebabs Gilafi", "Adana Kebab", "Ćevapi, Slavka Bodic", "Kabab-e Kubideh, Najmieh Batmanglij", "It’s a parametric party over here!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ground-meat-skewers-parametric-analysis"}, {"id": 337, "t": "Essential Grilling Equipment for Yakitori, Kebabs, and Skewers", "c": "Baking", "d": "We take grilling seriously around here. How seriously? Well, we came up with a way to make your own portable, high-precision, super high heat output skewer grill, so ... pretty seriously? Grilling skewers requires just a bit more than setting up your DIY hibachi. You’ll need skewers, of course, but what kind? How many? What about the charcoal? And how are you gonna light it? We’ve put together all", "i": [], "s": ["Quarter Sheet Pans", "Stainless Steel Wire Cooling Racks", "Metal Skewers", "Wooden Skewers", "Pastry Brushes", "Paddle Fan", "Binchotan Charcoal", "Charcoal Chimney Starter", "Got your gear? Grill with it!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/best-grilling-equipment-yakitori-kebabs-and-skewers"}, {"id": 338, "t": "Beef Chow Fun", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "The true test of any Cantonese restaurant is its beef chow fun. It has to be seasoned properly, the beef has to be tender, the noodles need to be slightly chewy, and—above all—it has to have the right amount of wok hei, the smoky, singed quality of properly stir-fried food. This recipe gets you restaurant-caliber beef chow fun at home. The most important part is using fresh, homemade hor fun, sinc", "i": ["226 g Beef top sirloin , or sirloin, tri-tip, flank, or flat iron", "25 g Dark Chinese soy sauce , divided", "20 g Light Chinese soy sauce , divided", "15 g Shaoxing wine , divided", "2 g Cornstarch", "1 g Baking soda", "3 g Toasted sesame oil , divided", "White pepper , ground , as needed", "15 g Oyster sauce", "2 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , or MSG (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Sugar", "210 g Neutral oil , divided", "0.5 recipe Hor Fun Noodles , (see “Before we begin” note)", "85 g Yellow onion(s) , (1/2 large onion) sliced into 1/4- to 1/2-inch-thick pieces", "85 g Scallion(s) , (5 scallions) white and green parts cut into 2-inch sections", "85 g Mung bean sprouts", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 medium cloves) minced"], "s": ["Slice and marinate beef", "Mix sauce", "Cook beef", "Cook noodles", "0.5 recipe", "Cook vegetables", "Finish and season", "Serve"], "tips": ["Bring wok hei indoors with “torch hei”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-chow-fun-gon-chow-ngau-ho"}, {"id": 339, "t": "Hor Fun Noodles", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Hor fun are thin, wide rice noodles that are perfect for stir-frying, and they’re the foundation for one of the most iconic dishes in Cantonese cuisine: Beef Chow Fun. Slightly porous, which makes them excellent at absorbing sauce, they’re also resilient enough to survive a spell in a ripping hot wok while retaining a pleasing chewiness, a perfect example of what Taiwanese call “Q” texture (basica", "i": ["5 g Neutral oil , plus extra as needed", "240 g Rice flour , (see “Before we begin” note)", "80 g Tapioca starch , (see “Before we begin” note)", "500 g Water"], "s": ["Set up steamer and ice bath", "Mix batter", "Test noodle batter", "Cook remaining noodle batter", "Cut noodles"], "tips": ["Check your level", "Use a double-stacked steamer to save time"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hor-fun-noodles"}, {"id": 340, "t": "Hainanese Chicken Rice", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Hainanese chicken rice is just poached chicken and rice, and yet it’s one of the most iconic dishes in the world. It illustrates how a seemingly simple preparation can be refined into a meal that’s a perfect expression of a single ingredient: poached chicken, served with rice that’s been cooked in the poaching broth. The broth is also seasoned and served with the chicken and rice for sipping, alon", "i": ["1 Chicken , whole (1.8 to 2.2 kg; 4 to 5 pounds)", "15 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "20 g Scallion(s) , (2 scallions) smashed and cut into 4-inch pieces, plus extra as needed for serving", "7.1 kg Water , divided", "52 g Neutral oil , divided", "60 g Pandan leaves , (6 leaves) fresh, divided, tied into 2 knots (see “Before we begin” note)", "9 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , or MSG, divided (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g White pepper , ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "28 g Toasted sesame oil", "450 g Jasmine rice", "45 g Fresh red chile(s) , thinly sliced (see “Before we begin” note)", "8 g Sugar", "30 g Calamansi juice , or lime juice (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Light Chinese soy sauce , (1 teaspoon)", "Cucumber(s) , (optional) , as needed", "Purple daikon , (optional) , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems (optional) , as needed", "Kecap manis , (optional) , as needed", "1 recipe Ginger-Scallion Sauce", "20 g Fresh ginger root , (2-inch piece) peeled, smashed and sliced", "20 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 cloves) lightly smashed", "600 g Chicken broth , from Step 7"], "s": ["Scrub chicken with salt", "Season, stuff, and truss chicken", "Blanch chicken", "Make poaching broth", "Poach chicken", "Ice down chicken and finish simmering broth", "Brush and rest chicken", "Cook rice", "Make Chile-Garlic Sauce", "Slice chicken", "Serve"], "tips": ["No rice cooker? No problem!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hainanese-chicken-rice"}, {"id": 341, "t": "Ginger-Scallion Sauce", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Ginger-scallion sauce is delicious on almost anything. Spoon it over rice, toss it with noodles, serve it alongside grilled, roasted, or poached meat, like Hainanese chicken rice—it works with it all! The key to its preparation is sizzling the fresh ingredients and dried spices with smoking hot oil, which “blooms” their flavors, releasing oil-soluble flavors into the sauce. save Print", "i": ["100 g Scallion(s) , (6 scallions) thinly sliced", "50 g Fresh ginger root , (3-inch piece) peeled and minced", "4 g White pepper , ground (2 teaspoons)", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Sand ginger , dried (2 small pieces; see \"Before we begin\" note), finely ground in a spice grinder", "1 g Sugar , (1/4 teaspoon)", "85 g Neutral oil", "10 g Light Chinese soy sauce", "5 g Toasted sesame oil , (1 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Combine ingredients", "Sizzle aromatics", "Let flavors meld, then use"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ginger-scallion-sauce"}, {"id": 342, "t": "Foolproof Sous Vide Eggs Benedict", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Every weekend, all over this great country, brunch spots serve up eggs Benedict by the dozens—all while wrangling byzantine Bloody Mary customizations and tantrum-prone toddlers and lines of hangry hipsters stretching out the door. How do they do it? Simple: timing and technique. And if you tap into the potential of sous vide, you, too, can use timing and technique to make serving up picture-perfe", "i": ["40 g Champagne vinegar", "25 g Shallot(s) , (1 medium shallot) minced", "150 g Unsalted butter", "85 g Egg yolk(s) , (from 5 to 6 large eggs)", "60 g Water", "20 g Lemon juice , fresh, from 1 lemon", "3 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon) plus extra as needed", "12 Egg(s) , large or extra-large, chilled", "6 English muffins , split", "340 g Ham , thinly sliced", "Dill , fresh, finely chopped , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make shallot-vinegar reduction", "Bag up hollandaise and eggs separately", "Cook hollandaise and eggs sous vide", "Toast and top English muffins", "Blend hollandaise", "Crack eggs and assemble", "Top with hollandaise and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/foolproof-sous-vide-eggs-benedict"}, {"id": 343, "t": "Sous Vide Duck Breast With Ultra-Crispy Skin", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Listen, we can all agree that a beautifully cooked duck breast is divine. Crispy skin and blushing pink meat separated by the thinnest layer of juicy fat—what’s not to love? Our favorite way to cook duck breast is by presearing the skin to render subcutaneous fat, then cooking it sous vide to a perfect rosy medium, before searing the skin once more right before serving for a super crispy finish. W", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 2 Duck breast(s) , boneless 3 Thyme , fresh sprigs, optional 2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed - Flake sea salt , for serving, optional , as needed", "2 Duck breast(s) , boneless 3 Thyme , fresh sprigs, optional 2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed - Flake sea salt , for serving, optional , as needed", "3 Thyme , fresh sprigs, optional", "2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "Flake sea salt , for serving, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Score the skin", "Presear duck skin", "Season and bag duck breasts", "Cook duck breasts sous vide", "Sear to crisp skin", "Slice and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-duck-breast-with-ultra-crispy-skin"}, {"id": 344, "t": "Crisp Sous Vide Pickles", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "You probably think of cucumbers when you think of pickles. But as that one Portlandia skit reminds us, cukes are just the beginning. Garlic? You can pickle that! Lychee? You can pickle that! Champagne grapes? You can pickle ... those. A pickle is any food that’s preserved in an acid. You can make pickles with fermentation but that takes more than a hot minute. Another way to pickle is to add vineg", "i": ["Vinegar , 5% acidity, such as white wine or distilled, see Step 3 , as needed", "Water , see Step 3 , as needed", "Sugar , see Step 3 , as needed", "Kosher salt , see Step 3 , as needed", "900 g Fruits or vegetables , see “Before we begin” note", "Spices and aromatics , see “Before we begin” note , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Inspect and clean jars", "Make pickle brine", "Savory pickling brine", "Sweet pickling “brine”", "Prep produce", "Jar up produce", "Cook pickles sous vide", "Cool pickles", "Serve or store pickles"], "tips": ["Sealing jars “fingertip tight” for sous vide cooking"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crisp-sous-vide-pickles"}, {"id": 345, "t": "Butter Burgers", "c": "Sauce", "d": "A better butter burger—say that three times fast! There’s a burger that’s served at Solly’s Grille in Milwaukee that’s so iconic, the James Beard Foundation gave the restaurant one of its America’s Classics Awards. It’s a griddled patty topped with stewed onions and so much butter that the burger comes with its own little melted fat moat of liquid gold. Our take on the iconic burger features two s", "i": ["225 g Unsalted butter , softened, divided", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 medium cloves) crushed", "400 g Sweet onion(s) , (about 2 medium onions) thinly sliced", "10 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra for seasoning burger patties", "10 g Worcestershire sauce", "2 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1 teaspoon)", "200 g Velveeta , room temperature", "910 g Ground beef , 20% fat (see “Before we begin” note)", "5 g Neutral oil , (1 teaspoon)", "8 American cheese , slices, homemade or store-bought", "4 Hamburger bun(s) , lightly toasted", "Yellow mustard, as needed"], "s": ["Stew onions", "Cream butter and Velveeta", "Portion ground beef", "Cook patties", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/butter-burger"}, {"id": 346, "t": "Sous Vide Pork Shoulder Chops", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The problem with cooking pork chops is no matter how well you cook them, they’re still pork chops. Classic loin chops are usually super lean, kind of bland and uninteresting—cooking pork chops perfectly can only take you so far. With sous vide, there’s another way: the pork shoulder chop. A pork shoulder, cooked at a low temperature for more than 16 hours, can be chilled and cut into “chops” that ", "i": ["1.8 kg Pork collar , or boneless pork shoulder", "9 g Kosher salt , (0.5% of total pork weight)", "Neutral oil , for searing , as needed", "28 g Unsalted butter , for basting, optional", "2 Garlic clove(s) , whole, for finishing, optional", "Fresh sage , for finishing, optional , as needed", "Thyme , fresh sprigs, for finishing, optional , as needed", "Rosemary , fresh sprigs, for finishing, optional , as needed", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, for finishing, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Season and bag pork", "Cook pork sous vide", "Chill", "Portion into chops", "Sear chops (or grill or broil them)", "Serve"], "tips": ["For perfect chops, reheat them sous vide"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-sous-vide-pork-shoulder-chops"}, {"id": 347, "t": "Ultimate Steak Frites", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Steak frites is a bistro classic: seared steak with a deeply browned crust and medium-rare (or “bleu”) interior, a towering pile of crispy golden fries, often accompanied by an aromatic sauce that’s just as delicious when doused over the meat as it is when used as a dipper for the spuds. The most iconic steak frites has to be served at Le Relais de Venise L’Entrecôte, a Parisian institution that h", "i": ["900 g Steak(s) , boneless, 1 to 2 inches thick (see “Before we begin” note)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "30 g Neutral oil , divided, plus extra for deep-frying french fries", "268 g Unsalted butter , divided", "2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional", "2 Thyme , fresh sprigs, optional", "90 g Shallot(s) , (3 large shallots) thinly sliced", "1 Lemon , peel and pith removed", "30 g Anchovies , (about 14 fillets)", "30 g Capers , drained, divided", "20 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves and tender stems, divided", "15 g Tarragon , fresh leaves (about 1 bunch), divided", "10 g Worcestershire sauce", "10 g Dijon mustard", "3 g White pepper , ground (1 1/2 teaspoon)", "1 Egg yolk(s)", "1 recipe Ultimate Crispy French Fries , prepared through Step 4 (see “Before we begin” note)"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Measure and season steak", "Presear steak", "Bag steak", "Cook steak sous vide", "Make sauce", "First fry", "Second fry", "Sear steak", "Finish sauce", "Serve"], "tips": ["Choose your own french fry adventure"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-steak-frites"}, {"id": 348, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Steak", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Not all steak cuts are created equal, but they all have their own strengths and weaknesses when it comes to how they perform when cooked—whether you’re pan-searing, cooking sous vide, or gilling in the great outdoors. So, we created this guide to help you become more informed when selecting the best cuts of beef for any occasion. With the help of our ChefSteps Meat Catalog—the world’s most in-dept", "i": [], "s": ["How We Rated These Cuts", "Low on Prep, Big on Taste, and High in Price", "Uncommon but EPIC Steaks", "The Biggest Flavor", "Bistro Cuts", "Best Value—Hands Down", "Big Cuts for Two or More", "Chefs’ Favorites", "Why are some cuts tough while others are tender?", "A great technique for tender cuts"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-guide-to-steak"}, {"id": 349, "t": "A Guide to Presearing for the Best Sous Vide Steaks and Roasts", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "There are several advantages to presearing some foods before cooking them sous vide. Presearing builds flavor; it produces better browning and a more robust crust; it can reduce the possibility of overcooking your perfectly cooked meat after it comes out of the sous vide bath; it can reduce the risk of foodborne contamination; and it makes for better looking food. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Better Flavor", "Better Crust, No Overcooking", "Food Safety", "Better-Looking Food", "Skip Presearing for Lamb", "How to Do It", "Sauces to go with that perfectly cooked meat!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/presearing-for-sous-vide"}, {"id": 350, "t": "Ultimate Crispy French Fries", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Like any proud parent, we love all our french fry recipes equally. Thin-cut, thick-cut, air-fried—each is delicious in its own right; each one has its time to shine. But this french fry recipe ... well, we love it just like the rest, but maybe a little more. Designed to go along with our Ultimate Steak Frites, these fries are the fluffiest of them all, thanks to the fact that they’re not made from", "i": ["1.1 kg Russet potato(es) , (3 to 4 large potatoes) peeled, cut into 1/2-inch pieces", "1 kg Water", "10 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "125 g Cornstarch , plus extra as needed", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed"], "s": ["Cook potatoes", "Pass potatoes and form “dough”", "Shape potato mixture and chill", "Cut and dust fries with cornstarch", "First fry", "Second fry", "Serve"], "tips": ["Frying on the fly? Rapidly chill in an ice bath.", "Cooling fries between ... fries", "Herb and garlic fries!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-crispy-french-fries"}, {"id": 351, "t": "Modernist Sous Vide Meatloaf", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This isn’t your local diner’s meatloaf. We drew on our experience making charcuterie to make a meatloaf recipe that’s completely dialed in. Roasted mushrooms and a red wine-onion jam add complexity to the farce, and the combination of a panade and eggs help to bind moisture and keep it all together. Cooked sous vide, it’s juicy, tender (but not too tender), and perfectly sliceable, every time. It’", "i": ["50 g Sourdough bread , cut into 1-inch cubes", "50 g Whole milk", "250 g Red wine , dry", "190 g Sweet onion(s) , (1 medium onion) cut into 3/4-inch dice", "400 g Cremini mushrooms , quartered", "28 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "17 g Kosher salt , divided", "7 g Black pepper , freshly ground, divided", "300 g Ketchup", "200 g Beef Stock , homemade or store-bought", "150 g Light brown sugar", "25 g Worcestershire sauce", "3 g Paprika , (2 teaspoons)", "1 g Sodium hexametaphosphate , (1/8 teaspoon)", "3 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F , (1 1/2 teaspoon)", "600 g Beef chuck , trimmed and cut into 1-inch cubes", "100 g Egg(s) , (2 large eggs)", "28 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves and tender stems, roughly chopped", "3 g Rosemary , (2 sprigs) fresh leaves, chopped", "Bronze gelatin, 140 bloom , (10 sheets), or 35 g Knox powdered gelatin", "200 g Roasted mushrooms , from Step 3", "100 g Onion Jam , from Step 2", "100 g Panade , from Step 1"], "s": ["Make panade", "Make onion jam", "Roast mushrooms", "Make and set glaze", "Heat sous vide bath", "Grind meat and seasonings", "Roll meatloaf", "Cook meatloaf sous vide", "Shear glaze", "Add gelatin to glaze and cast", "Chill meatloaf", "Roast meatloaf", "Glaze meatloaf", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["A non-modernist glaze"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-sous-vide-meatloaf"}, {"id": 352, "t": "Decoding Tough and Tender Cuts", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "What’s the difference between a brisket and a filet mignon? A pork shank and a pork chop? How about a lamb shoulder and a rack of lamb? In each of these examples, the first cut of meat is “tough” and the second cut of meat is “tender,” and the tender cut commands a higher price per pound than the tough one. Tender cuts are usually cooked hot and fast; these are the cuts that get marquee billing on", "i": [], "s": ["Tough Around the Edges", "Muscle Fibers and “Grain”", "Connective Tissue", "Making Tough Cuts Tender", "Collagen-to-Gelatin Conversion", "Enzymatic Tenderization", "Mechanical Tenderization"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/decoding-tough-and-tender-cuts"}, {"id": 353, "t": "Sous Vide Cottage Cheese", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Everybody grew up with someone—probably older, probably on some kind of diet—who used to do a little jig at lunchtime in anticipation of a platter of fruit salad with two perfect rounds of cottage cheese ice cream–scooped straight out of a huge tub in the fridge. Right? And it never really made sense: Fruit’s fine—we love fruit—but cottage cheese ... whatever it was, it was not good. Thing is, the", "i": ["3.8 kg Whole milk , divided", "0.4 g C201 thermophilic starter culture , (1 packet; 1/4 teaspoon) divided", "0.5 g Liquid vegetable rennet , (8 drops; 1/8 teaspoon) divided", "3 g Kosher salt , plus 0.75% of weight of drained curds and extra as needed", "300 g Half-and-half", "75 g Whey , reserved from Step 6"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Combine milk, starter culture, and rennet", "Culture dairy sous vide", "Cut cheese curds", "Firm up curd sous vide", "Separate curds and whey", "Drain curds", "Chop and season curds", "Finish cottage cheese", "Add toppings and enjoy"], "tips": ["Sealing jars “fingertip tight” for sous vide cooking", "Dry cottage cheese"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-cottage-cheese"}, {"id": 354, "t": "Sous Vide Farmer Cheese", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Farmer cheese, or fromage blanc, is a great entry point for making cheese. It’s super simple to make and gives you hands-on experience with the fundamental process by which all cheeses are made: turning milk into curds and whey. And if you use sous vide to make farmer cheese, it’s even easier to get consistent, deliciously complex results: a soft, smooth, spreadable, and slightly tangy cheese that", "i": ["1.9 kg Whole milk , divided", "0.2 g C101 mesophilic starter culture , (1/2 pack; 1/8 teaspoon) divided", "0.25 g Liquid vegetable rennet , (4 drops; 1/16 teaspoon) divided", "Kosher salt , (1% of weight of drained curds) , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Combine milk, starter culture, and rennet", "Culture dairy sous vide", "Separate curds from whey and let drain", "Rinse curds and drain again", "Season curds", "Pack and enjoy"], "tips": ["Sealing jars “fingertip tight” for sous vide cooking", "Farmer cheese styles"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-farmer-cheese"}, {"id": 355, "t": "Tips & Tricks: The Rave-Worthy Secret to Perfectly Picked Crab", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’ve eaten crab, you’ve eaten crab shell. It’s not pleasant! So how do restaurants and seafood counters churn out crab cakes, crab rolls, and crab Bennies without getting tons of complaints from people about crab shells messing up their meals? Easy: They buy shell–free crab meat picked by commercial processors. But how do the commercial processors get shells out of their crab meat? They make ", "i": [], "s": ["How to Do It", "Why It Works", "Frequently Asked Questions"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-tricks-all-crab-meat-no-shells"}, {"id": 356, "t": "Sous Vide Burgers", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Picture this: It’s the first barbecue of the summer, and you’ve got guests gulping beers in the backyard. And then there’s you: You’re an hour in and still stuck behind the grill, sweating beneath your novelty apron, flipping burgers a few at a time and worrying about who is getting fed and who isn’t. We love grilling as much as anyone, but if you’re manning the Weber, you’re missing the party. Th", "i": ["800 g Beef , coarsely ground (4.5 mm die), 20% fat (see “Before we begin” note)", "30 g Egg yolk(s) , (2 large yolks)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "15 g Neutral oil", "American cheese , homemade or store-bought, optional , as needed", "4 Hamburger bun(s) , homemade or store-bought, lightly toasted", "Ketchup, as needed", "Yellow mustard , optional , as needed", "Mayonnaise , optional , as needed", "Lettuce , shredded or whole leaves, optional , as needed", "Tomato(es) , sliced, optional , as needed", "Dill Pickle Chips , or store-bought, optional , as needed", "15 g Neutral oil - American cheese , homemade or store-bought, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Mix ground beef and egg", "Portion, form, and chill patties", "Season and bag patties", "Cook burgers sous vide", "Cool and dry patties", "Sear or grill burgers", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": ["No ring mold, no problem"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-burgers"}, {"id": 357, "t": "Foolproof Sous Vide Fried Chicken", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Fried chicken: Everybody loves it, but no one loves making it—until now. This fried chicken is delicious, and it’s nearly impossible to f* up. This technique is almost foolproof thanks to sous vide: We cook the chicken in a temperature-controlled water bath so it’s well-seasoned and perfectly cooked and juicy—both the dark meat and the white meat. Coated with buttermilk, flour, and our blend of no", "i": ["1.8 kg Chicken , whole or pieces (drumsticks, bone-in thighs, boneless skin-on breasts)", "28 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "450 g All-purpose flour", "100 g Cornstarch", "10 g Baking soda", "10 g Not-So-Secret 12 Herbs & Spices Fried Chicken Seasoning , (see “Before we begin” note)", "500 g Buttermilk", "Neutral oil , for deep-frying , as needed", "15 g Paprika", "15 g Onion powder", "3 g Garlic powder", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Break down chicken (optional)", "Season and bag chicken", "Cook dark meat sous vide", "Add white meat and finish cooking chicken", "Set up dredging station", "Dredge chicken", "Fry chicken", "Dig in!"], "tips": ["Level up the seasoning with our not-so-secret spice blend", "Want a simpler seasoned dredge? Here's the original formula", "Skip the double dredge for a thin and crispy coating"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/foolproof-sous-vide-fried-chicken"}, {"id": 358, "t": "Ultimate Sous Vide Leg of Lamb", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Impossibly tender, exquisitely seasoned, and showered with bright-green herbs and crunchy seeds, this sous vide leg of lamb is a showstopper for any special occasion. A whole, bone-in leg of lamb is a pricey hunk of meat that can be tricky to cook it using conventional methods, because it’s irregularly shaped and has a big insulating bone running right through its center. It’s a roast that seems d", "i": ["1 Leg of lamb , whole (about 4.3 kg; 9.5 pounds)", "80 g Mustard powder", "15 g Kosher salt", "10 g Black pepper , freshly ground", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "50 g Mint , fresh leaves, about 2 handfuls", "65 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves, about 2 handfuls", "9 g Rosemary , fresh leaves, picked, from 2 sprigs", "30 g Yellow mustard seeds , whole", "30 g Caraway seeds , whole", "500 ml Balsamic vinegar", "Frying oil, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Prep, trim, and score lamb leg", "Make spice rub", "Rub and bag lamb leg", "Cook lamb sous vide", "Fry herbs and seeds", "French lamb leg and strain cooking liquid", "Make glaze", "Finish lamb in oven", "Glaze and garnish", "Serve"], "tips": ["Cover for long cooks"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-sous-vide-leg-of-lamb"}, {"id": 359, "t": "Bomb Sous Vide Braised Short Ribs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Braised beef short ribs are undeniably good: Fork-tender with big, beefy flavor, the only real drawback is ... well, there are no drawbacks. Braised beef short ribs are just amazing. Short ribs cooked sous vide, however, are even better. You can take advantage of the precise temperature control sous vide affords to produce textures that aren’t possible with conventional cooking methods. And the co", "i": ["1.5 kg Beef short ribs , bone-in (3.3 pounds)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "15 g Neutral oil", "400 g Onion(s) , (1 large onion) cut into small dice", "140 g Celery , (3 stalks) cut into small dice", "140 g Carrot(s) , (1 large carrot) peeled and cut into small dice", "2 Garlic clove(s) , finely chopped", "45 g Tomato paste", "0.2 g Red pepper flakes , (1 teaspoon)", "250 g Red wine , dry", "45 g Demi-glace , homemade or store-bought (see “Before we begin” note)", "Chives , thinly sliced, for garnish (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Season and sear short ribs", "Sweat vegetables and make braise base", "Bag short ribs", "Cook short ribs sous vide", "Serve those shorties!"], "tips": ["No vacuum-seal bags? Double-bag it.", "Cover for long cooks"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bomb-sous-vide-braised-short-ribs"}, {"id": 360, "t": "Perfect Sous Vide Poached Eggs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "There are few things lovelier than a perfectly poached egg. Making a poached egg—a fundamental technique that can frustrate even the finest cooks—became infinitely easier, and perhaps even foolproof, with the rise of sous vide cooking. There aren’t any debates over whether to stir the water (or add vinegar to it) , how to drop the egg into the pot, or how to remove it. Now, all we need to do to en", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Egg(s) , large or extra-large, chilled (see “Before we begin”) , as needed", "Egg(s) , large or extra-large, chilled (see “Before we begin”) , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Cook eggs sous vide", "Cool or completely chill eggs", "Crack and serve"], "tips": ["Bag your eggs if cooking for a crowd"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/perfect-sous-vide-poached-eggs"}, {"id": 361, "t": "Sous Vide Filet Mignon", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "A steak so tender that tender is in its name, the tenderloin steak—or filet mignon—is the definition of luxury. So buttery and soft you can cut it with a spoon, a filet mignon’s mild beefy flavor is designed to be complemented by a rich sauce, like a red wine sauce or an au poivre. Unfortunately, the heights of luxury command a dizzying price point, and the last thing you want to do with a beautif", "i": ["2 Filet mignon(s) , center-cut, 1 to 2 inches thick", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "60 g Neutral oil , divided", "2 Thyme , fresh sprigs, or rosemary, optional", "2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional", "1 Bay leaf , fresh, optional", "28 g Unsalted butter , for basting, optional", "Flake sea salt , for finishing, optional , as needed", "30 g Neutral oil 2 Thyme , fresh sprigs, or rosemary, optional 2 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional 1 Bay leaf , fresh, optional"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Measure and season steaks", "Presear steaks (optional)", "Bag steaks", "Cook steaks sous vide", "Sear steaks", "Plate and serve!", "Sides for that steak", "Sauce on the side", "Steak knowledge"], "tips": ["Salt and meat texture"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-filet-mignon"}, {"id": 362, "t": "Sous Vide Steak", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Steak, man. There’s nothing like it. And the best way to cook a steak, bar none, is to cook it sous vide. Sous vide steak means perfectly cooked steak, every single time. No need to worry about “ruining” a pricey dry-aged ribeye; no need to babysit or fuss over your beef to cook it just right. Seal the steak in a bag, drop it in a precisely calibrated temperature-controlled bath, and all you have ", "i": ["2 Steak(s) , boneless, preferably 1 to 2 inches thick", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "60 g Neutral oil , divided", "2 Thyme , fresh sprigs, optional", "1 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional", "1 Bay leaf , fresh, optional", "28 g Unsalted butter , for basting, optional", "Flake sea salt , such as Maldon, for finishing, optional , as needed", "30 g Neutral oil 2 Thyme , fresh sprigs, or rosemary, optional 1 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional 1 Bay leaf , fresh, optional"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Measure and season steaks", "Presear steaks (optional)", "Bag steaks", "Cook steaks sous vide", "Sear steaks", "Slice and serve", "Five ways to finish a sous vide steak", "Sear it", "Broil it", "Flour and sear it", "Grill it", "Deep-fry it (yes, really)", "Know your steak cuts", "Where’s the beef?", "Get saucy", "Want some sides with that steak? Yeah, you do."], "tips": ["Salt and meat texture"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-steak"}, {"id": 363, "t": "Sous Vide Chicken Breast", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "How do you cook chicken breasts that are juicy, well-seasoned, and have a perfectly browned and crisped cap of skin? Easy: Cook them sous vide. Chicken breasts have a bad reputation: They’re dry; they’re bland; they’re the protein of choice for the elderly, the infirm, and people who meal prep on Sundays. They’re protein as medicine, for those with sensitive stomachs or insensate tongues. They’re ", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 2 Chicken breast(s) , (see “Before we begin” note) - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , freshly ground, optional , as needed 45 g Neutral oil , divided", "2 Chicken breast(s) , (see “Before we begin” note) - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , freshly ground, optional , as needed 45 g Neutral oil , divided", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground, optional , as needed", "45 g Neutral oil , divided"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Season and bag chicken", "Cook chicken sous vide", "Sear chicken breasts", "Slice and serve", "Serve that bird with some ..."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-chicken-breast"}, {"id": 364, "t": "Sous Vide Pork Chops", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Is a perfectly cooked pork chop even possible? Yes, thanks to sous vide. A lot of home cooks are afraid of pork, which is understandable. For decades, there was a mass misconception that even a blush of pink in a cooked pork chop meant the meat was almost certainly lethal. Fear of undercooking led to a profusion of unappetizing, overdone chops. Either the other white meat was going to kill you or ", "i": ["2 Pork chop(s) , boneless, 1 to 2 inches thick", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "45 g Neutral oil , divided", "2 Rosemary , fresh sprigs, or thyme or oregano, optional", "1 Garlic clove(s) , lightly crushed, optional", "28 g Unsalted butter , for basting, optional", "Flake sea salt , for finishing, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Season and bag pork chops", "Cook pork chops sous vide", "Sear chops", "Serve", "Make it a meal"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-pork-chops"}, {"id": 365, "t": "Sous Vide Salmon", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Salmon is Seattle’s spirit food—it’s impossible to live here and not be obsessed with this pink-fleshed, flavor-packed fish. Hearty yet delicate, a lovingly prepared salmon fillet always feels like something special, even in the Pacific Northwest, where it’s considered everyday eating. Unfortunately, salmon, like all fish, is easy to overcook using conventional cooking methods. Cook salmon sous vi", "i": ["2 Salmon fillet(s) , skin-on, preferably 1 to 1 1/2 inches thick", "20 g Kosher salt , optional, plus extra as needed", "5 g Sugar , optional", "45 g Neutral oil , divided", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "30 g Neutral oil - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Score skin (optional)", "Dry-cure salmon fillets (optional)", "Bag fillets", "Cook salmon sous vide", "Sear skin", "Serve", "Get inspired: Create an easy, elegant dish"], "tips": ["No nonstick? No problem. Use parchment for perfect crispy fish skin"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-salmon"}, {"id": 366, "t": "Sous Vide Crème Brûlée", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The key to perfect crème brûlée—and all custards, really—is to keep the internal temperature of the mixture below 185 °F / 85 °C. Above that point, they have a tendency to curdle (and they start tasting super eggy). By cooking crème brûlée in a sous vide bath, we can precisely control the cooking temperature, eliminating the risk of a curdled dessert. Prepped in small, wide-mouth mason jars, these", "i": ["160 g Egg yolk(s) , (about 11 large yolks)", "0.6 g Vanilla bean seed , (from 1 pod)", "90 g Sugar , plus extra for dusting", "3 g Kosher salt", "600 g Heavy cream"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Whisk and strain custard base", "Portion custard", "Cook custard sous vide", "Cool custards", "Brûler that crème", "Make ahead and storage"], "tips": ["Sealing jars “fingertip tight” for sous vide cooking"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-creme-brulee"}, {"id": 367, "t": "Ultimate Cheese Quiche", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is the ultimate cheese quiche recipe: a super silky and smooth custard perfectly set in the crispiest and most delicious pie crust you’ve ever had. Unlike a lot of the fillings-topped-with-eggs-in-a-pie-crust quiches out there, this one is all about nailing the cooking technique to produce the best possible version of a quiche. There’s just a handful of ingredients, treated correctly, cooked ", "i": ["1 recipe Perfect Pie Dough , (see “Before we begin” note)", "400 g Whole milk", "170 g Velveeta , cut into 1-inch cubes", "125 g Heavy cream", "6 g Kosher salt", "0.7 g White pepper , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "100 g Gruyère cheese , shredded", "600 g Egg(s) , (12 large eggs)"], "s": ["Blind-bake pie crust", "Melt cheese into dairy", "Finish custard base", "Fill pie crust and bake quiche", "Trim crust and serve"], "tips": ["Calculating the perfect amount of pie weights", "The secret to velvety smooth quiche custard? Velveeta", "Same quiche base, no cheese", "Carryover cooking and custards", "No fillings, no problem"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-quiche"}, {"id": 368, "t": "Big Macau Egg Tart", "c": "Baking", "d": "The Chinese egg tart is a staple of any Chinatown bakery: Individual servings of silky sweet, bright yellow custard encased in super flaky puff pastry. But what about a big version? An egg tart you can whip up for a potluck and share? Chefs like Brandon Jew of San Francisco’s Mister Jiu’s and Jonathan Tam of Copenhagen’s JATAK have offered their own riffs on the big egg tart, each of them celebrat", "i": ["360 g All-purpose flour , unbleached, divided, plus more for dusting", "170 g Unsalted European-style butter , chilled and cut into 12 pieces, plus more softened butter for greasing tart ring", "56 g Vegetable shortening , or lard", "90 g Water , chilled", "75 g Egg yolk(s) , (5 large yolks) divided", "212 g Sugar , divided", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon) divided", "530 g Whole milk", "1 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped (see “Before we begin”)", "27 g Custard powder , (see “Before we begin”)", "8 g Cornstarch", "175 g Heavy cream", "55 g Egg , (1 large egg)"], "s": ["Make “oil dough”", "Make flour dough", "“Lock in” oil dough", "Make first “book fold”", "Make second “book fold”", "Make final “book fold”", "Roll and shape dough", "Steep milk for custard", "Whisk egg mixture for custard", "Finish custard", "Bake tart", "Cool, slice, and serve"], "tips": ["Unlocking Chinese puff pastry", "For straight sides, use a straight edge"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/big-macau-egg-tart"}, {"id": 369, "t": "Dungeness Crab Chawanmushi", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This recipe captures all the flavors of Dungeness crab—the sweet flesh, the toasted, nutty notes of roasted shells, and the oceanic buttery flavor of its tomalley—by infusing crab shells into a delicious broth and using it to make a silky-smooth, savory custard, which is topped with a light and bright picked crab meat salad. Every part of the process is designed to yield the best crab flavor. The ", "i": ["1 Dungeness crab , whole, preferably live", "150 g Egg(s) , (3 large eggs)", "500 g Sous Vide Dashi", "15 g Mirin", "10 g White soy sauce", "1.5 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "100 g Asian pear , (1/2 pear) peeled and cored, cut into 1/4-inch dice", "30 g Lime juice , fresh, from 1 lime", "30 g Jalapeño(s) , (1/2 pepper) stemmed, seeded, white pith removed, cut into 1/8-inch dice", "20 g Roasted peanuts , salted, coarsely chopped", "15 g Ponzu , preferably Suehiro ponzu", "5 g Sugar , (1 teaspoon)", "8 g Cilantro , stems, finely chopped"], "s": ["Cook, clean, and pick crab", "Roast crab shells", "Make crab dashi", "Heat sous vide bath", "Whisk and strain custard base", "Cast into jars and seal", "Cook custards sous vide", "Chill chawanmushi", "Prepare salad and serve"], "tips": ["Sealing jars “fingertip tight” for sous vide cooking"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crab-chawanmushi"}, {"id": 370, "t": "Sous Vide Chawanmushi", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This silky-smooth steamed custard is perfect for waking up the palate at the beginning of a meal. Unlike other custards that have a lot of added sugar and dairy, chawanmushi is mostly eggs and dashi, an umami-packed and slightly smoky Japanese soup stock made with dried seafood. A little soy sauce and mirin season the custard—soy sauce for salinity and a big boost of glutamates, and mirin for its ", "i": ["150 g Egg(s) , (3 large eggs)", "475 g Sous Vide Dashi , divided", "20 g Mirin , divided", "15 g White soy sauce , divided", "1.5 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "120 g King oyster mushrooms , ends trimmed, cut into 1/8-inch dice", "5 g Ponzu , preferably Suehiro ponzu"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Whisk and strain custard base", "Cast into jars and seal", "Cook chawanmushi sous vide", "Prepare mushroom topping", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": ["Sealing jars “fingertip tight” for sous vide cooking"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-chawanmushi"}, {"id": 371, "t": "Eggsamining Custards: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "What is a custard? Well, it’s complicated! Technically speaking, a custard is a liquid that has been thickened or set via the coagulation of egg protein. And while the ingredient lists for different custards might look super similar, small differences in ingredient ratios and preparation can yield wildly different results. Mix eggs, dairy, and sugar together and heat them up gently, and you can ma", "i": [], "s": ["The Parametric", "The Custard Contenders", "Crème Anglaise", "Hollandaise", "Lemon Curd", "Pastry Cream", "Chawanmushi", "Crème Brûlée, Flan, Pot de Crème", "Macau Egg Tart", "Quiche", "Check out our other parametric analyses!"], "tips": ["All About Eggs"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/custard-parametric-analysis"}, {"id": 372, "t": "Unpacking Freshness: The Egg Carton Decoder", "c": "Baking", "d": "The ChefSteps Egg Carton Decoder Plant code Pack date Decode Plant code is the location where your eggs were packed, sometimes preceded by a “P”. Pack date is the day of the year the eggs were packed. Look for a 3-digit number from 001 to 365. When you look at the rows and rows of USDA-graded egg cartons at the grocery store, the first thing you’ll notice is there’s a lot of stuff on them. It’s te", "i": [], "s": ["Why is the Julian date more useful than an expiration date?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/egg-carton-decoder"}, {"id": 373, "t": "The Ultimate Katsu Egg Salad Sando", "c": "Baking", "d": "Katsu meets egg salad in this ultimate mash-up. You’ve maybe never heard “ultimate” and “egg salad” in the same sentence. But we’re sure that once you try this sandwich—where the texture of a katsu sandwich and the flavor of egg salad collide—you’ll totally agree. Imagine the perfect egg salad sandwich. Tender white bread loaded with a mixture of chopped hard-boiled eggs, creamy mayo, tangy Dijon ", "i": ["600 g Egg(s) , (12 large eggs), divided", "165 g Whole milk", "80 g Heavy cream", "10 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "15 g Distilled vinegar", "15 g Sugar", "75 g Celery , (2 ribs) sliced 1/8-inch-thick", "40 g Shallot(s) , (1 large shallot) sliced 1/8-inch-thick", "25 g Whole grain mustard", "130 g Panko breadcrumbs", "120 g All-purpose flour", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed", "0.5 recipe Not-So-Secret 12 Herbs & Spices Fried Chicken Seasoning , optional", "1 recipe Shokupan (Japanese Milk Bread) , or 1 loaf store-bought white sandwich bread", "28 g Unsalted butter , divided", "Bibb lettuce , leaves, thinly sliced , as needed", "Japanese (Kewpie-Style) Mayo , homemade or store-bought , as needed", "Dijon mustard, as needed"], "s": ["Whisk and rest eggs", "Prepare molds and bake custard", "Slice and mix relish", "Set up breading station", "Unmold and slice egg patties", "Bread patties", "Fry patties", "0.5 recipe", "Toast bread on one side (optional)", "Assemble sandwiches"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-egg-salad-sando"}, {"id": 374, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Dungeness Crab", "c": "Baking", "d": "Cracking Dungeness crabs can be a deliciously messy business. But it doesn’t have to be! The team at ChefSteps has tons of experience with these critters. We’re based in Seattle, which is famous for its crab, and we’ve shopped for, cleaned, cooked, cracked, and picked countless crabs both at home and in restaurant kitchens. We’ve pooled our collective knowledge about all things Dungeness crab and ", "i": [], "s": ["What Is Dungeness Crab?", "How to Shop for Dungeness Crab", "The Best Ways to Kill, Clean, and Cook Live Dungeness Crab", "How to Clean and Par-Cook Dungeness Crab for Stir-Fries", "Step 1: Open crab and remove innards", "Step 2: Separate into leg clusters", "Step 3: Blanch crab pieces", "How to Clean and Cook Dungeness Crab", "Step 1: Separate crab into individual parts", "Step 2: Boil crab parts in stages", "How to Thaw Previously Cooked and Frozen Dungeness Crab", "How to Reheat Cooked, Shell-On Dungeness Crab", "How to Pick Crab Meat", "Step 1: Remove top shell", "Step 2: Break down legs", "Step 3: Break down claws", "Step 4: Pick body meat", "Step 5: Look over picked meat to remove any shell pieces", "Why You Should Save Crab Shells and Guts", "How to Serve Cooked Dungeness Crab", "How to Store Dungeness Crab", "Essential Equipment and Tools", "Do something amazing with your crab!"], "tips": ["Why crabs should be cooked while alive (or just after being killed)", "How to boil a whole crab", "Serving leg and claw clusters? Prep them for easy eating.", "Is eating crab innards safe?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dungeness-crab-guide"}, {"id": 375, "t": "Dungeness Crab Fra Diavolo", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "There are basically two kinds of crab pasta dishes. There’s the one that a lot of restaurants love to put out, because it’s easy and cost effective: a pasta dish—it almost doesn’t matter what kind—topped with a bit of picked crab meat. And then there’s the one we want to eat: a pasta that’s packed with crab flavor, where each strand of spaghetti is both infused and coated with a super crabby sauce", "i": ["1 Dungeness crab , whole, preferably live", "84 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided", "30 g Tomato paste , divided", "335 g White wine , dry", "350 g Sweet onion(s) , (1 large onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice, scraps reserved, divided", "350 g Fennel , (1 large bulb) cored and cut into 1/4-inch dice, scraps reserved, divided", "200 g Celery , (3 ribs) cut into 1/4-inch dice, scraps reserved, divided", "20 g Garlic clove(s) , (6 cloves) cut in half", "4 g Black peppercorns , whole", "400 g Whole canned tomatoes , (14-ounce can)", "1.4 kg Water", "2 g Red pepper flakes , (1 teaspoon)", "250 g Spaghetti , dried", "Kosher salt, as needed", "28 g Basil , fresh leaves, chopped", "Lemon juice , fresh, from 1/2 lemon , as needed"], "s": ["Cook, clean, and pick crab", "Roast crab shells", "Make crab stock", "Sweat soffritto", "Cook pasta in crab stock", "Finish and serve pasta"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dungeness-crab-pasta"}, {"id": 376, "t": "Dungeness Crab Sloppy Joes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Going to town on a whole, cooked Dungeness crab with nothing more than your hands and a tub of clarified butter is a perfectly acceptable way to eat the delicious critter, but it’s not the only way. If you want to use the full flavor potential of a single crab to produce an elegantly crab-tastic meal, this supercharged crab sloppy joe is for you. Wait, sloppy joes? Well, sort of, but fancy-like. I", "i": ["1 Dungeness crab , preferably live", "505 g Unsalted butter , divided", "30 g Tomato paste", "5 g Fennel seeds , whole", "2 g Black peppercorns , whole", "135 g Whole milk , divided", "1.1 kg Water , divided", "20 g Mochiko sweet rice flour", "50 g Egg(s) , (1 large)", "13 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "5 g Instant dry yeast , (1/4 teaspoon)", "315 g Bread flour , unbleached, plus extra for dusting", "40 g Sugar", "10 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "28 g New Bay Seasoning Blend , or Old Bay Seasoning", "15 g Lemon juice , fresh, from 1/2 lemon, plus extra as needed", "15 g Flat-leaf parsley , fresh leaves and tender stems, finely chopped (1 1/2 cups fresh leaves)"], "s": ["Cook, clean, and pick crab", "Roast crab shells and tomalley", "Make crab butter", "Start milk bread rolls (gelatinize rice flour)", "Mix dough", "Incorporate butter into dough", "Divide and portion dough", "Heat and strain crab butter", "Pan and proof rolls", "Make soup while rolls proof", "Bake rolls", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crab-rolls"}, {"id": 377, "t": "Spicy Sizzling Yuba Salad", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "If you’ve been looking to add some sizzle, spice, and table-side theatrics to your salad game (because why should chain restaurant fajitas get all the glory?), then this dish is for you. This salad takes advantage of the textural marvels of yuba, balancing tender-chewy blanched tofu skin “noodles” with crunchy fried puffed yuba chips that get seasoned with a Yunnan-inspired dipping chile powder, s", "i": ["100 g Dried yuba , homemade or store-bought, divided", "2 g Cumin seeds , whole, toasted (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 g Fennel seeds , whole, toasted (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Sichuan peppercorns , whole, toasted (1 teaspoon)", "1 Bay leaf , dried, toasted", "1 Black cardamom , pod, toasted", "1 Star anise , pod, toasted", "1 g Sand ginger , (2 pieces) toasted (see “Before we begin” note)", "1 g Dried mandarin peel(s) , (1/2-inch piece) (see “Before we begin” note)", "10 g Sesame seeds , toasted", "14 g Sichuan chile powder", "3 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon) plus more as needed", "3 g Totole chicken bouillon powder , (1 teaspoon) (see “Before we begin” note)", "2 g Sugar , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1 g Cinnamon , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "100 g Neutral oil , divided, plus extra as needed", "10 g Light Chinese soy sauce", "5 g Toasted sesame oil , (1 teaspoon)", "30 g Large Chinese scallion(s) , or regular scallions, white parts only, thinly sliced lengthwise (see “Before we begin” note)", "10 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems, cut into 2-inch pieces", "12 g Dipping chile powder , from Step 4"], "s": ["Soak yuba", "Grind toasted spices", "Grind toasted sesame seeds", "Finish pounding dipping chile powder", "Drain, cut, and blanch soaked yuba", "Fry dried yuba", "Assemble salad", "Sizzle salad, mix and serve"], "tips": ["Toast your spices"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sizzling-yuba-salad"}, {"id": 378, "t": "How to Make Fresh Yuba", "c": "Baking", "d": "Yuba—aka fu pei, tofu skin, or bean curd skin—is the foundation of several classic dishes throughout Asia, from Cantonese dim sum like fried bean curd skin rolls to the more elemental presentations of Japanese Buddhist cooking, like yuba braised in dashi. Yuba can be eaten fresh, fried, boiled, and even dried. The process for making yuba is relatively straightforward but requires a lot of techniqu", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 220 g Dried soybeans , non-GMO (see “Before we begin” note) 1.9 kg Water , plus more for soaking beans, divided", "220 g Dried soybeans , non-GMO (see “Before we begin” note) 1.9 kg Water , plus more for soaking beans, divided", "1.9 kg Water , plus more for soaking beans, divided"], "s": ["Soak soybeans", "Blend soybeans", "Strain and dilute soy milk", "Heat soy milk to form yuba", "Skim and hang yuba", "Repeat skimming process", "Dry yuba sheets completely (or eat them right away)"], "tips": ["Using a blowtorch to get rid of pesky air bubbles", "Hanging yuba out to dry"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-yuba-tofu-skin"}, {"id": 379, "t": "How to Make the Ultimate Bánh Mì", "c": "Baking", "d": "A well-made bánh mì is a thing of beauty: a light roll with a crisp crust and tender, slightly chewy crumb that pulls apart like cotton candy. Smear it with mayo and pâté, stuff it with savory meats, tart and funky pickles, fresh herbs and chiles, and anointed with a couple dashes of Maggi Seasoning, and you’ve got yourself one of the best sandwiches in the world. The amount of technique required ", "i": ["250 g Pork Liver Pâté", "1 recipe Xíu Mại (Vietnamese Meatballs)", "1 recipe Bánh Mì Bread", "30 g Unsalted butter , melted", "1 English cucumber(s) , halved lengthwise, seeded, and cut into 4-inch by 1/4-inch matchsticks", "0.5 recipe Đồ Chua (Vietnamese Pickled Daikon and Carrots) , drained", "3 Jalapeño(s) , stemmed and thinly sliced into rounds", "50 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems (2 bunches), cut into 2-inch sections", "15 g Mint , fresh leaves (optional)", "Mayonnaise, as needed", "Maggi Seasoning, as needed", "1 recipe Bánh Mì Bread 30 g Unsalted butter , melted", "50 g Cilantro leaves and tender stems , (2 bunches) cut into 2-inch sections"], "s": ["Mix and temper pork liver pâté", "Preheat oven", "Reheat xíu mại", "Toast bread", "Assemble", "0.5 recipe"], "tips": ["Crush xíu mại to get the perfect bánh mì bite"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-banh-mi"}, {"id": 380, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Grilled Cheese Sandwiches", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is not a recipe for a grilled cheese. Who needs that, right? Everyone knows how to make a grilled cheese sandwich: Slap some slices of cheese between two pieces of bread and griddle that thing in a pan with a bunch of butter until the cheese melts and the bread is golden brown and delicious. Easy. So easy, in fact, that it’s the first thing a lot of us learned how to cook on our own as kids. ", "i": [], "s": ["“Classic” vs. “Artisanal” Grilled Cheese", "The Ultimate Grilled Cheese, Defined", "Leveling Up the Bread: Shokupan", "Leveling Up the Cheese: Better Kraft Singles", "How to Cook the Ultimate Grilled Cheese", "Check out our other sandwiches!"], "tips": ["Yudane, Tangzhong, and Autolyse", "Melting ... Salts?", "Getting the Picture-Perfect Cheese Pull"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-the-ultimate-grilled-cheese-sandwich-at-home"}, {"id": 381, "t": "Shokupan (Japanese Milk Bread)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "To make the fluffiest, softest white bread with the wispiest crumb, perfect for sandwiches and oversized slabs of buttery toast, you have to pre-gelatinize some starch. Pre-gelatinizing the starches in a portion of the flour in a dough recipe increases the amount of water you can incorporate into the dough. This affects dough handling—it’s easier!—and will increase its rise; all that water turns t", "i": ["55 g Water", "135 g Whole milk , divided", "20 g Mochiko sweet rice flour", "50 g Large egg(s) , (1 egg)", "13 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "5 g Instant dry yeast , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "315 g Bread flour , unbleached", "40 g Sugar", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "50 g Unsalted butter , softened"], "s": ["Gelatinize rice flour", "Mix dough", "Incorporate butter into dough", "Proof dough", "Divide and shape dough", "Final proof", "Bake loaf", "Cool"], "tips": ["Tangzhong is the key to unlocking amazing texture and shelf stability.", "Upgrade: Double the milk powder, double the flavor", "Proofing options", "Don’t pop your top"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/shokupan-japanese-milk-bread"}, {"id": 382, "t": "Melty Cheese Slices", "c": "Baking", "d": "Many American childhood involves processed cheese—there’s just something about a warm grilled cheese filled with gooey, melty Kraft American or a big bowl of creamy Velveeta Shells & Cheese that appeals to kids’ tastebuds. As adults, we still crave the comforting texture and unctuousness of processed cheese, but most of us also crave cheese that’s a little more nuanced in flavor—the nutty, earthy ", "i": ["400 g Sharp yellow cheddar cheese , such as Tillamook, cut into 1-inch cubes", "160 g Whole milk", "12 g Sodium citrate", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Sodium hexametaphosphate , (1/8 teaspoon)", "400 g Swiss cheese , cut into 1-inch cubes", "400 g Gruyère cheese , cut into 1-inch cubes", "6 g Salt", "400 g Blue cheese , such as Stilton, crumbled into 1-inch pieces", "40 g Sodium caseinate", "450 g Chèvre", "80 g Goat milk , or whole milk", "200 g Parmigiano-Reggiano , cut into 1-inch cubes", "260 g Fresh mozzarella , (about 2 balls) cut into 1-inch cubes", "300 g Fresh ricotta , drained", "180 g Fresh white cheddar curds , or low-moisture mozzarella", "200 g Cabot Clothbound Cheddar , cut into 1-inch pieces", "250 g Low-moisture mozzarella , cut into 1-inch cubes", "200 g Aged Gouda , cut into 1-inch pieces", "400 g Manchego , or tomme-style cheese, cut into 1-inch pieces"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Combine ingredients", "Heat cheese mixture", "Blend, cast, and chill", "Slice and use", "Other cheeses", "Swiss (Emmentaler)", "Gruyère", "Blue cheese", "Chèvre", "Parmigiano-Reggiano", "Ricotta", "Clothbound cheddar (Cabot)", "Aged Gouda (L'Amuse)", "Manchego/Tomme"], "tips": ["Troubleshooting blending", "White American cheese", "For G.O.A.T. flavor, level it up with a bloomy rind goat cheese", "Triple cream–style Parmesan"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/melty-cheese-slices"}, {"id": 383, "t": "Krafting Melty Cheese Perfection: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "Years ago, we explored the possibilities of transforming different kinds of cheeses with so-called “melting salts.” The idea was to give you the tools to make super flavorful versions of American cheese slices. We decided to revisit the project, using the experience and knowledge we’ve gained in the meantime, guided by your attempts (and the questions you had). And since all of our melty cheese va", "i": [], "s": ["Ricotta", "Chèvre", "Blue (Stilton)", "Leveled-Up American Cheese", "Swiss (Emmentaler)", "Manchego/Tomme", "Gruyère", "Aged Gouda", "Clothbound Cheddar (Cabot)", "Parmigiano-Reggiano", "Cheeses That Didn’t Make the Cut", "Check out our other parametrics!"], "tips": ["Melty Cheese Science"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/melty-cheese-parametric-analysis"}, {"id": 384, "t": "Ultimate McRib", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "It’s back! Or, wait … is it gone? I don’t know, and you don’t either. No one ever knows if you can get a McRib at McDonald’s at any moment in time. Since you can never trust that it’ll be there when you crave it, we made our own version of the pork patty shaped like a mini rack of ribs, slathered in barbecue sauce and nestled in a soft bun with tart pickles and raw onions. Of course, made with our", "i": ["1 kg Ground pork", "30 g Sweet and Spicy Kansas City Barbecue Rub", "15 g Light brown sugar", "2.5 g Prague powder #1 , (1/2 teaspoon) optional", "28 g Canola oil , divided", "2 recipes Kansas City-Style Barbecue Sauce", "1 recipe Milk Bread Sandwich Rolls , or store-bought rolls, split and lightly toasted", "0.5 recipe Dill Pickle Chips , or store-bought dill pickle chips", "150 g White onion(s) , (1/2 large onion) thinly sliced"], "s": ["Mix meat", "Bag and chill pork mixture", "Cook pork sous vide", "Sear and sauce patties", "Assemble and serve", "0.5 recipe"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/homemade-mcrib"}, {"id": 385, "t": "Milk Bread Sandwich Rolls", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "A good sandwich starts with good bread. A killer sandwich starts out with great bread. These milk bread sandwich rolls are great for all kinds of sandwiches: egg salad, tuna salad, pulled pork, pulled seitan chicken, a homemade McRib, or even a leveled-up, slapped-together sandwich made with cold cuts from the store. They’re beautifully soft through and through, from the blond crust to the tender ", "i": ["105 g Water , divided, plus extra as needed", "135 g Whole milk , divided", "20 g Mochiko sweet rice flour", "13 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "5 g Instant dry yeast , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "100 g Large egg(s) , (2 eggs) divided", "315 g Bread flour , unbleached, plus extra as needed", "40 g Sugar", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "50 g Unsalted butter , softened", "Fine cornmeal, as needed"], "s": ["Gelatinize rice flour", "Mix dough", "Incorporate butter into dough", "Proof dough", "Divide and portion dough", "Shape dough balls into logs", "Shape into rolls and final proof", "Egg wash, sprinkle, and score rolls", "Bake and cool rolls"], "tips": ["Proofing options"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/milk-bread-sandwich-rolls"}, {"id": 386, "t": "Bánh Mì Bread", "c": "Baking", "d": "You can’t make a bánh mì without bánh mì, the bread. That’s right: In Vietnamese, the name of the sandwich is the name of the bread. “Bánh mì” refers to a roll with a very crispy, crackly, fissured, eggshell-thin crust that shatters when you bite into it. It has a soft, tight crumb that has just the right amount of chew and a feathery cotton candy–like consistency. It’s the perfect sandwich bread.", "i": ["330 g Water , 105 °F / 41 °C to 110 °F / 43 °C, plus extra for creating steam during baking", "8 g Instant dry yeast", "10 g Sugar", "500 g Bread flour , unbleached", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "25 g Unsalted butter , softened", "1.5 g Ascorbic acid , (1/4 teaspoon)"], "s": ["First mix and autolyse", "Finish mixing dough", "Portion and first proof", "Shape rolls", "Final proof", "Score, spray, and bake"], "tips": ["What is an autolyse?", "Insurance dough"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/banh-mi-bread"}, {"id": 387, "t": "Xíu Mại (Vietnamese Meatballs)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Xíu mại are steamed or poached pork meatballs, often served with a light tomato sauce, that are as delicious as they are texturally interesting, just like the bánh mì they’re often served with. Typically made from seasoned fatty ground pork, these meatballs usually contain a mixture of cornstarch and grated jicama, which combine to barely bind the meat together, yielding savory, soft, and juicy me", "i": ["125 g Daikon radish , peeled, coarsely grated and finely chopped", "50 g Scallion(s) , (4 scallions) white and green parts separated, whites minced, greens thinly sliced; divided", "15 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems; stems minced, leaves reserved for garnish", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) finely grated", "15 g Fish sauce", "8 g Cornstarch", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/4 teaspoons)", "5 g Sugar , (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Black pepper , freshly ground (3/4 teaspoon)", "2 g White pepper , ground (3/4 teaspoon)", "1 g Prague powder #1 , (1/8 teaspoon) optional", "500 g Ground pork", "Maggi Seasoning, as needed", "Toasted sesame oil, as needed"], "s": ["Make meatball mixture", "Portion and form meatballs", "Set up steamer", "Steam meatballs and serve"], "tips": ["Don’t want to form meatballs? Make meatloaf instead."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/xiu-mai-vietnamese-meatballs"}, {"id": 388, "t": "Pork Liver Pâté", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Pork liver pâté is the best supporting actor in a bánh mì—it may not get all the shine, but when done right, it can steal the show. It underlines the importance of balance in a good sandwich. The pâté’s slightly bitter minerality and tang of its iron content are mellowed out by the acidity of pickles and mirrored by the bitterness in raw herbs. Its underlying sweetness is echoed by the raw vegetab", "i": ["15 g Neutral oil", "100 g Yellow onion(s) , (1/2 small onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "100 g Ground pork", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 large cloves) minced", "250 g Pork liver , or chicken livers, cut into 1-inch pieces", "100 g Large egg(s) , (2 eggs)", "45 g Soy sauce", "10 g Sugar", "1 g Prague powder #1 , (1/8 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g White pepper , ground (1/4 teaspoon)", "100 g Unsalted butter , melted"], "s": ["Cook onions and ground pork", "Blend and strain pâté base", "Cast into jars and seal", "Cook pâté sous vide", "Chill and serve"], "tips": ["Monitoring temperature while blending", "Sealing jars “fingertip tight” for sous vide cooking"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pork-liver-pate"}, {"id": 389, "t": "Đồ Chua (Vietnamese Pickled Daikon and Carrots)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Quick-pickled carrots and daikon are a staple of the Vietnamese table. The combination of the sweet, crunchy carrots, the slightly bitter and sulfurous daikon, and the sweet and tart brine is as versatile as it is delicious. They’re stuffed in bánh mì and bánh xèo, served alongside grilled meats, or submerged in nước chấm to add a little extra character to the dipping sauce. To get a uniform julie", "i": ["250 g Carrot(s) , (4 medium carrots) peeled", "250 g Daikon radish , (4- to 6-inch piece) peeled", "10 g Kosher salt , divided", "200 g Distilled vinegar", "125 g Sugar", "60 g Water"], "s": ["Cut vegetables into matchsticks", "Salt, rinse, and drain vegetables", "Quick-pickle vegetables in brine"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/do-chua-vietnamese-pickled-daikon-and-carrots"}, {"id": 390, "t": "Dill Pickle Chips", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Salty, sweet, crunchy, and tart, with a little garlicky bite and some heady dill notes, these pickle chips are perfect for burgers and sandwiches (including our homemade McRib!). But they’re also delicious straight out of the jar, and they’re super simple to make. With any refrigerator pickle, getting the right texture is the main goal. Dialing in the seasonings is a relatively simple matter—you w", "i": ["240 g Persian cucumber(s) , (8 cucumbers) unwaxed, ends trimmed", "20 g Kosher salt , divided", "Ice, as needed", "200 g Water", "200 g Distilled vinegar", "20 g Sugar", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (3 large cloves) crushed", "10 g Dill fronds , fresh", "2 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Calcium chloride , (1/4 teaspoon) optional"], "s": ["Cut and salt cucumbers", "Rinse and brine cucumbers"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dill-pickle-chips"}, {"id": 391, "t": "Starch Retrogradation and the Science of Staling", "c": "Baking", "d": "Wherever there’s bread, there’s stale bread. As soon as a freshly baked loaf of bread starts to cool down, staling begins. Bakers have puzzled over this process for millennia, and baked goods manufacturers have devised all kinds of methods to stave off the inevitable, even as home cooks have come up with ways for getting stale bread to revert to the ever-so-brief “freshly baked” state. The science", "i": [], "s": ["Staling and Starches", "Stalling Staling", "How to Store Bread to Minimize Staling", "Reversing Staling", "Mmmmm, bread ..."], "tips": ["Starch Molecules, Gels, and Retrogradation", "The Difference Between Tangzhong and Yudane/Yukone", "Wait, What About Supermarket Bread?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/starch-retrogradation-and-the-science-of-staling"}, {"id": 392, "t": "Carryover Cooking: Why You Should Let Meat Rest", "c": "Baking", "d": "When you’re roasting turkeys, butter-basting steaks, or air frying chops, you’re almost always told to leave the meat alone for a bit to let it “rest” after cooking. Why? Well, because of carryover cooking. Carryover cooking is just the natural consequence of thermodynamics, which is a fancy way of saying it’s the natural consequence of cooking with heat. save Print Explore other Recipes 32 SEE TH", "i": [], "s": ["What Is Carryover Cooking?", "Resting Meat: Letting Meats Come Up to Temperature", "Size Matters", "Resting Yields Juicy Meat", "Carryover Cooking Using Sous Vide and Low-Temperature Roasting", "So, Why Not Just Cook Everything Sous Vide?", "Carry on with carryover cooking"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/carryover-cooking-why-you-should-let-meat-rest"}, {"id": 393, "t": "Tips & Tricks: How to Get Perfectly Crispy Fish Skin, Every Time", "c": "Baking", "d": "Every cook has had to deal with fish skin sticking to a pan. Sometimes, even with a nicely seasoned, preheated skillet, fish skin just sticks. But there’s a foolproof fix: parchment paper. Sliding a piece of parchment paper between the fish and the pan’s surface guarantees a clean release. No need to hack away at it with a fish spatula, trying to get it to release; all you have to do is focus on g", "i": [], "s": ["How to Do It", "Why It Works", "Frequently Asked Questions", "We’ve got more tips & tricks for you right here"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/parchment-paper-crispy-fish-skin"}, {"id": 394, "t": "Seitan Barbecue Ribs", "c": "Baking", "d": "One of the best parts about seitan is it’s a blank canvas. You can use it as a vehicle for all kinds of flavors, and you can manipulate it in its raw state to mimic a range of different textures. In this recipe, we transform seitan dough into a dish that looks and tastes like a rack of barbecue ribs. Since a rack of ribs is relatively thin but long and wide, it’s pretty easy to get the seitan to t", "i": ["1 recipe How to Make Seitan , see “Before we begin” note", "24 g Black garlic , (6 cloves)", "80 g Red miso paste", "40 g Molasses", "32 g Sweet and Spicy Kansas City Barbecue Rub , divided", "12 g Liquid smoke", "4 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (3/4 teaspoon)", "200 g Vegetable stock", "30 g Neutral oil"], "s": ["Form seitan", "Make seasoning mixture", "Sear and braise seitan", "Add rub and roast", "Slice, serve, and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/seitan-barbecue-ribs"}, {"id": 395, "t": "Chilled Liángpí Salad With Celery and Sesame", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "There’s no better way to celebrate successfully making a batch of seitan and liángpí than a savory chilled noodle salad. It comes together in minutes and has a nicely balanced flavor profile, with soy sauce and coconut aminos providing salt and umami, seasoned rice vinegar providing sweetness and acidity, and sesame oil for toasty richness. Aside from the sauce and the noodles, the key to this dis", "i": ["30 g Coconut aminos", "30 g Soy sauce", "25 g Sesame oil", "20 g Seasoned rice vinegar", "20 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "4 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) finely grated", "10 g Sesame seeds , plus extra for garnish", "150 g Celery , (2–3 ribs) cut into 1/2-inch slices", "30 g Red bell pepper(s) , cut into small dice", "25 g Scallion(s) , (3 scallions) green parts only, thinly sliced", "1 recipe Liángpí (Wheat Starch Noodles) , (about 500 g noodles), see “Before we begin” note", "25 g Lime juice , fresh, from 1 lime", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed"], "s": ["Make dressing", "Dress salad", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/wheat-starch-noodle-salad"}, {"id": 396, "t": "Liángpí (Wheat Starch Noodles)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Making seitan from scratch requires rinsing away all the starch in a kneaded wheat dough, which gives you a hunk of pure wheat protein and a bunch of starchy water. You can toss that starchy water, if you want, but you can also use it to make deliciously snappy and chewy noodles. Called liángpí in Mandarin, which translates roughly to “cold skin,” these noodles are basically a starch gel that’s co", "i": ["36 g Sesame oil", "12 g Neutral oil", "600 g Wheat starch slurry , reserved from making 1 recipe seitan; see “Before we begin” note", "6 g Kosher salt", "Water, as needed"], "s": ["Set up steamer and ice bath", "Season slurry", "Test noodle batter and adjust if needed", "Cook remaining noodle batter", "Cut noodles"], "tips": ["Use 2 cake pans to save time"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/wheat-starch-noodles-liangpi"}, {"id": 397, "t": "Silky Seitan and Vegetable Stir-Fry", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "When you make seitan from scratch, a byproduct of the process is a slurry of wheat starch and water. There are a lot of things you can do with the starch slurry: You can make noodles with it or whip up a batter. Or you can use it to thicken sauces in seconds. Using a starch slurry to thicken sauces to a spoon-coating consistency right at the end of cooking is quite common in Chinese cuisine. Typic", "i": ["1 recipe How to Make Seitan , rested", "125 g Celery , (3 ribs) sliced into 1/2-inch-thick pieces", "125 g Sugar snap peas , halved crosswise", "100 g Red bell pepper(s) , (1/2 pepper) stemmed, seeded, pith removed, cut into 1/4-inch dice", "100 g Red onion(s) , (1/2 small onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "25 g Shallot(s) , (1 small shallot) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "50 g Scallion(s) , (4 scallions) white and green parts separated, thinly sliced; divided", "15 g Jalapeño(s) , (1/2 pepper) stemmed, seeded, cut into 1/4-inch dice", "100 g Shiitake mushrooms , trimmed, cut into bite-sized pieces", "150 g Shaoxing wine", "120 g Water", "90 g Soy sauce", "30 g Fresh ginger root , (3-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "20 g Toasted sesame oil", "12 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 large cloves) finely grated", "2 g White pepper , freshly ground (1 teaspoon)", "0.8 g Chile flakes , (1/2 teaspoon) optional", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "45 g Peanut oil , divided", "30 g Wheat starch slurry , reserved from making 1 recipe seitan; see “Before we begin” note", "30 g Cilantro , (1/2 bunch) fresh leaves and tender stems, chopped, for garnish", "30 g Roasted peanuts , chopped, for garnish", "Sesame seeds, as needed", "Lime(s) , quartered, for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Steam seitan", "Blanch and prep vegetables", "Prepare sauce", "Sear seitan", "Stir-fry vegetables and add sauce", "Add starch slurry and thicken", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/stir-fried-seitan"}, {"id": 398, "t": "Shredded Seitan Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe produces tender shreds of seasoned wheat protein, perfect for adding to soups and stews, stuffing into tortillas for tacos, or tossing with a dressing or sauce for sandwiches. Call it the other, other white “meat”! Seitan is essentially just pure gluten, or wheat protein, and it’s often used to create “meat substitutes,” since you can easily manipulate the long chains gluten forms to p", "i": ["10 g Provençal salt , or other herb salt", "4 g Nutritional yeast , (2 teaspoons)", "4 g Smoked paprika , (2 teaspoons)", "2 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1 teaspoon)", "1 recipe How to Make Seitan", "30 g Neutral oil", "454 g Vegetable stock , plus extra as needed"], "s": ["Make seasoning mixture", "Season and shape", "Sear and braise", "Shred seitan", "Cook or dress and serve", "Make-ahead and storage", "Put those shreds in something delicious"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/seitan-chicken"}, {"id": 399, "t": "Crispy Seitan Nuggets", "c": "Baking", "d": "These nuggets have everything you want: They’re super crispy and well-seasoned, with a delicate and light interior. And the best part is there’s no mystery about what’s inside them. They’re made from the wheatest of “meats”: seitan! This recipe came about due to a fortuitous accident. As I was fiddling with seitan to figure out how to mimic the flavor and texture of fish, I made a seitan dough tha", "i": ["1 recipe How to Make Seitan", "200 g Tofu , firm, drained and patted dry", "50 g Red miso paste", "10 g Goya Sazón sin Achiote (Without Annatto) , (2 packets)", "5 g Nutritional yeast , (2 1/4 teaspoons)", "200 g Panko breadcrumbs", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "180 g Hot water", "20 g Flax meal", "200 g All-purpose flour", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed"], "s": ["Season seitan", "Shape and form seitan", "Steam and chill seitan", "Portion nuggets", "Set up breading station", "Bread nuggets", "Fry nuggets", "Serve and enjoy"], "tips": ["Using an egg wash", "Air-frying the nuggets"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/seitan-nuggets"}, {"id": 400, "t": "How to Make Seitan", "c": "Baking", "d": "Seitan is a meat substitute popular in East Asian cuisines that is made by washing a wheat flour dough in changes of water to remove starch, leaving behind a dough of pure gluten protein. This dough is a blank canvas for flavor and texture that you can play around with to achieve a wide range of “wheat meat” results. Make vegan hot dogs by blending the dough with spices, liquid smoke, and vinegar.", "i": ["800 g Bread flour", "560 g Water"], "s": ["Mix the dough", "Soak and rest dough", "Wash away starch", "Final rest"], "tips": ["Adding color to seitan"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/seitan"}, {"id": 401, "t": "Faux-sciutto (Seitan Prosciutto)", "c": "Baking", "d": "So long, store-bought seitan! This wheat meat faux prosciutto is unlike anything you’ll find at the grocery store. Made with simple ingredients, it’s simply amazing—with a mildly “meaty” flavor and a chewy, springy texture that’s strikingly similar to the real deal. Rinsing away the starch from a kneaded wheat dough, instead of using vital wheat gluten and water, yields a seitan that has cleaner, ", "i": ["2 recipes How to Make Seitan , rested, divided", "60 g Coconut oil (refined) , refined", "8 g Kosher salt , (2 teaspoons) divided", "4 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , (3/4 teaspoon) divided", "40 g Miso paste", "40 g Brown sugar", "6 g Liquid smoke", "4 g Garlic powder , (1 teaspoon)", "4 g Nutritional yeast , (2 teaspoons)", "Neutral oil , for brushing , as needed"], "s": ["Enrich the white seitan dough", "Season the red seitan dough", "Marble the doughs", "Wrap the dough", "Steam and chill", "Slice and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/wheat-meat-pro-shoo-t"}, {"id": 402, "t": "Seitan Hot Dogs", "c": "Baking", "d": "Plant-based eaters have more options than ever before when it comes to summer cook-out staples like burgers and hot dogs. Along with classic frozen veggie patties and tofu dogs, a number of new faux-meat products have hit the market that are meant to look, cook, and taste like real meat. I’m not here to debate whether plants should be manipulated into imitation ground beef that can be smash-griddl", "i": ["1 recipe How to Make Seitan , see “Before we begin” note", "100 g Tofu , firm, drained and pressed", "65 g Coconut oil (refined) , plus extra for brushing", "15 g Soy sauce", "9 g Sugar", "8 g Rice wine vinegar , unseasoned", "8 g Kosher salt", "4 g Liquid smoke , (3/4 teaspoon)", "3 g Nutritional yeast , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "2 g Garlic powder , or granulated garlic (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 g Paprika , (1/2 teaspoon)", "8 Hot dog buns , for serving", "1 recipe Carrot-lina Gold BBQ Sauce , or yellow mustard, for serving", "1 recipe Quick-Style Kraut , or store-bought kraut, for serving"], "s": ["Blend seitan with seasonings", "Shape dough", "Steam dough", "Cool dough", "Portion hot dogs", "Cook hot dogs", "Serve them up"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/plant-based-hot-dogs"}, {"id": 403, "t": "What Is Seitan?", "c": "Baking", "d": "Seitan is life; seitan is love; seitan is the wheatest meat, a textural marvel that’s also one of the most versatile vehicles for flavor in the culinary world. What is seitan? Delicious, that’s what! At its most basic, seitan (pronounced the way you’d say, “Say, that’s a nice tan!”) is just pure wheat protein, or the substance that so many now appear to fear: gluten. Isolated from wheat starch and", "i": [], "s": ["Seitan’s Introduction to the U.S."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-is-seitan"}, {"id": 404, "t": "Gluten: A Guide to Seitan’s Super Powers", "c": "Baking", "d": "You hear a lot about gluten these days, although it’s usually buried in a word salad about what people won’t eat. “Gluten-free” is the watchword for the 1 percent of the U.S. population who have celiac disease and millions of people who don’t. And yet most people eat gluten—scratch that, most people love gluten—whether they know it or not. It’s a fundamental component of wheat flour, and the avera", "i": [], "s": ["What Is Gluten?", "Seitan Is Pure, Cooked Gluten", "Using Vital Wheat Gluten to Make Seitan", "Seitanology 101", "Gluten tag!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/gluten-seitan-and-vital-wheat-gluten"}, {"id": 405, "t": "Whole Wheat Utilization: How to Use Seitan’s Wheat Starch Byproduct", "c": "Baking", "d": "To make seitan from scratch, you have to make a dough out of wheat flour, knead it to develop the gluten network, then rinse away all the starch, leaving you with pure wheat protein. But what do you do with the starch? Even though bakers and seitan lovers spend a lot of time talking and thinking about gluten, even the highest-protein flours available at your local grocery store top out at around 1", "i": [], "s": ["Settling Starch", "What Is Starch?", "Using Starch as a Thickener", "Forming Gels With Starch", "Use that starch!", "\"I want all the food science!\""], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/seitan-how-to-use-the-wheat-starch-slurry"}, {"id": 406, "t": "A Guide to Seasoning and Tenderizing Seitan", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’ve ever eaten plain, cooked seitan, you know that it doesn’t taste like much. It’s almost all texture. Seitan’s blandness is in fact one of its greatest strengths since it can serve as a vehicle for all kinds of different seasonings, both dry and wet. With a little ingenuity, you can prepare a seasoned seitan dough that has a ton of flavor all on its own. And you can further flavor the cook", "i": [], "s": ["Seitan Seasonings", "Incorporating Seasoning Manually", "Incorporating Seasoning With Machines", "Seasoning During the Cooking Process", "How to Tenderize Seitan", "Common Seitan Tenderizers", "Seitan, seasoned perfectly", "A map to tender things"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/seasoning-and-tenderizing-seitan"}, {"id": 407, "t": "A Guide to Shaping and Cooking Seitan", "c": "Baking", "d": "As with bread and pastry, the method you use to shape seitan dough can have an extraordinary effect on its cooked texture. By folding seitan over itself or tying it into knots, you can create a range of textures. You can mimic the striated layers of marbled cuts of meat, you can produce fluffy yet chewy nuggets that resemble a well-made meat farce, and you can even make turn it in shreds that are ", "i": [], "s": ["The Importance of Resting Seitan", "Shaping Seitan", "Cooking Seitan", "Other Cooking Methods", "Can You Overcook Seitan?", "Let's see some of that shapely seitan", "Actually, let's see molded things!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/shaping-and-cooking-seitan"}, {"id": 408, "t": "Chef Recs: Essential Equipment for Making Seitan", "c": "Other", "d": "If you want to fully take advantage of seitan’s potential, having a little bit of gear helps. With a few tools and some creativity with cardboard and foil, you’ll be able to manipulate and cook seitan so it takes on a range of different textures, flavors, and forms. Our lawyers say we have to say this: “As an Amazon Associate I earn from qualifying purchases.” save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Stand Mixer", "Colander and Fine-Mesh Strainer", "Food Processor and Blender", "Bamboo Steamer", "Cheesecloth", "Dutch Oven", "Spider Skimmer", "Digital Instant-Read Thermometer", "Equipment IQ"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/recommended-equipment-for-making-seitan"}, {"id": 409, "t": "Milk Brew Coffee", "c": "Baking", "d": "Cold brew coffee has grown in popularity, even though it can be a hard sell for some folks. Coffee enthusiasts complain about its lack of acidity and complexity, but a lot of people like the fact that the cooler brew temperature produces sweet and mellow coffee notes, with little to no bitterness. Part of the issue is that a lot of coffee geeks look at cold brew as an inferior method for making co", "i": ["38 g Coffee beans , whole", "750 g Whole milk", "Simple Syrup , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Grind coffee beans", "Steep coffee in milk", "Strain and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cold-brew-latte"}, {"id": 410, "t": "Instant Chicken Noodle Soup", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Let’s say you’re feeling under the weather, and all you want is a chicken noodle soup made from scratch. What do you do? You don’t feel like chopping vegetables, and you can’t even think about touching raw chicken. You’re going to have to just settle on a can of soup, right? Well, no, you won’t ... if you’ve got some of our chicken bouillon cubes kicking around. This recipe is designed to produce ", "i": ["28 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 large cloves) grated", "35 g Onion , (1/2 small onion) coarsely grated", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "30 g Carrot(s) , (1/2 small carrot) peeled and coarsely grated", "650 g Water", "35 g Ultimate Chicken Bouillon Cubes , (1 cube)", "75 g Orzo , or small dried pasta of your choice", "1 Poached Chicken Breast , shredded, optional", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "5 g Flat-leaf parsley , (1/2 cup) fresh leaves and tender stems, chopped, optional"], "s": ["Sauté vegetables and make broth", "Cook pasta and finish soup"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/instant-chicken-noodle-soup"}, {"id": 411, "t": "Ultra-Porky Pork and Beans", "c": "Baking", "d": "There’s nothing like a pot of pork and beans. Even though the pork and beans I ate as a kid was closer to a creamy broth than anything else—the beans were blasted for so long, they’d collapse and thicken the broth—I still loved it, because it was what I wanted a comfort food to be: salty, hammy, creamy, and rich. This recipe makes a better version of pork and beans: nicely cooked corona beans, whi", "i": ["350 g Corona beans , dried", "1.9 kg Water", "600 g Ham hock , smoked, skin on", "200 g White onion(s) , (1 medium onion) cut into small dice", "70 g Ultimate Pork Bouillon Cubes , (2 cubes)", "200 g Carrot(s) , (2 carrots) peeled, halved lengthwise and sliced into 1/4-inch-thick pieces", "100 g Celery , (2 ribs) thinly sliced", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "20 g Flat-leaf parsley , roughly chopped, for garnish", "1.9 kg Water 600 g Ham hock , smoked, skin on"], "s": ["Soak beans", "Pressure-cook ham hock", "Cook beans and finish soup", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pork-bouillon-pork-and-beans"}, {"id": 412, "t": "Hacked French Onion Soup", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’ve got our beef bouillon cubes on hand, you’re well on your way to making an excellent bowl of French onion soup. Most of the recipes I’ve developed to showcase the utility of these bouillon cubes have focused on convenience. Deeply flavorful, perfectly seasoned pan sauces in minutes; a better-than-a-ramen-shop instant ramen; near-instant sipping broths … you get the idea. This recipe is di", "i": ["100 g Crusty bread , cut into 1-inch cubes", "56 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "3 Garlic clove(s) , 1 clove finely grated, 2 cloves thinly sliced; divided", "9 g Thyme , 1 g (1 teaspoon) fresh leaves, (8 whole fresh sprigs) wrapped in cheesecloth; divided", "5 g Kosher salt , (1 1/2 teaspoons), plus extra for as needed", "2 g Black pepper , (1 teaspoon) freshly ground, plus extra as needed", "50 g Unsalted butter", "500 g Yellow onion(s) , (2 large onions) thinly sliced", "485 g Water , divided", "100 g Red wine", "35 g Ultimate Beef Bouillon Cubes , (1 cube)", "15 g Bragg liquid coconut aminos", "200 g Gruyère cheese"], "s": ["Make croutons", "Caramelize onions", "Deglaze onions and reduce wine", "Add bouillon and finish soup", "Assemble crocks, broil, and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-bouillon-french-onion-soup"}, {"id": 413, "t": "Ultimate Beef Stroganoff", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Our beef bouillon cubes are super convenient for making tasty pan sauces and aromatic, warming sipping broths in minutes, but they can also be reconstituted and used whenever you need some good stock, like when you’re making beef stroganoff. My dad’s beef stroganoff was one of my favorite dinners as a kid: tender steak and cremini mushrooms swimming in packaged powdered beef gravy, served over egg", "i": ["30 g All-purpose flour , divided", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "4 g Black pepper , (2 teaspoons) freshly ground, plus extra as needed", "400 g Beef chuck , trimmed and cut into 1-inch cubes", "28 g Canola oil", "450 g Water", "250 g Yellow onion(s) , (1 large onion) cut into large dice", "35 g Ultimate Beef Bouillon Cubes , (1 cube)", "15 g Dried mushrooms , such as shiitakes or morels", "45 g Unsalted butter , divided", "200 g Radiatori pasta , dried", "20 g Flat-leaf parsley , finely chopped", "112 g Sour cream"], "s": ["Brown beef", "Pressure cook beef", "Strain and thicken broth", "Cook pasta", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-bouillon-stroganoff"}, {"id": 414, "t": "Instant Egg Drop Soup", "c": "Baking", "d": "A Chinese egg drop soup recipe that you can make in less time than it takes to figure out what else you want to order from your go-to takeout spot? That’s easy, because egg drop soup is pretty simple. But a really good Chinese egg drop soup? Well, that’s also easy, if you’ve got some of our chicken bouillon cubes kicking around. Aromatic stock, some eggs, some cornstarch … there isn’t all that muc", "i": ["455 g Water", "10 g Cornstarch", "35 g Ultimate Chicken Bouillon Cubes , (1 cube)", "10 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "3 g Sesame oil , (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g White pepper , (1/4 teaspoon) ground", "1 Egg(s) , lightly beaten", "1 Scallion(s) , thinly sliced"], "s": ["Make broth", "Add aromatics and egg", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-bouillon-egg-drop-soup"}, {"id": 415, "t": "Instant Au Poivre Pan Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "Our beef bouillon cubes are a cheat code for making an excellent au poivre sauce, fast. Steak au poivre is a classic preparation of seared steak with a rich and creamy stock-based sauce fortified with brandy and a whole bunch of black pepper. Traditionally prepared with a filet, the sauce is meant to provide all the flavor that the extremely tender, yet quite bland, tenderloin lacks. Our bouillon ", "i": ["50 g Unsalted butter", "40 g Shallot(s) , (4 small shallots) minced", "100 g Cognac , or brandy", "200 g Heavy cream", "35 g Ultimate Beef Bouillon Cubes , (1 cube)", "30 g Brined green peppercorns", "10 g Worcestershire sauce", "5 g Black peppercorns , (2 1/2 teaspoons) coarsely cracked", "5 g Sherry vinegar , (1 teaspoon) optional", "2 g Rosemary , (2 sprigs) fresh leaves, finely chopped, optional", "5 g Flat-leaf parsley , (1/2 cup) fresh leaves, finely chopped, optional"], "s": ["Cook shallots and reduce cognac", "Finish sauce"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bouillon-au-poivre-sauce"}, {"id": 416, "t": "Instant Red Wine Pan Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "Our beef bouillon cubes are packed with beefy flavor, but they’ve also got a ton of gelatin, which makes them ideal for use in pan sauces. Most store-bought stocks and instant stock products contain absolutely zero gelatin, which means they won’t thicken as they reduce, and they’re relatively terrible at making emulsions without the addition of some other ingredient (like powdered gelatin). Even i", "i": ["100 g Unsalted butter , chilled and cut into 1/2-inch dice, divided", "20 g Shallot(s) , (2 small shallots) minced", "50 g Red wine", "25 g Water", "18 g Ultimate Beef Bouillon Cubes , (1/2 cube)", "1 g Rosemary , (1 teaspoon) fresh leaves, finely chopped", "1 g Black pepper , (1/2 teaspoon) coarsely ground"], "s": ["Sauté shallots and reduce wine", "Add bouillon and finish sauce"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-bouillon-red-wine-pan-sauce"}, {"id": 417, "t": "Instant Chicken Pan Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The only thing better than a perfectly cooked piece of chicken is a perfectly cooked piece of chicken served with a nice sauce. With our chicken bouillon cubes on hand, you can whip up a sauce to serve alongside your chicken in the time it takes to set your table. Even if you’re cooking chicken breasts or chicken thighs sous vide, the perfectly cooked and seasoned protein can still use a little as", "i": ["25 g Water", "18 g Ultimate Chicken Bouillon Cubes , (1/2 cube)", "100 g Unsalted butter , chilled and cut into 1/2-inch dice", "10 g Lemon juice , fresh, from 1 lemon", "1 g Black pepper , (1/2 teaspoon) freshly ground", "0.5 g Thyme , (1 teaspoon) fresh leaves"], "s": ["Melt bouillon", "Mount with butter and finish sauce"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-bouillon-cube-pan-sauce"}, {"id": 418, "t": "Ultimate Instant Ramen", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "If you want near-instant ramen that’s way better than anything out of a packet (and comparable to what you can buy at a good local shop), then this recipe is for you. After developing the recipe for pork bouillon cubes, I immediately thought of using them to make a riff on instant ramen. And while I’m most familiar with tonkotsu ramen—the kind of ramen that uses a milky, emulsified pork stock as i", "i": ["10 g Bonito flakes", "10 g Dried anchovies", "10 g Dried mackerel flakes , optional", "80 g Soy sauce", "10 g Fish sauce", "10 g Mirin", "20 g Lard , melted, plus extra as needed", "10 g Scallion(s) , white and light green parts, finely chopped", "3 g Fresh ginger root , (1/2-inch piece) peeled and finely grated", "3 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 medium clove) peeled and finely grated", "1 g Sesame oil , (1/8 teaspoon)", "275 g Water , plus extra for cooking noodles", "18 g Ultimate Pork Bouillon Cubes , (1/2 cube)", "White pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "155 g Chewy Ramen Noodles , or 1 portion of store-bought noodles", "1 Ajitsuke Tamago (Marinated Ramen Eggs) , for garnish, optional", "1 piece Sous Vide Char Siu (Chinese Barbecue Pork) , for garnish, optional", "1 piece", "38 g Tare , from Step 2", "5 g Gyofun , from Step 1"], "s": ["A note on ingredients and ingredient quantities", "Grind gyofun", "Mix tare", "Assemble bowl", "Boil stock and cook noodles", "Garnish and serve", "piece"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-instant-ramen"}, {"id": 419, "t": "Instant Pork Pan Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pork chops are weeknight meal staples: They’re easy to cook, delicious when cooked perfectly, relatively inexpensive, and easy to find almost everywhere. Pork chops with a pork stock-based pan sauce? Well, that’s less common, in part because not many people have pork stock lying around. Our pork bouillon cubes can help change that. Full of porky flavor and gelatin, they’re the best stock option ou", "i": ["100 g Unsalted butter , chilled and cut into 1/2-inch dice, divided", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 cloves) minced", "30 g Water", "40 g Mustard , whole grain", "18 g Ultimate Pork Bouillon Cubes , (1/2 cube)", "5 g Flat-leaf parsley , (1/2 cup) fresh leaves and tender stems, finely chopped", "1 g Rosemary , (1 sprig) fresh leaves, finely chopped"], "s": ["Sauté garlic", "Add bouillon and finish sauce"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pork-bouillon-pan-sauce"}, {"id": 420, "t": "Boneless Beef Bone Broth", "c": "Baking", "d": "One of the simplest and most satisfying things you can make with our beef bouillon cubes is a sipping broth, which in our view is what a lot of people these days like to call “bone broth.” Deeply savory, wonderfully aromatic, and nicely seasoned, they’re perfect for when you’re feeling a little under the weather or waking up after a late night. The best part of this recipe is it comes together in ", "i": ["720 g Water", "35 g Ultimate Beef Bouillon Cubes , (1 cube)", "6 g Thyme , (5 sprigs) fresh", "4 g Black pepper , (2 teaspoons) freshly ground", "2 g Rosemary , (1 sprig) fresh"], "s": ["Reconstitute bouillon", "Steep broth with aromatics and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-bouillon-sipping-broth"}, {"id": 421, "t": "Boneless Chicken Bone Broth", "c": "Baking", "d": "There are few things as satisfying as sipping an aromatic chicken broth when it’s cold or rainy outside. With our chicken bouillon cubes, you can pour yourself a mug in less time than it takes to make hot cocoa or coffee. Since our bouillon cubes are already seasoned, all you need to do is dissolve them in hot water and steep in some herbs and aromatics—here, I chose to use thyme, parsley, black p", "i": ["720 g Water", "35 g Ultimate Chicken Bouillon Cubes , (1 cube)", "4 g Thyme , (3 sprigs) fresh", "4 g Flat-leaf parsley , (2 sprigs) fresh", "4 g Black pepper , (2 teaspoons) freshly ground", "4 g Lemon zest , from 1 lemon, peeled into large strips"], "s": ["Reconstitute bouillon", "Steep broth with aromatics and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-bouillon-sipping-broth"}, {"id": 422, "t": "Boneless Pork Bone Broth", "c": "Baking", "d": "Feeling under the weather? Did that “one drink” with pals from work turn into “a couple, plus cheese fries and nachos?” Well, if you have some of our pork bouillon cubes stashed in your freezer, you can make a warming and restorative pork sipping broth in just a couple minutes. Pork stock isn’t as commonly found in stores as chicken or beef stock, but it’s just as deliciously savory, with the uniq", "i": ["720 g Water", "35 g Ultimate Pork Bouillon Cubes , (1 cube)", "4 g Garlic clove(s) , (1 clove) thinly sliced", "2 g Fresh sage , (2 leaves)", "2 g Black pepper , (1 teaspoon) freshly ground", "1 g Fennel seeds , (1 teaspoon) whole"], "s": ["Reconstitute bouillon", "Steep broth with aromatics and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pork-bouillon-sipping-broth"}, {"id": 423, "t": "Vegan Chocolate-Peanut Butter Pudding", "c": "Baking", "d": "Okay, I did vegan vanilla pudding. I did vegan butterscotch pudding and vegan coffee pudding. I even did something specifically for the holidays: the “egg”nog pudding. And then I made a vegan banana pudding, because so many readers asked (so nicely) for it. But I still had one more pudding in me, and here it is. Behold: vegan chocolate-peanut butter pudding! I like to think of this as a peanut but", "i": ["450 g Water", "25 g Raw cashews", "132 g Peanut butter , organic, preferably CB’s", "132 g 58% bittersweet chocolate pistoles", "70 g Organic cane sugar", "3 g Kosher salt", "1 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F"], "s": ["Boil cashews", "Blend and set custard", "Shear custard", "Portion pudding and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vegan-chocolate-peanut-butter-pudding"}, {"id": 424, "t": "Vegan Banana Pudding", "c": "Baking", "d": "After publishing a bunch of my vegan pudding recipes—vanilla, butterscotch, coffee, and “egg”nog—a lot of readers asked for a banana version. So here it is: the best banana pudding I’ve ever tasted. The base recipe is the same. It harnesses the thickening power of low-acyl gellan gum to produce a creamy and rich fluid gel using a combination of blended cashew, water, and coconut oil. The only real", "i": ["700 g Banana(s) , (3–4 bananas) whole, unpeeled", "375 g Water", "100 g Raw cashews", "55 g Coconut oil (refined)", "50 g Organic cane sugar", "20 g Vanilla extract", "3 g Kosher salt", "1 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F", "300 g Roasted banana"], "s": ["Roast bananas", "Boil cashews", "Blend and set custard", "Shear custard", "Portion pudding and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/roasted-banana-pudding"}, {"id": 425, "t": "Crème Fraîche", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Crème fraîche is a couple fancy-sounding French words that translate to “fresh cream.” Does that mean you can just use cream fresh from your supermarket shelves whenever a recipe calls for crème fraîche? No, because what the French call fresh cream is closer to what we call sour cream—it’s a cultured dairy product. Crème fraîche is a little acidic with a whole lot of body, something you scoop and ", "i": ["475 g Heavy cream", "240 g Buttermilk , cultured", "80 g Yogurt , plain, whole milk, cultured"], "s": ["Combine dairy", "Ferment", "Chill and strain"], "tips": ["Using crème fraîche culture", "Alternative fermentation environments", "Drain it less, or more!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/creme-fraiche"}, {"id": 426, "t": "Crème Fraîche Ice Cream", "c": "Baking", "d": "Crème fraîche is delicious and simple to make at home, and there are countless ways to use it: dollop it on soups, stir it into pan sauces, scoop some onto pancakes and waffles, etc. You know what else you can use it for? Ice cream! Think of it like a richer, creamier version of milk ice cream, with intense dairy flavor and a slight tang that makes it way more interesting. Add in a little vanilla ", "i": ["60 g Sugar", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1.4 g Locust bean gum , (3/8 teaspoon)", "240 g Whole milk", "160 g Water", "90 g Glucose syrup", "200 g Crème fraîche , homemade or store-bought"], "s": ["Combine dry ingredients", "Heat milk and glucose", "Blend and strain ice cream base", "Chill ice cream base", "Churn ice cream"], "tips": ["Put a savory spin on ice cream!", "Using an immersion blender", "CAUTION: How to safely use liquid nitrogen"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/creme-fraiche-ice-cream"}, {"id": 427, "t": "Whey-Braised Cipollini Onions", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "When you make crème fraîche (and cheeses), you’re going to end up with whey, and the best and most practical way to use your whey is to cook vegetables in it. As whey reduces, it begins to thicken and its sugars start to caramelize, forming a glaze. Here, I chose to use cipollini onions (pearl onions work great as well), but you can use all kinds of vegetables—carrots, fennel, squash, mushrooms, e", "i": ["320 g Cipollini onions , peeled and trimmed (about 15 small- to medium-size onions)", "240 g Whey , from 1 recipe of crème fraîche", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Boil onions in whey", "Braise onions and reduce whey"], "tips": ["The easiest way to peel small onions? Give them a hot bath."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/whey-braised-onions"}, {"id": 428, "t": "Imfoiessible Pâté (Vegan Foie Gras Mousse)", "c": "Baking", "d": "This vegan riff on foie gras mousse has all the flavor of fatty duck liver, with none of the distraction of ethical debates. It’s just plants, and it's creamy and delicious! By using cashews and two powerful hydrocolloids—low-acyl and high-acyl gellan gums—we were able to replicate the texture and richness of foie gras mousse exactly. With a little of the same Sweet Spice mix we use in our classic", "i": ["150 g Raw cashews", "85 g Coconut oil (refined) , divided", "90 g Shallot(s) , (2 medium shallots) thinly sliced", "50 g Button mushrooms , cleaned and thinly sliced", "12 g Garlic clove(s) , (2 cloves) thinly sliced", "110 g Cognac , or brandy", "275 g Water , plus extra for soaking cashews", "25 g White miso paste", "15 g Tomato paste", "8 g Kosher salt", "2.5 g Sweet Spice , (1 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground", "1.5 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F", "0.4 g High-Acyl Gellan Gum LT100", "Vegan shortening , for fat cap (optional) , as needed", "150 g Raw cashews - Water, as needed"], "s": ["Soak cashews", "Cook aromatics and deglaze", "Add cashews and seasonings", "Blend mousse", "Cast into jars and set", "Serve"], "tips": ["Work fast with fluid gels"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vegan-foie-gras-pate"}, {"id": 429, "t": "How to French a Rack of Lamb", "c": "Baking", "d": "“Frenching” a rack of lamb refers to the removal of the fat, meat, and muscle membranes that encase the rib bones, creating an elegant roast that cooks evenly and is easy to carve and serve. That’s right: It means you’re taking a rack of lamb and making it all fancy. Since the goal is to make the rack of lamb attractive, you want to use a methodical approach; you don’t want to just hack and scrape", "i": [], "s": ["Cut reference points", "Score membrane", "Begin separating meat from bones", "Score and peel membrane from rib bones", "Remove excess meat, fat, and membrane", "Scrape and clean bones", "Now cook your beautiful, frenched rack of lamb!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-french-a-rack-of-lamb"}, {"id": 430, "t": "Glazed Seitan Ham", "c": "Baking", "d": "Seitan ham! “Seit-ham”? Nah. “Sei-ham”? Um … what about, “Heim”? Yuck. Okay, whatever! Seitan ham! Glazed ham is a traditional centerpiece for big holiday meals, and this recipe for a mock ham made from seitan is for anyone who’s gone plant-based but still has a nostalgic yearning for classic preparations they used to eat before they went vegan. It’s got all the hallmarks of a glazed ham: a sweet,", "i": ["2 recipes How to Make Seitan , see “Before we begin” note", "70 g Coconut oil (refined)", "45 g Red miso paste", "45 g Chickpea (garbanzo) flour", "40 g Soy sauce", "20 g Tomato paste", "12 g Kosher salt", "10 g Liquid smoke", "4 g Garlic powder , (1 teaspoon)", "3 g Onion powder , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "3 g Ascorbic acid , (1/2 teaspoon) optional, for color retention", "Neutral oil, as needed", "177 g Pineapple juice", "75 g Maple syrup", "50 g Brown sugar", "Cloves , whole, for garnish, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Flavor seitan", "Shape seitan", "Steam seitan", "Make glaze", "Score and stud seitan ham", "Roast and glaze seitan ham", "Slice and serve"], "tips": ["Shaping seitan"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/seitan-ham"}, {"id": 431, "t": "Real Pumpkin Spice Latte", "c": "Baking", "d": "Love it or hate it, the pumpkin spice latte is one of the most popular drinks during the fall. We wanted to make a better version of it by dialing up the amount of real pumpkin flavor. Not only that, we also wanted to make a real pumpkin latte. This drink has the sweetness and spice of the one made famous by that huge coffee chain, although the sweetness isn’t as outrageous and the warm spice mixt", "i": ["1 Sugar pumpkin , (about 680 g)", "30 g Sugar , plus extra as needed", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon) plus extra as needed", "0.3 g Pumpkin pie spice , (1/8 teaspoon) per latte, plus extra for garnish", "Whole milk, as needed"], "s": ["Peel and juice pumpkin", "Cook and strain juice", "Make pumpkin syrup", "Make a latte"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/real-pumpkin-spice-latte"}, {"id": 432, "t": "The Latte Art Challenge", "c": "Baking", "d": "You’ve watched the videos, you’ve read up on the technique, and you’ve put all of you’ve learned into action: pulling your (good) espresso shot, stretching and texturing your milk, and then pouring that milk in a smooth, flowing motion with as much confidence you can muster into your coffee. And it looks ... not great. Well, we all know exactly what that feels like, because we all started out maki", "i": [], "s": ["Whole latte love"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/latte-art-challenge"}, {"id": 433, "t": "Glossary of Espresso Terms", "c": "Baking", "d": "There’s a whole lot of words associated with espresso. Not just the ones English-speakers have borrowed from espresso’s creators, the Italians, and not just the weird vaguely Italianate ones that big, global coffee chain made up. There’s portafilters and tampers mixed up with doppios and brew ratios, knock boxes for after you’re done pulling a ristretto, and the purge that you give your steam wand", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/glossary-of-espresso-terms"}, {"id": 434, "t": "Vegan Eggnog", "c": "Baking", "d": "Making eggnog, the creamy classic holiday drink that may or may not be spiked with booze, presents a problem for people who don’t consume eggs or dairy. But they’re in luck: Despite its name, eggnog isn’t particularly eggy tasting. Instead, it’s all about the flavors and aromas of vanilla and warm spices, suspended in a liquid that has the consistency of heavy cream. Getting the flavor right seeme", "i": ["150 g Raw cashews", "500 g Water , plus extra for soaking cashews", "100 g Maple syrup", "12 g Vanilla extract , or 2 vanilla beans, split lengthwise and scraped", "3 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon)", "1 g Fresh turmeric root , freshly grated (1/4 teaspoon), or 1/8 teaspoon turmeric powder; optional, for color", "0.5 g Nutmeg , freshly grated (1/4 teaspoon), plus extra for garnish", "0.5 g Cinnamon , freshly grated (1/4 teaspoon)", "125 g Alcohol of choice , optional (rum, bourbon, or Scotch; Santa Teresa Rhum Orange Liqueur recommended)", "150 g Raw cashews - Water, as needed"], "s": ["Soak cashews", "Blend eggnog", "Cook half of the mixture to thicken", "Strain, chill, spike, and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vegan-eggnog"}, {"id": 435, "t": "Modernist Eggnog", "c": "Meat", "d": "Eggnog heralds the arrival of the holiday season, and our version takes advantage of some modern techniques to boost flavor and texture. Enjoy it plain or hooch it up with a nice shot of rum or bourbon. save Print", "i": ["160 g Sugar", "0.8 g Lambda carrageenan , (3/8 teaspoon)", "0.4 g Guar gum , (1/8 teaspoon)", "5 g Rum extract", "1.2 g Nutmeg , freshly grated (2 teaspoons)", "0.4 g Almond extract , (1/4 teaspoon)", "600 g Whole milk", "200 g Heavy cream", "120 g Egg yolk(s) , (8 large yolks)", "8 Cloves , whole"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Dry blend powders", "Add extracts and nutmeg", "Blend eggnog base", "Cook sous vide", "Chill and strain eggnog"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/modernist-eggnog"}, {"id": 436, "t": "Vegan Eggnog Pudding", "c": "Baking", "d": "This eggnog pudding is a perfect way to celebrate the holiday season: thick and “custardy,” with all the cozy, vibrant notes of warming spices. After making my egg-free chocolate “custard,” I knew I could use the same technique of blending cashews with low-acyl gellan to produce a perfectly textured pudding that tastes just like eggnog, without adding eggs or dairy. The combination of nuts, gellan", "i": ["375 g Water", "100 g Raw cashews", "60 g Maple syrup", "55 g Coconut oil (virgin, unrefined)", "30 g Vanilla extract", "25 g Organic cane sugar", "2 g Kosher salt", "1 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F", "1 g Nutmeg , grated", "1 g Cinnamon , ground", "0.5 g Turmeric root powder , (optional, for color)"], "s": ["Boil cashews", "Blend and set custard", "Shear custard", "Portion pudding and serve"], "tips": ["Types of coconut oil and substitutions", "Hydrating hydrocolloids"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/eggnog-pudding"}, {"id": 437, "t": "How to Make Great Espresso", "c": "Baking", "d": "What’s the difference between an okay shot and an amazing shot? Following a recipe with weighed “ins” and “outs,” paying close attention to grind size and temperature, and dialing in the right extraction time will all help you make good espresso. However, there are additional things you can do to ensure that the shot you’re pulling will be great. Taken together, these best practices will guarantee", "i": [], "s": ["Espresso by the Numbers", "Clean the Brew Basket", "Grind Your Coffee Beans to the Right Size", "Dose Your Coffee", "Tamp", "Brew", "Drink"], "tips": ["Espresso Myths: Grind Freshness", "Espresso Myths: Precision Tamping", "Shots, shots, shots ..."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-great-espresso"}, {"id": 438, "t": "How to Make a Macchiato", "c": "Baking", "d": "The term macchiato translates to “spotted” or “stained” in Italian. In Italy, you can order an espresso stained with microfoamed milk (caffè macchiato) or microfoamed milk stained with espresso (latte macchiato). In the U.S., a macchiato refers to the former. Check out the video above to watch Sarah Dooley demonstrate how to make a macchiato. And if you want to master latte art, we’ve got you cove", "i": [], "s": ["Macchiato by the Numbers"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-a-macchiato"}, {"id": 439, "t": "How to Make a Latte", "c": "Dessert", "d": "“Latte” means milk in Italian. In the context of espresso, that simply means that this is the milkiest of all espresso drinks. While cappuccinos also have a fair amount of milk, the distinction between the two isn’t just the quantity of milk, which is greater in a latte. It’s also the fact that a latte has slightly less foam and is more thoroughly mixed rather than layered. Since there is a greate", "i": [], "s": ["Latte by the Numbers"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-a-latte"}, {"id": 440, "t": "How to Make a Mocha", "c": "Baking", "d": "While a mocha is basically a chocolate-flavored latte, it can be any size, it can have a lot of foam or very little foam, or it can have dry foam spooned on top. In fact, it can be anything you want. There are two keys to making a mocha with the best chocolate flavor: using a good chocolate syrup and adding the chocolate syrup to the pulled shot of espresso after it has cooled down slightly. Addin", "i": [], "s": ["Mocha by the Numbers"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-a-mocha"}, {"id": 441, "t": "How to Make a Cappuccino", "c": "Baking", "d": "The standard morning coffee order in Italy, a cappuccino is a single shot of espresso combined with microfoamed milk in about a 1:2 ratio. There are a couple of different ways to make a cappuccino: You can pour in a layer of milk and spoon over dry milk foam, or you can free-pour microfoamed milk into the espresso, which is demonstrated in the video above. PRO TIP: For the best appearance, try to ", "i": [], "s": ["Cappuccino by the Numbers"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-a-cappuccino"}, {"id": 442, "t": "How to Make an Americano", "c": "Drink", "d": "An Americano is essentially a diluted espresso drink, in which an espresso shot is diluted with hot water. The level of dilution is entirely up to you, but we like to use about a 1:2 ratio of espresso to hot water. Check out the video above to watch Sarah Dooley demonstrate how to make an Americano. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Americano by the Numbers"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-an-americano"}, {"id": 443, "t": "How to Make a Flat White", "c": "Baking", "d": "A flat white has a similar ratio of espresso to microfoamed milk as a latte, but it has less foam. To accomplish this, it’s best to simply introduce less air into the milk during the steaming process by submerging the steaming wand head into the milk earlier than you would when steaming milk for a latte. However, like a latte, since there’s a large quantity of microfoamed milk, you’ll want to heat", "i": [], "s": ["Flat White by the Numbers"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-a-flat-white"}, {"id": 444, "t": "Vanilla-Chamomile Syrup", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you like starting off your mornings with a vanilla latte, you’ll want to make this vanilla-chamomile syrup and have it around all the time. As opposed to the vanilla-flavored syrups you find at grocery stores, this syrup uses whole vanilla beans for intense vanilla flavor. Adding a small amount of dried chamomile complements and heightens vanilla’s floral notes, taking an already aromatic syrup", "i": ["250 g Water", "108 g Sugar", "108 g Glucose syrup", "3 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped, seeds and pods reserved", "1 g Chamomile , dried blossoms", "1 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Make simple syrup", "Steep then strain"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vanilla-chamomile-syrup"}, {"id": 445, "t": "Pumpkin Spice Syrup", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Instead of buying the (overpriced) seasonal syrup from that one big coffee brand, you should make our pumpkin spice syrup. By steeping a whole vanilla bean, whole cinnamon sticks, fragrant cloves, and fresh ginger into a not-too-sweet syrup, we created a syrup that we’d put up against any pre-made version out there. save Print", "i": ["250 g Water", "108 g Sugar", "108 g Glucose syrup", "25 g Fresh ginger root , peeled and sliced into 1/4-inch-thick coins", "10 g Cinnamon stick(s)", "1 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped, seeds and pod reserved", "1 g Cloves , (15 pieces)", "1 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Make simple syrup", "Steep then strain"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pumpkin-spice-syrup"}, {"id": 446, "t": "Chocolate Syrup", "c": "Baking", "d": "This chocolate syrup will allow you to make a mocha that’s just as good, if not better, than the one at your favorite local coffee haunt. A stabilized simple syrup—a syrup made with both sugar and glucose syrup—is used as the base, which ensures the syrup won’t turn grainy and the chocolate remains evenly distributed. I added two kinds of high-quality chocolate: a single-origin cocoa powder loaded", "i": ["250 g Water", "108 g Sugar", "108 g Glucose syrup", "1 g Kosher salt", "120 g Meridian Kokoa Kamili cocoa powder", "60 g Milk chocolate , 38% Cacao Barry, pistoles or chopped"], "s": ["Make simple syrup", "Whisk in cocoa powder and chocolate"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chocolate-syrup"}, {"id": 447, "t": "Leftover Latte Ice Cream", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Coffee ice cream—rich, creamy, with a robust coffee flavor and a little caffeine kick—is one of the best ice cream flavors out there. It’s also a really good way to use up leftover lattes. Leftover lattes? I don’t mean the dregs of lattes left around a coffee shop. I mean all the lattes you’ve made as you’ve practiced and perfected making latte art like a pro barista. Like anything worth doing wel", "i": ["1.4 kg Coffee-flavored milk , (6 cups, from eight 6-ounce lattes), divided", "380 g Sugar , (25% of weight of milk plus egg yolks)", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Guar gum , (1/2 teaspoon)", "120 g Egg yolk(s) , optional and recommended (8 large yolks)", "12 g Vanilla extract , optional"], "s": ["Make ice cream base", "Chill ice cream base", "Churn ice cream base", "Freeze, then serve", "Make ahead and storage", "We all scream for ice cream!"], "tips": ["Blender anglaise", "CAUTION: How to safely use liquid nitrogen"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/latte-ice-cream"}, {"id": 448, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Pull Shots From Your Freezer With Espresso Ice Cubes", "c": "Drink", "d": "Freezing coffee into ice cubes is a great trick for icing down coffee beverages of all kinds without diluting their coffee flavor. But there’s a whole lot more you can do with them than just dunking them into an iced coffee. By batching a bunch of espresso shots, you can make a whole tray of ice cubes of very high-quality coffee, and you can use them as (literal) building blocks for a variety of c", "i": [], "s": ["Americanos on Demand", "Chill Espresso Martinis", "Frappuccinos!", "Make a Pan Sauce", "Shaved Espresso Ice", "Have some fun with your espresso, people!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/espresso-shot-ice-cubes"}, {"id": 449, "t": "Espresso: Defined", "c": "Baking", "d": "Espresso is a method for making coffee. Even though we often use the word “espresso” to refer to a coffee drink, espresso refers specifically to a process in which coffee grounds and hot water are combined under pressure to almost instantaneously produce coffee. The coffee produced by this method, when executed correctly, is viscous and full-bodied, highly aromatic, and delicious. Another way of t", "i": [], "s": ["Anatomy of a Shot"], "tips": ["Espresso Myths: Magical Crema"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/espresso-defined"}, {"id": 450, "t": "Basic Espresso Theory", "c": "Baking", "d": "Mastering espresso starts with a basic understanding of the core variables in the espresso-making process. This is often referred to as Basic Espresso Theory. You may think that something as nominally simple as making coffee wouldn’t require some grand unifying theory. After all, a shot of espresso only has two ingredients: hot water and ground coffee beans. And yet, much like other culinary under", "i": [], "s": ["Brew Ratio", "Brew Time", "Brew Temperature"], "tips": ["Espresso Myths: The God Shot"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/basic-espresso-theory"}, {"id": 451, "t": "The Elements of an Espresso Shot", "c": "Baking", "d": "Whether you’re working with a new machine or are new to espresso, it’s helpful to set some basic parameters for the extraction process. Think of these parameters as a basic recipe for espresso. If you want to broaden your understanding of how different variables can affect your results, you should start by calculating and recording the brew ratio, brew time, and brew temperature for every shot you", "i": [], "s": ["Dry Coffee Dose", "Target Brew Ratio (1:2)", "Brew Time", "Brew Water Temperature", "Taste the Extraction", "Geek Out With a Refractometer"], "tips": ["Why weigh? Let us explain."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-espresso-recipe"}, {"id": 452, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Espresso Drinks", "c": "Drink", "d": "Ordering espresso drinks can be daunting: There are so many terms to remember and so many options. This guide explains what goes into each drink and how they’re typically served, so you can pick the perfect one to suit your mood. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Espresso", "Ristretto", "Macchiato", "Caffè Corretto", "Espresso con Panna", "Cortado/Gibraltar", "Cappuccino", "Americano", "Flat White", "Affogato"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/drink-ratios"}, {"id": 453, "t": "Sourcing Great Coffee", "c": "Baking", "d": "A cup of espresso is only as good as the coffee you use to make it. Many people believe that coffee for espresso must always be dark and highly caffeinated; others think that the coffee must have “espresso” emblazoned on its bag. These are myths. In fact, espresso can be made from any kind of coffee bean—remember, espresso is a brewing method, not a type of bean. That being said, not all coffee be", "i": [], "s": ["Always Buy Whole-Bean Coffee", "Freshly Roasted Is Best", "Avoid Oily Beans", "Look for Beans Sealed in an Airtight Bag or Container"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beans"}, {"id": 454, "t": "Choosing the Right Grinder for Espresso", "c": "Baking", "d": "Dialing in the perfect grind for coffee beans requires constant fine-tuning, even for professional baristas. Several variables can affect the quality of ground coffee, including how freshly roasted the beans are, the humidity and temperature conditions under which they’ve been stored, and the means by which they’ve been ground. And a grind that’s either too fine or too coarse can affect the textur", "i": [], "s": ["Choosing the Right Grinder for Espresso", "Blade Grinders", "Burr Grinders", "What to Look for in a Burr Grinder", "Our Recommended Grinder: Baratza Sette 30"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grinders"}, {"id": 455, "t": "Steaming Milk for Espresso Drinks", "c": "Baking", "d": "Steaming milk may seem simple, but it’s difficult to do well. The key is to remember that there are two phases to steaming: aerating, which baristas call “stretching”; and emulsifying, which baristas call “texturing.” You need to do both to have a creamy, velvety batch of milk with enough body to create latte art or a great cappuccino. To aerate milk, place the steam wand’s tip into the milk and t", "i": [], "s": ["Fill your pitcher", "Purge the steam wand", "Get set", "Stretch (aerate) and texture (emulsify) the milk", "Turn off the steam valve", "Remove the pitcher; wipe the steam wand immediately", "Tap out the air bubbles; give it a swirl", "Pour the steamed milk into a drink and/or make latte art"], "tips": ["How much power should I use?", "Here’s another walk-through"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/steaming-milk-for-espresso-drinks"}, {"id": 456, "t": "Mastering Latte Art", "c": "Baking", "d": "We’ll be honest: Making latte art is hard. Would-be baristas are often deterred by a couple of crappy latte pours, which is a shame because you don’t just get better at it overnight. We considered making a ChefSteps-style how-to video for pouring a rosetta, but we decided against it. Even if we show a few beautiful pours, it’s not going to make you a latte artist. The only way to learn is by tryin", "i": [], "s": ["Begin with the cup tilted slightly away from you", "Pour steamed milk into the center of the cup", "Drop the pitcher closer to the cup; speed up your pour", "Wiggle", "Untilt the cup, slow down, raise the pitcher a half an inch, and finish the rosetta", "Making a latte in real time", "Latte Art Designs"], "tips": ["Charles Babinski on Latte Art"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/latte-art"}, {"id": 457, "t": "Chef Recs: Essential Espresso Equipment", "c": "Baking", "d": "Congratulations, hot shot! You now know all about the mechanics and science behind making espresso. You probably think you’re all set to start an award-winning café in sunny Napoli. Not so fast. While you might think you’ve got everything you need—you’ve got some milk and some nondairy alternatives; you have good beans and a quality grinder; you have the machine—there’s a lot of espresso-making eq", "i": [], "s": ["Tamper", "Gram Scale", "Milk Pitcher", "Black Microfiber Towels", "Cleaning Powder or Tablets", "Flathead Screwdriver", "Knock Box", "Shot Glasses", "Shot Timer", "Accessories"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/essential-equipment-for-making-espresso-at-home"}, {"id": 458, "t": "A Visual History of Espresso", "c": "Baking", "d": "We’re always fascinated by the evolution of kitchen tools and cooking equipment, and the espresso machine is no exception. So when we asked Scott Callender at La Marzocco to help us map out a history of espresso, imagine our delight when he invited us into a warehouse basement under the La Marzocco office, where a vast collection of antique espresso machines, arranged by date, sat unassumingly on ", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/a-visual-history-of-espresso"}, {"id": 459, "t": "Anatomy of An Espresso Machine", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’ve ever found yourself staring at your reflection in one of the many gleaming metal surfaces of an espresso machine, wondering what the heck is going on inside, you’re not alone. Underneath all those dials and knobs and pressure gauges is a complex network of wires, pipes, and heating coils, designed to produce water and steam at your command in the precise temperature ranges and amounts ne", "i": [], "s": ["Espresso Machine Components"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/anatomy-of-an-espresso-machine"}, {"id": 460, "t": "5 Chefs 5 Ways: Thanksgiving Leftovers", "c": "Baking", "d": "One of the best parts—perhaps the best part—of Thanksgiving is leftovers. And as much as we like to eat slapped-together turkey sandwiches with cranberry sauce (and smothered in gravy) and stuffing waffled to crispy perfection (and smothered in gravy), T-Day leftovers can be used to create all sorts of other crazy things. Check out the video above to watch as our five chefs go nuts with Thanksgivi", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/5-chefs-thanksgiving-leftover-5-ways"}, {"id": 461, "t": "2022 Thanksgiving Hotline Q&A", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "You’re making a Thanksgiving feast, but you’ve got questions. Well, we’re here to help! Studio Pass members can ask about anything and everything related to Thanksgiving in the comments section below, and our chefs—Grant Crilly, Nicholas Gavin, Kyl Haselbauer, and Matthew Woolen–will answer to the best of their abilities. We’re putting this page up well in advance of Turkey Day, and they’ll try to", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/2022-thanksgiving-hotline-q-a"}, {"id": 462, "t": "The ChefSteps Thanksgiving Game Plan: Ultimate Edition", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "For most people, the most challenging cooking project they’ll ever undertake is preparing an entire Thanksgiving meal from scratch. But you’re not most people. Turkey and all the sides? Child’s play. Tack on a pie? Sure thing. Making the bread that goes into the stuffing? You’re on all day. Well, we’ve got a challenge for you. The Ultimate ChefSteps Thanksgiving meal has everything you’d expect fr", "i": [], "s": ["What’s in the game plan", "Before you begin", "The Menu", "The Shopping List", "The Prep List", "The Schedule"], "tips": ["“But I like using my Notes app on my phone!”", "“But I want the prep list on my Notes app, too!”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-thanksgiving-game-plan"}, {"id": 463, "t": "The ChefSteps Thanksgiving Game Plan: Express Edition", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "If you want to get a full Thanksgiving meal on the table with as little stress and anxiety as possible, this game plan’s for you. The menu has everything you could want on T-day—turkey, stuffing, potatoes, cranberry sauce, gravy, a vegetable side, and a sweet and creamy pumpkin pie pudding—and each recipe was chosen to make the meal’s preparation as streamlined as possible. Some can be prepared fa", "i": [], "s": ["What’s in the game plan", "Before you begin", "The Menu", "The Shopping List", "The Prep List", "The Schedule"], "tips": ["“But I like using my Notes app on my phone!”", "“But I want the prep list on my Notes app, too!”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/express-thanksgiving-game-plan"}, {"id": 464, "t": "Dutch Baby With Berries and Crème Fraîche With Nik Sharma", "c": "Baking", "d": "Easy but elegant, a Dutch baby is what you serve when you have guests over for breakfast or brunch and you want to impress. It’s basically a super fluffy pancake, so the batter comes together quickly in a blender: flour, milk, sugar, and melted butter. Blending incorporates air into the batter, giving the Dutch baby its impressively fluffy volume. You could add all kinds of things to flavor the ba", "i": ["3 Egg(s) , large, room temperature", "120 g Milk , whole, room temperature", "60 g All-purpose flour", "12 g Sugar", "0.5 g Green cardamom , ground (1/4 teaspoon), or 1 teaspoon vanilla extract", "56 g Butter , unsalted, cubed, room temperature, divided", "Crème fraîche , for serving , as needed", "Berries , or jam, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Preheat pan and oven", "Prepare batter", "Bake Dutch baby", "Garnish and serve", "Explore The Road to Cooking"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dutch-baby-with-raspberry-jam-and-creme-fraiche-with-nik-sharma"}, {"id": 465, "t": "The Best Pie Doughs: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you love pie—and you do, you love pie—you love pie crust. After all, what’s a pie without the flaky, tender, crumbly, rich pastry that serves as an edible vessel for sweet and savory fillings of all kinds? But there are just so many pie dough recipes out there, even though all of them have basically the same list of ingredients. Some tell you to get out a food processor or stand mixer, others i", "i": [], "s": ["The infographic", "The Lee Bros. Southern Cookbook, Matt and Ted Lee", "Culinary Institute of America", "Stella Parks (Serious Eats)", "ChefSteps pâte brisée", "King Arthur Baking", "Art of the Pie, Kate McDermott", "The Fannie Farmer Cookbook", "The Pie and Pastry Bible, Rose Levy Beranbaum", "Professional Baking, Wayne Gisslen", "ChefSteps pie dough", "So...which pie crust is the best?!?", "Ok, now make some pie. Go!"], "tips": ["Before we begin: pie science"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/parametric-pie-dough"}, {"id": 466, "t": "Cran-pari Negroni Sbagliato", "c": "Baking", "d": "A Negroni is a classic cocktail for a reason: the bitterness of Campari, the sweetness of sweet vermouth, and the floral, juniper notes in gin come together for an elegant, eminently sippable drink that also just happens to be beautiful. While almost everyone is familiar with a Negroni, not as many people know about its lighter, brighter, and more bubbly cousin: the Negroni sbagliato. The “mistake", "i": ["Ice, as needed", "28 g Dolin Vermouth De Chambery Dry , (1 ounce)", "56 g Cran-pari (Cranberry Aperitif) , (2 ounces)", "Orange peel , fresh, peeled into a strip , as needed", "85 g Prosecco , chilled (3 ounces)"], "s": ["Mix and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cran-pari-negroni-sbagliato"}, {"id": 467, "t": "Cran-pari (Cranberry Aperitif)", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "If you like to sip on Campari cocktails during the long, leisurely meals of the holiday season, this recipe’s for you. That’s right, a Campari-like aperitif made with cranberries. Transforming sweet and tart cranberries into a bitters is pretty straightforward, although it did require a fair amount of testing to get the flavor, color, and texture just right. Using vodka as the base alcohol made se", "i": ["1 Orange(s)", "200 g Cranberries , fresh or frozen (thawed if using frozen)", "110 g Sugar", "500 g Vodka", "8 g Pectinex Ultra SP-L", "10 g Dried orange peel , optional", "2 g Gentian root , dried, optional (1 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Rhubarb root , dried, optional (3/4 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Angelica root , dried, optional (3/4 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Wormwood , dried, optional (1 tablespoon)", "1.5 g Siberian ginseng , dried, optional (1 1/4 teaspoons)"], "s": ["Peel orange", "Muddle cranberries", "Cook sous vide to infuse Cran-pari", "Strain"], "tips": ["Sealing jars “fingertip tight” for sous vide cooking"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cran-pari"}, {"id": 468, "t": "Green Bean Casserole Chaat", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Green bean casserole is a traditional side dish at Thanksgiving, but I’ve found it’s usually completely ignored. Every year, I try to jazz it up with a whimsical approach to making it more flavorful: making it “chatpata,” a Hindi adjective that’s used to describe spicy and tangy foods, including the vast and varied world of snacks known as chaat. Chaat means “to lick,” and it refers to how good th", "i": ["500 g Water", "350 g Tamarind pulp", "50 g Medjool dates , pitted", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "1.5 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon) divided, plus extra as needed", "500 g Green beans , fresh, trimmed and cut on bias into 1-inch pieces", "100 g Cilantro , fresh leaves and tender stems (1 bunch)", "50 g Mint , fresh leaves (1 bunch)", "4 Thai chile(s) , fresh, stemmed and roughly chopped", "56 g Butter , unsalted, divided, plus extra for greasing baking dish", "215 g Yellow onion(s) , (1/2 large onion) cut into 1/4-inch dice", "0.2 g Red pepper flakes , (1/8 teaspoon)", "50 g All-purpose flour", "340 g Coconut milk", "0.3 g Cayenne pepper , (1/8 teaspoon)", "0.3 g Nutmeg , ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "495 g Greek yogurt , full fat", "20 g Sugar", "Fried shallots , store-bought, for garnish , as needed", "Sev , (crunchy chickpea flour noodles) store-bought, for garnish , as needed", "Potato Chips , homemade or store-bought, for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare tamarind chutney", "Blanch green beans", "Prepare cilantro-mint chutney", "Cook onions", "Make roux", "Bake casserole", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/green-bean-casserole-chaat"}, {"id": 469, "t": "Spice-Crusted Pork Spareribs With Carla Lalli Music", "c": "Baking", "d": "These spice-crusted spareribs are a good example of how simple recipes don’t have to sacrifice on flavor. Cutting a rack up into individual ribs helps with distributing seasoning, and the irregular dimensions of the ribs result in a lot of craggy, crispy, and browned surfaces. Coarsely ground spices further improve the texture of the cooked ribs, and since the ribs are exposed on all sides to heat", "i": ["15 g Coriander seeds", "10 g Black peppercorns", "5 g Red pepper flakes , (1 1/2 teaspoons)", "1 St. Louis-style pork ribs , slab, (about 1.4 kg; 3 pounds total)", "12 g Kosher salt", "Extra-virgin olive oil , for drizzling , as needed", "60 g Water", "Cilantro , or mint, leaves, for serving , as needed", "Lime(s) , wedges, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Grind spices", "Separate and season ribs", "Roast ribs covered", "Uncover and finish cooking ribs", "Garnish ribs and serve", "Explore The Road to Cooking"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spice-crusted-pork-spareribs-with-carla-lalli-music"}, {"id": 470, "t": "Crispy and Juicy Chicken-Fried Turkey", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We’ve done turkey just about every way you can think of—yakitori-style, fried KFC-style, roasted, sous vide—but the very best way to cook turkey breast is to treat it like a chicken-fried steak. It’s simple to make; it can be eaten for breakfast, brunch, lunch, or dinner; it’s crispy and crunchy and juicy and tender, all at the same time; it’s delicious; and to top it all off, it comes with gravy.", "i": ["2 Turkey breast(s) , boneless, skinless (455–680 g each)", "450 g All-purpose flour , divided", "100 g Cornstarch", "10 g Baking soda", "22 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "10 g Not-So-Secret 12 Herbs & Spices Fried Chicken Seasoning , (optional, but recommended)", "6 Egg(s) , large", "50 g Cold water", "110 g Butter", "32 g Black pepper , coarsely ground, divided", "980 g Milk , whole", "8 g Granulated garlic", "Neutral oil , for frying , as needed"], "s": ["Pound turkey breasts", "Mix up dredge and egg wash", "Dredge turkey breasts", "Make gravy", "Fry turkey", "Cover with gravy and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crispy-and-juicy-chicken-fried-turkey"}, {"id": 471, "t": "Vegan Blender Bread Stuffing", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "How do you transform stuffing into a dish that’s gluten-free and vegan-friendly? Easy, just use blender bread! Blender bread is super easy to make, entirely gluten-free since it’s made with rice, and tasty in its own right; it has a porous crumb perfect for soaking up savory liquids; and it crisps up beautifully. The technical challenge of creating the creamy consistency provided by eggs, along wi", "i": ["1 recipe Quick & Easy Flourless Blender Bread , 2 mini loaves, cut into 1-inch cubes", "110 g Vegan butter", "1 Leek , large, trimmed, washed, white and light green parts finely chopped", "112 g Shiitake mushrooms , or maitake mushrooms, cleaned, trimmed, and roughly chopped (optional)", "90 g White onion(s) , cut into small dice", "80 g Celery , (2 ribs) cut into small dice", "1 Bay leaf , fresh", "950 g Vegetable stock", "17 g Parsley , fresh leaves and tender stems, roughly chopped", "4 g Sage , fresh, (about 10 leaves) roughly chopped", "4 g Rosemary , fresh, chopped", "4 g Thyme , fresh leaves, roughly chopped", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon)", "1.5 g Oregano , dried (3/4 teaspoon) (optional)", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/2 teaspoon)", "Extra-virgin olive oil, as needed"], "s": ["Cube and toast bread", "Sweat aromatics", "Marry the mix", "Bake stuffing and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/blender-bread-stuffing"}, {"id": 472, "t": "Perfect Sausage Stuffing", "c": "Baking", "d": "A great Thanksgiving stuffing needs to be savory, packed with aromatic herbs like sage and thyme, sweet with sweated onions, carrots, and celery, with a perfectly cooked, juicy center and a great crust on top. This version has all of that and more: big chunks of tender sausage and mushrooms, cooked just right, beautifully chewy sourdough bread for a little extra character, and a hit of Maggi Seaso", "i": ["455 g Sourdough bread , cut into 1-inch cubes", "115 g Butter , unsalted, divided", "400 g Italian sausage , removed from casing", "200 g Yellow onion(s) , cut into 1/4-inch dice (about 1/2 an onion)", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , minced (3 cloves)", "150 g Fennel bulb , trimmed, cored, and cut into 1/4-inch dice (about 1/2 a bulb)", "125 g Button mushrooms , quartered", "100 g Celery , cut into 1/4-inch dice", "50 g Carrot(s) , peeled and cut into 1/8-inch dice", "3 g Thyme , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "2 g Sage , fresh, finely chopped", "4 Egg(s) , large", "450 g Chicken stock , homemade or low-sodium store-bought stock", "20 g Maggi Seasoning", "15 g Parsley , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "2 g Kosher salt , (1/2 teaspoon)", "2 g Black pepper , freshly ground, (1 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Toast bread", "Cook sausage and aromatics", "Whisk egg mixture", "Assemble stuffing", "Bake and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sausage-and-mushroom-stuffing"}, {"id": 473, "t": "Perfect Cranberry Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "Making cranberry sauce is very simple: Cook some cranberries, sugar, and some warm spices together, and you’ve got something that’s perfectly acceptable to serve on Turkey Day. And yet there are a few things you can do to make a cranberry sauce that’s great. I think that the texture of your run-of-the-mill cranberry sauce is a little lacking, so I incorporate the flesh of a couple of oranges into ", "i": ["3 Orange(s) , divided", "120 g Sugar", "55 g Cointreau , or other liqueur such as amaretto (optional)", "1 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.2 g Cinnamon , ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "280 g Cranberries , fresh or frozen", "30 g Pistachios , sliced or roughly chopped"], "s": ["Process oranges", "Combine and cook the sauce", "Serve, or chill"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/perfect-cranberry-sauce"}, {"id": 474, "t": "Thrice-Baked Potatoes", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "The best twice-baked potato? Bake it three times! Or at least that’s what I initially thought. Twice-baked potatoes have a lot going for them—cheese, sour cream, bacon, and chives mixed with potato, come on!—but they also almost always have leathery skins. A third trip in the oven seemed like a simple way to give them a boost. But it wasn’t so simple. My first impulse was to air fry the scooped sk", "i": ["1 kg Russet potato(es) , (2 large potatoes)", "Neutral oil , such as canola , as needed", "345 g Sour cream", "325 g Gruyère cheese , grated, divided", "455 g Bacon , preferably slab, cut into small dice", "17 g Chives", "9 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "4 g Black pepper , freshly ground"], "s": ["Bake potatoes", "Cook bacon", "Scoop and mix potatoes", "Bake potatoes second time", "Cut and fry potato skins", "Broil for third bake"], "tips": ["How to calculate baker’s percentage"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/thrice-baked-potato"}, {"id": 475, "t": "Ultra-Cheesy Pommes Aligot", "c": "Baking", "d": "While you can argue about whether pommes aligot is the most delicious combination of potato and cheese in existence, it’s hard to argue that it isn’t the most impressive. A potato purée that you can stretch anywhere from 6 to 10 feet, as if it were some mutant melted mozzarella? Poutine could never. Getting pommes aligot to take on that texture is a little tricky, as you know if you’ve ever had a ", "i": ["550 g Yukon Gold potato(es) , scrubbed", "280 g Milk , whole", "115 g Butter , unsalted, cut into 1/2-inch dice", "20 g Cornstarch", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon) plus more as needed", "2 g Citric acid , (1/2 teaspoon)", "250 g Cheese curds , homemade or store-bought, finely ground"], "s": ["Cook potatoes", "Peel and process potatoes into a purée", "Heat and fold in cheese"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultra-cheesy-pommes-aligot"}, {"id": 476, "t": "Fluffy Mashed Potatoes", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "The best fluffy mashed potatoes are the ones you can flop a spoonful of on a plate and they’ll hold their shape. They’re designed to be sculpted into a well and filled with gravy. Thing is, you can get that effect with not-so fluffy mashed potatoes, too. You know the ones: gummy and leaden, you reach for the butter before you even think about the gravy. Making good fluffy mashed potatoes just come", "i": ["750 g Russet potato(es) , peeled, cut into 1-inch-thick pieces", "180 g Butter , unsalted", "90 g Milk , whole", "6 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed"], "s": ["Cook potatoes", "Heat milk and butter", "Dry and pass potatoes", "Incorporate milk mixture, serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/perfect-fluffy-mashed-potatoes"}, {"id": 477, "t": "Fully Loaded Duchess Potatoes", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’re going to take the trouble to make duchess potatoes—a potato purée enriched with egg yolks and piped out all fancy-like—you might as well load them up with flavor. A fully loaded baked potato is straightforward. Fully loaded duchess potatoes? Not so much. Since duchess potatoes are piped into pretty rosettes, incorporating the large amount of fat characteristic of a loaded baked potato in", "i": ["225 g Bacon , sliced", "800 g Yukon Gold potato(es) , scrubbed", "30 g Garlic clove(s) , (6 large cloves) peeled", "100 g Butter , unsalted, room temperature", "150 g Sour cream , divided", "10 g Parmesan , finely grated", "8 g Kosher salt", "80 g Egg yolk(s) , (5 large yolks)", "15 g Chives , thinly sliced"], "s": ["Cook and chop bacon", "Cook potatoes", "Peel and pass potatoes", "Load up the potato mixture", "Pipe and bake potatoes", "Pipe in sour cream"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fully-loaded-duchess-potatoes"}, {"id": 478, "t": "Perfect Pomme Purée", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "If you’ve ever wondered how to make pomme purée, the silkiest, smoothest mashed potatoes beloved by Michelin-starred chefs all around the world, you’re in luck: We have a step-by-step method you can use to replicate them at home. This dish is often referred to as Robuchon potatoes, in honor of Joël Robuchon, the chef who mastered the preparation. Robuchon’s innovation was, in retrospect, pretty si", "i": ["950 g Fingerling potatoes , scrubbed", "455 g Butter , unsalted, cut into a 1/2-inch dice, room temperature", "280 g Milk , whole", "8 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Cook potatoes", "Peel and pass potatoes", "Heat with milk", "Pass purée and serve", "Make ahead and storage", "French and a little fussy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/perfect-pomme-puree"}, {"id": 479, "t": "Creamy Smashed Potatoes", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Smashed potatoes are delicious and easy to make and hard to mess up: boil some spuds, mash ’em with a fork, and mix in some dairy and fat and you’ve got an excellent side dish for almost any meal. Great smashed potatoes, however, are just as easy to make, and all they require is some attention to detail. First, pick the right kind of potatoes; second, cook them with a little precision; third, inco", "i": ["400 g Fingerling potatoes , thoroughly scrubbed", "20 g Kosher salt , plus more to taste", "150 g Butter , unsalted, softened", "100 g Heavy cream , room temperature or warmed", "25 g Chives , sliced", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed"], "s": ["Boil potatoes", "Mash potatoes with cream and butter", "Fold in chives and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smashed-potatoes"}, {"id": 480, "t": "How to Butcher, French, and Tie a Prime Rib", "c": "Baking", "d": "A standing prime rib roast is the king of holiday centerpieces: a hulking piece of the best cut of beef, cooked until its exterior is bronzed and burnished and its interior is juicy and rosy pink. And while you can cook a prime rib without doing much to it other than showering it with salt, with a little smart knife work and some judicious use of kitchen twine, you can transform it into a roast th", "i": [], "s": ["Cut reference points and score membrane", "Begin separating meat from bones", "Remove membrane", "Peel membrane away from bones", "Remove fat, meat, and membrane around rib bones", "Clean bones", "Separate bones from roast", "Remove cartilage", "Tie roast", "That’s it! You’re ready to cook that prime rib!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-prepare-prime-rib"}, {"id": 481, "t": "How to Tie a Butcher’s Knot", "c": "Baking", "d": "Tying a butcher’s knot is a useful skill that every omnivorous cook should have in their bag of tricks. A butcher’s knot is commonly used to tie roasts and steaks, making them more compact and evenly shaped, which in turn ensures even cooking. It’s a simple slipknot, which means it’s quick to execute and you can cinch it tight by sliding the knot up the string. Of course, you don’t have to use a b", "i": [], "s": ["Tie all the roasts!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-tie-a-butcher-s-knot"}, {"id": 482, "t": "Measure by Weight: Why You Should Use a Scale", "c": "Other", "d": "We’ve said it before and we’ll say it again: Use a scale for measuring ingredients! While using measuring cups and spoons is common practice for many, if not most, home cooks, using a scale is more accurate, more precise, and ultimately more convenient. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Measuring by weight is more accurate and precise", "Measuring by weight is efficient", "The scales we recommend", "Put your scale to good use!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/why-you-should-use-a-scale"}, {"id": 483, "t": "Lamb Barbacoa With Claudette Zepeda", "c": "Baking", "d": "Lamb barbacoa is culinary alchemy at its easiest: You transform a relatively tough lamb leg or shoulder into fork-tender and juicy meat by smothering it with an adobo made from dried chiles and spices and cooking it for hours in aromatic banana leaves. There’s nothing fussy about the preparation, but you do need to pay attention to technique. The banana leaves need to be warmed so they become plia", "i": ["1 Pineapple", "3 Fresh banana leaves", "1.8 kg Lamb , boneless leg or shoulder", "225 g Lard", "36 g Kosher salt , plus more as needed", "5 Avocado leaves , (optional), divided", "2 Hoja santa , fresh (optional)", "950 g Water", "6 Morita chile(s) , dried, stemmed and seeded", "14 Ancho chile(s) , dried, stemmed and seeded", "1 Onion(s) , yellow, quartered", "3 Garlic , cloves", "6 g Allspice , ground", "6 g Cinnamon , ground", "15 g Sugar", "115 g Distilled vinegar", "Avocado(s) , thinly sliced for garnish , as needed", "Red onion(s) , thinly sliced for garnish , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves for garnish , as needed", "Lime(s) , wedges for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare pineapple", "Warm banana leaves", "Prepare adobo", "Season lamb and sear", "Roast lamb and serve", "Explore The Road to Cooking"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/lamb-barbacoa-with-claudette-zepeda"}, {"id": 484, "t": "Air-Fried Crispy Fish Fillets With Fennel and Pickled Lemon Salad", "c": "Baking", "d": "Light, crispy, delicate, and super moist fried fish is a tall order for the home cook—especially without a fryer. Fish can go from raw to overcooked in a flash, so the high, consistent heat produced by a vat of hot oil is well suited to the task. But an air fryer can make crispy fish fillets, too, and it can produce a result that’s equally delicious—if we make some careful adjustments. To keep the", "i": ["125 g Mayonnaise", "25 g Shallot(s) , (1 medium shallot) finely chopped", "50 g Dill pickles , cut into a small dice", "15 g Lemon juice , fresh, from 1 lemon", "5 g Parsley , fresh leaves, finely chopped", "5 g Old Bay seasoning", "100 g Panko breadcrumbs", "55 g Canola oil", "2 Lingcod , or halibut fillets, 1/2-inch-thick, 115–140 g each", "75 g All-purpose flour", "2 Egg(s) , lightly beaten", "Kosher salt, as needed", "1 Fennel bulb , trimmed, cored, and thinly sliced on a mandoline; fronds reserved", "0.5 recipe Fresh and Bright Instant-Pickled Lemons", "Extra-virgin olive oil, as needed"], "s": ["Make tartar sauce", "Grind and toast breadcrumbs", "Bread fish fillets", "Air fry fillets", "Make fennel salad", "0.5 recipe", "Finish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-crispy-fish-fillets-with-fennel-and-pickled-lemon-salad"}, {"id": 485, "t": "Air-Fried Pork Chops With Roasted Apple and Brussels Sprouts Salad", "c": "Baking", "d": "There are few combinations that are as evocative of fall and winter as the timeless trifecta of roasted pork chops, apples, and Brussels sprouts. Sweet, savory, and meaty, these ingredients work well together on the plate, but they’re tough to cook at the same time. When prepped, they’re typically different sizes and dimensions, and they tend to cook at different rates. With some careful planning,", "i": ["15 g Light brown sugar", "2 g Cumin seeds , ground (1 teaspoon)", "2 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce) , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Granulated onion , (1/4 teaspoon)", "1 g Granulated garlic , (1/4 teaspoon)", "1 g Sage , dried (2 teaspoons), divided", "2 Pork chop(s) , boneless, 2 inches thick, about 385 g each", "7 g Kosher salt , divided", "60 g Dijon mustard , divided", "400 g Brussels sprouts", "1 Apple(s)", "10 g Vegetable oil", "30 g Honey", "15 g Lemon juice", "15 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "5 g Parsley , finely chopped"], "s": ["Season pork chops", "Prep Brussels sprouts and apple", "Air fry chops, sprouts, and apples", "Prepare dressing", "Finish salad, slice pork, and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-pork-chops-with-roasted-apple-and-brussels-sprouts-salad"}, {"id": 486, "t": "Air-Fried Beef and Broccoli", "c": "Baking", "d": "Beef and broccoli is about as classic a combination for most Americans as peanut butter and jelly. While the dish is believed to have originated from the Chinese dish “gai lan chao niu rou” (芥兰炒牛肉), or “Chinese broccoli fried beef,” beef and broccoli as we know it came about because early Chinese immigrants couldn’t find Chinese broccoli. Instead, they went with the American cultivar, with its lar", "i": ["455 g Flank steak", "75 g Soy sauce , divided", "30 g Brown sugar , divided", "250 g Broccoli , (1 small head), cut into 1-inch florets, stem sliced crosswise into 1/4-inch-thick pieces", "100 g White onion(s) , (1/2 small onion) sliced into 1/4-inch-thick pieces", "15 g Vegetable oil", "8 g Ginger , fresh, finely grated (1-inch piece)", "5 g Garlic , (1 medium clove) finely grated", "150 g Beef Stock , homemade or store-bought low sodium stock", "8 g Cornstarch", "3 g Sesame oil , (1/2 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "Sesame seeds , toasted , as needed", "White rice , cooked (optional, for serving) , as needed"], "s": ["Slice and marinate beef", "Air fry beef and broccoli", "Simmer sauce", "Char-broil the beef", "Sauce and serve"], "tips": ["Partially freeze meat for easier slicing"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-beef-and-broccoli"}, {"id": 487, "t": "Air-Fried Tonkatsu (Japanese-Style Pork Cutlets)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "One of our favorite quick lunches is tonkatsu, Japanese-style pork cutlets. There’s something about a juicy piece of pork locked in a crisp panko crust that’s just so satisfying to eat. Smothered in a good tonkatsu sauce with rice and shredded cabbage on the side? Game over. Tonkatsu is usually deep-fried, which is how the breaded cutlet develops a crust with substantial crunch. We wanted to get t", "i": ["100 g Panko breadcrumbs", "55 g Canola oil", "2 Pork chop(s) , boneless, about 1-inch-thick, 170–225 g each", "75 g Mayonnaise", "40 g All-purpose flour", "400 g Green cabbage , (1/2 head), cored and finely shredded", "Tonkatsu sauce, as needed", "Short-grain rice , cooked , as needed", "Lemon wedges, as needed"], "s": ["Toast breadcrumbs", "Pound pork into cutlets", "Bread cutlets", "Air fry cutlets", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-tonkatsu-japanese-style-pork-cutlet"}, {"id": 488, "t": "Chicken-Air-Fried Steak", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Chicken-fried steak is perfect for breakfast, lunch, or dinner, and even when it’s poorly executed, it’s still pretty good. Who can resist fried meat smothered in an unholy amount of gravy? Usually, making chicken-fried steak means heating up a pot of oil and making a mess of dishes, but with the help of an air fryer you can have this American classic on your table in under 30 minutes with a fract", "i": ["100 g Panko breadcrumbs", "65 g Canola oil , divided", "2 Top sirloin steak , 170–225 g each", "150 g Mayonnaise", "100 g All-purpose flour , divided", "200 g Green beans , trimmed", "9 g Kosher salt , divided", "17 g Black pepper , freshly ground, divided", "55 g Butter , unsalted", "490 g Milk , whole", "4 g Granulated garlic , (1 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Toast breadcrumbs", "Pound steaks", "Bread steaks", "Season green beans", "Air fry steaks and green beans", "Make gravy", "Finish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-chicken-fried-steak"}, {"id": 489, "t": "Air-Fried Charred Broccoli With Bagna Càuda", "c": "Baking", "d": "The best way to cook broccoli is to char it: The tips of the florets become crispy and taste toasty and nutty, while the stems stay tender-crisp and retain all the sweetness and slight bitterness of the cruciferous vegetable in its raw state. It can be a little tricky to hit that combination perfectly, but with an air fryer it’s very easy. All you need to do is cut the broccoli into relatively uni", "i": ["30 g Panko breadcrumbs", "90 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided", "Lemon zest , from 1 lemon, finely grated , as needed", "5 g Parsley , fresh leaves, minced", "455 g Broccoli , (1 large head)", "18 g Anchovies , (about 8 fillets) minced", "15 g Garlic clove(s) , (4 cloves) finely grated", "15 g Lemon juice , from 1/2 lemon"], "s": ["Toast breadcrumbs", "Prepare broccoli", "Air fry broccoli", "Make bagna càuda dressing", "Combine and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/charred-broccoli-and-bagna-cauda"}, {"id": 490, "t": "Air-Fried Brussels Sprouts With Chile-Tamarind Dressing", "c": "Baking", "d": "The best way to enjoy Brussels sprouts is to roast them, but that doesn’t mean you can just throw them into a hot oven and produce something worth serving. Ideally, they should have a deep roasted flavor, crispy edges, and a still-tender crunch at the core. They shouldn’t be overly charred, bitter, or mushy. The air fryer is a great tool for roasting Brussels sprouts to that perfect doneness. Forc", "i": ["455 g Brussels sprouts", "30 g Canola oil , or other neutral oil", "35 g Tamarind concentrate", "30 g Lime juice , fresh, from 1 lime", "25 g Fish sauce", "10 g Palm sugar , softened, or light brown sugar", "20 g Cashews , roasted, roughly chopped", "15 g Shallot(s) , (1/2 medium shallot) minced", "2 Thai chile(s) , dried, stemmed and coarsely ground", "4 g Mint , fresh leaves, roughly chopped, plus extra whole leaves for garnish", "4 g Cilantro , fresh leaves, roughly chopped, plus extra whole leaves for garnish"], "s": ["Trim and oil Brussels sprouts", "Air fry Brussels sprouts", "Prepare chile-tamarind dressing", "Dress Brussels sprouts and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-brussels-sprouts-with-chile-tamarind-dressing"}, {"id": 491, "t": "Air-Fried Teriyaki Wings", "c": "Baking", "d": "Fun fact: You can find more teriyaki spots in Seattle proper than all other fast-food brands combined, which makes teriyaki the city’s iconic fast-food item. The first teriyaki shop, Toshi’s Teriyaki, opened in 1976, and ever since, the city's been in love with the stuff. But Seattle’s teriyaki is less traditional Japanese food than it is a homegrown evolution of a style of cooking. “Teriyaki” is ", "i": ["900 g Chicken wings", "125 g Soy sauce", "125 g Mirin", "125 g Water", "100 g Sugar", "17 g Ginger , fresh, finely grated (1-inch piece)", "5 g Garlic , finely grated (1 medium clove)", "3 g Sesame seeds , (1 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Braise chicken wings", "Cool wings", "Reduce and finish teriyaki sauce", "Glaze and air fry wings", "Sauce and toss wings"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-teriyaki-wings"}, {"id": 492, "t": "Air-Fried Lemon Pepper Wings", "c": "Baking", "d": "Lemon pepper wings are an S-tier food, a perfect mix of crunch and spice punctuated by pops of tangy citrus, all of it giving way to moist, succulent meat. The mild astringency of the lemon makes your mouth water from the first bite, and it keeps you coming back for more. The main obstacle to good wings is you typically have to fry them. With our go-to technique for making wings in an air fryer—dr", "i": ["2 Lemon(s) , or 3 g store-bought dried lemon peel", "25 g Black peppercorns , plus more as needed", "22 g Kosher salt , divided", "5 g Citric acid", "4 g Sugar , (1 teaspoon)", "3 g Granulated garlic , (1 teaspoon)", "25 g All-purpose flour", "12 g Baking powder", "910 g Chicken wings", "100 g Water", "112 g Butter , unsalted, or ghee"], "s": ["Peel and dry lemon zest (one day in advance!)", "Grind spice blend", "Dredge wings", "Bake wings", "Cool wings", "Air fry wings", "Clarify butter while air frying wings", "Sauce and toss wings"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-lemon-pepper-wings"}, {"id": 493, "t": "Perfect Air-Fried Frozen French Fries", "c": "Baking", "d": "Air fryers are powerful tools that excel at preparing all kinds of stuff, but their greatest strength may just be that they can produce excellent French fries. Of course, an air fryer can’t fry potatoes in the same way a vat of oil can. But what air frying can do better than any method out there is quickly reheat and crisp frozen, pre-fried foods, like frozen French fries. This is because the supe", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 360 g Frozen French fries , preferably Ore-Ida Extra Crispy Fast Food French Fries - Kosher salt, as needed", "360 g Frozen French fries , preferably Ore-Ida Extra Crispy Fast Food French Fries - Kosher salt, as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Air fry until golden and crispy", "Sauce with those fries?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-frozen-french-fries"}, {"id": 494, "t": "Epic Air-Fried Chicken Wings", "c": "Baking", "d": "When it comes to pub grub, finger foods, and game-day goodies, chicken wings always reign supreme. Deep-fried wings were once king, but a new air-fried contender has come to challenge the crown. To air fry foods successfully, you need to play to your air fryer’s strengths. You can’t prepare foods the same way you would if you were deep frying—at least not if you want the same kind of crispy, crunc", "i": ["24 g All-purpose flour", "12 g Baking powder", "10 g Kosher salt", "2 g Black pepper , freshly ground, optional", "910 g Chicken wings", "100 g Water"], "s": ["Dredge wings", "Bake wings", "Cool wings", "Air fry wings", "Sauce or serve plain", "Get saucy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smart-oven-air-fried-chicken-wings"}, {"id": 495, "t": "Crispy Air-Fried Tofu", "c": "Baking", "d": "With a few tricks, you can transform a block of tofu into amazingly crispy, crunchy, oh-so-craveable nuggets by using an air fryer. The challenge with getting tofu ultra-crispy is its water content. Pressing the tofu first is standard practice for getting rid of some of its moisture, but it will make it more dense. To level up the eating experience, we tear the tofu (instead of cutting it into cub", "i": ["455 g Tofu , (1 package) firm", "6 g Neutral oil", "15 g Baking powder", "5 g Kosher salt , divided", "2 g Sugar , optional", "1.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground", "1.5 g White pepper , ground", "0.5 g Ginger , ground, optional", "0.5 g Five-spice powder , optional"], "s": ["Drain and press tofu", "Make spice blend", "Portion and season tofu", "Air fry tofu", "Season and serve"], "tips": ["10 minutes?! But my oven beeps after 5!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-crispy-craggly-tofu"}, {"id": 496, "t": "Crispy and Crunchy Golden Air-Fried Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "Everybody loves fried chicken, but no one loves frying. This is the dilemma for every home cook who craves juicy, tender, flavorful meat encased in a crispy, crunchy, golden-brown crust. But what if you could get nearly identical results without firing up a vat of hot oil? After a lot of testing and fiddling, and by taking into account an air fryer's strengths and weaknesses, we've come up with an", "i": ["18 g Black peppercorns , for spice mix", "18 g White pepper , for spice mix", "18 g Green peppercorns , for spice mix", "15 g Yellow mustard seeds , for spice mix", "5 g Celery seeds , for spice mix", "2.5 g Fennel seeds , for spice mix", "1 g Chile flakes , for spice mix", "5 g Granulated garlic , for spice mix", "5 g Granulated onion , for spice mix", "1.5 g Marjoram , dried, for spice mix", "1.5 g Ginger , ground, for spice mix", "1.6 kg Chicken leg(s) , (4 leg quarters)", "24 g Kosher salt , 1.5% total weight of chicken", "400 g Cultured lowfat buttermilk", "623 g Curly fries , (1 bag) store-bought frozen fries, thawed", "226 g Lay’s Brand Classic Potato Chips , (1 bag)", "35 g Canola oil"], "s": ["Make spice blend", "Split chicken legs", "Season chicken", "Process curly fries into crumbs", "Par-cook chicken and toast fry crumbs", "Cool chicken completely", "Build breading", "Bread chicken", "Spritz breaded chicken", "Air fry chicken and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-chicken"}, {"id": 497, "t": "Amazing Air-Fried Vegetarian Buffalo Cauliflower “Wings”", "c": "Baking", "d": "When cooked properly, cauliflower can take on a range of different textures: crispy, meaty, tender, and even creamy. When air fried properly, you can transform this bland brassica into crunchy, delectable nuggets. Double-dip those nuggets in a spicy Buffalo sauce and every bite packs a delicious punch. Cauliflower can be challenging to air fry because it’s about 90 percent water. If overcooked, it", "i": ["600 g Cauliflower , (1 head) cut into bite-size florets", "60 g Frank’s RedHot Original Sauce", "30 g Butter , unsalted, or any neutral oil", "60 g Water", "40 g All-purpose flour", "5 g Kosher salt", "Celery , stalks, cut into sticks, for serving (optional) , as needed", "Carrot(s) , peeled and cut into sticks, for serving (optional) , as needed", "Dipping sauce of choice , for serving , as needed", "60 g Chickpea (garbanzo) flour", "4 g Flaxseed meal"], "s": ["Dehydrate cauliflower florets", "Make Buffalo sauce", "Mix batter", "Sauce and batter cauliflower", "Air fry cauliflower", "Sauce again and serve"], "tips": ["Increase the heat", "Make it gluten-free", "Step up your celery game"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/amazing-air-fried-vegetarian-buffalo-cauliflower-wings"}, {"id": 498, "t": "Golden Air-Fried Sweet Potato Fries", "c": "Baking", "d": "These thick-cut sweet potato fries are a genuine surprise—perfectly crispy on the outside and soft on the inside, and all done in an air-fryer. The secret to this recipe is a quick pre-bake with a little steam, which hydrates the starches in the spiced flour-and-cornmeal coating so the exterior of each fry gets delightfully crunchy—instead of dry and sandy—once the heat from the super convection f", "i": ["50 g All-purpose flour", "50 g Cornmeal", "4 g Onion powder", "3 g Paprika", "2 g Garlic powder", "0.5 g Cayenne pepper", "0.5 g Oregano , dried", "600 g Sweet potatoe(s) , (1 large or 2 medium sweet potatoes) golden variety", "30 g Canola oil", "4 g Kosher salt", "50 g Water", "Dipping sauce of choice , for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Make dredge", "Peel and cut potatoes", "Coat in oil and season", "Dredge fries", "Par-cook fries", "Air fry until crispy", "Serve and enjoy!", "Looking for sauces and condiments?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crispy-cornmeal-sweet-taters"}, {"id": 499, "t": "Crispy Air-Fried Smashed Potatoes", "c": "Baking", "d": "In our search for the perfect spud, many contenders have laid claim to the crown—from thick-cut French fries to pomme purée and the ultimate potato salad. But now, we think we’ve found a new queen to reign supreme. These golden brown air-fried potatoes are the best of the best, thanks to a two-stage cooking process in which you boil the spuds until they're just tender, smash them, then slide them ", "i": ["680 g Baby potatoes", "Water , to cover potatoes , as needed", "18 g Kosher salt , divided", "Extra-virgin olive oil, as needed", "2 g Black pepper , ground", "5 g Rosemary , fresh, chopped", "2 Garlic clove(s) , coarsely chopped"], "s": ["Simmer those taters", "Smash ’em", "Preheat the air fryer", "Prep to fry", "Cook", "Finish"], "tips": ["10 minutes?! But my oven beeps after 5!", "Do a little dip"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-smashed-potatoes"}, {"id": 500, "t": "Smoky Rub Pork Shoulder With Gregory Gourdet", "c": "Baking", "d": "If there’s a secret to this smoky and deliciously tender slow-roasted pork shoulder, it’s patience. Preparing the marinade and cooking the roast couldn’t be easier. The marinade comes together in a couple of minutes, and uses spices, herbs, and chiles that should be pantry staples: smoky and hot dried chipotles, fiery dried red chiles, fragrant thyme and oregano, and citrusy coriander seeds. Roast", "i": ["3 Chipotle chile(s) , dried, stemmed", "2 Thai chile(s) , dried, stemmed", "10 g Coriander seeds", "60 g Coconut sugar", "27 g Kosher salt", "9 g Smoked paprika (hot/picante)", "3 g Thyme , dried (1 tablespoon)", "1.5 g Oregano , dried (1 tablespoon)", "5 Lime(s) , zested and juiced", "2 Orange(s) , zested and juiced", "1 Pork shoulder , boneless, (about 2.25 kg; 5 pounds), preferably with fat cap"], "s": ["Make marinade", "Marinate pork", "Roast pork and serve", "Rest and carve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smoky-rub-pork-shoulder-with-gregory-gourdet"}, {"id": 501, "t": "Homemade Pumpkin Ding Dongs", "c": "Baking", "d": "When I was a kid, I loved eating Ding Dongs, the little, foil-wrapped circles of cream-filled chocolate cake, glazed with a thin chocolate shell. They have everything you want in a sweet treat: a range of contrasting textures, a double dose of chocolate, a combination of cake and candy in one bite. When I started thinking about coming up with a homemade Ding Dong recipe, I went out and bought a pa", "i": ["425 g Brown sugar , divided", "112 g Butter , unsalted, softened", "12 g Vanilla extract , divided", "2 Large egg(s) , room temperature", "Large egg(s) , room temperature", "170 g Cake flour", "50 g Dutch-process cocoa powder , divided", "7 g Baking soda", "5 g Pumpkin pie spice , divided", "3 g Kosher salt , (3/4 teaspoon) divided", "210 g Pumpkin purée , canned, divided", "140 g Boiling water", "65 g Egg white(s) , from 2 large eggs", "80 g Water", "120 g Heavy cream , chilled", "570 g Coating chocolate , 2 bags Ghirardelli dark", "240 g 70% dark chocolate", "120 g Coconut oil (refined)", "Sprinkles , (optional) for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Cream brown sugar and butter", "Mix cake batter", "Bake and cool cake", "Portion and hollow out cakes", "Whip egg whites", "Make syrup", "Finish pumpkin meringue", "Whip cream and fold into filling", "Fill and chill cakes", "Make glaze", "Glaze cakes"], "tips": ["Whip cream faster by keeping everything cold", "Picking the right fat for the glaze"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/homemade-ding-dongs"}, {"id": 502, "t": "Cheesy Artichoke Tart With Carolina Gelen", "c": "Baking", "d": "With a few simple tricks, you can turn store-bought puff pastry into a creamy and cheesy artichoke tart with a burnished, crispy crust. Scoring the dough with a knife gives you clear borders within which to pile up the filling, and docking the dough where the filling goes will ensure it doesn’t puff up and mess up the careful distribution of ingredients. A little egg wash guarantees good browning ", "i": ["490 g Puff pastry , (1 sheet) store-bought, thawed", "1 Egg(s) , beaten", "135 g Ricotta cheese", "125 g Mozzarella , low-moisture, shredded", "65 g Sour cream , or crème fraîche or full-fat Greek yogurt", "20 g Fresh herbs , such as parsley, tarragon, and chervil, finely chopped, plus more for garnish", "4 g Kosher salt , (1 teaspoon), plus more as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "250 g Artichoke hearts , canned, quartered", "1 Jalapeño(s) , or serrano chile, stemmed and thinly sliced into rounds (optional)", "30 g Capers , drained", "25 g Parmesan , finely grated (optional)", "2 g Lemon zest , finely grated, from 1/2 lemon (1 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Prepare pastry", "Mix cheese topping", "Assemble tart", "Bake and broil tart", "Garnish tart and serve", "Explore The Road to Cooking"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/artichoke-cheese-tart-with-carolina-gelen"}, {"id": 503, "t": "Ultimate Pumpkin Spice Latte Macarons", "c": "Baking", "d": "The goal of this recipe was to transform a pumpkin spice latte into a filling for the perfect cookie: a pumpkin spice latte macaron. Whether you love the infamous PSL or not, it’s hard to argue against the combination of pumpkin, the king of fall fruits, and warm spices. There’s a reason we all eat pumpkin pies spiked with cinnamon, ginger, nutmeg, and clove every year: They’re delicious. The PSL ", "i": ["125 g Heavy cream", "125 g Pumpkin purée , canned", "40 g Glucose syrup , (optional)", "250 g White chocolate , 35% Vahlrona or other couverture white chocolate, roughly chopped", "2 g Instant espresso powder , (1 1/2 teaspoons) (optional) plus extra for dusting", "1 g Pumpkin pie spice , (1/2 teaspoon) plus extra for dusting", "1 g Kosher salt , (1/4 teaspoon)", "350 g Almond flour", "300 g Powdered sugar", "110 g Egg white(s) , room temperature, divided", "0.5 g Orange powdered food coloring , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.1 g Red powdered food coloring , (pinch)", "1 g Egg white powder , (optional)", "55 g Water"], "s": ["Make ganache", "Cool ganache", "Make tant pour tant", "Make almond paste", "Whip egg whites", "Cook syrup", "Finish meringue", "Fold meringue into almond paste in stages", "Stencil parchment", "Pipe and dust cookies", "Dry to form pellicle", "Bake cookies", "Agitate ganache and fill piping bag", "Assemble macarons and chill"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pumpkin-spice-latte-macaron"}, {"id": 504, "t": "How to Color Macarons", "c": "Baking", "d": "Macarons aren’t just delicious, textural delights; they’re also beautiful. Part of that is their form. The light, crisp, and soft cookies that sandwich the sweet and creamy filling have a distinctive shape, with their perfectly smooth domed tops rising above their craggy feet. But part of it is also that the cookie parts of macarons are typically dyed to reflect the flavor of the fillings they con", "i": [], "s": ["The full tutorial", "Pick the right food coloring", "Mixing in the coloring", "A little color goes a long way", "Use a scale", "Multiple colors and marbling", "Adding extra flair", "Make some macarons!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/adding-color-to-macaron-cookies"}, {"id": 505, "t": "Roasted Cabbage With Coconut Beurre Blanc With Eric Adjepong", "c": "Baking", "d": "You can argue about where roasted cabbage sits in the pantheon of classic sides, but there’s no denying that it’s delicious. Crispy and charred on the outside, meltingly tender within, all it needs is proper seasoning and it’s a welcome accompaniment to any meal. But with a little creativity you can turn a side of roasted cabbage into the star of the table, the dish that people keep coming back to", "i": ["55 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "3 Garlic clove(s) , minced", "2 g Thyme , fresh leaves, finely chopped (1 teaspoon)", "1 Green cabbage , head (about 910 g; 2 pounds), cut crosswise into 3/4- to 1-inch-thick pieces", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "60 g Dry white wine", "60 g Coconut vinegar", "50 g Red onion(s) , (1/4 onion) thinly sliced", "15 g Fresh ginger root , (1-inch piece) peeled and roughly chopped", "75 g Coconut cream", "White pepper , ground , as needed", "225 g Butter , unsalted, chilled and cut into 1/2-inch cubes (1 stick; 8 ounces)"], "s": ["Season cabbage", "Roast and broil cabbage", "Make wine and vinegar reduction", "Make coconut beurre blanc", "Finish and serve", "Explore The Road to Cooking"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/roasted-cabbage-coconut-beurre-blanc"}, {"id": 506, "t": "Vegan Pumpkin Pie Pudding", "c": "Baking", "d": "An ultra-smooth, ultra-creamy, egg-less pudding with all the flavor of a (good!) pumpkin pie. There’s nothing worse than taking a bite of a pumpkin pie with a curdled texture and muddy flavor, especially if you’ve spent hours putting it together. This pudding recipe, based on my recipe for egg-free chocolate “custard,” comes together in just a few minutes and its flavors are clean and clear, all p", "i": ["375 g Water", "250 g Pumpkin purée , canned", "100 g Raw cashews", "25 g Coconut oil (virgin, unrefined)", "15 g Vanilla extract", "125 g Brown sugar", "3 g Kosher salt", "3 g Cinnamon , ground", "2 g Ginger , ground", "1 g Allspice , ground", "1 g Cloves , ground", "1 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F"], "s": ["Boil cashews", "Blend and set custard", "Shear custard", "Portion pudding and serve"], "tips": ["Types of coconut oil and substitutions", "Hydrating hydrocolloids", "Don’t scale this recipe!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pumpkin-pie-pudding"}, {"id": 507, "t": "Oysters Rockefeller", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "A good oysters Rockefeller is hard to beat: perfectly cooked oysters, lots of tender greens, a touch of cream, and a crunchy crumb topping. It’s not a complicated dish, but to get it right, you have to focus on the details, starting with selecting the right size oysters. For cooked oysters, I like getting ones that are just a little too big to comfortably shoot raw; a longer cooking time gives the", "i": ["12 Oysters , (large, 3 to 4 inches long), fresh, scrubbed", "55 g Butter , unsalted", "30 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "2 Shallot(s) , minced", "2 Garlic clove(s) , minced", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "35 g Pernod", "200 g Heavy cream", "8 g All-purpose flour", "300 g Fresh spinach , or other tender greens such as miners lettuce, roughly chopped", "75 g Oyster crackers , or saltines, lightly crushed", "35 g Parmesan , finely grated"], "s": ["Before we begin, let’s cover some basics!", "Shuck oysters", "Sweat aromatics", "Cook down greens with cream", "Mix breadcrumbs", "Assemble oysters", "Cook oysters", "Explore The Road to Cooking", "Seas the day", "Cook with the Joule Oven"], "tips": ["Pernod! What is it good for?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/oysters-rockefeller"}, {"id": 508, "t": "Creamy Vegan Coffee Pudding", "c": "Baking", "d": "Sweet and creamy, this vegan coffee pudding hits like a refreshing iced coffee on a summer day. When I developed my simple, egg-free chocolate custard, I noted that you could easily turn it into pudding if you messed up while unmolding it, transforming a potential disaster into something just as delicious to eat. The reason that works is because of the magic of low-acyl gellan gum, a powerful hydr", "i": ["250 g Coffee , brewed, French press", "150 g Water", "150 g Raw cashews", "100 g Coconut milk", "55 g Coconut oil (virgin, unrefined)", "185 g Organic cane sugar", "3 g Kosher salt", "2 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F"], "s": ["Boil cashews", "Blend and set custard", "Shear custard", "Portion pudding and serve"], "tips": ["Hydrating hydrocolloids"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/coffee-pudding"}, {"id": 509, "t": "Vegan Butterscotch Pudding", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is a silky smooth butterscotch pudding with real butterscotch flavor that’s almost as easy to make as the stuff out of a box. After developing my egg-free chocolate “custard,” I knew the combination of cashews and low-acyl gellan, a powerful hydrocolloid, creates a stable fluid gel out of any flavorful liquid, and gets out of the way to let the liquid’s flavor shine. In just the right quantit", "i": ["150 g Brown sugar , dark", "100 g Vegan butter", "375 g Water", "150 g Raw cashews", "15 g Vanilla extract", "3 g Kosher salt", "1.5 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F", "0.5 g Turmeric root powder , (optional, for color)", "2 g Butterscotch extract , (optional)"], "s": ["Dissolve the sugar", "Boil cashews", "Blend and set custard", "Shear custard", "Portion pudding and serve"], "tips": ["Hydrating hydrocolloids"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/butterscotch-pudding"}, {"id": 510, "t": "Perfect (Vegan) Vanilla Pudding", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is a super creamy and smooth vanilla pudding that’s similar to the pudding cups you ate when you were a kid, but much better. (It also just happens to be vegan.) After developing my egg-free chocolate “custard,” I wanted to showcase how the same, straightforward technique could be used to create perfectly textured puddings with clean and clear flavors. A vanilla pudding cup seemed to fit the ", "i": ["375 g Water", "100 g Raw cashews", "55 g Coconut oil (virgin, unrefined)", "75 g Organic cane sugar", "2 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped (or 40 g vanilla extract)", "3 g Kosher salt", "1 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F"], "s": ["Boil cashews", "Blend and set custard", "Shear custard", "Portion pudding and serve"], "tips": ["Types of coconut oil and substitutions", "Hydrating hydrocolloids"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vanilla-pudding"}, {"id": 511, "t": "The Mariscos-verse Guide", "c": "Baking", "d": "“Mariscos” means “seafood” in Spanish. The word is commonly used as an umbrella term to refer to the vast and varied library of recipes of Mexico’s coastal regions. With over 7,000 miles of coastline, Mexican cooks have had access to a stunning array of fresh seafood for millennia, as well as a steady influx of foreign ingredients due to robust maritime trade. The combination has produced one of t", "i": [], "s": ["Aguachiles", "Ceviches", "Cócteles", "Caldos", "Camarones", "Pescados"], "tips": ["How to Buy the Freshest Fish", "What’s the Difference Between Peruvian and Mexican Ceviche?", "Mariscos Sazón"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/guide-to-mariscos"}, {"id": 512, "t": "Cóctel de Camarón (Mexican-Style Shrimp Cocktail)", "c": "Baking", "d": "I’m a big fan of classic American steakhouse shrimp cocktail: the spicy-sweet cocktail sauce, the horseradish and lemon, and the perfectly poached shrimp. (Although let’s be honest, the shrimp doesn’t even have to be perfectly poached, and it often isn’t.) But I’m an even bigger fan of the cóctel de camarón served in Mexican restaurants that specialize in seafood, or marisquerías, where poached sh", "i": ["910 g Shrimp , (large 21-25 count), peeled and deveined, shells reserved", "3 kg Water , cold", "2 Celery , ribs, cut into large dice", "1 Carrot(s) , cut into large dice", "0.5 White onion(s) , cut into large dice", "50 g Cilantro , stems", "43 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "6 Garlic clove(s) , divided, 3 smashed, 3 finely grated", "4 g Black peppercorns , (1 teaspoon) plus extra freshly ground as needed", "2 Bay leaf", "0.5 Lemon", "500 g Ketchup", "195 g Lime juice , fresh, from 7 limes", "170 g Orange juice , fresh, from 3 oranges", "150 g Clamato", "25 g Valentina hot sauce , black label", "12 g Worcestershire sauce", "230 g Cherry tomatoes , quartered", "1 Persian cucumber(s) , halved lengthwise and thinly sliced", "50 g Red onion(s) , (1/2 small onion) thinly sliced", "30 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "1 Serrano chile(s) , stemmed, thinly sliced into rounds (optional)", "1 Avocado(s) , cut into 1/2-inch pieces", "Saltines, as needed", "Tostadas, as needed"], "s": ["Make shrimp stock", "Poach shrimp", "Mix cóctel broth", "Mix and marinate the cóctel", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": ["Fried Saltines? Yes, please."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/coctel-de-camaron-mexican-style-shrimp-cocktail"}, {"id": 513, "t": "Cóctel Amarillo Campechano (Mexican-Style Mixed Seafood Cocktail)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "This mixed seafood cocktail is a lateral jump from the classic dish of cóctel de camarón. Instead of perfectly poached shrimp in a tangy tomato-based sauce, this has perfectly poached octopus and shrimp, along with steamed clams, citrus-cured snapper, and raw oysters, and everything’s dressed with a cocktail sauce that takes its inspiration from an amazing mole amarillo I had while visiting the st", "i": ["4 Tomato(es) , yellow heirloom (about 800 g total)", "4 Tomatillos , (about 160 g total)", "2 Yellow bell pepper , (about 375 g total)", "1 Habanero pepper(s)", "65 g Canola oil", "1 White onion(s) , (about 225 g) cut into a large dice", "10 Garlic clove(s) , (about 50 g total) peeled", "50 g Golden raisins", "2 Guajillo chile(s) , dried, stemmed, seeded, and lightly toasted", "5 Allspice , whole", "3 Cloves , whole", "1 g Cumin seeds , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Mexican oregano , (1 teaspoon) dried", "25 g Kosher salt , divided, plus extra as needed", "10 g Sugar , plus extra as needed", "24 Clams , Manila or littleneck, fresh, scrubbed (optional)", "225 g Red snapper , boneless, skinless fillet, cut into 1/2-inch pieces (optional)", "15 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "125 g Lime juice , fresh, from 4 limes", "135 g Orange juice , fresh, from 3 oranges", "35 g Clamato", "225 g Shrimp , (large 21-25 count) cooked, cut into 1/2-inch pieces (optional)", "225 g Octopus , cooked, cut into 1/2-inch pieces (optional)", "12 Oysters , fresh, scrubbed, shucked, liquor reserved (optional)", "110 g Cherry tomatoes , quartered", "1 Persian cucumber(s) , cut into a small dice", "50 g Red onion(s) , (1/4 onion) thinly sliced", "30 g Cilantro , leaves, cut into a chiffonade", "1 Serrano chile(s) , stemmed and thinly sliced into rounds", "2 Avocado(s) , thinly sliced", "1 recipe Hoja Santa Oil , (optional) for finishing", "Tostadas, as needed", "Saltines, as needed", "Lime wedges, as needed", "Hot sauce, as needed"], "s": ["Char vegetables", "Cook cóctel amarillo base", "Blend cóctel amarillo base", "Purge clams", "Steam and shuck clams", "Mix and marinate cóctel", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": ["Fried saltines? Yes, please!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/coctel-amarillo-campechano"}, {"id": 514, "t": "Hoja Santa Oil", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Hoja santa, or Mexican pepperleaf, has an inimitable flavor and aroma, one that’s variously likened to licorice, anise, and sassafras. I think of it as a mix of mint, tarragon, and licorice, but...not quite. Again, there isn’t anything like it. This presents a bit of a problem, since I think of it as being an essential flavor component of my cóctel amarillio campechano because it was integral to t", "i": ["250 g Hoja santa , fresh, thick stems removed", "450 g Canola oil , chilled", "0.7 g Sodium bisulfite , (optional)"], "s": ["Blanch and shock hoja santa", "Blend with oil and chill"], "tips": ["Keep it green: preserving the color of herb oils"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hoja-santa-oil"}, {"id": 515, "t": "Aguachile Verde", "c": "Sauce", "d": "This dish is classic Sinaloan coastal food. Pristine shrimp dressed with “aguachile verde,” which translates to “green chile water,” a blended mixture of fresh-squeezed lime juice, green chiles, and a few aromatic vegetables. (For a little boost of glutamates, I add a little Maggi Seasoning.) While it’s common to serve raw shrimp dressed in aguachile verde, I like to “cook” the shrimp first in a c", "i": ["455 g Shrimp , (large 21-25 count) peeled and deveined", "5 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "5 g Kosher salt , divided", "0.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (1/8 teaspoon)", "345 g Lime juice , fresh, from 6 limes, divided", "45 g English cucumber(s) , roughly chopped, plus extra 1/2 cucumber thinly sliced into rounds for garnish", "30 g Cilantro , leaves and tender stems, plus extra leaves for garnish", "15 g Red onion(s) , roughly chopped, plus extra thinly sliced for garnish", "1 Serrano chile(s) , stemmed", "1 Garlic clove(s)", "1 g Maggi Seasoning , (1/8 teaspoon) plus extra for finishing", "1 g Sugar , (1/4 teaspoon)", "0.5 Avocado(s) , thinly sliced", "Dried chiltepín chiles , roughly chopped, or any red chile powder , as needed", "Tostadas, as needed", "Mayonnaise , (optional) , as needed", "Hot sauce , (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Marinate shrimp", "Blend aguachile", "Finish and garnish aguachile"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/aguachile-verde"}, {"id": 516, "t": "Roasted Strawberry Aguachile With Tuna", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is summertime on a plate. The aguachile broth checks all the boxes: sweet, spicy, sour, bright, and pretty, to boot. In addition to dressing pristine sashimi-grade tuna, you can use the aguachile in cocktails or stir it into some Topo Chico for a refreshing sipper while you cook. Roasting strawberries intensifies their sweetness, which pairs perfectly with the charred, slightly bitter, fruity", "i": ["360 g Strawberries , hulled, plus 6 extra, hulled and thinly sliced, for serving", "15 g Extra-virgin olive oil , divided", "12 g Kosher salt , divided", "2 Garlic clove(s) , peeled", "2 Fresno chile(s) , divided (1 whole and 1 stemmed and thinly sliced into rounds, for garnish)", "1 Habanero pepper(s) , whole", "270 g Lime juice , fresh, from 5 limes, divided", "250 g Orange juice , fresh, from 4 oranges", "20 g Red onion(s) , cut into a large dice, plus extra thinly sliced for garnish", "3 g Sugar , (1/2 teaspoon)", "455 g Tuna loin , sashimi-grade", "0.5 Avocado(s) , cut into 1/2-inch pieces", "0.5 English cucumber(s) , thinly sliced", "Cilantro , fresh leaves , as needed", "Salsa Macha , oil only, or other chile oil , as needed", "Tostadas, as needed"], "s": ["Roast strawberries", "Blister garlic and chiles", "Blend aguachile broth", "Slice and season tuna", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": ["Tatemar: charring for flavor", "How to Buy Fish"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/roasted-strawberry-aguachile-with-tuna"}, {"id": 517, "t": "Ceviche Negro", "c": "Baking", "d": "This dish is a showstopper. As the name suggests, it’s a black ceviche, with raw cubes of fish cured in citrus juice and dressed with a sauce made with charred vegetables. Charring vegetables—a technique called “tatemar”—is an integral part of Mexican cuisine. By using intense, direct heat (typically, a hot comal), we blacken vegetables without using any fat and incorporate them, charred bits and ", "i": ["5 Roma tomato(es) , whole", "1 White onion(s) , sliced into 1/2-inch-thick rounds", "10 Garlic clove(s) , whole, unpeeled", "4 Habanero pepper(s) , whole", "6 g Sugar", "8 g Kosher salt , divided", "100 g Water , chilled, to thin out paste", "245 g Lime juice , fresh, from 5 limes, divided", "225 g Orange juice , fresh, from 4 oranges, divided", "455 g Red snapper , boneless, skinless fillets, cut into 1/2-inch dice", "10 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "60 g Red onion(s) , (1/4 onion) cut into a small dice, plus extra thinly sliced for garnish", "1 English cucumber(s) , half cut into a small dice, half thinly sliced on a bias for garnish", "1 Fresno chile(s) , stemmed and thinly sliced into rounds", "1 Avocado(s) , thinly sliced", "Cilantro , leaves , as needed", "Tostadas, as needed", "Charred onion powder , (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Char vegetables", "Blend into a paste", "Mix paste with citrus, two ways", "“Cook” the fish", "Finish and garnish ceviche"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ceviche-negro"}, {"id": 518, "t": "Ceviche a la Mexicana", "c": "Baking", "d": "While ceviche is generally acknowledged as having originated in Peru, there are a lot of Mexican versions. One of the most common is ceviche “a la Mexicana,” and that just means that it contains tomatoes, white onion, and jalapeño chile, which mirror the colors of the Mexican flag. It's one of my favorite things to eat. Fresh fish, cured briefly in a bright and spicy citrus marinade, served cold a", "i": ["455 g Halibut , boneless skinless fillet, cut into 1 cm dice", "35 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "12 g Kosher salt , divided", "5 g Sugar , plus extra as needed", "200 g Lime juice , fresh, from 4 limes", "50 g Red onion(s) , (1/4 onion) cut into small dice, plus extra thinly sliced for serving", "2 Roma tomato(es) , cut into a small dice", "1 Jalapeño(s) , stemmed, seeded, cut into a small dice", "15 g Cilantro , leaves and tender stems cut into a chiffonade, plus extra leaves for serving", "Tostadas, as needed", "1 Avocado(s) , thinly sliced", "Salsa Macha, as needed"], "s": ["Season the fish", "Add aromatics and “cook” the ceviche", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ceviche-a-la-mexicana"}, {"id": 519, "t": "Salsa Macha", "c": "Baking", "d": "Salsa macha is one of the most flavorful salsas you can make. A spicy, sweet, salty, and crunchy condiment, it’s used more like chili crisp or nam prik pao, rather than as a dipper for tortilla chips. With toasty notes provided by fried nuts and seeds, deep and rounded heat from fried dried chiles, and a little acidity and sweetness from vinegar and sugar, it’s incredibly versatile. You can add it", "i": ["600 g Neutral oil , such as vegetable, peanut, or canola", "65 g Peanuts , roasted, unsalted", "75 g Pumpkin seeds , hulled, raw", "75 g Garlic clove(s) , peeled (1 head of garlic)", "60 g Ancho chile(s) , dried, stemmed and seeded", "60 g Chiles de árbol , dried, stemmed", "17 g Sesame seeds , raw", "5 g Mexican oregano , dried", "30 g Apple cider vinegar , plus extra as needed", "12 g Kosher salt , plus extra as needed", "8 g Sugar , plus extra as needed"], "s": ["Fry peanuts", "Fry seeds and chiles", "Blend and season salsa"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salsa-macha"}, {"id": 520, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Keys to Better Grilled Burgers", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We’ve covered just about every way to make a great burger, from sous vide burgers and deep fried burgers to smash burgers and sliders. Every way, that is, except maybe the simplest way: a grilled burger that tastes freaking awesome. I put together recipes for a beef patty, a fresh salmon burger, a mushroom burger, a shrimp burger and, yes, even a turkey burger. But grilling great burgers isn’t jus", "i": [], "s": ["Keep proteins cold", "Add salt and egg yolks, and nothing else", "Be gentle", "Bigger is better", "A nice, cold nap", "Parchment portion squares", "Prep like a pro", "Use a two-zone grilling setup", "Pre-sear sticky patties", "Refresh and toast your buns!", "Don’t overload your burgers!", "The Best Salmon Burger", "Actually Great Grilled Turkey Burgers", "The Classic", "Snappy and Tender", "Microwave-Grilled Portobello Burger!", "Other Grilling Resources"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/level-up-your-classic-grilled-burgers"}, {"id": 521, "t": "The Complete Guide to Two-Zone Grilling", "c": "Baking", "d": "The trickiest part of live-fire cooking and charcoal-grilling is heat source management. Things can go south pretty quickly for inexperienced or inattentive cooks working over a ripping hot grill. But with the right setup, grilling doesn’t have to be stressful. One of the best ways to set up your grill to give you more control over how fast or slow things cook is to use a two-zone system. The conc", "i": [], "s": ["Heat control", "Gentle finishing for perfect doneness", "Freedom from flare-ups", "Multitasking on the grill", "A more comfortable workstation", "How to set up a two-zone grill", "Got questions?", "Try the two-zone setup"], "tips": ["How much charcoal is enough?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/two-zone-grilling-guide"}, {"id": 522, "t": "Perfect Grilled Burgers", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We’ve covered just about every way to make a great hamburger—sous vide, smashed, fried, sliders—except the simplest way: cooked on a grill. How hard could it be? The mission here was simple: focusing on technique and perfectly repeatable execution to make iconic burgers packed with beefy flavor, kissed with char and smoke, with a final cooked patty that’s juicy on the inside and a little crisp on ", "i": ["910 g Beef , ground, 20% fat", "2 Egg yolk(s)", "4.5 g Kosher salt , 0.5% weight of beef (1 teaspoon) plus extra as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "Hamburger bun(s), as needed", "American cheese , sliced (optional) , as needed", "Ketchup, as needed", "Yellow mustard , (optional) , as needed", "Mayonnaise , (optional) , as needed", "Iceberg lettuce , shredded (optional) , as needed", "Onion(s) , chopped (optional) , as needed", "Dill pickles , sliced (optional) , as needed", "Tomato(es) , sliced (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["What’s so special about these burgers?", "Prep ground beef", "Portion beef", "Form patties", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Grill the burgers", "Build and serve"], "tips": ["Buying ground meat vs. grinding it at home", "Does adding egg yolks to ground beef make it meatloaf?", "Chilling before grilling", "Meats en Place: How to set up a grilling work station"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/perfect-grilled-hamburgers"}, {"id": 523, "t": "Super-Savory Grilled Portobello Mushroom Burgers", "c": "Baking", "d": "Whether you want to eat less meat or you just freaking love mushrooms as much as I do, this portobello burger recipe delivers everything you want in a burger: a deeply seasoned and juicy “patty” with a light char and substantial bite, packed with umami and spice. My goal was to maximize flavor and texture and minimize the amount of time the mushrooms spend on the grill, which can turn the caps lea", "i": ["4 Portobello mushrooms", "60 g Worcestershire sauce", "Montreal steak seasoning, as needed", "60 g Mayonnaise", "15 g Barbecue sauce", "55 g Butter , unsalted (4 tablespoons)", "1 Sweet onion(s) , sliced into 1/2-inch-thick slices", "Kosher salt, as needed", "4 Hamburger bun(s)", "4 Swiss cheese , slices", "Green leaf lettuce, as needed", "60 g Worcestershire sauce - Montreal steak seasoning, as needed", "4 Hamburger bun(s) 4 Swiss cheese , slices - Montreal steak seasoning, as needed"], "s": ["Score mushrooms", "Microwave and marinate mushrooms", "Make barbecue mayo", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Sizzle onions", "Grill mushrooms", "Build and serve", "Level up your burger game!"], "tips": ["How to set up a grilling work station"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-portobello-burger-leveled-up"}, {"id": 524, "t": "Perfect Grilled Shrimp Burgers", "c": "Baking", "d": "These shrimp burgers are snappy, crisp, nicely textured, and, unlike the shrimp patties you can buy at stores, they’re packed with shrimp flavor because all that’s in them is fresh shrimp and salt. The salt is super important. I don’t add the salt to season the patties completely (it seasons them a little); instead, the salt lightly cures the proteins, making them stickier and snappier, which help", "i": ["910 g Shrimp , jumbo (13-25 per pound), peeled and deveined", "4.5 g Kosher salt , 0.5% weight of shrimp (1 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "Hamburger bun(s), as needed", "60 g Mayonnaise", "15 g Gochujang , or other chile paste or hot sauce of your choice", "Green cabbage , shredded (optional) , as needed", "1 recipe Fast and Easy Pickled Onion , (optional)", "Jalapeño(s) , thinly sliced into rounds (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Chop shrimp", "Portion shrimp", "Form patties", "Make spicy mayo", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Grill burgers", "Build and serve"], "tips": ["Chilling before grilling", "How to set up a grilling work station"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-shrimp-burgers-leveled-up"}, {"id": 525, "t": "Perfect Grilled Turkey Burgers", "c": "Baking", "d": "Turkey burgers? Turkey burgers! I don’t know why people love turkey burgers, but they do. Maybe you do! I’m going to show you how to make a better one. All the ground turkey you can find in stores is super lean; the fattiest I could find was 93% lean. So any turkey burger is going to need some help if you want it to be juicy and nicely textured. My solution is to mix the turkey meat up with 0.5% o", "i": ["910 g Turkey , ground", "2 Egg yolk(s)", "4.5 g Kosher salt , 0.5% weight of turkey (1 teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "4 Hamburger bun(s)", "Mayonnaise , (optional) , as needed", "Bacon , cooked (optional) , as needed", "Iceberg lettuce , leaves (optional) , as needed", "Tomato(es) , sliced (optional) , as needed", "Avocado(s) , sliced (optional) , as needed", "4 Hamburger bun(s) - Bacon , cooked (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Prep and portion ground turkey", "Form patties", "Prepare two-zone grill", "Pre-sear patties", "Finish grilling burgers", "Build and serve"], "tips": ["Chilling before grilling", "Meats en Place: How to set up a grilling work station"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-turkey-burgers-leveled-up"}, {"id": 526, "t": "Fresh and Bright Instant-Pickled Lemons", "c": "Seafood", "d": "These instant-pickled lemon slices allow you to enjoy the full flavor and aroma of fresh lemons in a single bite, and they couldn’t be easier to make: whisk together a simple vinegar brine, slice whole lemons super thin on a mandoline, and submerge the slices in the brine for ten minutes. That’s it. They’re a perfect addition to burgers and sammies, and you can use them to brighten up salads or se", "i": ["300 g Distilled vinegar", "300 g Water", "100 g Sugar", "20 g Kosher salt", "2 Lemon(s) , whole"], "s": ["Make brine", "Thinly slice lemons and add to brine"], "tips": ["All-purpose instant-pickle brine"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fresh-bright-pickled-lemons-in-an-instant"}, {"id": 527, "t": "Oven Texas-Style Barbecue Brisket", "c": "Baking", "d": "Smoked brisket is quintessential Texas barbecue. A large “tough” cut of beef, seasoned with salt and pepper, smoked low and slow until tender and juicy. Sounds pretty straightforward, but barbecue brisket is a perfect example of the adage “simple ain’t easy.” It takes pitmasters years to perfect the craft of trimming, seasoning, smoking, and slicing briskets so that both muscles from the primal en", "i": ["120 g Water", "1 Brisket point , (about 1.5 kg; 3.3 pounds)", "50 g Molasses", "1 recipe Texas Black Pepper Barbecue Rub , as needed", "1 recipe Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue , as needed, optional", "1 recipe Sweet and Sticky Barbecue Sauce , optional, for serving", "50 g Molasses 1 recipe Texas Black Pepper Barbecue Rub , as needed 1 recipe Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue , as needed, optional"], "s": ["Prep the pan", "Trim brisket", "Season brisket", "Wrap and slow-roast brisket", "Rest, slice, and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/oven-barbecue-brisket"}, {"id": 528, "t": "Oven Kansas City-Style Barbecue Ribs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Kansas City-style ribs are known for a burnished, sticky, glazed coating that stands in stark contrast to the crust on dry-style barbecue ribs. Pitmasters achieve this lacquered surface by seasoning the ribs with a simple rub and smoking them dry for the first part of the cook before mopping them with a sweet, tangy, and slightly spicy sauce to finish. Starting the ribs dry allows for bark to form", "i": ["120 g Water", "1.5 kg Baby back rib rack , (1 rack, 13 bones; 3.3 pounds)", "7.5 g Kosher salt", "1 recipe Kansas City-Style Barbecue Sauce", "1 recipe Sweet and Spicy Kansas City Barbecue Rub , as needed", "1 recipe Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue , as needed, optional", "7.5 g Kosher salt 1 recipe Kansas City-Style Barbecue Sauce 1 recipe Sweet and Spicy Kansas City Barbecue Rub , as needed 1 recipe Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue , as needed, optional"], "s": ["Prep the pan", "Prep and trim ribs", "Season ribs", "Wrap and slow-roast ribs", "Mop ribs and finish cooking", "Portion and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/oven-kansas-city-style-barbecue-ribs"}, {"id": 529, "t": "Oven Barbecue Pork Shoulder", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The Carolinas are famous for pork barbecue. Old-school barbecue shops smoke whole hogs or shoulders low and slow, and then chop—rather than pull—the meat into a tantalizing mix of crunchy skin, fatty morsels, and lean bites. Pitmasters toss the chopped pork with a sharp, tangy sauce that cuts through the richness, before serving it up. There are several regional sauces from this part of the countr", "i": ["120 g Water", "2 kg Pork butt , boneless, skinless (4.4 pounds)", "50 g Yellow mustard , such as French's", "1 recipe Carolina Gold Barbecue Rub , as needed", "1 recipe Bark Builder: The Secret to Better Indoor Barbecue , as needed, optional", "1 recipe Carolina Gold Barbecue Sauce , (choose one sauce)", "1 recipe Lexington-Style Barbecue Sauce , (choose one sauce)", "1 recipe Eastern North Carolina–Style Vinegar Barbecue Sauce , (choose one sauce)"], "s": ["Prep the pan", "Season pork", "Wrap and slow-roast pork", "Rest, chop, dress, and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/oven-north-carolina-style-barbecue-pork"}, {"id": 530, "t": "Texas Black Pepper Barbecue Rub", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Beef is the undisputed star of Texas barbecue. In order to let the flavor of the meat take center stage, seasoning is generally kept simple—most purists publicly favor a no-frills combination of equal parts of salt and pepper, known as Dalmatian rub in central Texas, for seasoning brisket and beef ribs. But when pushed a little on the subject, many renowned pitmasters admit to embellishing their d", "i": ["85 g Black peppercorns", "70 g Kosher salt", "30 g Brown sugar , light", "15 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce)", "10 g Granulated garlic", "7 g Celery seeds", "4 g Cumin seeds", "3 g Bay leaf , dried, ground"], "s": ["Mix spices", "Grind spices"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/texas-black-pepper-barbecue-rub"}, {"id": 531, "t": "Sweet and Spicy Kansas City Barbecue Rub", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Making a great rub for barbecue ribs isn’t as easy as it sounds, but after months of development in the ChefSteps test kitchen, we’re pretty stoked about this updated version of our existing Rib Rub recipe. Drawing inspiration from Kansas City-style ’cue and its distinctive balance of salty, sweet, savory, and spicy notes, this rub blends the trinity of salt, brown sugar, and paprika with bold aro", "i": ["55 g Kosher salt", "30 g Black peppercorns", "30 g Yellow mustard seeds", "28 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce)", "26 g Brown sugar", "23 g Celery seeds", "18 g Cumin seeds", "15 g Mace , ground", "3 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG)"], "s": ["Mix spices", "Grind spices"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/rib-rub"}, {"id": 532, "t": "Carolina Gold Barbecue Rub", "c": "Sauce", "d": "The bright, tangy, mustard-forward flavor of Carolina Gold barbecue sauce has been a long-time favorite here at ChefSteps—we’ve even got a carrot-based spin on the classic recipe. Hailing from the Midlands region of South Carolina, the sauce is thought to have originated from German immigrants who settled in the area and extended the Bavarian tradition of pairing pork and mustard to smoked barbecu", "i": ["55 g Kosher salt", "45 g Mustard powder", "35 g Yellow mustard seeds", "20 g Brown sugar , light", "10 g Onion flakes", "9 g Granulated garlic", "9 g Citric acid", "9 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce)", "9 g Cayenne pepper", "9 g Annatto seeds", "9 g Turmeric root powder", "5 g Black peppercorns"], "s": ["Mix spices", "Coarsely grind spices"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/carolina-gold-barbecue-rub"}, {"id": 533, "t": "Carolina Gold Barbecue Sauce", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Deep in the heart of South Carolina, between Columbia and Charleston, where German immigrants settled in the eighteenth century, there is a pocket of barbecue connoisseurs who pair barbecue pork with a bright mustard-based sauce rather than the vinegary stuff favored by their North Carolina neighbors. These South Carolinians can thank their German heritage for that: pairing pork and mustard is an ", "i": ["15 g Vegetable oil", "150 g Yellow onion(s) , (about ½ onion) cut into a small dice", "10 g Garlic , (2 medium cloves) minced", "150 g Yellow mustard , such as French's", "150 g Distilled vinegar", "150 g Apple cider vinegar", "60 g Worcestershire sauce", "45 g Brown sugar", "8 g Kosher salt", "0.5 g Cayenne pepper , ⅛ teaspoon", "0.25 g Xanthan gum , optional", "300 g Dijon mustard", "8 g Salt , kosher"], "s": ["Sweat onions and garlic", "Blend sauce"], "tips": ["The original recipe"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/carolina-gold-bbq-sauce"}, {"id": 534, "t": "Sweet and Sticky Barbecue Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "In Texas, where beef barbecue is king, purists keep spice rubs simple and discourage dressing smoked brisket and the like with sauce. Proponents of this minimalist approach argue that any seasonings beyond salt and pepper are superfluous, and detract and distract from the flavors of the beef and smoke. In central Texas, many barbecue joints don’t even offer sauce. The pitmasters of East Texas are ", "i": ["210 g Ketchup", "125 g Brown sugar , light", "40 g Soy sauce", "40 g Apple cider vinegar", "35 g Tomato paste", "30 g Worcestershire sauce", "10 g Molasses", "5 g Kosher salt", "4 g Celery seeds , ground (1 ¾ teaspoons)", "1.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (¾ teaspoon)", "1.5 g Garlic powder , (¾ teaspoon)", "1.5 g Onion powder , (¾ teaspoon)", "1 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce) , (½ teaspoon)", "0.5 g Cayenne pepper , (¼ teaspoon)"], "s": ["Simmer sauce"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sweet-and-sticky-bbq-sauce"}, {"id": 535, "t": "How Induction Cooktops Work", "c": "Baking", "d": "For a long time, you only had two options for cooktops: gas or electric. You probably have your preference, and you’ve probably engaged in endless debates with the partisans of the other side. “Gas is more powerful!” “Electric is more reliable!” “Nobody says, ‘We’re cooking with electric, now, baby!’” Etcetera, etcetera—you know the drill. However, there’s a third option: induction. As appliance m", "i": [], "s": ["Gas vs. Electric vs. Induction: Cooktops and Heat Transfer", "How Do Induction Cooktops Work?", "The Benefits of Induction Cooktops", "Precise temperature control", "Quicker temperature “recovery” time", "Energy efficient", "No fumes", "The Drawbacks of Induction Cooktops", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Induction all day!"], "tips": ["A very brief history of induction cooking", "How to cook with non-induction cookware on an induction burner"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-induction-works"}, {"id": 536, "t": "Chef Recs: Equipment for Bakers", "c": "Baking", "d": "Bakers are a finicky bunch. What we like: precision, accuracy, clean lines, repeatable results. What we don’t like: imprecision, inaccuracy, messy lines, haphazard results. Designed with the most exacting baker in mind, this list has something for every baker, whether you like baking sweet stuff or you’re into turning out beautiful boules. All recommended products are independently chosen by ChefS", "i": [], "s": ["A Good Scale", "Danish Dough Whisk", "Mini Slab Roller", "Challenger Bread Pan (and Accessories)", "Sweetapolita Sprinkles", "Rubber Spatulas", "LloydPans Detroit-Style Pizza Pans", "Black Walnut Lame", "Canelé Molds", "Ateco Cake Turntable", "Silpats", "Pre-Cut Parchment Paper", "Bundt Pans", "Marble Rolling Pin", "Bread Baker’s Pocket Companion", "Let the baking begin!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/baking-gifts"}, {"id": 537, "t": "Chef Recs: Our Favorite Knives", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you love cooking, you probably love sharp, stabby things—it comes with the territory. The tool you end up using more than any other is probably your chef’s knife or petty knife, no matter what you get up to in the kitchen. Here are our recommendations for knife nerds. All recommended products are independently chosen by ChefSteps staff. However, if you buy products using links on our website, w", "i": [], "s": ["Fujiwara Maboroshi no Meito Gyuto", "Yamamoto Asai Enji Damascus Steel Santoku", "Fujiwara Maboroshi no Meito Petty Knife", "MAC Honesuki", "Serrated Bread Knife", "Mushroom Knife", "Sharpening Stone Set", "Camellia Oil", "Saya Pins", "Pruning Shears", "Sharpen up!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/knife-gifts"}, {"id": 538, "t": "Chef Recs: Stocking Stuffers", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Stocking stuffers are the best gifts to pick out and choose. They don’t have to be pricey (but they can be!), and they don’t even have to be useful (but they can be!). The only real requirement is that they have to be on the small size. Otherwise, they’re all about delight, whether that means picking something out that you know your giftee will use a lot or grabbing something totally impractical b", "i": [], "s": ["Chef’s Press", "Thermapen One", "Big Tera Scraper", "Y Peelers", "Kitchen Tweezers", "Bowl Scraper", "Cake Testers", "FryAway", "Colatura di Alici", "Tomato Estratto", "E-Fish Gift Card", "Mala Market Pantry Kit", "The Japanese Pantry Gift Card", "Joule Big Clamp", "Maldon Sea Salt", "Make Something Great!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/stocking-stuffer-gifts"}, {"id": 539, "t": "Chef Recs: Gear for Coffee and Tea Lovers", "c": "Baking", "d": "People go nuts over coffee and tea, and we get it: We go nuts over coffee and tea, too. Here are our recommendations for all you warm and cozy drink lovers. All recommended products are independently chosen by ChefSteps staff. However, if you buy products using links on our website, we may earn a commission. Our lawyers say we have to say this: “As an Amazon Associate I earn from qualifying purcha", "i": [], "s": ["Acaia Lunar Coffee Scale", "Acaia Pearl Coffee Scale", "Really Good Coffee", "Breville Smart Kettle", "Bonavita Gooseneck Kettle", "Insulated Travel Mug", "Baratza Encore Burr Grinder", "Baratza Sette 30 Conical Burr Grinder", "Chemex", "Breville Dual Boiler Espresso Machine", "Nice Cups", "Time to get caffeinated!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/coffee-and-tea-gifts"}, {"id": 540, "t": "Chef Recs: Splurge Gifts", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "If someone did something exceptionally nice for you this year, or you want to treat yourself to something special, these are gifts worth considering. Whether you want to send someone off on a culinary tour of Oaxaca or want to give your favorite snacker the best potato chips in the game, read on for our splurge gift recommendations. All recommended products are independently chosen by ChefSteps st", "i": [], "s": ["Torchio Pasta Extruder", "Ice Maker", "Masienda Molinito Masa Grinder", "Tortilla Press", "Molcajete", "Konro Grill", "PK Grill/Smoker", "Mettler Toledo Scale", "Bonilla a la Vista Potato Chips", "Award-Winning Panettone", "Worth the Splurge"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/splurge-gifts"}, {"id": 541, "t": "Chef Recs: Equipment for Modernist Cooking", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you’re a culinary mad scientist who’s always trying strange, delicious things, you’ll appreciate this curated list of modernist cooking tools and ingredients. From the ultimate modernist cooking kit to nifty powders, there’s something unusual and interesting here for literally any kind of cook. All recommended products are independently chosen by ChefSteps staff. However, if you buy products us", "i": [], "s": ["Ultimate Modernist Cooking Kit", "Superbags", "Crisp Coat", "Batter Bind", "ThermoWorks ThermaQ 2", "ThermoWorks Q-Series Probe", "iSi Whipping Siphon", "Jeweler’s Scale", "Modernist inspo!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/modernist-cooking-gifts"}, {"id": 542, "t": "Chef Recs: Equipment for Cocktail Connoisseurs", "c": "Baking", "d": "Everybody enjoys a fancy drink on occasion; some people like fancy drinks at all occasions. Here are our recommendations for all the people you know who like to make fancy drinks, whether they’re spiked with alcohol or not. All recommended products are independently chosen by ChefSteps staff. However, if you buy products using links on our website, we may earn a commission. Our lawyers say we have", "i": [], "s": ["Scrappy’s Bitters Gift Set", "The Smoking Gun and Cloche", "Muddler", "Channel Knife/Zester", "Cocktail Shaker", "Hawthorne Strainer", "Fine-Mesh Cocktail Strainer", "Bar Spoon", "Measuring Jigger", "Pour us a drink!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cocktails-gifts"}, {"id": 543, "t": "Chef Recs: Our Favorite Cookbooks", "c": "Other", "d": "There are so many great books out there, on every conceivable subject. Rather than go through the endless possibilities, we selected some of our favorite books about cooking and food. All recommended products are independently chosen by ChefSteps staff. However, if you buy products using links on our website, we may earn a commission. Our lawyers say we have to say this: “As an Amazon Associate I ", "i": [], "s": ["The Whole Beast: Nose to Tail Eating", "Let’s Eat France!", "Let’s Eat Italy!", "Food & Drink Infographics. A Visual Guide to Culinary Pleasures", "Pasta Grannies: Comfort Cooking: Traditional Family Recipes From Italy’s Best Home Cooks", "Midwest Made: Big, Bold Baking From the Heartland", "Masa, the Book: Techniques, Recipes and Reflections on a Timeless Staple", "Spice: Flavors of the Eastern Mediterranean", "The Sioux Chef’s Indigenous Kitchen", "Fäviken", "The Art of Fermentation", "Hartwood: Bright, Wild Flavors From the Edge of the Yucatán", "Liquid Intelligence", "The Food of Sichuan", "Chicken and Charcoal"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cookbook-gifts"}, {"id": 544, "t": "Chef Recs: Our Favorite Kitchen Gadgets", "c": "Baking", "d": "Gadgets ... the delight of geek dads and moms everywhere (also geek kids and uncles and aunts, geek grandparents ... geeks just like us, basically). What do gadgets do, even? Well, for one thing, they make life easier. For another, they make certain impossible things possible, like a warm and wet bath that cooks food perfectly without creating conditions in which bacteria will multiply and kill yo", "i": [], "s": ["Pepper Cannon", "Joule Turbo", "Rice Cooker", "Conche", "Ninja Creami", "Joule Oven Air Fryer Pro", "Control °Freak", "Go, go gadget!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/gadget-lover-gifts"}, {"id": 545, "t": "Eastern North Carolina–Style Vinegar Barbecue Sauce", "c": "Sauce", "d": "In the Carolinas, where barbecue is all about pork, the sauces that pitmasters pair with smoked hog tend to adhere to the following blueprint: high acidity to cut through the fattiness of the meat, with a touch of sweetness for balance, and background heat that sneaks up on you on the finish. This particular sauce, found in coastal Eastern North Carolina and rolling down to South Carolina, is char", "i": ["325 g Apple cider vinegar", "30 g Brown sugar , light", "15 g Kosher salt", "3 g Red pepper flakes , (1½ teaspoons)", "2 g Cayenne pepper , (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce) , (½ teaspoon)"], "s": ["Combine, simmer and steep"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/eastern-north-carolina-style-vinegar-barbecue-sauce"}, {"id": 546, "t": "Lexington-Style Barbecue Sauce", "c": "Sauce", "d": "In the Carolinas, where barbecue is all about pork, the sauces that pitmasters pair with smoked hog tend to adhere to the following blueprint: high acidity to cut through the fattiness of the meat, with a touch of sweetness for balance, and background heat that sneaks up on you on the finish. In Lexington, North Carolina, the self-proclaimed barbecue capital of the world, the sauce of choice is a ", "i": ["325 g Apple cider vinegar", "60 g Ketchup", "50 g Brown sugar , light", "15 g Kosher salt", "3 g Red pepper flakes , (1½ teaspoons)", "3 g Cayenne pepper , (1½ teaspoons)", "1.5 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce) , (¾ teaspoon)"], "s": ["Combine, simmer, and steep"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/lexington-style-barbecue-sauce"}, {"id": 547, "t": "Kansas City-Style Barbecue Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "Kansas City-style barbecue is famous for its thick, tangy-sweet sauce. For plenty of folks, it’s the platonic ideal of barbecue sauce—a lot of supermarket and fast food sauces are modeled after this style, and label it a masterpiece. We’re not gonna argue with that assessment, but we are confident that this recipe blows the gloppy store-bought stuff out of the water. This version balances the swee", "i": ["140 g Ketchup Recipe", "120 g Apple cider vinegar", "100 g Brown sugar , light", "30 g Molasses", "25 g Worcestershire sauce", "20 g Tomato paste", "10 g Kosher salt", "5 g Garlic powder , (1 teaspoon)", "0.5 g Cumin seeds , ground (¼ teaspoon)", "0.5 g Cayenne pepper , (¼ teaspoon)", "140 g Ketchup"], "s": ["Simmer sauce"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/kansas-city-style-barbecue-sauce"}, {"id": 548, "t": "Grilled Beet and Chard Salad With Tahini Dressing and Dukkah", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "For a fresh take on a summer side for your next cookout, try this grilled beet salad with hearty swiss chard, dukkah, and a creamy tahini dressing. Beet salads usually require time-consuming cooking methods like sous vide or slow-roasting to get the famously crunchy root vegetables to the perfect tender texture before pairing them with usual suspects like creamy, tangy goat cheese. Not this salad.", "i": ["50 g Tahini", "8 g Dukkah , plus extra for garnish", "55 g Lemon juice , fresh, from 2 lemons, divided", "30 g Water", "3 g Kosher salt , (¾ teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "0.5 g Black pepper , freshly ground (⅛ teaspoon), plus extra as needed", "600 g Beet(s) , red, scrubbed (3 medium beets)", "300 g Swiss chard , washed (1 bunch)", "Extra-virgin olive oil, as needed", "20 g Fresh herbs , such as parsley, chives, and cilantro"], "s": ["Make dressing", "Prepare the grill", "Prepare beets and chard", "Grill beets and chard stems", "Cut beets and chard stems", "Dress salad and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-beet-and-chard-salad-with-tahini-dressing-and-dukkah"}, {"id": 549, "t": "Grilled Stone Fruit Panzanella", "c": "Baking", "d": "When it’s stone fruit season, there’s no reason to only use peaches, plums, and the like in desserts. There are so many ways to put fruit to use in savory dishes, and this riff on Tuscan panzanella is a perfect example of that. This dish combines in-season tomatoes with grilled stone fruit, charred bread, fresh herbs, and a bright dressing for a refreshing salad that will get you through the dog d", "i": ["400 g Tomato(es) , assorted varieties (such as cherry and heirloom tomatoes)", "600 g Stone fruit , assorted varieties (such as peaches, apricots, plums, and cherries)", "200 g Crusty bread , cut into 4 (1-inch-thick) slices", "80 g Extra-virgin olive oil , plus extra as needed for grilling fruit and bread", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "35 g Lemon juice , from one lemon", "35 g Basil , torn (1 bunch)", "30 g Shallot(s) , minced (1 small shallot)", "10 g Parsley , finely chopped", "Flake sea salt , for finishing (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare tomatoes", "Prepare stone fruit", "Prepare the grill", "Grill fruit and bread", "Assemble salad"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-stone-fruit-panzanella"}, {"id": 550, "t": "Hot and Cold Grilled Cucumber Salad With Greek Yogurt and Mint", "c": "Baking", "d": "There’s nothing wrong with being cool as a cucumber when it comes to making a refreshing summer salad. But have you ever tried cooking cukes? This salad proves that cucumbers are delicious when served hot or cold, or in this case both ways, with a combination of grilled, charred cukes and dressed raw ones tossed with herbs and served with creamy seasoned Greek yogurt. Briefly charring cucumbers on", "i": ["80 g Greek yogurt , plain", "10 g Extra-virgin olive oil , plus extra as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "400 g Persian cucumber(s) , (6 to 8 cucumbers)", "250 g English cucumber(s) , (½ cucumber)", "15 g Shallot(s) , (1 small shallot) minced", "5 g Parsley , finely chopped", "1 g Lemon zest , finely grated, from ½ lemon", "20 g Lemon juice , fresh, from ½ lemon", "5 g Mint , large leaves torn, small leaves left whole", "10 g Nigella seeds , or black sesame seeds, lightly toasted (optional)", "Flake sea salt , for finishing (optional) , as needed", "30 g Calabrian chile pepper(s) , roughly chopped (optional)", "Lemon wedges , for finishing (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Season yogurt", "Prepare the grill", "Prepare charred cucumbers", "Dress raw cucumbers", "Cut charred cucumbers", "Assemble and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-cucumber-salad-with-yogurt-and-mint"}, {"id": 551, "t": "Grilled Radicchio Salad With Raisin Agrodolce", "c": "Baking", "d": "This radicchio salad proves that even leafy vegetables can stand up to the intense heat of a grill, and it pairs charred bitter radicchio with a sweet and tart agrodolce dressing. Agrodolce—Italian for “sour” (agro) and “sweet” (dolce)—is a versatile, intensely flavored Sicilian condiment made by simmering sugar, red wine vinegar, dried fruit, and red onions into a savory-sour jam. With a little t", "i": ["9 g Black peppercorns", "9 g Orange zest , from ½ orange, peeled into thick strips", "7 g Lemon zest , from ½ lemon, peeled into thick strips", "20 Thyme , fresh sprigs (½ bunch)", "2 Bay leaf", "40 g Extra-virgin olive oil , plus more as needed", "80 g Red onion(s) , (about ¼ onion), cut into a small dice", "2 g Red pepper flakes , (1 teaspoon)", "200 g Red wine vinegar", "100 g Golden raisins", "70 g Sugar", "15 g Tomato paste , (optional)", "20 g Lemon juice , fresh, from ½ lemon", "30 g Orange juice , from ½ orange", "2 Radicchio , heads, quartered, cores left intact (about 600 g total)", "Kosher salt, as needed", "10 g Fresh herbs , such as basil and parsley"], "s": ["Make a sachet", "Cook agrodolce", "Prepare the grill", "Grill radicchio", "Dress and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-radicchio-salad-with-raisin-agrodolce"}, {"id": 552, "t": "Grilled Fennel Salad With Preserved Lemon Dressing", "c": "Baking", "d": "This simple grilled fennel salad dressed with a bright, tangy preserved lemon dressing is a great example of how fresh and flavorful summer can be without having to turn on your stove. Fennel’s bracing anise notes develop a milder, sweeter flavor when grilled. Combined with juicy oranges, sharp ricotta salata, pine nuts, fresh herbs and a burst of bright lemon acidity, this salad will give you Med", "i": ["2 Preserved lemons , (about 120 g each)", "100 g White wine vinegar", "20 g Dijon mustard", "10 g Sugar", "2 g Kosher salt , (½ teaspoon), plus extra for seasoning", "225 g Extra-virgin olive oil , plus extra for brushing fennel", "2 Fennel bulb , bulbs (about 200 g each), trimmed, fronds reserved", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "40 g Pine nuts , lightly toasted", "80 g Ricotta salata , or mizithra cheese, shaved", "2 Orange(s) , peeled and cut into ½ -inch-thick rounds", "5 g Parsley , finely chopped", "5 g Dill , finely chopped", "20 g Lemon juice , from one lemon"], "s": ["Make the dressing", "Prepare the grill", "Grill fennel", "Finish and dress salad"], "tips": ["Toasting pine nuts"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-fennel-salad-with-preserved-lemon-dressing"}, {"id": 553, "t": "Popsicle Geekery", "c": "Baking", "d": "We all grew up chasing down ice cream trucks and trying to eat frozen treats as quickly as possible before they melted in the hot sun. An ice-cold treat on a stick is everything that’s right about summer. We wanted to develop recipes for some killer popsicles of our own that shine bright with seasonal ripe fruit, and incorporate “grown-up” flavors like cold-brew coffee. In terms of frozen treats, ", "i": [], "s": ["What Are Popsicles?", "Three Categories of Popsicles: Icy, Chewy, Creamy", "Fruit juice popsicles", "Blended fruit popsicles", "Creamy popsicles", "Controlling Popsicle Texture", "Freezing rate"], "tips": ["What is Brix?", "Molds: Which one do I use?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/popsicle-geekery"}, {"id": 554, "t": "Creamy Cold-Brew Mocha Crunch Popsicles", "c": "Baking", "d": "This pop has all the flavors of a refreshing iced latte, cloaked beneath a crunchy mocha magic shell. It’s the perfect pick-me-up treat for hot summer days when you need to get stuff done or just want a little extra pep in your step. To create that perfect balance of creaminess and robust coffee flavor, I make a base with cold brew, instant espresso powder, cream, half-and-half, and vanilla. Using", "i": ["200 g Heavy cream", "135 g Cold-brew coffee", "100 g Half-and-half", "105 g Sugar", "18 g Vanilla extract , or 1 vanilla bean, split lengthwise and scraped (optional)", "1.5 g Instant espresso powder , 1 teaspoon", "1 g Kosher salt , ¼ teaspoon, divided", "290 g 58% bittersweet chocolate pistoles", "90 g Cocoa butter , raw, or coconut oil", "15 g Coffee beans , roughly chopped", "15 g Cacao nibs"], "s": ["Chill molds", "Whisk base", "Chill base", "Fill molds and partially freeze", "Stir, stick, and freeze solid", "Make mocha magic shell", "Unmold", "Dip and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/creamy-mocha-crunch-popsicles"}, {"id": 555, "t": "Peach Cobbler Popsicles", "c": "Baking", "d": "When you crave a classic summer fruit cobbler, but it’s too hot to turn on the oven, this frozen pop made with sweet peaches and cream, and coated with a crunchy streusel hits the spot. For the base, I cook down ripe peaches with sugar, cinnamon, and vanilla, and then blend them up with sugar, cream and a splash of lemon juice. The result: bright peach flavor with a dense, soft, chewy texture like", "i": ["40 g Butter , unsalted, softened", "40 g Brown sugar", "80 g Bread flour", "3 g Kosher salt , (¾ teaspoon), divided", "35 g Freeze-dried peaches , broken into small pieces", "450 g Peaches , (about 3 large peaches) pitted and quartered", "110 g Sugar", "18 g Vanilla extract , or 1 vanilla bean, split and scraped", "2 Cinnamon stick(s)", "1 g Malic acid , (⅛ teaspoon)", "135 g Heavy cream", "20 g Lemon juice"], "s": ["Chill molds", "Make streusel", "Bake streusel and add freeze-dried peaches", "Cook peach base", "Blend base", "Chill base", "Fill molds, stick, and freeze solid", "Unmold, coat with streusel, and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/peach-cobbler-popsicles"}, {"id": 556, "t": "Roasted Plum and Tarragon Popsicles", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Intensely aromatic herbs in fruit popsicles? Does the combination even work? It absolutely does. Pairing jammy notes of roasted stone fruit with licorice-y fresh tarragon, these plum pops burst with sweet and savory flavor. The trick to these popsicles is broiling fresh ripe plums before blending them with the other base ingredients. This intensifies their sweetness and creates a texture that’s si", "i": ["550 g Plum(s) , halved, pitted, and cut into 1-inch pieces", "50 g Sugar", "20 g Honey", "20 g Lemon juice , fresh", "1 g Tarragon , fresh, (15–20 large leaves)", "0.5 g Kosher salt , (⅛ teaspoon)", "0.5 g Malic acid , (1/16 teaspoon)"], "s": ["Chill molds", "Broil plums", "Blend base", "Chill base", "Fill molds, stick, and freeze solid", "Unmold and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/roasted-plum-and-tarragon-popsicles"}, {"id": 557, "t": "Orange Creamsicles", "c": "Baking", "d": "This riff on a summertime classic combines bright citrus with rich dairy and vanilla in a simple-to-make popsicle. Fresh orange juice and zest provide a burst of floral sunny refreshment, with the fruit’s sweetness amplified by sugar and a little maple syrup. For creaminess, I settled on a mixture of heavy cream and half-and-half in a two-to-one ratio, which gives these pops a silky rich texture b", "i": ["200 g Heavy cream", "135 g Orange juice , from 2 large oranges", "6 g Orange zest , finely grated, from 2 large oranges", "100 g Half-and-half", "70 g Sugar", "35 g Maple syrup", "18 g Vanilla extract , or 1 vanilla bean, split lengthwise and scraped, (optional)", "0.5 g Kosher salt , (⅛ teaspoon)"], "s": ["Chill molds", "Whisk together base", "Chill base", "Fill molds and partially freeze", "Stir, stick, and freeze solid", "Unmold and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/orange-creamsicles"}, {"id": 558, "t": "Piña Colada Popsicles", "c": "Baking", "d": "A tropical beach vacation? In this economy?? For those of us who don’t have island-hopping travel plans on the books, these booze- and dairy-free piña colada pops are perfect for a summer staycation. Made with fresh pineapple and a touch of coconut milk, these sweet treats strike the perfect balance between bright acidity and rich creaminess. Sugar and maple syrup in the base enhance the natural s", "i": ["350 g Pineapple , fresh, about ½ pineapple, peeled, cored cut into 1-inch pieces", "120 g Coconut milk", "90 g Sugar", "25 g Maple syrup", "6 g Vanilla extract , or 1 vanilla bean, split lengthwise and scraped", "1 g Malic acid , (⅛ teaspoon)", "0.5 g Kosher salt , (⅛ teaspoon)"], "s": ["Chill molds", "Blend base", "Chill base", "Fill molds and partially freeze", "Stir, stick, and freeze solid", "Unmold and enjoy"], "tips": ["Choosing the right coconut milk"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pina-colada-popsicles"}, {"id": 559, "t": "Super Strawberry Popsicles", "c": "Baking", "d": "These popsicles pack a double dose of strawberry flavor thanks to a combination of fresh fruit and freeze-dried berries blended into the base. Agave syrup and sugar provide sweetness while also lending the pops a perfectly bite-able texture when frozen. A splash of lemon juice and a pinch of malic acid amplifies the brightness of peak season strawberries, and preserves their deep red color by prev", "i": ["400 g Strawberries , fresh, washed and hulled", "70 g Agave syrup", "40 g Sugar", "23 g Freeze-dried strawberries", "28 g Lemon juice , fresh, from 1 lemon", "2 g Lemon zest , finely grated, from 1 lemon (1 teaspoon)", "1 g Malic acid , (⅛ teaspoon)", "0.5 g Kosher salt , (⅛ teaspoon)"], "s": ["Chill molds", "Blend base", "Chill base", "Fill molds, stick, and freeze solid", "Unmold and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/super-strawberry-popsicles"}, {"id": 560, "t": "Mango-Pineapple Popsicles", "c": "Baking", "d": "The intensely sweet, creamy, and dense flesh of mangoes makes them particularly well-suited for blending into a smoothie, lassi, sorbet base, or in this case, a paleta-style popsicle. These pops combine fresh mango with pineapple juice and freeze-dried fruit for a burst of bright tropical acidity that will keep you refreshed all summer long. Mangoes are rich in fiber, which helps give the popsicle", "i": ["365 g Mango , peeled and cut into 1-inch pieces", "125 g Pineapple juice", "50 g Sugar", "45 g Freeze-dried pineapple", "1 g Malic acid , (⅛ teaspoon)", "0.5 g Kosher salt , (⅛ teaspoon)"], "s": ["Chill molds", "Blend base", "Chill base", "Fill molds, stick, and freeze solid", "Unmold and enjoy", "Variations"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/mango-pineapple-popsicles"}, {"id": 561, "t": "Rhubarb Popsicles", "c": "Baking", "d": "As a kid, I loved chomping on stalks of fresh rhubarb that I’d pick from the plant growing behind my family’s home in Indiana. Juicy and crisp, with bracing tartness from oxalic acid, rhubarb may technically be a vegetable, but it makes sense that it’s often treated more like fruit, simmered into jams and baked into pies. Combining rhubarb with sugar helps balance its sour punch, and lends notes o", "i": ["800 g Rhubarb , (about 9 medium stalks) cut into 1-inch pieces", "140 g Sugar", "1 g Malic acid , (⅛ teaspoon)"], "s": ["Chill molds", "Juice rhubarb", "Clarify and strain base", "Chill base", "Fill molds and partially freeze", "Stir, stick, and freeze solid", "Unmold and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/rhubarb-popsicles"}, {"id": 562, "t": "Pomegranate Popsicles", "c": "Baking", "d": "Fruit juice, frozen on a stick. There are few things as simple and satisfying as a popsicle on a sweltering summer day. This sweet and tart pomegranate pop delivers icy refreshment with minimal prep work in the kitchen—a big plus when it’s hot outside and the last thing you want to do is spend hours cooking over a hot stove. There are a lot of variables that affect the texture of frozen treats. Fa", "i": ["475 g Pomegranate juice , (such as POM), divided", "70 g Sugar"], "s": ["Chill popsicle molds", "Make pomegranate syrup", "Chill base", "Fill molds and partially freeze", "Stir, stick, and freeze solid", "Unmold and enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pomegranate-popsicles"}, {"id": 563, "t": "5 Chefs Make Hot Dogs 5 Ways", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Summer is here and we’ve got five of our chefs putting their own unique spin on the season’s perennial cookout companion: hot dogs. Grant gives hot dogs the smash burger treatment, Nick riffs on a Seattle dog (yup, cream cheese is involved), and Anjana Shanker ups the ante on crunch with a dog garnished with crispy curry leaves, peanuts, shallots, and a cilantro relish. You can check out how these", "i": [], "s": ["Matthew’s homemade seitan makes one helluva hot dog", "Get fancy with Kyl’s boudin blanc sausage sandwiches"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/5-chefs-make-hot-dogs-5-ways"}, {"id": 564, "t": "Sausage Sandwiches with Serrano Cheese Sauce and Pepper Relish", "c": "Baking", "d": "Boudin blanc—French for “white pudding”—is one of my favorite sausages to throw on the grill during the summer. Made with a combination of pork and chicken, boudin blanc is an emulsified sausage similar in texture to a hot dog, but much heftier in size. It also boasts a more delicate flavor than a ballpark frank, with warm spices rather than the heavy smoke and salt of a traditional dog. While thi", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 4 Boudin blanc sausages , or hot dogs 1 recipe Spicy Serrano Cheese Sauce 4 Demi-baguettes , or hot dog buns 1 recipe Sweet and Spicy Pepper Relish", "4 Boudin blanc sausages , or hot dogs 1 recipe Spicy Serrano Cheese Sauce 4 Demi-baguettes , or hot dog buns 1 recipe Sweet and Spicy Pepper Relish", "1 recipe Spicy Serrano Cheese Sauce", "4 Demi-baguettes , or hot dog buns", "1 recipe Sweet and Spicy Pepper Relish", "1 recipe Spicy Serrano Cheese Sauce 4 Demi-baguettes , or hot dog buns"], "s": ["Simmer the sausages", "Warm the cheese sauce and baguettes", "Assemble the sandwiches", "Fancy franc accoutrements"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sausage-sandwiches-with-serrano-cheese-sauce-and-pepper-relish"}, {"id": 565, "t": "Sweet and Spicy Pepper Relish", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Drawing inspiration from Basque piperade, this relish features fresh peppers and shallots cooked down in a mixture of sugar and sherry vinegar for a bright, jammy condiment that can star as a sandwich spread or cheese board accompaniment. Sweet and sour, with a kick of background heat thanks to Fresno chiles, you’ll find yourself reaching for a jar of this any chance you can get. During summer gri", "i": ["125 g Sugar", "50 g Sherry vinegar , plus extra as needed", "150 g Red bell pepper(s) , stemmed, seeded, and cut into a small dice", "75 g Shallot(s) , cut into a small dice", "40 g Fresno chile(s) , stemmed, seeded, and cut into a small dice", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed"], "s": ["Boil vinegar and sugar", "Cook peppers and shallots", "Reduce vinegar and sugar to a syrup", "Combine syrup and pepper mixture", "Relish the opportunity"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sweet-and-spicy-pepper-relish"}, {"id": 566, "t": "Spicy Serrano Cheese Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "A great cheese sauce should be smooth, creamy, and most importantly, it should taste like cheese. Can Tex-Mex queso and American whiz fit that bill? Absolutely. Those sauces are made with processed cheese that can be easily melted into a smooth, stable state thanks to melting salts such as sodium citrate. When heated with cheese and a little liquid, melting salts swap in sodium for the calcium bou", "i": ["375 g White wine , dry", "50 g Butter , unsalted", "50 g Shallot(s) , finely chopped", "35 g Serrano chile(s) , stemmed and thinly sliced into rounds", "50 g All-purpose flour", "450 g Milk , whole", "200 g Mozzarella , low-moisture, shredded", "4 g Kosher salt , to taste"], "s": ["Reduce the wine", "Cook shallot and chiles", "Toast flour", "Blend in milk and wine reduction", "Thicken sauce", "Blend in cheese", "Serve as is or charge in a whipping siphon", "Made for dippin’"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spicy-serrano-cheese-sauce"}, {"id": 567, "t": "Poached Chicken Breast", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Poached chicken often gets a bad rap for being dry, chalky, and boring. But that’s just because people tend to underseason and overcook poultry. Long ago, we took the guesswork out of cooking moist, flavorful chicken breast by using the precise temperature control of sous vide. But we recognize that not everyone has a Joule (even though they should), and that doesn’t mean they shouldn’t be able to", "i": ["1 kg Water", "15 g Kosher salt , 1.5% of water", "8 g Black peppercorns , optional, .5% of water", "900 g Bone-in chicken breasts , (2 split breasts)"], "s": ["Poach the chicken", "Cool, then shred or slice"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/stovetop-poached-chicken-breast"}, {"id": 568, "t": "Epic Spatchcocked Roast Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "Butterflying or “spatchcocking” is a great way to roast or grill a whole chicken. In its simplest form, this butchering method involves removing the backbone with a pair of sturdy kitchen shears, and then pressing down on the breastbone to flatten and splay out the bird. This ensures the bird cooks evenly, resulting in tender, juicy and flavorful meat with golden, crispy skin. Flattening the chick", "i": ["1 Chicken , whole", "15 g Canola oil", "50 g Chicken bouillon powder", "Black pepper, as needed"], "s": ["Spatchcock the bird", "Roast the bird", "Winner, winner..."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/epic-spatchcocked-roast-chicken"}, {"id": 569, "t": "Enchiladas Verdes de Pollo (Green Enchiladas With Chicken)", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Enchiladas come in many forms, but in terms of instant name recognition and popularity, it’s hard to compete with enchiladas verdes. After recently developing a recipe for salsa verde, it only seemed logical to take the next step and put it to use in a batch of chicken enchiladas. For this recipe, I like to keep things simple with lightly fried corn tortillas wrapped around perfectly cooked chicke", "i": ["1 recipe Epic Spatchcocked Roast Chicken , or", "1 recipe Poached Chicken Breast , choose one chicken option", "2 recipes Quick and Easy Salsa Verde (Mexican Tomatillo Salsa) , cooked through step 2, divided", "Kosher salt, as needed", "55 g Canola oil", "10 Tortillas , corn, homemade or store-bought", "Cotija cheese , for serving , as needed", "Mexican crema , for serving , as needed", "Cilantro , sprigs, for serving , as needed", "Radish , thinly sliced, for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Shred the chicken", "Fry tortillas", "Assemble enchiladas", "Bake enchiladas", "Garnish and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/enchiladas-verdes"}, {"id": 570, "t": "Salsa Mexicana", "c": "Baking", "d": "Ask someone to describe the quintessential Mexican salsa, and odds are that they will list the following ingredients: tomatoes, onion, cilantro, and fresh chiles. These are the key components of salsa Mexicana, the iconic condiment commonly served at restaurants alongside a bowl of crispy totopos to tide you over while you decide on drink orders. If this sounds a lot like pico de gallo, you’re rig", "i": ["650 g Tomato(es) , roughly chopped", "100 g Onion(s) , white, roughly chopped", "50 g Serrano pepper , stemmed and roughly chopped", "30 g Cilantro , leaves and tender stems, roughly chopped", "25 g Garlic clove(s)", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Blend and serve", "Get down in salsa town"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salsa-mexicana"}, {"id": 571, "t": "Xnipec (Yucatecan Habanero Salsa)", "c": "Baking", "d": "In its simplest form, xnipec (pronounced shnee pec) is a fiery salsa made with sour Seville orange juice, habanero chiles, and red onion. Served as a table condiment in the Yucatán peninsula, xnipec shares characteristics with another classic salsa: pico de gallo. Like its milder sibling, xnipec is also fresh and bright, and incredibly versatile. Its sharp acidity and chile punch help to balance t", "i": ["400 g Seville (sour) orange juice , or fresh lime juice", "80 g Habanero pepper(s) , stemmed", "80 g Red onion(s) , roughly chopped", "15 g Cilantro , stems, cut into 2-inch pieces"], "s": ["Blend", "Give the salsa a rest, then serve", "Get down in salsa town"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/xni-pec"}, {"id": 572, "t": "Salsa Arriera (Charred Chile Salsa)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Salsa arriera is a jammy, roasted chile salsa that is typically served as an accompaniment to grilled meats. While it is most commonly made with serrano chiles, we opted for a milder mix of poblano and Fresnos, which bring grassy and fruity notes to this version. We start by lightly charring the chiles, along with onion and garlic, under the broiler (you can also char the vegetables over the direc", "i": ["750 g Poblano pepper(s) , whole", "250 g Fresno chile(s) , whole", "150 g Onion(s) , white, roughly chopped", "75 g Garlic clove(s)", "15 g Canola oil", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Roast the vegetables", "Cover vegetables to finish cooking", "Stem chiles, blend, and serve", "Get down in salsa town"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salsa-arriera"}, {"id": 573, "t": "Salsa de Árbol (Simmered Tomato and Dried Chile Salsa)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Salsa de árbol is a cooked tomato salsa, spiked with spicy dried árbol chiles. For this version, I start by lightly frying onion, garlic, and dried chiles in a generous amount of oil until the onion just begins to color around the edges. I then add tomatoes, simmer them until softened, and then blend the mixture into a smooth and creamy emulsion. The resulting salsa packs plenty of chile punch fro", "i": ["250 g Canola oil", "200 g Onion(s) , white, roughly chopped", "50 g Garlic clove(s)", "5 g Chiles de árbol , dried, stemmed and seeded", "400 g Tomato(es) , quartered", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Fry chiles and alliums", "Simmer tomatoes", "Blend, cool, and serve", "Get down in salsa town"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salsa-de-arbol"}, {"id": 574, "t": "Quick and Easy Salsa Verde (Mexican Tomatillo Salsa)", "c": "Sauce", "d": "It’s hard to beat the versatility of salsa verde. The combination of tangy tomatillos, grassy fresh chiles, sharp white onion, and fresh cilantro makes for a bright salsa that can stand on its own as a condiment, or can be used as a flavor base for chilaquiles, enchiladas, tamales, braised meats, and more. Without changing the ingredients, you can easily alter the flavor and texture of salsa verde", "i": ["400 g Tomatillos , husked, stemmed, and quartered", "100 g Onion(s) , white, roughly chopped", "50 g Jalapeño(s) , stemmed and roughly chopped", "40 g Garlic clove(s)", "20 g Cilantro , leaves and tender stems, roughly chopped", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Blend and serve", "Or simmer for using in enchiladas", "Get down in salsa town."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/quick-salsa-verde"}, {"id": 575, "t": "5 Quick & Easy Blender Salsas To Brighten Your Summer", "c": "Baking", "d": "Not many things can beat bright, vibrant bowls of fresh salsa in the warm summer months to remind you just how beautiful the season can be. But when it’s hot out, the last thing most of us want to do is spend a lot of time working in the kitchen. With that in mind, we’ve developed five simple salsa recipes that come together in a flash with the help of a blender. Whether you’re a chile-loving thri", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/5-easy-blender-salsas-to-brighten-your-summer"}, {"id": 576, "t": "Johnny’s Crazy Deep-Dish Corn Skillet Cake", "c": "Baking", "d": "Johnnycake, also known as hoe cake, jonakin, ashcake, and johnny cake, has been described as New England’s answer to the tortilla, since it is said to have originated in Rhode Island, where starving settlers learned from the Shawnee Tribe how to make food from ground corn. It remains an immensely popular regional dish to this day. Johnnycake roots also run deep in Black, Indigenous and Caribbean c", "i": ["110 g Pastry flour", "132 g Cornmeal", "100 g Sugar", "7 g Baking soda", "7 g Baking powder", "7 g Kosher salt", "108 g Egg(s) , whole", "165 g Milk , whole", "165 g Sour cream", "132 g Butter , unsalted, melted"], "s": ["Gather your goods", "Preheat oven", "Choose your fighter: Skillet or cake pan?", "Blend the cornmeal to flour consistency", "Sift dry ingredients", "Mix the wet ingredients", "Mix it up", "Bake", "Let cool and serve", "An earful on heirloom corn", "Johnnycake toppers"], "tips": ["Want a sweet yellow corn cake?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/johnny-deep-dish-corn-skillet-cake"}, {"id": 577, "t": "Quick & Easy Flourless Blender Bread", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Need bread in a hurry? Want a gluten-free variety that doesn’t taste like cardboard? Do you consider bread-making a hassle? Are you a neophyte baker who wants to take baby steps towards dough enlightenment? If the answer to any of these questions is yes, this recipe is for you. The best part about this bread is that it’s foolproof. Plus, you likely already have all of the required ingredients hang", "i": ["350 g Jasmine rice", "210 g Water , plus extra for soaking", "80 g Fat , or oil of your choice", "25 g Sugar", "14 g Instant dry yeast", "8 g Salt , kosher", "350 g Jasmine rice 1 l Water , for soaking"], "s": ["Soak the rice", "Preheat oven", "Blend", "Pan and proof", "Bake", "Cool, slice, serve", "Can other grains be used?", "We can’t emphasize this enough: don’t overproof or underbake", "Crostini"], "tips": ["Soak comparison"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bread-in-a-blender"}, {"id": 578, "t": "Coffee Cake With a Twist", "c": "Baking", "d": "Coffee cake made from dough instead of batter? You bet! Think of an incredible tasting coffee cake, made in the fashion of a Danish pastry, and you get where we’re going with this recipe. This European spin on an American-style coffee cake is layered with streusel, making it almost muffin-like with loads of cinnamon. Add a dense crumb structure and a cream cheese and jam filling, and you’ll never ", "i": ["0.5 recipe Easy, Breezy, Beautiful Brioche (Plus Two Ways to Upgrade)", "105 g Butter , unsalted, divided", "100 g Cream cheese , (we use Philadelphia Original)", "15 g Egg yolk(s) , (from 1 egg)", "15 g Sugar", "2 g Kosher salt , divided", "0.5 g Vanilla bean seed , (from 1/2 vanilla bean)", "40 g Freezer Jam: Why It’s the Real Jam , or jam of your choice", "20 g Brown sugar", "40 g Bread flour", "3 g Cinnamon , optional", "Egg wash, as needed", "35 g Whole milk", "250 g Confectioners’ sugar", "15 g Dark rum , optional", "650 g Brioche dough"], "s": ["Make brioche", "Laminate brioche (optional)", "Make cream cheese filling", "Make streusel", "Don’t like cream cheese? Use frangipane.", "Make icing", "Prepare pan", "Roll out dough", "Assemble dough with fillings", "Divide, cut, twist", "Place in pan, but make it creative!", "Proof, egg wash, top with streusel", "Bake", "Glaze", "Enjoy with some joe", "Level Up Your Filling", "Bake Like a Pro"], "tips": ["Flavor your brioche", "Do I have to laminate?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/coffee-cake-with-a-european-twist"}, {"id": 579, "t": "Five Chefs Make Pancakes Five Ways", "c": "Baking", "d": "We’d wager that 90 percent or more of the pancakes prepared in America are made with a boxed mix, and there’s no shame in that game. Boxed mixes make it easy to get breakfast on the table and provide consistent, bulletproof results. But, when it comes to pancakes, there are plenty of ways to cook outside the box. So, whether you’re on Team Boxed Mix or Team Made From Scratch, our chefs are here to", "i": [], "s": ["Bulk up your boxed mix with Grant", "Get a little corny with Kyl", "Matthew will make you believe in the power of plant-based (and gluten-free!)", "Start your day with something sweet with Otto’s caramel crepes", "Go big, bold, and gut-busting with Nick’s molten chocolate lava pancake"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/five-chefs-five-pancakes"}, {"id": 580, "t": "Otto’s Nostalgic Dulce de Leche Crêpes", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Chef Otto Romer’s mother made him these crêpes throughout his childhood in Venezuela. A two-day affair, she’d make the dulce de leche the day before, and then rise early to make the batter and cook the crêpes, sending him to school with this sweet treat in his lunch box. Without a kitchen torch, she heated a dinner fork over the gas stove and used that to caramelize the sugar on top. Inspired by t", "i": ["1 recipe So Simple Sous Vide Dulce de Leche", "480 g Milk , whole", "4 Egg(s) , whole, beaten", "25 g Brown butter", "235 g All-purpose flour", "50 g Sugar", "5 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Otto demonstrates his crêpe technique", "Prepare dulce de leche", "Mix batter", "Let the batter rest", "Preheat and butter your pan", "Cook those crêpes", "Assemble", "Serve", "Pancake perfection", "A brunch of epic proportions"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dulce-de-leche-crepe"}, {"id": 581, "t": "Gluten-Free Chewy Gnocchi Noodles", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Imagine a noodle that has the flavor of potato gnocchi, and a texture that’s somewhere between an udon noodle and a rice cake. It’d be pretty cool, yeah? Imagine no more. This recipe relies on the concept of using potato starch for chewiness and potatoes for tenderness and flavor—otherwise known as a winning combination. The texture, thickness, and overall visual appeal of these noodles is pretty ", "i": ["480 g Yukon Gold potato(es) , peeled and cooked, about 2 large raw potatoes", "130 g Potato starch", "5 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Prep the potatoes for steaming", "Steam the potatoes", "Make the dough", "Knead the dough", "Roll out the dough", "Cook", "Special sauce"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chewy-gnocchi-noodle"}, {"id": 582, "t": "Chili-Garlic Everything Sauce", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "“The more the merrier” could easily be the unofficial motto of craveable all-purpose sauces that you can slather on anything. You can never have too many in your repertoire. This sauce might look like a ton of ingredients, but it’s a super versatile, nearly impossible to f*-up recipe that allows room for improv. Don’t have garlic chives? You can just use regular chives, or omit chives all together", "i": ["30 g Ginger , grated", "13 g Garlic , grated, about 4 cloves", "40 g Cilantro , sliced, about 1 small bunch", "35 g Garlic chives , sliced", "100 g Chile paste", "150 g Dark sweetened vinegar", "120 g Soy sauce", "15 g Sesame oil", "25 g Fish sauce", "75 g Distilled vinegar , or sub lime juice", "15 g Chile oil"], "s": ["Prep herbs and combine ingredients", "This sauce pairs great with..."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chili-garlic-all-purpose-sauce"}, {"id": 583, "t": "Love Spuds? These Recipes Are Anything But Small Potatoes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Baked, fried, or served as a side, it’s the starch we idolize most. The humble potato has become a pantry staple in homes across the globe—even if it’s just a bag of chips. But the potato was a novelty back in the 16th century, when it arrived in Europe from the Americas via the Spanish (​​potato is derived from the Spanish word patata). By the 18th century, it had emerged as an essential food, wi", "i": [], "s": ["Taters gonna tate", "Potato cosplay", "Crunch time", "Joined at the dip", "Side piece", "Keep your eyes peeled"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/love-spuds-these-recipes-are-anything-but-small-potatoes"}, {"id": 584, "t": "The Ultimate Air Frying Hub", "c": "Meat", "d": "If you already have an air fryer in your kitchen, or are thinking of buying one of these compact workhorses, this essential guide is for you! Here, we’ve assembled some of our favorite air fryer recipes, along with some tips and tricks, to enable you to become an air frying ninja in the time it takes to cook a batch of cauliflower wings. No, really. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["But first...", "Get the best results", "Leveled-up shake and bake", "Game-changing potatoes"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-air-frying-hub"}, {"id": 585, "t": "Impossibly Good: The Ultimate Plant-Based Brownie", "c": "Baking", "d": "When we made the Rich as F*¢K Brownie, we didn’t think there was any possible way to top it. But then the Yeti Brownie came along. And now we’re back with yet another ultimate brownie—one so good, you won’t believe it’s vegan and gluten-free. This all-inclusive brownie is the ultimate crowd-pleaser. Love gluten, eggs, and dairy? You’ll love this brownie, too. Can’t have gluten or grains? We gotchu", "i": ["365 g Purple sweet potato , about 1 large", "15 g Flaxseed", "75 g Boiling water", "150 g 70% dark chocolate , vegan if you desire", "90 g Red palm oil , or vegan butter substitute", "200 g Water", "425 g Dark brown muscovado sugar", "8 g Vanilla extract", "115 g Dutch-process cocoa powder (Brute)", "125 g Cassava flour , Otto's", "7 g Salt , kosher", "3 g Baking soda", "75 g Hot water", "100 g Raw cashews", "35 g Maple syrup", "60 g Sugar , organic"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Preheat the oven to 350 °F / 177 °C", "Bake the sweet potato", "Make the flax egg", "Melt chocolate and fat", "Process wet ingredients", "Add dry ingredients", "Bake", "Cool, slice, and serve", "Store any leftovers"], "tips": ["If you can’t find purple sweet potatoes", "Icing takes these brownies to the next level"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/plant-based-brownie-with-purple-sweet-potato-power"}, {"id": 586, "t": "Make “Instant” Kombucha with a Fruity Shrub and Whipping Siphon", "c": "Baking", "d": "Refreshing and bursting with flavor, kombucha (fermented and flavored tea) is a balance of sweet and sour. Enticing and tangy, kombucha—like all fermented foods—takes time and patience to make. We wondered if there was a way to speed up the process. Part vinegar-y shrub, part sweet tea, this bubbly rapid infusion is ready in one day and doesn’t require sourcing a SCOBY (the “symbiotic culture of b", "i": ["750 ml Water", "20 g Tea , loose leaf or 8 to 12 teabags", "250 g Fresh fruit , of your choice", "80 g Apple cider vinegar , raw", "40 g Sugar , optional", "Soda water , optional (if you do not have an iSi whipping siphon) , as needed", "750 ml Water 20 g Tea , loose leaf or 8 to 12 teabags"], "s": ["Make tea", "Make the shrub mixture", "Marry the two infusions", "Charge it", "Strain, serve, sip, and have a zen moment"], "tips": ["Choosing fruits", "Don’t have a whipping siphon?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/you-might-think-it-s-kombucha-but-it-s-not"}, {"id": 587, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Turn Stems and Scraps Into Delicious Dishes", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Brassica cores are not meant for the compost. While florets are the most visually and texturally compelling, stems and cores are equally divine and delicious in their own right. They can be roasted, sautéed, grated, steamed and smashed, and even “riced.” Below, we’re sharing just a few quick and easy ways that you can save your scraps and put them to delicious use. This technique works well for th", "i": [], "s": ["Save those scraps", "Put those cores to work", "Roast whole", "Upgrade those salads", "Toss with pasta"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/use-those-scraps"}, {"id": 588, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Make the Most of Your Microplane Grater", "c": "Baking", "d": "Most commonly used for zesting citrus, handheld Microplane graters are available in a variety of shapes and sizes and are a great tool to add to your kitchen arsenal. An excellent alternative to mincing by hand or bulkier box graters, a Microplane yields fluffy threads of cheese and truffles, shavings of chocolate perfect for garnishing, and finely minced aromatics that are easily dispersed in dis", "i": [], "s": ["Choose Your Weapon", "From Grate to Great: Our Best Tips", "Let’s Get Grating", "What will you grate next?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-and-tricks-five-ways-to-microplane-magic"}, {"id": 589, "t": "Plant-Based, Gluten-Free, and Grain-Free Cookies That Are Impossibly Delicious", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. The key building blocks of drop cookies are simple and straightforward: flour, butter, eggs, and sugar. But these cookies do the impossible—they’re freakin’ delicious without butter, eggs, and gluten-y flour. In fact, they’re made entirely without grains! The not-so-secret ingredient that makes these cookies epic and suitable for any and all e", "i": ["7 g Flaxseed", "42 g Hot water", "65 g Dark brown muscovado sugar", "90 g Maple syrup , or cane/golden syrup", "60 g Coconut oil (refined) , soft or melted", "12 g Vanilla extract", "226 g Almond flour", "2.5 g Salt , kosher", "3.5 g Baking soda", "225 g Plant-based chocolate chips", "75 g Pecans", "100 g Peanut butter", "150 g Peanuts , whole or ground", "90 g Molasses", "2 g Spices , your choice, like cinnamon, ginger, and cloves", "Sugar, as needed", "250 g Raisins , or apricots", "75 g Medjool dates", "125 g Rolled oats", "1.5 g Cinnamon", "0.5 g Cloves"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Make flax egg", "Mix together the wet ingredients", "Incorporate dry ingredients", "Portion and rest", "Preheat the oven", "Pan and press", "Bake", "Cool and enjoy", "Three Epic Flavor Alternatives", "Peanut Butter", "Molasses and Spice", "Oatmeal and Dried Fruit", "Build your cookie-baking skills", "Level up", "Drop cookies: Gotta bake ’em all!"], "tips": ["Why scoop size matters", "Freezing raw cookie dough", "What size baking pan to use", "The edge test: it’s the best way to tell if your cookies are done", "We can’t believe these are plant-based!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-four-plant-based-recipes"}, {"id": 590, "t": "The Ultimate Date Night Dinner: Chocolate Steak", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Yes, you read that right but it’s not quite what it sounds like. When it comes to delicious date nights, especially Valentine’s Day, two things typically come to mind—chocolate and steak. Instead of keeping those courses separate, we suggest combining the two for a double aphrodisiac dinner that’s an ultimate easy win. This meal is surprising, and surprisingly simple. You’ll need to sous vide some", "i": ["Steak(s) , your favorite cut , as needed", "Aromatics , like shallot, garlic, and fresh herbs; for steaks; optional , as needed", "150 ml Light red wine , 1 glass, reduced to 15 grams", "10 g Sugar", "50 g 70% dark chocolate", "Bay leaf , fresh, or thyme leaves for butter; optional , as needed", "150 g Butter , unsalted, room temperature, plus extra to baste the steaks", "1 g Cocoa powder , to garnish", "Kosher salt , to taste , as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "Flake sea salt , to garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath and sear those steaks", "Cook sous vide", "Make the compound butter", "Whip it up", "Finish the steaks", "Butter ’em up and enjoy!", "May we suggest a side dish, or two?", "Chocolate for dessert, too? Don’t mind if we do!"], "tips": ["Going for filet mignon? Shop for skinnier steaks"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chocolate-steak"}, {"id": 591, "t": "Simple, Silky Smooth, Egg-Free Chocolate Custard", "c": "Baking", "d": "Creamy and custard-like but firm enough to slice and serve in style, this is a dessert that will satisfying picky eaters, little kiddos, sophisticated gourmands, and chocolate lovers alike. Making traditional custards can be finicky and time-consuming. This is a bulletproof version that comes together with just a handful of ingredients, steps, and hands-on minutes. Chef Kyl Haselbauer shows you ho", "i": ["750 g Water", "150 g Raw cashews", "140 g Organic cane sugar", "330 g 70% dark chocolate , coarsely chopped", "2 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F", "2 g Kosher salt , optional"], "s": ["Prep the mold", "Boil and blend the cashews", "Add chocolate", "Blend in the gellan gum", "Cast and tap", "Doll it up, slice, and enjoy!"], "tips": ["Add extra flavor (optional)", "The good word on gellan gum", "Mess up? It’s okay. You can make pudding!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vegan-no-bake-chocolate-custard"}, {"id": 592, "t": "From Dive Bar to Michelin Star Koji-Pickled Eggs", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "These aren’t the pickled eggs you fish out of a plastic tub filled with suspiciously neon green liquid at your neighborhood watering hole. By comparison, these cured eggs are the ultimate, upgraded, Michelin-star version—naturally vibrant in color thanks to thinly sliced beets (optional, but highly recommended), they have creamy yolks and an umami-rich flavor provided by rice koji. Koji is grains ", "i": ["900 g Water , plus extra to boil the eggs", "350 g Malt vinegar", "250 g Soy sauce", "35 g Mirin", "80 g Fresh ginger root", "35 g Serrano pepper", "30 g Garlic clove(s)", "8 g Salt , kosher", "6 g Black peppercorns", "1 kg Beet(s) , red (for color), optional", "35 g Rice koji", "12 Large egg(s)", "Large egg(s)", "Flake sea salt , to finish eggs , as needed", "1 kg Red beets , optional, for color", "4 quart Water 12 Large egg(s)", "4 quart Water", "4 quart"], "s": ["Make pickling liquid", "Optional: Add beets", "Add koji and rest", "Cook eggs", "quart", "Pickle!", "Serve", "Koji is cool", "The incredible egg"], "tips": ["Other ways to color your eggs"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/koji-pickled-eggs"}, {"id": 593, "t": "10 Minutes or Less to a Stunningly Simple and Vibrant Spinach Side Dish", "c": "Baking", "d": "Sautéed spinach is often watery, bitter, or bland. But with the reverse sauté technique, you can have juicy and flavorful spinach on the table in less time than it would take Popeye to crack open a can. Unlike other vegetables prepared using the reverse sauté method, spinach doesn’t require any extra water added to the pan—it naturally contains a lot of moisture that will cook out and make the fin", "i": ["454 g Fresh spinach , or other greens like kale, chard, or mustard", "1.5 g Butter", "4 g Kosher salt", "Red bell pepper(s) , shaved, to finish , as needed", "Lemon zest , to finish , as needed", "Black pepper , to finish , as needed"], "s": ["Refresh your reverse sauté skills", "Optional: Brown the butter", "1.5 Tbsp.", "Sauté", "Finish", "Aye, aye, Popeye! Enjoy your spinach alongside...", "Side dishes in a snap"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/reverse-saute-spinach"}, {"id": 594, "t": "10 Minutes or Less to a Warming and Spicy Cauliflower Side Dish", "c": "Baking", "d": "Cauliflower gets a bad rap as being boring and bland, but it’s really anything but! This hearty cruciferous veg is incredibly versatile, and the perfect blank canvas for any flavor combination. Rather than breaking cauliflower into randomly sized florets, we slice it thinly with the stems intact. This helps the cauliflower to cook quickly and evenly without getting mushy. Using the reverse sauté t", "i": ["0.5 Cauliflower , half a head", "50 ml Water", "35 g Ghee , (1.5 tablespoons)", "6 g Curry powder", "4 g Kosher salt", "Raisins , to finish , as needed", "Chives , fresh, chopped for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Refresh your reverse sauté skills", "Slice cauliflower", "Sauté", "Finish", "Cauliflower is delish with...", "Side dishes in a snap"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/reverse-saute-cauliflower"}, {"id": 595, "t": "10 Minutes or Less to a Vibrant and Flavorful Carrot Side Dish", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The humble carrot is endlessly versatile. Thinly sliced into coins or matchsticks, carrots quickly become a stellar side dish that takes just minutes to prepare thanks to the reverse sauté technique. This is also a great way to show off the beautiful colors of rainbow carrots. When it comes to carrots, what can’t they do? They’re delish in desserts—like cakes, bars and even modernist “fruit roll-u", "i": ["400 g Carrot(s) , about 2 bunches", "25 g Coconut oil (refined) , unrefined, virgin", "50 ml Water", "1 g Coriander seeds , crushed", "4 g Kosher salt", "1 Orange(s) , navel, zested and juiced, to finish", "2 Medjool dates , sliced, for garnish", "Unsweetened coconut flakes , toasted, for garnish , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Refresh your reverse sauté skills", "Slice carrots", "Sauté", "tsp.", "Finish", "These carrots pair well with ...", "Rapidly sauté your way to more side dishes"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/reverse-saute-carrots"}, {"id": 596, "t": "10 Minutes or Less to a Snappy and Savory Cabbage Side Dish", "c": "Baking", "d": "When it comes to cabbage, you may only think of coleslaw or sauerkraut piled high. But when quickly sautéed, thinly sliced cabbage transforms into crisp-tender bites that retain the leaves’ beautiful color and pair well with a range of flavors and ingredients. Using the reverse sauté technique, a little water added to the pan helps to quickly tenderize the cabbage without making it mushy. Once tha", "i": ["0.5 Red cabbage , or green, about half a head", "20 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "50 ml Water", "1 g Creole Spice Blend", "4 g Kosher salt", "Lemon juice , freshly squeezed, to finish , as needed"], "s": ["Refresh your reverse sauté skills", "Slice cabbage", "Sauté", "Tbsp.", "Finish", "Cabbage goes great with...", "Rapidly sauté your way to more side dishes"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/reverse-saute-red-cabbage"}, {"id": 597, "t": "10 Minutes or Less to a Spicy and Aromatic Beet Side Dish", "c": "Baking", "d": "Sweet and earthy beets are the perfect base for spicy harissa paste. Thinly sliced into half moons, beets cook up super quick and transform into a side dish that is loaded with bright flavors. Forget what you think you know about cooking this rock-hard root vegetable. Using the reverse sauté technique, thin slices of beets go from crunchy to crisp yet tender in just a few minutes. Since beets pair", "i": ["454 g Beet(s) , medium size", "20 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "50 ml Water", "4 g Kosher salt", "1.5 g Harissa paste", "1 Lime(s) , zested and juiced, to finish", "Parsley , Italian flat-leaf, freshly chopped, to garnish , as needed", "1.5 Tbsp. Harissa paste 1 Lime(s) , zested and juiced, to finish - Parsley , Italian flat-leaf, freshly chopped, to garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Refresh your reverse sauté skills", "Slice beets", "Sauté", "Finish", "1.5 Tbsp.", "Beets pair beautifully with...", "Side dishes in a snap"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/reverse-saute-beets"}, {"id": 598, "t": "Reverse Sauté: A Super Easy Technique to Cook Vegetables Super Fast", "c": "Baking", "d": "You don’t need a ton of time or fancy tools to get a delish side dish on the table. So, whether you’ve spent your time and energy perfecting the protein, or just need to get dinner done before hunger makes you hangry, the super fast reverse sauté method will give you incredible, flavorful, toothsome vegetables in just a few minutes. A typical sauté is a quick and delicate balance between extreme h", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Any vegetable , your choice , as needed - Fat , any fat of your choice , as needed - Water, as needed - Seasoning , your choice , as needed - Kosher salt, as needed", "Any vegetable , your choice , as needed - Fat , any fat of your choice , as needed - Water, as needed - Seasoning , your choice , as needed - Kosher salt, as needed", "Fat , any fat of your choice , as needed", "Water, as needed", "Seasoning , your choice , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Prep your veggies", "Choose your fat and flavors", "Sauté", "Serve", "Put this technique to work"], "tips": ["Easy ways to add extra flavor and texture"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/reverse-saute-technique"}, {"id": 599, "t": "Super Flavorful, Fresh, and Vibrant Vegetable Broth—Fast!", "c": "Baking", "d": "Vegetable broths—both store-bought or homemade—are often dull in color and bland in flavor. They lack the boldness and body of meatier broths and stocks because of the obvious lack of umami, bones, and meaty bits that have undergone the Maillard reaction. This technique makes it not only possible but extremely quick and easy to create a vegetable-forward broth that’s vibrant in flavor and color wi", "i": ["3000 ml Water", "800 g Onion(s) , about 3 onions, peeled, julienned", "600 g Carrot(s) , about 6 medium", "400 g Celery , about 1 bunch or 6 ribs", "65 g Parsley , 1-2 bunches", "25 g Thyme , 1-2 bunches", "4 g Black peppercorns , cracked", "1 g Bay leaf , fresh is best", "100 g Sunflower seed(s) , optional", "40 g Kombu , optional", "12 g Salt , to finish broth", "Fresh ginger root , optional , as needed - Fresh turmeric root , optional , as needed - Miso paste , optional , as needed - Fat , or oil of your choice , as needed", "Fresh turmeric root , optional , as needed", "Miso paste , optional , as needed", "Fat , or oil of your choice , as needed"], "s": ["Grate mirepoix", "Cook", "Steep that broth", "Strain and season", "Level it up for sipping", "Easy alternatives: How to make broth even faster, with mushrooms, or more Maillard", "Put that broth to work"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/rapid-vegetable-broth"}, {"id": 600, "t": "Level Up Your Egg White Scramble With a Surprising Pantry Staple", "c": "Baking", "d": "Tender, creamy, and custardy are words not typically used to describe an egg white-only scramble. Instead, you might think rubbery, chewy, tough, and bland. While understanding a little egg science—particularly how proteins coagulate and the temperatures at which they begin to firm up—can help you make a better scramble, you’ll still need a surprising, simple ingredient to pull it all together. Co", "i": ["300 g Egg white(s) , about 12 ea", "11 g Cornstarch", "22 g Water", "2 g Kosher salt", "10 g Avocado oil"], "s": ["Blend egg base", "Preheat pan", "Scramble", "Serve", "There’s more than one way to scramble eggs", "For our egg-free friends", "Even more incredible eggs!"], "tips": ["Use those yolks!", "Make an omelet instead"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/egg-white-scramble-omelet"}, {"id": 601, "t": "Light as a Cloud Egg", "c": "Baking", "d": "This isn’t the cloud egg that dominated social media feeds a few years ago. Forget those images of brilliant yellow yolks surrounded by puffy whipped egg whites. True clouds those eggs are not—they’re more akin to “nests,” really, or perhaps like low-lying stratus clouds. These eggs are the cumulus of cloud eggs—big fluffy whipped whites completely enrobe tender and runny yolks. Visually stunning,", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 4 Egg(s) , whole - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper, as needed - Fresh herbs , any, to garnish , as needed - Scallion(s) , sliced, to garnish , as needed", "4 Egg(s) , whole - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper, as needed - Fresh herbs , any, to garnish , as needed - Scallion(s) , sliced, to garnish , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "Fresh herbs , any, to garnish , as needed", "Scallion(s) , sliced, to garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Prep the steamer", "Separate eggs", "Prep the wrappers", "Whip the whites", "Portion the whites and add yolks", "Take your clouds to new heights with extra additions", "Secure the cloud bundles", "Steam", "Carefully unwrap", "Plate", "A quick comparison: Cloud egg versus poached egg"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cloud-egg"}, {"id": 602, "t": "Otto’s Silky Smooth Bain Marie Scrambled Eggs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Low cooking temperatures provide the best safety margins for delicate foods, which is why custards and other egg-based treats are often cooked in a bain marie (water bath), sous vide, or whisked in a bowl over a pot of steaming water. So, it’s no surprise that a technique similar to cooking crème brûlée, cheesecake, and crema catalana would also work well for scrambled eggs. While scrambling eggs ", "i": ["5 Large egg(s) , whole", "Large egg(s) , whole", "20 g Butter , unsalted, cubed, room temperature", "30 g Heavy cream", "Salt , kosher , as needed", "Chives , fresh, minced, for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["See Otto Scramble", "Bring water to a simmer", "Prep eggs", "Cook", "Finish off the heat", "Garnish and enjoy", "There’s more than one way to scramble an egg", "For our egg-free friends", "Omelets are also technically scrambles", "Beyond the scramble"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/otto-silky-scrambled-eggs"}, {"id": 603, "t": "Matthew’s Plant-Based Tofu Scramble (Egg-Free)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Crumbled firm tofu is quick and easy to sauté and is an excellent alternative to eggs for breakfast. Chef Matthew Woolen demonstrates his technique in the video below, and shares a few tips and secret ingredients to give tofu an “eggy” appearance and flavor. Just like scrambled eggs, this dish is quick and easy to prepare but it does need some extra hands-off prep time to press moisture out of the", "i": ["1 Tofu , firm, 14 to 16 ounce block", "3 Scallion(s) , light green parts, thinly sliced", "12 g Red palm oil", "5 g Bamboo salt", "0.5 g Turmeric root powder", "Fresh herbs , mixed, optional for garnish , as needed", "Black pepper , optional , as needed"], "s": ["See Matthew Scramble", "Drain and press tofu", "Crumble tofu", "Prep seasonings", "Cook", "Garnish and enjoy", "Plant-based perfection", "Eat eggs? Make a scramble", "Cook more eggs!"], "tips": ["The secret is salt"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/this-is-your-brain-on-tofu-plant-based-scramble"}, {"id": 604, "t": "Kyl’s Extra Fluffy Quick-Fire Scrambled Eggs", "c": "Baking", "d": "When you’ve gotta get a protein-rich breakfast on the table super quick (and preferably without dirtying too many dishes), chef Kyl Haselbauer’s cold-start scrambling technique is sure to do the trick. In the video below, Kyl shows you how to toss everything—eggs, milk, and butter—right into a cold pan for the quickest breakfast ever. He also shares his tips to avoid overcooking and how to prep yo", "i": ["6 Large egg(s)", "Large egg(s)", "56 g Butter , unsalted, cubed", "56 g Whole milk", "Salt, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed"], "s": ["See Kyl Scramble", "Combine ingredients in the cold pan", "Scramble away", "Serve", "There’s more than one way to scramble an egg", "For our egg-free friends", "Omelets are also technically scrambles", "Beyond the scramble"], "tips": ["Our fave nonstick pan for scrambled eggs"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/kyl-two-minute-scrambled-eggs"}, {"id": 605, "t": "Nick’s Tender and Creamy Precision-Poached Scrambled Eggs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Looking for a fun and easy way to upgrade your morning scrambled eggs? Look no further than chef Nicholas Gavin’s modernist-inspired method. Nick first discovered this technique when mastering the two-step modernist omelet which is filled with incredibly light scrambled eggs that have been cooked sous vide and then “fluffed” using an iSi whipping siphon. He realized that the sous vide-poached scra", "i": ["250 g Egg(s) , whole, about 5 large", "65 g Heavy cream", "25 g Butter , unsalted, melted and cooled slightly", "3 g Kosher salt", "Fresh herbs , for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["See Nick Scramble", "Heat water to 176 °F / 80 °C", "Make the egg base", "Transfer to the water bath", "Serve", "There’s more than one way to scramble an egg", "For our egg-free friends", "Omelets are also technically scrambles", "Beyond the scramble"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/scrambled-egg-nick-s-version"}, {"id": 606, "t": "Grant’s Springy, Creamy “Reverse” Scrambled Eggs", "c": "Baking", "d": "The mighty egg is capable of achieving a range of textures—from fluffy foams to creamy emulsions. Without a lot of tools or time, it’s easy to whip up a scramble that stretches across a spectrum of textures—from bouncy and springy to fluffy, tender, and creamy. Chef Grant Crilly demonstrates his go-to technique in the video below. To maximize texture, he barely whips his eggs and he “reverses” the", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 6 Egg(s) , whole - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed 57 g Cream - Chives , fresh, minced, for garnish , as needed", "6 Egg(s) , whole - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed 57 g Cream - Chives , fresh, minced, for garnish , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed", "57 g Cream", "Chives , fresh, minced, for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["See Grant Scramble", "Whisk eggs to your preference", "Preheat pan", "Scramble!", "Add cream and finish cooking", "Garnish and enjoy", "There’s more than one way to scramble an egg", "For our egg-free friends", "Omelets are also technically scrambles", "Beyond the scramble"], "tips": ["Our fave nonstick pan for scrambled eggs"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/reverse-scramble-egg"}, {"id": 607, "t": "Five Chefs Scramble Eggs Five Ways", "c": "Baking", "d": "There’s more than one way to crack an egg, and even more ways to scramble it up. Using their personal favorite methods, our chefs demonstrate five different methods for achieving tender, succulent curds to help you get eggcellent results. Scrambling an egg isn’t difficult, per se—when quickly whisked and cooked over high heat, you’ll have breakfast ready in 60 seconds or less. But achieving curds ", "i": [], "s": ["Super Fast and Fluffy Cold-Start Scramble", "A Quick Way to Make Creamy, Springy Curds—in Reverse!", "A Tender Scramble Takes Time and Precision", "The Gentlest—and Fanciest—Way to Make a Silky, Creamy Scramble", "The Scramble for Egg-Free Friends", "The incredible egg"], "tips": ["What’s salt got to do with it?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/five-chefs-five-scrambles"}, {"id": 608, "t": "Flaky Pull-Apart Brioche Rolls", "c": "Baking", "d": "Buttery brioche and flaky laminated doughs are the foundations for so many delectable pastries. From croissants to toaster tarts and panettone to kouign amann. We love a good baking mashup—like this sweet croissant-cinnamon roll hybrid—which made us wonder: what happens when you laminate a brioche dough? Like flaky biscuits and bread had a baby, these buttery pull-apart rolls have a gentle yeast f", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 recipe Easy, Breezy, Beautiful Brioche (Plus Two Ways to Upgrade) - Egg wash, as needed", "1 recipe Easy, Breezy, Beautiful Brioche (Plus Two Ways to Upgrade) - Egg wash, as needed", "Egg wash, as needed"], "s": ["Prepare brioche dough with half the butter", "Roll out dough and add butter", "Fold, roll, and rest", "Cut rolls", "Proof until almost double in size", "Preheat the oven", "Bake", "Cool and enjoy!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turning-brioche-into-flaky-pull-apart-rolls"}, {"id": 609, "t": "Easy, Breezy, Beautiful Brioche (Plus Two Ways to Upgrade)", "c": "Baking", "d": "Rich and eggy, brioche is a thing of buttery beauty. Is it bread or is it cake? Some say that Marie Antoinette’s famously divisive (and perhaps entirely made up) proclamation, “Let them eat cake” was actually “Let them eat brioche.” Incredibly versatile, this bakery standard can be sweet or savory and is an excellent foundation for burger buns, dinner rolls, panettone, and other pastries. Enriched", "i": ["100 g Milk , whole", "30 g Instant dry yeast", "250 g Egg(s) , whole", "550 g Bread flour", "75 g Sugar , granulated", "12 g Kosher salt", "300 g Butter , unsalted, softened", "Egg wash , for the top of the brioche loaves , as needed", "100 g Egg yolk(s)"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Mix dough", "Knock in the butter", "Smooth and chill", "Prepare loaf pans", "Shape the loaves", "Proof", "Preheat the oven", "Brush with egg wash", "Bake in two stages", "Cool", "Serve", "Troubleshooting brioche", "Rich with dough"], "tips": ["Upgrade: Make it rich as f*¢k!", "Braid the loaves instead of rolling", "How to turn your home oven into a proof box"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/building-upon-the-foundational-brioche"}, {"id": 610, "t": "In the Know with Enriched Doughs", "c": "Baking", "d": "Brioche is the most versatile dough in the bakery. It can be made sweet or savory, shaped into loaves or laminated into pastries. The base for danishes and sweet rolls, an enriched dough is equally capable of yielding soft hamburger buns or pillowy beignets coated in powdered sugar. Enriched bread doughs, like brioche, contain more fats, sugar, eggs, milk products, and yeast, compared to lean doug", "i": [], "s": ["Brioche is versatile", "Beyond brioche: Rich and savory breads", "Laminated with lots of layers", "Sweet treats"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/in-the-know-enriched-doughs"}, {"id": 611, "t": "How to Turn Cheap Wine into Bubbly “Champagne” (and Make Fizzy Grapes)", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "We all love Champagne, but we don’t love the hefty price tag. This technique makes “champagne” that tastes great, almost instantly, for cheap. And unlike traditional bottled Champagne, this method will also give you fresh, carbonated, fizzy grapes that you can enjoy in or alongside your glass of bubbly. We’re calling this “champagne with a lowercase c” because it’s not made in the Champagne region", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Wine , any white, rosé or red that you like , as needed - Grapes , your favorite variety (in season) , as needed", "Wine , any white, rosé or red that you like , as needed - Grapes , your favorite variety (in season) , as needed", "Grapes , your favorite variety (in season) , as needed"], "s": ["Chill wine and slice grapes", "Get fizzy with it", "Chill and rest", "Pop the top and pour", "Behind the scenes: Grant’s blind taste test"], "tips": ["Grant talks “real Champagne”", "How to charge your siphon", "CO2 versus N2O"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/diy-fresh-fizzy-champagne-grapes"}, {"id": 612, "t": "American Drop Cookies: Baking", "c": "Baking", "d": "This page is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. This is where all of your cookie-making skills shine. If you’ve prepared a poor dough, no amount of good baking can save it. But if you’ve been following every step in the Drop Cookie Class and your dough is well mixed and well rested, you’ll still have an enjoyable end product, even if you mess up the baking. (As long as you don’t burn the cook", "i": [], "s": ["Proper Baking", "The edge test", "Next step: Enjoy! Then storage and/or freeze your leftovers"], "tips": ["Baking multiple types of cookies?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookies-baking"}, {"id": 613, "t": "Pro Tips & Tricks to Master Your Cookie Destiny", "c": "Baking", "d": "This page is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. Cheers, cookie connoisseur! In the Drop Cookie Class, you’ve learned what a drop cookie is, and the fundamentals for baking them up right. You’ve got your equipment stocked and your desired textures dialed in. Maybe you’ve already even baked a batch—or a few. But we’ve still got a few cookie tricks and tips up our sleeves. Curious about coatings", "i": [], "s": ["You can dough it!", "Add a little sourdough starter", "Brown the butter", "Roll, roll, roll your dough", "You can even roll cookies in other cookies!", "Play with shapes & textures", "Smash it real good", "Turn your cookies into bars", "Better baking", "Test the spread rate", "Double the pan, reduce the browning", "Reduce and reuse your parchment paper!", "What to do with leftover cookies", "Make a cheesecake crust", "Make ice cream sandwiches or cookie ice cream!", "Dig into the Drop Cookie Class", "Bake something!"], "tips": ["Level up your cookie baking know-how", "Cookie storing and freezing tips"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-tips-and-tricks"}, {"id": 614, "t": "Sugar Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. The value of a well-made sugar cookie should never be underestimated. As the foundation from which so many other cookies originate, this one deserves a spot near the top of the cookie hierarchy. Drop sugar cookies are simple and straightforward, so high-quality ingredients are essential for the buttery, vanilla-forward flavor to shine. Egg yol", "i": ["273 g Sugar , plus extra for dredging", "227 g Butter , unsalted, soft", "18 g Vanilla extract", "50 g Large egg(s) , 1 each", "30 g Egg yolk(s) , 2 each", "375 g All-purpose flour", "6 g Baking soda", "5 g Kosher salt", "2.5 g Cream of tartar"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Cream together butter, sugar, and eggs", "Incorporate dry ingredients", "Portion and rest", "Preheat the oven", "Pan and press", "Bake", "Cool", "Easy upgrades!", "Build your cookie-baking skills", "Level up", "Drop cookies: Gotta bake ’em all!"], "tips": ["Why scoop size matters", "Freezing raw cookie dough", "What size baking pan to use", "The edge test: it’s the best way to tell if your cookies are done"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-sugar"}, {"id": 615, "t": "Maple Pecan Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. This isn’t that dusty ol’ store-bought shortbread cookie with a few nut pieces here or there. It’s a buttery drop cookie with crisp, lacy edges and a soft interior. When developing this recipe for our Drop Cookie Class, we tested batch and batch to dial in the perfect balance of butter, maple flavor, and pecans. Adding a liquid sweetener meant", "i": ["180 g Butter , unsalted, soft", "150 g Brown sugar", "115 g Sugar", "110 g Maple syrup B grade", "10 g Maple extract", "50 g Large egg(s) , 1 each", "310 g All-purpose flour", "5 g Kosher salt", "4 g Baking soda", "140 g Pecans"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Cream together butter, sugar, syrup, and egg", "Incorporate dry ingredients", "Portion and rest", "Preheat the oven", "Pan and press", "Bake", "Cool", "Easy upgrades!", "Build your cookie-baking skills", "Level up", "Drop cookies: Gotta bake ’em all!"], "tips": ["Toasting pecans", "Why scoop size matters", "Freezing raw cookie dough", "What size baking pan to use", "The edge test: it’s the best way to tell if your cookies are done"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-maple-pecan"}, {"id": 616, "t": "Snickerdoodle Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. A really good snickerdoodle might make you question our nation’s fealty to chocolate chips. One bite of this one and you’ll be Team ’Doodle, for sure. It’s perfectly balanced: sweet, spiced, rich with eggs, and brightened with a hint of acidity from an absolutely essential snickerdoodle ingredient: cream of tartar. Cream of tartar is powdered ", "i": ["298 g Sugar", "152 g Butter , unsalted, soft", "75 g Coconut oil (refined)", "100 g Large egg(s) , 2 each", "12 g Vanilla extract", "350 g All-purpose flour", "9 g Cream of tartar", "6.5 g Baking soda", "5 g Kosher salt", "0.5 g Nutmeg , grated", "25 g Cinnamon , ground, for dredging"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Cream together butter, oil, sugar, and eggs", "Incorporate dry ingredients", "Prepare cinnamon and sugar coating", "Portion and rest", "Preheat the oven", "Pan and press", "Bake", "Cool", "Easy upgrades!", "Build your baking skills", "Level up", "Drop cookies: Gotta bake ’em all!"], "tips": ["Why scoop size matters", "Freezing raw cookie dough", "What size baking pan to use", "The edge test: it’s the best way to tell if your cookies are done"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/snickerdoodle-drop-cookies"}, {"id": 617, "t": "Oatmeal Raisin Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. How do you describe the inimitable texture of a warm, perfectly baked oatmeal raisin cookie? Darn good, that’s how. This cookie, developed as part of our Drop Cookie Class, may just be the best oatmeal raisin cookie ever. The edges are crisp and golden, the raisins are plump and sweet, and the center is gloriously soft and gooey. Our secret? G", "i": ["75 g Butter , unsalted", "130 g Vegetable oil", "180 g Brown sugar", "130 g Sugar", "20 g Vanilla extract", "50 g Large egg(s) , 1 each", "15 g Egg yolk(s) , 1 each", "300 g Rolled oats", "135 g Bread flour", "15 g Cornstarch", "6 g Kosher salt", "4.5 g Baking soda", "2 g Cinnamon , ground", "280 g Raisins , any variety"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Cream together butter, oil, sugars, and eggs", "Incorporate dry ingredients", "Portion and rest", "Preheat the oven", "Pan and press", "Bake", "Cool", "Easy upgrades!", "Build your cookie-baking skills", "Level up", "Drop cookies: Gotta bake ’em all!"], "tips": ["Want to make a gluten-free or vegan version?", "Why scoop size matters", "Freezing raw cookie dough", "What size baking pan to use", "The edge test: it’s the best way to tell if your cookies are done"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-oatmeal-raisin"}, {"id": 618, "t": "Triple Chocolate Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. When the chocolate craving hits hard, a cookie with chips alone just won’t cut it. Triple the chocolate means triple the fun—and triple the craving satiation, too. When developing this recipe for our Drop Cookie Class, we set our sights on a true chocolate overload. We boosted the dough with cocoa powder and a variety of chocolate chunks. A fi", "i": ["227 g Butter , unsalted, soft", "171 g Brown sugar", "171 g Sugar", "8 g Vanilla extract", "100 g Large egg(s)", "363 g All-purpose flour", "57 g Cocoa powder", "5 g Kosher salt", "4.5 g Baking soda", "175 g 70% dark chocolate , chopped", "150 g 40% milk chocolate , chopped", "Flake sea salt , optional, for finishing , as needed"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Cream together butter, sugars, and egg", "Incorporate dry ingredients", "Portion and rest", "Preheat the oven", "Pan and press", "Bake", "Cool", "Easy upgrades!", "Build your cookie-baking skills", "Level up", "Drop cookies: Gotta bake ’em all!"], "tips": ["Why scoop size matters", "Freezing raw cookie dough", "What size baking pan to use", "The edge test: it’s the best way to tell if your cookies are done"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-triple-chocolate"}, {"id": 619, "t": "Peanut Butter Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. With their iconic hashmark tops, peanut butter cookies are Americana classics, right at home alongside deep-dish apple pie, regional BBQ, and soup-laced casseroles. Our version has the best balance of intense peanut butter flavor, crispy edges, and a soft center. When developing the recipes for the Drop Cookie Class, we knew we had to include ", "i": ["260 g Peanut butter , creamy or crunchy", "227 g Butter , unsalted, soft", "225 g Sugar", "100 g Brown sugar", "12 g Vanilla extract", "50 g Large egg(s) , 1 each", "235 g Bread flour", "5 g Kosher salt", "4.5 g Baking soda", "150 g Peanuts , roasted and ground", "25 g Milk , whole"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Cream together butters, sugars, and egg", "Incorporate dry ingredients", "Add peanuts and milk", "Portion and rest", "Preheat the oven", "Pan and press", "Bake", "Cool", "Easy upgrades!", "Build your cookie-baking skills", "Level up", "Drop cookies: Gotta bake ’em all!"], "tips": ["Want to make a gluten-free or vegan version?", "Why scoop size matters", "Freezing raw cookie dough", "What size baking pan to use", "The edge test: it’s the best way to tell if your cookies are done"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/peanut-butter-cookies"}, {"id": 620, "t": "Molasses Spice Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. With a little sugar and a little spice, these cookies are everything nice. With a soft and chewy texture, rich flavor, and heady aroma, this molasses spice cookie is sure to trigger warm and fuzzy feelings. When developing this and other recipes for the Drop Cookie Class, we drew inspiration from anywhere and everywhere. This recipe originally", "i": ["217 g Sugar , plus more for dredging", "200 g Butter , unsalted", "130 g Molasses", "50 g Large egg(s) , 1 each", "302 g All-purpose flour", "13 g Baking soda", "4 g Kosher salt", "8 g Cinnamon , ground", "6 g Ginger , ground", "3 g Cloves , ground", "2 g Allspice , ground", "120 g Crystallized ginger , chopped", "26 g Fresh ginger root , grated"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Cream together butter, sugar, molasses, and egg", "Incorporate dry ingredients", "Portion and rest", "Preheat the oven", "Pan and press", "Bake", "Cool", "A gingery upgrade!", "Build your cookie-baking skills", "Level up", "Drop cookies: Gotta bake ’em all!"], "tips": ["Want to make a gluten-free or vegan version?", "Why scoop size matters", "Freezing raw cookie dough", "What size baking pan to use", "The edge test: it’s the best way to tell if your cookies are done"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-molasses-spice"}, {"id": 621, "t": "Macadamia White Chocolate Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This recipe is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. The combination of macadamia nuts and white chocolate chips in a cookie has an almost cult following, and we can see why! It’s a buttery drop cookie with notes of honey that is studded with macadamia nuts and loaded with chunks of white chocolate. At its core, this is a chocolate chip cookie. So, to develop this recipe for our Drop Cookie Clas", "i": ["180 g Butter , unsalted, soft", "150 g Brown sugar", "50 g Sugar", "50 g Honey", "12 g Vanilla extract", "50 g Large egg(s) , 1 each", "15 g Egg yolk(s) , 1 each", "270 g All-purpose flour", "5 g Kosher salt", "4 g Baking soda", "150 g Macadamia nuts , raw", "350 g White chocolate , chopped or chips"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Cream together butter, sugars, honey, and eggs", "Incorporate dry ingredients", "Portion and rest", "Preheat the oven", "Pan and press", "Bake", "Cool", "Easy upgrades!", "Build your cookie-baking skills", "Level up", "Drop cookies: Gotta bake ’em all!"], "tips": ["To toast or not?", "Why scoop size matters", "Freezing raw cookie dough", "What size baking pan to use", "The edge test: it’s the best way to tell if your cookies are done"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-macadamia-white-chocolate"}, {"id": 622, "t": "An Introduction to Drop Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This page is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. While there are dozens upon dozens of different types of cookies and many cookie-baking techniques—from piping French macarons to rolling and cutting out festive shortbread dressed up with royal icing and vibrant freeze-dried fruit—the drop cookie is, and always will be, a classic. Drop cookies are easy to mix, bake, and enjoy. They freeze well,", "i": [], "s": ["The scoop on drop cookies", "Why make drop cookies?", "What you’ll learn in this class", "Let’s get started", "Level up", "Dive into the recipes"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-an-introduction-to-drop-cookies"}, {"id": 623, "t": "American Drop Cookies: Scaling and Mixing", "c": "Baking", "d": "This page is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. The first step to baking an incredible drop cookie is properly scaling (aka measuring) your ingredients. Measuring by weight (in grams) rather than by volume (using cups and spoons) gives you immense control and ensures consistency—from our recipe to your kitchen, and from batch to batch that you bake. Once you’ve got your ingredients measured a", "i": [], "s": ["Scaling", "Mixing", "Next step: Portioning and resting"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookies-scaling-and-mixing"}, {"id": 624, "t": "American Drop Cookies: Portioning and Resting", "c": "Baking", "d": "This page is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. Now that you’ve mixed up a beautiful dough, it’s time to portion those cookies and then take a nap. While every step of the cookie-making process is important, portioning and resting are key for baking cookies that look like cookies. Uniformly portioning the dough ensures that all of the cookies are the same size and will bake evenly. The easies", "i": [], "s": ["Portioning", "Rest up", "Next step: Baking"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookies-portioning-and-resting"}, {"id": 625, "t": "American Drop Cookies: Storing and Freezing", "c": "Baking", "d": "This page is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. You’ve successfully baked a batch of cookies! Once you’ve satisfied your inner Cookie Monster, make sure to store any leftovers properly to prevent your cookies from going stale. If you have portioned raw dough remaining, you can save it to bake later on whenever another cookie craving strikes. (Psst! All of these cookies can easily be baked fro", "i": [], "s": ["Best ways to store cookies", "How to freeze raw dough to bake later", "How to freeze leftover baked cookies", "Bake some more cookies", "Level up your baking"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookies-freezing-and-storing"}, {"id": 626, "t": "American Drop Cookie: Baking Tools and Equipment", "c": "Baking", "d": "This page is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. As we’ll explore in other parts of the Drop Cookie Class, this kind of cookie is relatively simple to bake compared to its fancier piped, meringue-based, rolled, and stenciled brethren. But you still need to scale smartly, master the creaming method, and find the best baking pans that fit your oven and yield beautiful results. You don’t need muc", "i": [], "s": ["For scaling", "For mixing", "For portioning", "For baking: An oven", "For baking: Sheet pans and cooling racks", "For storage", "Level up your cookie baking", "Bake some cookies!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-tools-and-equipment"}, {"id": 627, "t": "How to Adapt the Texture of Your Drop Cookies and Dial in Your Perfect Recipe", "c": "Baking", "d": "This page is part of our American Drop Cookie Class. Hello, cookie classmates! Welcome to the next level of making drop cookies. You’ve learned the fundamentals of mixing dough and baking, and have your tools and equipment prepped and ready. Now that you know the rules, we’re going to show you how to break ’em. It’s time to go from rookie to rockstar (without trashing any hotel rooms). Everyone ha", "i": [], "s": ["Need to brush up on your baking knowledge?", "To make softer, cake-like cookies:", "To make ooey, gooey, chewy cookies:", "To make crispy, crunchy cookies:", "Level up", "Let’s bake some cookies!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/american-drop-cookie-texture-techniques"}, {"id": 628, "t": "Family Meal: A Holiday Feast at ChefSteps", "c": "Baking", "d": "“Family meal” is a venerated tradition in restaurants where staffers gather and enjoy a meal together before service begins. Typically prepared by the kitchen staff and served buffet-style, the family meal helps to bring the team together around a table—just like at home. The chefs carried over this tradition to ChefSteps because we believe that cooking and eating together makes us better at our j", "i": [], "s": ["Whether you’re cooking for a few or a crowd, keep these things in mind", "On the Menu:", "Can it still be called a “centerpiece” if you made five?", "On the side", "Sauce it up", "Don’t forget dessert"], "tips": ["More amazing family meals", "Wondering about that butternut squash Wellington?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/family-meal-a-holiday-feast"}, {"id": 629, "t": "Your 2021 Thanksgiving Cooking Hotline Q&A", "c": "Baking", "d": "Welcome to your one-stop-Thanksgiving-cooking-question-shop. Hit us with your best Qs in the comments below, and we’ll get you our best As as quick as we can. If you need menu or recipe inspiration, check out our collection of Thanksgiving deliciousness. Our chefs—Grant Crilly, Nicholas Gavin, Kyl Haselbauer, and Matthew Woolen—are here and ready to help you with meal planning and prep on the days", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/studio-pass-chef-answered-thanksgiving-questions"}, {"id": 630, "t": "Leftover Thanksgiving Turkey Popped Pot Pie", "c": "Baking", "d": "Step up your Thanksgiving leftovers with this new take on a pot pie. It’s faster—no need to deal with pie dough, and can even be prepped ahead of time. It’s also lighter than your average pot pie with an amazing savory soufflé topping. It’s not just pot pie. It’s popped pie! The soufflé topping is loaded with cheese and potato purée, making this dish one part pot pie, one part cottage pie, and one", "i": ["0.5 recipe Classic Double-Crusted Turkey Pot Pie , Filling only!", "58 g Bread flour", "58 g Butter , unsalted, plus a little extra to rub the ramekins", "9 g Kosher salt", "225 g Milk , whole", "2 g Black pepper , coarsely ground", "5 Egg white(s)", "5 Egg yolk(s)", "200 g Baked potato purée , Yukon Gold or russets", "55 g Gruyère cheese"], "s": ["Prepare filling", "0.5 recipe", "Preheat the oven", "Prepare baking dish or individual ramekins", "Fill buttered dish(es)", "Combine flour, butter, and salt", "Heat milk and cook your roux", "Add egg yolks, potato, and cheese", "Whip the egg whites", "Fold the meringue into the soufflé base", "Top the pie filling", "Bake", "Serve it up", "Other ways to use leftover Thanksgiving turkey"], "tips": ["Make filling and soufflé base in advance!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/popped-pot-pie"}, {"id": 631, "t": "Skinny Whip 2.0 (with Vegan Options)", "c": "Baking", "d": "We’ve heard your whipped cream comments and cries! While our originally Skinny Whip recipe is beloved by many, we’ve collected lots of requests over the years for gelatin- and dairy-free alternatives. We donned our research-and-development caps and created this low-fat, low-sugar alternative that we love even more than the original. This is an easy formula to follow with whatever milk you like—the", "i": ["500 g 2% milk", "50 g Sugar", "1.5 g Kosher salt", "2.5 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F", "0.75 g Xanthan gum", "8 g Vanilla extract"], "s": ["Combine dry ingredients", "Heat milk and vanilla", "Blend to hydrate", "Cool completely", "Dice and shear", "Sieve", "Fill siphon, charge twice, and shake", "Chill for one hour before serving", "Watch me whip"], "tips": ["Tips for making your own nut milk", "More fun with whipping siphons"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/skinny-whip-2-0"}, {"id": 632, "t": "Level Up Your Thanksgiving Stuffing Into Epic, Crispy, Air-Fried Muffins", "c": "Baking", "d": "Whether you call it stuffing or dressing, this Thanksgiving side dish is a staple for a reason—it’s hearty, filling, and flavorful. But the absolute best version strikes a satisfying balance between crispy, crunchy, tender, and moist. Unfortunately, most stuffing recipes end up stuck on one end of that texture spectrum. Our first journey to texture town led us to a waffle iron—stuffing waffles are", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 600 g Store-bought stuffing mix , cooked and cooled 3 Egg(s) , whole", "600 g Store-bought stuffing mix , cooked and cooled 3 Egg(s) , whole", "3 Egg(s) , whole"], "s": ["Prepare stuffing according to package directions", "Preheat the oven to 400 °F / 204 °C", "Make the muffin mix", "Add herbs (optional)", "Scoop stuffing into the preheated muffin pan", "Bake", "Air fry to finish", "Enjoy"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/extra-crispy-stuffin-muffin"}, {"id": 633, "t": "Showstopper Turkey Elixir: Paint Your Way to A Norman Rockwell-Worthy Thanksgiving", "c": "Baking", "d": "When it comes to magazine cover-worthy models, maybe she’s born with it—or maybe it’s Maybelline. (Or, more likely, it’s Photoshop.) When it comes to magazine cover-worthy Thanksgiving turkeys, maybe it’s this elixir—or maybe it’s dish soap. Wait. Hold up. Did we just say dish soap? It’s a common food stylist hack for commercial photoshoots—raw or ever-so-slightly cooked poultry is often brushed w", "i": ["80 g Bourbon whiskey", "14 g Cranberry bitters", "10 g Kitchen Bouquet Browning and Seasoning Sauce", "2 g Liquid soy lecithin , optional but we highly recommend it"], "s": ["Optional: Brine that bird!", "Make the elixir", "“Elixir” what?", "Cook your turkey", "Carve it up", "For an epic Thanksgiving, you’ll also need these"], "tips": ["Each ingredient serves an important purpose", "Want to brush this elixir on a turkey using a different recipe?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/elixir-three-thanksgiving-turkey"}, {"id": 634, "t": "All-Purpose Holiday Seasoning Blend–Two Ways", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "If the holidays were a spice blend, we think they would taste something like this. Warm and comforting, this savory blend hits all the right spice and herbaceous notes to season everything from Thanksgiving turkey and gravy to mashed potatoes, caramelized carrots, and even butter to top off your fresh-baked dinner rolls. A few years ago, we bottled the flavors of Thanksgiving by infusing oil with ", "i": ["300 g Red onion(s) , julienned", "100 g Scallion(s) , sliced thin", "85 g Fresh ginger root , peeled, sliced thin", "50 g Orange(s) , 2 large navel variety, zest only", "15 g Rosemary , fresh, leaves only", "15 g Thyme , fresh, leaves only", "5 g Sage , fresh, leaves only", "8 g Salt , kosher", "25 g Dried garlic flakes", "20 g Dried orange peel", "15 g Black peppercorns", "7 g Cinnamon stick(s)", "5 g Ginger", "8 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Fresh Veggie Version", "Easy Pantry Spice Rack Version", "Jar it up, then use it!", "Pairs well with ..."], "tips": ["If you can’t find dried orange peel"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/thanksgiving-spice-blend"}, {"id": 635, "t": "Two-Hour Roast Turkey", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "In our quest to cook the best ever Thanksgiving turkey, we’ve cooked birds sous vide, rolled up roulades, deep-fried those pieces KFC-style, and even buried it in super-heated salt. Through all of these turkey trials, tribulations, and successes, we’ve stayed away from roasting that big bird whole. We’re staunch believers that the key to getting the best-tasting white meat and the most succulent d", "i": ["1 Turkey", "1 Onion(s) , sweet", "50 g Garlic , about 5 cloves", "7.5 g Kosher salt , 0.5% to the weight of the legs", "7.5 g Baking soda , 0.5% to the weight of the legs", "25 g Brown sugar , light", "250 g Turkey stock", "25 g All-Purpose Holiday Seasoning Blend–Two Ways , 1.6% to the weight of the legs", "200 g Butter , unsalted, for the gravy", "7.5 g Salt , 0.5% to the weight of the legs"], "s": ["An important note on pressure cookers and thermometers", "Butcher the Turkey: Separate the Crown and Hindquarters", "Butcher the Turkey: Separate the Hindquarters into Legs and Thighs", "Prepare and Roast the Turkey Crown", "Preheat the oven", "Sear the crown", "Get ready for roasting", "Into the oven for the first roast", "While the Crown is Roasting, It’s Time to Cook the Legs", "Season the meat", "Cook the onions and garlic", "Sear the legs and seal it up", "Shred the legs", "Make gravy", "Finish the Crown", "Time to enjoy!", "Need more for your Thanksgiving table?"], "tips": ["How to trim the drumettes (an optional upgrade for presentation)"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turkey-perfection-in-only-2-hours"}, {"id": 636, "t": "Add a Kiss of Smoke with the Smoking Gun® Pro", "c": "Baking", "d": "From traditional barbecue to smokerless “smoked” meats perfect for apartment living (check out these ribs, chicken, and brisket), we love the flavor and aroma that smoke can bring to our food. We’ve turned plant scraps into smoked meals, and shown you how to create a quick and inexpensive countertop cold smoker. Another great way to infuse foods with smoky delicious flavor is to use the Smoking Gu", "i": [], "s": ["Pro tips to use the Smoking Gun Pro", "Our favorite ways to enhance foods with smoke", "Before cooking", "Amp up common condiments", "Bring together land and sea", "Add a little savory to sweets", "Get creative with cocktails", "Jazz up store-bought snacks", "What’s your favorite?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/add-a-kiss-of-smoke-with-the-smoking-gun-pro"}, {"id": 637, "t": "Can You Cook a Turkey in a Cauldron Filled With Salt?", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "When it comes to Thanksgiving turkey, we eschew tradition in pursuit of epic perfection. While Norman Rockwell’s aesthetic is the turkey that home cooks aspire to create year after year, we’d argue that bird looks a tad overcooked. We ask you—why roast that big bird whole when you can sous vide breasts and legs separately to perfection, prepare a stunning crown and satisfying roulade, turn it into", "i": [], "s": ["The set up", "The surprises", "The results", "The sides", "Take your Thanksgiving turkey up a notch—reasonably"], "tips": ["The Cowboy Cauldron feeds a crowd"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cauldron-turkey"}, {"id": 638, "t": "Easy Sous Vide Pork Terrine", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We love making homemade charcuterie and building incredible grazing boards and appetizer spreads for dinner parties and holiday gatherings. From chicken liver pâté and turkey rillettes to vegan prosciutto, you don’t need a ton of time to create a savory, satisfying spread to round out your next meat, cheese, and cracker platter. Classic tête de cochon (“head cheese”) is one of our chefs’ favorites", "i": ["2.3 kg Ham hock , skin on, about 3 hocks (raw, unsmoked)", "30 g Black peppercorns", "15 g Yellow mustard seeds , yellow", "3 g Juniper berries", "1.5 g Caraway seeds", "4.5 g Star anise", "7.5 g Chile flakes", "30 g Garlic , cloves peeled", "5.7 g Prague powder #1 , wait to scale until Step 4", "33.8 g Kosher salt , wait to scale until Step 4", "35 g Parsley , leaves, chopped", "30 g Garlic clove(s) , peeled"], "s": ["Bone out the ham hocks", "Make the spice blend", "Finely chop the garlic", "Scale the salts and season the meat", "Preheat Joule or Oven to 167 °F / 75 °C", "Bag or tray it up", "Cook", "Pull and rest", "Prep the terrine mold", "Shred and pack", "Weigh it down and refrigerate", "Remove and slice", "Build your charcuterie board"], "tips": ["Swap those spice blends", "Keep it covered"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/terrine-de-jarret"}, {"id": 639, "t": "Beyond Breading: Create a Crunchy Crust on Fried Foods with Anything from Cheetos to Pretzels", "c": "Baking", "d": "Around here, we’re big fans of fried chicken (and turkey). Crispy, crunchy, savory, and salty—we love it deep-fried, air-fried, stacked up in a sandwich, and spicy Korean-style. While the OG pairing of all-purpose flour and buttermilk is the classic that never disappoints, we couldn’t help but wonder if there were other ways to get that beloved salty crunch. In the throes of mega munchies, who has", "i": [], "s": ["Raid the pantry", "How to swap chips or crackers into your recipe", "Blend it up", "Let’s fry up some chicken!", "First, precook that poultry to perfection", "Whisk up the wet mix", "Dredge it up", "Fry away", "Our results", "What’s in your pantry?", "Dip, dunk, drizzle that chicken", "Put your pantry to work"], "tips": ["Does size matter?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/guide-to-pantry-breading"}, {"id": 640, "t": "In Search of Golden Brown: The Best Way to Make Toast", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "From basic buttered or smeared with mayo and topped with thick slices of heavily salted in-season tomatoes to piled high on the side of that all-day diner-style pancake brekkie and the real reason why millennials apparently can’t afford to purchase their own homes (yeah, looking at you, avocado toast)—toast really isn’t just toast. Whether part of a well-balanced meal or made as a meal entirely on", "i": [], "s": ["Before we get toasted: Dialing in our control slice", "Let’s talk about heat", "The bread you choose makes a difference", "Okay, it’s time to test some toast!", "Comparing fats", "Comparing toasting techniques", "A few of our favorite ways to toast", "Matt’s diner-style delight", "Nick’s cinny whip", "Jason’s chocolate sprinkle snack", "Let’s toast something"], "tips": ["For best results, preheat your toaster", "How to identify hot spots in your oven"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ways-to-toast"}, {"id": 641, "t": "The Secret to Crispy Air-Fried Food: Amazing Results Out of Thin Air", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We all love the crispy and crunchy texture of deep-fried foods, but deep frying—especially at home—leaves a lot to be desired. Once those delish chicken wings or French fries are devoured, there’s a stinky, greasy mess to clean up and a lot of oil to properly discard. (Not to mention, consuming deep fried foods on the reg ain’t exactly good for the ol’ ticker.) Air frying has taken the world by st", "i": [], "s": ["A frying face-off: Air versus oil", "Our top tips, tricks, and best practices for epic air frying", "Preheating is key", "Maximize air circulation", "Space it out", "A little oil goes a long way", "Improve color and texture with a two-stage cook", "Add a sprinkle of magic dust (aka baking powder)", "Now you know, go air fry something!"], "tips": ["Cook frozen foods faster"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/get-the-most-out-of-your-smart-oven-air-fryer"}, {"id": 642, "t": "Air-Fried Crispy Shrimp", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "We may love these crunchy shrimp even more than their classic deep-fried counterparts. The results are nearly identical—a crispy exterior and perfectly cooked and succulent, not rubbery, interior—but this air-fried version is even more flavorful and requires way less fat. The secret here is kataifi, a shredded phyllo dough that’s commonly used in Mediterranean and Middle Eastern pastries. The verm", "i": ["10 Shrimp , (16-20 per pound), heads off", "100 g Butter , unsalted", "20 g Garlic , coarsely chopped", "1 Kataifi , shredded phyllo dough (1 box)", "Sweet chile sauce , for serving , as needed"], "s": ["Prep the shrimp", "Make the garlic butter", "Preheat the air fryer", "Wrap the shrimp", "Cook", "Enjoy!", "Shrimp: small but mighty!"], "tips": ["What’s in a number—decoding the size of your shrimp", "Using a different kind of air fryer?", "Are your shrimp slightly smaller or larger?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-crispy-shrimp"}, {"id": 643, "t": "Fully Loaded Air-Fried Potato Wedges", "c": "Baking", "d": "Give your appetizers the ultimate air-fried upgrade with these fully loaded wedges. They’re the perfect game-day party food, late-night snack, or hangover helper. The air fryer’s super convection and radiant heat are the perfect match for bacon—deliciously, desirably crispy with a slight chew. (Just how we like it.). A lower air-frying temperature ensures the potatoes have time to cook through and", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 Russet potato(es) 8 Bacon , slices - Sour cream, as needed - Cheddar , finely shredded , as needed - Scallion(s) , thinly sliced , as needed - Frank’s RedHot Original Sauce, as needed", "1 Russet potato(es) 8 Bacon , slices - Sour cream, as needed - Cheddar , finely shredded , as needed - Scallion(s) , thinly sliced , as needed - Frank’s RedHot Original Sauce, as needed", "1 Russet potato(es)", "8 Bacon , slices", "Sour cream, as needed", "Cheddar , finely shredded , as needed", "Scallion(s) , thinly sliced , as needed", "Frank’s RedHot Original Sauce, as needed"], "s": ["Slice potato into wedges", "Preheat the air fryer", "Wrap the wedges in bacon", "Transfer potatoes to pan", "Sprinkle on some cheese", "Load ’em up with all the fixin’s"], "tips": ["Using a different kind of air fryer?", "Skip the sprinkle and level up with a cheesy sauce"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fully-loaded-potato-wedges"}, {"id": 644, "t": "Air-Fried Salmon Nuggets", "c": "Baking", "d": "Succulent, with a delicate, crispy crust, these tender salmon nuggets are as flavorful as they are versatile: serve them with a dipping sauce for a delightful appetizer or snack, or pile them high on toasted buns with lettuce, tomato, and mayo for a quick salmon “burger.” The super convection in an air fryer makes it so easy to cook salmon quickly. Make sure to dice your nuggets evenly so no piece", "i": ["400 g Salmon , fillet with skin and pin bones removed", "15 g Baking powder", "5 g Brown sugar", "3 g Kosher salt", "2 g Black pepper , freshly cracked", "2 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce)", "6 g Vegetable oil"], "s": ["Dice the salmon", "Mix up the spice blend", "Season the salmon", "Preheat the air fryer", "Get ready to fry", "“Fry” that fish", "Serve and enjoy!", "A lot more ways to air fry"], "tips": ["Using a different kind of air fryer?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-salmon-nugs"}, {"id": 645, "t": "How to Decode a Bag of Flour", "c": "Baking", "d": "What’s in a bag of flour? There’s more that meets the eye than finely milled wheat—from protein content to enrichments, wheat varieties, and harvesting seasons. These are the factors that differentiate all-purpose from bread flour, and influence your baking results. For as many differences there are between the types of wheat and flours themselves, there are even more variations and discrepancies ", "i": [], "s": ["The power of protein", "What in the world do these words mean?", "Exploring the wide world of wheat flours", "How much protein?", "Fantastical flour", "Put that flour to work"], "tips": ["Can’t find bread flour? Make your own!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-decode-a-bag-of-flour"}, {"id": 646, "t": "Wood-Fired Tomahawk Steak", "c": "Baking", "d": "Move over, pizza. There’s more than one thing you can cook in your high-performance backyard brick oven, including a truly epic tomahawk steak. The DIY brick oven is very efficient, but cooking with it is not an exact science. It’s like a hotrod, and it takes a renegade to drive it. Once you get comfortable controlling the fire to create different oven “functions,” from broiling to baking to low-a", "i": [], "s": ["Get that fire going", "Temper the steak", "Preheat the pan", "Cook that steak", "Add butter and baste", "Let it rest", "Slice and serve", "Fire it up"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/wood-fire-basted-tomahawk-steak"}, {"id": 647, "t": "Wood-Fired Brick Oven Rosemary Focaccia", "c": "Baking", "d": "Can you bake a loaf of bread in your backyard brick oven? You betcha! This wood-fired focaccia may be even better than loaves baked in a traditional home oven where it’s challenging to get enough heat energy in the bottom of the pan to create that delicious, crunchy crust. With an outdoor oven, you can kiss those wall oven worries goodbye—and instead give your focaccia a gentle kiss of smoke and c", "i": [], "s": ["Make the focaccia dough", "Build that oven with an extra layer of bricks", "Fire it up", "Prepare the pan and transfer the dough", "Season the bread and add a few ice cubes", "Bake", "Finish with rosemary (optional)", "Let cool slightly and enjoy!", "What else can this brick oven do?"], "tips": ["Skillet or Dutch oven?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/wood-fire-crusty-rosemary-focaccia"}, {"id": 648, "t": "Gooey Wood-Fired Brick Oven Queso Fundido", "c": "Baking", "d": "Making a rich, stretchy, and gooey queso fundido with a deliciously crispy crust is easy to do in your “hotrod” backyard brick oven. You sauté your toppings of choice right in the oven—Grant keeps it simple with poblano and jalapeño peppers, but you could add onions, mushrooms, or even chorizo—before melting the cheese. Briefly searing right on the embers helps to develop that gorgeous crust, and ", "i": [], "s": ["Pick your cheese", "Get that fire going", "Preheat the pan", "Prep your ingredients", "Precook the fillings", "Add more wood", "Add the cheese and fire away", "That’s fundido!", "Make that outdoor oven work for you"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crispy-crusty-wood-fire-queso-fundido"}, {"id": 649, "t": "Wood-Fired Brick Oven Lobster and Dungeness Crab", "c": "Seafood", "d": "The efficiency of the DIY backyard brick oven makes it a surprisingly ideal vessel to cook crustaceans using a simple two-step process. The heat is high enough to bring water to a boil to first steam that shellfish. Amp up the fire with more wood and you’ve gone from efficient oven to blazin’ broiler, perfect for finishing the split lobster and crab with lots of herbaceous compound butter. save Pr", "i": [], "s": ["Build that oven with an extra layer of bricks", "Fire it up", "Preheat the pan", "Add water and bring to a boil", "Steam the lobster and crab", "Make the compound butter", "Increase the heat", "Clean the lobster and crab", "Broil", "Enjoy!", "There’s more where that wood-fired goodness came from"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/butter-baked-wood-fire-lobster-dungeness-crab"}, {"id": 650, "t": "Wood-Fired Brick Oven Set-It-And-Forget-It Tomato Jam", "c": "Baking", "d": "You’ve spent all day tending a fire and radiant coal bed to heat your “hotrod” backyard brick oven. You’ve fired a few pizzas, and maybe a steak. You’ve baked bread, seared gooey queso fundido to get an ultra-crispy and chewy bottom, and basted a whole lobster and crab. Now the day—and those coals—are winding down. But that heat isn’t going anywhere fast. So, put it to good use. The oven has lots ", "i": [], "s": ["Let that fire burn down to coals", "Get the veggies in the pan", "Roast", "Enjoy!", "Do more with your brick oven"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/wood-fired-juicy-chewy-tomato-jam"}, {"id": 651, "t": "5 Things to Cook in Your High-Performance Backyard Brick Oven That Aren’t Pizza", "c": "Baking", "d": "Since we first showed you how to make your very own high-performance wood-fired backyard brick pizza oven (for less than $50), a lot has happened. We’ve seen so many epic builds, pizzas, and fun from our community—and a lot of great questions, too. (Make sure to check out our new Q&A video in the original pizza oven activity.) We’re back for pizza oven 2.0—but this time, we’re focusing on cooking ", "i": [], "s": ["Don’t have a brick oven? Better build one!", "Fire an epic steak", "Bake beautiful bread", "Make ooey-gooey queso fundido", "Baste lobster and crab", "Turn juicy tomatoes into jammy deliciousness"], "tips": ["Buy a few extra bricks to adjust the deck height as needed"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/high-performance-wood-fired-brick-oven-frenzy"}, {"id": 652, "t": "The Truth About Marinades: Separating Fact from Fiction", "c": "Baking", "d": "The most common marinade refrain is that they make meats more flavorful and more tender—and that the longer you marinate, the better. But the truth is, marinades are not all they’re cracked up to be. Marinating involves submerging meat in a flavorful liquid that usually includes salt, seasonings, an acidic liquid, and sometimes an enzyme or other liquids like wine or beer. In general, marinades ar", "i": [], "s": ["Marinade Myth #1: They Add Flavor", "Marinade Myth #2: They Make Meat More Tender", "Marinade Myth #3: The Longer, The Better", "Marinade Myth #4: You Need to Add a Fat", "Key takeaways", "What are your marinade myths and facts?", "Marinate something special"], "tips": ["Add a little sugar, especially if you are grilling.", "Use mechanical tenderization to achieve the texture you want.", "Are bottled salad dressings a good shortcut?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/marinade-resource-page"}, {"id": 653, "t": "5 Techniques to Perfectly Cook Salmon in Under 30 Minutes", "c": "Baking", "d": "You know what they say about teaching a man to fish. We’re taking it one step further, and showing you five easy ways to cook delicious salmon dinners in less than 30 minutes. When you want something healthy on the table but don’t have a ton of time, use one of these techniques as your guide. Each recipe below includes a video of Grant in his home kitchen, sharing his chef secrets for perfectly co", "i": [], "s": ["Ready? Let’s get cooking!", "A quicker way to sous vide", "Broiled, baby!", "Air-fried, oh yea!", "Pan seared to perfection", "A great way to grill"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salmon-101-techniques"}, {"id": 654, "t": "How to Sous Vide Salmon—Fast!", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This isn’t your low-and-slow sous vide. This is hot and fast rapid sous vide. Unlike traditional sous vide, we’re going to overset the water bath so it’s hotter than our desired internal core temperature. This allows us to reduce the total cooking time by nearly 50 percent! That’s fast. You can use the app to determine your desired salmon doneness and then increase and manually set the temperature", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Salmon fillet(s), as needed", "Salmon fillet(s), as needed"], "s": ["Select your salmon", "Prep", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sous vide", "Pull and flake", "Serve", "Seriously stunning"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/rapid-sous-vide-salmon"}, {"id": 655, "t": "How to Make Air-Fried Salmon Sandwiches", "c": "Baking", "d": "Air frying—aka super or “ultra” convection—makes it incredibly quick and easy to cook salmon. (Seriously, it takes just 4 minutes!) In the video below, Grant shows you how to transform bite-sized nuggets of salmon into succulent and tender morsels that are perfect for piling high on buns, burger-style, loaded up with mayo, lettuce, tomato, onion, and pickles. Making nuggets instead of burger patti", "i": [], "s": ["Fry it up with Grant", "Select your salmon", "Prep & preheat", "Air fry", "Serve"], "tips": ["Wait, isn’t Steelhead a trout?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fry-salmon"}, {"id": 656, "t": "How to Broil Salmon", "c": "Baking", "d": "Who’s afraid of their oven broiler? Not us! With the right cut, a little prep (and, ideally, a super efficient countertop oven), it’s easy to broil salmon to perfection. In less than 30 minutes, you’ll be sitting down to enjoy a quick, easy, and delicious meal with a centerpiece salmon that’s juicy, succulent, and tender with exquisitely crispy skin and just the slightest hint of char. In the vide", "i": [], "s": ["Let Grant show you how", "Select your salmon", "Prep", "Preheat the broiler", "Into the oven", "Serve"], "tips": ["Wait, isn’t Steelhead a trout?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/broiling-salmon"}, {"id": 657, "t": "How to Grill Salmon", "c": "Baking", "d": "It’s easier than you might think to get tender, flaky, succulent salmon on the grill with that delectable kiss of smoky aroma and flavor. Below, Grant shows you his go-to technique for grilling salmon to perfection. Instead of tossing that fillet right on the grates, Grant keeps it on a small rack, which makes it easy to move the salmon from hot to cool zones without falling apart. Keeping the gri", "i": [], "s": ["Grill that fish with Grant!", "Select your salmon", "Prep", "Grill", "Serve"], "tips": ["Wait, isn’t Steelhead a trout?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/easy-grilled-salmon"}, {"id": 658, "t": "Three-Ingredient Plant-Based Ground “Meat”", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Unlocking epic vegan ground “meat” that pleases even the pickiest carnivores requires just three simple ingredients—cauliflower, cremini mushrooms, and walnuts—and one surprising cooking method. Easy can be epic, and epic doesn’t have to be high tech. There are amazing meat replacements on the market these days, but making faux-meat at home usually requires complex or hard-to-find ingredients and ", "i": ["400 g Cauliflower", "160 g Cremini mushrooms", "120 g Walnuts"], "s": ["Slice and dehydrate", "Process the dry ingredients", "Mix it up", "From meatless base to amazing dinner"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/our-epic-hack-for-plant-based-ground-meat"}, {"id": 659, "t": "Plant-Based “Beef” Bolognese", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "While we tend to associate “heartiness” with meatiness, this recipe makes it easy to have a comforting and hearty meal, sans the meat. If you’re on a vegan or vegetarian diet, looking for a delish pasta dish that will satisfy even the most diehard meat-eaters, or simply want to make a meal for Meatless Monday, this recipe checks all the boxes. (Regardless of whether or not you make your own pasta ", "i": ["50 g Fennel bulb , diced", "50 g Red onion(s) , diced", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "50 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "200 g Three-Ingredient Plant-Based Ground “Meat”", "200 g Red wine", "795 g Canned crushed tomatoes , one 28-ounce can", "2 g Fennel seeds", "1 g Chile flakes", "Kosher salt, as needed", "20 g Beef stew seasoning mix", "5 g Zesty Italian dressing mix", "Oregano , fresh , as needed", "Mint , fresh , as needed"], "s": ["Make the “meat” base", "Dice the veggies", "Get toasty", "Add the ground meat mix", "Add red wine and reduce", "Add the tomatoes and seasonings", "Serve it up", "Plant-based but not boring"], "tips": ["Want to make fresh pasta? We gotchu!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/plant-based-beef-bolognese"}, {"id": 660, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Charcoal for Grilling", "c": "Baking", "d": "Cooking over coals is an evocative, almost primal experience. But in this day and age, with so many choices on the market, picking out a bag of charcoal at the store can be a daunting task. Within the two standard categories of charcoal—briquette and lump hardwood—you’ll find many different options, from size and shape to wood type and even infusions. This guide is here to help you find the “right", "i": [], "s": ["Pressed Briquettes $", "Hardwood (aka lump charcoal) $$", "Extruded Briquettes $$$", "Binchotan $$$$", "Geek out"], "tips": ["Get that grill ready", "Make the most of it", "Fire up the hibachi"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/charcoal-more-than-just-burnt-wood"}, {"id": 661, "t": "Chicken Adobo Three Ways", "c": "Baking", "d": "Rich, succulent, flavorful, and tender, Filipino adobo is a classic and comforting dish. Inspired by a friend and former colleague, and ChefSteps old school “family meals,” Nick Gavin wanted to dive into the components that make adobo so special and delicious. This recipe isn’t about finding the best or right way to make adobo. As the saying goes, if it ain’t broke, don’t fix it. Instead, Nick wan", "i": ["400 g Silver Swan Soy Sauce", "320 g Datu Puti Sukang Iloco Native Vinegar", "16 g Black pepper , coarsely ground", "4 g Chile flakes", "8 g Bay leaf , fresh", "40 g Garlic", "4 piece Chicken leg(s) , skin on, drums and thighs separated", "4 piece", "Chicken leg(s) , skin on, drums and thighs separated", "400 ml Coconut milk , optional", "500 g Datu Puti Sarap Asim (clear) Vinegar", "10 g Salt", "60 g Lime juice", "10 g Fresno chile(s) , sliced into thin rings", "40 g Korean green chile , sliced into thin rings", "8 g Fresh ginger root , grated", "4 g Lemongrass , minced", "3 g Curry leaves", "2 g Lime leaves , about three or four", "120 g Water"], "s": ["Select your vinegar", "Make the adobo sauce", "Pick your cooking method", "Dutch oven on the stovetop", "In a pressure cooker", "Serve it up", "Rice is essential", "Level it up with longanisa, hard boiled eggs, and sliced green onions", "In the test kitchen with Nick", "Nick’s special summertime sauce"], "tips": ["Marinating is optional", "Presearing is optional"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-adobo-r-d"}, {"id": 662, "t": "The Ultimate Grilled Veggie Sando", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you've ever been skeptical of a vegetable sandwich, we understand. Between wilty lettuce, watery cucumbers, and underripe everything else, the standard veg sando has a reputation for being underwhelming—to say the least. But it doesn’t have to be that way. With the right bread, toppings, and technique, vegetable sandwiches can be an out-of-this-world experience. Right and ready for meatless Mon", "i": ["Bell pepper(s) , any color , as needed", "Red onion(s), as needed", "Portobello mushrooms, as needed", "Zucchini, as needed", "Tomato(es), as needed", "Eggplant, as needed", "Romaine , or iceberg lettuce , as needed", "Mozzarella, as needed", "Paneer cheese, as needed", "160 g Kewpie mayonnaise , for the lemon mayo", "40 g Dijon mustard , for the lemon mayo", "1 Lemon , for the lemon mayo", "1 Basil , bunch, for the lemon mayo", "45 g Castelvetrano olives , pitted for the tapenade", "15 g Kalamata olives , pitted for the tapenade", "15 g Garlic , about 2 cloves, for the tapenade", "30 g Shallot(s) , about 1 ea, for the tapenade", "35 g Extra-virgin olive oil , for the tapenade", "10 g Sherry vinegar , for the tapenade", "Ciabatta bread, as needed", "35 g Olive oil"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Prep your sauces", "Olive tapenade", "Lemon & basil mayo", "Fire up the grill", "Grill, baby, grill", "Toast yer bread", "Build those sandos", "Dig in"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-veggie-sando"}, {"id": 663, "t": "Grill Ultra-Thin Steaks With Max Flavor and Texture", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "When it comes to big money steak cuts like ribeyes, strips, and tenderloins, we rely on precision cooking with sous vide to protect our investment and achieve perfect doneness. Sous vide and other low-and-slow methods are a great way to transform tough cuts—like chuck—into tender steaks that rival those more expensive options. But there’s a wide world of steak cuts to discover and there are other ", "i": ["2 Skirt steak , about 3 lbs 0.5 Lime(s) 0.5 Orange(s) 2 Garlic clove(s) 0.5 Onion(s) 0.5 Jalapeño(s) - Cumin seeds , ground fine , as needed - Kosher salt, as needed - Rainier Beer , or your favorite lager, cider, wine, soda, or broth , as needed 1 Cilantro , 1 bunch chopped", "0.5 Lime(s)", "0.5 Orange(s)", "2 Garlic clove(s)", "0.5 Onion(s)", "0.5 Jalapeño(s)", "Cumin seeds , ground fine , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Rainier Beer , or your favorite lager, cider, wine, soda, or broth , as needed", "1 Cilantro , 1 bunch chopped", "0.5 Lime(s) 0.5 Orange(s) 2 Garlic clove(s) 0.5 Onion(s) , white 0.5 Jalapeño(s)", "0.5 Orange(s) - Cumin seeds , ground fine , as needed - Kosher salt, as needed - Rainier Beer , or your favorite lager, cider, wine, soda, or broth , as needed 1 Cilantro , 1 bunch chopped"], "s": ["Tools of the tenderizing trade", "It’s tenderizing time", "Make the “marinade”", "Layer on that flavor", "Roll it up", "Fire up the grill", "Get these steaks on the grill already!", "Slice and serve", "Grant and his Grill: The DVD Extras", "On the side"], "tips": ["You are the master of your mandoline—not the other way around", "More marinade inspiration"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tenderize-thin-steaks-before-grilling"}, {"id": 664, "t": "Make These Flavor-Packed Dips, Spreads, and Sauces on the Grill", "c": "Baking", "d": "So, you’re standing at the grill flipping burgers, brats, or chicken legs when you think to yourself—man, I really want something saucy on the side for dipping. With one of these grilled spreads, you can turn this passing thought into a smoky, delicious dip. Grilling vegetables and fruits before chopping or blitzing in a food processor adds extra layers of flavor—from a kiss of smoke to heavily ch", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Fruits or vegetables, as needed - Neutral oil, as needed - Salt and pepper, as needed", "Fruits or vegetables, as needed - Neutral oil, as needed - Salt and pepper, as needed", "Neutral oil, as needed", "Salt and pepper, as needed", "1 kg Eggplant , about 2 large", "200 g Extra-virgin olive oil , for the eggplant, plus more for optional garnish", "15 g Garlic , peeled cloves", "90 g Tahini", "100 g Lemon juice , freshly squeezed (from about 3 lemons)", "13 g Kosher salt", "Parsley , optional, chopped for garnish , as needed", "180 g Scallion(s) , trimmed and cleaned, about 2 bunches", "15 g Any oil , of your choice, for the scallions", "125 g Red miso paste", "50 g Water", "12 g Lime juice", "30 g Rice vinegar , aged", "10 g Brown sugar , like muscovado", "6 g Soy sauce , or tamari", "2 g Black pepper , freshly cracked", "1 Bell pepper(s) , any color", "1 Orange(s) , navel", "50 g Hazelnuts", "4 g Thyme , fresh", "150 g Mustard greens , 1 bunch", "35 g Shallot(s) , minced", "18 g Red chiles , cleaned and diced small, about 2, like Fresno chiles", "35 g Flat-leaf parsley , leaves, about 1 bunch", "80 g Sherry vinegar", "3 g Cumin seeds , ground", "1 g Oregano , dried", "3 Lemons", "3 g White pepper , coarsely ground", "110 g Onion(s) , white, about 2 medium", "70 g Pumpkin seeds", "6 g Lemon peel , from 1 lemon", "60 g Basil , one bunch", "5 g Pink peppercorns", "2 g Allspice", "3 g Star anise", "0.5 Pineapple", "3 g Mint , fresh leaves, chiffonade", "3 g Cilantro , fresh leaves, minced", "15 g Distilled vinegar"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Grill, char, flip", "Mix it up", "Baba Ganoush", "Scallion Miso", "Burnt Orange Romesco", "Mustard Green Chimichurri", "Lemon Pepper Jam", "Pumpkin Seed Pesto", "Pineapple Pepper", "Dip, dunk, spread, glaze", "Let’s get it on—the grill, that is"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-dips-spreads-sauces"}, {"id": 665, "t": "Fagoza", "c": "Baking", "d": "Fagoza is a fully loaded bread loaf that’s one part savory monkey bread and one part focaccia, with a hint of pizza, too. It’s a unique and uncommon recipe—a bread that had been all but forgotten, until now. Chef Matthew Woolen pulled this idea from his time in culinary school and gave it a ChefSteps-level revival. The base dough, traditionally the same as a soft dinner roll, gets a milk bread upg", "i": ["325 g Bread flour , divided", "55 g Water", "135 g Milk , whole (divided)", "13 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "50 g Egg(s) , about 1 large", "5 g Instant dry yeast , dry", "5 g Kosher salt", "40 g Sugar", "50 g Butter , unsalted, room temperature", "500 g Inclusions , your choice, see our favorites and more suggestions below", "30 g Extra-virgin olive oil , for inclusion mixture", "10 g Flake sea salt , for inclusion mixture", "1 g Black pepper , freshly ground for inclusion mixture", "Egg wash , optional , as needed", "20 g Black garlic , smashed", "150 g Swiss cheese , grated", "40 g Green olives , sliced or chopped", "100 g Mushrooms , sliced and cooked", "100 g Bell pepper(s) , roasted and chopped", "15 g Basil , fresh, hand torn", "10 g Flat-leaf parsley , rough chopped", "40 g Scallion(s) , sliced"], "s": ["Gather your goods and equipment", "Make the PGF “water roux”", "Mix the dough, stage 1", "Mix the dough, stage 2", "Bulk ferment", "Prepare the inclusions", "Chop chop", "Pop that chop into the prepped pan", "Proof it up", "Preheat the oven to 350 °F / 177 °C", "Bake that bread", "Prevent a soggy bottom", "Enjoy!"], "tips": ["The power of pre-gelatinized flour (PGF)", "More great flavor combos"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fagoza-the-bread-you-have-been-missing"}, {"id": 666, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Turn the Drippings in Your Sous Vide Bag into a Delicious Jus", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Got juices? Just like the drippings from a delicious oven roast, the liquid that’s left over in your sous vide bag holds incredible flavor. With a little time and effort, you can turn those juices into a delicious jus. We love making pan sauces to capture that flavorful fond (aka tasty brown bits) that’s left in the skillet after searing steaks or chops. This technique is similar, but we first hav", "i": [], "s": ["From liquid to luscious in less than 10 minutes", "Skim off the fat (optional)", "Reduce and caramelize", "Deglaze the pan", "Mount with butter (optional)", "Serve and enjoy!", "How do you jus?"], "tips": ["Strain it (optional)"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bag-sauce"}, {"id": 667, "t": "Bold and Beefy: Transform Tough Chuck into These Tender, Delicious Recipes", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The humble chuck roast is an overlooked fellow often overshadowed by his two polished pals, tenderloin and prime rib. Ridiculously inexpensive and often unfairly packaged as low-quality stew beef, chuck is, in fact, one of the most flavorful cuts on the steer. From a hard working muscle group, chuck is tough and full of fat and connective tissue. That translates into lots of flavor, but also requi", "i": [], "s": ["Where does chuck come from", "Sous vide superstars", "Pressure-cooked to perfection"], "tips": ["Tough versus tender", "A look inside the pressure cooker"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-chuck-recipes"}, {"id": 668, "t": "The Epic Outdoors: Our Coolest Moments of Cooking With Fire", "c": "Baking", "d": "We love an epic cooking challenge, especially if it’s in the great outdoors. It takes a lot to mastermind how to build huge fires and harness that heat to perfectly cook a lot (like, a lot) of meat. These adventures have helped us to get outside—of our office, our kitchen, and our comfort zone—to try new things and show you what we’ve learned. Sure, extreme cooking exploits are incredibly entertai", "i": [], "s": ["Great walls of fire!", "Roastmaster", "Good cookin’ out", "Brick by brick-oven pizza", "Hibachi on a hike"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-epic-outdoors"}, {"id": 669, "t": "Tips & Tricks: How to Make a Hibachi Grill Anywhere", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "The next time you head to the great outdoors—whether a campsite, cave, or your own backyard—give this makeshift hibachi grill a try! Our team loves cooking outdoors over, or next to, an open fire. And whenever Grant heads out on a hike, he challenges himself to devise creative ways to cook out with very minimal equipment. While hiking in the mountains near Santa Fe, New Mexico, Grant set up camp i", "i": [], "s": ["Hibachi? What’s that?", "Collect your rocks", "Build the base", "Build up the sides", "Light your fire", "Prep your skewers", "Grill and enjoy", "Safely and completely extinguish your fire"], "tips": ["Looking for a permanent hibachi grill?", "Practice good fire safety!", "No skewers? No problem!", "How did Grant grill that rice?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/camping-how-to-make-a-hibachi-that-really-grills"}, {"id": 670, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Build an Easy and Inexpensive Portable Cold Smoker", "c": "Baking", "d": "In mere minutes, you can transform two rectangular cake pans, some aluminum foil, and wood chips into a tabletop cold smoker to quickly and easily infuse your favorite foods with fresh wood smoked flavor. Sure, you could invest in dedicated equipment like an outdoor smoker or this cool Smoking Gun. But this inexpensive hack—a method commonly used in professional kitchens—is a great technique to tr", "i": [], "s": ["Set it up outside", "Pick your pans", "Foil it up", "Make a packet for the wood chips", "Assemble the base of the cold smoker", "Fire it up", "Get smoking", "Pull", "Get cooking"], "tips": ["Smoking shellfish", "Pro tip: Place a probe thermometer", "Maximize surface area for max flavor infusion", "Keep it cool"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tip-trick-diy-cold-smoker"}, {"id": 671, "t": "McSalmon Fishwich Deluxe", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The catch o’ the day is in, and it’s slammin’! For epic fishwiches and salmon burgers, we turned to our recipe for the World’s Best Fish Sticks to inspire this salmon patty that’s moist, tender, and flavorful. We didn’t want to simply replicate a boring frozen salmon burger or slap together a patty that technically serves up salmon but doesn’t bring much texture to the table. Salting the patty and", "i": ["700 g Salmon , skinned, boned, and diced", "11 g Salt", "11 g Knox gelatin", "35 g Wondra flour", "200 g Egg(s) , whole, for breading station", "100 g All-purpose flour , for breading station", "100 g Panko breadcrumbs , for breading station", "1 recipe New Bay Seasoning Blend", "Vegetable oil , for deep-frying , as needed"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Make the salmon patty mixture", "Mold that mix", "Let it rest", "Heat sous vide bath", "Cook the giant salmon patty", "Pull, rest, clean, and chill", "Turn one big patty into 6", "Prep your fryer", "Build your breading station", "Fry those fishwiches", "Season with your favorite spice blend", "Build those fishwiches", "You be the judge ..."], "tips": ["Want to add extra seasonings or inclusions?", "Don’t want to fry?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smashed-salmon-burgers"}, {"id": 672, "t": "The Secret to Epic Grilled Chicken? Bake It First!", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Memorial Day may be the official start of summer in the US, but we think grilling is the true herald of our favorite season—and that starts now! Hello shorts weather, barbecues, bonfires, and plenty of popsicles. We missed you. One hallmark of the season is inexpensive, accessible, flavorful chicken legs. But they can be tough to cook—and if you don’t cook them quite right, you’ll end up with seri", "i": ["30 g Molasses", "10 g Wright’s hickory liquid smoke", "5 g Black pepper , optional", "6 Chicken leg(s) , skin on", "5 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Let’s chat grilled chicken", "Mix up that secret sauce", "Preheat your oven", "Sauce those legs and tray ’em up", "Get baked", "Cool the chicken (optional)", "Get grilling", "Sauce it up", "Great sides to grill", "Quick tips for epic grilling"], "tips": ["We love liquid smoke", "Take the chill off"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/magic-grilled-chicken-legs-in-half-the-time"}, {"id": 673, "t": "Mother Clucker! Let’s Cook Some Chicken", "c": "Meat", "d": "The humble chicken offers a little something for everyone: crispy skin, lean white meat, succulent dark meat. It can be prepared as an elegant entrée or casual finger food. From family meals and kiddo faves (hello, dino nuggets), to Super Bowl essentials—what can’t the chicken do? This ubiquitous bird is a staple, from restaurant menus to weeknight meals at home. Wonderfully versatile, it has a bi", "i": [], "s": ["The whole kit and ca-bird-le", "For fans of white meat", "Deeeelicious dark meat", "Fry, fry away", "Greater when grilled", "Wings ‘n’ things", "Stock it up", "Fly the coop with these adventurous ideas", "Tips for tricky chicks"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/epic-chicken-recipe-collection"}, {"id": 674, "t": "How to Go From Fresh Ingredients to Flavorful Soups—Fast", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Ahhh, soup. Comforting and cozy, it’s good for the soul—and any time of year. From simple broths to complex bowls bolstered with vegetables, dumplings, meats, or noodles, there’s a seemingly infinite selection of souper ideas and combinations. Soups are a great way to use up any produce, and it’s easy to make a delicious soup with a few key, quality ingredients. So, whether you have an abundance o", "i": ["Fresh vegetables , your choice (see recipes below for specifics) , as needed", "Stock , or water , as needed", "Fat , or oil of your choice , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Lemon juice , freshly squeezed, optional , as needed", "Black pepper , freshly ground, optional , as needed", "Garnishes , optional , as needed", "360 g Fresh spinach , (about 2 bunches)", "40 g Green onion(s) , sliced into 1/2-inch chunks", "100 g Raw cashews", "1 kg Water", "2 g Nutritional yeast , optional", "450 g Carrot(s) , peeled and grated", "20 g Fresh turmeric root , peeled and thinly sliced", "450 g Golden beet(s) , peeled and sliced into half moons 1/4-inch thick", "Orange juice , (from 1 orange) , as needed", "Orange zest , (from 1 orange) , as needed", "400 g Coconut milk , (from 1 small can)", "80 g Medjool dates , pitted", "25 g Fresh ginger root , peeled and thinly sliced", "100 g Sunflower seed(s)", "400 g Sugar snap peas , fresh, whole", "15 g Mint , fresh leaves", "450 g Cremini mushrooms , thinly sliced", "150 g Onion(s) , thinly sliced", "60 g Celery , stalk, thinly sliced", "20 g Morel mushrooms , dried", "5 g Thyme , fresh", "70 g Walnuts", "450 g Cauliflower , sliced (about 1/2 a large head)", "80 g Golden raisins", "10 g Curry powder , South Indian (Madras) recommended", "160 g Red bell pepper(s) , diced (about 1 pepper)", "500 g Tomato(es) , ripe (blanched or blistered, peeled, and roughly diced)", "12 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce)", "48 g Garlic , roasted, one whole head", "20 g Basil , 1 bunch", "Oregano , dried (or 3 g fresh)", "30 g Any oil , of your choice", "450 g Corn , fresh kernels from about 3 ears, (cobs reserved)", "130 g Yellow bell pepper , diced (about 1 pepper)", "10 g Lemon zest", "120 g Mirin", "500 g Belgian endive , quartered and chopped (about 5 heads)", "100 g White miso paste"], "s": ["Three Easy Steps to Soup Success:", "Prep that produce", "Sauté and/or simmer", "Blend it up!", "The Soup Recipes:", "Spinach 🍃", "Carrot 🥕", "Golden Beet 🟡", "Fresh Pea 🌱", "Mushroom 🍄", "Cauliflower ⚪️", "Spicy Tomato and Pepper 🍅", "Corn 🌽", "Belgian Endive 🥬"], "tips": ["Checking your stock options", "The quickest stock in the world", "The best way to blister & peel tomatoes? Torch ’em!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/flavorful-vibrant-blender-soups"}, {"id": 675, "t": "Our Best Recipes for an Incredible Mother’s Day Brunch", "c": "Baking", "d": "We think breakfast foods might just be the best foods. With that in mind, we’ve compiled our bestest brunch ideas to help you prepare a very memorable Mother’s Day. Whether you’re planning a classic breakfast-in-bed situation, a lovely brunch, or even brinner (that’s breakfast-for-dinner, friends), these recipes are guaranteed crowd-pleasers. But, more importantly, they’re mom pleasers—because mom", "i": [], "s": ["Brunchy basics", "Pancakes or waffles?", "Make an Eggs Benny bar", "Eggs make eggceptional mains", "Fluffy scrambled eggs", "Amazing omelets", "Studly muffins", "Quite carbacious", "Pretty, perfect pastries", "Coffee and cocktails (and coffee cocktails!)", "Bonus! Cook for mom all day long"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/mothers-day-brunch-ideas"}, {"id": 676, "t": "Why Is It So Hard to Keep Guacamole Green?", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Brown, oxidized guacamole is hardly an appetizing sight. There are many methods, and some actual myths, out there about how best to keep your guacamole fresh and green—from keeping the avocado pit or adding lots of lime juice, to more modernist ingredients and techniques, like sodium bisulfate and vacuum sealing. We wanted to find out if one may be better than rest. The culprit responsible for mak", "i": [], "s": ["The tests", "So, what’s happening here?", "Results", "Goes great with guac"], "tips": ["Did you know? Room temp is more flavorful"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/is-it-true-does-the-avocado-pit-keep-guacamole-green"}, {"id": 677, "t": "24 Hours to an Epic Taco Feast—from Scratch", "c": "Other", "d": "Let’s get ready to taco party. In 24 hours (or less), you can have a full taco spread entirely made from scratch—including fresh corn masa tortillas or flour tortillas. Below, we’ve laid out an easy to follow two-day plan to set you up for success. Day 1 is prep and Day 2 is all about finishing touches, firing, and eating! With this roadmap, you’re in the driver’s seat—choose the recipes below tha", "i": ["Lime(s) , fresh, cut into wedges , as needed - Radish , thinly sliced , as needed - Cilantro , fresh leaves and thin stems , as needed - Yellow onion(s) , chopped , as needed - Queso fresco , crumbled , as needed", "Radish , thinly sliced , as needed", "Cilantro , fresh leaves and thin stems , as needed", "Yellow onion(s) , chopped , as needed", "Queso fresco , crumbled , as needed"], "s": ["Day 1: Prep it and forget it", "Nixtamalize your corn for fresh-made masa", "Get this easy overnight carnitas in the oven", "Day 2: Shaping and set up", "Make the tortilla dough", "Make more fillings!", "Make sauces and sides", "Shape and sear the tortillas", "Prep the mise en place", "End of Day 2: Dig in!"], "tips": ["Want more than one meat? Get these prepped and ready", "Make it a masa party with tamales and pupusas", "Looking for a paleo or keto taco shell?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/epic-taco-party-from-scratch"}, {"id": 678, "t": "Leveled-Up Flour Tortillas", "c": "Baking", "d": "What’s the secret to an epic scratch-made flour tortilla? Corn! Not just any old corn, though. We’re talking about hominy—white corn that’s gone through the nixtamalization process. To make a corn tortilla from scratch you first have to soak dried corn kernels in a cal (aka calcium hydroxide) solution. This takes up to 24 hours. But cheap canned hominy has already gone through the process, which s", "i": ["822 g Hominy , (Canned liquid + corn)", "20 g Chicken bouillon powder , optional", "16 g Kosher salt , optional", "700 g All-purpose flour", "120 g Butter , unsalted, melted", "8 g Baking powder"], "s": ["Blend it up", "Mix it up", "Add the flour and take it to the bench", "Prep your press", "Preheat your pan", "Portion, form, and press", "Sear ’em up", "Storing and serving", "Got extra dough kicking around?", "Let’s talk about tacos", "Masa magic"], "tips": ["What to do if your hominy is par-cooked", "Selecting fats and butter alternatives", "No press? No prob!", "Tortilla shaping tips"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/flour-corn-hybrid-tortilla"}, {"id": 679, "t": "From Corn Kernels to Fresh Masa", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Unlike a really great pasta dough—which you can whip up with some flour and water (and maybe an egg yolk or two)—you cannot combine cornmeal and water and expect an amazing tortilla. There’s nothing quite like the aroma and flavor of a freshly made tortilla. Once you’ve had one, it’s hard to go back to those plastic-wrapped store-bought stacks. The good news is, it’s super easy to make fresh masa ", "i": ["350 g Dried corn (kernels)", "3.5 g Calcium hydroxide", "800 g Water , plus more, as needed", "Masa harina, as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Parcook the corn kernels", "Soak overnight", "Rinse the nixtamal", "Weigh the nixtamal", "Blend it up", "Thicken with store-bought masa harina", "Your masa is ready to par-tay!", "Shape it up", "How we landed on this blender method", "A full taco feast"], "tips": ["What is calcium hydroxide? The key to nixtamalization", "Have a Joule? Skip the stove and sous vide that corn!", "Making a taco feast from scratch? Get your meaty main going!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/make-your-own-fresh-masa-with-just-a-blender"}, {"id": 680, "t": "Masa Magic: What We Learned in Pursuit of the Ultimate Tortilla", "c": "Baking", "d": "Dive in to our fresh masa research and development—from sourcing corn and the nitty-gritty details of nixtamalization, to our trial notes on cooking, hydration, and pressing tortillas. This page explores things we tested and the lessons learned over many, many months of making masa from scratch. Our trials led us to develop the fresh masa recipe made using readily accessible kitchen equipment and ", "i": [], "s": ["The magic of nixtamalization", "The type of corn does—and does not—matter", "Different ways to precook the kernels"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-we-learned-while-pursuing-the-easiest-from-scratch-masa"}, {"id": 681, "t": "Homemade Corn Tortillas", "c": "Baking", "d": "So, you’ve made fresh masa dough. Now what? Transform that magical masa into the tastiest tortillas for tacos or burritos! The world of tortillas is wide and vast. We personally prefer to eat a bunch of tacos—different fillings, different salsas, different flavors. So we don’t fill up too fast (and can therefore eat even more tacos), we like to make smaller tortillas that are about 4.5 to 5 inches", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 recipe From Corn Kernels to Fresh Masa", "1 recipe From Corn Kernels to Fresh Masa"], "s": ["Tortilla shaping overview", "Portion the dough and roll it into balls", "Press ’em", "Get that pan rippin’ hot", "Cook", "Let ’em rest and enjoy!"], "tips": ["A note on burrito-sized tortillas", "If you don’t have a tortilla press", "Skillet size matters", "No puff?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-shape-your-homemade-masa-tortillas"}, {"id": 682, "t": "Tamales", "c": "Baking", "d": "Like tortillas, the style of tamales varies depending on geography. We like a version that combines the techniques found in both northern and southern Mexico. In northern and central Mexico, tamales are most commonly made using dried masa flour, stock (or water), and lard or butter. A leavening agent, like baking soda, is sometimes also included to lighten the dough. This is the style of tamale mo", "i": ["Dried corn husks , 1 package , as needed", "200 g Fat , such as lard, butter, or palm oil (1 part fat to 5 parts masa)", "5 g Kosher salt", "5 g Baking soda , (0.5% to the total weight of the masa), optional", "1 recipe From Corn Kernels to Fresh Masa", "Filling of choice, as needed"], "s": ["Tamale shaping overview", "Make the masa dough", "Soak the corn husks", "Pick your fat and whip it up", "Make the tamale dough", "Prep your fillings", "Shape and fill the tamales", "Steam the tamales", "Let them rest, and enjoy!"], "tips": ["Infuse your fat with extra meaty flavor (optional)", "Why add leavening?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-shape-your-homemade-masa-tamales"}, {"id": 683, "t": "Pupusas", "c": "Baking", "d": "From Honduras and El Salvador, pupusas are round, filled masa pockets cooked up on a griddle. They’re one of our favorite snacks. Using fresh masa dough, you can fill pupusas with refried beans, cheese, or a mix of both. Shaping these takes a little practice (believe us—we had some not-so-pretty results at the start). Check out the video and steps below for guidance. Once you really get the hang o", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 recipe From Corn Kernels to Fresh Masa - Filling of choice, as needed", "1 recipe From Corn Kernels to Fresh Masa - Filling of choice, as needed", "1 recipe From Corn Kernels to Fresh Masa", "Filling of choice, as needed"], "s": ["Pupusa shaping overview", "Make the masa dough", "Prepare fillings", "Portion the masa dough and fillings", "Shape the pupusas", "Preheat your skillet or griddle", "Cook ’em up", "Enjoy!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-shape-your-homemade-masa-pupusas"}, {"id": 684, "t": "Overnight Oven-Baked Carnitas", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Bathe a pork shoulder in a delicious marinade, tuck it into a Dutch oven, and put it to bed in a low temperature oven overnight. In the morning, you’ll be greeted with the most delicious fuss-free meat that’s ready to be shredded, crisped up, and stuffed into fresh tortillas. Over the years, we've put the ChefSteps spin on a few different styles of carnitas. There's the fully loaded fusion kung pa", "i": ["1 Pork shoulder , (anywhere from 1kg to 3kg)", "400 g Onion , (about 2 large)", "25 g Garlic , peeled (about 5 cloves)", "2 Serrano pepper", "50 g Poblano pepper(s) , seeded (about 2)", "160 g Lime , fresh, peeled and sliced (about 2)", "100 g Cilantro , 1 bunch", "10 g Kosher salt", "4 g Cumin seeds , ground"], "s": ["Preheat the oven", "Roast the veggies", "Blend the marinade", "Slather the pork", "Toss it in the oven and go to bed", "The next day: a delicious wake-up call", "Get shredded", "Get crispy with it", "Who’s ready to taco party?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/epic-over-night-oven-carnitas"}, {"id": 685, "t": "Hearty Greens Wellington", "c": "Baking", "d": "A Wellington? On a weeknight?! Oh, heck yea! We’re big fans of beef Wellingtons around here—we’ve got our easy and delicious “dough boy” version and this ultimate upgrade (which includes a beautiful butternut option for our vegetarian friends). They’re rich, indulgent, time-consuming, and totally worth it. But we wanted to find a way to lighten it up—in terms of both prep and cook time, and the ea", "i": [], "s": ["Pick and prep your protein", "Beef tenderloin", "Tenderloin Steak, Silver Skin Off See the beef", "See the beef", "Pork loin", "Lamb loin", "Firm fish fillet", "Pick and prep those gorgeous greens", "Pick your flavors", "Beef flavor pairings", "Pork flavor pairings", "Lamb flavor pairings", "Fish flavor pairings", "Layer on the flavor", "Wrap and roll", "Keep those greens in place with a quick truss", "Roast", "Finishing sear", "Slice and serve", "Suggested sides"], "tips": ["Can’t find a center cut? Purchase a whole tenderloin & butcher it yourself!", "What is tender meat?", "Need flavor inspiration? Check out the ChefSteps spice pantry", "Finding your desired doneness", "Tips to get that grill going"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hearty-greens-wellington"}, {"id": 686, "t": "Naturally Colored Rainbow Rice", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "It’s time to take rice from regular to remarkable. We’re inviting Roy G. Biv to dinner and showing you how to cook with color. Whether you want to devise an entire meal inspired by the color wheel or just jazz up your next batch of rice, these colorful ideas will add pep—and a pop of flavor—to your plate. Unlike the art you made as a kid, you can’t hang this one up on the fridge. But, if you snap ", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 454 g Vegetable juice , homemade or store-bought - Calrose white rice, as needed - Kosher salt, as needed", "454 g Vegetable juice , homemade or store-bought - Calrose white rice, as needed - Kosher salt, as needed", "Calrose white rice, as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "6 Red bell pepper(s) , seeded 1 Beet(s) , small, red 2 Garlic clove(s) , peeled 2 Fresno chile(s) , seeded", "1 Beet(s) , small, red", "2 Garlic clove(s) , peeled", "2 Fresno chile(s) , seeded", "6 Carrot(s) , peeled, large 57 g Fresh ginger root , peeled 1 Fresh turmeric root , small thumb-sized nub, peeled", "57 g Fresh ginger root , peeled", "1 Fresh turmeric root , small thumb-sized nub, peeled", "2 Onion(s) , small, white", "1 Cucumber(s) , English 1 Cilantro , fresh bunch 1 Jalapeño(s) , seeded 1 Poblano pepper(s) , seeded 3 Tomatillos , husks removed", "1 Cilantro , fresh bunch", "1 Jalapeño(s) , seeded", "1 Poblano pepper(s) , seeded", "3 Tomatillos , husks removed", "454 g Coconut water , unflavored", "2 g Dried butterfly pea flowers", "1 Apple(s) , Fuji, skin-on, core removed"], "s": ["The ChefSteps Rainbow Rice Color Guide", "Red Rice", "Orange Rice", "Yellow Rice", "Green Rice", "Blue-Indigo Rice", "Magenta Rice", "Rice is nice"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/naturally-colored-rainbow-rice"}, {"id": 687, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Use Leftover Juice Pulp to Tie Dye Tee Shirts", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "These days, it seems like you can’t scroll the ’Gram without seeing someone wearing something that’s tie-dyed. With the recent resurgence, we realized it was past time to revive one of our favorite childhood summer camp pastimes. We love a vibrant, flavorful fruit-and-vegetable juice, but we don’t love leaving that pretty pulp in the compost pile. Enter: juice-pulp tie-dye. This is a fun and easy ", "i": [], "s": ["Mordant", "Make your juices and reserve the pulp", "Discard soy milk and rinse", "Time to tie-dye!", "Unwrap your bundle and dry in the sun", "It’s a juicy world"], "tips": ["Need juice inspiration? Here are a few of our favorite blends!", "Speed it up with steam", "Tips for laundering pulp-dyed shirts"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-tie-dye-with-juice-pulp"}, {"id": 688, "t": "A Carrot Walks Into a Bar: Unlocking the Future of Lemon Bars with Vegetable Juice", "c": "Baking", "d": "When you think of a tart and zesty silky-smooth custard set upon a tender cookie-like crumb, what do you picture? Lemon bars, right? A classic, they’re like edible sunshine. But we wondered if it was possible to create a similarly enjoyable eating experience with different flavors and colors. It turns out, the answer is yes! We’re raising the bar and unlocking the future of lemon squares with a ju", "i": ["168 g Butter , (unsalted) room temperature", "523 g Sugar , (granulated) divided", "250 g Large egg(s) , divided, room temperature (about 5 eggs)", "353 g Pastry flour , divided", "6 g Salt , kosher, divided", "350 g Carrot(s) , peeled", "15 g Fresh ginger root , peeled", "8 g Fresh turmeric root , peeled (optional)", "1 g Orange zest , from 1 orange", "3 g Malic acid , (can substitute citric acid)"], "s": ["Gather your goodies", "Make the dough for crust", "Wrap and chill the dough", "Roll it out and chill again", "Preheat the oven", "Bake the crust", "Disperse dry ingredients for the filling", "Juice those roots!", "Combine the wet ingredients", "Prepare the filling", "Fill the crust", "Bake those bars", "Cool", "Portion and garnish", "In juice we trust"], "tips": ["Want to mix up those juice ratios?", "The importance of letting the filling rest"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/carrot-ginger-juice-bars"}, {"id": 689, "t": "A Reuben-esque Smashed Patty Melt", "c": "Baking", "d": "Perfect for St. Patrick’s Day (or maybe the day after, if you’re nursing a heckuva hangover), this smash-burger-patty-melt mashup is a gosh darn gastronomic delight with a punch of corned beef flavor and the satisfying texture of a smash burger. The trick to smash burgers is an enriched patty, the right lean-to-fat ratio, and a screaming hot cooking surface. A higher percentage of fat creates a su", "i": ["912 g Ground beef , 20-30% fat", "30 g Egg yolk(s) , 1 yolk per pound of ground beef", "9 g Salt , kosher, 1%", "14 g Knox gelatin", "54 g Corned Beef Spice Blend , 6%", "90 g Ketchup", "150 g Japanese (Kewpie-Style) Mayo", "45 g Dill pickles", "15 g Horseradish , prepared"], "s": ["Gather your goodies and prep your components", "Bulk up that beef", "Creaming and forming", "Get that griddle ready", "The secrets to a perfect smash patty", "Sear and flip", "Put it all together", "On the side"], "tips": ["Quick and easy Thousand Island Dressing", "Make the most of that store-bought ground beef", "Level up: Grind your own beef", "More on the creaming technique", "Ultimate indoor hack"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/reuben-style-patty-melt"}, {"id": 690, "t": "Corned Beef Spice Blend", "c": "Baking", "d": "We all agree that corned beef—whether chopped up with potatoes in a hash, piled high on rye as a Reuben sandwich, or cooked up with cabbage—is a quintessential comfort food. Fragrant, hearty, intensely savory, and delicious—we wanted to capture those sweet, sour, spicy, and meaty flavors of this deli counter favorite, and concentrate them into an easy-to-use and versatile spice blend. Now you can ", "i": ["20 g Black peppercorns", "20 g Yellow mustard seeds", "34 g Coriander seeds", "8 g Dill seeds", "4 g Star anise", "2 g Mace blades", "2 g Cloves", "2 g Chile flakes"], "s": ["Measure and mix", "Process according to your preferred application", "Put this blend to work!", "Spice up your life"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/corned-beef-spice-blend"}, {"id": 691, "t": "Light and Pillowy Marbled Rye Milk Bread", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Soft and pillowy, this Marbled Rye Milk Bread is a real wonder thanks to the tangzhong method, which locks in moisture and produces a loaf that’s super tender and fluffy. When bread bakes, water content escapes and overall hydration is reduced. The tangzhong method—also called pre-gelatinized starch (PGF)—involves making a “water roux” from a cooked slurry of flour, water, and milk. By hydrating t", "i": ["20 g Mochiko sweet rice flour", "55 g Water", "135 g Milk , whole, divided", "13 g Nonfat dry milk powder", "50 g Large egg(s) , (about 1 egg)", "5 g Instant dry yeast", "225 g Bread flour , unbleached", "90 g Rye flour , divided", "40 g Sugar , granulated", "5 g Salt , kosher", "50 g Butter , unsalted", "5 g Caraway seeds , optional", "20 g Molasses", "6 g Dutch-process cocoa powder (Brute)"], "s": ["Gather your goods and equipment", "Make the PGF water roux", "Mix the dough, stage 1", "Mix the dough, stage 2", "Split the dough", "Bulk ferment", "It’s marble time", "Pan it up", "Proof the loaf", "Preheat the oven", "Bake for 35 to 45 minutes", "Cool, slice, and serve"], "tips": ["If you don’t have a Pullman loaf pan", "If you don’t have glutinous (sweet) rice flour", "Tangzhong is the key to unlocking amazing texture and shelf stability.", "If you don’t want to marble"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/marbled-rye-milk-bread"}, {"id": 692, "t": "The Yeti Brownie: Elusive, Magical, White as Snow", "c": "Baking", "d": "In the quest to create the ultimate recipe, we baked a bona fide mountain of brownies. And when our brownie mountaineers reached the summit of that experiment, they discovered a new brownie experience beyond their wildest imaginations. The culmination of our quest—the Ultimate Rich As F*¢k Brownie recipe—takes brownies to the flavor and texture extreme. The experience made the chefs wonder—could w", "i": ["225 g Bread flour", "8 g Salt , kosher", "20 g Titanium dioxide , optional", "300 g White chocolate", "100 g Butter , unsalted", "2 g Vanilla bean seed , from 2 beans, optional", "150 g Egg(s) , whole", "300 g Sugar", "150 g Water", "Confectioners’ sugar , for garnish, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare to make your snow monster snack", "Preheat the oven", "Sift together dry ingredients", "Melt the chocolate and butter", "Make the sugar syrup", "Start whipping the eggs when the sugar syrup reaches 235 °F / 113 °C", "Combine the sugar syrup and eggs", "Whip the mixture for 10 minutes", "Pour in the melted chocolate", "Add in the dry ingredients", "Batter up", "It’s baking time", "Cool, cool, cool", "Dust with powdered sugar and devour"], "tips": ["Make these brownies gluten- and grain-free", "Get a brighter white with titanium dioxide", "Bulk it up (optional)"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/yeti-brownies-far-from-abominable"}, {"id": 693, "t": "The Easiest Way to Make Milk Chocolate Bars at Home", "c": "Baking", "d": "Rejoice, you dreamer of dreams! It’s now possible to make your wildest Willy Wonka chocolate fantasies a reality—and you don’t need any special equipment, a river of chocolate, or an industrial extractor pipe (this is especially good news if you’re Augustus Gloop). After developing our artisanal dark chocolate bar, visions of milk chocolate still danced in our heads. But unlike that recipe, in whi", "i": ["75 g Meridian Kokoa Kamili cocoa powder", "175 g Meridian Camino Verde cocoa butter", "150 g Powdered sugar", "100 g Powdered milk , whole"], "s": ["Pre-grind the milk powder", "Sift the dry ingredients", "Melt the cocoa butter", "Blend it up", "It’s tempering time", "Cast into molds", "Let that chocolate cool"], "tips": ["An easy way to clean your spice grinder", "Tempering is temperamental", "When to skip tempering"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/make-milk-chocolate-at-home"}, {"id": 694, "t": "The Easiest Way to Make Creamy White Chocolate at Home", "c": "Baking", "d": "White chocolate is a wonder. Intensely creamy with a different mouthfeel than dark chocolate (due to the higher percentage of cocoa fat), mass-produced white chocolate is also often overwhelmingly sweet. Following the successful development of our artisanal dark chocolate bar, we wondered if we could make an easy at-home version of white chocolate with a balanced flavor that’s not cloying. Unlike ", "i": ["175 g Meridian Camino Verde cocoa butter", "152 g Powdered milk , whole", "152 g Powdered sugar", "4 g Vanilla bean , chopped fine"], "s": ["Pre-grind the milk powder", "Sift the dry ingredients", "Melt the cocoa butter", "Blend it up", "It’s tempering time", "Cast into molds", "Let the chocolate cool"], "tips": ["An easy way to clean your spice grinder", "Tempering is temperamental"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/make-white-chocolate-at-home"}, {"id": 695, "t": "The Ultimate Rich as F*¢K Brownie", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is one bold, beguiling brownie. Swirled with dulce de leche and topped with a sprinkle of sparkling finishing salt, it’s ultra-decadent with nuanced savory notes. Perfectly crisp around the edges, the crackly top is shiny and glassy and gives way to a dense and fudgy interior that’s loaded with chocolate. Our quest to develop the ultimate brownie started with a deep dive into ten popular brow", "i": ["77 g Unsweetened chocolate", "128 g 70% dark chocolate", "261 g Butter , unsalted", "212 g Large egg(s) , about 4", "671 g Sugar", "100 g White miso paste , optional", "3 g Salt , kosher", "9 g Vanilla extract", "170 g Bread flour", "47 g Dutch-process cocoa powder", "1 recipe So Simple Sous Vide Dulce de Leche , optional, cooked for 4 hours", "200 g 36% milk chocolate , chunks or pistoles, optional", "250 g Water"], "s": ["Prep your brownie building blocks", "Preheat the oven", "Sift together the dry ingredients", "Melt the chocolate and butter", "Make the sugar syrup", "Start whipping the eggs", "Combine the sugar syrup and eggs", "Whip the mixture for 15 minutes", "Drizzle in the melted chocolate and season it up!", "Add the dry ingredients", "Batter up!", "Bake that brownie", "Cool, slice, and serve ’em up", "It’s a brownie bonanza"], "tips": ["Make these brownies gluten- and grain-free"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-chocolate-caramel-brownie"}, {"id": 696, "t": "The Best Brownies Out There: A Parametric Analysis", "c": "Baking", "d": "What makes a brownie, a brownie? The combination of chocolate, flour, sugar, eggs, and some kind of fat seems so simple, but is actually incredibly complex. From fluffy and cake-like to dense and fudgy, the brownie universe is nearly boundless. To uncover the mysteries of scratch-made brownies, we scoured the internet and cookbooks, and baked batch after batch of the most popular recipes from thes", "i": [], "s": ["You know we love a good infographic", "Let’s take a closer look at the brownies we baked", "Matthew Woolen", "Michelle Lopez, Weeknight Baking", "Johnny Iuzzini, Sugar Rush", "Stella Parks, BraveTart: Iconic American Desserts", "Hershey’s", "Wayne Gisslen, Professional Baking", "Martha Stewart", "Bo Friberg, The Professional Pastry Chef: Fundamentals of Baking and Pastry", "Betty Crocker", "Alton Brown", "Calculating and testing the average", "The brownie quest continues ...", "Our “ultimate average” inspiration"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-best-brownies-parametric-recipe"}, {"id": 697, "t": "The Brownie Building Blocks: From Boxed Mix to Epic and Ultimate", "c": "Baking", "d": "Welcome to the ChefSteps Build-a-Brownie Workshop! Everyone has a particular style of brownie that they prefer—from fluffy to fudgy; with crispy edges or soft throughout; a top that’s shiny, crackly, or crunchy; loaded with nuts or chocolate chips; swirled with cream cheese, or peanut butter, or tahini. The options are nearly limitless. Now the brownie of your dreams is within reach. This page exp", "i": [], "s": ["The brownie texture spectrum", "How to manipulate flavor and texture with ingredients", "How to manipulate flavor and texture with techniques", "The flavor factor", "Bulk up that brownie", "The pan you choose makes a difference", "Baking times and temperatures", "Continuing the brownie bonanza"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/brownie-building-blocks-ingredients-textures"}, {"id": 698, "t": "How to Make Artisanal Chocolate At Home — No Special Equipment Required", "c": "Baking", "d": "From s’mores-essential Hershey’s chocolate to extra-rich and indulgent artisanal bars, there are few things in life better than well-made chocolate. There are some sizeable barriers to making chocolate from scratch at home. Professional chocolatiers use a conche (and other high-end specialty equipment) to transform roasted cacao nibs into smooth chocolate. While there are conches available for at-", "i": ["225 g Meridian Camino Verde cocoa butter", "200 g Powdered sugar", "135 g Meridian Kokoa Kamili cocoa powder , single origin, natural (not Dutch-processed)"], "s": ["Whisk and sift the powders", "Melt the cocoa butter", "Add the powders in stages", "Time to temper", "Cast into molds", "Let it cool, let it cool", "Snap off a piece of that chocolate bar"], "tips": ["Not all cocoa powders are created equal", "Tempering is temperamental", "What to do if you don’t have molds"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/from-bean-to-bar-understanding-chocolate"}, {"id": 699, "t": "ChefSteps and the Chocolate Factory: Our Favorite Decadent Dishes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Come with us, and we trust, you’ll find incredible chocolate inspiration. We hope you read that to the tune of “Pure Imagination” by Gene Wilder! Chocolate is an amazing creation. It can be a liquid, a thick-but-flowing syrup, and a soft or firm solid—from a molten, melty chip in the perfect cookie to a shiny, snappy bar. From beverages to brownies, candy, cookies, cakes, and even savory dishes, t", "i": [], "s": ["Make your own chocolate at home", "Brownies and cakes, baby!", "Cocoa butter bonanza", "C is for cookies and candy", "Pot de crème, custard, and pudding", "Ultra decadent desserts", "Fantastic frozen treats", "Make modernist chocolate", "Stunning savory chocolate dishes"], "tips": ["The scientific secrets to really good ganache"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-chocolate-hub"}, {"id": 700, "t": "Cracking the Egg: Understanding This Incredible Ingredient", "c": "Baking", "d": "What’s in an egg? And how is this humble ingredient so versatile and valuable in the kitchen? An egg appears so simple, but is actually a complex network of protein, fats, vitamins, minerals, and water. On their own, eggs are delicious, convenient and pragmatic—they can be prepared and enjoyed in so many different ways. But look beyond those classic preparations and you’ll see that the egg touches", "i": [], "s": ["What’s In An Egg", "From the chicken...", "...to the egg", "Detour! Let’s look at other kinds of eggs", "Not All Eggs Are Created Equal", "Fresh is best", "Egg grades and carton labeling", "Pasteurization", "Eggs are the Key to Unlocking These Textures", "Emulsifications", "Eggstra, Eggstra, Read All About It", "Crack Into It"], "tips": ["Peeling fresh eggs", "An egg and a toque", "How temperature affects yolks and whites differently", "Eggs in cakes: foams and emulsions working together"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cracking-the-egg-resource"}, {"id": 701, "t": "Help Us Create the Ultimate Brownie", "c": "Baking", "d": "Rich, chocolatey, and oh-so-delicious, brownies hold a special place in our hearts. Whether they were the first bar you baked (back when you were a Brownie), or something you love to keep in the pantry and whip up on a whim, we want to hear how you feel about brownies. What are your favorite brownie features? Do you like them rich and fudgy or light and cake-like? Prefer boxed mixes or made-from-s", "i": [], "s": ["Update: We did it. Thank you for your help."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/help-us-create-the-ultimate-brownie"}, {"id": 702, "t": "Traditional French Omelette", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "The French know how to turn three eggs, butter, and chives into something ethereal. The French omelette is 10% ingredients and 90% technique—a beautiful light yellow exterior and just cooked interior that’s silky and custard-like. Today’s gold standard for a French omelette is Jacques Pépin’s version. Using very little ingredients (his only addition is minced fresh chives), this omelette is truly ", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 3 Large egg(s) 10 g Butter , unsalted - Salt , kosher , as needed - Chives , fresh, minced, for inside the omelette and to garnish , as needed", "3 Large egg(s) 10 g Butter , unsalted - Salt , kosher , as needed - Chives , fresh, minced, for inside the omelette and to garnish , as needed", "3 Large egg(s)", "Large egg(s)", "10 g Butter , unsalted", "Salt , kosher , as needed", "Chives , fresh, minced, for inside the omelette and to garnish , as needed", "3 Large egg(s) - Salt , kosher , as needed - Chives , fresh, minced , as needed"], "s": ["Watch this technique in action first", "Whisk those eggs", "Do the omelette dance", "Our secrets to omelet(te) success"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/traditional-french-omelette"}, {"id": 703, "t": "Tornado Omelet", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Give your morning omelet an eggsquisite upgrade with this twirling technique. As a popular street food in Korea, the tornado omelet is traditionally served draped over a mound of fried rice, which accentuates the spiral shape. Here we’re concentrating on the technique to help you achieve that perfect spiral. Serve your omelet over rice, on top of avocado toast, or even in place of a poached egg on", "i": ["450 g Large egg(s) , about 9", "17 g Cornstarch", "33 g Water", "3 g Salt , kosher", "Clarified butter , about 5g per omelet , as needed", "Canola oil , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Key steps for a perfect swirl", "Get crackin’", "It’s tornado time", "Serve it up", "Our secrets to omelet success"], "tips": ["Temper the batter if you chilled it overnight", "Why clarified butter?", "Studio Pass bonus video: A close-up of the tornado technique"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tornado-omelet-technique"}, {"id": 704, "t": "Potatoes Meet Eggs in this Spanish-Style Omelet (aka Tortilla Española)", "c": "Baking", "d": "This pillowy omelet is filled with tender confit potatoes and onions. Similar to an Italian frittata, this Spanish egg dish is cooked entirely on the stove (instead of finishing in the oven or under the broiler). Hearty and filling, the Spanish tortilla can be enjoyed any time of day. Often served as a tapas dish and eaten at room temperature, this tortilla is perfect for breakfast, lunch, brunch,", "i": ["8 Large egg(s) , whole", "Large egg(s) , whole", "8 g Kosher salt , divided", "Black pepper, as needed", "200 g Russet potato(es) , about 1/2 potato", "100 g Sweet onion(s) , optional, about 1/2 an onion", "75 g Extra-virgin olive oil"], "s": ["Watch this technique in action first", "Tortilla tips", "Get crackin’", "Cook the filling", "It’s tortilla time", "Serve it up", "Our secrets to omelet success"], "tips": ["Tortilla versus frittata", "Just for fun—fluff it up!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spanish-tortilla-omelet"}, {"id": 705, "t": "The Modernist Method for an Epic Omelet That’s Perfect Every Time", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The ideal French omelet has two parts: a smooth exterior untouched by the Maillard reaction, and a creamy interior with delicate, silken curds that dance on the palate. By focusing on preparing each aspect of the omelet separately, this modernist method yields reliable, tender, and flawless results. Inspired by the “striped” mushroom omelet technique and recipe included in volume five of Modernist", "i": ["420 g Large egg(s) , about 8, for the exterior omelet", "90 g Heavy cream , for the exterior omelet", "Salt , kosher , as needed", "25 g Butter , unsalted at room temp, for interior scramble", "Herbs , fresh for garnish (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Watch this technique in action first", "Make the exterior omelet “blanket”", "Heat sous vide bath", "Get those creamy interior curds on lock", "Bake that “blanket”", "Time to build a beautiful modernist omelet"], "tips": ["Jazz it up and make it your own!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/modernist-omelet-technique"}, {"id": 706, "t": "Shio Koji-Cured Egg Yolks", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "We’d like to introduce you to a new kind of cured egg yolk. Tender custardy, they really knock the socks off traditional boring and rigid salt-cured yolks. Salt-cured yolks are commonly grated over pasta to add richness and umami. But Parmesan cheese accomplishes the same thing. (And, it tastes better and requires way less effort.) Instead of overwhelming saltiness, we wanted a cured yolk that ret", "i": ["300 g Liquid shio koji", "12 Egg yolk(s)", "5 g Thai chile(s) , sliced thin", "15 g Garlic , cloves (grated using a microplane)", "20 g Cilantro , stems from 1 bunch, roughly chopped", "10 g Fresh ginger root , grated using a microplane", "20 g Fish sauce", "50 g Mirin", "30 g Fresh lime juice", "25 g Shallot(s) , minced", "15 g Scallion(s) , whites only, sliced thin"], "s": ["Make the curing liquid", "Get crackin’", "Flip after one hour", "Yer yolks are ready", "Serve ’em up!", "Optional: Firm ’em up and make ’em extra “fudgy”", "Fudgy yolks are perfect for tartare", "BONUS! Step into our kitchen: Other cures we tried"], "tips": ["Keep it simple using only shio koji", "A note on food safety"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cured-egg-yolks"}, {"id": 707, "t": "Let’s Get Cracking: 37 Ways and Counting to Cook an Egg", "c": "Baking", "d": "Ah, the humble egg. The foundational building block of life, an egg is an enigma. (Egg-nigma?) At once both simple and complex, they make so many culinary experiences possible. In On Food and Cooking: The Science and Lore of The Kitchen, Harold McGee writes of the humble egg, “Modern science has only deepened the egg’s aptness as an emblem of creation. The yolk is a stockpile of fuel obtained by t", "i": [], "s": ["Eggs 101: Start here", "Light as a ☁️", "The perfect scramble", "Amazing omelets", "Poached eggs on point", "Cured and deviled", "A little something different", "Brunch it up!", "Crazy for quiche", "Duck-ing delicious", "The modernist made-up egg"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-egg-hub"}, {"id": 708, "t": "Almond Croissants, Twice Baked", "c": "Baking", "d": "Looking for an easy way to refresh day-old croissants? Simply swipe with simple syrup, generously spread on some homemade frangipane, top with sliced almonds, and bake! Waste not, want not. Just like croutons and bread crumbs make good use of old bread, almond croissants were born out of necessity, allowing bakeries to maximize their production and enhance day-old pastries for sale. Rich, buttery,", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 recipe The Secret to Mastering Croissants at Home 1 recipe Classic Frangipane , room temperature - Simple Syrup, as needed - Almonds , sliced , as needed - Confectioners’ sugar, as needed", "1 recipe The Secret to Mastering Croissants at Home 1 recipe Classic Frangipane , room temperature - Simple Syrup, as needed - Almonds , sliced , as needed - Confectioners’ sugar, as needed", "1 recipe The Secret to Mastering Croissants at Home", "1 recipe Classic Frangipane , room temperature", "Simple Syrup, as needed", "Almonds , sliced , as needed", "Confectioners’ sugar, as needed", "Frangipane, as needed"], "s": ["It starts with croissants", "Preheat the oven", "Split croissants", "Brush with simple syrup", "Spread frangipane on bottom halves", "Sandwich the croissants and spread with more frangipane", "Dip it!", "Bake", "Garnish and enjoy"], "tips": ["Enhance your simple syrup with liqueur"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/almond-croissants-twice-baked"}, {"id": 709, "t": "How Do You Like Your Eggs?", "c": "Baking", "d": "Fried, scrambled, over-easy, sunny-side up. Perfectly poached atop hash, or as an omelet—Spanish, or French à la Jacques Pépin. In a box with a fox, late night at Waffle House, or hard-boiled with truffle salt and a Rex Stout novel...how do you like your eggs? There’s more than one way to cook an egg. We’re hard at work trying to crack the code of making the edible, incredible. We want to hear wha", "i": [], "s": ["Update! Eggcellent new resources for you"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-do-you-like-your-eggs"}, {"id": 710, "t": "Aerated Peanut Butter Brittle", "c": "Baking", "d": "What’s better than peanut brittle? The ultimate peanut brittle made with peanut butter and pumped full of air. It’s extra peanut-y with a crisp crunch that won’t crack your teeth. We put the ChefSteps spin on this hard sugar candy, using several of our favorite secret weapons to take this confection to new heights. Baking soda enhances the Maillard reaction for a caramel-y color and flavor, and it", "i": ["180 g Sugar , granulated", "180 g Corn syrup , light", "100 g Water", "40 g Butter", "30 g Peanut butter , smooth or chunky", "5 g Baking soda", "75 g Peanuts , roasted, chopped"], "s": ["The vacuum-sealed secrets of our peanut brittle", "Set up your mise en place", "Boil the syrup", "Add the butter", "Cook to the hard-crack stage", "Add the peanut butter", "Stir in baking soda", "Fold in the chopped peanuts", "“Cast” the candy onto the baking mat", "It’s vacuum time", "Break it up", "Level it up and dip pieces in chocolate", "Package and store it", "Bonus! Try this with Nutella"], "tips": ["More about chamber vacuum sealers", "What to do if you don’t have a chamber sealer"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/aerated-peanut-butter-brittle"}, {"id": 711, "t": "So Simple Sous Vide Dulce de Leche", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This is caramel sauce’s older, wiser, and more sophisticated sibling. With sous vide and a can of sweetened condensed milk, you can make the simplest caramel sauce ever that’s dialed in to your liking. The longer the milk cooks sous vide, the darker, richer, and thicker it will be. If you’re looking for a drizzly sauce to top off your next dessert, choose a shorter cooking time. If you want a thic", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 Sweetened condensed milk , 14-ounce can", "1 Sweetened condensed milk , 14-ounce can"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Pick your desired doneness", "Cook that can", "Use that caramel sauce"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-dulce-de-leche"}, {"id": 712, "t": "Holiday Panettone", "c": "Baking", "d": "Light and luxurious, panettone is like a fruitcake and a brioche had a baby. A sweet, rich, citrus-scented dough is studded with booze-soaked cherries and candied orange zest, this Italian holiday classic can’t be beat. Traditional panettone takes days to bake—made with a wild yeast starter, the dough is built over time and left to ferment and rise as nature works her magic. We’ve sped up the proc", "i": ["180 g Bulgarian buttermilk", "10 g Instant dry yeast", "120 g How to Make a Sourdough Starter", "360 g Bread flour", "120 g Egg yolk(s) , about 8", "90 g Sugar , granulated", "10 g Salt , kosher", "2 g Mandarin essential oil , around 70 drops", "0.5 g Lemon essential oil , around 30 drops", "2 g Vanilla bean , seeds", "90 g Butter , unsalted and softened", "125 g Dried tart cherries , soaked in bourbon (we used Bulleit bourbon)", "90 g Candied orange zest", "Pearl sugar, as needed", "Egg wash, as needed"], "s": ["Make the starter", "Start the dough", "Add the flavorings", "Knock in the butter", "Add the inclusions", "Bulk fermentation", "Stretch and fold to capture more air", "Prepare the mold and hanging supports", "Shape it up", "Proof that panettone", "Preheat your oven", "Final egg wash, score, and garnish", "Bake in two stages", "Flip it upside down", "Let it cool", "Slice, serve, and store", "BONUS: Peek into our panettone development"], "tips": ["How to split this process into two days", "If you do not have a sourdough starter", "Use those egg whites!", "Amp up the color with astaxanthin", "Speed it up", "Go for the traditional top", "The power of steam"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/classic-panettone-in-one-day"}, {"id": 713, "t": "Level Up Any Bun or Roll With a Spiced, Seeded Topping", "c": "Baking", "d": "Here’s the easiest and most flavorful way to revive and customize boring buns and basic dinner rolls. Below is our go-to blend plus our easy trick to get those seeds to stick. Use this as a source of inspiration to bedazzle your burger or brat buns. Mix it up for whatever you’re making. Grilling up Chicago dogs? Dress your buns in poppy seeds. Making Hungarian goulash-style sloppy joes? Top your b", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Dinner Rolls , or store-bought buns , as needed 80 g Seed and spice blend , as needed, (see below) - Egg wash, as needed", "Dinner Rolls , or store-bought buns , as needed 80 g Seed and spice blend , as needed, (see below) - Egg wash, as needed", "80 g Seed and spice blend , as needed, (see below)", "Egg wash, as needed", "30 g Poppy seed , black", "30 g Sesame seeds , white", "3 g Ajwain seeds", "6 g Caraway seeds , ground", "10 g Salt , Maldon flake", "6 g Hawaiian black salt"], "s": ["Preheat the oven", "Toast seeds and spices", "Mix it up", "Make an egg wash", "Brush rolls and sprinkle on those seeds", "Bake the rolls", "Level up those burgers and brats", "Bake buns your way"], "tips": ["Why this mix?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-seed-any-roll"}, {"id": 714, "t": "Sous Vide Deli-Style Turkey", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Forget standing at the deli counter. With a special dry brine, the magic of sous vide, and a little bit of patience, you can make your very own deli turkey meat at home. This turkey meat is perfect for stacking on sandwiches and building quick snack boards with sliced apples and cheese. Using our dry cure as a guideline, you can add and adjust ingredients to create your very own blend that suits y", "i": ["27 g Kosher salt", "27 g Brown sugar , light", "1.4 g Prague powder #1", "7 g Wright’s hickory liquid smoke", "5 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG)", "850 g Turkey breast(s) , boneless and skinless (about 1 large)"], "s": ["Mix up the cure", "Season the meat and let it rest", "Heat sous vide bath", "Cook sous vide and cool", "Slice it up", "Make an amazing sandwich"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-turkey-deli-meat"}, {"id": 715, "t": "Air-Fried Turkey Poutine", "c": "Baking", "d": "With the building blocks of classic poutine in place, we’re putting a Thanksgiving twist on this Canadian classic. Whether you need a hangover cure, a stick-to-your-ribs snack, Black Friday fuel, or just want a delicious, creative way to clean out your fridge, this turkey poutine can do it all. Below you’ll find a roadmap to choose your own adventure to perfect poutine. You can make epic cheese cu", "i": ["1 recipe Turkey Gravy 1 recipe How to Make Squeaky Cheese Curds Just Like Beecher’s 1 recipe French Fries: Achieve the Holy Grail of Air Frying 1 recipe Cheddar Cheese Sauce 1 recipe Turkey Jus Gras - Sage , pan fried (optional) , as needed - Shredded cooked turkey , (optional) , as needed", "1 recipe Turkey Gravy", "1 recipe How to Make Squeaky Cheese Curds Just Like Beecher’s", "1 recipe French Fries: Achieve the Holy Grail of Air Frying", "1 recipe Cheddar Cheese Sauce", "1 recipe Turkey Jus Gras", "Sage , pan fried (optional) , as needed", "Shredded cooked turkey , (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Go classic with cheese curds", "Save time with these modernist hacks", "Amp it up", "Other ways to fry"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/air-fried-turkey-poutine"}, {"id": 716, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Waffle Your Stuffing", "c": "Baking", "d": "A staple on many Thanksgiving tables, stuffing rarely disappoints. No matter what mix you make, whether you add some sausage, diced green apples or dried cranberries, it’s always moist and flavorful. The one thing that would take stuffing to the next level: texture. Our waffle iron frenzy a few years ago showed us just how many things you can successfully “waffle.” With those experiences in mind, ", "i": [], "s": ["Start with your favorite stuffing", "Preheat your waffle iron", "Break up those bread bits", "Test your temp and time", "Remove the waffles carefully", "Top it off"], "tips": ["Add an egg"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/stuffing-waffles"}, {"id": 717, "t": "Tear Your Bread for Better Croutons", "c": "Baking", "d": "An essential component of many salads, croutons don’t deserve to be an afterthought. Save those dull, dry, stale store-bought cubes for stuffing or bread pudding. Just like a loaf of freshly baked bread or a crusty baguette, croutons should be as enjoyable to eat on their own as they are in salads. With a few simple steps, you can transform a whole loaf of bread into croutons that are crispy on th", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Bread , Country loaf or baguette is ideal , as needed - Olive oil , 10 to 15% (can also use canola or peanut oil) , as needed - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , cracked , as needed", "Bread , Country loaf or baguette is ideal , as needed - Olive oil , 10 to 15% (can also use canola or peanut oil) , as needed - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , cracked , as needed", "Olive oil , 10 to 15% (can also use canola or peanut oil) , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , cracked , as needed"], "s": ["Preheat your oven", "Tear up that bread", "Get ’em good & seasoned", "Bake", "Salad up!"], "tips": ["Add extra oomph with a flavor-infused oil", "Add another layer of flavor (optional)"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/torn-croutons"}, {"id": 718, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Level Up Your Pie Crust Layers with Liquor", "c": "Baking", "d": "One way to improve flakiness and boost layers in a pie crust is to add a bit of booze, typically vodka. But how much do you add to ensure proper hydration, keep the dough manageable, and still get great results? And are you limited to the liquor store’s least flavorful option? We’re not here to just add a bit of alcohol and call it a day. We pushed the percentage to the max to find the hydration b", "i": [], "s": ["How It Works", "The Booze Bell Curve", "Boost That Flake Factor", "Pie’s the limit!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/level-up-your-layers-boozy-pie-dough"}, {"id": 719, "t": "All You Need to Know to Master Lattice Pie Crust", "c": "Baking", "d": "A lattice crust atop a pie is the epitome of eating with our eyes. An excellent way to make your next dessert absolutely irresistible, latticing provides the perfect balance of sweet, juicy filling and buttery, flaky, lightly crunchy bites of pastry. Because of its beauty and visual intricacy, creating a lattice crust can be intimidating. Pastry chef Matthew Woolen demonstrates the process below, ", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 recipe Perfect Pie Dough - Egg wash, as needed", "1 recipe Perfect Pie Dough - Egg wash, as needed", "1 recipe Perfect Pie Dough", "Egg wash, as needed"], "s": ["Watch the lattice in action", "Make your pie dough", "Roll out the dough", "Cut the top dough into strips", "Lattice away!", "Master pie dough", "Perfect for a lattice top"], "tips": ["Chilling and resting between each step is key", "Use a cookie sheet as your work surface", "The best fillings for lattice tops"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-lattice-a-pie"}, {"id": 720, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Make Your Quiche Velvety Smooth With Velveeta", "c": "Dessert", "d": "Put a little spring in your quiche’s step with a surprisingly simple ingredient: Velveeta! Velveeta is prized for its ooey gooey creamy cheesiness, and when you blend it into a quiche base, the resulting custard becomes super rich, springy, silky, and smooth. WHAT YOU’LL NEED:", "i": [], "s": ["How to Do It", "Why It Works"], "tips": ["“Real” Cheese", "Peek Into Our Development Process"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/quiche-velveeta"}, {"id": 721, "t": "ChefSteps LIVE Episode 1: Talking Turkey", "c": "Meat", "d": "Thanks for tuning in to watch our inaugural episode of ChefSteps LIVE! If you weren’t able to join us live or want to watch it again, you can find the full video here (scroll down a bit to see it). Below, you’ll also find links to the recipes and resources that Grant mentioned on air, as well as a recap of his chat with chef and food scientist Chris Young about brining. We appreciate your comments", "i": [], "s": ["Watch it again and again", "Episode shortcuts", "Grant and Chris talk about brining", "Turkey recipes and resources", "Coming soon"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chefsteps-live-ep-1"}, {"id": 722, "t": "Sous Vide Cultured Butter", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Like all delicious fermented foods, culturing cream to churn into butter takes time, but the results are totally worth it. Cultured butter has a rich flavor that varies depending on the cream and fermentation time—it can be nutty, tangy like buttermilk, full-bodied, savory, and even a little funky. With traditional methods, the process can take several weeks as the bacteria slowly ferments the cre", "i": ["500 g Heavy cream , for whipping", "80 g Live-culture yogurt", "1.3 g Flora Danica mesophilic aromatic culture , 0.25% (optional, instead of yogurt)", "Sea salt , finely ground, 0.5% to total butterfat , as needed", "Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , 0.25% to total butterfat (optional) , as needed", "Carrot(s) , grated, 9–12% juice to total fat (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Choose your cream", "Choose your culture", "Heat sous vide bath", "Combine the cream and culture", "Sous vide that cream", "Cool it down", "Churn, churn, churn", "Strain off the buttermilk", "Add some color (optional)", "Rinse your butter ball", "Add flavor", "Paddle and press the butter", "Pack it up"], "tips": ["Cover that container!", "How to churn without a food processor", "Save some buttermilk for your next batch!", "Other ways to add color"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-cultured-butter"}, {"id": 723, "t": "How to Turn Any Biscuit into an Ultra Tall and Flaky One", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Adding more layers to your biscuits is as simple as 3x3. Three folds, three times, plus a generous rest (chill) in between each step will equal epic height, way more layers, and the lightest, fluffiest, flakiest biscuit you ever ate. Get ready to take your favorite biscuit recipe down to flaky town. WHAT YOU’LL NEED: Rolling pin Bench scraper High-quality plastic wrap 1/4 Sheet pan(s) Parchment pa", "i": [], "s": ["Let’s build some biscuits", "Make your favorite biscuit dough", "First fold", "First rest", "Second fold", "Second rest", "Third and final fold", "Third rest", "Roll out the dough and cut biscuits", "Brush with egg wash and chill", "Preheat the oven", "Bake the biscuits", "The proof is in the puff", "You know what goes good with biscuits?"], "tips": ["Dough upgrade: coat the fat in flour", "Why rest and chill?", "Bake from cold"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turn-any-biscuit-into-a-flaky-one"}, {"id": 724, "t": "How to Take Your Dinner Rolls from Basic to Beyond Epic", "c": "Baking", "d": "Look beyond the world of Parker House rolls and biscuits from a can to see these epically delicious dinner rolls waiting to grace your next holiday table. These are truly the dinner rolls of your dreams with layers of flavor and texture—soft, fluffy interior, golden-brown exterior, and crispy bottoms. Based on our original dinner roll recipe, we cranked the flavor up to 11 by brushing the dough wi", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 2 recipes Dinner Rolls - Rendered fat , (turkey, chicken, or infused oil) , as needed", "2 recipes Dinner Rolls - Rendered fat , (turkey, chicken, or infused oil) , as needed", "2 recipes Dinner Rolls", "Rendered fat , (turkey, chicken, or infused oil) , as needed", "Kosher salt, as needed", "90 g Milk", "90 g Egg(s)"], "s": ["Make your fat", "Make the dough", "Prep your pan", "Shape the rolls", "Roll out the dough", "Slice the dough into strips and season", "Stretch and roll", "Brush the rolls", "Let them rest and rise", "Preheat the oven", "Bake the rolls", "Level up the flavor", "Enjoy!", "Add even more flavor"], "tips": ["How to make a smaller batch"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dinner-rolls-leveled-up"}, {"id": 725, "t": "Turkey Jus Gras", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Give your traditional Thanksgiving spread an easy, savory upgrade by swapping your gravy for this quick and easy turkey jus gras. Traditional chicken jus gras (the inspiration for this recipe) requires roasting chicken bones until golden brown, deglazing the pan with wine, and then adding water (or broth) and simmering for hours until you have a richly flavored stock. Then you strain and reduce th", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 kg Turkey stock , homemade or store-bought 160 g Holiday Herb Oil , or your fave fat of choice - Knox gelatin , 9% to 12% , as needed - Xanthan gum , 0.3% to 0.4% , as needed", "1 kg Turkey stock , homemade or store-bought 160 g Holiday Herb Oil , or your fave fat of choice - Knox gelatin , 9% to 12% , as needed - Xanthan gum , 0.3% to 0.4% , as needed", "160 g Holiday Herb Oil , or your fave fat of choice", "Knox gelatin , 9% to 12% , as needed", "Xanthan gum , 0.3% to 0.4% , as needed"], "s": ["Reduce the stock by half", "Mix in the magic", "Emulsify", "Enjoy"], "tips": ["A note on percentages"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turkey-jus-gras"}, {"id": 726, "t": "Level Up Your Gravy’s Umami Game", "c": "Baking", "d": "Make your gravy the greatest this year. With simple pantry items, you can dial up the umami of any gravy, enhancing its savory richness and leaving your guests wondering what your secret is. These recommended additions are intended to elevate already seasoned gravy. The suggested percentages provide a subtle umami lift but won’t overpower (nor will they season bland gravy). Choose your umami adven", "i": ["100 g Turkey Gravy", "1 g Soy sauce , 1%", "0.5 g Worcestershire sauce , 0.5%", "0.5 g Fish sauce , 0.5%", "3.5 g White miso paste , 3.5%", "1 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , 1%", "1.5 g Bragg liquid coconut aminos , 1.5%", "0.5 g Dry sherry , 0.5%", "1 g Shiitake mushrooms , dried and powdered, 1%", "3 g Dashi , 3% (made with turkey stock, bonito flake & kombu, steeped & strained)"], "s": ["Choose your umami adventure", "Add that umami oomph", "Pour it on thick"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/level-up-your-gravy-s-umami-game"}, {"id": 727, "t": "Great Gravy! How to Thicken Anything With Cornstarch or Flour", "c": "Baking", "d": "Turkey and pumpkin pie always steal the spotlight, but we think the real MVP of Thanksgiving is gravy. Whether you only put it on potatoes or drizzle it across your entire plate, you can’t deny the delicious magic of this sumptuous, savory sauce. While whisking is of the utmost importance (no one wants a taste of dry flour lumps and clumps), there are so many ways to thicken sauces—from roux and s", "i": [], "s": ["One or the other ...", "Thin and drizzly", "The Goldilocks gravy: not too thick, nor too thin", "A little bit thicker now", "Great gravies and glazes"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/roux-vs-slurry"}, {"id": 728, "t": "Sous Vide Turkey Rillettes", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Here’s how to turn confit into charcuterie. Traditionally a preservation method, rillettes is an easy way to turn confit turkey legs into an hors d’oeuvre, anytime snack, cheeseboard accoutrement, or picnic-perfect protein. To round out the flavor of our turkey rillettes (aka “potted turkey”), we created a golden honey and apricot gastrique which adds a satisfying sweet-tart flavor that balances t", "i": ["753 g Turkey legs , skin off, raw (about 2)", "15 g Kosher salt", "1.5 g Prague powder #1 , optional", "7.5 g Brown sugar , light", "2 g Black peppercorns", "100 g Apple cider vinegar", "40 g Clover honey", "33 g Dried apricots", "27 g Shallot(s)", "15 g Olive oil"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Season the turkey legs and bag ’em up", "Make the gastrique", "Pull the turkey legs and shred the meat", "Mix the meat and gastrique", "Serve!", "Build that charcuterie board"], "tips": ["Top with rendered fat (optional)"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turkey-rillettes-potted-turkey"}, {"id": 729, "t": "Extra-Crispy KFC-Style Fried Turkey", "c": "Baking", "d": "Deep-fried turkey may be a thing of aspirational Thanksgiving dreams, or oil-splattered nightmares. But now you can go beyond the basic roast and indulge in perfectly cooked turkey enveloped in an extra crispy, crunchy crust. This is stress-free fried turkey. You don’t need a ginormous stockpot and gallons of hot oil. No crazy lever and pulley system to lift your bird in and out of the pot. You do", "i": ["1 Turkey , whole, up to 24 lbs", "1 recipe Not-So-Secret 12 Herbs & Spices Fried Chicken Seasoning , as needed to season your turkey (you will have leftovers)", "1 gallon Peanut oil , or more, as needed", "1 gallon", "Peanut oil , or more, as needed", "1 kg All-purpose flour", "250 g Cornstarch", "50 g Trisol", "25 g Baking soda", "25 g Kosher salt", "800 g Buttermilk"], "s": ["Butcher that bird", "Heat sous vide bath", "Season the turkey", "Bag up that bird", "Cook sous vide", "Pull the turkey and cool it down", "Portion the cooked and cooled turkey", "Day of", "Set up your fryer and preheat the oil to 370 °F / 188 °C", "Mix the breading", "Season the buttermilk", "Let’s build that breading!", "Breading Step 1", "Breading Step 2", "Breading Step 3", "Breading Step 4", "Fry that turkey", "Hold ’em warm ’til you’re ready to eat", "Store and use leftovers", "Serve it up right"], "tips": ["Yes, you read that right. Fried. Turkey. Skin.", "To salt or not to salt", "Double the fry, double the fun (optional)", "Flavor it up"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/extra-crispy-fried-turkey"}, {"id": 730, "t": "Triple Chili Crisp", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Nashville hot chicken has swept the nation with crispy chicken so spicy you’ll shed a tear (or two). The secret is chili oil that’s drizzled on right as the chicken comes out of the fryer. Up to our ears in fried poultry, we were inspired by both Nashville’s hot take and Chinese chili crisp: a tongue-tingling spicy, crispy, crunchy, chunky condiment that’s stirred into noodles, sprinkled on fried ", "i": ["275 g Peanut oil , or canola oil, or conditioned fry oil", "75 g Unsalted butter", "15 g Black peppercorns", "10 g White pepper", "4 g Chile threads , optional", "15 g Pequin peppers , or dried arbol chilis", "50 g Garlic , cloves (sliced – about 8 whole)", "225 g Shallot(s) , (sliced – about 8 whole)", "5 g Thyme , leaves picked", "5 g Cayenne pepper", "150 g Peanuts , chopped, raw or roasted, unsalted"], "s": ["Let’s talk about heat", "Toast the peppercorns and chilis", "Grind the peppercorns and chilis", "Crush the peanuts", "Brown the butter", "Fry the sliced shallots and garlic", "Mix it all up", "Storage and reheating", "Put it on EVERYTHING"], "tips": ["Sweeten it up"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/put-it-on-everything-chili-crisp"}, {"id": 731, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Fried Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "There’s something truly magical about fried chicken. It’s so magically delicious, in fact, that 49% of Americans eat it at least once a week! But we’ve all experienced the less magical side of fried chicken: meat that’s tough or dry, chewy skin, a soggy or doughy breading, a crust that cracks off like a shell. We are here to lay the foundations of frying, gathering together the hows and whys so yo", "i": ["200 g All-purpose flour", "50 g Cornstarch", "5 g Baking soda , optional", "5 g Kosher salt", "10 g Trisol", "5 g Not-So-Secret 12 Herbs & Spices Fried Chicken Seasoning", "250 g Buttermilk", "80 g Mochiko sweet rice flour", "Everclear , (sub 100g vodka and reduce the water to 100g)", "Water , (reduce to 100g if using vodka)", "5 g Salt"], "s": ["Pretreatments", "Portioning", "Brining", "Precooking", "Build texture with breading", "Enhance your breading with modified starches", "Traditional breading—with a twist", "Take tempura to the next level", "The fats for frying", "The oil of your choosing", "Frying methods", "Recommended times and temperatures for frying", "Level up the flavor", "Make a sammie"], "tips": ["Level it up with extra breading layers", "Don’t dump your oil down the drain!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-guide-to-fried-chicken"}, {"id": 732, "t": "Not-So-Secret 12 Herbs & Spices Fried Chicken Seasoning", "c": "Baking", "d": "A closely guarded seasoning is one of the pillars of really good fried chicken. We’re pulling back the curtain and sharing our own variation of the iconic 11 herbs and spices. (Okay, technically, our ingredient count comes to 12. But we’re betting the Colonel’s not counting sea salt as one of his 11, either.) As we embarked on a journey of epic fried poultry proportions—from uncovering all things ", "i": ["35 g White pepper", "35 g Black peppercorns", "35 g Green peppercorns , dried", "40 g Kosher salt", "30 g Yellow mustard seeds", "10 g Celery seeds", "5 g Fennel seeds", "2 g Chile flakes", "10 g Granulated garlic", "10 g Granulated onion", "3 g Marjoram , dried", "3 g Ginger , ground"], "s": ["Third pepper’s the charm", "Grind up the whole spices", "Mix all the spices together", "Sprinkle generously", "Store it"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fried-chicken-spice-blend"}, {"id": 733, "t": "Enhancing Textures: An Introduction to the Hydrocolloid Universe", "c": "Baking", "d": "With names like Ultra-Tex 3, Methocel F50, and agar agar, hydrocolloids sound like they’re meant for science fiction novels, not our pantries. But these seemingly mysterious white powders are incredibly valuable in food development and can provide fun new experiences for home chefs. Derived from natural sources (like seaweed, tapioca, and plant matter), hydrocolloids have been used for centuries t", "i": ["Soy lecithin powder, as needed", "Versawhip 600K, as needed", "Methylcellulose F50, as needed", "Xanthan gum, as needed", "Ultra-Tex 3, as needed", "Sodium alginate, as needed", "Calcium lactate gluconate, as needed", "Agar agar, as needed", "Carrageenan, kappa, as needed", "Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F, as needed", "LM pectin, as needed", "Rapid set HM pectin, as needed", "Slow set HM pectin, as needed"], "s": ["Foaming", "Soy lecithin powder", "Versawhip 600K", "Methocel F50", "Thickening", "Xanthan gum", "Ultra-Tex 3", "Spherification", "Sodium alginate", "Calcium lactate gluconate", "Gelling", "Agar agar", "Kappa carrageenan", "Iota carrageenan", "Gellan gum F (low-acyl gellan gum)", "Low methoxyl (LM) pectin", "High methoxyl (HM) pectin", "Resources"], "tips": ["Other cool ways to use Methocel F50"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/unlock-your-hydrocolloid-starter-pack"}, {"id": 734, "t": "Cooking, Visualized", "c": "Meat", "d": "We love graphics at ChefSteps. In videos, infographics, and even the app, we use graphics to help conceptualize and bring to life the parts of cooking that you can’t see—like what’s happening in your microwave and the types of heat at work in your oven. They’re also a fun way to tell stories visually, like how to select the perfect turkey and sides for Thanksgiving. This gallery will continue to g", "i": [], "s": ["How would you like that cooked?", "Chart a course around the sous vide world", "Whet your knife knowledge", "How to pace a multi-course meal", "Understanding ice cream", "When you give ChefSteps a cookie ...", "Design a better burger", "The modernist guide to gums", "The many states of water", "Brick-by-brick pizza oven instructions"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cooking-visualized"}, {"id": 735, "t": "Sous Vide Risotto", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "When you want the creamy, comforting payoff of perfectly cooked risotto but don’t want to stand at the stove vigilantly stirring, let sous vide stir instead. Traditionally, getting the most out of your risotto is all about lovingly tending to the mixture as it simmers, slowly adding stock and stirring consistently, giving it the time and energy that it needs to shine. While there are nights when w", "i": ["200 g Rice , Arborio or Carnaroli", "50 g Parmesan , grated", "10 g Kosher salt", "1 g Black peppercorns , finely ground", "600 g Water , or stock", "120 g Butter , unsalted, room temp", "2 Egg yolk(s) , room temp", "1 Shallot(s) , about 25 grams 1 Garlic , one clove, about 8 grams 200 g White wine", "1 Garlic , one clove, about 8 grams", "200 g White wine"], "s": ["Let’s talk about rice", "Rinse the rice", "Heat sous vide bath", "Bag it up", "Cook the risotto", "Gently mix the bag", "Optional: Add flavor with wine and alliums", "Pull the risotto and make it creamy", "Four ways to finish it", "Traditional lemon, basil, and Parmesan", "Browned butter mushrooms and herbs", "Tomato, basil, and a sous vide egg", "Lemon garden scallop"], "tips": ["Our favorite way to cover sous vide containers", "Check out Kyl’s top scallop-searing tip"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sous-vide-risotto"}, {"id": 736, "t": "Steak From the Future: The Modernist Strategy to Dry Age Beef", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "How do you make a steak better? Age it. Like the finest wines and funkiest cheeses, aging techniques transform beef to reveal new depths of flavor and tenderness. Dry aging is a process that takes time, care, and precision. Big cuts of beef are exposed to air in a humidity-controlled environment so enzymes and good bacteria can go to work, breaking down and transforming the molecular structures of", "i": ["800 g Steak(s) , 2 each (1 in to 1 1/2 in thick New York Strips)", "50 g Blue cheese , (Papillon Roquefort Black Label A.O.C Blue Cheese)", "15 g Liquid shio koji", "15 g Haku Iwashi Whiskey Barrel Aged Fish Sauce"], "s": ["The devil’s in the dry-aged details", "The cost & loss of dry aging", "Make that funky “marinade”", "“Age” your steaks", "Sous vide those steaks!", "Grill ’em, sear ’em, get that crust!", "Serve them in style", "A look into our research & development", "Trials & testing", "“Aging” ingredients", "Tasting notes", "Beef up your meat knowledge"], "tips": ["Want to try a different steak?", "The magic of koji", "Can’t wait overnight?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/rapid-dry-aged-steaks"}, {"id": 737, "t": "You tell us: What makes fried chicken so darn good?", "c": "Baking", "d": "There’s more than one way to fry a chicken, and we're hard at work trying to crack that crispy, crunchy code. We want to hear what YOU love most about fried chicken. It’s about more than just a secret blend of herbs and spices. There’s meat that’s marinated, brined, or dunked in buttermilk. Crunchy coatings that are thick or thin, made with flour or cornstarch, breadcrumbs, or even crushed up chip", "i": [], "s": ["Update!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/you-tell-us-what-makes-fried-chicken-so-darn-good"}, {"id": 738, "t": "Quick-Style Kraut", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you love the briny tang of sauerkraut but feel intimidated or ill-equipped to make it at home, this recipe is for you! We’re donning our conductor’s hats to help you safely and confidently arrive at fermentation station. At its most simple, sauerkraut is fermented cabbage. Microscopic organisms and good bacteria, like Lactobacillus, thrive in the salt-brine environment and transform crunchy raw", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1.4 kg Green cabbage , 100% 28 g Salt , kosher, 2% - Brine , from your last batch of fermented vegetables, 2%, optional , as needed", "1.4 kg Green cabbage , 100% 28 g Salt , kosher, 2% - Brine , from your last batch of fermented vegetables, 2%, optional , as needed", "28 g Salt , kosher, 2%", "Brine , from your last batch of fermented vegetables, 2%, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Optional: Use a starter", "Gather and clean equipment", "Wash and cut the cabbage", "Salt the cabbage", "Let it be", "Pack the cabbage", "Keep an eye on the kraut", "Decide when the kraut is done", "Visit new fermentation flavor destinations"], "tips": ["What if I don’t have enough brine to cover the cabbage?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/quick-style-krauts"}, {"id": 739, "t": "Relish Kraut", "c": "Baking", "d": "The ultimate condiment, having this relish kraut in your refrigerator makes your eating life easier. Crafted using the same principles as our basic quick kraut, this relish kraut is enhanced with the flavors of fermented kale, cauliflower, scallions, and black garlic. Use it in sandwiches or salads. Make it a zingy salad unto its own by adding dried fruits, a drizzle of honey, toasted onions or sh", "i": ["900 g Green cabbage , 1 head, 82%", "200 g Red cabbage , 1/4 head, 18%", "275 g Cauliflower , 1/2 head, 25%", "85 g Bell pepper(s) , 1/2 pepper, 8%", "75 g Carrot(s) , 2 peeled, 7%", "20 g Garlic , 3 cloves, 2%", "40 g Scallion(s) , 3 onions, 4%", "40 g Kale , 3 leaves, 4%", "15 g Black garlic , 1.5%", "30 g Salt , kosher, 2.5%"], "s": ["Gather and clean the equipment", "Clean and prep the vegetables", "Salt it up", "Let it be", "Pack the vegetables", "Keep an eye on your kraut", "Decide when the kraut is done"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/relish-kraut"}, {"id": 740, "t": "Salsa Kraut", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Using the same technique and timing of our quick-style kraut, this salsa sauerkraut is bold, bright, zesty, and a little peppery thanks to chilis, cilantro, garlic, and lime. Top off your favorite Mexican dishes for a kick of flavor, add a little spice to grain salads, slide into sandwiches, or roll up in wraps! save Print", "i": ["1.2 kg Green cabbage , 1 head, 100%", "140 g Poblano pepper(s) , 2 peppers, 11.5%", "30 g Jalapeño(s) , 1 pepper, 2.5%", "40 g Fresno chile(s) , 3 chilis, 3%", "45 g Cilantro , fresh stems from 1 bunch, 3.5%", "200 g Red onion(s) , 1 onion, 16.5%", "20 g Garlic , 3 cloves, 1.5%", "25 g Fresh lime juice , 1 lime, 2%", "30 g Salt , kosher, 2.5%"], "s": ["Gather and clean equipment", "Clean and prep vegetables", "Salt the vegetables", "Let it be", "Pack the vegetables", "Monitor the salsa kraut", "Decide when the kraut is done", "Make more ferments"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salsa-kraut"}, {"id": 741, "t": "Perfect Crust Paella in Any Pan", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Perfect paella is a thing of beauty. Layers of rich flavors and satisfying textures—moist rice studded with succulent seafood, meat, and fresh vegetables all nestled atop a crispy, crackly, caramelized crust. When executed correctly, that socarrat is hands down the best and most defining part of paella. But achieving that balance isn’t easy—it takes patience, perseverance, a special pan, and even ", "i": ["115 g Sweet onion(s)", "60 g Chorizo", "40 g Garlic , cloves", "60 g Extra-virgin olive oil , plus some for frying the rice", "500 g Bomba rice", "1.5 kg Chicken stock , split 850g, 600g", "2 g Espelette pepper , optional; sub chili flakes", "0.5 g Saffron threads , optional", "12 g Parsley , Italian, chopped"], "s": ["Blend the sofrito", "Fry the sofrito and cook the rice", "Cool it down", "Make the magic socarrat sauce", "OVERVIEW: Finish and flip", "Start the crust", "Build the paella", "Release the crust", "Optional: Flip it", "Serve it up"], "tips": ["Level up leftover rice, paella style!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/paella"}, {"id": 742, "t": "Carrot-lina Gold BBQ Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "Inspired by tangy mustard-centric Carolina Gold BBQ sauce, we’re going from the garden to the grill with this versatile barbecue sauce that we’ve nicknamed “garden gold.” It all starts with the humble carrot and a chemical reaction. For a bold flavor base, we pressure cook carrots with a secret, surprisingly simple ingredient that increases the Maillard reaction, enhancing the natural earthy and s", "i": ["50 g Yellow mustard seeds", "270 g Water , divided", "500 g Carrot(s) , peeled", "2.5 g Baking soda", "10 g Salt , kosher", "60 g Mustard oil", "100 g Brown sugar , light", "150 g Apple cider vinegar", "2 g Liquid smoke , optional", "1 g Black pepper , ground", "0.25 g Xanthan gum , optional", "1 recipe Carrot-lina Gold BBQ Sauce", "10 g Serrano pepper , about half a pepper, about 1%", "1 g Granulated garlic , about .01% or to taste", "1 g Granulated onion , about .01% or to taste", "235 g Honey , 25%", "1 recipe Carrot-lina Gold BBQ Sauce - Horseradish , prepared (about 1%) , as needed", "Horseradish , prepared (about 1%) , as needed"], "s": ["Cook the mustard seeds", "Cook the carrots", "Strain the mustard seeds", "Blend it up", "Choose Your Own Adventure—Option 1: Serve it up", "Choose Your Own Adventure—Option 2: Slather, drizzle, or dip", "Golden Gardens Mopping Sauce", "Honey Mustard Dipping Sauce", "Hot Horseradish Mustard Sauce"], "tips": ["Sweet, mellow, or spicy—how do you like your mustard?", "A note on mustard oil"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/carrotlina-gold-bbq-sauce"}, {"id": 743, "t": "Grilling Elixir 2: Taming the Flame", "c": "Baking", "d": "We’ve all experienced it—flames flare up and suddenly the edges of your steak go from perfectly crispy to charred and crunchy. This elixir was created to help tame those flame-grilled flavors by helping to mellow the bitterness caused by charring. On its own, this magical concoction adds bright and refreshing notes that balance the rich smoky and savory flavors of grilling. Acid is a great way to ", "i": ["150 g Apple cider vinegar", "300 g Apple juice", "12 g Liquid smoke", "300 g Honey", "6 g Lemon peel", "9 g Thyme", "150 g Lemon juice , fresh", "3 g Black peppercorns , crushed"], "s": ["Steep the vinegar mixture", "Add the lemon juice and strain", "Spray away!", "Use it on...", "Grilled vegetables", "Grilled fish", "Chicken"], "tips": ["Make it your own", "How to store this elixir"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilling-elixir-2-taming-the-flame"}, {"id": 744, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Modernist BBQ", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Everyone loves good barbecue. Slowly cooking tough cuts of meat in p dry, smoky environment creates tender, succulent meat and some of the most robust and earthy flavors around. But unless you’re a pro, making good smoked meats at home can leave you feeling a little like Goldilocks struggling to find that just right result. Traditional barbecue at home requires a significant commitment of time and", "i": [], "s": ["Choose your own barbecue adventure", "Pick your protein", "Before you start cooking: Truss it or treat it", "Activa (aka “meat glue”)", "Trussing", "Bag it up", "The cure", "Create your own cure", "Get that pit barbecue pink smoke ring", "Ideal sous vide barbecue setup", "Choose your doneness", "Cook sous vide", "Build the bark", "Finish on the grill, or in an oven", "Serve it up!", "Sauce it up", "On the side", "Perfect for pulled pork"], "tips": ["Modernist versus traditional curing methods", "Chill it if you’re cutting portions"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-guide-to-modernist-bbq"}, {"id": 745, "t": "The Ultimate Modernist Barbecue Pork Shoulder", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The perfect barbecue pork shoulder—succulent, shreddable meat; dark, glassy crust; a smoky flavor; and that hallmark pink smoke ring—is achieved by hours and hours of low and slow cooking with lots of woodsmoke. Though it’s a fun and flavorful project, traditional smoked barbecue can be challenging to do at home. It requires a lot of active time and attention to tend the coals and the woodsmoke. A", "i": ["2.5 kg Pork shoulder , bone-in, 100%", "125 g Brown sugar , 5%", "50 g Smoked salt , 2% for the dry cure", "2.5 g Prague powder #1 , 0.1% for the dry cure", "125 g Honey , 5%", "12.5 g Liquid smoke , 0.5%", "25 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce) , for the rub", "25 g Black pepper , coarsely ground, for the rub", "25 g Yellow mustard seeds , ground, for the rub", "10 g Garlic powder , for the rub", "5 g Onion powder , for the rub"], "s": ["Pick your pork shoulder", "Scale and mix the dry cure", "Bag the meat, add the cure and liquids", "Heat sous vide bath", "Cook sous vide", "Make a spice rub", "Remove the meat from the bag (and save some juice!)", "Apply the rub and build the bark", "Finish on the grill", "Shred it up", "Serve it up"], "tips": ["How to truss a boneless pork shoulder", "The science of the pink smoke ring", "Adding layers of smoky flavor with precision", "Cover your container with a yoga mat"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-modernist-bbq-pork-shoulder"}, {"id": 746, "t": "Grilling Elixir 1: The Booster", "c": "Baking", "d": "Conquer the wild west of Maillard reactions. A real ace in the hole, sling a spray bottle filled with this magical mixture whenever and wherever you want to experience new levels of flavor, color, and texture. From ordinary pantry ingredients to extraordinary elixir, this four ingredient sauce accelerates the Maillard reaction, adding layers of sweet, smoky flavor. It deepens colors for ultra-desi", "i": ["60 g Molasses", "90 g Clover honey", "150 g Worcestershire sauce", "35 g Wright’s hickory liquid smoke"], "s": ["Maximizing the Maillard reaction", "Warm up your sugars", "Mix ’em up", "Spray away!", "Use it on...", "Pork chops", "Chicken legs", "Mushrooms / Veggies"], "tips": ["To spray or sous vide, that’s your choice", "Make it your own", "How to store this elixir"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/elixir-cs-party-potion"}, {"id": 747, "t": "It’s Not Delivery—It’s Your Own High-Performing Wood-Fired Pizza Oven", "c": "Baking", "d": "The things we love most about perfectly cooked Neapolitan-style pizza—thin, chewy crust, puffed and perfectly toasted edges, and leopard-spotted underside—are the products of a precise balance of conduction, convection, and thermal radiation. Translation: you need a really great pizza oven to make really great pizza. A Neapolitan pizza crust is so good because it’s cooked quickly (no more than 90 ", "i": [], "s": ["Before you begin", "Build the foundation", "Build the base, deck, and vent", "Build the oven space and light your fire", "A few quick for cooking pizza", "Got oven questions? We got answers!", "Build instructions: LEGO style", "The perfect pizza pie", "Use that oven for more than just pizza"], "tips": ["How temperature and heat move through this oven", "How to customize your oven", "It’s time to stretch, toss, and top your dough!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/diy-wood-fired-neapolitan-pizza-oven-for-less-than-50"}, {"id": 748, "t": "All New for July: The Greatest for Grilling, from Seasoning to Salmon and the Best Steak Cuts, plus Smoked Ice Cream and Dill-Pickled Lettuce Cores", "c": "Dessert", "d": "Nothing says summer more than firing up the grill. This month we’re diving into the deep end to level up your grilling game—from mastering salmon to designing your own steak that rivals world-renowned Wagyu. We’ve got a few twists on cookout classics—like pickles and ice cream—as well a new grilling powder that drops a serious umami-bomb on whatever you sprinkle it on. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Get ready for grilled salmon perfection", "Design your own “Wagyu” chop steak", "Who says smoke is just for steaks?", "Never again question what cut to grill", "Top it off"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/all-new-for-july"}, {"id": 749, "t": "The Ultimate Grilled Salmon Steak", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Want to be the master of grilled salmon that everyone looks up to? Do you want that perfectly-seared, caramelized, smoky crust with a succulent interior that is bursting with flavor? Our Ultimate Grilled Salmon is a combination of smoked salmon candy from the Pike Place Market in Seattle and a juicy ribeye steak—BUT SALMON! We start this recipe off with a whole fish. We love starting from the begi", "i": ["900 g Salmon steaks , two, each 1 1/2-in thick", "13.5 g Salt , kosher or smoked salt, 1.5%", "90 g Brown sugar , 10%", "9 g Wright’s hickory liquid smoke , 1%"], "s": ["Remove the scales", "Cut some thick salmon steaks", "Truss your steaks", "Dry cure your salmon", "Sous vide that fish!", "Get your grill ripping HOT!", "Get the steaks ready to grill", "Grill ’em off", "Time to eat!", "Step into our kitchen", "Curing trials", "Make it a meal", "Your guide to all things salmon"], "tips": ["Farmed vs. wild—what’s the difference?", "Fresh vs. frozen", "Why steaks?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-grilled-salmon"}, {"id": 750, "t": "Dill-Pickled Lettuce Cores", "c": "Baking", "d": "Burger season is here and it’s time to break out the condiments. Even if you don’t like cucumber pickles, you’ve got to try these. What if you could have refreshing crunchy lettuce that was the pickle too? Don’t throw out those lettuce cores! Make some pickles, and make them in an instant. If you’re a fan of grilling, chances are good that you’ll have some classic fixins’ for those outdoor session", "i": ["100 g Champagne vinegar", "25 g Sugar", "8 g Dill , fresh chopped", "5 g Salt , kosher", "120 g Lettuce cores , from about 2 heads", "100 g Cold water"], "s": ["Gather your ingredients", "Make the pickling liquid", "Slice the lettuce cores", "Bag it up and seal it", "Open it up", "Enjoy!", "The inspiration", "The accompaniments"], "tips": ["If you don’t have a chamber vacuum sealer"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/do-not-throw-out-those-lettuce-bottoms-make-pickles"}, {"id": 751, "t": "Smoked Ice Cream", "c": "Baking", "d": "Want a new spin on ice cream this summer? Enter the delicious dark side of soft serve. With just a kiss of smoke added—this ice cream will make you scream, “Hell, yeah!” You can turn any ice cream base into smoked ice cream. We like to use our ChefSteps soft serve recipe for this because you don’t need a big fancy machine to produce this summertime classic. All you need is a stand mixer and some d", "i": ["1 recipe Soft Serve Ice Cream", "1 g Wright’s applewood liquid smoke , 1/4 teaspoon", "3.5 g Applewood smoked salt , to replace salt in recipe", "Applewood chips, as needed", "1 recipe Soft Serve Ice Cream - Applewood chips, as needed", "33 g Activated charcoal powder , 2%"], "s": ["Method One: Fast hack", "Method Two: Cold smoke while churning", "Method Three: Smoke the powdered milk", "The dark side", "Level up with smoked almonds and homemade cones", "Enjoy!", "Other ice cream bases to smoke out", "Accompaniments", "The science"], "tips": ["Be mindful of the smoke", "Try malted milk"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smoked-ice-cream"}, {"id": 752, "t": "Cinnamon Croissant Crunch", "c": "Baking", "d": "When we started seeing cereal made of tiny baked goods showing up in our social feeds, it felt like a challenge. Sure, tiny pancakes, that’s cute. But what would be even cuter? What would take true skill and intense attention to detail? We picked up the gauntlet. Use this recipe to blow up your own internet feed. There are two tricks to making these little croissants so crunchy: a sugary glazed co", "i": ["1 recipe Master Croissants in an “Instant”", "100 g Water", "100 g Sugar", "10 g Cinnamon", "Egg wash, as needed"], "s": ["Roll out your dough", "Make cinnamon syrup glaze", "Trim and portion the dough", "Roll ’em up!", "Egg wash", "Proof and bake", "Glaze", "Dehydrate", "Package", "Enjoy!", "Step up your game"], "tips": ["Make an egg wash"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cinnamon-croissant-crunch"}, {"id": 753, "t": "All New for June: Smash Burgers, Patty Engineering, Malted Mustard & Umami Ketchup", "c": "Meat", "d": "School’s out, but we have some summer studies in what is hopefully a very applied science. Get your master’s degree in burgers this month. There are burgers, and there are burgers engineered with an understanding of beef patties, mix-ins, and lean-to-fat ratios—all cooked expertly by people who want to be able to make the best burgers. Use the pages below to make sure you’re eating the ones from t", "i": [], "s": ["Grant smash!", "The beef", "Amazing condiments, bar none", "Extra credit"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/all-new-this-month-right-here"}, {"id": 754, "t": "The Ultimate Smash Burger", "c": "Baking", "d": "The smash burger has been around a long time. The core principle is this—take a pile of loosely packed ground beef, lay it onto a very hot griddle, press it down flat as a pancake, and then let it cook almost all the way through on one side. This creates a maximum surface area for a crispy bite and for Maillard reactions to run rampant. But if you want maximum flavor and texture, you’re also going", "i": ["454 g Brisket", "15 g Egg yolk(s) , (1 yolk per pound of ground beef)", "4.5 g Kosher salt , (per pound of ground beef)", "7 g Knox gelatin", "454 g Ground beef"], "s": ["Brisket breakdown", "The grinding", "If you are really serious about this—grind your own meat. It’s really simple.", "Upgrading your beef", "Creaming and forming", "Get your gear ready", "The smashing", "Cook and flip", "Putting it all together", "Smash burger bonus: The DVD extras"], "tips": ["Using store-bought ground beef? Here’s how to upgrade it.", "Creaming technique", "Don’t have a charcoal grill?", "Buns!", "Ultimate indoor hack version"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-smash-burger"}, {"id": 755, "t": "The Ultimate Burger Patty Guide for Purists", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "What’s the difference between sausage and hamburger? It’s pretty simple. Sausage is what you call hamburger once you add seasoning, mix it up, and emulsify. Hamburger should be pure and simple—perfectly ground, loosely packed, and seasoned after you shape the patties. You can cook them sous vide, smash them, or even slice them for super sliders. We’ll walk you through how to get the best results w", "i": [], "s": ["Understanding lean-to-fat ratios", "Choose your own burger adventure!", "Sous vide burger", "Smash burger", "Slider", "Chop steak", "Understanding your options—different cuts of beef", "Brisket—why it’s the meat king of burgers", "Understanding binders and bulkers", "Understanding mixing and process", "Understanding your grinder", "Let’s get grinding", "Separate your cut of choice into lean and fat", "Precutting", "Pick your ratio", "Grind it up", "Mix-Ins and portioning", "Tips for other meats", "How to temp your patties (non-sous vide)", "Troubleshooting"], "tips": ["Keep it all ice-cold", "Upgrade—align your grind for a tender burger"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-burger-patty-guide-for-purists"}, {"id": 756, "t": "Umami Mushroom Ketchup", "c": "Baking", "d": "Tomatoes make great ketchup because of their umami flavor properties. But mushrooms also make fantastic ketchup—they naturally contain MSG which makes them an umami powerhouse. This super umami and super silky mushroom ketchup ticks all the boxes that make a great condiment. It’s sweet, acidic and super savory. Did we mention that it’s savory? Chock-full of toasty umami-rich mushrooms and onions f", "i": ["500 g Portobello mushrooms , about 4-5 large caps and stems", "250 g Onion(s) , about 1 large", "Black pepper, as needed", "Canola oil, as needed", "12 g Salt , kosher", "300 g Apple cider vinegar", "150 g Brown sugar , light", "50 g Blackstrap molasses", "0.2 g Allspice , about 2 whole berries", "0.1 g Cloves , about two whole cloves", "1 g Xanthan gum , optional"], "s": ["Prepare mushrooms and onions", "Fire up the grill", "Get to grillin’", "Cook vinegar mixture", "Blend it", "Bottle it", "Keep condiment-ing"], "tips": ["Grilling trick", "Why xanthan gum?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/old-school-mushroom-ketchup"}, {"id": 757, "t": "Double Malted Mustard", "c": "Baking", "d": "Need a break from the run-of-the-mill yellow or Dijon mustard? Try making this double malted mustard. Malting usually takes time, but by using malt vinegar and barley malt syrup, this mustard comes together quickly: No malting required. Malted mustard is a little different and may not look like any mustard you are familiar with because of its jet-black color. Don’t be fooled—it is mustard to the c", "i": ["1 kg Onion(s) , about 3 large", "10 g Garlic , about 3 cloves", "40 g Horseradish root", "55 g Malt vinegar", "120 g Malt syrup", "180 g Dijon mustard", "5 g Salt , kosher", "1 g Black pepper , ground"], "s": ["Char onions and garlic", "Grate horseradish and add to vinegar", "Blend it", "Pack it", "Use it up!", "Check out the malt on these!", "Other toasted and charred recipes", "Take a deeper look at broiling"], "tips": ["Want to skip the broiler? Use the grill instead"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/double-malted-mustard"}, {"id": 758, "t": "Top 10 Burger Upgrades", "c": "Other", "d": "Here are our top 10 favorite upgrades to make your burgers EPIC this grilling season. When you’re really ready to master burgers and blow minds, take our ultimate Burger Class. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["You’ll never go back to plain old bacon!", "Upgrade any cheese into melty cheese slices", "Be the master of your own ketchup destiny", "Master the mustard", "Master the mayo", "This red onion jam changed our lives!", "Brioche buns made more tender than ever", "Upgrade your grill skills", "Dial in your patty doneness with ultimate precision", "Would you like fries with that?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/top-10-ultimate-burger-upgrades"}, {"id": 759, "t": "Our Favorite Grilling Tips and Tricks", "c": "Baking", "d": "Over the many years of ChefSteps teaching the hows and whys of cooking, we have developed loads of grilling tips, tricks, and recipes. Grilling season is now upon us, so we thought we’d feature just a few of our favorite highlights so you can get the most out of your grill this summer—don’t forget to start with the old seasonal cleaning! save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Has it been a while since you used your grill?", "Or maybe your grill just isn’t hot enough...", "Get to know where grilling flavor comes from", "You might even try leveled-up, grilling-on-the-go this year", "Or just keep it simple with grilled vegetables", "If you are sous viding something, you’ll want maximum searing", "How about boiling first for that perfect grilled potato?", "Why doesn’t anyone toast their buns?", "Another simple one—the perfect grilled tomato", "When science fails, reach for the mayonnaise", "Become the oyster grilling master your town needs", "Sometimes the best grill is no grill at all", "Go back to the beginning—caveman style"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/our-favorite-grilling-tips-and-tricks"}, {"id": 760, "t": "Master Croissants in an “Instant”", "c": "Baking", "d": "These “instant” croissants are about the best return-on-pastry-investment we know of. That’s because they taste about 80 percent as good as our ultimate croissant rolls, but with only 20 percent of the work. Don’t get us wrong, we still love and stand by our guide to mastering handmade croissants at home, but this recipe is perfect in any circumstance where you need delicious croissants ready and ", "i": ["45 g Warm water", "15 g Instant dry yeast", "575 g Bread flour , unbleached", "445 g Butter , unsalted", "60 g Sugar", "15 g Salt , kosher", "225 g Ice water", "Egg wash, as needed"], "s": ["Watch the top to bottom process in less than one minute", "What is lamination?", "Get everything together", "Bloom the yeast, mix dry ingredients", "Cut in the butter", "Mix the dough", "Laminating time—first fold", "Second fold", "Third and final fold", "Rest the dough", "Roll and trim", "Cut and shape pastry", "Egg wash, then proof the rolls", "Egg wash and bake the rolls", "Cool the rolls and enjoy!", "What else can I do with this dough?", "Advanced method", "Get your baking on!", "Inspiration"], "tips": ["Lamination time", "Cutting trick", "Need a break or out of time?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/croissants-for-beginners-getting-started-with-lamination"}, {"id": 761, "t": "From Zero to Ramen in Less Than 60 Minutes—Your Guide to Ramen Nirvana", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "There are a lot of recipes out there for ramen. How to make the broth, how to make noodles, how to make those gooey cured eggs—and we have those too. But here we will show you how to make it EPIC—from scratch, step-by-step—in less than 60 minutes! save Print", "i": ["Fresh ginger root , thinly sliced , as needed - Scallion(s) , fresh, thinly sliced , as needed - Ogo seaweed , rehydrated , as needed", "Scallion(s) , fresh, thinly sliced , as needed", "Ogo seaweed , rehydrated , as needed"], "s": ["Prep the big three", "Start with the cured eggs", "The noods", "Finally—it’s broth time", "Mise en place", "Fire! It’s service time!", "Check out some alternative flours for your noodles here", "Need some more things to throw in your bowl?", "If you liked this timeline guidance—check out this one"], "tips": ["Garnishes first"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/from-zero-to-ramen-in-less-than-60-minutes-your-guide-to-ramen-nirvana"}, {"id": 762, "t": "Super Umami Ramen Broth in Less Than 20 Minutes", "c": "Baking", "d": "How do you turn only a few cheap vegetables into an umami-packed ramen broth in less than 20 minutes? Turns out you need two things—a pressure cooker and a high pH level. This flavor-packed broth is transformed with the addition of a household ingredient you might have never thought to use outside of baking—baking soda. The addition of baking soda increases Maillard reactions, darkening the broth ", "i": ["120 g Soy sauce", "30 g Kombu", "125 g Scallion(s)", "100 g Fresh ginger root", "30 g Garlic , cloves", "2 kg Water", "5 g Baking soda", "85 g Shiitake mushrooms", "Chicken wings , optional for chicken ramen broth , as needed", "Pork spareribs , or meaty pork bones, optional for pork ramen broth , as needed", "50 g Mirin , optional for miso broth", "50 g White miso paste , optional for miso broth"], "s": ["Video Overview", "Prepare your broth base", "Add additional inclusions (optional)", "Cook the broth", "Strain and serve", "What do I do now?", "Other broths we love to pressure cook"], "tips": ["How Do Pressure Cookers Work?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/super-umami-ramen-broth-in-less-than-20-minutes"}, {"id": 763, "t": "Chewy Ramen Noodles", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Where does ramen get that famous chew and stretch from? You might think it’s some rare type of flour or some technique you could never master at home, but you’d be wrong. You probably have everything you need in your pantry to make these stretchy noodles right now. The thing that makes ramen noodles different than any other kind of noodle is that they are alkaline—this means they have a higher pH ", "i": ["140 g Water", "8 g Lye water , or baked baking soda", "4 g Kosher salt", "300 g Bread flour , unbleached", "9 g Bob’s Vital Wheat Gluten", "Cornstarch , for rolling noodles , as needed"], "s": ["Noodle Process: What It Looks Like", "How we developed this recipe", "Make your dry mix", "Make your wet mix", "Add your wet blend into your dry ingredients", "Knead the dough", "Let it rest", "Roll out the dough", "Cut your noodles", "Cooking your noodles"], "tips": ["The secret ingredient—lye water", "Don’t have lye water? No problem.", "Save those edge pieces", "Cutting noodles by hand", "Enjoy now or later?", "Love cold noodles?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/handmade-ramen-noodles-easier-than-you-think"}, {"id": 764, "t": "Slip’n & Slide’n Our Way to Alkaline Noodles Trials", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "We set out to make a super-easy, handmade ramen noodle at home. Along the way, we discovered that our formula was versatile enough to allow you to use almost any flour you might have on hand. They were all slightly different, but nearly every version was better than store-bought. So check out the trials and work we did here to make your homemade ramen noodles easier for you. save Print", "i": ["300 g Bread flour", "4 g Kosher salt", "8 g Lye water", "9 g Bob’s Vital Wheat Gluten", "140 g Water", "100 g Additional flour , sub the flour below here"], "s": ["Raising the pH", "The pH trials", "Here’s what we tried", "What we prefer", "The baked baking soda", "Lye water", "The flour trials", "The great subs", "Some awesome blends", "Whole wheat", "Buckwheat", "Corn masa", "Get started here on your ramen journey", "Check out these other dishes where baking soda is used to affect the pH"], "tips": ["Don’t have lye water? No problem.", "Love cold noodles?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/slip-n-slide-n-our-way-to-alkaline-noodles-trials"}, {"id": 765, "t": "Double Strawberry Toaster Oven Tarts", "c": "Baking", "d": "Rich fresh strawberries highlighted by bright freeze-dried strawberries inside a super flaky pastry—these are pop tarts on steroids. To get maximum strawberry flavor, we start with never cooked freezer jam and get an added boost from store-bought freeze-dried berries—all bundled up in flaky pie dough. The key to achieving the optimal flakiness is placing a very cold dough into a very hot oven with", "i": ["1 recipe Perfect Pie Dough , add the optional 38 g sugar", "300 g Freezer Jam: Why It’s the Real Jam , or any other jam", "30 g Freeze-dried strawberries , divided", "2 Egg(s) , 1 egg + 1 egg yolk for egg wash", "Powdered sugar , (optional 100 g for cream cheese icing)", "30 g Hot water", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Cold water , splash , as needed", "200 g Cream cheese", "80 g Butter , unsalted, softened", "10 g Vanilla bean paste"], "s": ["If you want epic oven tarts, simply put these two recipes together", "Roll out pie dough into an even sheet", "Make some egg wash", "Make icing", "Level up your icing game with cream cheese", "Cut shapes", "Dock the pastry", "Assemble the tarts", "Big crimpin’", "Get ’em really cold for maximum flaky layers", "Bake ’em", "Glaze ’em", "Enjoy and store"], "tips": ["Plain or iced?", "Flavor booster!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/double-strawberry-toaster-oven-tarts"}, {"id": 766, "t": "Love Chewy Candy But Feel Bad About It? Try Modernist Fruit Roll-Ups", "c": "Baking", "d": "Looking for better testing, and slightly healthier alternative to chewy candy? How about pulling out the juicer, getting creative with essential oils and making an insanely flavor-packed real fruit snack. Two things matter in the recipe. One, juicing the fruits removes fiber which concentrates the flavors and two, adding essential oils really punches up the flavor in way that is otherwise impossib", "i": ["300 g Clear fruit juice , from about 600 grams of fruit", "15 g Freezer pectin , 5%", "30 g Sugar , 10%", "10 drop Essential oil", "10 drop", "Grapeseed oil, as needed", "Fresh fruit , of your choice , as needed", "2 g Flake sea salt , optional", "2 g Malic acid", "10 drop Lemon essential oil", "100 g Mango , Peeled and diced", "150 g Strawberries , Washed and hulled", "10 drop Grapefruit essential oil"], "s": ["Prepare fruit", "Get the most out of your juice", "Let juice settle and decant the flavorful stuff", "Dry blend pectin and sugar", "Add dry mix and essential oils, then disperse", "drop", "Let it be", "Dive deeper into essential oils", "Prep your pan", "Dehydrate it—it’s almost a roll-up now!", "Remove from dehydrator", "Peel away and package", "Get creative or try a variation below!", "Carrot Mandarin", "Sour Apple Ginger", "Strawberry Lemonade", "Tropical Fruit Punch", "Check out these other candy recipes", "Extra sweet tooth fun"], "tips": ["Maximize that fresh fruit flavor", "DEEP DIVE: Understanding pectin", "Make sure your pan is nice and level", "Use a spoon to help let the moisture escape", "Is it done yet? Let’s talk about time and temperature."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/love-chewy-candy-but-feel-bad-about-it-try-modernist-fruit-roll-ups"}, {"id": 767, "t": "How To Turn Jam Into Fresh Fruit Roll-Ups", "c": "Baking", "d": "Wish candy was tastier? Wish fruit was naughtier? You can actually have both. All you need is jam and a couple of tricks. This is as simple as, well, jam. Take your favorite jam, purée it, strain it and dehydrate it for a spell and you will end up with some tasty fruit leather. But you may want to level it up along the way. To take it a step further and get creative—use fresh juice and essential o", "i": ["300 g Freezer Jam: Why It’s the Real Jam , or any other jam", "1 g Citric acid , optional", "Grapeseed oil, as needed", "20 g Alcohol of choice , optional"], "s": ["Choose your jam", "Blend it", "“Cast” the jam", "Spread and dehydrate", "Portion and package", "Ready to get creative and seriously level it up?"], "tips": ["Not all jams are created equal", "Season it with acid and... a little booze?", "Is it done yet? Let’s talk about time and temperature."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-turn-jam-into-fresh-fruit-roll-ups"}, {"id": 768, "t": "No-Egg Mayo From a Can of Beans", "c": "Baking", "d": "Mayonnaise from plants? Yep! No Eggs! Mayonnaise without eggs? Is that even possible? Yes, it is. You can make it yourself, and it will be just as silky-smooth as the grocery store version. Using a plain and simple can of chickpeas (garbanzo beans), you can transform their liquid into some tasty mayonnaise. So if you have a can of beans, some oil, and a blender, you can make mayo in no time. Some ", "i": ["Chickpeas , One can , as needed", "15 g Dijon mustard", "10 g White wine vinegar", "200 g Canola oil", "4 g Salt , kosher"], "s": ["Open can, strain, and reduce", "Whip that bean water", "Add helpers and some seasoning", "Slowly add oil", "Store it", "Starting from dried chickpeas?"], "tips": ["A note on seasoning"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/no-egg-mayo-from-a-can-of-beans"}, {"id": 769, "t": "What Do I Do With All This Kimchi???", "c": "Baking", "d": "We love kimchi and it’s great all by itself—but what else can you do with it? We asked ourselves this question after we ended up with SO MUCH KIMCHI leftover from developing our fermented kimchi recipe. Well, we started adding kimchi to damn near everything, and some of the results were pleasantly surprising. We’ve added a few of our favorite ideas from our experiments below—try them out and get i", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 recipe How to Make Kimchi at Home", "1 recipe How to Make Kimchi at Home"], "s": ["Dip chips into kimchi salsa", "Leverage the umami with a kimchi marinade", "Mellow it out into kimchi mayo", "Would you like fries with that kimchi ketchup?", "Level up salad with a kimchi dressing", "Drizzle the dressing"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-do-i-do-with-all-this-kimchi"}, {"id": 770, "t": "Our Favorite Ingredient Suppliers—Where ChefSteps Shops", "c": "Baking", "d": "For years you have been asking us where we buy our favorite products, and now seems like a good time to show you. To support you—and these companies—we compiled a list of our favorite food producers in one place. We have meats, seafood, produce, and pantry goods. Do you need more good coffee right now? We bet you do. Find out what we drink at the office. Cheese, charcuterie, and chocolate—we have ", "i": [], "s": ["Produce", "Meats & Poultry", "Seafood", "Cheese & Charcuterie", "Pantry Goods", "Coffee & Chocolate", "Where do you get the good stuff? Tell us in the comments below."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/our-favorite-ingredient-suppliers-where-chefsteps-shops"}, {"id": 771, "t": "The Control °Freak", "c": "Baking", "d": "It’s a commercial-grade induction burner with precise temperature control through a surface thermometer and a probe that you can put inside of the pan. Basically, it allows you to maintain a steady temperature in the pan or pot instead of dealing with the turning up and down that you end up doing to stay in the right temperature range on a regular burner. Since ChefSteps was acquired by Breville, ", "i": [], "s": ["Precision Temperatures", "Grant Actually Likes It"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-control-freak"}, {"id": 772, "t": "The Baking Hub", "c": "Baking", "d": "Baking is a measured process. Weigh the ingredients, make up your mise en place, and follow the directions. This clear path is what makes baking ideal for people who are new to the kitchen. (Little ones feel like they are bakers if they add that one egg and oil to the brownie mix.) If you follow the guidelines, and do what the recipe directs, that baked good will come out well. That’s because of s", "i": [], "s": ["It’s a good question.", "Can’t find bread flour at the store right now? We can help.", "Here are some classics—reinvented and refined.", "Make some simple cakes, frosted with science.", "It is still baking if you make it in the microwave.", "These are some serious cakes.", "Raise the roof.", "When you are ready to level up, tackle the macaron.", "Feel like baking some American classics?", "This one is Super American.", "Want to go down a rabbit hole? Conquer the canelé.", "Follow the laminated road.", "If you deep fry, they will come.", "Yes, Virginia, there are delicious gluten-free baked goods.", "Baking that does not require baking.", "Savory baking can be amazing.", "These are your basecamps for baking projects."], "tips": ["Stiff peaks!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-baking-hub"}, {"id": 773, "t": "How to Make Any Flour Into “Bread Flour”", "c": "Baking", "d": "There are no secrets here, only simple conversions. When you want high-gluten flour, you simply buy it. But if you have a small bag of vital wheat gluten on hand, you’ll most likely never run out bread flour again. We can’t tell you how to easily get the gluten out of your flour, but we can show you just how much gluten to add to your flour—take a look below. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Vital wheat gluten is a “dough improver,” it’s not magic", "The conversions—based on Bob’s Red Mill Vital Wheat Gluten (75% protein)"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-any-flour-into-bread-flour"}, {"id": 774, "t": "This Is What Happens When You Freeze Dry Everything", "c": "Baking", "d": "Freeze drying can yield fresh and unexpected flavors, bright colors, and crisp foods. So why is it hard to find freeze-dried foods in the store? Sure, freeze-dried fruit, Lucky Charms marshmallows and “space ice cream” are terrific, but they’re just the tip of the (freeze-dried) iceberg. We decided to freeze dry every food that interested us. Below, you’ll find all sorts of items not easily found ", "i": [], "s": ["What is freeze drying?", "THE GOOD", "THE BAD", "THE UN-TASTY", "ALL IN ALL—A GOOD TIME", "Want To Freeze-Dry More?", "Other Unexpected Results In Tools"], "tips": ["Understanding the role of water in cooking"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/this-is-what-happens-when-you-freeze-dry-everything"}, {"id": 775, "t": "Understanding the Role of Water in Cooking", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Managing water is often one of the biggest challenges in cooking. Concentrating a sauce’s flavor requires evaporation. Without freezing, there is no ice cream. Distilling spirits? That requires condensing. You cannot spread butter on hot toast without some melting. Want to avoid freezer burn? You need deposition. To make bright food last for a long time—sublimation. Understand the phases of water ", "i": [], "s": ["Master the Phase Change", "Evaporation matters for concentrated flavor", "Condensation matters for boozy sprits", "Freezing matters for super-smooth ice cream", "Melting matters for an instant release of flavor", "Deposition matters for avoiding freezer burn", "Sublimation matters for freeze drying", "Other fun kitchen science bits..."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/understanding-the-role-of-water-in-cooking"}, {"id": 776, "t": "French Fries: Achieve the Holy Grail of Air Frying", "c": "Baking", "d": "For a couple of days here at ChefSteps, we did some really difficult work. We ate a lot of french fries together to ensure we could figure out the best batch size and timing to make french fries in your countertop oven on the air fry setting. Sure, you can make your own fries—we taught you how in this recipe—but unless you want to measure the initial water content and sugar content in the potatoes", "i": [], "s": ["TLDR: Which trial won?", "Setting the benchmark", "Different batch sizes", "Results of the batch-size trials", "Frozen or thawed?", "Multiple racks?", "Cook times", "What did we learn about time?", "What about temperature?", "Extras", "In conclusion"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/french-fries-achieve-the-holy-grail-of-air-frying"}, {"id": 777, "t": "Microwaved Scrambled Eggs", "c": "Baking", "d": "We heard you. After we published Microwave Frenzy, many of you requested a recipe specifically for the eggs. Here you go. Microwave ovens might be the best method for making scrambled eggs because the cooking that happens in them is super localized. The microwaves that are at work in your microwave oven are small, targeted, and follow precise patterns. Whisked eggs are a massive liquid. When you c", "i": ["170 g Egg(s) , 3 large", "14 g 2% milk , just a splash, but optional.", "28 g Butter , unsalted"], "s": ["Watch this to understand how microwaves work", "Watch this to see how we cooked the eggs in the microwave", "Crack your eggs", "Mix them all together", "Cook it up", "Want to cook more food in your microwave?"], "tips": ["A note on adding milk and butter"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/microwaved-scrambled-eggs"}, {"id": 778, "t": "How to Malt Your Own Grains", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Raise your hand if you hear the word “malt” and think of beer or whiskey. Yes, malting—the process of controlled germination and drying of grain—is an important process in making beer and thus grain alcohol like whiskey because you create the enzyme amylase. Malting grains makes them a bit sweeter, softer, more savory—this is good news for your food! The key steps are simple, hydrate the grain, le", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 200 g Whole emmer farro 1000 ml Filtered water", "200 g Whole emmer farro 1000 ml Filtered water", "200 g Whole emmer farro", "1000 ml Filtered water", "Cold water, as needed"], "s": ["Learn how to malt grains so you can make this umami risotto", "Hydrate", "Germinate", "On rinsing", "Dehydrate"], "tips": ["Upgrade! Cold smoke them for a real Scotch taste", "Optional: Remove the culms"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-malt-your-own-grains"}, {"id": 779, "t": "Umami Risotto", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "This umami risotto is a scraping dish—your spoon scrapes against the bowl repeatedly, searching for one more bite. Together, everything in this risotto tastes smoky from the malted emmer to the cheesy, sweet flavor from the slices of apples and the fresh and green from the herbs. You need to make this. Our chef Matthew Woolen first made this when he worked at The Old Sage, a Seattle Scotch bar wit", "i": ["180 g How to Malt Your Own Grains , divided", "130 g Onion(s) , about half an onion", "80 g Olive oil , divided", "8 g Salt , kosher", "1.2 kg Stock", "75 g White wine , or hard cider", "20 g Comté cheese , plus extra for garnish", "30 g Butter , unsalted", "10 g Herbs , parsley and chives", "Apple(s) , for garnish , as needed", "10 g Roasted malted emmer powder - Stock, as needed"], "s": ["Before you make the risotto, you have to malt the grains", "Make roasted malt powder", "Sweat the onions", "Heat the stock", "Add the grains and alcohol", "Add the first liquid addition", "Add more stock and malt powder", "Finish the risotto"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/umami-risotto"}, {"id": 780, "t": "How to Make a Sourdough Starter", "c": "Baking", "d": "What is the benefit of using a sourdough starter to leaven bread instead of just using store-bought yeast? Well, it’s complicated… but the short answer is flavor. There are really two halves to the yeasted bread family tree—quick or instant rise bread (anywhere from 30 minutes to a few hours) and slow/fermented bread (anywhere from 24 hours to weeks). Adding the yeast from a packet directly to dou", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Bread flour , or any other flour you want to use , as needed - Water, as needed", "Bread flour , or any other flour you want to use , as needed - Water, as needed", "Water, as needed"], "s": ["Keys to getting started", "Day one", "Start the starter", "Day two", "Feed the starter", "Feed the starter for the next five days", "Test the sourdough starter before you use it", "One storage option—the refrigerator", "Another storage option—freeze it", "How to wake up your frozen starter", "Use the old dough"], "tips": ["How much starter should I make?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/make-a-sourdough-starter-it-s-not-that-hard"}, {"id": 781, "t": "Knife Skills", "c": "Baking", "d": "Being confident with a knife is far more important than having camera-ready skills. Sure, it’s impressive to be able to brunoise carrots, quickly. But you don’t need rapid-fire movements to make a good meal. Stop stressing about perfection. Time to practice. Need a dish to practice your knife skills? Start by mincing a shallot, and then try our hand-chopped steak tartare. Sure, some chefs put the ", "i": [], "s": ["This is a knife", "This is how they work", "This is where you can buy the best of them", "This is the basic skill that will help you with all others", "But you should know how to sharpen a knife first...", "For mass slicing, you may want a mandoline.", "Ok, ready. Your first challenge is...", "And your second challenge will be...", "And if you think you are ready for it, well—here’s a doozy...", "Now you’re in the club, so we’ll show you ours", "Want to level up your steak cutting game—2x BONUS CHALLENGE!", "Also, how to use a sword", "Okay...we’ll admit that this one went too far."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/knife-skills"}, {"id": 782, "t": "The Bread Universe", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "We want to help you bake bread. Here at ChefSteps, we have worked over the years to create recipes for breads—brioche; bagels; and buttermilk biscuits—that are bullet-proof and predictable. You can count on our bread recipes. Why bake bread? Bread has been a fundamental food foundation of humanity for thousands of years. Making bread is pretty inexpensive. The process of putting together ingredien", "i": [], "s": ["No Bread Flour? This might help.", "Quick, yeasted, and tender bread", "Yeasty and enriched with butter", "Slow, chewy, and lean", "Quick, chewy, and lean", "Rich, easy, and on the sweeter side... and maybe not even bread", "Bread for breakfast?!", "What can I put on it?", "What else can I make with it?", "Rising stars in the bread universe—recipes from the ChefSteps community", "What else should I know?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-bread-universe"}, {"id": 783, "t": "French Country Bread in One Day", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is the technique you should use to achieve a country bread full of flavor, with an airy crumb and crisp crust, in less than one day. Once you make this no-knead bread, you are going to want to make more. Jim Lahey’s method is solid since it is based on trial and error in his bakery. This technique delivers. (That’s why everyone and their friends have a version of it on their blogs.) I have ch", "i": ["400 g Bread flour", "300 g Water", "3 g Active dry yeast", "4 g Salt", "20 g Sugar", "Cornmeal, as needed"], "s": ["Gather your ingredients", "Activate the yeast", "Your yeast is ready when it looks like this", "Add the yeast mixture to the flour", "Add the salt", "Mix the dough", "Cover and let rest", "After 24 hours, it should look like this", "Get ready to shape the bread dough", "Portion, if needed", "Shape your dough", "Prep a banneton", "Whaaaaat? You don’t have a banneton?", "Get the dough into the banneton", "It should look like this", "Proof the dough", "Make sure you cover it", "Preheat your oven and Dutch oven to 482 °F / 250 °C", "Dutch oven or a baking stone?", "Time to transfer the dough!", "Place the baking paper on the dough", "Add the cardboard", "Press the cardboard onto the banneton", "Then, flip it over", "And, carefully remove your banneton. Voilà!", "Baking—here is the game plan", "Baking the bread—phase one", "Baking the bread—phase two", "Let cool to slice", "This recipe made faster at a glance", "Want bread faster or easier breads to make, look no further.", "Have extra time?", "Want to know how baking really works, here you go!"], "tips": ["UPGRADE—Autolyze?", "What the heck is a “crumb?”", "Use your pizza peel"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/french-country-bread-in-one-day"}, {"id": 784, "t": "Scratch English Muffins, Slow and Classic", "c": "Baking", "d": "This is a straightforward, classic English muffin recipe. The goal here is maximum nooks and crannies. In order to get them, we take the slow approach to resting the dough, resting the muffins before cooking, and using a fork (never a knife) to split them open. The best result comes from lots of resting, up to 24 to 48 hours. But if you scroll to the end of the activity below, you will see the res", "i": ["450 g Bread flour", "450 g Milk", "40 g Sugar", "10 g Active dry yeast", "10 g Salt", "Cornmeal, as needed"], "s": ["Get your ingredients together", "Mix the dough", "Let sit overnight", "It should look like molten dough lava", "Prep a tray (or two) for portioning", "Portion them", "Optional tidying", "Once portioned, sprinkle some cornmeal on top", "Cut (or tear) parchment paper for each portion", "Griddle them!", "For maximum nooks and crannies use a fork to open!", "Toast and enjoy!", "IN CASE YOU ARE WONDERING..."], "tips": ["On “nooks and crannies”", "Flip tip"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/scratch-english-muffins-slow-and-classic"}, {"id": 785, "t": "Cocktails!", "c": "Baking", "d": "ChefSteps has been mixing drinks since 2014. Until we put all the recipes together into one activity, we had forgotten how many cocktail recipes we have made over the years. Hmm, maybe we shouldn’t think about the relationship between those things too much. While we always love a classic Manhattan, we also like to push the limits and try new techniques with our cocktails. Have you ever carbonated ", "i": [], "s": ["Dark and Rich", "Vegetal and Refreshing", "Somewhere In-Between", "Take the edge off with dairy", "Inners", "Toppers", "Level It Up With A Whipping Siphon", "Skip the Booze", "Eat the Booze", "Cheers!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cocktails"}, {"id": 786, "t": "Anzac Biscuits", "c": "Baking", "d": "For those of you who don’t know, ChefSteps is now part of the Breville family. And if you didn’t know, Breville is an Australian company. I have already learned so much about Aussie food and culture. Tim Tam biscuits, vegemite toast, flat whites, fairy bread, sausage rolls, and Anzac biscuits. I love the history of these biscuits too, the name Anzac is really A.N.Z.A.C. (Australian and New Zealand", "i": ["8 g Baking soda", "15 g Water , (to dissolve baking soda)", "125 g Butter", "35 g Lyle’s Golden Syrup", "100 g Sugar", "85 g Rolled oats", "40 g Sweetened shredded coconut", "150 g All-purpose flour"], "s": ["It started with a family recipe", "Scale your ingredients up front", "Preheat the oven to 375 °F / 191 °C", "Dissolve baking soda into the water in a small glass", "Brown butter and add golden syrup in a large pan", "Add baking soda to butter and stir until foaming subsides", "Mix in all dry ingredients", "Roll into balls", "Bake for seven minutes...or eight, or nine", "Observe the thin wafers of gold", "Try these other yummy cookies!"], "tips": ["Brown the butter and cook out all the baking soda"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/anzac-biscuits"}, {"id": 787, "t": "Pasta", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "It’s your time. Make some homemade pasta tonight. Homemade pasta is always a good choice. First of all, pasta requires minimal ingredients: flour, water, and salt. If you want to venture off into more complex directions, you can add eggs or olive oil. That’s it. Secondly, if you invest a little time and energy into making pasta, you can make some incredible meals. This is a simple, cheap, and ther", "i": [], "s": ["The Pastas", "The Pasta Dishes", "The Pasta Sauces"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pasta"}, {"id": 788, "t": "Gnudi—more flavor, more tender, made better.", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Some people believe that gnudi are difficult to make tender, light, and fluffy. Well, that’s because—for some reason—everyone has been telling you to make gnudi with high protein pasta or bread flour. Why? Rather than try to answer that question, I tried to answer the root question. How do you get a super tender gnudi that’s also easy to make? The answer came quickly. One, get rid of any extra tou", "i": ["450 g Ricotta cheese", "45 g Egg yolk(s)", "150 g Cake flour", "10 g Salt"], "s": ["Press the water out of the ricotta", "Make your gnudi dough", "Roll and cut them into actual gnudi", "Boil those buggers", "My favorite sauce for these gnudi", "Here are some more sauce ideas:"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/gnudi-more-flavor-more-tender-made-better"}, {"id": 789, "t": "The Secret to Mastering Croissants at Home", "c": "Baking", "d": "The secret to a great croissant? It’s the perfect amount of layers. Croissants are a marriage of bread and butter. Golden crust and dozens of lighter-than-air layers that crunch down into one exquisite, buttery bite. This is the dream of bakers. To get those layers, professional bakers rely on machines that cost $10,000 to 30,000—but we will make them by hand. There are two secrets to great croiss", "i": ["308 g Water , warm", "120 g Milk , whole", "10 g Instant dry yeast", "14 g Diastatic malt powder", "710 g Bread flour , divided", "60 g Sugar", "16 g Salt , kosher", "63 g Butter , soft, for dough", "Egg wash, as needed"], "s": ["Day One: Make the dough", "The sponge", "The dough", "Day Two: Lamination", "Roll out the dough", "The butter block", "The lamination", "Day Three: Shape, proof, and bake", "Roll, cut, and shape", "Egg wash and proof", "Bake the croissants"], "tips": ["Whoa! What’s all this “Day One” stuff? Don’t have three days, try this recipe instead.", "Folds and math", "Stop here (if you want to)", "A note on scaling"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-secret-to-mastering-croissants-at-home"}, {"id": 790, "t": "If Croissants and Cinnamon Rolls Had a Baby ...", "c": "Baking", "d": "Combine the flaky, buttery nature of croissants and the chewy brown sugar goodness of a cinnamon roll, and what do you have? This delight. Our chef Matthew Woolen was doing some research and development for the croissant recipe. (Translation: Everyone on staff, aside from Matthew and another staff member who must eat gluten-free, ate warm croissants for lunch for days.) In all that baking, he foun", "i": ["200 g Brown sugar", "12 g Cinnamon , ground", "2 g Salt", "0.5 recipe The Secret to Mastering Croissants at Home", "400 g Cream cheese", "160 g Butter , softened", "200 g Confectioners’ sugar", "20 g Vanilla bean paste", "0.5 recipe All About Laminated Doughs"], "s": ["Make the filling", "Roll out the dough", "0.5 recipe", "Spread the butter and filling", "Roll up the log of dough", "Cut the dough into rolls", "Stop here or move on", "Proof the cinnamon rolls", "Make the icing", "Preheat the oven", "Bake the rolls", "Ice the rolls"], "tips": ["Tip: Baking Dish"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/if-croissants-and-cinnamon-rolls-had-a-baby"}, {"id": 791, "t": "Red Cabbage With Koji", "c": "Baking", "d": "Turn on the broiler. You are going to cook up wedges of red cabbage until they are charred and toasty at the edges, then toss them with a creamy koji dressing. This simple technique might be one of the most deeply flavored vegetable dishes you have tried. Some beginner cooks are afraid of burning their food, so they pull it out from under the broiler when the dish is barely warm. Chefs? We love fr", "i": ["800 g Red cabbage , about 1 head", "100 g Creamy koji", "40 g Lemon juice , about 1", "28 g Scallion(s) , about 2", "15 g Black sesame seeds", "Salt , kosher, , as needed", "Black pepper , ground , as needed", "Canola oil, as needed"], "s": ["Make the koji dressing", "Wash and prepare the cabbage", "Preheat the broiler", "Season the cabbage", "Broil the cabbage", "Chop and toss the cabbage with dressing"], "tips": ["What is koji?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/red-cabbage-with-koji"}, {"id": 792, "t": "Countertop Ovens – Small but Mighty", "c": "Baking", "d": "Power-to-Volume ratio. This is why you want to use a countertop oven. How much power do you have to heat all that metal, air and food? And how much power do you have to create efficient airflow so you have faster, more even cooking? Home appliances are limited to the power that comes out of the wall, so if you want more performance, you might consider a smaller oven. Let’s think about cars for a m", "i": [], "s": ["Smaller and shinier = quicker heating", "Temperature precision", "Smaller oven = better performance"], "tips": ["Really want to go precise? Go sous vide."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/countertop-ovens-small-but-mighty"}, {"id": 793, "t": "Types of Heat", "c": "Drink", "d": "Three types of heat cook your food in an oven: convection, thermal radiation, and conduction. We experience these three types of heat every day— convection makes a cold day with a breeze feel colder, thermal radiation warms us when we stand in front of a roaring fire, and conduction warms our hands when we hold a hot mug of coffee. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Convection", "Thermal Radiation", "Conduction", "Against Cooking: Evaporative Cooling, Reflection, and Insulation", "Air as Insulation", "Evaporative Cooling", "Reflection and Absorption"], "tips": ["Meat Math"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/types-of-heat"}, {"id": 794, "t": "On Humidity and Cooking–How and When to Use It.", "c": "Baking", "d": "Guess what? All your favorite foods are mostly made up of water. In fact, they range from about 75 percent water in meats to 90 to 95 percent water in fruits and vegetables. Want to know something else? Water is arguably the most important factor in most cooking processes—and you can’t even see it. For example, a boost of humidity when you bake bread lets the dough puff and spring and create a lig", "i": [], "s": ["When high humidity is not a good thing.", "When high humidity is a good thing.", "When you want lots of humidity only at the beginning of cooking.", "When you want no humidity at the beginning of cooking.", "When you want varying levels of humidity throughout the cooking.", "Do ovens control humidity for you?", "Wet-bulb temperature and humidity.", "Wet food: Why it’s all about the surface of your food.", "TIPS AND TRICKS – Managing Humidity"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/on-humidity-and-cooking-how-and-when-to-use-it"}, {"id": 795, "t": "What Is Baking?", "c": "Baking", "d": "There is evidence that humans began baking bread over 14,000 years ago, but the oldest ovens discovered are only about 6500 years, so was the first bread even baked? In fact, the word bake originally comes from the word bhõg in the prehistoric Indo-European protolanguage. It meant “to dry something out inside of an oven.” And were those folks baking bread? Nope. They were baking bricks in those ea", "i": [], "s": ["What happens in the process of baking?", "How can you become a better baker?", "What to bake in your countertop oven"], "tips": ["Baking vs. Roasting"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-is-baking"}, {"id": 796, "t": "Strawberry Shortcake Soufflé", "c": "Baking", "d": "Soufflés seem complicated to those who have rarely made them. The medium glossy peaks of meringue sometimes intimidate people and cause them to turn away from the task of making a soufflé. We can show you—with science and clear guidelines—how to give yourself the gift of this elevated dessert. Making a soufflé will never be as simple as opening a carton of ice cream for dessert. However, once you ", "i": ["10 g Unsalted butter , for the ramekins", "108 g Sugar , divided, plus extra for the ramekins", "140 g Heavy cream", "34 g Bread flour", "12 g Vanilla bean paste", "4 g Salt , kosher", "65 g Egg yolk(s) , about 4 eggs", "132 g Egg white(s) , about 4 eggs"], "s": ["Preheat the oven", "Prepare the molds", "Cook the soufflé base", "Add the egg yolks", "Whip the meringue", "Marry the meringue and base", "Fill the ramekins", "Clean the edges of the ramekins", "Bake the soufflés", "Garnish the soufflés"], "tips": ["Baker’s tip"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/strawberry-shortcake-souffle"}, {"id": 797, "t": "What Is Roasting?", "c": "Meat", "d": "Picture this—a pig on a spit, slowly turning over a hot fire. Someone is sitting by the fire, manually turning the handle to make that pig go around and around so it does not burn. As the pig roasts, the fat glistens and spits into the flames, the skin browns golden to tawny brown to dark pecan, and the warm aroma drifts through the room. Now that is a roast. Can you get the same kind of intense r", "i": [], "s": ["What is roasting?", "Roasting fundamentals", "Traditional roasting inspiration", "Oven roasting inspiration"], "tips": ["Baking versus roasting"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-is-roasting"}, {"id": 798, "t": "Oven-Roasted Honey Apples & Pears", "c": "Baking", "d": "We love giving you the science of cooking and insights into new ingredients. However, sometimes we like to offer you delicious food without a lot of fuss. Roasting pears and apples with honey and thyme transform them into something sublime yet versatile. Here’s what you need to know. Cooking the fruit at just the right temperature promises a nice caramelization and a sliceable toothy texture. Too ", "i": ["300 g Apple(s) , about 1 large, we used Cosmic Crisp", "245 g Pears , about 1 large", "1 g Thyme", "3 g Flake sea salt", "10 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "Black peppercorns, as needed", "16 g Honey"], "s": ["Slice and season the fruit", "Put the apples and pears on a sheet pan and drizzle the honey", "Roast the fruit", "Do more with apples"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/oven-roasted-honey-apples-pears"}, {"id": 799, "t": "What Is Broiling?", "c": "Baking", "d": "For many home cooks, the broiler might as well be just be referred to as “the cheese-melter.” And that’s a shame, because there’s much, much more to broiling than making a tasty tuna melt. When used correctly, the broil function on home ovens offers so many practical uses, from getting that coveted char on meats and vegetables usually only achievable with outdoor, high-temperature grills to super-", "i": [], "s": ["What is broiling?", "How broilers work", "Best practices"], "tips": ["Finding the “sweet spot”"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-is-broiling"}, {"id": 800, "t": "Blackened Broccolini", "c": "Baking", "d": "You might have a habit of roasting trays of vegetables in the winter. Keep it up. Those root vegetables are hearty and delightful to have in the refrigerator any time you want. However, if you want a cooking method that brings you crunch and bright greens in the midst of winter, broil some broccolini. Broiling uses high heat to cook vegetables faster than roasting can. Roasting broccolini means th", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 290 g Broccolini , one bunch - Canola oil, as needed - Salt , kosher , as needed - Black pepper, as needed - Lemon, as needed", "290 g Broccolini , one bunch - Canola oil, as needed - Salt , kosher , as needed - Black pepper, as needed - Lemon, as needed", "Canola oil, as needed", "Salt , kosher , as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "Lemon, as needed"], "s": ["Preheat the broiler", "Wash, trim, and season", "Put the broccolini under the broiler", "Jazz up the broccolini"], "tips": ["What oil should I use for charring vegetables?", "How do I prevent too much steaming?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/blackened-ini-broccolini"}, {"id": 801, "t": "What Is Slow Cooking?", "c": "Baking", "d": "Low and slow—that’s the tempo. “Slow cooking” is a bit of a general term, as it can go by many names—pot roasting, braising, or stewing. Technically, these are all different forms of slow cooking (differentiated by their varying amounts of moisture) but all with the same goal in mind: to break down tough cuts of meat and turn them into something tender and delicious using low temperatures and long", "i": [], "s": ["The science of slow cooking", "The slow cooking automated function", "Best practices"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-is-slow-cooking"}, {"id": 802, "t": "Charred Lettuces Will Blow Your Mind", "c": "Baking", "d": "You will never think of lettuce the same way again. Lettuces are 95 percent water, so they’re a perfect candidate for broiling. The leaves on the top, closest to the broiler, start to desiccate as they char. The water exudes from the lettuce and starts the self-steaming transformation of the lettuce. The char transforms the texture of the top of the lettuce, which means the final result is soft, s", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 280 g Lettuce , whole head - Canola oil, as needed - Salt , kosher , as needed - Black pepper, as needed - Dressing , of your choice , as needed", "280 g Lettuce , whole head - Canola oil, as needed - Salt , kosher , as needed - Black pepper, as needed - Dressing , of your choice , as needed", "Canola oil, as needed", "Salt , kosher , as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "Dressing , of your choice , as needed"], "s": ["Preheat the broiler", "Prepare the lettuce", "Season and cook", "Chop and dress the lettuce", "What to serve with your charred lettuce"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/charred-lettuces-will-blow-your-mind"}, {"id": 803, "t": "Vegetable Jerky", "c": "Baking", "d": "We wanted to create a textural experience similar to beef jerky with some of our favorite vegetables instead. Initially, we ran trials brining the vegetables with calcium oxide, which we hoped would give the surface an interesting texture and dried-out look. However, that did not improve the texture of the jerky. We stopped going that direction. Instead, we tried the classic route of using a simpl", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 2 Bell pepper(s) , 1 yellow, 1 red 4 Carrot(s) 1 Yams 2 Daikon radish , red 1 Eggplant 4 Beet(s) , 2 red, 2 yellow 2 Portobello mushrooms", "2 Bell pepper(s) , 1 yellow, 1 red 4 Carrot(s) 1 Yams 2 Daikon radish , red 1 Eggplant 4 Beet(s) , 2 red, 2 yellow 2 Portobello mushrooms", "4 Carrot(s)", "1 Yams", "2 Daikon radish , red", "1 Eggplant", "4 Beet(s) , 2 red, 2 yellow", "2 Portobello mushrooms", "3 kg Water", "90 g Salt", "90 g Sugar", "Filtered water, as needed"], "s": ["Make brine", "Prep the vegetables", "Decide the shape and size of the jerky you want", "Brine the vegetables", "Roast the vegetables", "Dehydrate the vegetables", "Rehydrate the vegetables", "Want more vegetables?"], "tips": ["Seasoning your jerky"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vegetable-jerky"}, {"id": 804, "t": "What Is Dehydration?", "c": "Baking", "d": "Long before we had access to modern machines—with a controlled heat source and electric fans—humans have been drying food. In fact, humans began changing from a constant hunter-gatherer mode to settling down into communities as soon as they discovered how to preserve food. Being able to save some food for later meant that humans could begin to live in one spot and form villages. There is evidence ", "i": [], "s": ["What is dehydration?", "How to dehydrate"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-is-dehydration"}, {"id": 805, "t": "Stones, Salt, and Steels", "c": "Baking", "d": "There are so many ways to get heat from the source that’s making it into the food you are cooking. Pots, pans, and baking sheets are the standard. But what about some of the other more fun things you can do to get heat into food. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["The baking steel and the pizza stone", "Stones, as in actual stones", "It's a slate of mind.", "Put a salt crust on it"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/stones-salt-and-steels"}, {"id": 806, "t": "How to Make Kimchi at Home", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you don’t like kimchi, this recipe might change your mind. If you like eating kimchi, this recipe will blow your mind. What a lot of kimchi recipes don’t have or don’t at least mention is this—it is ready to eat within minutes, you can eat it fresh the same day and it's amazing. But if you make a lot, and pick at it from the fridge over time, it will ferment and develop deeper, more nuanced (an", "i": ["1.2 kg Napa cabbage", "120 g Daikon radish", "24 g Garlic", "48 g Shallot(s)", "72 g Fresh ginger root", "84 g Carrot(s)", "36 g Scallion(s)", "12 g Fresno chile(s)", "36 g Salt", "150 g Filtered water", "12 g Sugar , 2%, optional", "48 g Korean chile flakes (gochugaru)", "72 g Ginger , 6%"], "s": ["Adding the right amount of salt is key.", "Gather all the ingredients and clean the equipment", "Prepare and clean the vegetables", "Blend and make the brine", "Toss the cabbage", "Rest the cabbage overnight", "Pack the cabbage into jars", "Weigh down the cabbage", "Tidy up the jars", "Close the jars and start fermenting", "Monitor the fermentation activity", "Decide when the kimchi is done", "Use that kimchi to transform your condiment game", "Don’t have a week? Make this kimchi."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-make-kimchi-at-home"}, {"id": 807, "t": "It’s a Salt Crust Frenzy! From Fruits and Veg to Meats and More", "c": "Baking", "d": "Salt crusting meat, vegetables, fish, and fruit makes each one of those foods interesting and delicious in new ways. Plus, it’s fun! While the practice of serving salt-crusted whole fish has fallen out of trend in American restaurants, this remains a cooking technique worth exploring. Packing food with a paste made of salt, liquid, and other binders creates a shell that seals in heat, moisture, an", "i": [], "s": ["Before we begin: The Salt Crust Trials", "Make the salt mix", "Make the salt igloo", "Baking with a salt crust", "Saltwater branzino", "Sunchokes", "Cheese", "Pineapple", "Red daikon radish", "Cabbage", "Yukon Gold potatoes", "Golden beets", "Whole chicken", "In conclusion ..."], "tips": ["What is a flax “egg”?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/do-you-even-salt-crust-bro"}, {"id": 808, "t": "Sous Vide Italian Meatballs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Do Nonna proud and make some meatballs! Our recipe is a comfort-food classic, combining ground beef and pork with a fragrant mixture of herbs and spices. And the texture? Mamma mia! Fork-tender and practically begging to be slathered in tomato sauce, we’ll understand if you pile them dangerously high on your plate of pasta. save Print", "i": ["100 g Baguette(s)", "400 g Milk , whole", "160 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "10 g Garlic , minced", "10 g Black pepper", "4 g Chile flakes", "5 g Coriander seeds", "7 g Cinnamon", "10 g Fennel seeds , whole", "10 g Marjoram , fresh, 1-2 sprigs", "15 g Flat-leaf parsley", "500 g Ground pork", "500 g Ground beef", "15 g Kosher salt", "50 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "75 g Egg(s) , whole"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Soak the baguette", "Prep your flavoring ingredients", "Make the meatball mixture", "Shape the meatballs and add to bag", "Cook sous vide", "Serve them up"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/meatballs--3"}, {"id": 809, "t": "Sauces Engineered for Sous Vide, Curated for You", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Wondering what to make for dinner? We have more than a month’s worth of easy weeknight meals for you here. Each of the sauces we have created—deeply flavored curries; French mother sauces; and sauces with flavors from around the world—are optimized to be a sous vide sauce. Make the sauce, sous vide your protein in it, and put together a couple of sides while you wait. Dinner is ready. All the sauc", "i": [], "s": ["Before we begin", "Better with beef", "Pretty with poultry", "Fine with fish/Super with seafood/Optimized for the ocean", "Playful with pork"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sauces-engineered-for-sous-vide-curated-for-you"}, {"id": 810, "t": "Steak With Périgord Black Truffle Sauce Over Mashed Potatoes and Roasted Carrots", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with an opulent sauce—earthy, glossy, and filled with truffles—that we pair with steak, pomme purée, and roasted carrots. Our truffle sauce—inspired by the flavors of black Perigord truffles from France—packs a rich punch, with fresh truffles chopped and folded in, and the sauce emulsified with a truffle-infused olive oil. It’s decadent. Simply place the protein—in this case, stea", "i": ["120 g Black Truffle Butter Sous Vide Sauce", "Olive oil , as needed , as needed", "2 Steak(s) , such as New York, ribeye, or tenderloin, about 450 grams", "732 g Carrot(s) , about 6 large", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "1 Lemon , large", "1.5 kg Yukon Gold potato(es) , about 8 large", "65 g Cream", "75 g Butter", "Herbs , fresh—such as parsley, tarragon, or chives, for garnish as needed , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the steaks", "Bag it up and start cooking", "Make the roasted carrots", "Make the mashed potatoes", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/steak-with-perigord-black-truffle-sauce-over-mashed-potatoes-and-roasted-carrots"}, {"id": 811, "t": "Black Truffle Butter Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This is a steakhouse sauce, one that drapes a dish on the expensive end of the menu. Imagine a rich sauce, thick and full of deep flavors, filled and finished with fresh black truffles. This is decadent celebration food. Sure, you could make this sauce for steak—we recommend a ribeye—and no one would complain. However, this sauce works atop roasted tofu as well. (Try it. You will believe us.) Driz", "i": ["20 g Butter , unsalted", "10 g Shallot(s) , minced", "3 g Garlic , cloves, chopped", "152 g Vegetable stock", "26 g Black truffle juice", "45 g Black truffle oil", "15 g Knox gelatin", "6 g Kosher salt", "1 g Xanthan gum"], "s": ["Make this meal with your sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Thicken the sauce", "Add the magic and season the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/black-truffle-butter-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 812, "t": "Teppanyaki Steak Over Rice With Steamed Bok Choy", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a bright sauce—acidic, zingy, and with a depth of umami—that we pair with steak, rice, and steamed bok choy. The term Teppanyaki refers to the act of cooking food quickly over a hot griddle. This cooking method not only spawned a lot of great Japanese steakhouses—including the American chain, Benihana—but deeply flavored sauces for cooking and dipping. With ginger, soy sauce,", "i": ["150 g Teppanyaki Sous Vide Sauce", "Olive oil, as needed", "450 g Steak(s)", "448 g Water", "Kosher salt, as needed", "235 g Short-grain rice", "170 g Baby bok choy , whole", "5 - Shiitake mushrooms , sliced , as needed", "Pickled ginger , for garnish , as needed", "Toasted sesame seeds , for garnish , as needed", "100 g Green onion(s) , bunch, thinly sliced, for garnish", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the steaks", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the rice", "Braise the bok choy", "Sauté the mushrooms", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/teppanyaki-steak-over-rice-with-steamed-bok-choy"}, {"id": 813, "t": "Teppanyaki Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This bright acidic sauce—with the depth of umami and the zing of ginger—is a perfect partner to a steak. Teppanyaki refers to the act of cooking food quickly over a hot griddle. This Japanese cooking style favors deft knife skills, rapid cooking, and big flavors in the sauces. (You might have eaten Teppanyaki style if you have ever eaten at a Benihana restaurant, which entered the American market ", "i": ["36 g Butter , unsalted", "22 g Shallot(s) , minced", "53 g Shiitake mushrooms , rough chopped", "41 g Ginger , peeled and chopped", "45 g Shaohshing rice wine", "55 g Low-sodium soy sauce", "5 g Wright’s hickory liquid smoke", "8 g White wine vinegar", "60 g Demi-glace", "14 g Sugar", "1 g Xanthan gum", "31 g Lemon juice", "13 g Sesame seeds , toasted", "5 g Wright’s applewood liquid smoke", "13 g Toasted sesame seeds"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook your vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/teppanyaki-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 814, "t": "Meatball Pomodoro Over Fusilli Corti Bucati With Fresh Basil, Parmesan, and Mushrooms", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a marinara sauce—garlicky; a bit smoky from roasted tomatoes; full of big flavor—that we pair with meatballs, fusili, and mushrooms. Our fire-roasted tomato marinara has the flavors of the slow-simmered tomato sauce in a big pot on the stove, but in far less time. It has a sweet balsamic punch, the earthy taste of roasted mushrooms, and basil. We think Nonna would approve. Si", "i": ["400 g Fire-Roasted Tomato Marinara Sous Vide Sauce", "8 Sous Vide Italian Meatballs , preformed, 8 to 16 ounces", "Olive oil, as needed", "6 Shiitake mushrooms , , sliced", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "454 g Fusilli pasta , (or other pasta of choice)", "Basil , for garnish , as needed", "Parmesan , for garnish , as needed", "400 g Fire-Roasted Tomato Marinara Sous Vide Sauce 8 Sous Vide Italian Meatballs , preformed, 8–16 oz", "Water, as needed 454 g Fusilli pasta , (or other pasta of choice)"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Sauté mushrooms", "Prepare your noodles", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/meatball-pomodoro-over-fusilli-corti-bucati-with-fresh-basil-parmesan-and-mushrooms"}, {"id": 815, "t": "Fire-Roasted Tomato Marinara Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "There’s nothing like a slow-simmered tomato sauce in a big pot, the aromas wafting through the room and making everyone hungry for giant meatballs on top of pasta. That sauce dripping off the meat and onto the fork—now that is a good Sunday supper. Want those flavors a little more quickly? Put the meatballs into the sauce to cook them sous vide and have those flavors of marinara and meatballs ming", "i": ["8 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , minced", "300 g Crushed tomatoes , Fire roasted san Mariano brand", "41 g Balsamic vinegar", "17 g Sugar", "4 g Marjoram", "1 g Black peppercorns , ground", "8 g Salt , kosher", "16 g Basil"], "s": ["Make this meal with your sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fire-roasted-tomato-marinara-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 816, "t": "New York Strip With Red Wine Beef Demi-Glace, Thick-Cut Steak Fries, and a Wedge Salad", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a decadent sauce—beefy, buttery, and full of umami—that we pair with a New York strip cooked rare, steak fries, and a wedge salad. Red wine demi-glace is a traditional French sauce, full-bodied with beef stock, butter, shallots, tomato paste, and red wine reduced by more than half in volume, then simmered with all of this to make a hearty sauce you want to slurp. Simply put t", "i": ["120 g Red Wine Demi-Glace Sous Vide Sauce", "Olive oil , as needed , as needed", "450 g Steak(s)", "513 g Russet potato(es) , cut into wedges", "200 g Canola oil , cup (you can use the leftover oil from the potatoes)", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "22 g Thyme , or rosemary, small bunch (optional)", "30 g Garlic clove(s) , smashed (optional)", "257 g Milk", "75 g Shallot(s) , about 3, thinly sliced", "150 g Bacon", "350 g Iceberg lettuce , head, cleaned and trimmed", "150 g Red onion(s) , thinly sliced", "Cherry tomatoes , sliced, as needed , as needed", "Dill fronds , as needed , as needed", "Ranch dressing , as needed , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the steaks", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the steak fries", "Make the crispy shallots", "Make the wedge salad", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/new-york-strip-with-red-wine-beef-demi-glace-thick-cut-steak-fries-and-a-wedge-salad"}, {"id": 817, "t": "Red Wine Demi-Glace Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Red wine demi-glace is a traditional French sauce, full-bodied with beef stock, butter, shallots, tomato paste, and red wine reduced by more than half in volume, then simmered with all of this to make a hearty sauce you want to slurp. This is traditionally a sauce for beef, akin to Bordelaise, so we have paired it with a rare New York strip with steak fries and a wedge salad. Imagine having a grea", "i": ["36 g Butter , unsalted", "25 g Shallot(s)", "62 g Red wine reduction , red wine reduced by 50%", "70 g Bragg liquid aminos", "110 g Beef Stock , or veal stock", "10 g Black garlic", "1 g Xanthan gum", "1 g Thyme", "18 g Sugar", "15 g Knox gelatin"], "s": ["Make this sauce with this meal", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/red-wine-demi-glace-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 818, "t": "Beef Short Rib Goulash Over Egg Noodles With Grilled Peppers and Sour Cream", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a goulash sauce—hearty, a bit heated, and full of depth—that pairs with short ribs, egg noodles, and grilled peppers with sour cream. Our goulash sauce—a play on the traditional Hungarian stew—has the sweet heat of paprika and the unexpected umami of black garlic, with the taste of tomatoes and garlic. This sauce will stick to your ribs. Simply add the protein—in this case, s", "i": ["454 g English-cut beef short ribs , about 8 oz each", "1 Neutral oil , tbsp", "200 g Winter Goulash Sous Vide Sauce", "314 Baby sweet bell peppers , or whole bell peppers", "25 g Olive oil", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "1 Lemon", "340 g Egg noodles , 1 package (or other pasta of choice)", "Sour cream , as needed , as needed", "Fresh herbs , such as parsley, as needed , as needed", "Smoked paprika (hot/picante) , as needed , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the protein", "Bag it up and start cooking", "Make the grilled sweet peppers", "Prepare your noodles", "Plate and serve", "Bonus: Make spaetzle"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface", "Cover for long cooks"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-short-rib-goulash-over-egg-noodles-with-grilled-peppers-and-sour-cream"}, {"id": 819, "t": "Winter Goulash Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Make this goulash sauce today to make a hearty meal without having to wait for the stew to braise in the oven. Goulash has a humble beginning. Hundreds of years ago, cowherds in Hungary, in bands of five or six men, roamed the plains, following cows in their meandering fashion. These men cooked meals for themselves in big cauldrons, based on whatever they had at hand: lard, onions, grains, salt, a", "i": ["10 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "75 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "15 g Black garlic", "22 g Tomato paste", "145 g Crushed canned tomato", "100 g Demi-glace , savory choice", "4 g Sugar", "20 g Paprika", "4 g Caraway seeds , toasted and ground", "1 g Oregano", "8 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/winter-goulash-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 820, "t": "Steak au Poivre With Creamy Mashed Potatoes and Steamed Rapini", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a sauce—peppery, beefy, and aromatic with brandy—that we pair with a New York steak served with mashed potatoes and rapini. This classic French sauce usually requires a dense layer of peppercorns, which forms a crust when you sear the steak. We made it easier for you by including three kinds of peppercorns in the sauce, along with brandy, mushrooms, and cream. Simply place th", "i": ["120 g Au Poivre Sous Vide Sauce", "Olive oil , as needed for searing , as needed", "450 g Steak(s)", "400 g Yukon Gold potato(es)", "100 g Cream", "150 g Butter", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "400 g Rapini", "Chile flakes , to taste , as needed", "112 g Water"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the steaks", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the mashed potatoes", "Steam the rapini", "0.5 cup", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/steak-au-poivre-with-creamy-mashed-potatoes-and-steamed-rapini--2"}, {"id": 821, "t": "Au Poivre Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Imagine the taste of a deeply flavored mushroom and demi-glace sauce drizzled slowly over a peppercorn-crusted steak. Each bite is a wave of flavors: brandy, cream, beef, and the spike of three different kinds of pepper. We have made this easy for you. This classic French sauce usually requires the labor of crusting a steak with a dense layer of peppercorns, which forms a crust when you sear the s", "i": ["55 g Butter , unsalted", "81 g Shallot(s)", "8 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "110 g Crimini Mushrooms , sliced", "36 g Sherry vinegar", "13 g Dijon mustard", "57 g Demi-glace , savory choice", "6 g Worcestershire sauce", "41 g Sour cream", "83 g Water", "10 g Brandy", "5 g Knox gelatin", "5 g Kosher salt", "2 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG)", "1 g Xanthan gum", "1 g Thyme", "35 g Green peppercorns", "1 g Szechuan pepper , coarse ground", "5 g Black peppercorns , coarse ground", "5 g White pepper , coarse ground", "2 g Italian parsley , dried"], "s": ["Make this sauce with this meal", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Thicken the sauce", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/au-poivre-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 822, "t": "Spicy Miso Sesame Chicken Thigh With Broccoli Over Udon", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a flavor bomb of a sauce—hot, zingy, and full of umami depth—that we pair with chicken thighs, udon noodles, and broccoli. This sauce has the funkiness of miso, the warmth of sesame oil, and the zing of ginger, folded in with the nuttiness of tahini and the fruity numbing heat of Szechuan peppercorns. You will want this sauce again and again. Just put the chicken into a bag w", "i": ["150 g Spicy Miso Sesame Sous Vide Sauce", "12 g Neutral oil", "450 g Chicken thighs", "300 g Broccoli , or broccolini", "112 g Water", "269 g Udon noodles", "Black sesame seeds , as needed , as needed", "Green onion(s) , as needed , as needed", "Chile oil , as needed , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the chicken", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Steam the broccoli", "Prepare your noodles", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spicy-miso-sesame-chicken-thigh-with-broccoli-over-udon"}, {"id": 823, "t": "Spicy Miso Sesame Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Have you ever felt like everything in the world would be manageable if you only had a big bowl of slippery noodles coated in a spicy, warm sauce full of depth and sweetness? Here you go. This spicy miso sesame sauce has so many incredible ingredients together, yet it is so easy to make. We have done all that playing-with-our-food work for you. This sauce has the funky saltiness of miso, the warmth", "i": ["55 g Butter , unsalted", "25 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "4 g Ginger , peeled, chopped", "4 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "116 g Vegetable stock", "14 g White miso paste", "72 g Tahini", "40 g Creamy koji", "5 g Rice vinegar", "33 g Sesame oil", "5 g Chile oil", "17 g Sugar", "2 g Szechuan pepper , fine ground", "2 g Star anise , ground", "8 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spicy-miso-sesame-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 824, "t": "Good Gravy Chicken Breast Over Gnocchi With Roasted Carrots and Herb Oil", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a good gravy—rich, thick, and silky smooth—that we pair with chicken breast, gnocchi, and roasted carrots with herb oil. Our gravy—which happens to be gluten-free—builds flavor with butter, butternut squash, carrots, and chicken stock. It tastes both bright with vegetables and warm with the onions and thyme. This is a cozy weeknight sauce. Just place the chicken in a bag with", "i": ["450 g Chicken breast(s)", "12 g Neutral oil", "200 g Good Gravy Sous Vide Sauce", "24 g Olive oil , as needed", "732 g Carrot(s)", "1 Lemon , whole", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "482 g Gnocchi , about 1 package (find in the freezer section or pasta aisle)", "86 g Parsley", "2 Tbsp. Olive oil 6 Carrot(s) , whole 1 Lemon , whole - Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the chicken", "Tbsp.", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the roasted carrots", "Prepare the gnocchi", "Make the herb oil", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/good-gravy-chicken-breast-over-gnocchi-with-roasted-carrots-and-herb-oil"}, {"id": 825, "t": "Good Gravy Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Think about good gravy—rich with flavor, thick, silky smooth and sliding over mashed potatoes. Now think about the process of making it. Certainly, it’s not that difficult to cook once you know how to do it, but gravy usually involves making a roux, building that flavor, and whisking and whisking to make sure there are no lumps. This gravy? So much easier than that. This rich gravy is the sous vid", "i": ["40 g Butter , unsalted", "25 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "28 g Celery , chopped", "95 g Butternut squash , peeled, grated", "25 g Carrots , peeled, grated", "1 g Black peppercorns , course ground", "165 g Chicken stock", "15 g Potato starch , bobs", "10 g Kosher salt", "1 g Thyme", "1 g Xanthan gum"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Thicken the sauce and season"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/good-gravy-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 826, "t": "Thai Green Curry Chicken Over Rice With Roasted Eggplant and Sweet Pepper-Herb Salad", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a green curry sauce—sour, sweet, and hot—that pairs with chicken breast over rice with grilled eggplant and a pepper-herb salad. Our sauce—an adaptation a traditional Thai green curry— has a zing, with vivid tastes from the vibrant spices and flavors of lemongrass, garlic, ginger, and Thai bird chiles. It also contains most of the strong, rich flavors of green curry in far le", "i": ["250 g Quick Thai Green Curry Sous Vide Sauce", "18 g Neutral oil , as needed", "450 g Chicken breast(s)", "336 g Water , for rice", "Kosher salt, as needed", "235 g Short-grain rice", "240 g Red bell pepper(s)", "100 g Cilantro , small bunch", "52 g Mint , small bunch", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "Lime juice , from half a lime (optional) , as needed", "Olive oil , to taste , as needed", "350 g Eggplant , small (Chinese or Japanese)", "1 Lemon"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the chicken", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the rice", "Make the pepper-herb salad", "Grill the eggplant", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/thai-green-curry-chicken-over-rice-with-roasted-eggplant-and-sweet-pepper-herb-salad"}, {"id": 827, "t": "Quick Thai Green Curry Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This green curry sauce is sour, sweet, salty, and hot. It has a zing, with vivid tastes from the vibrant spices and flavors of lemongrass, garlic, ginger, and Thai basil. An even more complex green curry than this one requires more ingredients and time. However, this sauce has most of the strong, rich flavors of green curry in far less time than the original takes. Pair it with our chicken over ri", "i": ["14 g Lemongrass , sliced thin", "8 g Thai chile(s) , green ones", "60 g Dates , rough chop", "42 g Fresh ginger root", "46 g Scallion(s)", "46 g Garlic clove(s)", "100 g Coconut milk", "50 g Cilantro", "30 g Thai basil", "22 g Fresh mint", "6 g Lime leaves", "52 g Bragg liquid aminos", "8 g Fish sauce", "400 g Coconut cream", "54 g Fresh lime juice", "26 g Kosher salt", "34 g Sugar", "2 g Xanthan gum , optional"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Blend your paste", "Toast your paste", "Add the liquids", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": ["Can I skip the toasting step?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/quick-thai-green-curry-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 828, "t": "Chicken Panang Curry Over Rice With Sautéed Sugar Snap Peas, Fresh Cilantro, and Lime", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a creamy curry sauce—bright, vibrant, and slightly sweet—that we pair with chicken breasts, rice, and sautéed sugar snap peas. Our panang curry—a play on the traditional Thai suace—uses cashews for a mild nuttiness, lemongrass and lime for bright acidity, and coconut milk for creaminess. This sauce is an easy way to bathe mild proteins and vegetables in full, intense flavors.", "i": ["200 g Panang Curry Sous Vide Sauce", "450 g Chicken breast(s)", "24 g Neutral oil", "336 g Water , for rice", "Kosher salt, as needed", "235 g Short-grain rice", "226 g Sugar snap peas", "Chopped mint , for garnish , as needed", "Chopped cilantro , for garnish , as needed", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "1 Lime , cut into wedges for garnish"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the protein", "Bag it up and start cooking", "Make the rice", "Sauté snap peas", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-panang-curry-over-rice-with-sauteed-sugar-snap-peas-fresh-cilantro-and-lime"}, {"id": 829, "t": "Panang Curry Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Thai panang curry sauce is slightly sweet, bright and vibrant with lemongrass and lime leaves, and the mildest of all the Thai curries. This is a new, quick take on Thai panang curry. Traditionally, panang curry uses boiled or roasted peanuts with a touch of nutmeg, which is where the mild sweetness emerges. Here, we use cashews for an even milder flavor. Double plus? The cashews help to thicken t", "i": ["40 g Raw cashews , chopped", "15 g Ginger , peeled, chopped", "19 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "2 g Lime leaves", "3 g Lemongrass , chopped", "20 g Fresno chile(s) , chopped", "72 g Coconut cream", "145 g Coconut milk", "42 g Red bell pepper(s) , seeded and chopped", "5 g Galangal root , peeled and ground to a paste", "8 g Kosher salt", "1 g Toasted ground coriander", "28 g Sugar"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Put it all in a pot", "Blend it up", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/panang-curry-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 830, "t": "Adobo Chicken Thighs With Jasmine Rice and Bok Choy", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a tangy sauce—with a hint of sweet, heat, and umami depth—that we pair with chicken thighs, rice, and braised bok choy. Our take on adobo sauce—the ubiquitous dish of the Philippines—relies on the enticing blend of vinegar, soy sauce, and the creaminess of coconut milk. It has an incredible depth of flavor that surprises and satisfies. Just put the protein—in this case, chick", "i": ["200 g Tangy Adobo Sous Vide Sauce", "12 g Neutral oil", "450 g Chicken thighs", "448 g Water", "Kosher salt , as needed , as needed", "235 g Jasmine rice", "170 g Baby bok choy", "1 Green onion(s) , bunch, sliced", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the chicken", "Bag it up", "Make the rice", "Braise the bok choy", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/adobo-chicken-thighs-with-jasmine-rice-and-bok-choy"}, {"id": 831, "t": "Tangy Adobo Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This enticing, tangy Filipino sauce is pretty hard to resist. This sauce is a blend of cultures through time, more of a cooking process than a recipe. The first settlers of the Philippines—the Malays—braised meat and poultry in vinegar and salt to preserve it. The wave of Chinese settlers after added soy sauce to the mix. It was the Spaniards who named it, since they were taken with the vinegar fl", "i": ["28 g Coconut oil (refined)", "160 g Sweet onion(s)", "16 g Garlic clove(s)", "1 g Bay leaf", "2 g Chile flakes", "3 g Black peppercorns", "40 g Distilled vinegar", "80 g Soy sauce", "181 g Coconut milk", "26 g Light brown sugar", "2 g Xanthan gum , optional", "40 g Distilled vinegar 80 - Soy sauce, as needed 181 - Coconut milk, as needed"], "s": ["Make this meal with tangy adobo sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tangy-adobo-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 832, "t": "Muhamarra Grilled Chicken With Couscous and Sweet Pepper-Herb Salad", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a creamy sauce—vibrantly colored; a little sweet; a bit of heat—that we pair with grilled chicken, couscous, and a fresh herb-pepper salad. Our Muhamarra sauce—our play on the thick Syrian dip for a mezze platter— is an incredible mix of flavors, like pomegranate molasses, walnuts, and Aleppo pepper. This sauce is pretty irresistible. Put the protein—in this case, chicken—int", "i": ["450 g Chicken breast(s)", "Olive oil , as needed , as needed", "200 g Muhamarra Sous Vide Sauce", "150 g Israeli couscous", "Water, as needed", "Salt and pepper , as needed , as needed", "240 g Red bell pepper(s)", "100 g Cilantro", "52 g Mint", "1 Lemon"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the chicken", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make couscous", "Make sweet pepper-herb salad", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/muhumarra-grilled-chicken-with-couscous-and-sweet-pepper-herb-salad"}, {"id": 833, "t": "Muhamarra Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This spicy, nutty sauce will make even the plainest of meals into a south-east Mediterranean feast. Muhamarra, a thick dip meant for a mezze platter, originated in Syria. This ancient culture prizes the time around the table highly. Dinner might last hours, after women have been in the kitchen together, cooking and talking, for hours before that. And with food influences from France and the Ottoma", "i": ["71 g Walnuts , raw, crushed", "100 g Water", "4 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "8 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "8 g Sugar", "165 g Roasted red peppers , drained, chopped", "3 g Aleppo pepper", "4 g Cumin seeds", "30 g Pomegranate molasses", "6 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Simmer all the ingredients", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/muhumarra-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 834, "t": "Barbecue Chicken Thighs With Lettuce, Grilled Scallions, and Steamed Rice", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a spicy citrus barbecue sauce—sweet, savory, and acidic—that we pair with chicken thighs, rice, and grilled scallions. Our citrus barbecue sauce—created with the Korean spice gochujang and dipping sauce ssamjang—has a swirl of heat from chiles and garlic, pungent flavor from fermented soybeans and sesame, and a little sweetness from honey and sugar. Once you taste this dark s", "i": ["200 g Spicy Citrus BBQ Sous Vide Sauce", "Neutral oil , as needed for searing , as needed", "900 g Chicken thighs , about 8-12 oz", "336 g Water", "Kosher salt, as needed", "235 g Short-grain rice", "100 g Green onion(s)", "Sesame seeds, as needed", "330 g Green leaf lettuce , one head", "Salt and pepper, as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the protein", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the rice", "Char the green onions", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/barbecue-chicken-thighs-with-lettuce-grilled-scallions-and-steamed-rice"}, {"id": 835, "t": "Spicy Citrus BBQ Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This thick, sticky barbecue sauce will make your meal memorable. The sauce takes its flavors from the Korean spice paste, gochujang, and a Korean dipping sauce called ssamjang. These ingredients make the final barbecue sauce a swirl of heat from chiles and garlic, pungent from fermented soybeans and sesame, and a little sweet from honey and sugar. Once you taste this dark sauce, concentrated in it", "i": ["15 g Sesame oil", "50 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "9 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "21 g Fresh ginger root , minced", "120 g Low-sodium soy sauce", "90 g Water", "41 g Gochujang", "12 g Ssamjang", "79 g Sugar", "1 g Xanthan gum , optional", "8 g Sesame seeds", "10 g Chives , sliced fine", "5 g Lime zest", "5 g Orange zest"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spicy-citrus-bbq-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 836, "t": "Chicken Tikka Masala Over Rice With Sweet Onion and Fresh Herbs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal offers a creamy sauce—spicy, slightly sweet, and complex in taste—with chicken, fluffy rice, and a refreshing onion-herb salad. Our tikka masala sauce—the British play on an Indian chicken dish—has a buttery tomato gravy feeling, with not-too-hot spices and plenty of enticing aromatics, like ginger, garlic, cumin, and dried curry leaves. You will want more. Simply put the protein—in this", "i": ["200 g Tikka Masala Sous Vide Sauce", "18 g Neutral oil", "900 g Chicken thighs", "336 g Water", "Kosher salt, as needed", "235 g Short-grain rice", "175 g Sweet onion(s)", "3.5 g Mint , fresh leaves", "10 g Cilantro leaves and thin stems", "1 g Cumin seeds , whole", "20 g Lime juice", "Black pepper , freshly ground , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the chicken", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the rice", "Make sweet onion and herb salad", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface", "Bonus: Make some naan"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chicken-tikka-masala-over-rice-with-sweet-onion-and-fresh-herbs--2"}, {"id": 837, "t": "Tikka Masala Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This tikka masala sauce, suited for cooking meat sous vide, is a play on Britain’s most popular sauce. Stories vary as to where this creamy spicy-sweet sauce originated, but the most common story seems to be that a Bangladeshi chef in Scotland changed his chicken tikka—chicken pieces marinated in yogurt, cooked on a skewer—to be milder by adding a creamy tomato sauce. (That matched the customer’s ", "i": ["175 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "20 g Butter , unsalted", "10 g Fresh ginger root , peeled and diced", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "60 g Tomato paste", "156 g Heavy cream", "32 g Light brown sugar", "16 g Tikka massala spice mix , World Spice Seattle", "2 g Cumin seeds", "15 g Curry leaves , fresh", "10 g Kosher salt", "20 g Lemon juice"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Char the onions", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the tomato paste", "Add the liquids and blend", "Season the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tikka-masala-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 838, "t": "Curried Chicken Thigh Over Rice With Roasted Carrots", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a creamy curry sauce—warm, tangy, and slightly spicy—that we pair with chicken thighs over rice with roasted carrots. Our Vadouvan sauce—a take on the French-fusion version of masala in India—has the warmth of turmeric, cardamom, cumin and fenugreek, plus the unexpected sweetness of cloves and nutmeg, all with a touch of heat. This sauce is a blend of the expected and surpris", "i": ["140 g Quick Vadouvan Curry Sous Vide Sauce", "450 g Chicken thighs", "Olive oil, as needed", "336 g Water", "Kosher salt, as needed", "235 g Short-grain rice", "732 g Carrot(s)", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "1 Lemon", "1 Lime(s)", "100 g Cilantro", "1 Lime(s) 1 Cilantro , small bunch, optional for garnish"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the chicken", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Get your oven ready", "Make the rice", "Make the roasted carrots", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/curried-chicken-thigh-over-rice-with-roasted-carrots"}, {"id": 839, "t": "Quick Vadouvan Curry Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This quick Vadouvan curry sauce has a warmth, heat, and inherent sweetness that make it irresistible. Pre-made curry powder blends can feel like a shortcut that erases the authenticity of the country from which they come. We acknowledge that. However, we have found that a Vadouvan curry blend can be quite good, a fully-acknowledged fusion that doesn’t claim to be typically Indian. (We especially l", "i": ["16 g Butter , unsalted", "46 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "13 g Vadouvan curry spice , world spice market", "121 g Plain Greek-style full-fat yogurt", "85 g Bulgarian buttermilk", "90 g Vegetable stock", "10 g Fresh lime juice", "15 g Sugar", "10 g Kosher salt", "1 g Xanthan gum"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/quick-vadouvan-curry-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 840, "t": "Creamy Carrot Cod Over Quinoa With Sweet Pepper-Herb Salad", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a sauce—creamy, redolent of carrots and coconut, and smooth—that we pair with red quinoa and a sweet pepper-herb salad. Our carrot-coconut sauce has the satisfying zing of carrot-ginger soup, with a hint of the brandy bitterness of vermouth, and the citrusy heat of Aleppo pepper. This is a bright sauce, comforting on a cold day. Just put the protein—in this case, cod—into a b", "i": ["450 g Fillets of fish (we like black cod)", "120 g Carrot & Coconut Cream Sous Vide Sauce", "230 g Red quinoa", "448 g Water", "450 g Red bell pepper(s)", "100 g Cilantro", "52 g Mint", "1 Lemon", "Olive oil , to taste , as needed", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make quinoa", "Make sweet pepper-herb salad", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/creamy-carrot-cod-over-quinoa-with-sweet-pepper-herb-salad"}, {"id": 841, "t": "Carrot & Coconut Cream Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "We have paired gently cooked carrots with the creaminess of coconut milk—plus a bit of heat—to make this sauce well-rounded in the mouth. Carrots and coconut milk pair with each other beautifully, since they both have some inherent sweetness. This sauce has the satisfying zing of carrot-ginger soup, with a hint of the brandy bitterness of vermouth, and the citrusy heat of Aleppo pepper. This is a ", "i": ["10 g Sweet vermouth", "210 g Coconut milk", "6 g Kosher salt", "100 g Carrot(s) , pureed", "20 g Fresh ginger root , diced", "25 g Coconut oil (refined)", "3 g Chile flakes", "3 g Aleppo pepper , flakes", "10 g Sugar", "1 g Xanthan gum"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Simmer the ingredients", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/carrot-coconut-cream-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 842, "t": "Cod Beurre Blanc With Mashed Potatoes and Green Beans", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Since lemon beurre blanc is traditionally paired with fish, we created this bright, acidic sauce to allow you to sous vide cod in it, then pair it with mashed potatoes and green beans. This classic French butter sauce has lots of bright, lip-smacking lemon, with a touch of koji for sweetness and umami. It’s creamy, acidic, and will be gone from your plate soon. You can pair it with any kind of fis", "i": ["450 g Fillets of cod", "120 g Lemon Beurre Blanc Sous Vide Sauce", "397 g Yukon Gold potato(es)", "99 g Cream", "150 g Butter", "Kosher salt , to taste , as needed", "Black pepper , to taste , as needed", "227 g Green beans", "2 Lemon wedges , as needed for garnish", "Chopped fresh dill , (or other herbs) for garnish , as needed", "2 Lemon wedges - Chopped fresh dill , (or other herbs) for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the mashed potatoes", "Blanch the green beans", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cod-beurre-blanc-with-mashed-potatoes-and-green-beans--2"}, {"id": 843, "t": "Lemon Beurre Blanc Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This lemon beurre blanc sauce comes together easily and adds a level of sour-smooth creaminess to fish or chicken. The story goes that Clémence Lefeuvre, a female chef in Nantes, France, invented lemon beurre blanc—at the beginning of the 20th century—when she forgot to add the eggs to her béarnaise sauce. And thus, this delicious, light lemony sauce was born. (Hm. We are a little dubious about th", "i": ["82 g Butter , unsalted, divided in two steps", "25 g Shallot(s)", "5 g Kosher salt", "228 g Vegetable stock", "21 g White wine vinegar", "19 g Creamy koji", "20 g Water", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , minced", "White pepper, as needed", "10 g Lemon juice", "3 g Lemon zest", "1.5 g Xanthan gum"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids", "Blend the sauce and thicken", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/lemon-beurre-blanc-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 844, "t": "Spicy Banana Spaghetti With Sausage, Cherry Tomatoes, and Oregano", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal offers a banana ketchup sauce—spicy, a little sweet, and still made with tomatoes—with sausage, spaghetti, and cherry tomatoes. Our zingy banana ketchup sauce is a play on the popular Filipino ketchup invented when there was a shortage of tomatoes during World War II. It has an unexpected flavor for spaghetti: sour with vinegar, zingy with ginger, spicy with chilis, with a depth of flavo", "i": ["200 g Spicy Banana Ketchup Sous Vide Sauce", "12 g Neutral oil", "450 g Pork sausage(s)", "454 g Spaghetti , dried", "300 g Cherry tomatoes", "20 g Oregano , fresh", "Salt and pepper, as needed", "Salt , for pasta water , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the sausages", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make spaghetti", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spicy-banana-spaghetti-with-sausage-cherry-tomatoes-and-oregano"}, {"id": 845, "t": "Spicy Banana Ketchup Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "If you have never eaten the Filipino banana ketchup sauce, you are in for a treat here. This ubiquitous dish of the Philippines was created out of an urgent need, as is true for so many good foods. During World War II, the country experienced a radical shortage of tomatoes and tomato paste. Someone ingenious—a food scientist named María Orosa—decided to use an ingredient plentiful in the Philippin", "i": ["10 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "64 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "3 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "20 g Fresh ginger root , peeled and minced fine", "0.8 g Allspice", "6 g Chipotle chile powder , seeded and ground", "41 g Tomato paste", "14 g Soy sauce", "65 g Water", "10 g Distilled vinegar", "24 g Light brown sugar", "1 g Xanthan gum", "6 g Salt , kosher", "136 g Banana(s) , peeled, ripe"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the tomato paste", "Add the liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/spicy-banana-ketchup-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 846, "t": "Adobo Pork Chops Over Rice With Grilled Green Onions, Fresh Cilantro, and Lime", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a thick sauce—deeply spiced with chiles; the suggestion of nuttiness; and a bit of chocolate—that we pair with pork chops, rice, and grilled green onions. You might know adobo only as the sauce in which chipotles are stored in a can. Nothing wrong with that flavor, but adobo is so much more than sauce in a can. This sauce has smoky depth, a lot of full flavor from beef stock ", "i": ["200 g Ancho Chile Adobo Sous Vide Sauce", "Olive oil, as needed", "450 g Pork chop(s)", "336 g Water", "Kosher salt, as needed", "235 g Short-grain rice", "110 g Green onion(s)", "Cilantro , chopped , as needed", "Lime(s) , ½, cut into wedges , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the pork", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the rice", "Char the green onions", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface", "Bonus: Make tamales"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/adobo-pork-chops-over-rice-with-grilled-green-onions-fresh-cilantro-and-lime"}, {"id": 847, "t": "Ancho Chile Adobo Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "You might know adobo sauce only as the thick, deeply spiced sauce in which chipotles are stored in a can. Nothing wrong with that flavor. However, adobo sauce is so much more than sauce in a can. This sauce has smoky depth, a lot of full flavor from beef stock and canned tomatoes, a kick from a blend of chiles and spices, and the surprise of dark chocolate. Once you make this sauce, you will want ", "i": ["63 g Sweet onion(s)", "11 g Coconut oil (refined)", "2 g Garlic clove(s)", "225 g Beef Stock , or veal stock", "63 g Canned crushed tomatoes , blended", "3 g Wright’s applewood liquid smoke", "13 g Kosher salt", "1 g Cumin seeds", "1 g Fennel seeds", "2 g Cinnamon", "2 g Oregano", "34 g Ancho chile(s) , dried", "4 g Chipotle chile powder , ground", "33 g Sugar", "1 g Xanthan gum", "94 g 58% bittersweet chocolate pistoles", "1 g Toasted sesame seeds"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids", "Add the spices", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ancho-chile-adobo-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 848, "t": "Overnight Pork Barbacoa Tacos With Beans and Salsa", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a spicy sauce—rich with different chiles; warm with cinnamon; and earthy with cumin—that we pair with pork you sous vide overnight, rice, and slow-simmered beans. Our barbacoa sauce—a quicker version of the traditional Mexican barbecue sauce— is loaded with fragrant ground chilies—chipotle, pasilla, and guajillo—adds depth to a rich chicken stock, which balances the sauce’s h", "i": ["454 g Pork shoulder", "200 g Barbacoa Sous Vide Sauce", "2 cup Black beans , dried, soaked overnight in the fridge", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "2 cup Short-grain rice", "3 cup Water", "16 Baby sweet bell peppers", "25 g Olive oil", "1 Lemon", "6 Corn tortillas", "Salsas , for garnish , as needed", "Avocado(s) , for garnish , as needed", "Cilantro , for garnish , as needed", "Lime(s) , for garnish , as needed", "Green onion(s) , for garnish , as needed", "2 cup Short-grain rice 3 cup Water", "16 Baby sweet bell peppers 25 g Olive oil - Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed 1 Lemon"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Heat sous vide bath", "Choose the perfect pork shoulder", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the beans", "Make the rice", "Make the grilled sweet peppers", "Heat the tortillas", "“Pull” that pork in the bag", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/overnight-pork-barbacoa-tacos-with-beans-and-salsa"}, {"id": 849, "t": "Barbacoa Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This fiery tomato sauce, with cinnamon and cumin, is a complex barbecue sauce you will want to keep eating. Traditional barbacoa, as it is made in Mexico, involves roasting an entire sheep in a giant fire pit, wrapped in maguey leaves, then cooked for days and days. It’s the ultimate low and slow process, a gorgeous celebration of the meat, but one not easily replicable in American kitchens. This ", "i": ["20 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "65 g Sweet onion(s)", "50 g Tomato paste", "207 g Chicken stock", "23 g Sugar", "13 g Pasilla chile(s) , seeded and ground", "13 g Guajillo chile(s) , seeded and ground", "1 g Cinnamon , ground", "2 g Cumin seeds , ground", "2 g Chipotle chile powder , seeded and ground", "2 g Oregano", "12 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/barbacoa-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 850, "t": "Chamoy Pork Chop Tacos With Apricot-Tomato Salsa", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a dark sauce—sour, sweet, and a little pickled—that pairs with pork chop tacos with apricot salsa. Our chamoy sauce—a play on the salty chile candies from Mexico—is spiked with ancho chiles and softened with chopped apricots, then finished with a hit of refreshing lime zest. Walk away to make our apricot-tomato salsa. Heat up the tortillas. Dinner. Just place the pork chops i", "i": ["200 g Salsa Chamoy Sous Vide Sauce", "450 g Pork chop(s)", "18 g Neutral oil , as needed", "148 g Apricot(s) , about 2, or substitute 1 peach or 1 nectarine", "116 g Beefsteak tomato , about 1", "79 g Sweet onion(s) , about ½ onion", "110 g Jalapeño(s) , seeds removed", "21 g Cilantro", "1.5 g Lime , (from 1 lime)", "40 g Lime juice", "6 Tortillas , corn, 4–6 as needed", "Salt , pinch , as needed", "6 Corn tortillas , 4-6 as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the pork chops", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the fruit and tomato salsa", "Heat the tortillas", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chamoy-pork-chop-tacos-with-apricot-tomato-salsa"}, {"id": 851, "t": "Salsa Chamoy Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Chamoy sauce might be new to you but it won’t be for long. Make this sauce once and you’re going to want to make it again and again. Originally—and still for most people—chamoy comes in the form of Mexican candy, a sour-sweet pickled salty candy with some heat from chiles. Only recently have chefs begun to play with that combination of flavors, taking the intoxicating combination from candy aisles", "i": ["7 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "60 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "5 g Garlic clove(s) , minced", "66 g Dried apricots , chopped", "160 g Water", "20 g Ancho chile(s) , seeded and ground", "4 g Chipotle chile powder", "90 g Sugar", "12 g Kosher salt", "1 g Xanthan gum , optional", "3 g Lime zest", "50 g Fresh lime juice"], "s": ["Make this meal with the chamoy sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquid and fruit", "Add the spices", "Season the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salsa-chamoy-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 852, "t": "Teriyaki Pork Chops Over Rice With Broccoli and Green Onions", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with teriyaki sauce—sweet, salty, and gingery—that we pair with pork chops, rice, and broccoli. Our teriyaki sauce—a play on the traditional Japanese grilling sauce— features major citrus tang and a rich boost from pan-roasted garlic and onions. Sesame brings in a layer of earthiness, making this sauce hard to put down. Simply put the protein—in this case, chicken—into a bag with ", "i": ["120 g Teriyaki Sous Vide Sauce", "18 g Neutral oil", "450 g Pork chop(s)", "448 g Water", "Kosher salt, as needed", "235 g Short-grain rice", "300 g Broccoli , head", "110 g Green onion(s) , sliced", "Toasted sesame seeds , for garnish , as needed", "Salt and pepper, as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the protein", "Bag it up and get cooking", "Make the rice", "Steam the broccoli", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/teriyaki-pork-chops-over-rice-with-broccoli-and-green-onions"}, {"id": 853, "t": "Teriyaki Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "If you have ever tasted a good teriyaki sauce, you already know the joys of a piece of meat slathered in that sweet, salty, gingery dark sauce. Traditionally, teriyaki is used for grilling. In Japanese, yaki means to cook over direct heat. (Teri means shiny or lustrous, which is the quality of the thickened sauce required for grilling.) Here, we are not cooking over direct heat, so this is a ChefS", "i": ["20 g Sesame oil", "55 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "10 g Garlic clove(s) , chopped", "45 g Fresh ginger root", "145 g Low-sodium soy sauce", "10 g Distilled vinegar", "20 g Light brown sugar", "1 g Xanthan gum", "10 g Toasted sesame seeds", "28 g Chives , sliced thin"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the vegetables", "Add the liquids and blend", "Finish the sauce", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/teriyaki-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 854, "t": "Mostarda Pork Loin Chops Over Creamy Polenta With Green Beans and Thyme", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This meal starts with a striking sauce, with the fruity-sweet heat of figs and mustard. Drizzle the sauce over pork loin and pair it with creamy polenta and green beans. This sauce—our take on the flavors of the northern Italian preserve of mostarda—has the heat of mustard powder, whole-grain mustard, and black pepper, which is balanced by the sweetness of the balsamic vinegar, figs, and apricots.", "i": ["120 g Fig & Apricot Mostarda Sous Vide Sauce", "18 g Neutral oil , as needed", "450 g Pork loin chops", "400 g Water", "36.9 g Cream", "34 g Butter", "99 g Polenta", "51 g Parmesan , grated", "227 g Green beans", "Salt , pinch , as needed", "0.5 Lemon , optional", "Thyme , for garnish , as needed", "2 Pork chop(s) , about 8-16 oz 1.5 Tbsp. Neutral oil , as needed"], "s": ["Prepare your sauce", "Choose your protein", "Heat sous vide bath", "Sear the pork chops", "1.5 Tbsp.", "Bag it up and start cooking", "Make creamy polenta", "Blanch the green beans", "Plate and serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/mostarda-pork-loin-chops-over-creamy-polenta-with-green-beans-and-thyme"}, {"id": 855, "t": "Fig & Apricot Mostarda Sous Vide Sauce", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This sauce is our take on the flavors of the northern Italian preserve of figs and mustard oil, cooked in a simple syrup. It’s a potent combination. Since mustard oil is not available for sale in the United States—even though it is used extensively through India—we made this sauce with mustard powder instead. The heat of that mustard powder, plus whole-grain mustard and black pepper, is balanced b", "i": ["12 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "41 g Sweet onion(s) , diced", "110 g Vegetable stock", "120 g Balsamic vinegar", "75 g Mustard , whole grain", "5 g Black pepper , course ground", "5 g Mustard powder", "10 g Kosher salt", "55 g Sugar", "60 g Dried figs , small dice", "60 g Dried apricots , small dice"], "s": ["Make this meal with this sauce", "Cook the onions", "Add the liquids", "Add the dry ingredients", "Add the fruit", "Got questions?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fig-apricot-mostarda-sous-vide-sauce"}, {"id": 856, "t": "The Science of Xanthan Gum", "c": "Baking", "d": "Xanthan gum is an essential ingredient in some ChefSteps recipes. Why? It’s a quick thickener for sauces. Quite a few gluten-free baked goods contain it. Xanthan gum has a range of commercial purposes as well. Interested in learning more about this hydrocolloid? Food scientist Chris Young describes the properties and uses of xanthan gum. Spoiler alert: It turns out that the name is the scariest th", "i": [], "s": ["Where to put all this xanthan gum you just ordered"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-science-of-xanthan-gum"}, {"id": 857, "t": "Vegetable and Seed Crackers", "c": "Baking", "d": "You might think these look like hippie crackers. You know the ones: flat with ragged edges, free of anything but seeds and dirt, and frankly nothing like a cracker. Sawdust with nutritional yeast—these we have tasted. These are not hippie crackers. Sure, these are non-traditional crackers. They have no flours, so they are gluten-free and grain-free. They do not contain any animal products, so they", "i": ["200 g Sunflower seed(s) , divided", "Cold water , for sunflower seed , as needed", "50 g Flaxseed", "100 g Hot water , for flaxseed", "160 g Kale , cleaned, about one bunch", "225 g Kimchi , or sauerkraut", "80 g Kimchi brine , can sub water", "15 g Tamari sauce (gluten free) , sub soy sauce if you don’t need gluten free", "15 g Maple syrup", "8 g Salt , kosher", "10 g Onion powder", "4 g Nutritional yeast", "10 g Oregano , fresh", "10 g Poppy seed", "10 g Black sesame seeds", "5 g Fennel seeds", "5 g Nigella seeds", "3 g Aleppo pepper , coarse ground", "1 Carrot(s)", "2 Scallion(s)", "Canola oil , for scallions , as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "Flake sea salt, as needed", "1 Carrot(s) 2 Scallion(s) - Canola oil , for scallions , as needed - Black pepper , as needed, , as needed - Flake sea salt, as needed"], "s": ["Gather everything together", "Soak the seeds", "Clean the kale", "Soak the flaxseed", "Strain and separate the sunflower seeds", "Blend the ingredients", "Make the seed mix", "Mix the cracker base", "Spread out the purée and garnish the crackers", "Dehydrate the crackers", "Portion the crackers"], "tips": ["Dehydration temperatures"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/vegetable-and-seed-crackers"}, {"id": 858, "t": "ChefSteps 101", "c": "Baking", "d": "Welcome to ChefSteps. We’re glad you are here. We are a bunch of chefs, scientists, writers, photographers, and video makers who love to cook and feed people. Every day—in our kitchen studio in Pike Place Market in Seattle— we are roasting chickens, baking cookies, making posset, and milk washing punch. Once? Oh heck no. We are testing dozens of different iterations of each dish to make sure we ca", "i": [], "s": ["How We Measure", "Using a Scale", "Thermometer Basics", "Food Science", "Let’s Start Cooking", "In-Depth Classes", "Knife Sharpening", "Sous Vide: Getting Started", "Sous Vide: Beyond the Basics", "Espresso", "Burgers", "French Macarons", "Questions and Comments"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chefsteps-101"}, {"id": 859, "t": "Ultimate Beef Wellington", "c": "Baking", "d": "This Ultimate Beef Wellington that Grant has created is, in his own words, “No-holds barred—epic.” It is level 11. Turn it up. Imagine a perfectly cooked tenderloin, wrapped in a layer of rich mushroom duxelles insulation, swathed in prosciutto, which is enrobed in a flaky pastry crust sturdy enough to stick to the rest of that deliciousness. This is the best kind of savory pie, made into a roll, ", "i": ["800 g Beef, center-cut tenderloin", "500 g Cremini mushrooms", "250 g Shallot(s) , minced", "85 g Butter , unsalted", "15 g Black truffle oil", "6 g Salt , kosher, divided", "4 g Black pepper , divided", "8 g Thyme , fresh, leaf only", "6 piece Prosciutto , slices", "6 piece", "Prosciutto , slices", "10 g Dijon mustard", "Parsley , flat-leaf , as needed", "Egg wash, as needed", "Rosemary , fresh, leaf only , as needed", "Sherry , dry fino , as needed"], "s": ["Make your dough", "Make the mushroom duxelles", "Precook the tenderloin", "Make the egg wash", "Roll out the dough", "Preheat the oven", "Roll it up", "piece", "Wrap the tenderloin in dough", "Add the lattice top", "Bake the Wellington", "Vegetarian Wellington"], "tips": ["Spot Deglazing", "Using a thermometer"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-beef-wellington"}, {"id": 860, "t": "Whole Tenderloin Roast: How to Butcher and Cook it up Like a Pro.", "c": "Baking", "d": "Want to save money, eat cuts of meat you love, and learn how to meditate while making dinner simply delicious? Learn how to butcher a whole tenderloin. Instead of buying parts of a beef tenderloin shrink wrapped from the grocery store, buy a whole tenderloin from a butcher you trust. Watch this video a few times. After your initial trepidation, you will feel more confident when you get into it. (K", "i": [], "s": ["Butcher’s Knot"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-butcher-a-whole-tenderloin-roast"}, {"id": 861, "t": "How to See the Future with a Thermometer", "c": "Baking", "d": "An accurate instant-read digital thermometer is an essential tool for success in the kitchen. If you don’t already own one, you need to buy one. The realization that your steak is too well-done, your cake sags in the middle because it was not fully baked, or your simple syrup for cocktails has crystallized because you stirred it too much, since you worried it would burn? No one needs that. Get a t", "i": [], "s": ["Which Thermometer Do I Use?", "Why does placement of the thermometer matter?", "Where to place the thermometer in roasts", "Where to place the thermometer in poultry", "Where to place the thermometer in steaks, chops, and breasts", "Where to place the thermometer in patties", "Where to place the thermometer while cooking syrups", "Where to place the thermometer in baked goods"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-see-the-future-with-a-thermometer"}, {"id": 862, "t": "The Ultimate Guide to Roast Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "We set out to re-imagine our already-awesome Ultimate Chicken recipe. And in the process, we roasted at least 72 whole chickens over a course of a few weeks. (Staff meals were delicious, if repetitive.) Everything we tested and learned helped us to make the best roast chicken we have ever tasted. Should you brine a chicken? (Yes, but not in the way you imagine.) Should we dry out the skin? (Absolu", "i": [], "s": ["Brining by submersion or with syringe", "Poaching", "Drying the chicken skin", "Butchering the chicken", "Roasting the chicken", "Resting"], "tips": ["Airflow matters"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-ultimate-guide-to-roast-chicken"}, {"id": 863, "t": "Ranch Chicken", "c": "Baking", "d": "One of our chefs, Kyl Haselbauer, loves to dip things in ranch. Chicken strips, pizza, quesadillas, fries—you get the point. So, after roasting nearly 80 chickens to enhance our Ultimate Roast Chicken and create our Ultimate Roast Chicken guide, Kyl had only one thing left to do: put ranch powder on a chicken and roast it. He went straight to the source and used the super-condensed flavor bomb of ", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 Chicken 2 Ranch dressing powder 750 g Baby potatoes , small one inch potatoes will be best - Salt, as needed - Black peppercorns , ground , as needed", "1 Chicken 2 Ranch dressing powder 750 g Baby potatoes , small one inch potatoes will be best - Salt, as needed - Black peppercorns , ground , as needed", "1 Chicken", "2 Ranch dressing powder", "750 g Baby potatoes , small one inch potatoes will be best", "Salt, as needed", "Black peppercorns , ground , as needed", "1 Chicken 2 Ranch dressing powder - Black peppercorns , ground , as needed", "1 Chicken 750 g Baby potatoes , small one inch potatoes will be best"], "s": ["Cook your potatoes", "Smash the potatoes", "Spatchcock that bird", "Score the bird", "Season with ranch dressing powder", "Assemble​ the dish", "Roast the chicken", "Let the chicken rest"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ranch-chicken"}, {"id": 864, "t": "FROZEN: Cryogenic “Cooking” With Liquid Nitrogen", "c": "Baking", "d": "Cryo poaching with liquid nitrogen is like deep frying, but using extreme cold instead of heat. A beignet batter is a foam. Put it into super-hot oil and the inside stays soft and the outside crust turns crisp and golden. Making anything with liquid nitrogen is the same process. Freeze the outside of the foam quickly with liquid nitrogen so the inside stays soft. The uses for quick-freezing are on", "i": [], "s": ["Why we love it", "What is liquid nitrogen?", "Potential dangers—be safe", "Acquisition and storage", "Why churn ice cream with liquid nitrogen?", "More recipes to get you started cooking with cold", "Don’t try this at home", "Additional info"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/frozen-cryogenic-poaching-with-liquid-nitrogen"}, {"id": 865, "t": "Sous Vide Pork Shoulder “Ham”", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This overnight pork-shoulder ham is ridiculously easy to make and better than any grocery store ham. The ham at the store is typically made from the hind leg of a pig, from hip to thigh—the leanest and therefore toughest part on the animal. That’s why the ham you find wrapped in fishnet-stocking netting at the store is brined—sometimes for weeks—before it’s smoked. If you make your own ham with a ", "i": ["4 kg Pork shoulder , bone-in", "120 g Light brown sugar", "60 g Salt", "20 g Sweet Spice , or any spice blend you love", "20 g Liquid smoke , (Wright’s hickory), optional", "Cloves, as needed", "120 g Brown sugar , light"], "s": ["Choosing the cut", "Measure the ingredients", "Choose your doneness", "Release the ham", "Score the ham", "Make the glaze", "Glaze and bake"], "tips": ["Roasting veggies"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/transform-pork-shoulder-into-a-spiral-fresh-glazed-ham"}, {"id": 866, "t": "Everything You Need to Know About Truffles", "c": "Baking", "d": "Rare and elegant, a shaving of fresh truffles instantly elevates and enhances a dish. But what are these foreign fungi, and why is such an odd-looking ingredient so darn sexy and sought after? These dense and knobby masses may not look like much, but their scarcity, aroma, and flavor have made them symbols of refined taste and elegance. Like mushrooms, truffles are the fruiting bodies of a fungus.", "i": [], "s": ["Where do truffles come from?", "What do truffles taste like?", "Where can I buy truffles?", "How do I use truffles?", "How do I clean truffles?", "How do I store and keep truffles?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/all-about-that-truffle"}, {"id": 867, "t": "Light, Crispy Popovers", "c": "Baking", "d": "If you have never made popovers before, you’re missing out on something quite extraordinary. They puff up like a blousy dress blown up by the wind. The crust is crisp, with a snap on the teeth. The inside is soft, almost creamy, like custard. These are savory Sunday roast and rich gravy food. Popovers came across the ocean with British citizens settling into the new America. No one knows when York", "i": ["300 g Egg(s) , large", "300 g Milk , whole", "300 g Bread flour", "12 g Salt , kosher", "Grapeseed oil, as needed"], "s": ["Get it all together", "Preheat the oven", "Make the batter", "Prepare the muffin pan", "Fill the muffin cavities and bake"], "tips": ["What kind of fat works best?", "Keep it traditional or let those creative juices flow"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/light-crispy-popovers"}, {"id": 868, "t": "Festive, Freeze-Dried Fruity Shortbread Cookies", "c": "Baking", "d": "This season, we made a lot of shortbread cookies and freeze-dried fruit so your cookie dreams will be made of bright colors and flavors that you will never forget. Sure, we’re all fond of those soft sugar cookies with overly vibrant frosting. You can pick them up in any grocery store or make them at home with the same recipe you have been using for decades. However, we wanted to find a way to make", "i": ["1 recipe Simple Shortbread Cookies , minus the milk solids", "80 g Egg white(s)", "225 g Powdered sugar", "16 g Lemon juice , 1/2 lemon", "0.8 g Malic acid", "Freeze-dried fruit, as needed", "0.25 g Salt , kosher"], "s": ["The cookie recipe", "Royal icing", "Make fruit powders", "Make fruity icing", "Decorate the cookies", "What else can you freeze dry?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/festive-freeze-dried-fruity-shortbread-cookies"}, {"id": 869, "t": "Oaten Shortbread", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "We played with our original shortbread cookie recipe to make it with oat and rice flour, both traditional ingredients in shortbread. This cookie is buttery, with a texture that crumbles into little pieces if you nudge one too firmly. And yet, with a gentle touch, this plain, slightly sweet cookie holds up to a dunk in a cup of tea or hot chocolate. It also happens to be gluten-free. These days, we", "i": ["190 g Butter , unsalted, soft", "30 g Sugar", "30 g Confectioners’ sugar , sifted", "4 g Vanilla extract", "5 g Salt , kosher", "150 g Oat flour", "50 g Mochiko sweet rice flour"], "s": ["Gather everything you need", "Make the dough", "Chill the dough", "Preheat the oven", "Portion the cookies", "Bake the cookies"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/oaten-shortbread"}, {"id": 870, "t": "The ChefSteps’ Starter Kitchen", "c": "Baking", "d": "We hear one question repeatedly from our ChefSteps community members: “What tools should I have in my kitchen?” That is, of course, a question with a thousand answers, which lead to a thousand more questions. What do you want to make? How confident are you with sharp implements? How much money do you want to spend? What matters to you in a kitchen utensil or appliance—cost or quality? The answers ", "i": [], "s": ["A really, really good knife or two", "Meet the board", "Joule Turbo", "Pots and pans to make you proud", "Digital thermometer", "Digital scale", "Mandoline", "Whipping siphon", "Spice grinder", "Microplane", "Blowtorch", "Fine-mesh sieve", "Pressure cooker"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-chefsteps-starter-kitchen"}, {"id": 871, "t": "Let’s Talk About Thanksgiving", "c": "Baking", "d": "We’re here to help you have a great stress-free Thanksgiving cooking experience, whether you are feeding a crowd or taking a dish to a Friendsgiving party. Below you’ll find a roadmap to picking the perfect turkey (or duck or chicken), some answers to common turkey cooking questions, and our favorite apps, libations, turkeys, sides, gravies, pies, and sweets. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Determine this year’s turkey destination", "Frequently Asked Questions", "Welcome your guests with boozy libations!", "Get the party started with these tasty bites", "Prep the bird", "The main event", "Great gravy!", "Get your side hustle on!", "Bread, rolls, biscuits and butter", "Pie's the limit"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/let-s-talk-about-thanksgiving"}, {"id": 872, "t": "Super Apple Pie", "c": "Baking", "d": "Beware! Once you make this Super Apple Pie, you might find that your favorite family apple pie suddenly tastes of cinnamon and sugar and not much else. This one tastes like apples. Sometimes around here we try crazy food experiments, just to see what happens. Grant said to Matthew one day, \"Hey, how many apples do you think you can get into a pie?\" It turned out to be 114. 114 apples in one pie! H", "i": ["210 g Freeze-dried apples", "2130 ml Apple juice concentrate", "880 g Pie dough", "48 g Apple powder", "60 g Butter , unsalted", "6 g Sweet Spice", "3 g Cinnamon , ground", "3 g Allspice , ground", "950 g Apple(s) , fresh, about 5", "9.6 g Low-Acyl Gellan Gum F", "1 Vanilla bean", "100 g Brown sugar", "1.5 g Kosher salt", "210 g Freeze-dried apples 710 ml Apple juice concentrate , 2 cans worth"], "s": ["Freeze-dry some apples", "Make the apple crust", "Dehydrate some apples", "Freeze dry the apples again", "Make the apple gel", "Hydrate the apples again", "Cook the filling", "Roll out the crust", "Assemble the pie", "Add an egg wash", "Bake the pie", "Cool the pie", "Developing the pie: behind the scenes", "We want you to have even more pie knowledge"], "tips": ["How do I make this pie without all the specialized equipment?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/super-apple-pie"}, {"id": 873, "t": "Transform Thanksgiving With Turkey Yakitori", "c": "Baking", "d": "Look, you might be locked into the traditional Thanksgiving turkey, or maybe your family is insisting on it. However, since you’re with us here at ChefSteps, we have a feeling you might be more daring in the kitchen than the average cook. Interested in innovating the feast of brown starches and over-cooked turkey into something memorably delicious instead? We’re happy to offer you this. Turkey yak", "i": [], "s": ["First Things, First: Butchery", "How to Grill That Turkey Yakitori Style", "Turkey Toppings: Thanksgiving Togarashi and Cranberry Glaze", "If Making Yakitori Seems Too Much, We Have Other Turkey Recipes"], "tips": ["Behind-The-Scenes: Turkey Yakitori Work-In-Progress"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/transform-thanksgiving-with-turkey-yakitori"}, {"id": 874, "t": "How to Butcher Turkey: Yakitori Style", "c": "Baking", "d": "Here’s the good news. You can go as deep as you like into this, or make it as easy as you want. And you don’t have to stress out about butchering a turkey with any perfection since nothing goes to waste. Anything you goof up can go right into making meatballs or a turkey stock to make a reduction glaze. So, no stressing allowed. This is impossible to mess up! We are going to take you from the whol", "i": [], "s": ["Butchery Prep: Tools and Mise en Place", "How to Butcher the Turkey into Breasts, Hindquarters, and Carcass", "Thigh and Leg Yakitori Butchery and Skewers", "Breast, Tender, Drumette, and Wing Yakitori Butchery and Skewers", "Meatball Skewers", "Make Stock With the Bones and Extra Bits", "Make a Stock Reduction Glaze"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-butcher-turkey-yakitori-style"}, {"id": 875, "t": "Thanksgiving Yakitori: Grilling", "c": "Baking", "d": "Grilling skewers of turkey thighs, breasts, tenders, oysters, skin, and meatballs could be the best Thanksgiving turkey you have ever made. Let’s grill some Thanksgiving yakitori! Yakitori is the ultimate form of grilling. It’s super hot and super fast. Everything is prepared ahead of time and trimmed down to the best version of itself. There is no time to waste. Grilling is happening now. Classic", "i": [], "s": ["Hibachi Classic", "Binchotan – The Coals", "Hibachi BBQ Hacks", "Oven Hack", "Other Suggestions for Grilling Hot", "Additional resources"], "tips": ["Cool Your Coals in Water to Use Them Again and Again!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/thanksgiving-yakitori-grilling"}, {"id": 876, "t": "Thanksgiving Cranberry Yakitori Glaze", "c": "Baking", "d": "When we set out to make a yakitori glaze for our yaki-turkey, we wanted to infuse it with the flavors of Thanksgiving. After we tasted it, we realized we had created a bittersweet glaze to liven up the taste of that turkey. We also realized we had yakitori cranberry sauce to give you. For many of us, that Thanksgiving meal would not taste delicious without cranberry sauce and gravy. Both are the f", "i": ["500 g Turkey stock", "350 g Cranberries , fresh", "60 g Soy sauce", "2 g Orange zest", "200 g Sugar", "2 g Flake sea salt"], "s": ["Reduce the turkey stock", "Cook down the sauce", "Zest it up", "Make some yakitori for that cranberry sauce"], "tips": ["Need it to be gluten-free?", "How to use this sauce"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/thanksgiving-cranberry-yakitori-glaze"}, {"id": 877, "t": "Thanksgiving Togarashi​ Spice", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "We believe that once you have made this Thanksgiving Togarashi mix once, you will make it again and again. When we made our turkey yakitori, we used some of the classic garnishes to go with it: lemon zest and pepper and a sauce made of soy sauce, mirin, sake, and spices to glaze the skewers. However, since we are giving you a new way to make turkey on Thanksgiving, we also wanted to make a turkey ", "i": ["50 g Kosher salt", "10 g Korean chile flakes (gochugaru)", "10 g Thyme , fresh", "1 Lemon", "1 Lemon zest , of one lemon"], "s": ["Dry the thyme and lemon zest in microwave", "Mix up the togarashi", "Make some more Japanese dishes"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/thanksgiving-togarashi-spice"}, {"id": 878, "t": "Million Dollar Cream of Mushroom", "c": "Baking", "d": "So many of us have powerful sensory memories of cream of mushroom soup. You can do so much with a cream of mushroom soup base: green bean casserole, tater tot casserole, pork chops simmered in it, and a pretty great gravy. We might have grown up with cream of mushroom soup from a can, but we have grown up now. So many of us in the Northwest love cooking with wild mushrooms. How can we honor the OG", "i": ["300 g Chicken stock", "10 g Knox gelatin", "40 g White truffle oil", "30 g All-purpose flour", "100 g King oyster mushrooms , porcini, chanterelle, or button work great too", "2 g Thyme , fresh", "2 g Rosemary , fresh", "3 g Salt", "3 g Black pepper", "200 g Heavy cream"], "s": ["Reduce the stock", "Reduce the heavy cream", "Make the roux", "Cook the mushrooms", "Finish the cream of mushroom base", "Use this sauce in other recipes!"], "tips": ["On truffles", "Make the soup", "Storing truffles", "Kyl’s favorite—Hot Dish"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/million-dollar-cream-of-mushroom"}, {"id": 879, "t": "Cream of Mushroom Base", "c": "Baking", "d": "We know that many folks go to Thanksgiving celebrations where a table laden with dishes requires one staple: Campbell’s Cream of Mushroom condensed soup. This thick, gelatinous mass in a can is the basis for green bean casserole, scallop potatoes, broccoli and cheese casserole, and something called creamed onion bake. (No one here has eaten this before. Have you?) Most folks want Thanksgiving dinn", "i": ["400 g Matsutake , Diced, fresh, substitute king oyster if needed", "100 g Butter", "100 g All-purpose flour", "1 kg Chicken stock", "2 g Thyme , fresh", "2 g Rosemary , fresh", "1 kg Heavy cream", "25 g Knox gelatin", "Salt, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed"], "s": ["Gather your mise", "Chicken stock reduction", "Blend in the gelatin", "Reduce the heavy cream", "Make a roux", "Cook the mushrooms", "Finish the mushroom base"], "tips": ["How to clean matsutake mushrooms", "Make the soup"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cream-of-mushroom-base"}, {"id": 880, "t": "Cream Of Mushroom Base, Gluten-Free and Plant-Based", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Once we developed our Wild Cream of Mushroom base, we were thrilled with the taste. Then, we realized that we should take it one step further. We believe in feeding people here. Food is so important to us that the idea of anyone at our table feeling left out? It sits with us the wrong way. Like you, we are bound to have someone at our Thanksgiving table who cannot eat gluten due to celiac, someone", "i": ["454 g Cremini mushrooms", "100 g Sweet onion(s)", "1.1 kg Water", "50 g Coconut oil (refined)", "100 g Mochiko sweet rice flour", "400 g King oyster mushrooms", "1 g Thyme , fresh sprigs", "1 g Rosemary , fresh sprigs", "75 g Coconut cream", "80 g Black truffle oil", "5 g Flake sea salt", "4 g Black pepper , whole", "500 g Mushroom stock"], "s": ["Make the mushroom stock", "Make “roux”", "Thicken the stock", "Cook the mushrooms", "Finish the soup"], "tips": ["How to make gluten-free roux"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cream-of-mushroom-base-gluten-free-and-plant-based"}, {"id": 881, "t": "Green Bean Casserole​", "c": "Baking", "d": "Green bean casserole has never been given its due. It is easy to make fun of green bean casserole, since almost every grandmother has made it for Thanksgiving, based on what was on her family’s table in the 1950s. Guess what? Green bean casserole is delicious, and we want you to enjoy the heck out of it this year. The fact is, this recipe was made in waves across the country in the 1950s, since it", "i": ["520 g Green beans , fresh", "500 g Cream of Mushroom Base", "170 g Crispy fried onions , French’s or homemade"], "s": ["Blanch Your Beans", "Warm Up the Cream of Mushroom", "Mix Them Up", "Bake the Casserole", "Top with Fried Onions"], "tips": ["Make Your Own Fried Onions"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/green-bean-casserole"}, {"id": 882, "t": "Savory Bread Pudding​", "c": "Baking", "d": "This savory bread pudding–made with good bread and our cream of mushroom base—makes a crunchy, custardy deliciousness that everyone will love. You might want to plan on making two batches, to feed everyone who wants some. This might sound like stuffing, but it’s frankly better. Stuffing—let’s face it, probably most that you have tried—can be dry. Take the same idea of cubes of bread and something ", "i": ["300 g Cream of Mushroom Base", "450 g Heavy cream", "100 g Egg(s)", "30 g Egg yolk(s)", "1 g Black pepper , whole", "5 g Salt", "85 g Walnuts", "4 g Sage", "1 g Thyme , fresh leaves", "2 g Rosemary , freshly minced", "1 Garlic , minced", "360 g Potato bread , we used bread from Seattle’s Macrina Bakery. You can also sub King’s Hawaiian Rolls."], "s": ["Cut the bread", "Mix it all up together", "Soak your bread", "Let it rest", "Bake it up!", "Serve it up!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/savory-bread-pudding"}, {"id": 883, "t": "Plant-Based Caesar Dressing", "c": "Baking", "d": "This Caesar dressing without eggs or dairy has so much depth of flavor we would choose it for our salad, even those of us who can eat traditional Caesar dressing. We have a clear rule here: we don’t publish recipes for food that are just good enough. There are plenty of those on the internet already. Have a dairy-free or egg-free guest coming to your holiday dinner? You might do a Google search, l", "i": ["75 g Sunflower seed(s)", "500 ml Cold water , Soaking liquid for seeds", "1 Garlic , whole head, to yield 30 g roasted garlic", "Extra-virgin olive oil , for the roasted garlic , as needed", "Black pepper , for the roasted garlic , as needed", "Salt , kosher, for the roasted garlic , as needed", "200 g Dry cider , reduce this amount to 20% or 40 g", "24 g Black garlic , peeled", "6 g Garlic clove(s)", "11 g Tamari sauce (gluten free)", "25 g White miso paste", "30 g Lemon juice", "5 g Nutritional yeast", "18 g Red wine vinegar", "185 g Canola oil", "75 g Sunflower seed(s) 500 ml Cold water , Soaking liquid for seeds"], "s": ["Prepare to prepare", "Soak the sunflower seeds", "Roast the garlic", "Reduce the cider", "Blend the dressing", "Other plant-based goodies for you and your friends"], "tips": ["What to do with roasted garlic", "Introducing black garlic"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/plant-based-caesar-dressing"}, {"id": 884, "t": "Plant-Based “Parmesan”", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "There is nothing like a good Parmesan cheese. It cannot be replicated exactly, right? Right. That’s still true. However, if you want to add some “cheesy” flavor to your salad, we have that. Want something earthy and salty with umami flavor and a texture that adds depth to your dish? We have that. Want something with only a few ingredients that is easy to blitz into finish in the food processor? We", "i": ["150 g Walnuts", "3 g White miso paste", "3 g Nutritional yeast", "3 g Salt", "7 g Extra-virgin olive oil"], "s": ["Get Everything Together", "Mix It Up", "Need Some More Plant-Based Sides for Your Feast?"], "tips": ["Let’s Talk About Miso"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/plant-based-parmesan"}, {"id": 885, "t": "Holiday Herb Oil", "c": "Meat", "d": "We bottled up all the flavors of Thanksgiving into a fragrant, delicious herb oil so you can use it to enliven any holiday meal. If you’re anything like the rest of America, you’re probably loading your cart at the grocery store with 1-ounce packs of fresh herbs for holiday meals. Not only are those expensive, but they wither and blacken quickly in the refrigerator. It’s a much better idea to make", "i": ["7 g Sage , fresh", "20 g Rosemary , fresh", "10 g Thyme , fresh", "4 g Bay leaf , fresh", "5 g Chives , fresh", "600 ml Grapeseed oil", "85 g Shallot(s)", "50 g Garlic , elephant", "10 g Lemon peel , 1 lemon", "2 g Coriander seeds", "4 g Black pepper , whole", "Nonfat dry milk powder, as needed"], "s": ["Knowledge: Removing moisture and stopping enzymes", "Get everything together", "Prep the herbs", "Prep the aromatics", "Start cooking", "Add the aromatics", "Add dry milk powder", "Add the herbs", "Strain and bottle the oil", "How to use this oil", "Behind the Scenes: Developing the Holiday Herb Oil"], "tips": ["Trials: How We Landed On This Recipe", "Weighing in reverse", "Make a garnish!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/holiday-herb-oil"}, {"id": 886, "t": "Corn Pie, Pumpkin-Style", "c": "Baking", "d": "Think about pumpkin pie—that tender crust, that soft custard made of mashed pumpkin, sugar, eggs, evaporated milk and the spices redolent of the holidays. On top, a dollop of fresh whipped cream. Everyone seems to crave a pumpkin pie for Thanksgiving. We decided to revisit this autumnal dessert and make it with corn instead of pumpkin. Why corn? Sure, tradition says that we need pumpkin pie for th", "i": ["0.5 recipe Perfect Pie Dough , blind-baked in a 9-inch pie plate", "420 g Corn , kernels—frozen, fresh, or canned (thawed if using frozen)", "325 g Evaporated milk", "126 g Sugar , divided", "110 g Egg(s) , (2 extra-large eggs)", "1.5 g Ginger , ground", "0.3 g Turmeric root powder , ground", "2 g Kosher salt", "0.5 Vanilla bean , split lengthwise and scraped (or 5 g vanilla extract)", "1.5 g Sweet Spice , or store-bought pumpkin pie spice"], "s": ["Make corn purée", "Finish pie filling", "0.5 recipe", "Make spiced sugar and sprinkle over pie", "Bake pie"], "tips": ["Why bake on the bottom rack?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/corn-pie-pumpkin-style"}, {"id": 887, "t": "A Guide to Pie Dough: The Ingredients", "c": "Baking", "d": "Making a flaky, delicious pie dough is one of the great joys of life, mostly because of the joy it can bring. Push a fork through the top crust and listen to it shatter into softness. The bottom is firm and fully baked, not the soggy bottom most people create unintentionally. The edges of the pie dough are crimped, the edges unfurling in a hundred layers like a croissant. Best of all is the look o", "i": [], "s": ["The Flours", "The Fats", "The Liquids"], "tips": ["What About a Gluten-Free Crust?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/a-guide-to-pie-dough-the-ingredients"}, {"id": 888, "t": "A Guide to Pie Dough: The Process", "c": "Baking", "d": "Ingredients matter to a pie dough, of course. However, a great pie dough really is made in the process, the way you mix the dough, the temperature of the dough, how long you let it rest, and how you handle it in the end. Process matters. Can you use a machine to make pie dough? Or should you mix by hand? We found you can make good pie dough with any method of mixing. Just use the tool correctly. M", "i": [], "s": ["Hand mixing on a bench", "Hand mixing in a bowl", "Stand mixer", "Food processor", "Grated butter", "Resting", "Shaping", "Blind-Baking", "Making pie crust: all the hand business"], "tips": ["Cutting in the butter"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/a-guide-to-pie-dough-the-process"}, {"id": 889, "t": "Apple Cranberry Galette", "c": "Baking", "d": "Are you daunted by the task of making a pie? (You’re not alone.) What if you don’t own a pie pan? Or you don’t have the time to wait for the pie dough to rest, then blind bake the shell, and then let it cool down? We have the answer for you. Make a galette. To make a galette, all you need is an oven, a sheet to bake it on, pie dough, and a filling. And you also have the chance to do it free-form a", "i": ["400 g Perfect Pie Dough , include optional sugar indicated in the recipe", "85 g Brown sugar", "1.5 g Lemon zest", "1.5 g Orange zest", "1.2 g Cinnamon , ground", "540 g Apple(s) , about 3 apples", "0.4 g Allspice , ground", "1 g Salt , kosher", "30 g Butter , unsalted", "15 g All-purpose flour", "60 g Cranberries", "1 Vanilla bean , scraped", "0.5 g Malic acid", "Egg wash , or evaporated milk wash , as needed"], "s": ["Gather everything together", "Make the filling", "Roll out the pie dough", "Assemble the galette", "Chill the galette", "Bake the galette"], "tips": ["Make an egg wash", "Why use flour in the filling?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/make-galette-not-pie"}, {"id": 890, "t": "Pressure-Cooked Chile Verde", "c": "Baking", "d": "When I wrote up a narrative recipe of my home-kitchen pork chile verde in one of our emails, many of you asked if we could develop the recipe in the ChefSteps kitchen with specific measurements. Of course! That’s what we do for you. A couple of years ago, Kenji López-Alt published a great recipe for a pork chile verde he made in the pressure cooker. I loved how fast and flavorful it was. Around th", "i": ["300 g Tomatillos , medium to large, sliced in half", "240 g Onion(s) , large yellow chopped", "250 g Poblano pepper(s) , about 4 large, pith and seeds removed", "50 g Jalapeño(s) , pith and seeds removed", "4 Lime(s) , fresh peeled", "50 g Garlic , cloves", "2 kg Pork shoulder , bone in", "20 g Salt", "20 g Cumin seeds", "2 Cilantro , large fresh bunches", "200 g Green onion(s)", "700 g Hominy , 1 large can", "20 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Put the vegetables into the pressure cooker", "Add the meat", "Pressure cook for 45 minutes", "Blend the sauce", "Blend in the green onions and cilantro", "Finish the chile verde"], "tips": ["Butcher your vegetables", "Keep the spice for those who want it", "Increase aroma and flavor", "Take great care when blending hot items", "Get 100% juice yield from limes"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pressure-cooked-chile-verde"}, {"id": 891, "t": "Work in Progress: Turkey Yakitori", "c": "Sauce", "d": "We’re working on a sort of Yakitori treatment of Turkey for this November. Skewers, butchery, grilling, sauces, the whole works. save Print", "i": [], "s": ["Skewers: We aren’t doing the final skewers this way", "On the Set: Turkey Yakitori Butchery Shoot", "Cooking Trials: Balcony Cookout", "Skewer Photoshoot", "Desserts in Progress"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/work-in-progress-turkey-yakitori"}, {"id": 892, "t": "Flavor Essentials: Your Guide to Essential Oils", "c": "Baking", "d": "I would rather have a fridge full of essential oils than a drawer full of dried spices. How do you add a fresh zesty taste of citrus without the bits of citrus? Essential oils. How do you flavor your eggs with French tarragon without green bits on the top? Essential oils. How can you add thyme into a buttery frying pan without worrying about burning and make your steak taste like something new? Es", "i": [], "s": ["How to use essential oils", "How to store essential oils", "Where to buy essential oils", "Some ideas for using them"], "tips": ["TIP—Use a spoon to add oils to dishes"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/flavor-essentials-your-guide-to-essential-oils"}, {"id": 893, "t": "Ultimate Sliders", "c": "Baking", "d": "Super crispy, tender, juicy, and ready to eat in 2 minutes—sliders are the best burgers sometimes. We’re not knocking other burgers. Burgers are great, no matter how they arrive. However, sometimes these days burgers come with a side of precious arrogance—heck, we have been guilty of this too—and that tastes less and less delicious to us now. No one could be pretentious about a slider. Sliders are", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 kg Ground beef 30 g Egg yolk(s) , 2 yolks - Hawaiian Sweet Rolls, as needed - Onion(s), as needed - Lettuce, as needed - Dill pickles, as needed - American cheese, as needed - Mayonnaise, as needed - Yellow mustard, as needed - Ketchup, as needed", "1 kg Ground beef 30 g Egg yolk(s) , 2 yolks - Hawaiian Sweet Rolls, as needed - Onion(s), as needed - Lettuce, as needed - Dill pickles, as needed - American cheese, as needed - Mayonnaise, as needed - Yellow mustard, as needed - Ketchup, as needed", "1 kg Ground beef", "30 g Egg yolk(s) , 2 yolks", "Hawaiian Sweet Rolls, as needed", "Onion(s), as needed", "Lettuce, as needed", "Dill pickles, as needed", "American cheese, as needed", "Mayonnaise, as needed", "Yellow mustard, as needed", "Ketchup, as needed"], "s": ["Before you start cooking", "Prep it all up", "Get slide’n", "Assemble for the win"], "tips": ["Knowledge: Burger Family Tree", "Go gently on the meat", "You’re not grilling. You’re griddling.", "Fold your cheese"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/you-want-these-sliders"}, {"id": 894, "t": "What the Heck Could Posset Possibly Be?", "c": "Baking", "d": "All you need to know is this—posset is a decadent custard dessert. It can be any flavor you want. And it only takes a few minutes to make. If you like cheesecake, but you hate that it takes a long time to bake and be ready, you want to make posset. If you like yogurt, but you can't quite convince yourself that yogurt and berries are really a dessert, you want to make posset. Posset pleases and tea", "i": ["500 g Heavy cream", "100 g Sugar , granulated", "3.5 g Citric acid", "Essential oil , a few drops will do , as needed"], "s": ["Attention! Time to mise up", "Measure everything", "Dissolve the citric acid", "Add the flavoring", "Add the acid to the posset to set it", "Put the posset in the refrigerator", "Enjoy your posset"], "tips": ["Knowledge: Citric acid trials", "Make a fruit sauce to top the posset", "Prepare a chiffonade"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-the-heck-could-posset-possibly-be"}, {"id": 895, "t": "Seamless Ravioli", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "We figured out a way for you to make ravioli without a pasta roller, ravioli cutter, or any experience with fresh pasta at all. Chefs have been making filled pasta for a very long time. Learning how to combine the right ratio of the right flour with the perfect amount of eggs—or egg yolks—with your hands until the pasta is just the right supple texture for rolling out sheets of it? It’s a task wor", "i": ["454 g Ricotta cheese , we used Polly-O brand.", "1 Lemon zest", "Salt, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "5 g Basil , diced small", "30 g Egg yolk(s)", "1.4 kg Semolina flour"], "s": ["Make the filling", "Portion the filling", "Bury the filling", "Cook the ravioli"], "tips": ["Varied Results With Different Brands Of Semolina", "About the filling texture", "Make some egg yolk Ravioli", "Save that semolina!", "More Pasta, More Sauces..."], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/seamless-ravioli"}, {"id": 896, "t": "Six-Minute Microwave Funfetti Cake", "c": "Baking", "d": "It’s your kid’s birthday party today. You didn’t have time to make the cake. You could go out and buy one of those already-decorated cakes, the one with the roses and thick corners of frosting made out of powdered sugar and shortening. Or you could bake a Funfetti cake in the microwave in six minutes. It’s so easy your kid can help you make it. We made a lot of cakes in the microwave to find out e", "i": ["1 Pillsbury Funfetti cake mix , (1 box)", "3 Large egg(s)", "Large egg(s)", "115 g Canola oil", "235 g Cold water", "Funfetti frosting with sprinkles, as needed", "115 g Neutral oil"], "s": ["Get Everything Together", "Mix the Cake", "Microwave the Cake", "Chill the Cake", "Decorate the Cake"], "tips": ["Tip: Two Cakes are Better Than One Cake"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/need-an-epic-funfetti-cake-in-six-minutes-microwave-it"}, {"id": 897, "t": "One Pasta Dough. No Machines. Four Shapes.", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "We know that making your own pasta sounds stressful when you have never made it. Play with this method for making great hand-shaped pasta, however, and you will soon know what we do: making pasta is a form of meditation. You can use your mixer to save your forearms if you want, but overall this is a bulletproof way to make some hand-shaped pasta. This pasta recipe is a “no-machine-kneaded” recipe.", "i": ["200 g Pasta flour , Caputo pasta fresca e gnocchi", "200 g Semolina flour , Caputo semolina", "190 g Egg yolk(s)", "70 g Water", "4 g Kosher salt"], "s": ["Sift the flours together", "Chop in the egg yolks", "Finish the pasta dough", "Set the dough down for a nap", "How to shape orecchiette", "How to shape troffie", "How to shape pici", "How to shape gnocchetti"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/one-pasta-dough-no-machines-four-shapes"}, {"id": 898, "t": "Cryo-Poached Concord Grape", "c": "Baking", "d": "Crispy on the outside, sour-fruity mousse on the inside—this dessert is delicious but also hard to beat for its showmanship. Want to turn a room full of adults into little kids? Give them this dessert. These are the most refreshing grapes you will ever eat. How do you make something as spectacular as this treat? Liquid nitrogen, of course. There is no substitute for that here. Treat liquid nitroge", "i": ["30 g Grape Jolly Rancher", "10 g Rapid set HM pectin", "2.5 g Malic acid", "2 g Calcium chloride", "25 g Fructose", "300 g Frozen concord grape juice concentrate", "6 g Silver gelatin, 170 bloom", "70 g Egg white(s)", "2 g Calcium"], "s": ["Dry blend", "Dissolve gelatin in half of the concentrate", "Dissolve the dry blend into the other half of the juice concentrate", "Mix and whip", "Chill the mixture", "Have a cryo party", "Chill the spoon and pipe some grapes", "Poach foam in liquid nitrogen", "Adjust the poaching time and make more"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/cryo-poached-concord-grape"}, {"id": 899, "t": "Should You Steam It or Boil It? The Difference Matters", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Steaming makes your vegetables taste better. Steaming is faster than boiling. Steaming is far more energy- and time-efficient than boiling. Have we convinced you yet? We have to talk about steaming vs. boiling because most of you are wasting your time, waiting for a big pot of water to boil while your hungry family sits growing more famished. There are a couple of exceptions to the steaming-is-bet", "i": [], "s": ["Steaming Yields Tastier Food", "Let’s Test It", "Is It Faster to Boil or Steam?", "Consider This Experiment", "The Discussion of the Experiment", "The Experiment", "In Conclusion"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/should-you-steam-it-or-boil-it-the-difference-matters"}, {"id": 900, "t": "Jell-O Marshmallows", "c": "Baking", "d": "Making marshmallows requires eight ingredients, including unflavored gelatin and corn syrup. After all that work, homemade marshmallows taste a little disappointingly bland. Make marshmallows with Jell-O! You have a simpler process, with more flavor and bright colors. We wanted to see if we could make festive marshmallows—bright, bouncy, and bound to start a conversation—with as few ingredients as", "i": ["50 g Cornstarch", "50 g Powdered sugar", "510 g Jell-O , three large boxes Jell-O", "175 g Cold water"], "s": ["Mise en Place", "Dissolve Jell-O in Water", "Cook to 226 °F / 108 °C", "Whip the Hot Mixture", "Cast the Marshmallows", "Portioning"], "tips": ["Make Cleanup Easy", "Lucky Charms Marshmallows"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/jell-o-marshmallows"}, {"id": 901, "t": "The Boiled Omelet", "c": "Baking", "d": "Grant is pretty sure he has invented the boiled omelet. Honestly, it’s the lightest, fluffiest omelet you will ever eat. Plus, it’s ridiculously easy to make. The key is that the boiling water transfers so much heat so quickly, the eggs souffle. Think egg drop soup intersects omelet—go with it. Chef Daniel Patterson of Coi published a recipe for poached scrambled eggs more than a decade ago. In ou", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 3 Egg(s) 1 Egg yolk(s) 2 piece American cheese - Salt, as needed - Black pepper, as needed - Herbs, as needed - Butter , melted , as needed", "3 Egg(s) 1 Egg yolk(s) 2 piece American cheese - Salt, as needed - Black pepper, as needed - Herbs, as needed - Butter , melted , as needed", "3 Egg(s)", "1 Egg yolk(s)", "2 piece American cheese", "2 piece", "Salt, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "Herbs, as needed", "Butter , melted , as needed", "3 Egg(s) 1 Egg yolk(s) - Salt, as needed"], "s": ["Bring water to boil", "Whisk the eggs", "Stage your sieve", "Poach the omelet", "Form the omelet"], "tips": ["Salt the eggs before cooking"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/the-boiled-omelette"}, {"id": 902, "t": "Freezer Jam: Why It’s the Real Jam", "c": "Baking", "d": "Usually, here at ChefSteps, we reinvent. However, after a lot of testing, we found that when we want to make jam, the technique for making freezer jam printed on the instructions inside a box of Pomona Pectin is still the best. Let us show you. Jam should be bright. Jam should be the color of the fruit from which it was made. Jam should taste like the season of that fruit. So why is most jam on th", "i": ["525 g Strawberries , trimmed and washed", "112 g Sugar", "5 g Pectin , Pomona Universal Pectin", "0.3 g Malic acid", "90 g Cold water", "5.5 g Calcium water , from Pomona Universal Pectin packet", "90 g Water", "1.3 g Calcium powder"], "s": ["See the Difference. Smell the Difference. Taste the Difference.", "Prepare the Jam Containers", "Clean the Fruit", "Macerate the Fruit", "Activate Pectin", "Make the Calcium Water", "Mix It Up", "Pack the Jam"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/freezer-jam-why-it-s-the-real-jam"}, {"id": 903, "t": "Use Your Microwave to Make Buttery Bourbon Caramels — Right Now", "c": "Baking", "d": "Have you been wanting to make caramels but feel too intimidated by some of the instructions to try the process for the first time? Wipe down the sides of the pan with a damp pastry brush frequently to avoid crystallized sugar to form. Take the caramel to the soft ball stage of candy making, and test it by dropping a ball of hot syrup into cold water. Most folks have already moved on to another rec", "i": ["233 g Heavy cream", "268 g Sugar", "108 g Clover honey", "59 g Bourbon whiskey", "1 g Flake sea salt", "25 g Butter , unsalted"], "s": ["Get everything together", "Cook the caramels", "Stir in the butter and set", "Portion the caramels"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/use-your-microwave-to-make-buttery-bourbon-caramels-right-now"}, {"id": 904, "t": "Steamy-Hot Sexy Whole Fish in 5 Minutes—It’s Microwave Magic", "c": "Baking", "d": "You put a whole fish in the microwave?! Blasphemy! What has the world come to? Really, ChefSteps? Take a breath. Let us explain. The microwave can be a tool for quick reheats of leftovers. sure. But if you know how to cook, the microwave can truly be a great cooking tool. When you score a whole fish, flavor it, and wrap it in plastic wrap, you are setting up a steaming station. This is akin to the", "i": ["1 Whole fish , 1.5-2# - Soy sauce, as needed - Fresh ginger root, as needed - Garlic, as needed - Habanero pepper(s), as needed - Fresno chile(s), as needed - Green onion(s), as needed - Cilantro, as needed - Basil , fresh , as needed - Lime(s) , fresh , as needed", "Soy sauce, as needed", "Fresh ginger root, as needed", "Garlic, as needed", "Habanero pepper(s), as needed", "Fresno chile(s), as needed", "Green onion(s), as needed", "Cilantro, as needed", "Basil , fresh , as needed", "Lime(s) , fresh , as needed"], "s": ["Prep the Fish", "Garnish the Fish", "Wrap the Fish", "Cook the Fish"], "tips": ["A Note on Fresh Fish", "On Cooking Fresh Aromatics", "On Water, Steam, and Pressure"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/steamy-hot-sexy-whole-fish-in-5-minutes-it-s-microwave-magic"}, {"id": 905, "t": "It’s a Microwave Frenzy: From Epic Delicious to Epic Fail!", "c": "Baking", "d": "We spent the day with seven microwaves, trying to invent the impossible and create some pretty amazing dishes through the process. No reheating coffee or making things explode. We wanted to make truly incredible food in the microwave. Have you ever steamed whole fish in a microwave? Did you know it can actually be amazing? Have you ever made perfect scrambled eggs (and we mean that word—PERFECT) i", "i": [], "s": ["We learned some things", "Steaming", "Caramelizing food", "Searing", "Baking", "Deep frying", "More experimenting we did that we think you will like"], "tips": ["HOW DOES A MICROWAVE REALLY WORK?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/it-s-a-microwave-frenzy-from-epic-delicious-to-epic-fail"}, {"id": 906, "t": "An Instant Way to an Even Better Hollandaise", "c": "Baking", "d": "4 ingredients, 3 steps, 2 minutes. Time to make hollandaise an easier way. The traditional method for making hollandaise involves 3 bowls, 3 pots, a bain-marie (that’s a double boiler in ’merican), a whole lot of ingredients, and a finicky technique. You know why people still think we need to make hollandaise the pain-in-the-ass way? A Frenchman named Carême codified the sauce as one of the French", "i": ["Butter , (100g butter per egg)", "150 g Egg(s) , 3 large", "40 g Lemon juice , 1 lemon", "8 g Salt", "Tarragon , fresh, optional , as needed", "Chicken bouillon powder, as needed"], "s": ["Old school vs new school", "Cut butter and bring to boil", "Question: Why aren’t we clarifying the butter?", "Add most of the ingredients to the blender", "Make the hollandaise", "Question: Why whole eggs and not just yolks?", "Go deeper into a Hollan-daze"], "tips": ["Get more juice from your lemons", "Make it Béarnaise", "Make it Foyot"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/an-instant-way-to-an-even-better-hollandaise"}, {"id": 907, "t": "A Little Bit of Glacier in Your Glass", "c": "Baking", "d": "Imagine glacier ice cubes—zero bubbles, zero cracks, so clear they become invisible in the glass—floating in your cocktail. How? It’s simple. All you need is a small insulated cooler and water. Let’s go! This summer, Grant ended up 2,300 miles away from Seattle, on a sailboat in Alaska with his family. Grant’s father-in-law took small chunks off a glacier to make cocktails. This meant the family d", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Water, as needed", "Water, as needed"], "s": ["Get the right cooler for your freezer", "Fill cooler", "Put the cooler in the freezer", "Take the cooler out of the freezer", "Take the ice out of the cooler", "Separate the ice from the glacier", "Saw the ice into cubes", "Make cocktails", "Your house = your rules", "Let’s make some more ice, baby!", "Behind the scenes: the bandsaw"], "tips": ["Don’t make more ice in your freezer", "Make the right-sized glacier for your glass", "Freeze your ice cubes well"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/a-little-bit-of-glacier-in-your-glass"}, {"id": 908, "t": "Clarified Milk-Washed Punch", "c": "Baking", "d": "Put a little time into making this milk-washed punch and you won’t need to shake any refills at your cocktail party. The final punch is deceptively lush and seductive. Plus, the milk-washing process helps to preserve the punch, which means a big batch can sit in your fridge for a long time. Having a cocktail party? Pull out a pitcher of this elixir and pour it into glasses filled with glacier ice.", "i": ["300 g Lemon juice , about 8 lemons", "150 g Fresh lime juice , about 5 large limes", "783 g Pineapple , 1 large", "0.47 g Coriander seeds", "1.2 g Star anise , whole", "4 Cloves", "3.1 g Cinnamon stick(s) , 1 stick", "710 g Dark rum", "710 g White rum", "164 g Bourbon whiskey", "34 g Pernod", "47 g Angostura bitters", "355 g Water", "313 g Sugar", "861 g 2% milk"], "s": ["Peel and juice the lemons and limes", "Make super strong green tea", "Combine the liquids", "Grind the spices and steep", "Strain the punch", "Time to milk wash", "Strain the curds away", "Pour the punch and enjoy", "Try some other cocktails!"], "tips": ["Don’t throw away that pineapple!", "LEVEL-UP! Wash twice for crystal clear punch"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/what-s-the-secret-to-making-the-world-s-tastiest-punch-wash-it-with-milk"}, {"id": 909, "t": "Help Us Create the Ultimate Roast Chicken", "c": "Meat", "d": "Do you like crackling crisp skin on your roast chicken? Juicy white meat? Are you a thigh fan? Or do you just want it done in 45 minutes flat? Lemony? Herby? Crusted with salt and in your mouth now? Let us know what you want in the comments below and help our kitchen team create your new favorite roasted chicken recipe. save Print", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/help-us-create-the-ultimate-roast-chicken"}, {"id": 910, "t": "Fully-Loaded Focaccia", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Focaccia is a chewy, flavorful, perfectly salty flatbread that pairs just as beautifully with lazy summer antipasto as it does a hearty plate of spaghetti and meatballs. Its charming dimples and craggy, bubbly interior make it a perennial crowd favorite. In Italy, focaccia is a hyper-local food, with a wide variety of textures and toppings. Think olives, peppers, little fishes, potatoes, onions, s", "i": ["338 g Bread flour", "1.8 g Active dry yeast", "7.5 g Salt", "2 g Fennel seeds , fine ground", "2 g Chile flakes , fine ground", "263 g Water", "54 g Honey , divided", "26.8 g Extra-virgin olive oil , plus more for finishing", "Neutral oil , for coating pan , as needed", "Semolina flour , for dusting pan , as needed", "Toppings , such as olives, peppers, anchovies, pickled or roasted garlic, onions, fresh or sundried tomatoes , as needed", "1 Egg(s)", "40 g Milk", "Flake sea salt, as needed"], "s": ["Combine dry ingredients", "Combine wet ingredients", "Mix the dough", "Let the dough proof overnight", "Fold the dough, let it rest, repeat", "Prepare your baking pan and transfer the dough", "Add toppings and egg wash", "Bake", "Serve it up", "Get up in there"], "tips": ["Bread-Time Magic—What's Happening During Proofing and Folding?"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fully-loaded-focaccia"}, {"id": 911, "t": "Hot Tip: Simple Schmaltz + Gribenes", "c": "Baking", "d": "Schmaltz—golden, rendered chicken fat—isn’t as widely appreciated as it should be, and that’s why you’re probably going to have to make it yourself. But it’s as easy as can be: Simmer chopped up chicken skin in water until the water evaporates, the fat renders, and the pieces of skin become golden brown and crispy, and you’ll have a bunch of delicious chicken fat to cook with (as in our Chicken Fa", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Chicken skin and trimmings, as needed - Water, as needed", "Chicken skin and trimmings, as needed - Water, as needed", "Water, as needed"], "s": ["Simple schmaltz & gribenes"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hot-tip-simple-schmaltz-gribenes"}, {"id": 912, "t": "Lemon Beurre Blanc With a Twist—Four Ways to Transform the Iconic Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "Lemon beurre blanc is the classy, saucy addition your culinary repertoire has been missing. Silky and luscious and undeniably buttery, we hit it with just enough lemon at the end to keep it bright without losing any of that richness you came here for—butter is in the title, after all. But beurre blanc is more than a sauce. It’s actually the basis for some clever hacks we’ve come up with to transfo", "i": ["454 g Whole butter , unsalted", "20 g Shallot(s) , minced, about 1", "110 g Dry white wine", "2 g Kosher salt", "110 g White wine vinegar", "1 g White pepper , finely ground", "0.5 g Xanthan gum , optional", "Lemon juice, as needed", "Lemon zest, as needed", "150 g Beurre Blanc , homemade", "50 g Egg yolk(s) , from 2–3 eggs", "10 g Dijon mustard", "Cayenne pepper, as needed", "Salt, as needed", "14 g Tarragon , fresh leaves, minced", "30 g Tomato paste", "16 g Black Moroccan olives , cured, minced", "Sun-dried tomatoes , optional , as needed", "1 g Garlic , about 1 clove, microplaned", "1 g Black pepper , coarsely ground", "30 g Capers , whole", "12 g Parsley , fresh, minced"], "s": ["Let’s Meet Our Hero: Beurre Blanc", "We’ve got this—let’s make our beurre blanc", "Give it a Twist—Four Ways to Transform Beurre Blanc", "Beurre Blanc to Hollandaise", "Beurre Blanc to Béarnaise", "Beurre Blanc to Sauce Choron", "Beurre Blanc to Piccata"], "tips": ["Science Break: Emulsions"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/lemon-beurre-blanc-with-a-twist-four-ways-to-transform-the-iconic-sauce"}, {"id": 913, "t": "Homemade Baked Bao", "c": "Baking", "d": "Smell that? That warm, eggy, slightly sweet, but oh-so-savory scent wafting from your oven? We’ve eaten enough baked bao over the last few weeks to know that smell on an intimate level, and trust us, we are never mad about it. A traditional Chinese bun, bao have been adapted in countless ways and come in all manner of shapes, sizes, and cooking methods. Many bao are steamed, but ours go the happy ", "i": ["270 g Milk", "74 g Vegetable oil", "110 g Egg(s) , about 2 large, divided", "7 g Active dry yeast", "450 g Bread flour , unbleached", "50 g Sugar", "8 g Kosher salt", "Filling of choice, as needed", "Furikake , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Whisk wet ingredients", "Sift in dry ingredients and mix dough", "Proof the dough", "Portion the dough and fill the bao", "Proof again", "Bake", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bao-down-homemade-buns"}, {"id": 914, "t": "Superb, Simple Spaetzle", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Part noodle, part dumpling, all comfort—spaetzle is the miracle side dish you’re not making. And why not? The batter comes together in a flash, with a quick mix of pantry staples that you shape right over a pot of boiling water, and then finish with a bit of butter and herbs. Oh, and did we mention you can have them on the table in about 30 minutes? The decadence-to-ease ratio is out of this world", "i": ["300 g Bread flour , unbleached", "0.4 g Nutmeg", "5 g Salt", "1 g White pepper", "230 g Sour cream", "210 g Whole eggs , about 4 large", "50 g Egg yolk(s) , about 3 large", "1 g Butter , unsalted"], "s": ["Sift dry ingredients", "Whisk wet ingredients", "Add wet ingredients to dry", "Shape and cook spaetzle", "Finish with a quick saute", "Tbsp.", "Serve it up"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/superb-simple-spaetzle"}, {"id": 915, "t": "Dine In: Three Courses for a Special Occasion", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Cooking is hot. And we’re not just talking temperature. When you cook for someone special—or with that special someone—you get a chemical boost that, unscientifically, makes food taste better. Your senses fire, endorphins abound, serotonin rises, and the dopamine kicks in. That’s not just love, that’s nourishing someone you love with a dope dinner. With your love life in mind, we’ve crafted an exc", "i": ["100 g Kale , one small bunch", "200 g Radicchio di Treviso , one small head", "20 g Egg yolk(s) , about 1", "2 g Garlic , minced, about 1 clove", "40 g Lemon juice , about 1 lemon", "Lemon zest , from 1 lemon , as needed", "30 g Parmesan , grated", "30 g Fish sauce , we used Red Boat", "0.5 g Black pepper , ground", "160 g Olive oil , light", "20 g Mint , freshly picked leaves", "25 g Cilantro , freshly picked leaves", "10 g Fresno chile(s) , freshly sliced", "Lemon wedges, as needed", "500 g Celery root", "100 g Water", "100 g Butter , unsalted", "3 g Salt", "30 g Extra-virgin olive oil", "440 g Fingerling potatoes , about 12 medium-sized", "30 g Apple cider vinegar , we like Bragg", "165 g Cipollini onions , about 6–8", "18 g Sugar", "Chives, as needed - Chervil, as needed - Flat-leaf parsley, as needed", "Chervil, as needed", "Flat-leaf parsley, as needed", "454 g Beef tenderloin , (about 2 steaks) 1 recipe Black Truffle Butter Sous Vide Sauce", "1 recipe Black Truffle Butter Sous Vide Sauce"], "s": ["First Course: Spicy Caesar With Fresno Chili and Parmesan Frico", "Select salad greens", "Whip up dressing", "Get your frico on", "Assemble the salad course", "Second Course: Black Truffle Butter Filet Mignon with Celery Root Purée, Roasted Potatoes, and Cipollini Onions", "Prepare the celery root purée", "Prep the potatoes", "Prep the onions", "Make garlic butter", "Prep the potatoes, round two", "Gather the garnish", "Sous vide beef in the black truffle sauce", "Finish the potatoes and onions", "Assemble the main course", "Third Course: Cloud Cake With Fresh Berries and Whipped Cream", "Take this meal to 11 with wine pairings"], "tips": ["Not into truffles? Try one of these sauces instead!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/dine-in-three-courses-for-a-special-occasion--2"}, {"id": 916, "t": "Double Chocolate Tart", "c": "Baking", "d": "Is there such a thing as too much chocolate? “Sometimes it gets a little too intense for me,” a nonbeliever will decry—to whom the chocolate faithful respond, “What is even wrong with you?” So be warned, our intensely chocolate tart is not for the faint of heart. But if you fall into the give-me-all-the-chocolate-you-have-I-dare-you camp, this dessert is squarely up your alley. No part of this tar", "i": ["115 g Salted butter", "85 g Confectioners’ sugar", "200 g Pastry flour", "35 g Cocoa powder", "4.5 g Salt , divided", "3 Egg yolk(s) , divided", "1 Egg(s) , whole", "400 g Valrhona Manjari dark chocolate, 64%", "195 g Whole milk", "240 g Heavy cream"], "s": ["Make the chocolate shell", "Shape the shell", "Blind-bake the shell", "Make the filling", "Fill the crust and bake", "Slice and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/double-chocolate-tart"}, {"id": 917, "t": "Hot-to-Trot Tamales", "c": "Baking", "d": "There are about as many variations on tamales as there are people who love them—which is to say a lot. A traditional dish in Mexico and many parts of Central and South America, tamales consist of masa-based dough filled with any number of meats, cheeses, chilies, vegetables, and seasonings, wrapped into perfect little corn-husk packages, and steamed. If you could gift wrap dinner, it’d look like a", "i": ["Dried corn husks , 1 package , as needed", "560 g Maseca corn tamal mix", "12 g Kosher salt", "9 g Baking powder", "870 g Chicken stock", "325 g Lard", "Filling of choice, as needed", "Toppings , such as salsa, cotija, sour cream, herbs, lime wedges, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Soak husks", "Make the masa mixture", "Whip the lard", "Add the masa mixture to the whipped lard", "Assemble the tamales", "Steam", "Unwrap and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hot-to-trot-tamales"}, {"id": 918, "t": "Level Up Your Grandma’s Pot Roast", "c": "Meat", "d": "In the realm of beef—often, what’s for dinner—the humble pot roast continues to be a crowd-pleasing winner. We’ll investigate the origin of the dish, explore the best techniques for cooking tough cuts, geek out with our local butcher, and develop a killer weeknight recipe for this American household favorite. save Print", "i": ["2 quart Beef broth , low sodium", "2 quart", "Beef broth , low sodium", "32 g Knox gelatin", "4 g Black pepper", "1.8 kg Eye of chuck roll , 4-6 lb", "Salt and pepper , as needed , as needed", "600 g White onion(s) , about 2 medium, sliced", "50 g A.1. sauce", "30 g Ranch dressing powder", "800 g Yukon Gold potato(es) , about 8 medium, cut into 1 in chunks", "500 g Carrot(s)", "300 g Celery , about 4 stalks", "1 Parsley , bunch, chopped"], "s": ["Why Do We Roast?", "Show-and-Tell: Pot Roast Edition", "What Does the Butcher Have to Say?", "Feeling the Pressure", "Level Up Your Grandma’s Pot Roast", "Make the roasting sauce", "quart", "Sear the roast", "Cook the onions", "Pressure cook the roast", "Cook the carrots and potatoes", "Steam the celery", "Garnish and enjoy!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/level-up-your-grandma-s-pot-roast"}, {"id": 919, "t": "Beef Wellington Level 1; The Doughboy", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Winston Churchill was famously discussing the difficulty of cooking a perfect beef Wellington when he said, “It is a riddle wrapped in a mystery inside an enigma.” Well, we’ve unraveled it all—the riddle is a perfectly done tenderloin, the mystery is rich mushroom duxelles in a prosciutto hammock, and the enigma is crescent roll dough from a can. What does it all mean? It’s bloody delicious, that’", "i": ["200 g Shallot(s)", "600 g Cremini mushrooms", "10 g Garlic clove(s)", "100 g Butter", "750 g Beef, center-cut tenderloin , approximately 6 in long", "Salt , to season the tenderloin , as needed", "Pepper , to season the tenderloin , as needed", "10 g Thyme", "4 piece Prosciutto", "4 piece", "Prosciutto", "2 Store-bought pastry dough , we like Pillsbury Crescent Rolls", "1 Egg(s) , for egg wash", "4 piece Prosciutto 2 Store-bought pastry dough , we like Pillsbury Crescent Rolls"], "s": ["Prep the mushroom duxelles", "Prep and sear the tenderloin", "Cook the tenderloin with Joule", "Cook the mushroom duxelles", "Get ready to wrap", "piece", "Wrap and roll", "Seal the roll", "Gussy up that Welly", "Bake the Welly", "Plate and enjoy!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beef-wellington-level-1-the-doughboy"}, {"id": 920, "t": "No-Bake Pumpkin Cheesecake Pie", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pumpkins are lovable in their decorative form—you get to pick your favorite one in the patch, plump and round and simply funny-looking—but we can all agree that pumpkins are especially fawn-worthy when they’re in the form of delicious pie. This Pumpkin Cheesecake Pie is creamy, warm-spiced, and not too sweet. And the coolest part? The filling comes together in a blender, no oven required. It’s a c", "i": ["255 g Graham crackers , for optional homemade crust", "128 g Butter , melted, for optional homemade crust", "440 g Pumpkin purée", "370 g Bulgarian buttermilk , full fat", "100 g Cream cheese , (we use Philadelphia Original)", "50 g Egg yolk(s) , about 3", "21 g Vanilla extract", "150 g Sugar", "5 g Kosher salt", "2.3 g Carrageenan, kappa", "2 g Cinnamon", "0.5 g Ginger"], "s": ["Choose your crust", "So you wanna make your own crust", "Bake your crust", "Assemble your mise en place", "Scale wet ingredients into blender", "Scale dry mixture", "Begin blending wet ingredients and gradually incorporate dry mixture", "Bring the filling to 203 °F / 95 °C", "Cast the filling", "Form the filling", "Chill overnight", "Serve and enjoy!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pumpkin-cheesecake-pie"}, {"id": 921, "t": "Skillet Apple Pie", "c": "Baking", "d": "When it comes to quintessentially American desserts, there are few more revered than apple pie. Classically double-crusted and filled with fresh fruit and warming spices, there’s a reason it’s an anchor of any Fourth of July picnic or Thanksgiving dessert spread. Never mind that the apple pie isn’t strictly an American invention—a hat tip here to its medieval European ancestors. But heck, there’s ", "i": ["2 recipes Buttery, Flaky, All-Purpose Pie Crust (Pâte Brisée)", "1.3 kg Apple(s) , (about 8)", "300 g Light brown sugar", "60 g Cornstarch", "15 g Kosher salt", "5 g Cinnamon , ground", "0.5 g Allspice , optional", "8 g Malic acid", "100 g Maple syrup", "110 g Bourbon whiskey", "20 g Vanilla extract", "Lemon zest , (from 1 lemon)", "1 Egg(s)", "50 g Water , or milk", "30 g Turbinado sugar", "1 Egg(s) 50 g Water , or milk"], "s": ["Make the crust and chill", "Make the filling and chill", "Roll out the bottom crust", "Place bottom crust in the pan, and fill", "Roll out the top crust", "Assemble the pie and chill", "Preheat oven to 450 °F / 232 °C", "Get ready to bake", "Bake three times", "Chill at room temperature overnight", "Eat it"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/skillet-apple-pie"}, {"id": 922, "t": "Slab Bacon", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "It may be convenient to buy packs of presliced bacon rashers to throw in a frying pan for breakfast, but there is nothing like preparing your own. A type of salt-cured pork, slab bacon is taken from the belly or less fatty back of the pig, and can be cooked sous vide with Joule Turbo for 12 to 48 hours, yielding an unparalleled moreish, moist, and tender result. All you have to do is slice and sea", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Slab bacon, as needed - Olive oil , for searing , as needed", "Slab bacon, as needed - Olive oil , for searing , as needed", "Olive oil , for searing , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Know the cut", "Add food to the bag", "Cook sous vide", "Press bacon (optional)", "Sear", "Serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface", "Cover for long cooks"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/slab-bacon"}, {"id": 923, "t": "Oxtail", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "A whole cow’s tail typically weighs about one to 2 kg and is bought skinned and sliced into round sections. Rich in gelatin, there will be a piece of bone and some marrow in the middle of each one. The meat is tough so it’s best when it is cooked slowly to soften it up in stews and soups, just like Grandma made. Cooking it sous vide with Joule Turbo for 24 hours will guarantee a wonderful savory, ", "i": ["1 Beef oxtail , cut at the joints into 7 to 9 pieces - Kosher salt, as needed - Black pepper , ground , as needed - Neutral oil, as needed 60 g Butter 3 Shallot(s) , cut into quarters 3 Garlic clove(s) , sliced - Rosemary , 1–2 fresh sprigs , as needed 250 ml Red wine 55 ml Demi-glace", "Kosher salt, as needed", "Black pepper , ground , as needed", "Neutral oil, as needed", "60 g Butter", "3 Shallot(s) , cut into quarters", "3 Garlic clove(s) , sliced", "Rosemary , 1–2 fresh sprigs , as needed", "250 ml Red wine", "55 ml Demi-glace", "60 g Butter 3 Shallot(s) , cut into quarters 3 Garlic clove(s) , sliced - Rosemary , 1–2 fresh sprigs , as needed 250 ml Red wine 55 ml Demi-glace"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Know the meat cut", "Season and sear", "Make pan sauce", "Add food to the bag", "Start cooking", "Serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/oxtail"}, {"id": 924, "t": "Turbot Fillets", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Turbot is a large saltwater flat fish native to the North Atlantic, Baltic, and Mediterranean seas. It can be a little pricey, but the meaty, firm, white flesh is delicious. Whereas pan-frying and grilling can dry the fillets out, cooking them sous vide with Joule Turbo will enable you to lock in moisture and retain its mild flavor (complemented well by champagne, white wine, and lobster sauces). ", "i": ["2 Turbot fillets", "4 g Salt", "1 g Sugar", "Olive oil, as needed", "4 piece Lemon peel , (optional)", "4 piece", "Lemon peel , (optional)"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Select your product", "Dry-cure and rinse", "Add food to the bag", "piece", "Protect your work surface", "Start cooking", "Sear", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turbot-filets"}, {"id": 925, "t": "Rack of Lamb", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Chops are the priciest cut of meat from the lamb, taken from the ribcage of the animal, and when removed collectively, come in the form of a rack. Serving a rack, which will consist of eight ribs, for your next roast dinner is bound to impress, but it’s essential to get the cooking right. Using Joule Turbo’s sous vide method means you will get exactly the result you want in just two hours. When de", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Rack of Lamb , 8-bone , as needed - Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed - Olive oil , to taste , as needed", "Rack of Lamb , 8-bone , as needed - Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed - Olive oil , to taste , as needed", "Salt and pepper , to taste , as needed", "Olive oil , to taste , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Know the meat cut", "Score unfrenched rack (optional)", "Season the rack of lamb", "Add food to the bag and cook", "French-trim (optional)", "Finish the lamb", "Serve", "Please tell us how it went"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/rack-of-lamb--2"}, {"id": 926, "t": "Roast Beef Silverside", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "The best Sundays always involve a roast dinner, especially when it’s cooked at home for friends and family. As the chef, there is a lot of pressure on you to get it right, but by cooking your joint sous vide, you can’t go wrong. Beef silverside is a cut from the hindquarters of the cow that is large and lean, with little in the way of fat marbling. Depending how you prepare it, there is a risk tha", "i": ["1 Beef silverside joint , trussed", "Salt, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "30 g Thyme , fresh", "30 g Rosemary , fresh", "Demi-glace, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Know the cut", "Season", "Add food to the bag", "Cook sous vide", "Make rub (optional) and brown the roast", "Serve", "Please tell us how it went"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/roast-beef-silverside"}, {"id": 927, "t": "Venison Loin Roast", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "With its subtle gamy taste, ruby red colour, high amounts of protein, and low amounts of fat (gram for gram, less than skinless chicken breast), venison makes a sophisticated—and healthy—option for your next roast. Cooking venison loin sous vide for just one hour means you can retain the juiciness of this lean cut, which can otherwise get dried out. Complementary flavours include red wine, tomatoe", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 Venison loin , whole - Kosher salt , to taste , as needed - Black pepper , to taste , as needed - Olive oil, as needed 2 Butter , knobs 2 Garlic clove(s) , skin removed - Fresh herbs , such as rosemary and thyme , as needed", "1 Venison loin , whole - Kosher salt , to taste , as needed - Black pepper , to taste , as needed - Olive oil, as needed 2 Butter , knobs 2 Garlic clove(s) , skin removed - Fresh herbs , such as rosemary and thyme , as needed", "Kosher salt , to taste , as needed", "Black pepper , to taste , as needed", "Olive oil, as needed", "2 Butter , knobs", "2 Garlic clove(s) , skin removed", "Fresh herbs , such as rosemary and thyme , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Know the cut", "Truss the meat", "Season", "Sear", "Add food to the bag", "Protect your work surface", "Start cooking", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/venison-loin-roast"}, {"id": 928, "t": "Smoky Maple Pork Belly", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Get your hands on a 1.5 kg slab of pork belly and you can make your own bacon for the ultimate full English, or add it to stews, sandwiches, and salads. You can also serve the pork belly whole as a roast, finishing it by searing it on the stove for perfect crispy crackling. When preparing the meat sous vide, you can easily achieve quick-curing in the bag and fuss-free cooking for 7 to 48 hours for", "i": ["1.5 kg One slab pork belly", "85 g Maple syrup", "17 g Liquid smoke", "10 g Black pepper", "4 g Ground dried garlic", "70 g Salt", "90 g Light brown sugar"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Know the meat cut", "Make the quick cure", "Apply cure to the pork belly", "Cook sous vide", "Crisp it up (optional)", "Serve"], "tips": ["Protect your work surface", "Cover for long cooks"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smoky-maple-pork-belly"}, {"id": 929, "t": "Everything Nice Jerk Chicken Legs", "c": "Baking", "d": "Bananarama says it’s a cruel summer, but they haven’t had Everything Nice Jerk Chicken Legs, so called because—and let’s talk this through up front—this recipe does not feature Scotch bonnets. The oft scorchingly hot peppers are not always a crowd-friendly ingredient, and this jerk chicken is meant to play nice at all your summer barbecues. Rather, the spice blend is layered with tang, earthiness,", "i": ["8 Chicken leg(s) , skin on", "0.8 g Bay leaf", "1.2 g Cloves", "5.5 g Smoked salt", "5.5 g Kosher salt", "6.5 g Cinnamon", "10 g Allspice", "15 g Paprika (hot/picante)", "15 g Dried garlic flakes", "18.5 g Fenugreek seeds", "24 g Black pepper", "24 g Fresh ginger root", "41 g Brown sugar", "Jalapeño(s) , grilled, optional , as needed", "Thinly sliced green onions , optional , as needed", "Lime wedges , optional , as needed", "Fresh herbs , such as thyme, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make the jerk spice rub", "Bag and season the chicken", "Cook chicken sous vide", "Optional: Cool chicken and finish later", "Grill to finish"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/everything-nice-jerk-chicken-legs"}, {"id": 930, "t": "BBQ Pork Cheek Sliders", "c": "Baking", "d": "Pork cheek is a delicious, clandestine cut. It comes from underneath the eye and above the jaw, making it the absolute perfect-sized hunk of meat for a slider. The cheek is unique. It doesn’t carry a lot of fat, but it’s loaded with collagen. Over a long, slow cook, the collagen breaks down, the tissues yield, and the flavor intensifies. The result is a pudgy morsel of incredibly tender, yet tooth", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Pork cheeks, as needed 1 recipe Slider Buns 1 recipe Soft Roll Seed Mix 1 recipe Red Coleslaw - Barbecue sauce , we used Sweet Baby Ray’s , as needed - Chicken demi-glace , we used Glace de Poulet Gold , as needed", "Pork cheeks, as needed 1 recipe Slider Buns 1 recipe Soft Roll Seed Mix 1 recipe Red Coleslaw - Barbecue sauce , we used Sweet Baby Ray’s , as needed - Chicken demi-glace , we used Glace de Poulet Gold , as needed", "1 recipe Slider Buns", "1 recipe Soft Roll Seed Mix", "1 recipe Red Coleslaw", "Barbecue sauce , we used Sweet Baby Ray’s , as needed", "Chicken demi-glace , we used Glace de Poulet Gold , as needed", "60 g Poppy seed", "60 g Sesame seeds", "3 g Ajwain seeds", "6 g Caraway seeds , ground", "20 g Salt , Maldon flake", "12 g Hawaiian black salt"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make slider buns and top with seed mix", "Make the slaw", "Sauce those cheeks", "Enjoy!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bbq-pork-cheek-sliders"}, {"id": 931, "t": "Campfire Chicken and Corn Dumplings", "c": "Baking", "d": "It was 9 °F when we arrived at Pipestone Canyon Ranch in Eastern Washington’s Methow Valley. Greeted by icy mountain air and curls of campfire smoke, we stood in awe of the snow-blanketed property. Thick cloud cover helped keep the temperature bearable, while a trio of bonfires warmed our hands and cheeks. A pristine sledding hill beckoned the offspring—and a few brave adults. At the foot of the s", "i": ["3 quart Water", "3 quart", "Water", "142 g Chicken bouillon powder , 5 oz, our favorite brand:", "2 g Black pepper", "907 g Chicken thighs , 2 lb, cut into bite-sized pieces", "210 g Onion(s) , 1 medium onion, cut into ½ in chunks", "140 g Corn , frozen, thawed", "50 g Milk", "87 g Egg(s) , approx 2", "8 Jalapeño(s) , seeded", "150 g Bread flour", "50 g Cornmeal", "4 g Baking soda", "7 g Salt", "140 g Oyster mushrooms , cut into bite-sized pieces", "160 g Celery , diced", "100 g Leeks , cut into ¼ in coins", "42 g Parsley , 1 bunch, roughly chopped", "2.5 g Thyme , chopped", "16 g Chives , minced", "50 g Green onion(s) , 1 bunch, ¼ in chunks", "Cream , for garnish , as needed", "2 g Pepper"], "s": ["Make the soup base and cook the chicken", "quart", "Make the dumpling batter", "Cook the dumplings", "Add the vegetables", "Garnish and serve!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/campfire-chicken-and-corn-dumplings"}, {"id": 932, "t": "Crispy Chicken-Skin Taco Shells", "c": "Baking", "d": "Delicate, yet crisp—with a crackling bite reminiscent of chicharróns—these taco shells fashioned from fried chicken skin will delight even the most ardent soft-taco lover at the table. There is a comforting chicken essence, but the technique doesn’t yield an overly poultry-ish shell. This is about texture—which is why we like to fill these crisp carriers with a flavor-packed poke. We’ve also used ", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 3 Chicken leg(s) , large, skin-on - Fry oil, as needed", "3 Chicken leg(s) , large, skin-on - Fry oil, as needed", "Fry oil, as needed"], "s": ["Remove the chicken skin", "Blanch the chicken skin", "Cool the chicken skin", "Cut your taco-shell molds for frying", "Shape your taco-shell molds", "Trim your chicken skins for taco shells", "Fry your chicken skin into crispy taco shells", "Remove the crispy chicken-skin taco shells from their molds while still hot", "Fill your taco shells!", "Or skip the mold and make nachos!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crispy-chicken-skin-taco-shells"}, {"id": 933, "t": "Easy, Amazing Pressure Cooker Shepherd’s Pie", "c": "Baking", "d": "A hot, comforting meal for a cold, rainy day, shepherd’s pie only has two constants: a meaty center and a mashed potato crust. In our simple take on the Irish staple, everything goes in the pressure cooker at once—everything! Then you remove the potatoes, mash ’em up, and brown the top of the pie for a crisp, cheesy crust. You heard correctly. This is our attempt at making a fast and easy shepherd", "i": ["2 kg Beef chuck , about 4 lb is fine for this recipe", "1 Gravy seasoning packet , or equivalent", "2 Sweet onion(s) , diced", "6 Carrot(s)", "3 Russet potato(es)", "3 Parsnips", "1 Parsley , bunch", "Cheese , to put on top , as needed", "Milk , (optional) , as needed", "Salt, as needed", "Fresh herbs , (optional) , as needed", "Butter , (optional) , as needed", "Horseradish , grated (optional) , as needed", "3 Russet potato(es) 3 Parsnips", "2 Green onion(s) , bunch"], "s": ["Gather your ingredients", "Prep meat", "Begin cooking", "Prep potatoes and parsnips for cooking", "This is how they look, raw, in the pressure cooker", "This is how they look after cooking", "On with the pressure-cooking", "Mash the potatoes and parsnips", "Season and garnish the pie filling", "Top with mashed potatoes and parnsips", "Add cheese, if you please", "Broil and serve!", "Enjoy!", "Want some??"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/easy-amazing-pressure-cooker-shepherd-s-pie"}, {"id": 934, "t": "Turn Cheap Kosher Salt Into Fancy, Flaky Salt Crystals", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Everyone talks about all the fancy salts these days—Maldon this, Jacobsen that—and they are great salts; don’t get me wrong. But the best part is not the flavor. They all taste like salt—and bottled-water branding comes to mind. What makes fancy flake salt awesome is the texture—light, crispy, beautiful, airy crystals that make any dish even better. What if you could turn the cheapest salt you can", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 1 kg Kosher salt - Water, as needed", "1 kg Kosher salt - Water, as needed", "1 kg Kosher salt", "Water, as needed", "1 kg Kosher salt 4 kg Water"], "s": ["Redissolve your kosher salt", "It should look like this", "Recrystalize into fancy, flaky crystals", "When they sink, they are ready", "Drain and let dry", "Master the Technique"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/turn-cheap-kosher-salt-into-fancy-flaky-salt-crystals"}, {"id": 935, "t": "Salmon & Opal Apple Poke", "c": "Baking", "d": "Close your eyes. You’re on a beach. The sun warms your face. With an icy mai tai in one hand and a pair of chopsticks in the other, you dig in to your oceanside lunch. A sour pop, a juicy smack, and a tinge of heat builds as you eat. Rich salmon and creamy avocado anchor this aromatic, flavor-packed poke—the now-ubiquitous raw-fish chopped salad from Hawaii. This dish was born out of a craving for", "i": ["12 g Coconut vinegar , 1 tbsp", "16 g Coconut aminos , 1 tbsp", "6 g Sesame oil , 3 tsp", "20 g Shallot(s) , 1 tbsp or ½ small shallot", "Thinly sliced green onions , 2 green onions (just the greens), 5 g reserved for garnish", "150 g Salmon , diced (5 oz)", "100 g Avocado(s) , ½ small avocado", "70 g Opal apple , (or your favorite apple), small diced, ½ apple or 1 cup", "4 g Fresno chile(s) , or Thai bird chiles, minced, ½ tbsp", "1.5 g Toasted premium white sesame seeds , ½ tsp", "1.5 g Toasted premium black sesame seeds , ½ tsp", "Cilantro leaves , optional for garnish , as needed", "25 g Lime juice , fresh (from 1/2 lime)", "Sea salt and black pepper, to taste, as needed"], "s": ["Mix dressing", "Combine diced ingredients", "Assemble your poke", "Enjoy!", "Gone Fishing"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/salmon-opal-apple-poke"}, {"id": 936, "t": "Red Wine–Poached Pears", "c": "Sauce", "d": "An elegant dessert needn’t be difficult. This deceptively simple, classic sweet is destined for your dinner-party shortlist. Fragrant, warm spices marry your favorite red wine to create a bright, aromatic sauce for poaching floral pears. Serve sliced pears—or keep them whole for a more dramatic look—atop vanilla ice cream, or offer a bowl of fluffy whipped cream alongside. No matter how you serve ", "i": ["4 Pears , whole", "1 Red wine , bottle or 750 ml", "Whole mace, as needed", "1 g Nutmeg", "5 g Cinnamon stick(s)", "2 g Cloves", "1.5 g Allspice", "135 g Sugar", "Lemon juice , optional, as needed , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Pick your pears", "Make the poaching liquid", "Reduce the poaching liquid; strain; chill", "Peel the pears and reserve in water", "Buff the pear (optional)", "Bag ’em up!", "Cook", "Reduce the sauce", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/red-wine-poached-pears"}, {"id": 937, "t": "Sous Vide Butterscotch Pudding", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Farrah Fawcett hairdo. Diner breakfast. Stranger Things. All of these are retro in the right ways. Know what else is? Butterscotch pudding. It’s a nostalgic dessert that’s actually a banging way to end any meal. With little more than a few key ingredients and Joule, you can have a modernist take on a classic dessert that’s ready to impress—or be eaten on the couch while wearing your jammies. While", "i": ["35 g Egg yolk(s) , about 2", "35 g Cornstarch", "86 g Sugar", "460 g Whole milk", "185 g Light cream (30% milk fat)", "5 g Salt", "5 g Butterscotch extract", "Vanilla wafer streusel , or topping of your choice , as needed", "5 .75 g Salt", "5 .75 g"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Separate your egg yolks", "Combine cornstarch and sugar", "Combine milk, cream, and cornstarch mixture", "Combine egg yolks with remaining sugar and salt; add milk mixture and extract", "Strain", "Fill them jars and seal “fingertip tight”", "Cook for 1 hour", "Chill", "Enjoy that pudding!", "Jars make the best desserts!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/butterscotch-pudding-in-a-jar"}, {"id": 938, "t": "Sous Vide Chocolate Pudding", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Chocolate pudding. There’s never been an easier dessert because whether you’re cooking for kids or a scrum of sophisticated gourmands, everyone loves the stuff. Truly, what’s not to love? Pudding has it all—that creamy-yet-light texture and the decadent chocolate we all crave. And when you cook up your favorite pudding with Joule Turbo, you know you’ll get rich, creamy results every time. Suddenly", "i": ["35 g Egg yolk(s) , about 2", "35 g Cornstarch", "86 g Sugar", "32 g Cocoa powder", "480 g Whole milk", "185 g Light cream (30% milk fat)", "5 .75 g Kosher salt , Optional. We like our stuff at the high end of salt.", "5 .75 g", "Kosher salt , Optional. We like our stuff at the high end of salt.", "5 .75 g Salt", "Salt"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Separate egg yolks", "Combine cornstarch and sugar", "Stir together cocoa powder and cornstarch mixture; gradually add in milk and cream", "Combine egg yolks, sugar, and salt; add hot milk mixture into egg yolk mixture", "Strain", "Fill them jars and seal “fingertip tight.”", "Cook sous vide", "Chill", "Enjoy", "Sweets, please!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chocolate-pudding-in-a-jar"}, {"id": 939, "t": "Rich and Creamy Sous Vide Eggnog Custard", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "For a fresh and festive twist on a holiday classic, whip up this eggnog custard for your nearest and dearest. It’s simple, sophisticated, and super-creamy. The trick is to use your favorite store-bought eggnog as a base and add many, many egg yolks to make this custard holiday-level rich. It’s an excellent option for make-ahead cooking; simply store jars in the fridge and, when you’re ready to ser", "i": ["160 g Egg yolk(s) , about 11", "600 g Eggnog , store-bought", "Cinnamon , for topping , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Separate yolks like this", "Whisk yolks together; add ’nog; whisk some more", "Strain (optional)", "Fill jars and seal “fingertip tight.”", "Cook", "Chill", "Serve!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/rich-and-creamy-eggnog-custard"}, {"id": 940, "t": "Ultimate Korean Fried Chicken", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Korean fried chicken came to be when Americans sold soul food to troops stationed in South Korea during the Korean War. Food vendors capitalized on the popularity of American fried chicken, developing their own versions with a cracklier, thinner coating than the craggy, denser American counterpart. Originally there was simple, naked huraideu—Korean fried chicken sans postfry seasoning—but later ca", "i": ["4 piece Chicken thighs , boneless, skinless, 3.2 lb", "4 piece", "Kosher salt , for seasoning , as needed", "Sugar , for seasoning , as needed", "30 g Cornstarch , 2 tbsp", "160 g Gochujang , 6 tbsp", "200 g Lemon juice , ¾ cup", "114 g Rice wine vinegar , ½ cup", "18 g Garlic , 3 large cloves, minced", "60 g Ginger , 1 fresh ginger root, minced", "60 g Fish sauce , ⅓ cup", "40 g Sesame oil , 2 tbsp", "116 g Salted butter , melted, ½ cup", "420 g Potato starch , 2⅔ cup, plus more for breading process", "420 g Soju , 2 cups, 20% ABV", "96 g Egg(s) , Approx 2 eggs", "9 g Baking powder , 2 tsp", "1.2 g Xanthan gum , 1⁄16 tsp", "250 g Shrimp chips , 1 package, unfried", "Canola oil, as needed", "Scallion(s) , 1 small bunch, sliced , as needed", "0.5 g Sesame seeds"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Season chicken thighs", "Bag and cook", "Make Korean fried chicken sauce", "Prepare three-step breading station", "Cut and bread", "Fry your thighs", "Sauce and serve!", "What to serve with KFC"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-korean-fried-chicken"}, {"id": 941, "t": "Ultimate Poached Egg Upgrade", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Poach your eggs? No, sir. The only way you get textures like these—just-set whites, silky yolks—is by cooking eggs sous vide with Joule Turbo. Stir ’em into carbonara, make a bunch of bomb Benedict for a brunch crowd, or just pop atop your toast and enjoy a serious breakfast upgrade. Oh, and you can make a bunch in advance and store them in the fridge for up to 5 days—eat chilled or heat for 15 mi", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Grade AA extra-large eggs , chilled or room temp , as needed", "Grade AA extra-large eggs , chilled or room temp , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Gently add the eggs and cook sous vide", "Remove the cooked eggs; begone, goopy bits!", "Serve immediately", "Put those eggs to good use!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ultimate-poached-egg-upgrade"}, {"id": 942, "t": "Party Time: Chilled “Smoked” Salmon", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "With the help of a simple liquid-smoke glaze, you can create the best at-home version of smoked salmon with nothing more than a beautiful piece of fish and Joule Turbo. Seriously, the holidays are coming and it’s time to step up your game. This dish has a sophisticated, lightly smoky flavor that is bound to impress and delight at your next event. Serve it as an appetizer or cocktail party snack, p", "i": ["900 g Salmon , a whole side", "Salt, as needed", "Sugar, as needed", "100 g Molasses", "55 g Liquid smoke", "50 g Brown sugar", "5 g Black pepper", "Olive oil , (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Remove the skin", "Cure the fish and rinse it in an ice bath", "Make the glaze", "Pat fish dry and apply glaze", "Bag it up", "Cook for 1 hour", "Ice and chill 8 hours", "Serve!", "And now, for our next party trick..."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/party-time-chilled-smoked-salmon"}, {"id": 943, "t": "Brilliant Butternut Squash", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Vitamin-packed, vibrantly hued, and tasty as all get-out, butternut squash is all the rage for a reason. It has swept the nation as the latest, greatest winter vegetable, which means you have to know how to cook it right. Cooking squash correctly is about getting that tender, slightly toothsome texture and preserving its naturally bright flavor. With Joule Turbo and a vacuum sealer, there’s no gue", "i": ["1 Butternut squash , medium", "Salt, as needed", "Olive oil , roughly 2–3 tbsp , as needed", "16 g Super-Simple Pumpkin Seed Pesto", "20 g Sage , pan fried", "16 g Parmesan , thin slices", "Pumpkin seed oil, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "20 total Sage , pan fried", "20 total", "16 total Parmesan , thin slices"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Trim and peel the squash with a sharp knife", "Portion", "Get it all in the bag", "Seal your veggies", "Cook sous vide", "Serve it up", "Tbsp.", "total"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/brilliant-butternut-squash"}, {"id": 944, "t": "Tender Turnips to Change Your Mind", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "As children, when we heard something was nutritious and inexpensive, it usually meant one thing—boooooring. As adults, food that is good for you and cheap to boot is elusive and desirable. Turnips are one such food—a vegetable that you may have overlooked in your youth that you should absolutely be adding to the weekly repertoire now. Not only do they boast a whole slew of benefits (boosting metab", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 60 ml Olive oil 3 Garlic , cloves, peeled 8 Turnips , medium-sized - Salt, as needed", "60 ml Olive oil 3 Garlic , cloves, peeled 8 Turnips , medium-sized - Salt, as needed", "60 ml Olive oil", "3 Garlic , cloves, peeled", "8 Turnips , medium-sized", "Salt, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Roast your garlic (optional)", "Peel turnips", "Portion turnips", "Season and bag", "Seal your veggies", "Cook sous vide", "Serve!", "Bring on the healthy sides!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tender-turnips-to-change-your-mind"}, {"id": 945, "t": "Bright & Tender Parsnips", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Temperatures are dropping, daylight is lessening, and—as the age-old adage says—winter is coming. Enter the parsnip. This pale, savory cousin to the carrot is arguably one of the tastiest winter vegetables, but finds itself woefully underused in homes everywhere. It’s a shame because the humble parsnip is truly one of the greats—it adds brightness and delicacy to any hearty dish, can be cooked in ", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 60 ml Olive oil 3 Garlic clove(s) 3 Parsnips , large 1 Thyme , fresh sprig - Salt, as needed", "60 ml Olive oil 3 Garlic clove(s) 3 Parsnips , large 1 Thyme , fresh sprig - Salt, as needed", "60 ml Olive oil", "3 Garlic clove(s)", "3 Parsnips , large", "1 Thyme , fresh sprig", "Salt, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Roast your garlic (optional)", "Peel ’em good", "Portion those parsnips", "Bag and season", "Seal your veggies", "Cook for 30 minutes", "Serve", "Bring on the braised meats!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/bright-tender-parsnips"}, {"id": 946, "t": "Pumpkin Pie in a Jar", "c": "Baking", "d": "A new fall tradition is born. Presented in sweet little mason jars, these personal pumpkin pies will delight your friends and family with silky texture and lively flavor. And because you can make them in advance, you can relax knowing dessert will be an easy-to-serve delight. save Print", "i": ["425 g Pumpkin purée", "165 g Sugar", "2 g Cinnamon , ground", "0 g Nutmeg", "1 g Ginger", "0 g Cloves , ground", "0 g Allspice , ground", "2 g Kosher salt", "110 g Whole eggs , about 2", "370 g Evaporated milk", "2 .5 g Cinnamon , ground", "2 .5 g"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Combine ingredients and mix", "Add those eggs", "Add evaporated milk", "Strain (optional)", "Transfer to the jars; seal", "Cook sous vide", "Chill", "Serve!", "Jars make the best desserts!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/pumpkin-pie-in-a-jar"}, {"id": 947, "t": "Beautiful, Aromatic Beets for Any Occasion", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "It's plain and simple—we love beets. Sliced over yogurt, chilled for a cheese plate, or partnered with an earthy meat braise, beets are a dreamy combination of sweet and savory—with impeccable color and mouthfeel to boot! Using Joule Turbo and a vacuum sealer, it’s effortless to dial in the texture, trap tantalizing aromas, and capture the natural sweetness of this outstanding root vegetable. Once", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 4 - Medium-sized beets, as needed - Salt, as needed - Olive oil, as needed - Citrus zest , optional , as needed - Thyme, as needed", "4 - Medium-sized beets, as needed - Salt, as needed - Olive oil, as needed - Citrus zest , optional , as needed - Thyme, as needed", "Salt, as needed", "Olive oil, as needed", "Citrus zest , optional , as needed", "Thyme, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Peel beets, then slice in half", "Bag ’em up!", "Seal your veggies", "Cook and cover", "Eat those beets", "Need some root veg inspiration? We've got you covered:"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/beautiful-aromatic-beets-for-any-occasion"}, {"id": 948, "t": "Fresh & Vibrant Sweet Potatoes", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Packed with flavor, sweet potatoes—seen here adorned in edible flowers, fresh mint, and spicy peppers—are bright, hearty, and inexpensive. The best thing about these amiable li'l tubers? With nothing more than Joule Turbo and a vacuum sealer, you can easily achieve exemplary sweet-tater texture: tender, but never mushy. Cooked to perfection, these sous vide sweeties are the ideal base for a meatle", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 60 ml Olive oil 3 Garlic clove(s) 4 Sweet potatoe(s) , medium - Salt, as needed", "60 ml Olive oil 3 Garlic clove(s) 4 Sweet potatoe(s) , medium - Salt, as needed", "60 ml Olive oil", "3 Garlic clove(s)", "4 Sweet potatoe(s) , medium", "Salt, as needed", "60 ml Olive oil 3 Garlic clove(s)"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Roast your garlic (optional)", "Use sweet potatoes that look like this", "Cut and peel potatoes", "Slice into evenly sized pieces", "Season and bag", "Seal your veggies", "Cook sous vide", "Serve!", "Need some more tubular tubers? We've got the taters you're craving:"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fresh-vibrant-sweet-potatoes"}, {"id": 949, "t": "Thanksgiving Sauce With Tyler Florence", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Food Network superstar chef Tyler Florence is full of cool ideas, and this gluten-free, made-from-vegetables gravy substitute is both innovative and delicious. Our chefs took his recipe, tweaked it a little bit, and wound up with this savory, flavor-packed sauce you can cook with Joule and then return to the pot to keep warm until it’s time to serve—such a tasty, foolproof way to simplify the Than", "i": ["180 g Butternut squash , 6.35 oz", "54 g Celery , 1–2 stalks", "50 g Carrot(s) , 1 whole", "50 g Sweet onion(s) , about half", "180 g Yukon Gold potato(es) , about 1 whole", "8 g Salt , 1½ tsp", "0.6 g Black pepper , about a pinch", "320 g Chicken stock , 1⅓ cups", "45 g Butter , 3 tbsp", "3.5 g Sage , about 4 picked leaves", "12 g Lemon juice , ¾ tbsp"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Chop, chop", "Pack ingredients into the jar, and seal", "Cook for one hour", "Blend and strain (the straining part is optional)", "Adjust seasoning", "Serve", "Ladle this sauce over Thanksgiving favorites"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/thanksgiving-sauce-with-tyler-florence"}, {"id": 950, "t": "Wild Boar Schweinebraten (Roast Pork), With Wild Game Expert David Draper", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Wild hogs have a bad rap as table fare. Truth is, feral pigs are flavorful but can run a little lean since they’re constantly foraging for feed. But a liability for traditional cooking techniques is an opportunity for Joule Turbo. Cooked sous vide, with a traditional marinade of Austrian beer and mustard, this wild boar comes out tender, juicy, and incredibly tasty. OTHER PEOPLE’S IDEAS: A Series ", "i": ["1.5 kg Wild boar shoulder", "5 g Kosher salt", "1 g Black pepper", "Grapeseed oil, as needed", "170 g Brown ale", "50 g Ground mustard", "5 g Paprika", "5 g Caraway seeds", "3 g Cloves", "7 Juniper berries , whole", "10 g Cornstarch", "15 g Water", "1 .4–1.8 kg Wild boar shoulder", "1 .4–1.8 kg"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Know your meat", ".4–1.8 kg", "Let’s talk about salt-n-pepa", "Brown it", "Time for a beer", "Bag it", "See you tomorrow!", "Get on the gravy train", "Pig out!", "Thanks, David! Got any more wild game recipes?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/wild-boar-schweinebraten-roast-pork-with-wild-game-expert-david-draper"}, {"id": 951, "t": "Elk in a Smoked Cherry Reduction, With Wild Game Expert David Draper", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Running up to three feet long, the backstrap, or loin, of an elk is a surprisingly tender cut. But it also has little to no marbling, making it the perfect candidate for cooking with Joule Turbo. Preparing the elk sous vide ensures the meat won’t dry out or overcook. For this recipe, ChefSteps guest contributor and wild game expert David Draper smokes cherries before reducing them into a simple pa", "i": ["1 Elk backstrap chunk , 20–25 cm", "5 g Kosher salt", "45 g Butter , divided", "3 Garlic clove(s) , smashed", "2 Thyme , fresh sprigs", "Neutral oil, as needed", "150 g Cherries , pitted and halved", "180 ml Port", "15 ml Balsamic vinegar", "Cloves , a pinch , as needed", "30 g Butter 3 Garlic clove(s) , smashed 2 Thyme , fresh sprigs", "180 ml Port 15 ml Balsamic vinegar - Cloves , a pinch , as needed 15 g Butter"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Know yer meat", "Season", "Bag the elk", "Cook", "Sear for flavor", "Smoke ’em if you got ’em", "Simmer the sauce", "Slice, sauce, and serve", "Thanks, David! Got any more wild game recipes?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/elk-in-a-smoked-cherry-reduction-with-wild-game-expert-david-draper"}, {"id": 952, "t": "Ginger-Chili Duck Legs, with Wild Game Expert David Draper", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Even the most enthusiastic duck hunters are often at a loss when it comes to ideas for cooking the bird’s legs. Enter ChefSteps guest contributor and wild game expert David Draper. His recommendation for tackling this fowl’s tough, lean muscles? Sous vide. Long cooking times break down the meat into delicious little drumsticks made to be picked up with your fingers and eaten like chicken wings. Th", "i": ["12 Duck legs , skin on", "5 g Kosher salt", "75 ml Sweet chile sauce", "30 ml Soy sauce", "15 ml Hoisin sauce", "30 ml Rice wine vinegar", "15 ml Honey", "1 g Fresh ginger root", "Sesame seeds, as needed", "Chives , diced , as needed", "75 ml Sweet chile sauce 30 ml Soy sauce 15 ml Hoisin sauce 30 ml Rice wine vinegar 15 ml Honey 1 g Fresh ginger root"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Grab your duck!", "Salt the duck legs", "Bag the duck legs", "Duck and cover", "Make an amazing glaze", "Crisp that skin", "Toss with sauce, and dig in", "Thanks, David! Got any more wild game recipes?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ginger-chili-duck-legs-with-wild-game-expert-david-draper"}, {"id": 953, "t": "Squirrel Confit-Stuffed Banh Mi, With Wild Game Expert David Draper", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Squirrels have long been traditional hunters’ fare, but this might be the first time these small game animals have received the sous vide-and-confit combo treatment. With this recipe, ChefSteps guest contributor and wild game expert David Draper turns a classic, widely available game meat into a true modern delicacy. After a long cook in duck fat (or olive oil), lean squirrel meat becomes tender a", "i": ["1 Squirrel , dressed", "60 ml Fresh lime juice 30 ml Soy sauce 15 ml Fish sauce 15 ml Rice wine vinegar 12 g Sugar 3 Garlic clove(s) , minced 1 Jalapeño(s) , finely diced 15 ml Sesame oil", "60 ml Fresh lime juice", "30 ml Soy sauce", "15 ml Fish sauce", "15 ml Rice wine vinegar", "12 g Sugar", "3 Garlic clove(s) , minced", "1 Jalapeño(s) , finely diced", "15 ml Sesame oil", "Kosher salt, as needed", "2 Baguette(s) 60 ml Mayonnaise - Sriracha , to taste , as needed - Pickled carrots and daikon radishes , for garnish , as needed - Fresh cilantro , for garnish , as needed", "2 Baguette(s)", "60 ml Mayonnaise", "Sriracha , to taste , as needed", "Pickled carrots and daikon radishes , for garnish , as needed", "Fresh cilantro , for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Your squirrel should look like this", "Make the marinade", "Marinate your squirrel", "Heat sous vide bath", "Drain, dry, and bag", "Cook (and by that, we mean walk away)", "Debone and shred meat", "Build your banh mi and chow down", "Thanks, David! Got any more wild game recipes?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/squirrel-confit-stuffed-banh-mi-with-wild-game-expert-david-draper"}, {"id": 954, "t": "Venison Osso Buco, With Wild Game Expert David Draper", "c": "Baking", "d": "Layered with sinew and covered in silver skin, deer forelegs (or shanks) are an oft-forgotten cut. Wild game expert and ChefSteps contributor David Draper thinks this is unfortunate, since the shanks are the most delicious meat on the animal. Cooked correctly—for a long time and at a low temperature—that tough connective tissue breaks down and dissolves, leaving behind a flavorful, toothsome treat", "i": ["2 Crosscut venison shanks , 2.5–3.8 cm thick", "60 g All-purpose flour", "5 g Kosher salt", "Black pepper, as needed", "0.5 Onion(s) , medium", "1 Carrot(s) , medium", "1 Celery , medium", "3 Garlic clove(s) , smashed", "Olive oil, as needed", "200 g Red wine", "200 g Chicken stock", "400 g Crushed tomatoes", "2 Bay leaf", "Parmesan , grated for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Your meat should look like this", "Secure and season the shanks", "Prep your veggies", "Brown for a boost of flavor", "Start the sauce", "Deglaze and reduce", "Bag those shanks", "Cook", "Let’s eat!", "Thanks, David! Got any more wild game recipes?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/venison-osso-buco-with-wild-game-expert-david-draper"}, {"id": 955, "t": "Black Pepper Chicken, With Chef Gregory Gourdet", "c": "Baking", "d": "Behold, Chef Gregory Gourdet’s winning formula for tender, char-crusted chicken inspired by Thai barbecue. A robust marinade of pepper, sugar, and lemongrass seasons the meat perfectly for a dish you’ll return to time and again. save Print", "i": ["6 piece Boneless chicken breast , skin on", "6 piece", "150 g Lemongrass , thinly sliced", "125 g Garlic clove(s)", "150 g Tamari sauce (gluten free)", "25 g Fish sauce", "25 g Palm sugar", "83 g Black pepper , toasted", "100 g Cilantro , stems, chopped", "25 g Coriander seeds", "2.5 g Kosher salt , or just a pinch", "Grapeseed oil, as needed", "Red pepper , thinly sliced , as needed", "Fresh lime juice, as needed", "Fried onions, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make your marinade", "Spread sauce atop chicken; place in bag; cook", "piece", "Grill!", "Garnish and serve your chicken"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/black-pepper-chicken-with-chef-gregory-gourdet"}, {"id": 956, "t": "Three Asian Grilling Classics Reimagined, With Gregory Gourdet", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Gregory Gourdet—the Top Chef alum at the helm of Portland, Oregon’s Departure—creates modern riffs on Asian classics. Sushi, dim sum, and bibimbap all on one menu? Yes, please! If you’re not lucky enough to feast on pan-Asian cuisine at Departure, you can recreate one of Gourdet’s dishes tonight. For a fresh take on three boldly flavored classics, you just need one simple formula: sauce + sous vid", "i": [], "s": ["Get cooking with Gregory!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/three-asian-grilling-classics-reimagined-with-gregory-gourdet"}, {"id": 957, "t": "Ssamjang Steak, With Chef Gregory Gourdet", "c": "Meat", "d": "A little funky, a little spicy, and a little sweet, this saucy steak packs a flavorful punch. Inspired by Korean BBQ, Chef Gregory Gourdet developed this recipe with the home cook in mind. With three simple steps, it’s as easy to make as your standard weeknight staples—and way tastier. save Print", "i": ["1.4 kg Ribeye steak(s) , (you can also use New York, Tenderloin, or T-bone)", "150 g Doenjang (fermented soybean paste)", "150 g Gochujang", "35 g Green onion(s) , sliced, plus more for garnish", "10 g Garlic , minced", "33 g Shallot(s) , small diced", "35 g Ginger , small diced", "50 g Honey", "20 g Sesame oil", "150 g Rice wine vinegar", "35 g Grapeseed oil , plus more for grilling", "Sesame seeds, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make your marinade", "Season steak; bag with marinade; cook", "Remove steak from water; drizzle with oil; grill", "Garnish and serve!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/ssamjang-steak-with-chef-gregory-gourdet"}, {"id": 958, "t": "Char Siu-Style Pork Tenderloin, With Chef Gregory Gourdet", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "This dish is inspired by Chef Gregory Gourdet’s childhood memories of eating char siu pork from Chinese takeout restaurants. To make his spin on the purplish classic, grab a pork tenderloin—one of the easiest cuts to work with in all of Meatdom—make a simple marinade, cook your tenderloin with Joule Turbo, and finally give it a quick spin on a hot grill to develop a char on the outside. Then it’s ", "i": ["1 Pork tenderloin , whole", "118 g Honey", "5 g Five-spice powder", "5 g Smoked paprika (sweet/dulce)", "4.5 g White pepper", "40 g Shaohshing rice wine", "5.5 g Sesame oil", "150 g Hoisin sauce", "33 g Molasses", "50 g Garlic , minced"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make your marinade", "Prep and season pork; cook", "Grill", "Sauce and serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/char-siu-style-pork-tenderloin-with-chef-gregory-gourdet"}, {"id": 959, "t": "Tips & Tricks: The Best Way to Grill Oysters", "c": "Baking", "d": "It’s known all around the world—well, at least the shellfish world—that Taylor Shellfish Farms raises some of the best bivalves in the biz. Over 120 years old, the company is known for innovation and excellence—but the crew is also known for throwing down some top-of-the-line mollusk recipes. Taylor’s Marco Pinchot has spent years at the company, and he’s picked up some pretty handy culinary skill", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-tricks-the-best-way-to-grill-oysters-with-marco-pinchot-of-taylor-shellfish"}, {"id": 960, "t": "Tips & Tricks: 5 Reasons to Grill With a Pan", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Butter-basted steaks. Freshly opened mussels. Melty queso fundido. Smoky greens. A crust of perfectly browned rice at the bottom of your paella. There are many reasons to grill with a cast iron pan, but these five are some of the tastiest. And then there are the practical reasons: Grilling your goods with a cast iron pan gives you the best of both worlds—you get that signature smoky flavor with no", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-amp-tricks-5-reasons-to-grill-with-a-pan"}, {"id": 961, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Turn Plant Scraps Into Smoked Meals", "c": "Baking", "d": "You don’t need a Big Green Egg to smoke up perfectly pink cuts of meat or flaky fresh fish—all you need is a green thumb. Grilling is fast, but you sacrifice the complex BBQ flavor you get from a low-and-slow turn in the smoker. This trick preserves the speed and ease of grilling but injects some smoky goodness into your food using stuff you’re sure to have lying around—veggie scraps, garden clipp", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-tricks-turn-plant-scraps-into-smoked-meals"}, {"id": 962, "t": "Smoky Salsa Verde", "c": "Baking", "d": "This salsa gives you a lot of bang for your buck—or should we say sour for your dollar? Our smoky take on the Mexican staple has simple ingredients and just two steps: char tart li’l tomatillos on the grill along with some jalapeños and onions for kick, then blend it all up with cilantro and lime juice. Drizzle it on tacos, smother some enchiladas, or brighten up our tongue-searing carne asada keb", "i": ["207 g Sweet onion(s) , about 1 medium", "128 g Jalapeño(s) , about 4 large", "495 g Tomatillos , about 10 large", "66 g Cilantro , chopped, about 1 bunch", "23 g Lime juice", "9.5 g Salt"], "s": ["Char", "Blend", "Salsa time!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smoky-salsa-verde"}, {"id": 963, "t": "No-Hassle Kebabs for a Crowd", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "It’s pretty simple. Meat + stick = happiness. Once you’ve got the formula down, go wild! We really like how simple kebabs are—they make cooking outside a snap because everything gets prepped, cooked, and ready to rumble at home, making the last step quick and easy. (Plus, you’ve got your meat and veg all in one tidy package.) Kebabs can be seared to order over a hot grill, making them the perfect ", "i": [], "s": ["General Kebabery", "Spend some time with Joule", "Cube it up and add flavor", "Prep your accompaniments", "Make up your ’babs", "Grill ’em up!", "Ready, set, kebab!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/no-hassle-kebabs-for-a-crowd"}, {"id": 964, "t": "Carne Asada Chuck Steak Kebabs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Here, a favorite three-chili marinade teams up with a long sous vide cook time to make cheap chuck steak a total star. From there, the spicy meat gets skewered with radishes, red onions, and avocados for a kicker of a kebab. Serve these up in tortillas with bright salsa verde, and you’ve got a perfect all-in-one outdoor meal. Get even more kebab ideas over here! save Print", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 567 g Beef chuck steak 1 recipe Tangy Marinade for Steak Tacos 1 recipe Smoky Salsa Verde 3 Radishes 1 Red onion(s) 1 Avocado(s) , just barely ripe 10 Tortillas", "567 g Beef chuck steak", "1 recipe Tangy Marinade for Steak Tacos", "1 recipe Smoky Salsa Verde", "3 Radishes", "1 Red onion(s)", "1 Avocado(s) , just barely ripe", "10 Tortillas", "3 Radishes 1 Red onion(s) 1 Avocado(s) , just barely ripe"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make your marinade", "Make your salsa", "Gather the supporting cast", "Cube and flavor", "Skewer ’em up!", "Grill and enjoy!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/carne-asada-chuck-steak-kebabs"}, {"id": 965, "t": "Greek-Style Fenugreek-Fennel Lamb Rub", "c": "Meat", "d": "Fragrant fenugreek and fennel seeds team up with fresh herbs for a vibrant rub that’ll remind you of your favorite shawarma joint. Using high-quality spices will make a difference here—we love our neighbors, World Spice Merchants, for their amazing selection. Fresh herbs take the rub up a notch—the rosemary in particular gets smoky and delicious when it hits the grill. We use this rub on our lamb ", "i": ["35 g Fenugreek seeds", "35 g Fennel seeds", "23 g Dried garlic flakes", "12 g Cumin seeds , whole", "30 g Thyme , fresh", "6 g Rosemary , fresh", "6 g Salt", "3 g Black pepper , ground"], "s": ["Blend spices", "Chop herbs", "Combine", "Put it to work!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/greek-style-fenugreek-fennel-lamb-rub"}, {"id": 966, "t": "Lemon-Scented Yogurt Sauce", "c": "Baking", "d": "This yogurt sauce is a quick, easy way to perk up a dish. The yogurt balances spicy meals with a welcome chill, and the lemon doubles down on the sour flavor for another level of interest and intrigue. We whipped this one up to serve with our lamb kebabs, but it’d be great on just about any Mediterranean-inspired dish. Serve atop grilled meat or fish, drizzle over roasted veggies, or just pour in ", "i": ["435 g Greek yogurt", "80 g Lemon juice , from about 4 lemons", "50 g Olive oil , extra virgin", "4 g Lemon zest", "3.5 g Salt", "1.5 g Garlic , minced", "0.6 g Black pepper , ground"], "s": ["Combine all ingredients", "Put a dollop on top!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/lemon-scented-yogurt-sauce"}, {"id": 967, "t": "Greek-Style Lamb Kebabs With Fenugreek-Fennel Rub", "c": "Baking", "d": "Flavor booster, engaged! These lamb kebabs take things up a notch from your average cookout fare. The Greek-style rub alone is enough to delight your palate. Fenugreek and fennel, rosemary and thyme—the gang’s all here. Grill these ’babs up and serve them in a warm flatbread or pita (with lemony yogurt sauce!) for a complete picnic meal. Snag some more kebab ideas over here. save Print", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 567 g Lamb shoulder 1 recipe Greek-Style Fenugreek-Fennel Lamb Rub 1 recipe Lemon-Scented Yogurt Sauce 1 Red onion(s) 1 Cucumber(s) 10 Cherry tomatoes 10 Flatbread , or pita", "567 g Lamb shoulder", "1 recipe Greek-Style Fenugreek-Fennel Lamb Rub", "1 recipe Lemon-Scented Yogurt Sauce", "1 Red onion(s)", "1 Cucumber(s)", "10 Cherry tomatoes", "10 Flatbread , or pita", "1 Red onion(s) 1 Cucumber(s) 10 Cherry tomatoes"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make the lamb rub", "Make the yogurt sauce", "Prep the veggies", "Cube and flavor lamb", "Make some skewers!", "Grill and feast"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/greek-style-lamb-kebabs-with-fenugreek-fennel-rub"}, {"id": 968, "t": "Gochujang Glaze", "c": "Sauce", "d": "Fish sauce and gochujang. What more do you need? We came up with this quick glaze for our Kung Pao Ribs, but we also love tossing it with cubes of pork collar for some Korean-style kebabs. It comes together in a snap on the stovetop and adds a funky, spicy kick to anything it touches. save Print", "i": ["50 g Gochujang", "50 g Sugar , granulated", "30 g Lime juice , fresh", "30 g Fish sauce", "6 g Cornstarch", "4 g Monosodium glutamate (MSG) , optional", "2 g Garlic , peeled and grated", "2 g Ginger , peeled and grated"], "s": ["Make the glaze", "How should I use this glaze?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/gochujang-glaze"}, {"id": 969, "t": "Korean BBQ Pork Collar Kebabs", "c": "Sauce", "d": "This right here is an extra-spicy, extra-fun kebab we came up with when we had skewers on the brain. The gochujang glaze is a sweet-spicy instant classic, and the kimchi gives these a nice, funky kick. Serve up these meaty morsels in lettuce cups for a simple but stellar BBQ treat. save Print", "i": ["567 g Pork collar", "1 recipe Gochujang Glaze", "142 g Kimchi , made with napa cabbage", "2 Jalapeño(s)", "1 Cucumber(s)", "10 Bibb lettuce , large leaves"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make the glaze", "Prep your veggies and lettuce cups", "Cube and flavor the pork", "Skewer time!", "Grill & chill"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/korean-bbq-pork-collar-kebabs"}, {"id": 970, "t": "How to Throw the Ultimate Summer Sous Vide Cookout", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "There’s something magical about cooking and eating outdoors. Smoke, sun, beers, friends—you know, all the good stuff. Here in Seattle, we go into a frenzy in the summer—for as long as the sun graces us with its presence, we feel like we need to be soaking it up. So it’s no surprise cookouts are a Seattle summer staple. But we’re not talking wizened hot dogs or 24-packs of frozen burgers here. Whet", "i": [], "s": ["Sous vide it up", "Play cooler Tetris", "Chill ...", "... and grill", "Some ideas for your next big cookout:", "Chicken Legs", "Pork Shoulder", "Short Ribs", "Kebabs"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/throw-the-ultimate-summer-cookout-with-joule"}, {"id": 971, "t": "Poolside Paella, With Tyler Florence", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Sunscreen, inflatables, a competitive game of Marco Polo—the summer pool party is no joke. You know what else is no joke? Cooking the perfect meal to feed your hungry hordes after a day full of splashing around. But you’re in luck. Superstar chef and friend of ChefSteps Tyler Florence has come up with the ultimate solution: poolside paella cooked with Joule. Paella is one of those crowd-pleasing d", "i": ["225 g Butter , about 2 sticks", "385 g Olive oil , extra virgin, divided, plus more for garnish", "4 Shallot(s)", "7 Garlic , cloves, divided", "1.1 kg White wine , dry, about 1.5 bottles, divided", "1 Thyme , bunch, plus 6 sprigs", "3 Lemon , divided", "Salt, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "1.4 kg Shrimp , peeled and deveined, roughly 3 lb", "1.4 kg Manila clams , in the shell, roughly 3 lb", "8 Orange(s) , divided", "62 g Pimentón de la Vera , or other smoked paprika, divided", "8 Chicken thighs", "8 Chicken drumsticks", "450 g Chorizo , dried, casings removed, about 1 lb", "6 Torpedo onions", "6 Fennel bulb , small bulbs", "227 g Mayonnaise , about 1 cup", "227 g Sour cream , about 1 cup", "4 Roasted red peppers , divided", "1.5 kg Paella rice , about 8 cups", "2 g Saffron threads", "3.9 kg Chicken stock , about 1 gal", "450 g English peas , blanched, about 3 cups", "0.5 Parsley , bunch, for garnish", "0.5 Tarragon , bunch, for garnish", "1 Chives , bunch, for garnish", "8 Chicken thighs 8 Chicken drumsticks 1.4 kg Manila clams , in the shell, roughly 3 lb 1.4 kg Shrimp , peeled and deveined, roughly 3 lb 3 Roasted red peppers , sliced"], "s": ["Preheat Joule to 165 °F / 74 °C", "Make seafood marinade", "Make chicken marinade", "Cook your protein", "Ready ingredients for sofrito", "Make pimentón aioli", "Sear chicken", "Saute sofrito and toast rice", "Deglaze; reduce", "Cook the rice", "Add in chicken and seafood", "Dig in!", "Get inspiration from more of our favorite chefs!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/poolside-paella-with-tyler-florence"}, {"id": 972, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Searing Right on the Embers", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Sometimes the best way to grill is with no grill at all. To give your food that signature charred flavor, all you need are some embers. Just light your charcoal and wait for it to burn red and grey, then place the food directly on the coals, and voilà! The most rustic fire-grilled food of your life. So how does it work? Stacking your food on the coals smothers the embers, blocking airflow and cool", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-tricks-searing-right-on-the-embers"}, {"id": 973, "t": "Going Off Script: Remixing Your Favorite Recipes to Create New, Memorable Dishes", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Cooking is just like any other pursuit: practice makes perfect. Okay, let’s be honest. Perfection may be unattainable. Let’s just say practice makes better. And becoming a better cook is a lifelong journey. From the moment you realize your boxed macaroni and cheese would taste just a little bit better if you threw in some peas and bacon, to the first time you undertake a complete Thanksgiving feas", "i": ["Peaches, as needed - Olive oil, as needed", "Olive oil, as needed", "265 g Balsamic vinegar , 1 cup", "5 Black Mission figs , cut in half - Olive oil, as needed", "Basil , fresh leaves, optional , as needed"], "s": ["New-School Peach Melba", "Make jam", "Make Olive Oil Cake", "Make Jersey cow milk sorbet", "Get yer peach on", "Plate and serve", "Savory-Sweet Grilled Figs", "Make Fromage Blanc Sorbet", "Make Crispy Prosciutto", "Make Basil Oil", "Make a balsamic reduction", "Grill figs", "Plate like you mean business.", "Put that recipe repertoire to good use!", "Whatever you do, don’t forget to photograph your masterpiece and share using #ChefSteps!"], "tips": ["Not a fan o’ the jam?", "Grilling fruit is no sweet task!"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/going-off-script-remixing-your-favorite-recipes-to-create-new-memorable-dishes"}, {"id": 974, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Tiny & Mighty, This Grill Is Hot", "c": "Baking", "d": "Think you need to shell out for a big, fancy grill to achieve juicy cheeseburgers or checkerboard-charred steaks? Think again—because some of the best searing we’ve ever done has been on this super-tiny, rippin’-hot grill. You can achieve truly killer crusts with nothing more than a chimney starter, a bit o’ charcoal to burn, and a grill rack. So whether you’re serving an army of Lilliputians, a f", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-tricks-tiny-mighty-this-grill-is-hot"}, {"id": 975, "t": "Grilled Vegetable Tuna Tartare", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "There are few things that evoke the feeling of summer more than smoky grilled vegetables and fresh-caught raw seafood. So why not put them together? In this twist on one of our favorite preparations—tartare—we grill up fresh-from-the-market veggies hibachi-style and pair them with mild, high-grade ahi tuna. This bright, healthy dish is a perfect afternoon snack to munch on with homemade potato chi", "i": ["165 g Low-sodium soy sauce", "165 g Mirin", "30 g Rice wine vinegar", "10 g Kombu", "50 g Brown sugar", "100 g Scallion(s) , divided, thinly sliced", "10 g Fresh ginger root , thinly sliced", "13 g Garlic , crushed", "150 g Lemon juice", "150 g Fresh lime juice", "1 Zucchini , small", "5 Cherry tomatoes", "1 Cucumber(s)", "1 Bell pepper(s)", "1 Lemon , for garnish (optional)", "113 g Ahi tuna , high-grade", "2 Nasturtium flowers , fresh, for garnish (optional)", "Toasted sesame seeds , for garnish (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Make ponzu", "Prep your grill", "Ready your vegetables and lemon", "Put tuna in the freezer", "Grill your vegetables", "Dice vegetables", "Dice tuna", "Put it all together and serve", "Want to make your meal a bit more substantial?", "Try all our favorite tartare recipes!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-vegetable-tuna-tartare"}, {"id": 976, "t": "Grilled Hamachi Collar With Marinated Mushrooms and Quick Pickles", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Sometimes, the best things in life are simple. Lighting up a charcoal grill. Cracking open a longneck bottle of beer. Making quick and easy food that can feed a crowd. You might be imagining burgers and dogs, corn on the cob, and other summertime American classics. But what if we told you that you could just as easily impress your guests with a hibachi-grilled fish collar and quick-pickled vegetab", "i": ["175 g Low-sodium soy sauce , divided", "165 g Mirin", "485 g Rice wine vinegar , divided", "10 g Kombu", "50 g Brown sugar", "50 g Scallion(s) , sliced, plus more for garnish", "150 g Lemon juice", "130 g Fresh lime juice", "335 g Water", "93 g Granulated sugar , divided", "21.5 g Kosher salt , divided", "100 g Young ginger , thinly sliced", "320 g Persian cucumber(s)", "10 g Hot sesame oil", "750 g Daikon radish , thinly sliced", "1 g Turmeric root powder", "570 g Shiitake mushrooms", "815 g Hamachi collar , 4 collars", "70 g Dry cure , 4:1 salt to sugar", "20 g Fresh ginger root , thinly sliced", "13 g Garlic , crushed"], "s": ["Make ponzu", "Pickle young ginger", "Pickle cucumbers", "Pickle daikon radish", "Prep your grill", "Grill, chill, and marinate shiitake mushrooms", "Dry-cure your hamachi", "Grill that hamachi", "Serve it all together!", "Keep that grill going—we’ve got more where this came from!"], "tips": ["PRO TIP: It’s Mandoline Time, Baby"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/grilled-hamachi-collar-with-marinated-mushrooms-and-quick-pickles"}, {"id": 977, "t": "Hibachi-Cooked Eggplant and Long Beans to Step Up Your Grill Game", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Hibachi. Shichirin. These may sound like difficult techniques that take years to master, but creating Japanese-inspired meals on your own charcoal grill is easier than you think. All you need is a super-hot grill, some ripe vegetables, and a little bit of time to make a perfectly cooked meal that’s impressive as all get-out. So because you love a good cooking project that gets the blood flowing, m", "i": ["10 g Kombu", "165 g Low-sodium soy sauce", "165 g Mirin", "50 g Brown sugar", "30 g Rice wine vinegar", "150 g Lemon juice", "130 g Fresh lime juice", "110 g Canola oil", "25 g Lemongrass , minced", "10 g Serrano pepper , minced", "1.4 kg Long beans , about 1 bundle", "520 g Chinese eggplant , about 3 whole", "Salt, as needed", "Black pepper, as needed", "Chiles , sliced , as needed", "Mint, as needed", "Cilantro, as needed", "Lime(s) , sliced , as needed", "Edible flowers, as needed", "30 g Scallion(s) , sliced", "13 g Garlic , crushed", "20 g Fresh ginger root , sliced"], "s": ["Make ponzu", "Cool; add citrus", "Make the marinade", "Slice and marinate your veggies", "Prep your grill", "Grill!", "Remove from grill and trim", "Serve", "’Tis the season for grilling, and we’ve got you covered."], "tips": ["PRO TIP: Readying Lemongrass"], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/hibachi-cooked-eggplant-and-long-beans-to-step-up-your-grill-game"}, {"id": 978, "t": "Tasty, Tender Baby Bok Choy", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Mild with a hint of pepper, baby bok choy makes a great side dish for stir-fry while also balancing out rich, meaty fare like braised short ribs or sous vide pork belly. What a versatile little sonuvagun! With Joule and a vacuum sealer, you can retain the vegetable’s fresh flavor while achieving a nice texture. This is tried-and-true, never mushy, totally tender bok choy. save Print Explore other ", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 60 ml Olive oil 3 Garlic , cloves, peeled 8 Baby bok choy 1 recipe Tangy Soy-Vinegar Sauce for Baby Bok Choy and Other Vegetables , for garnish (optional) - Parsley , for garnish (optional) , as needed - Sesame seeds , for garnish (optional) , as needed", "60 ml Olive oil 3 Garlic , cloves, peeled 8 Baby bok choy 1 recipe Tangy Soy-Vinegar Sauce for Baby Bok Choy and Other Vegetables , for garnish (optional) - Parsley , for garnish (optional) , as needed - Sesame seeds , for garnish (optional) , as needed", "60 ml Olive oil", "3 Garlic , cloves, peeled", "8 Baby bok choy", "1 recipe Tangy Soy-Vinegar Sauce for Baby Bok Choy and Other Vegetables , for garnish (optional)", "Parsley , for garnish (optional) , as needed", "Sesame seeds , for garnish (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Slice each bok choy in half", "Roast your garlic (optional)", "Season and bag the veggies", "Vacuum-seal your bok choy", "Cook with sous vide for 20 minutes", "Serve it up", "Sous vide veggies allllllllllllll summer long!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tasty-tender-baby-bok-choy"}, {"id": 979, "t": "Tender and Snappy Broccoli", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Broccoli is good when it’s good, yet oh so bad when it’s bad. But have you ever had truly great broccoli? Welp, you are about to—because sous vide broccoli is truly great broccoli. With Joule Turbo and a vacuum sealer, you can cook those little green trees just to the point of being tender yet snappy, with a sweetness that will make even picky eaters smile. And if all else fails, just remember a l", "i": ["1 Broccoli , head", "3 Garlic clove(s) , peeled", "60 ml Olive oil", "1 Rosemary , fresh sprig", "Salt, as needed", "Pepper , (optional) , as needed", "Parmesan , for garnish (optional) , as needed", "Lemon juice , for garnish (optional) , as needed", "Aleppo pepper , for garnish (optional) , as needed", "60 ml Olive oil - Salt, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Trim and portion the broccoli head", "Roast your garlic (optional)", "Season and bag broccoli", "Vacuum-seal your broccoli", "Cook sous vide", "Chow down!", "Or cover that broccoli in cheese. We dare ya."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tender-and-snappy-broccoli"}, {"id": 980, "t": "Crisp-Yet-Tender Rapini", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Rapini, known to many as broccoli rabe, is common in both Italian and Chinese cuisines. This stalky veg may look like a cousin to broccoli, but it’s actually part of the turnip family and should be treated as such. It’s pleasantly bitter and tastes great with rich, braisey meats or mixed into a hot or cold salad. We love the tender crispness you get preparing it with Joule Turbo and a vacuum seale", "i": ["1 Rapini , large bunch, about 460 g", "5.5 g Salt", "Olive oil, as needed", "Pepper , (optional) , as needed", "Pickled red chiles , (optional) , as needed", "Lemon juice , (optional) , as needed", "Lemon zest , (optional) , as needed", "Breadcrumbs , (optional) , as needed", "Parmesan , (optional) , as needed", "5.5 g Salt - Olive oil, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Here is what rapini looks like", "Trim it up", "Season and bag up the rapini", "Seal your veggies in your vacuum sealer", "Cook sous vide", "Serve"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crisp-yet-tender-rapini"}, {"id": 981, "t": "How To Transform Kitchen Scraps Into Modern Dishes, With Brothers & Co.", "c": "Baking", "d": "Childhood: After eight hours of playing outside—because your family didn’t have a computer and Netflix didn’t exist yet—you’d run into the kitchen, open the fridge, and, despite all the containers full of leftovers, yell, “Mom! There’s nothing to eat in this house!” As adults we’re no different. In all probability, right now your fridge is filled with leftovers from your numerous cooking projects,", "i": [], "s": ["Make dressing out of almost anything", "Reinvent days-old veggies", "Use every part of the plant", "Give a second life to stale cooked grains", "When in doubt, make cookies", "Want More From the Brothers?", "Now go forth and create!", "Get inspired by Other People’s Ideas!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-transform-kitchen-scraps-into-modern-dishes-with-brothers-co"}, {"id": 982, "t": "Roasted Carrot Pot de Crème, With Brothers & Co.", "c": "Dessert", "d": "Breathe new life into yesterday’s leftover roast veg—make a savory pot de crème. With just a few adaptations to a classic dessert recipe, Seattle pop-up chef team Brothers & Co. have transformed leftovers into something truly special. Now this is how we want to get our daily serving of vegetables. save Print", "i": ["625 g Heavy cream", "120 g Egg yolk(s) , about 8 yolks", "350 g Carrot(s) , roasted", "5 g Salt", "Sugar , optional , as needed", "5 g Salt - Sugar , optional , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Warm heavy cream", "Separate yolks", "Blend roasted carrots and cream", "Temper cream into egg yolks", "Season", "Strain and cast", "Rest", "Close jars until “fingertip tight”", "Cook sous vide", "Chill", "Serve!", "See more from Brothers & Co."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/roasted-carrot-pot-de-creme-with-brothers-co"}, {"id": 983, "t": "Smoky Ash Aioli, With Brothers & Co.", "c": "Sauce", "d": "You can make something out of everything, even onion skins and vegetable scraps. Seattle food wizards Brothers & Co. turn veggie bits into a smoky ash aioli to pair with cured fish or slather on sammies. save Print", "i": ["Vegetable , bits and scraps, to make smoky vegetable ash , as needed", "200 g Olive oil", "14 g Egg yolk(s) , 1 yolk", "20 g Lemon juice", "4 g Salt", "1.6 g Mustard powder"], "s": ["Make vegetable ash", "Grind vegetables into ash", "Infuse oil with ash", "Combine ingredients to make aioli", "Serve!", "See more from Brothers & Co."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/smoky-ash-aioli-with-brothers-co"}, {"id": 984, "t": "Crispy Rice Puffs, With Brothers & Co.", "c": "Pasta & Grain", "d": "Hate tossing leftover rice almost as much as you hate eating hard, dry leftover rice? Your solution is here. With a little bit of time, you can transform leftover grains into crispy, puffy treats that make awesome toppers to almost any dish. Whether accompanying fried chicken, salad, soup, or tartare, these crackly treats lend professional flourish to your food, showing off your ability to balance", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Leftover rice, as needed - Water, as needed 1 l Frying oil , (we like canola)", "Leftover rice, as needed - Water, as needed 1 l Frying oil , (we like canola)", "Water, as needed", "1 l Frying oil , (we like canola)"], "s": ["Mix leftover rice and water", "Purée rice and water mixture in a food processor", "Dehydrate rice", "Deep-fry", "Serve!", "See more from Brothers & Co."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crispy-rice-puffs-with-brothers-co"}, {"id": 985, "t": "Perfect Pantry Cookies, With Brothers & Co.", "c": "Baking", "d": "Those potato chip bits and slivered nuts stacking up in your pantry? You can use them to make some mighty fine cookies. Seattle-based chefs Brothers & Co. will show you how to make cookies from whatever’s hanging out in your cupboard. save Print", "i": ["1 g Flaxseed meal", "0.5 g Apple cider vinegar", "1 g Water", "0.5 cup Nuts and seeds , various", "0.5 cup Neutral oil", "0.75 cup Sugar", "1 Dates , pitted", "0.5 Banana(s)", "1.5 cup All-purpose flour", "1.5 g Baking powder", "1.5 cup Potato Chips , broken into 1/2 inch pieces", "1 tsp. Flaxseed meal 0.5 tsp. Apple cider vinegar 1 tsp. Water", "1.5 cup All-purpose flour 1.5 tsp. Baking powder 1.5 cup Potato Chips , broken into 1/2 inch pieces"], "s": ["Combine flaxseed meal, vinegar, and water", "tsp.", "0.5 tsp.", "Mix nuts, seeds, oil, and sugar", "0.5 cup", "0.75 cup", "Add fruit and hydrated flaxseed", "Add the rest of the ingredients", "1.5 cup", "1.5 tsp.", "Portion and bake", "Serve!", "See more from Brothers & Co."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/perfect-pantry-cookies-with-brothers-co"}, {"id": 986, "t": "Sweet, Tender Fennel: A Most Satisfying Side Dish", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Need something new for your veggie repertoire? Sweet, bright fennel is a vitamin-packed, aromatic treat that transforms into a tender wonder when you vacuum-seal it and cook with Joule Turbo. With hints of the anise flavor we love from the raw stuff, sous vide fennel mellows and becomes a mild, vegetal treat as it cooks. We top ours with parm, herbs, and lemon to accent the natural sweetness, but ", "i": ["1 Fennel bulb , large", "Salt, as needed", "Olive oil, as needed", "Pepper , for garnish (optional) , as needed", "Fresh herbs , such as dill, chopped sprigs, for garnish (optional) , as needed", "Lemon juice , for garnish (optional) , as needed", "Parmesan , grated, for garnish (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Trim that fennel", "Bag it up; add salt and olive oil", "Seal your veggies", "Cook sous vide", "Slice, garnish, and serve!", "Step up your vegetable game with sous vide"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/sweet-tender-fennel-a-most-satisfying-side-dish"}, {"id": 987, "t": "Yukon Gold Potatoes", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Thin-skinned and yellow-tinged, Yukon Golds pack big flavor in a little package. These all-purpose taters are equal parts starchy and waxy, which makes them perfect for just about any way you like to cook ’em. Here at ChefSteps, we think they’re best when you toss them in a vacuum sealer bag, seal it up, and cook them to perfection with Joule Turbo. Try these tubular tubers tonight for a bright, v", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 4 Garlic clove(s) , peeled, optional 60 ml Olive oil 4 Yukon Gold potato(es) , large - Salt, as needed 1 Rosemary , fresh sprig", "4 Garlic clove(s) , peeled, optional 60 ml Olive oil 4 Yukon Gold potato(es) , large - Salt, as needed 1 Rosemary , fresh sprig", "60 ml Olive oil", "4 Yukon Gold potato(es) , large", "Salt, as needed", "1 Rosemary , fresh sprig"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Roast your garlic (optional)", "Trim and portion the potatoes", "Bag and season", "Seal your veggies", "Cook", "Serve!", "Spud it to me!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/yukon-gold-potatoes"}, {"id": 988, "t": "Fingerling Potatoes With Roasted Garlic and Rosemary", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Is there anything better than making starchy, flavor-packed potatoes? Making foolproof, starchy, flavor-packed potatoes! Joule Turbo and a vacuum sealer can’t be beat when it comes to creating consistently amazing fingerling taters for potato salads, hors d’oeuvres, starchy sides, and more. Seriously, serve these sweet sous vide spuds with octopus or in a salad with confit tuna, smash into a mash,", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units 60 ml Olive oil 4 Garlic clove(s) , peeled (optional) 1 Rosemary , fresh sprig (optional) 12 Fingerling potatoes , washed - Salt, as needed - Pepper , for serving (optional) , as needed - Crème fraîche , for dipping (optional) , as needed", "60 ml Olive oil 4 Garlic clove(s) , peeled (optional) 1 Rosemary , fresh sprig (optional) 12 Fingerling potatoes , washed - Salt, as needed - Pepper , for serving (optional) , as needed - Crème fraîche , for dipping (optional) , as needed", "60 ml Olive oil", "4 Garlic clove(s) , peeled (optional)", "1 Rosemary , fresh sprig (optional)", "12 Fingerling potatoes , washed", "Salt, as needed", "Pepper , for serving (optional) , as needed", "Crème fraîche , for dipping (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Roast your garlic and rosemary (optional)", "Bag it all up", "Seal your veggies", "Cook", "Serve!", "Stellar spuds, all with Joule Turbo!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/fingerling-potatoes-with-roasted-garlic-and-rosemary"}, {"id": 989, "t": "Banana Cream Pie in a Jar", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Authentically southern and decidedly charming, banana cream pie is one of the greats. From Mobile, Alabama, to Norfolk, Virginia, these banana and wafer delights come in all shapes and sizes, but we opt for crafting ’em in a jar. Cooking them with our favorite technique—sous vide—creates an oh-so-creamy, puddinglike texture that pairs nicely with crunchy vanilla wafer streusel. Let Joule Turbo do ", "i": ["120 g Egg yolk(s) , about 8", "15 g Cornstarch", "75 g Sugar , used in two steps", "400 g Whole milk", "160 g Light cream (30% milk fat)", "5 g Salt", "5 g Banana extract", "Banana(s) , for topping , as needed", "Whipped cream , for topping , as needed", "Crunchy Graham Cracker Streusel , for topping, substitute vanilla wafers for graham crackers , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Separate the egg yolks and whites", "Combine cornstarch and sugar", "Make the milk mixture", "Whisk the eggs yolks", "Temper the milk mixture", "Rest and skim", "Fill those jars", "Cook sous vide", "Chill", "Enjoy!", "Jars make the best desserts!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/banana-cream-pie-in-a-jar"}, {"id": 990, "t": "Sous Vide Chocolate Pot de Crème", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Remember those pudding snack cups you loved as a kid? Rich, custardy Chocolate Pot de Crème is that snack cup—only all grown up. We use sous vide to crank out lots of little jars at once—perfect for serving at dinner parties or packing in your fancy adult lunchbox. Your palate might be more sophisticated now, but these creamy treats will easily bring you back to your childhood—if only for a bite. ", "i": ["110 g Egg yolk(s) , about 7", "550 g Ultra-pasteurized heavy cream", "175 g 70% dark chocolate , 70%", "115 g Sugar", "4 g Salt"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Separate yolks", "Make chocolate cream", "Add sugar, salt, and egg yolks; blend again", "Strain", "Skim the surface", "Fill ’em up", "Cook", "Chill in the fridge", "Top and serve!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/chocolate-pot-de-creme-y-all"}, {"id": 991, "t": "Grilled Sous Vide Sausages", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Sous vide and sausage: a combo made in juicy-meat heaven. With Joule Turbo, links cook to a precise temperature so you get perfect flavor and texture every time. We teamed up with our Pike Place Market neighbor Uli’s to bring you this essential guide to cooking up sausages. Use your fave sausage, order direct from Uli’s, or make your own. Any way you stuff it, it’s gonna be good. save Print Explor", "i": ["1 Sweet onion(s) , large", "Neutral oil, as needed", "170 g Light beer", "170 g Stock , such as chicken, beef, or vegetable", "6 Pork sausage(s) , whole"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Slice onion", "Caramelize onions", "Combine onions, beer, and stock", "Get it all in the bag", "Cook sous vide", "Serve the sausages!", "What pairs best with sausages? Everything!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/juicy-snappy-links-with-uli-s-famous-sausage"}, {"id": 992, "t": "Secrets to Eating Well With Jef Nelson of Shogun Fitness", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Eating clean, delicious, convenient meals every day sounds nearly impossible. But we promise it’s not, and we know just the guy to prove it. Enter Jef Nelson. The owner of Shogun Fitness in Seattle, Jef has a simple formula for balanced meals—a healthy mix of lean protein, complex carbohydrates, fibrous veggies, and a little bit of fat. He keeps his clients healthy throughout the week by batch coo", "i": [], "s": ["Now give it a try!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/secrets-to-eating-well-with-jef-nelson-of-shogun-fitness"}, {"id": 994, "t": "Batch-Cooked Chicken Breast, Broccoli, and Potatoes with Jef Nelson", "c": "Baking", "d": "Wanna batch cook a week’s worth of tasty lunches? Ready whenever the midday meal craving hits, this prep-ahead delight from Jef Nelson of Seattle’s Shogun Fitness gets the job done and then some. The recipe follows Nelson’s formula for winning meals: lean protein + complex carbs + fibrous veggies, and a wee bit of fat. Here, fresh herbs lend earthy vibrancy to the chicken. When healthy meals are t", "i": ["510 g Chicken breast(s) , skinless", "Salt, as needed", "Olive oil, as needed", "Fresh herbs , such as rosemary , as needed", "900 g New potatoes", "Garlic clove(s) , about 4–5 , as needed", "Chile flakes, as needed", "3 Broccoli , heads", "1 Lemon , whole", "900 g New potatoes - Garlic clove(s) , about 4–5 , as needed - Chile flakes, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Season and cook chicken", "Prep and cook potatoes", "Prep broccoli", "Brown your chicken", "Pack it all up!", "Heat it before you eat it", "Batch cook the day away!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/batch-cooked-chicken-breast-broccoli-and-potatoes-with-jef-nelson"}, {"id": 995, "t": "Batch-Cooked Flank Steak, Lentils, and Green Beans With Jef Nelson", "c": "Baking", "d": "Wanna batch cook a week’s worth of tasty lunches? Ready whenever the midday meal craving hits, this prep-ahead delight from Jef Nelson of Seattle’s Shogun Fitness gets the job done and then some. The recipe follows Nelson’s formula for winning meals: lean protein + complex carbs + fibrous veggies, and a wee bit of fat. A hit of heat—here we top the beef with fresh chili pepper—adds a little flair ", "i": ["570 g Flank steak", "Marinade , store-bought , as needed", "Salt and pepper, as needed", "Chile flakes, as needed", "450 g Dried lentils", "1.8 kg Water", "0.5 Onion(s) , diced, to garnish lentils (optional)", "Fresh herbs , chopped, to garnish lentils (optional) , as needed", "900 g Fresh green beans", "Fresh chile(s) , sliced, for garnish , as needed", "1 Lime(s) , whole", "570 g Flank steak - Marinade , store-bought , as needed - Salt and pepper, as needed - Chile flakes, as needed", "450 g Dried lentils 1.8 kg Water 0.5 Onion(s) , diced, to garnish lentils (optional) - Fresh herbs , chopped, to garnish lentils (optional) , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Bag up beef with seasoning and marinade; cook", "While the steak cooks, make the lentils", "Prep green beans", "Sear and slice the steak", "Pack it all up", "Heat it before you eat it", "Batch cooking bonanza!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/batch-cooked-flank-steak-lentils-and-green-beans-with-jef-nelson"}, {"id": 996, "t": "Balanced Meal Planning With Jef Nelson of Shogun Fitness", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "At ChefSteps, a typical afternoon in the kitchen involves deep-frying steaks and waffle-ironing tater tots. That’s a lot of temptation for our hardworking kitchen team! To stay healthy, svelte, and full of energy, they rely on fitness experts just like everyone else. And not just in the gym, but in the kitchen too. Enter Jef Nelson. The owner of Shogun Fitness in Seattle, Jef has a simple formula ", "i": [], "s": ["Creating balanced meals", "Protein", "Complex carbs", "Fibrous veggies", "Healthy fats", "Put it all together", "Now give it a try!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/balanced-meal-planning-with-jef-nelson-of-shogun-fitness"}, {"id": 997, "t": "Tips & Tricks: Beer Bath Brats", "c": "Baking", "d": "Nothing beats having friends over for homecooked food, but a few things can easily ruin it. Like spending all of your time in the kitchen and not being able to enjoy any of the fun, for example. It’s your party—don’t you want to actually see the people you invited? Grant has the perfect fix for summer dinner parties and day-long events with people eating at different times: beer bath sausages. Thi", "i": [], "s": [], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/tips-tricks-beer-bath-brats"}, {"id": 998, "t": "How to Design Your Own Sausage, With Uli of Uli’s Famous Sausage", "c": "Baking", "d": "When it comes to wursts, Uli Lengenberg of Uli’s Famous Sausage is the best. He knows his stuff—and how to make the perfect stuffing for any brat, link, or banger. He’s been a German Master Butcher for over 30 years, traveling from Germany to Taiwan before setting up shop in Pike Place Market almost two decades ago. He’s the man with the plan when it comes to franks, but also knows that sausages c", "i": [], "s": ["Cheese", "Texture", "Test and edit", "Be creative", "You’ve Got Your Beer. You’ve Got Your Sausage. Now Get Those Sides."], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/how-to-design-your-own-sausage-with-uli-of-uli-s-famous-sausage"}, {"id": 999, "t": "Homemade Sausage: Like a Master, With a Master", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Our Seattle heritage is a huge part of who we are and what we do here at ChefSteps. From the PNW Salmon that creates sous vide believers to the fresh produce we get daily at Pike Place Market, Seattle runs through the veins of our little development kitchen. And the same can be said for our neighbors all around the market. Seattle is a city rich with history, and nothing embodies that history more", "i": ["Ingredients Edit Scale & Units - Hog casings, as needed - Pork shoulder, as needed - Coriander seeds, as needed - Caraway seeds, as needed - Marjoram, as needed - Thyme, as needed - Rosemary, as needed - Salt, as needed", "Hog casings, as needed - Pork shoulder, as needed - Coriander seeds, as needed - Caraway seeds, as needed - Marjoram, as needed - Thyme, as needed - Rosemary, as needed - Salt, as needed", "Pork shoulder, as needed", "Coriander seeds, as needed", "Caraway seeds, as needed", "Marjoram, as needed", "Thyme, as needed", "Rosemary, as needed", "Salt, as needed"], "s": ["Set up a grinding station", "Check and soak your casing", "Ready your meat", "Season it up", "Grind yer meat", "Set up a stuffing station", "Mix sausage and add it to the stuffer", "Stuff your sausages", "Portion your brats", "Cook and devour!", "Mahlzeit!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/homemade-sausage-like-a-master-with-a-master"}, {"id": 1000, "t": "Righteous Russet Potatoes", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Want to grab something from the pantry to make a great weeknight dinner? All hail the russet potato. Russets contain more starch than any other potato, which makes them creamy when cooked with Joule Turbo in a vacuum-sealed bag. These spuds are velvety soft to the spoon. Get them set to cook for 45 minutes, then sear up a pork chop you prepared with Joule the day before. Easy Monday night dinner, ", "i": ["3 Russet potato(es) 4 Garlic clove(s) , peeled, optional 60 ml Olive oil , about 1/4 cup, or a glug if not making infused oil - Salt, as needed - Pepper , optional , as needed - Scallion(s) , optional, for garnish , as needed - Sour cream , optional, for garnish , as needed", "3 Russet potato(es)", "4 Garlic clove(s) , peeled, optional", "60 ml Olive oil , about 1/4 cup, or a glug if not making infused oil", "Salt, as needed", "Pepper , optional , as needed", "Scallion(s) , optional, for garnish , as needed", "Sour cream , optional, for garnish , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Peel your potatoes", "Slice up those potatoes; soak them in water", "Roast garlic to make an infused oil (optional)", "Bag and season taters", "Seal your veggies", "Cook sous vide", "Serve!", "Starch-crossed lovers"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/righteous-russet-potatoes"}, {"id": 1001, "t": "Crisp Corn With Butter and Fresh Herbs", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Hoping to find a vibrant summer side dish that’s easy to make? You want to cook your sweet and savory corn sous vide with Joule Turbo! You’ll have crisp corn and the bright flavor of fresh herbs, along with golden drippings of butter. It tastes of summer sunlight. Best yet? This dish requires no active cooking time—all you need is your trusty Joule Turbo and the patience to wait before digging in.", "i": ["60 ml Olive oil , optional", "3 Garlic clove(s) , peeled, optional", "383 g Corn , roughly 4 ears", "2.8 g Salt", "57 g Butter", "5 - Thyme , fresh sprigs , as needed", "2.8 g Black pepper , optional", "Fresh herbs , of your choosing, optional , as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Roast garlic to make an infused oil (optional)", "Remove the husk and silk on your corn", "Remove kernels from the cob", "Bag it up and seal it", "Cook sous vide", "Serve that summertime side", "Looking for more vegetables?"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/crisp-corn-with-butter-and-fresh-herbs"}, {"id": 1002, "t": "These Grilled Chicken Legs are Pure Magic", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "As the temperatures start rising, the days get a little bit longer, and the need for a jacket becomes a distant memory, we can focus on only one thing here at ChefSteps. Grilling. You know, that wonderful tradition of cooking that heralds the start of summer, shorts weather, and three glorious months of popsicle eating. And the only thing that makes grilling better? You guessed it—sous vide! All j", "i": ["4 Chicken leg(s)", "10 g Liquid smoke", "30 g Molasses", "5 g Black pepper , optional", "Salt, as needed", "4 Chicken leg(s) - Salt, as needed"], "s": ["Heat sous vide bath", "Make the “secret sauce”", "Bag and season the chicken", "Cook the legs", "Cool the chicken (optional)", "Grill to finish", "Grill, baby, grill!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/these-grilled-chicken-legs-are-pure-magic"}, {"id": 1003, "t": "So You Wanna Buy a Vacuum Sealer?", "c": "Sous Vide", "d": "Just because you don’t need a vacuum sealer to sous vide your favorite foods, it doesn’t mean you might not want one. These handy suckers are getting less expensive by the day. Plus, they are great for sous viding choice vegetables, make batch cooking a breeze, and keep things super sanitary in the kitchen. The best news yet? You don’t need to purchase an expensive chamber vacuum that takes up val", "i": [], "s": ["Why bother with vacuum sealing?", "The best darn veggies you’ve ever tasted", "The easiest, most waste-free batch cooking", "Vacuum sealing keeps you and your loved ones safe", "When should I vacuum seal?", "When can I skip it?", "What kind of vacuum sealer should I get?", "All right, I’m sold. Now gimme some recipes!"], "tips": [], "url": "https://www.chefsteps.com/activities/so-you-wanna-buy-a-vacuum-sealer"}];